<SLUG> BC-OBIT-O'MARA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN MICHAEL O'MARA, 84, NYU ADMINSTRATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Michael O'Mara, a retired vice president of New York
University who had an earlier career as a rackets investigator,
died on June 19 at Hackensack University Medical Center in New
Jersey. A former resident of Leonia, N.J., he was 84 and more
recently lived in Norwood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a cerebral hemorrhage, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1984 after about 20 years as assistant vice
president for business affairs and later vice president for
institutional facilities at NYU.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Worcester, Mass., 'Mara graduated from Holy Cross
College there in 1936, attended Harvard Law School and received his
law degree from Boston College in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the FBI as a special agent and for 10 years dealt with
major criminal and espionage investigations in New York, including
the Alger Hiss perjury case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, he was named chief investigator for a newly formed New
York City Anti-Crime Committee. Privately financed, it was a
citizens' initiative headed by Spruille Braden, a retired diplomat.
Its purpose was to expose rackets and thereby spur officials to
prosecute the racketeers. Its activities led to confrontations with
the Police Department, District Attorney Frank Hogan and
politicians from both major parties.
</P>
<P>
   O'Mara was promoted to executive director, but internal quarrels
on the committee and a public dispute over wiretaps forced his
resignation in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   O'Mara then was a vice president at Webb &AMP; Knapp, the real
estate empire of William Zeckendorf Sr., until NYU recruited him.
</P>
<P>
   O'Mara is survived by his wife of 54 years, Elisabeth; three
daughters, Kathleen of Modesto, Calif., Patricia Adair of New
Canaan, Conn., and Elisabeth Sutter of Milbrae, Calif; a son,
Michael, of Nantucket, Mass.; three sisters, Christine Sullivan of
Boston, Sister Claire O'Mara of New Rochelle, N.Y., and Lucille
Murphy of Dennis, Mass.; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 0002EDT &QL; 
