<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HAUSMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK HAUSMAN, 96, EXECUTIVE; RAISED MILLIONS TO COMBAT PALSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jack Hausman, a retired textile manufacturer who
raised millions of dollars as a founder of New York and national
organizations to benefit people with cerebral palsy, died on Friday
at his home in Manhattan. He was 96 and for many years also had a
home on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Hausman and his wife, Ethel, together with Leonard and
Isabelle Goldenson and Jane Hoving, gathered a group of parents to
raise money for medical care for children with the disorder. The
Hausmans' middle son, Peter, had been born with it and some of the
children of the parents' group had been as well.
</P>
<P>
   Their effort produced what was initially called the Cerebral
Palsy Society. It, in turn, spawned about 150 United Cerebral Palsy
affiliates, along with the United Cerebral Palsy Associations in
Washington, an umbrella organization that Hausman helped to
organize in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The Hausmans and the Goldensons succeeded in mobilizing
thousands of business and labor leaders, celebrities and parents as
volunteers. Under their leadership, United Cerebral Palsy raised
more than $100 million for medical research and a variety of
clinical, educational, recreational, training and employment
services and family support for children and adults with palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Hausman also helped bring about the first United Cerebral Palsy
telethon in 1951. He initiated the New York chapter's annual awards
dinner in 1955, with Bob Hope as the guest of honor, and he
remained a central figure in the event until his death.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former chairman, president and executive vice president
of the New York and national groups. In 1955, he also helped create
the national group's Research and Development Foundation, a
separate organization based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Hausmans also played a crucial role in creating North Shore
University Hospital in Manhasset on Long Island. They established
the Ethel and Jack Hausman Lectureship in Pediatrics and supported
the Hausman Department of Pediatrics. Hausman was the hospital's
president in the 1960s and endowed the Jack Hausman Professorship
in Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Vienna, Hausman came to New York as a boy. His
father, Morris, started M. Hausman &AMP; Sons, and Jack joined the
company at 14 as its bookkeeper while studying accounting at night.
</P>
<P>
   The sons, Jack, Leo and Sam, helped to build it into a concern
with nationwide operations. They bought out Belding Heminway &AMP; Co.
in 1960, and Jack Hausman remained its board vice chairman until
the company was sold in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ethel Hausman died in 1993 after nearly 65 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Hausman is survived by two sons, Richard, of Montauk, N.Y., and
Michael, of Manhattan; his brother, Leo, of Manhattan, who is
president of New York United Cerebral Palsy; eight grandchildren
and nine great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
