A3414 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PUBLINKS-LADN     07-14 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PUBLINKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOGARTH LAUDS PUBLINKS' COMMON VIRTUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Tim Hogarth said the appeal of the U.S. Amateur
Public Links Championship is the fact that it's the people's golf
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth, who won the 1996 final in Hawaii to earn a 10-year
exemption, will play in the event that is being held again this
week at Torrey Pines Golf Course in La Jolla.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, one of 13 conducted annually by the U.S. Golf
Association, is for public-course players only and excludes players
who are members of private courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings together the normal guys,'' Hogarth said, ``the guys
that are there on the weekends waiting for the starting times. The
school teachers, the policemen, even the health-food salesman _
it's their tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth, a health-food broker, and 155 other golfers began two
rounds of stroke play Monday. After today's round, the low 64 will
advance to match play that runs through Saturday's 36-hole final.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth, who played golf at Alemany High School and was later an
All-American at Cal State Northridge, says nothing in the sport has
affected him as much as winning the PubLinks title.``It's a chance
to make history for yourself and memories that will last you the
rest of your life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has achieved much, winning a Los Angeles City championship
two years ago and reaching the semifinals of last year's state
amateur after setting a medalist record of 16-under-par 138. But
nothing compared to his PubLinks title of '96. Because of that, he
got the opportunity to play in last year's Masters. And at every
tournament he has played in since winning the PubLinks, he has been
introduced as a former USGA champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any victory in a USGA event changes your life dramatically,''
Hogarth said. ``You can ask (1997 U.S. Amateur champion) Matt
Kuchar what his life has been like since he won.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar's trademark smile and impressive play in this year's
Masters and U.S. Open have made him one of the most recognizable
amateurs in the country. Hogarth understands what Kuchar is
enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't believe that he's on that peak,'' Hogarth said. ``The
opportunity to play in the Masters is something every golfer will
cherish, and its all possible with this event.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a Masters invitation, PubLinks champions are
granted exemption into the next U.S. Amateur and Mid-Amateur finals
and into the final round of qualifying for the next U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth, who had some success playing professionally on the
Golden State Tour before regaining his amateur status three years
ago, says he has come to appreciate amateur golf more the longer he
plays it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows someone who loves golf the opportunity to compete at
a very high level,'' he said. ``The older I get, the more respect I
have for (1994 PGA Senior Tour rookie of the year) Jay Sigel. He
was able to golf (as an amateur) for so long, and then he plays on
the senior tour and he's a winner there also.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth said national tournaments such as the PubLinks
demonstrate how high the quality of play can be below the
professional level.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing amateur golf, but it's not really that far of a
step below,'' he said. ``The U.S. Open and Masters have certainly
showed that your champion amateur golfers can compete at all
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Hogarth will attempt to follow in the footsteps of
another former Alemany High star and win a second PubLinks title.
Sylmar's David Berganio accomplished that in 1991 and '93 before
going on to a professional golf career that earned him a PGA Tour
card last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Finneran, a longtime area golf instructor and teammate of
Hogarth's at Northridge, expects Hogarth to do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that can play in the Masters and all those other
tournaments he's been in will do just fine,'' Finneran said. ``He
can hit it long, and he's tough on the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth will tee it up with the best of the nation's
public-course players, some of them once-a-week golfers who are
living the dream in this tournament. That's what Hogarth likes best
about the PubLinks _ that it's open to players who might not
otherwise have the chance to compete in a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still the opportunity,'' he said, ``for someone to
play the best golf that they ever played and jump out from nowhere
and win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
