<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS IN FILM AND STILL COUNTING 
FILM FESTIVAL SHAKE-UP  
 AU REVOIR, DANIEL 
BUT CAN HE SING?
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I just found out I was born the day women got the
vote,'' Shelley Winters was saying. ``I was watching a documentary.
A state voted in favor, I forget which state. I've been telling
everyone I take two years off, but now I'll put them back.'' The
date, she said, was Aug. 18, 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days before she turns 76 _ no, 78 _ Ms. Winters will
receive a lifetime achievement award at the Hollywood Film
Festival. Looking back on a career of 150 films, she singled out
``A Place in the Sun'' as a favorite. ``It's a universal story,''
she said. ``All the women weep, and the men go, `Oh.' Forty-eight
years later. My God, I've been in movies for 50 years. But 50 years
isn't as long as it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation turned to her latest film, ``Gideon's Web,'' an
independent feature. ``I should have played the part where I was in
the nursing home, but they had me running it,'' she said. ``It
showed the kind of stopping of living people do when they retire. I
think retiring is the worst thing people can do.''
</P>
<P>
   FILM FESTIVAL SHAKE-UP
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There has been a shake-up at another film festival.
Denise Kasell, a film producer who ran the Hudson Valley Film
Festival, has taken over the Hamptons International Film Festival,
whose star power seemed somewhat dim last year (``Bigwigs Skip
Expanded Fest,'' Variety declared in a headline). The festival has
also recruited David Schwartz of the American Museum of the Moving
Image for its programming committee.
</P>
<P>
   But will the stars bring their reading glasses? The program at
another festival in Ms. Kasell's new neighborhood, the Music
Festival of the Hamptons, promised the aria ``There's Nothing So
Fat as a Woman'' by the 17th century composer Henry Purcell. It was
not an ode to Weight Watchers: The tenor Robert White told the
audience that the correct title was, ``There's Nothing So Fatal as
a Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   AU REVOIR, DANIEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I didn't bring you here just to celebrate the World
Cup,'' the French-born chef Daniel Boulud told the lunchtime crowd
at Restaurant Daniel on East 76th Street. Certainly not: He wanted
to talk about his restaurant's fifth anniversary, and the fact that
it is closing next month.
</P>
<P>
   Well, moving. The room where Boulud's customers have been seated
since 1993 will be remodeled as Cafe Boulud, a less formal
restaurant. Daniel will reopen at the end of the year at 65th
Street and Park Avenue, where Le Cirque used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd looked at blueprints and drawings, as well as
prototypes of plates on which the food will be served. ``They
haven't made hundreds of these yet, have they?'' asked Joel Smilow,
Boulud's financial partner, looking at a plate on which the words
``Cafe Boulud'' appeared, over and over, in a circle. He suggested
simplifying the design, then declared, ``I never try to interfere
or second-guess creative or restaurant-type decisions.'' Nor did he
try to rein in the ever-exuberant Boulud. ``When he'd be asked to
go on the David Letterman show, he'd say it would be great for
business. I'd say, `Daniel, how can it be great for business? You
can't serve more people than you're serving already.'''
</P>
<P>
   BUT CAN HE SING? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from Bert Parks: Boomer Esiason, a former
quarterback for the Cincinnati Bengals, will be the host of this
year's Miss America Pageant. Esiason will also make his debut as a
commentator on ABC's ``Monday Night Football,'' which took over the
pageant broadcast last year.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Horn, the longtime president and chief executive of the
pageant, announced Esiason's arrival at the same time that he
announced his own departure. Horn, 61, said that after the Sept. 19
pageant, he would move to Jackson, Tenn., his wife's hometown, to
become a ``country lawyer.'' His replacement has not been named.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
