<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-JUDGE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: WAS FORMER JUDGE A SCAPEGOAT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is safe to say that Lorin Duckman, formerly Judge
Lorin Duckman, is one of the more reviled public figures in New
York City. The attacks against him have been so harsh, you would
almost think that Duckman alone stood between New York and
Periclean bliss.
</P>
<P>
   His critics' line of reasoning leads to one logical conclusion:
Now that he has been booted off the bench, in a decision upheld
last week by the state Court of Appeals, we can expect a flawless
city where no one is murdered, no man beats his wife and everyone
is ineffably courteous.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it did not seem an affront to democracy to visit Duckman
Monday in his house near Prospect Park in Brooklyn to hear his
version of events. What he went through these last two years, he
said, was nothing less than a ``lynching.'' It was an opinion that
might be dismissed as mutterings of a bitter man, except that
dissenting judges on the Court of Appeals came close to saying the
same thing in more judicial language.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a dissenting opinion is more of an eye-opener than a
majority ruling, especially when, as in this case, the majority
writes with the blandness of someone going through the motions and
the minority writes with fervor. Here is what one impassioned
dissenter, Judge Vito Titone, said in part about the Duckman
affair:
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication of the present disciplinary proceeding is that
judges whose rulings displease the political powers that be may be
subjected to a modern-day witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   You will remember that the state's most powerful politicians
went after Duckman in 1996 after he set relatively low bail for a
man jailed on domestic-abuse charges. Once released on bail, this
man, Benito Oliver, killed a former girlfriend, Galina Komar, and
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani lost no time
screaming for Duckman's scalp. Then other judges came in their
cross hairs, damned as responsible for New York's crime problems.
It was an all-out assault, abetted mightily by baying tabloid
headlines about ``junk justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the noise was a critical fact: The state Commission on
Judicial Conduct and other bodies that reviewed the Oliver case
determined that Duckman had done nothing wrong. But by then, he had
become the poster child in a conservative campaign against
pointy-headed, lenient judges. Officials were determined to build a
case against him, and, in Duckman's view, ``it was a done deal from
the very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   He charged that the office of the Brooklyn district attorney,
Charles Hynes, had kept a dossier on him, and that it still does
with other judges deemed anti-prosecution. In response, a Hynes
spokesman said, ``We don't do that.'' But Titone, for one, was
willing to believe that anti-Duckman files were kept, and said so.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the case against Duckman was built on episodes in
which he used intemperate language, as well as 16 cases in which
his dismissal of criminal charges was questionable or even, as he
now acknowledges, flat-out wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But are we seriously to believe that no judge still on the bench
has uttered intemperate words in the hurly-burly of the New York
court system? Bear in mind, too, that no one had brought
disciplinary charges against Duckman until after the Oliver case.
</P>
<P>
   As for those 16 dismissals, all involved misdemeanors, and the
district attorney appealed not one of them. How outraged could he
have been?
</P>
<P>
   And even if Duckman's judgment was off, they were 16 cases out
of 55,000 _ repeat, 55,000 _ that he handled in five years as a
Criminal Court judge. To another Court of Appeals dissenter, Judge
Joseph Bellacosa, the ax that fell was ``disproportionate to the
nature, number and gravity of the proven and acknowledged judicial
misdeeds, misspeaks and mishaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument here is not that Duckman was the wisest judge since
Learned Hand. He is clearly a quirky character, as evidenced by the
whimsical duck themes that fill his house: wooden ducks, Donald
Duck, posters for the Marx Brothers' ``Duck Soup.''
</P>
<P>
   But you have to ask how well anyone's reputation would hold up
if put under a microscope the way his was once the politicians
decided that he must go. More important is whether other judges
have been intimidated by his example. Absolutely, Duckman said,
``judges are in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a serious charge, and, the appellate dissenters agreed, no
canard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
