<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E.Y. TAKES TURN ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Second baseman Eric Young, who leads the National
League with 33 stolen bases despite missing 14 starts with a
strained quadriceps, was placed on the 15-day disabled list after
doctors determined his leg was not improving.
</P>
<P>
   Young, sidelined the past two games after going 4 for 11 to
start the second half, was placed on the DL on Monday after
undergoing an MRI exam. Young first injured the leg May 19 in
Chicago and has missed playing time on four separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers wanted to put Young on the DL June 26 in Texas when
he reinjured the leg a third time, but he talked general manager
Tom Lasorda out of making the move. Instead, he missed the final
five games of the first half and hoped the three-day All-Star break
would get him back to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to play against the Giants and the Padres, and I
respect his desire to take one for the team,'' Lasorda said. ``But
we can't have this continue. We need him healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Young becomes the fourth member of the Dodgers' starting infield
to go on the DL. First baseman Eric Karros missed the season's
first 22 games after knee surgery. Shortstop Jose Vizcaino has been
out since June 22 with a severely sprained right ankle. Third
baseman Bobby Bonilla, who since has been moved to left, was on the
DL from June 20 to July 3.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hubbard back: Trenidad Hubbard, who was sent down Sunday to
make room on the roster for pitcher Brian Bohanon, was recalled
Monday to take Young's spot.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Dodgers tried to option Hubbard to the
minors, but he came up with a sore left knee and was placed on the
disabled list. Hubbard is batting .323 in 39 games with the
Dodgers, including four homers and eight RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hubbard never left Los Angeles, the Dodgers did burn an
option by sending him down. A player is allowed three with each
team before he has to clear waivers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hershiser comes home: On Wednesday, former Cy Young
Award-winning right-hander Orel Hershiser will make his first
appearance at Dodger Stadium since leaving the club in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was moved up in the Giants rotation after left-hander
Shawn Estes, Wednesday's scheduled starter, was scratched because
of shoulder fatigue. He faced the Dodgers on July 3 in San
Francisco and won 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely will be special,'' said Hershiser, who is 7-7
with a 4.01 ERA this season. ``I mean, that goes without saying. I
don't think it's going to be emotionally hard because, like I
explained in San Francisco, it's really not against guys that I
lived and died with other than a couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big series for the Dodgers. So I know that it's going
to be a big game for us, because they're trying to climb back in
the race and we're trying to chase the Padres.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
