</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS FOR SUSPECTS ACCUSE POLICE OF CONCEALING EVIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Also see MISSING-MILLIONAIRE)   (sw) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nine days after Irene Silverman mysteriously
vanished, the lawyers for the mother and son under investigation in
the case went to the socialite's lavish East Side mansion on Monday
and accused the police of concealing evidence that might clear the
suspects of any suspicion in her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a combative news conference that used Mrs.
Silverman's East 65th Street home as a backdrop, the lawyers gave
the first glimpse of their possible defense in the case, should any
charges be brought against their clients, Sante Kimes and Kenneth
Kimes. The lawyers described Mrs. Silverman, 82, as a domineering
woman whose contentious personality might have provided motives for
a long list of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, Matthew Weissman and Jose Muniz, also accused the
police of using the news media to smear their clients' reputations
by portraying them as a mother-and-son con artist team who traveled
the country preying on the wealthy, and suggested that members of
Mrs. Silverman's staff of 10 servants might be involved in her
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tough lady, she treats her help very abruptly, she's
hard on her employees,'' Weissman said. ``She has a lot of
arguments with them. She's not the lovely eccentric old lady who's
devoted to the arts and other things.''
</P>
<P>
   With television cameras rolling, Weissman later banged on the
mansion's front door demanding that detectives let him in so that
he could monitor the investigation and find evidence to prove his
clients' innocence inside the $6,000-a-month suite in the mansion
that Kimes rented from Mrs. Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered.
</P>
<P>
   Kimes, 23, and Mrs. Kimes, 63, were arrested in Manhattan on
July 5 on the relatively minor charge of using a bad check to
purchase a Lincoln Town Car in Utah, but have since been linked to
a series of disappearances and a murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles police have said the Kimeses are suspects in the
shooting death in March of their former business partner after they
used his property to obtain a fraudulent $280,000 loan. The
authorities in the Bahamas have said the Kimeses are under
investigation in connection with the disappearance of a bank
auditor in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The New York police have found no sign of Mrs. Silverman, who is
presumed dead by many of her friends, but detectives have
discovered tantalizing links between her and the Kimeses. Four days
before Mrs. Silverman vanished, for example, the Kimeses took a
notary public to Ms. Silverman's office and asked her to sign a
power of attorney form, according to an investigator who spoke on
the condition of anonymity. The Kimeses were also carrying Mrs.
Silverman's passport and other identification when they were
arrested, the police have said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Kimeses' arrest, their car contained business
documents, a loaded 9-millimeter handgun and the same brand of
.22-caliber ammunition used in the March 14 slaying of David
Kazdin, their former business partner in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   New York detectives have found a small spot of blood on a seat
belt of the Lincoln Town Car and a small patch of blood outside
Mrs. Silverman's home, but have not yet received laboratory
results.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz and Weissman offered explanations for some of the
evidence. The gun had been purchased by a former employee of the
Kimeses, Weissman said. He suggested that the employee, who later
became an informer for the FBI and helped the authorities arrest
the Kimeses, had close ties to Kazdin before his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gambled together in Las Vegas,'' he said, ``and whether
the FBI put the heat on him and he found it appropriate or adept to
pass the buck to our clients, we'll find out down the line.'' Los
Angeles police investigators say the former employee is not a
suspect in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz also said he is confident that a DNA examination will show
that the blood did not come from Mrs. Silverman or the Kimeses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
