<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RAY OF HOPE FOR RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Gordon Edes 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ ``So, where we going, Braggie?'' Mo
Vaughn cracked to Darren Bragg the other day, when talk of Vaughn's
contract negotiations dominated the Red Sox clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg looked puzzled for a moment, then broke into a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can afford to take both of us,'' said Bragg, the
Connecticut brown-bagger who this spring had to ask his agent how
much he'd signed for.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bragg's $367,500 salary barely registers on the Red
Sox' $51 million payroll, there was no overlooking his value to the
team Monday night in a 2-0 win over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays that
ended a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox right fielder followed a two-out, carpet-rolling
double by Mike Benjamin with an RBI single to break a scoreless tie
in the fifth, and threw out Wade Boggs at the plate in the sixth to
preserve a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs's 40-year-old legs were no match for Bragg's strong right
arm, which easily cut down the former Red Sox at the plate as he
tried to score on Dave Martinez's single off Steve Avery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were going to send him,'' Bragg said, ``so I just
tried to get to it quick and make a good throw. I threw it on the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary singled in Boston's second run, only his second hit
in 17 at-bats since the All-Star break, in the eighth. Though the
Red Sox had 10 hits, all but one were singles, which hardly
constituted an end to the offensive drought that struck with a
vengeance in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But it was enough against the pitiful Devil Rays, who have lost
11 in a row and six of seven to the Sox this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first five innings, you're pushing, pushing, pushing,''
Vaughn said, ``but then Braggie got a big hit, made a big play to
keep us in it, and we went on to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is like anything. You feel it, you know how to get it
done. But it's never easy when you go through a slide like that.
The first one you win is always a close game, always tight, but
that kind of game, when you win, can change your attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragg and Vaughn also were involved in the night's comic relief,
when the scoreboard operator at Tropicana Field drew Vaughn's ire
for stating, big as life on the jumbo-sized screen, that Bragg once
knocked out Vaughn in a high school football game.
</P>
<P>
   That set Vaughn to gesturing toward the press box, and prompted
the following message to appear on the board: ``Sorry about that,
Mo, that intern has been fired.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Vaughn was asked, did the pride of Taft High in Watertown
really smoke the joy of Trinity Pawling Prep on the football field?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you crazy?'' Vaughn asked.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Bragg acknowledged the big man was right. ``We had
some good collisions,'' he said. ``He might have had double vision
a couple of times, but I never knocked him out, and he never
knocked me out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where they got that, but it's a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays stirred late when Boggs singled off lefty
reliever Ron Mahay in the eighth. But Tom Gordon, who hadn't
pitched since his All-Star appearance, retired pinch hitter Aaron
Ledesma on a ground ball and struck out pinch hitter Fred McGriff
to end the inning, then finished off the Devil Rays in the ninth
for his 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   The win went to Avery, who is now 6-2 and matched his victory
total from last season, when he was one start away from becoming
history in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays had no shortage of runners against Avery,
posterboy for five-inning pitchers, who was rescued in the sixth by
a big strikeout of Mike Kelly by Derek Lowe with runners on second
and third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable,'' Avery said. ``I mostly got outs
on sheer will. And (the Devil Rays) were probably a little anxious,
pressing a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The lefthander gave up five hits, walked four, and threw a wild
pitch in his 5 2/3 innings, but he also struck out the side in the
third and benefited from two double plays, one of his own making.
</P>
<P>
   That came in the second, when John Flaherty hit a line drive
back at the pitcher with Martinez on second after a walk and stolen
base. Avery got his glove on the ball, then when it popped loose,
grabbed it with his pitching hand and fired to second baseman Mike
Benjamin to double up Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was self-defense,'' Avery said. ``It knocked my glove
off. The ball popped up, my glove was half on, and I grabbed it
with my other hand. Then I looked to second, nobody was really
close, so I decided to throw it to the first guy I made eye contact
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a screwed-up play, but the kind of break you need to
get a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
