<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT &LR;      07-14 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEAL SET IN RULING ON SECRET SERVICE TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has decided to appeal a
decision last week ordering Secret Service agents to testify before
a federal grand jury in the Lewinsky matter, a senior
administration official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that Attorney General Janet Reno had decided
on Monday to support a further appeal to the full panel of the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. On July 7, a
three-judge panel from the appeals court unanimously rejected the
administration's argument that Secret Service agents should be
entitled to a novel privilege that would shield them from
testifying in most criminal inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   The decision follows a debate within the top ranks of the
Justice Department about the wisdom of a further appeal. Some
officials had argued that because there was virtually no law on the
administration's side to establish such a privilege, it would be
counterproductive to seek a further review. But Lewis Merletti, the
director of the Secret Service, had strenuously argued that the
president would distance himself from his bodyguards _ putting his
life in danger _ if Secret Service employees were compelled to
testify about his private life.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the office of Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel, have been seeking the testimony of three
Secret Service officials for months to help determine whether
anyone committed obstruction of justice, witness tampering or
perjury in the inquiry of the relationship between President
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Those three were identified as John Kelleher, the chief counsel
of the Secret Service, and Gary Byrne and Brian Henderson, both
uniformed officers, lawyers involved in the appeal said. The
lawyers said investigators wanted to know whether the uniformed
officers discussed Ms. Lewinsky with Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1996, Byrne had apparently informed Evelyn
Lieberman, then deputy chief of staff at the White House, that he
had seen Ms. Lewinsky in the West Wing when he did not believe she
was authorized to be there. Ms. Lieberman has said Ms. Lewinsky was
transferred to the Pentagon and removed from her White House job
because of ``immature and inappropriate behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of success in continuing the appeal, which was
first reported in the early Tuesday edition of The Washington Post,
seems slim. The full court of appeals does not usually accept such
reviews. If the court decides not to consider the matter, the
Justice Department may appeal the decision to the Supreme Court,
which would not hear the case until after it returned in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service case is one of two being litigated over legal
privileges and the independent counsel. A different panel is
expected to rule soon on over whether Bruce Lindsey, deputy White
House counsel and one of Clinton's closest aides, can refuse to
answer some questions on the grounds that they are protected by the
lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
