<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS SNAP YANKEES' 10-GAME WINNING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Orlando Hernandez is already renowned for his
ability to make adjustments on the fly, but on Monday night the
Cleveland Indians made their own adjustments to Hernandez and beat
the right-hander, 4-1, snapping the Yankees' 10-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thome hit a home run and a triple against Hernandez, and
Jaret Wright (9-5) pitched seven innings to become the first
pitcher to beat the Yankees (65-21) twice this season. The only run
allowed by Wright was a long home run to Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we're not doing it lately,'' Paul O'Neill said.
``We're putting a lot of pressure on our pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed nine hits, two walks and four runs in six and
two-thirds innings. Two of the hits he yielded were homers: one to
Thome, the first homer Hernandez had given up in 44 innings, and
the other to Kenny Lofton, only the third the Cuban pitcher has
allowed since joining the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Yankees won, their 66-20 mark would have been the best
86-game record in the 20th century, one game better than that of
Honus Wagner's 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates. As it stands, the Yankees
and the 1902 Pirates are tied, along with the 1912 New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Indians for the second time in less than a month,
Hernandez dominated in the early innings, confusing batters,
forcing them to swing on his terms, throwing almost everything on
the outer edge of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   After Omar Vizquel stole second with one out in the first,
Hernandez struck out David Justice swinging on a straight changeup,
and with a 2-2 count on Thome, Hernandez chose that moment to throw
his first curve. Thome watched it bend over the plate for strike
three.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright, Cleveland's burly bleached-blond pitcher, matched
Hernandez in the early innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wright retired Tino Martinez and Tim Raines to open the fourth
inning. Strawberry walked to the plate, in the midst of a 1-for-19
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Wright threw him what appeared to be a high fastball, and
Strawberry smashed it more than 400 feet, the ball carrying until
it bounced on top of the ledge of the center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Johnson, the second-base umpire, immediately signaled home
run _ Strawberry's 12th, the most in a season for him since 1991 _
and Lofton, the center fielder, and others complained that the ball
had struck the yellow border above the fence and should have been
in play.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's call stood, and the Yankees had a lead, something they
do not often relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' hitters made an adjustment, however, and lurched
ahead. Realizing that Hernandez was throwing outside repeatedly,
Thome leaned across the plate with one out in the fourth inning and
drove the first pitch to the opposite field, instead of trying to
pull it, for a home run into the left-field stands, his 24th.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians seemed to ascertain what Thome did right in going to
the opposite field. After Manny Ramirez walked, the
left-handed-hitting Brian Giles banged a first-pitch fastball to
left field, off the wall, Ramirez stopping at third base. With two
right-handed batters due to hit, Hernandez was still in control:
right-handed batters had just 7 hits in 72 at-bats against the
pitcher known as El Duque, because they have such a difficult time
with his sidearm slider.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez threw a sidearm slider to Sandy Alomar, who stretched
his arms to reach the ball out of the strike zone. He barely hit
the ball, but hit it enough. The ball fell over the head of
Martinez, the first baseman, scoring Ramirez with the run that gave
Cleveland a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thome again reached out in the sixth inning to drive a ball to
the opposite field, and when it bounced against the wall and above
the leaps of outfielders Raines and Chad Curtis, Thome rambled into
third with a triple. He scored on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton homered in the seventh, his fifth hit in eight at-bats
against Hernandez. Two batters later, Manager Joe Torre relieved El
Duque, who stalked off, self-torture evident in his grimace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to go more away,'' catcher Jorge Posada said
afterward of Hernandez's pitching pattern. ``For him to do well,
he's got to pitch inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
