<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN, SHOW SOME FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers don't care if they have
been reduced to the watered-down wild card. They were facing the
San Francisco Giants on Monday night and that always means
something.
</P>
<P>
   Their 7-5 victory didn't draw much of a crowd, which isn't
surprising from fans hoping for more than the chase for second
place. But the Dodgers showed 36,409 a few pluses they hope will
make the second half worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Dodgers within 5{ games of San Francisco
for the wild-card spot in the National League. Of course, there are
four other teams between the Giants and Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   On a less realistic front, the Dodgers even picked up a game on
West-leading San Diego, creeping within 12{ games of first place.
</P>
<P>
   There were individual efforts worth watching as well, and more
than just the first-inning home runs by Raul Mondesi and Eric
Karros. Gary Sheffield, who had three hits and two runs and now has
reached base in 15 of his past 20 plate appearance. He is 7 for 11
with six walks and has been hit twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also finally saw a glimpse of the Bobby Bonilla they
hoped they traded for in the big May 15 Mike Piazza deal. Bonilla,
who lost much of his power with an intestinal infection, finally
hit a ball with authority in the seventh inning. He even tried to
stretch the single into a double but was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Dave Mlicki (5-4) ran his record to 4-0 since
joining the club June 5. He allowed eight hits and four runs in
62/3 innings before giving way to Scott Radinsky and Jeff Shaw, who
earned his first save as a Dodger and 24th overall.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there was Wilton Guerrero, who will be playing
second base for the next two weeks. Before the game, Eric Young was
placed on the 15-day disabled list with a strained right
quadriceps. Guerrero, who had a career-high four hits Sunday night,
tripled to open the Dodgers' four-run first inning and made a
brilliant defensive play to end he seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers nearly chased Giants starter Danny Darwin (6-6) in
the first inning when they scored four times on four extra base
hits.
</P>
<P>
   With Guerrero on third, Mondesi drove a 1-0 breaking ball off
the cement facing of the second deck. For Mondesi, who hit his
team-leading 20th home run, had a hitting streak snapped Sunday at
11 games but entered Monday's game only 3 for 17 in the first four
games of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, however, has had no such ups and downs. When he
followed Mondesi with a double to left, it marked the 25th
consecutive game he has reached base. It also was his fifth hit in
11 at-bats. He added two more, including a third-inning single
through a vacant second-base hole created when the Giants put three
players on the left side of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first, Sheffield's double set up Karros, who followed
with a two-run homer to left. It was his 10th of the season and his
48th and 49th RBI despite missing the first 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers extended their lead to 5-0 in the third when
Sheffield singled, took third on the first of two fielding errors
by Giants second baseman Jeff Kent and scored on a sacrifice fly by
Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants got back in the game in the fourth when former
Dodger Stan Javier hit a three-run homer with two outs. Mlicki had
allowed a one-out double to Barry Bonds then gave up a two-out walk
to J.T. Snow. The switch-hitting Javier, batting left-handed
against the right-handed Mlicki, drove the first pitch into the
left-field stands for his second homer of the season and first in
207 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla made it 6-3 in the fifth with a sacrifice fly that
scored Juan Castro. Kent got the run back in the sixth with his
eighth homer, and his first since missing a month with a sprained
right knee. He returned to the Giants' lineup on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki reached on a throwing error by Kent with one out in the
sixth and later scored on a single by Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki was replaced by left-hander Radinsky after Darryl
Hamilton singled with two outs in the seventh. Radinsky got out of
the inning when Guerrero made a diving stop at second and got up to
throw out Bill Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds opened the eighth by doubling to left center, stole third
and scored when Charles Johnson's throw got away from Adrian
Beltre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
