<HEADER>
A3480 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MONAHAN-SPI &LR;      07-14 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MONAHAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONAHAN STAKES CLAIM IN LEFT FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Undoubtedly, Shane Monahan will be one of those
players who is known as gritty, hard-nosed, tough. That's the
exterior and the mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Monahan also might be recognized as an angry young
man, but only occasionally and just because the Mariners' new left
fielder is such a perfectionist. When his own expectations aren't
met, tantrums result with helmets flying, teammates scattering.
</P>
<P>
   It is in his competitive nature, not to mention his genes. This
descendant of two Hockey Hall of Famers would body check you into
the boards, a candidate for the penalty box if he still played the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe only his fiancee has seen the flip side of Monahan's
apparent ruggedness. If you think the biggest catch he ever made
was the one that saved two runs and the game for Randy Johnson on
Saturday afternoon, Monahan would tell you otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred during spring training. Monahan went to his
girlfriend's school, where she is a sixth-grade teacher in the
Phoenix area. The morning announcements in each class are aired on
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan popped up on the monitor as a special guest. He told his
soon-to-be fiancee, Alisha, that he loved her with all of his heart
and proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I said if your answer is yes, open your door and run
out,'' Monahan said. ``I was standing out in the hallway, and sure
enough, she came running out. I do have a romantic side to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, if there have ever been love stories in left field,
they have been quick-readers with sad endings. The most recent
chapter featured Glenallen Hill, who was dismissed last week,
taking his iron glove to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   When he started last Thursday's game against Anaheim, Monahan
became the 58th left fielder to play alongside Ken Griffey Jr.
Monahan might be the solution. The 6-foot, 200-pound 24-year-old is
a scrapper who likes to play defense, hit line drives and run the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Monday night's game, Monahan was averaging .417 in
his first three games since being called up from Tacoma. His first
hit was a two-run single, delivered when the bases were loaded, an
exception to the Mariner trend.
</P>
<P>
   His most significant contribution occurred two days later when
he dived to snare Tim Salmon's sinking liner in the eighth inning,
preserving Johnson's 2-0 victory. Monahan said later he would have
rather had his teeth knocked out than to have the ball get by him.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner can appreciate that type of dedication. The Mariners'
right fielder sees too many youngsters who don't respect the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see a kid coming up who is not afraid to leave a
little skin on the Astroturf,'' Buhner said. ``He plays the game
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Buhner playfully criticized Monahan for being too
outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to teach him not to be so diarrhea-mouthed, and then
he'll be just fine,'' Buhner said. ``He has a tendency to open his
trap a little too much. That's the only fault he has.''
</P>
<P>
   The perception surprised Monahan, who said: ``To my standards,
I've been quiet. I'm not going to speak unless I'm spoken to.''
</P>
<P>
   He intends for the last word to be different from the first.
Monahan carved out a hot-headed reputation in the minor leagues. He
got into one scuffle last year. He has tossed helmets and broken
bats.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan's fiancee cautioned him about his behavior, reminding
him that kids were watching, to ``chill out.'' He tries to watch
himself now, admitting that he has to fight the urge.
</P>
<P>
   The nut-outs are still one play away, like when Monahan ran home
the other night, even though third-base coach Steve Smith told him
to see the ball through the infield. He was gunned down by the
second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just pumped up, I guess, trying to make things happen,''
Monahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan was trying to score, just like his father, Hartland,
frequently did as a right-winger in the NHL. His grandfather is
Bernie ``Boom-Boom'' Geoffrion who starred in Montreal and New York
and those Miller Lite commercials. His great-grandfather, former
Canadien Howie Morenz, was the best of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan quit playing hockey when he became a teenager. The
Mariners spotted him at Clemson, where Monahan was a two-time
All-American, selecting him in the second round of the '95 draft.
</P>
<P>
   He wears No. 12, though he is actually No. 58, hopeful that the
Mariners can stop counting and start experiencing a little
stability in left field.
</P>
<P>
   M'S LOG: Utility player Rickey Cradle was sent down to Class AAA
Tacoma to make room for pitcher Ken Cloude. . . . Reliever Greg
McCarthy suffered a sprained right ankle during pregame drills.
While McCarthy ran sprints he stepped on a baseball. His foot
buckled, and he limped off the field and into the clubhouse. His
status was not announced. . . . The season attendance total for 46
Mariners home games is a little more than 1,550,000, a drop of more
than 12 percent from a year ago, when the club drew nearly
1,800,000 for its first 46 home dates. . . . The M's got a visit
from retired hitting coach Lee Elia prior to the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
