<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3482 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-14 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Diamondbacks keep Astros reeling
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ Bank One Ballpark must have looked like an oasis to the
Astros, who arrived in the desert thirsty for a victory after
losing three games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Make that four.
</P>
<P>
   The most woeful team in the majors added to the Astros' miseries
Monday night, tagging them with a 5-3 loss that extended their
losing streak to a season-worst four games.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Arizona Diamondbacks should have been just what
the doctor ordered, but these are sickly times indeed for the
Astros. Temperatures are expected to exceed 100 degrees in the
Phoenix area today. Perhaps the Astros should allow their bats to
soak up some rays. Anything to break the cold spell.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have the second-worst pitching staff in the
National League, and Monday's starter, Amaury Telemaco, hadn't won
a game outside of relief appearances since Aug. 13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the way the Astros are struggling, Telemaco might as
well have been Greg Maddux, and the Diamondbacks might as well have
been the Atlanta Braves. Telemaco (3-3) and relief pitchers Bobby
Chouinard and Gregg Olson held the Astros to five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not swinging the bats well,'' said Astros second
baseman Craig Biggio, who is hitting .158 since the All-Star break.
``It's as simple as that. We usually don't get so many guys
struggling at once, but sooner or later we're going to break out.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and Moises Alou have only eight hits among
them in the five games since the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the offensive capabilities that we have, offense
is always the excuse people want to use when we lose,'' Astros
center fielder Carl Everett said. ``You're going to go through your
dry spells offensively. That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who lead the NL in runs, enjoyed one of their most
fertile offensive stretches just before the All-Star break when
they averaged 8.3 runs over an eight-game span. They've averaged
3.6 runs in the first five games of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from (Arizona's)
pitching,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said, ``but when we don't
hit for three or four days in a row, it's more than just the other
team's pitching. It's us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been an unparalleled losing streak for the
Astros, who remained four games ahead of the second-place Chicago
Cubs in the NL Central. Although more than a few batting helmets
and bats have been slammed into the ground over the past four days,
the Astros insist they have not begun to press.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we supposed to do, panic?'' right fielder Derek Bell
asked. ``We've only lost four games in a row. It's not like we've
lost 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Pete Schourek didn't allow an outrageous number
of hits, but the ones he surrendered were big. Four of the seven
hits the Diamondbacks collected while Schourek was in the game went
for extra bases, and three of them produced runs.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek (5-6), who missed a chance to extend his winning streak
to three games, allowed five runs and three walks in six innings.
It was only the second time in his last seven starts that Schourek
allowed three or more runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't make good enough pitches,'' he said. ``That's
the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek allowed five Diamondbacks to reach base in the first
three innings, but he managed to keep each of them from crossing
the plate. The veteran lefthander ran out of escape tricks in the
fourth inning when the Diamondbacks put three runs on the board.
</P>
<P>
   An oxygen tank might have done Everett as much good as a glove
considering the workout Schourek put him through in the fourth.
After Schourek issued a leadoff walk to Jay Bell, Everett had to
chase down back-to-back triples by David Dellucci and Damian
Miller. Each three-base hit produced a run for the Diamondbacks, as
did Telemaco's sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I should've been able to get out of that inning in
better shape than I did, but I didn't,'' Schourek said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he probably could have used a break, Everett led off
the fifth inning with a single and scored along with Brad Ausmus on
Schourek's opposite-field double to left. They were the first two
RBIs of the season for Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Schourek, his bat was working better than his
pitches. Diamondbacks second baseman Danny Klassen led off the
bottom of the fifth with a homer into the left-field seats. The
second run of the inning was preceded by a controversial call that
resulted in the second ejection of the season for Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams, who drew a walk and stole second after Klassen's
homer, was called safe at third on a fielder's-choice grounder by
Jay Bell. Dierker immediately bolted from the dugout and engaged in
the most spirited protest of a call in his 254 games as a manager.
When third-base umpire Angel Hernandez had heard enough, he
banished Dierker to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker didn't miss much. His offense managed only an infield
single after he was tossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hernandez) missed that call by a mile,'' Dierker said. ``That
was a costly run. Sometimes you get the breaks, and sometimes you
don't. I guess I was a little frustrated and got madder than I
should have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
