<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BLAST RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ken Cloude stood with his right arm heavily encased in
ice, talking about his career performance.
</P>
<P>
   All Ken Griffey Jr. did was flash a smile before he brushed off
a night that makes most careers.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, if it were only that easy.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cloude looked more like a hospital patient than a
guy who threw a career-high eight innings, he helped the Mariners
score a casual 10-3 victory over the Texas Rangers on Monday night
at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude (5-7) supplied the sweat and stamina. Edgar Martinez
produced the power.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey _ in his own
simple-but-don't-you-try-this-at-home-manner _ manufactured the
breath-taking highlight.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 7-3 in the fifth inning, Griffey robbed Will Clark of an
extra-base hit with a spectacular catch. Clark belted a Cloude
fastball 400 feet into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, running hard with his back to the ball, reached out his
glove and made an over-the-shoulder catch before crashing into the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   The play was reminiscent of Willie Mays, but is becoming
routinely Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   About the only other spectacular part of the game was Cloude's
pitching. He allowed just two earned runs and struck out four.
Cloude, who returned from Class AAA Tacoma yesterday, could have
worked the ninth if not for having pitched three days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Griffey stole his thunder. But what else is new?
</P>
<P>
   At least Cloude got a good look at the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best catches I've ever seen,'' said Cloude,
who was asked how Griffey makes such plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does he do a lot of the things he does? He's amazing. He's
the best player in baseball,'' Cloude said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a reporter mentioned that to Griffey before the
game. Griffey responded, ``I don't play for that. I play to win
ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who went 3-for-5 with 2 RBIs, did not want to comment
after the game. However, he helped the Mariners win for the third
time in five games since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh boy, what a play,'' M's manager Lou Piniella said. ``Over
the shoulder, over the play and against the wall. He just turned it
perfectly, and made it look easy. ... We played crisp on the field.
It was a good ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   As for their chances in the American League West, the M's crept
to within 12 games of first-place Anaheim, which lost to Oakland.
If only for one more day, the Mariners remain optimistic about
climbing out of the division basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the talent (to get back in the race),'' said Martinez,
who hit his 16th home run in the first inning and 17th in the
sixth. ``We can do it. I believe in this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas starter Todd Van Poppel (1-2) took the loss. He struggled
with his control from the outset. What Van Poppel got over the
plate, the Mariners picked up. Martinez registered the biggest blow
of the first inning, popping a three-run blast deep into the
right-center-field bleachers. It came on Van Poppel's first pitch
to Martinez, only moments after Griffey's RBI single scored Joey
Cora.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners sent nine batters to the plate in the first,
beginning with Cora's leadoff single.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-0 cushion out of the gate did not preclude a shaky start
from Cloude. He threw six pitches before walking the first hitter
he faced. Cloude's inconsistency quickly cost him three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude threw 117 pitches, although he settled down in the middle
innings. He ended the third with two strikeouts and didn't allow a
runner to get in scoring position in the next three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mariners chased Van Poppel and distanced
themselves from the Rangers with three runs in the fourth. The
Rangers used three pitchers in that inning, which ended with the
Mariners ahead 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Alex Rodriguez's two-out RBI double put the
Mariners ahead 8-3. They took a 9-3 advantage on Martinez's second
homer in the sixth. It was his 1,300th career hit. Another run
before the inning ended gave the M's a 10-3 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
