<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-14 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET MARINER WOES AND JUST ENJOY WATCHING GRIFFEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For any citizens of Marinerville who have spent too
much time senselessly worrying about whether Ken Griffey Jr. smiles
too much or not enough _ are we a society with too much time on our
hands or what? _ do yourself a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Walk up and buy a ticket for Tuesday night's Mariner game
against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   For one night, try not to care that some of the money will help
ease the burden on the Mariner owners _ those indecisive fellas too
paralyzed to have pulled the trigger on any moves that would have
salvaged this frustrating season and put this should-be contender
back on track.
</P>
<P>
   For now, forget about all that.
</P>
<P>
   Just for tonight, let it go.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Marinerville, Griffey is doing great stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Like making catches that make his seen-it-all manager glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, boy, was that a pretty catch,'' Lou Piniella said Monday
night after his MVP center fielder ran down a ball and let it drop
into his glove with so much ease you wonder what Griffey would do
if baseball was basketball and he could have the ball at the end of
every game.
</P>
<P>
   People talk about why Griffey doesn't inflict his will on his
team. People are wondering why he doesn't blow up his clubhouse and
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   People wonder whether he is a natural-born leader, but for
everyone who wonders, Griffey has his answer.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, you have to wait your turn. It takes 25 guys to
win. It takes all nine on the field to perform.
</P>
<P>
   So he can't take over. He can't demand and take over. It's not
the way it works _ and give Griffey some credit for not thinking he
could save the Mariners. His ego truly isn't that large.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Griffey made a catch Monday night on Will
Clark's long fly ball that made your mouth drop. It elevated a 10-3
victory into the realm of entertainment and wonder _ a nice thing
considering so much of the Mariners' season has been such a bloody
and blood-curdling disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was over the shoulder. Over the back. Against the wall,''
Piniella said, almost reveling in his description of the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that play once in the 1954 World Series. Willie Mays
caught a fly ball by Vic Wertz,'' Piniella said, recounting the
immortal Mays play at the Polo Grounds that also doubled up the
Cleveland runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're seeing those kinds of plays a couple times a summer.
He timed it perfectly. He made it look so pretty,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had themselves that kind of night. Ken Cloude
pitched through some trouble and got the 10-3 win. Edgar Martinez
cashed in for two homers. The Kingdome crowd got to stand and cheer
in the ninth, when Bobby Ayala came on in relief and preserved the
win.
</P>
<P>
   All those boos in Denver did perk his ears and his conscience.
He has been thoughtful and patient since his return, trying to
explain the pressure and demands on him and the reasons he has for
handling the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing, he says, is what he does on the field.
</P>
<P>
   And right now, he is racking up hits faster and with more
persistence than a lumberjack taking cuts at the tallest Douglas
fir.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey now has 1,499 hits to his major league credit.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, No. 1,500 should go in the books, considering
that Griffey has seemed all but bent on making contact and getting
base hits and driving up his batting average.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after hitting .282 a month before the All-Star break,
Griffey has gone on a deliberate march toward hiking his batting
average. It culminated in Monday night's 3-for-5 effort, nailing
three singles and collecting two more RBIs. That puts him at .303 _
the first time since June 2 he has been over .500. He has 38 RBI in
the last 39 games.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. All while cranking out 38 homers _ enough to keep him
on pace with McGwire to make September a time for a national
feeding frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if he's the fastest major leaguer to collect 1,500
hits. This is Griffey's 10th season _ hard to believe he is 28
years old with a decade of experience. And we all know Griffey has
a long way to go to even think about Pete Rose's 4,256 career hits.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey is no Pete Rose, who Griffey called the leader of
the Big Red Machine and who said he could never be like on the
field or in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is a different sort of star. Superlative. Superior.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a different sport, like the one Michael Jordan
plays, Griffey could take over. But he is learning all the time
what this game demands of him, just as much as he continues to show
what he can give to it. And to us.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
