<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-DEATHS-SFCHRON(2TAKES) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET REPORT BLASTED CARE OF DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD W. LEMPINEN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ The Wilson administration has suppressed for
nearly a year a blistering internal study of deaths among the
developmentally disabled in community care, instead releasing a
series of reports that play down the problems.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The secret report, obtained by The Chronicle, directly
challenges the safety and the philosophy of the state policy that
has moved more than 2,000 people with severe mental retardation and
other disabilities from hospitallike institutions into community
homes sometimes ill-prepared to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   Staff competence at the community homes is ``too often
inadequate'' to meet the needs of severely disabled clients, says
the August 1997 draft report. Caretakers ``often'' did not
recognize life-threatening conditions and did not try to get
medical attention for them.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the report says, ``some deaths, while perhaps not
preventable, exhibited incompetence, neglect or mismanagement by
facility staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson's administration has defended the controversial
transfer policy and the quality of care in the community. Monday,
officials in the governor's office declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the suppressed report, prepared by a division of the
Department of Social Services, suggests that officials found grave
problems last year and then attempted to conceal them from public
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The report was never circulated among disabled advocacy groups
or lawmakers who have been collaborating on reforms. Lawyers for
the Department of Social Services stonewalled or denied requests
for its release until late last week, when they promised to provide
a copy _ with most details about the client deaths and the authors'
analysis blacked out.
</P>
<P>
   In the draft obtained by The Chronicle, the researchers reviewed
20 deaths and concluded that 16 were ``preventable or
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a 51-year-old man died after he suffered severe
burns in a scalding bathtub that was unattended. When staff members
discovered him, the report says, ``the large amounts of white
tissue floating on the surface around the client was thought to be
toilet paper instead of his skin.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a 47-year-old client died of a medication
overdose after members of the group home staff did not recognize
``pronounced overdose symptoms.'' A profoundly retarded 67-year-old
man died of cardiac arrest ``after being forced to attend a day
program while recuperating from pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle last year documented life-threatening breakdowns
in state care for those with mental retardation, cerebral palsy,
autism and other disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have since approved broad reforms to improve care and
tighten state oversight of disabled programs, and other reforms are
under consideration. Many advocates have argued, however, that the
reforms do not provide sufficient funds to hire, train and retain a
qualified staff in care facilities.
</P>
<P>
   While state officials never released the critical internal
report, they commissioned and circulated several others, all more
favorable.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Smoley, secretary of Wilson's Health and Welfare Agency,
in March heralded a $500,000 study that found no evidence of
elevated death rates. She also sponsored two public forums to
publicize the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's system of providing services to the
developmentally disabled is very sound,'' she said in a statement
released with the report, ``and is as good as any such program in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoley declined to comment on the secret mortality study done by
Social Services' Community Care Licensing Division, which also is
under her command.
</P>
<P>
   But the head of one influential family group said she was
``appalled'' that the report was not widely circulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly didn't publicize it _ they didn't say anything
about it,'' said Barbara Turner, president of the California
Association of State Hospital Parent Councils for the Retarded.
``In that regard, I think they're disingenuous, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most other states, California has long attempted to move
the developmentally disabled from institutions. The practice
accelerated sharply in 1993 after a group of parents and advocates
sued to protest poor conditions in the state hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was settled when the Wilson administration and another
branch of his Health and Welfare Agency, the Department of
Developmental Services, agreed in 1993 to discharge 2,000 state
hospital residents into community care over a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement created an unusual alliance of hard-line
disability rights advocates and the Wilson administration. The
former believe that institutional care is dehumanizing even for the
most vulnerable people; for the administration, community care
offered millions of dollars in potential savings over state
hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those who were discharged had extremely limited
intellectual function, complex medical conditions and sometimes
destructive behavior disorders. Although most completed the
transfer without incident, parents' and advocacy groups heard
scattered reports of injuries and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-1995, a team of researchers based at the University of
California at Riverside had approached developmental services
officials with preliminary but troubling findings: Death rates
appeared to be significantly higher in community care than for
comparable clients in the institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In a later study, the team found that among nearly 1,900 people
who had been moved from the state hospitals under the legal
agreement, 45 had died _ a death rate more than 50 percent higher
than the rate for similar clients still in state hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Those studies became the flash point for an acrimonious fight
among rival factions of parents, interest groups and policymakers
over the size and scope of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Despite warnings from the researchers and some family groups,
the state pressed ahead and finished the transfers 18 months ahead
of schedule. And as the controversy became a public embarrassment
for the Wilson administration, state officials often tried to cloud
the issues and cast doubt on critics who offered devastating
reports of danger, injury and death among the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we did was geared to make closure of the
institutions look like a really wonderful thing,'' says one source
familiar with operations at the Department of Developmental
Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important not to release any information or to let
people know of anything critical of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   In a copy of a handwritten 1996 memorandum obtained by The
Chronicle, then-department Director Dennis G. Amundson instructed
his staff to find ``favorable'' research on community care that
could be used to ``counter some of the . . . hoopla'' arising from
the death-rate studies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  MORE
</P>
<P>
   The department also tried to discredit the head of the research
team, UC Riverside Professor David Strauss. And department
employees who questioned the policy said they, too, had been
subject to retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo written last year for Wilson, Amundson described how
the department was orchestrating a letter-writing campaign against
The Chronicle and other media and was aiding groups that joined the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   When the department withheld important data on the system's
performance and finances, The Chronicle filed 11 requests for
information under the California Public Records Act. All were
initially stalled or refused by Amundson's department.
</P>
<P>
   The delays and denials were, in effect, state policy.
</P>
<P>
   Officials kept track of the requests for information on private
logs, some of which were obtained by The Chronicle. One column
listed how much ``actual'' time it would take to comply with a
request; the next column, under the heading ``est. time including
Fudge Factor,'' doubled or tripled the response time, adding weeks
or months to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the data and documents were eventually
released, and San Francisco Superior Court Judge Raymond Williamson
ordered the state to pay $27,336 in attorney's fees to The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Amundson's department was scrambling to quell criticism
last year, alarms were sounding in other quarters of Smoley's
Health and Welfare Agency. The licensing division of the Department
of Social Services quietly opened an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the August 1997 draft report, researchers from the
division's Rohnert Park office counted 66 deaths among more than
2,000 state hospital residents moved to community care between
April 15, 1993, and Oct. 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, they conducted a ``comprehensive'' review of the 20
deaths among clients assigned to homes regulated by the licensing
division.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers noted ``many examples . . . of exemplary
practices'' among care homes and state oversight staff. But among
the 20 who died, they found a pattern of inadequate care and
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five (of the deaths) were clearly preventable and 11 were
questionable,'' the researchers wrote. ``It appears that some
deaths were the result of staff mismanagement, incompetent staff or
gross neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the preventable deaths and eight of the questionable
deaths had ``implications of staff mismanagement'' _ medication
errors, communication breakdowns, the caretakers' ``inability to
adequately understand and provide care for high-need clients.'' In
two deaths, staff at the homes had not received legally required
emergency health training.
</P>
<P>
   While licensing officials had already disciplined the homes in
three cases, the authors said, 16 of the deaths had never been
investigated. Seven had never even been reported to the licensing
office.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond such breakdowns, though, the researchers raised strong
doubts about the philosophy of placing the most severely disabled
in community care.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires that the developmentally disabled be placed
in the ``least restrictive'' suitable setting. But according to the
study, overzealous pursuit of that goal may have resulted in forced
transfers and inadequate care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the cases reviewed indicated a high risk in community
placement,'' the researchers wrote. ``(We were) struck by the
discrepancy between the care needs of such profoundly disabled and
medically fragile clients and the level of care being offered to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly who knew of the report remained unclear Monday. Eloise
Anderson, director of social services, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Lopez, deputy director in charge of Community Care
Licensing, said some of the data gathered by the researchers were
sent to Wilson's office to support the department's proposed budget
increase. But, she said, the finding that 16 of the 20 deaths were
questionable or preventable was not included.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said she was ``not sure'' whether her division had passed
the report up the chain of command. Said Peter Castillo, an
attorney with the Department of Social Services: ``That's a
question for the Health and Welfare Agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez declined to comment on most other aspects of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Some influential advocates speculated that because the report
was such a strong repudiation of state policy, officials may have
felt compelled to suppress it.
</P>
<P>
   One advocate, who asked to remain anonymous, put it bluntly:
``He (Wilson) doesn't want negative press, especially if he's going
to run for president.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings of the secret report parallel those in another
internal state study quietly completed March 9 by the Department of
Developmental Services and released last week.
</P>
<P>
   That report counted 106 deaths among 2,641 people moved from the
state hospital from 1993 through 1997. Of those, 29 occurred within
a year of the move. Twenty resulted from homicide, automobile
accidents, medication errors and other ``possibly preventable''
causes.
</P>
<P>
   But that report, like the licensing division's mortality study,
has not been widely circulated. Instead, Smoley's agency and its
branches have been more eager to circulate reports that cast their
programs in a positive light.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Wilson administration has released several
studies on mortality among the disabled, all of which cast doubt on
the UC Riverside research:
</P>
<P>
   -- In March, a $500,000 study by Citygate Associates, a
Sacramento management consulting firm, detailed problems in the
community care system: inadequate quality assurance at community
homes; elevated use of powerful sedatives; less access to medical
care.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement released with the report, Smoley stressed the
favorable findings of Citygate's simple mortality review:
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish to note that the study found that mortality rates for
consumers in the community were not higher than those in the (state
hospitals), and were, in some cases, actually lower.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied 28 deaths and found that ``only one . .
. was indisputably related to community placement.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Two professors with another consulting firm _
Pennsylvania-based Columbus Medical Services _ found 34 deaths
among those moved from the state hospitals from April 14, 1993,
through Dec. 31, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In two similar mortality studies released in October and in
January, the authors did not review individual cases. But based on
their statistical analysis, they reached a dramatic conclusion:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is highly probable that all 34 deaths might have occurred
anyway, even if the individuals had remained (in institutions).''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus has a $1.2 million contract to provide services to the
department. The state paid $40,100 for the studies.
</P>
<P>
   -- A fourth study, conducted by two professors at the California
State University School of Business Administration, found that
death rates were 26 to 43 percent higher in community care than in
state hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the authors said, ``one must question whether this
difference (in death rates) is significant from a social
perspective, especially when one considers a greater possible
quality of life for all individuals placed in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   That study, released in June, cost the department $22,940.
</P>
<P>
   Amundson could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Allenby, his successor, stressed that the secret report
was not done by his department and that he had never heard of it.
He conceded that the array of conflicting studies would do more to
confuse the issues than to clarify them.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, he said, is that some preventable deaths
apparently occurred and that the state now must continue to repair
its system of care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were perfect, they might not have occurred,'' he said.
``I don't know if, given the fragile nature of many of our clients,
you could ever get to the point where there's zero deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to try to . . . get it as close to zero as we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Reynolds Holding contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
