<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-NYT &LR;      07-14 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL DEFENDS ACTS THE FTC SEES AS ANTICOMPETITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its first formal response to an antitrust suit
brought by the Federal Trade Commission, the Intel Corp. insisted
it was within its legal rights when it withheld some technology and
sought to retrieve other technology from three computer companies
with whom it was engaged in litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC filed an antitrust suit last month against Intel,
accusing the company of injuring three computer manufacturers,
including the Compaq Computer Corp., in an attempt to coerce them
to turn over rights to patented technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Intel is accused of withholding information about
its chips that the computer makers _ the Digital Equipment Corp.,
the Intergraph Corp. and Compaq Computer, which has acquired
Digital, _ considered crucial to developing their own products
based on Intel microprocessors. At the same time, Intel asked the
companies to return to it other technology it had given them
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In its 15-page response Monday, Intel said it did not violate
any law nor did the company constitute a monopoly in the
microprocessor industry. The case is scheduled to go before an
administrative law judge on Jan. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Molloy, a spokesman for Intel, said the company had been
in litigation with the other three companies and ``we thought it
prudent not to give our intellectual property to the people who
were suing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Molloy also said that Intel would argue that there was no
diminution to competition in the microprocessor industry because
those three companies are not principally makers of
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all systems companies,'' he said. ``Even if they left
the market there is still ample competition in the microprocessor
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
