<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-STARFISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA TO BUY SOFTWARE MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Motorola Corp. said Monday that it would
acquire a software company that has developed technology to link
wireless devices like cellular phones with a wide range of
information appliances, including personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Starfish Software Inc., was founded in 1994 by
Philippe Kahn, the Silicon Valley software entrepreneur who founded
Borland International in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn has focused Starfish on technologies that permit users of
computers and consumer appliances to easily synchronize information
like electronic calendars and datebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Growney, Motorola's president and chief operating officer,
said the Starfish software would be built into a new version of
Motorola's cellular telephones to be announced in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, which the two companies valued
at ``several hundred million'' dollars, Kahn will remain chief
executive of Starfish and will become a technology adviser to top
Motorola executives.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Motorola said it was reorganizing its
communications-related businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
