A3683 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACREPORT15-COX     07-14 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACREPORT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New desktop computer designed to turn heads
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will the iMac's iridescent blue gumdrop body be the candy that
at last lures new users to the Mac platform?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Apple Computer is hoping with the August release of
its latest consumer desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   While it has some weaknesses, the iMac looks like Apple
Computer's best chance in years to expand its market share.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the iMac was designed to draw people's attention. Its
body, like the original Mac's, includes a monitor. This one,
though, is 15 inches and displays color.
</P>
<P>
   Enough power
</P>
<P>
   The speed of the iMac's microprocessor, the chip that controls
most functions of the computer, is 233 megahertz. While not the
latest that Apple Computer offers, it's pretty darn powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac also includes a 56k bps modem, 32 megabytes of RAM, a
CD-ROM drive and a 4.6 gigabyte hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   You get all this for $1,299.
</P>
<P>
   That's the best deal Apple Computer has ever offered and is
competitive with the lower end of the PC market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, budget computer maker Micro Express offers a
computer similar to the iMac for $1,349. There are less expensive
PCs, but they have slower microprocessors and fewer features than
the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the iMac's design is to offer novice users an
all-in-one design that lets them do most things without ever
opening the hood of their computer. The key markets intended for
the iMac are the home and schools.
</P>
<P>
   In my view, the iMac has one serious, potentially debilitating
drawback. It's missing an internal floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that the floppy drive is on the way out, it
remains today the best and least expensive way to copy and move
files.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing easier than copying a homework assignment or a
document onto a floppy and sticking it in the pocket of your shirt.
</P>
<P>
   You can add an external floppy or Zip drive, but that will add
an extra $200 to the cost of buying the iMac, which lessens its
appeal as a good buy.
</P>
<P>
   While Apple says the iMac will provide fast and easy use of the
Internet, it may be exaggerating. Its 56k modem is the fastest
modem for consumer use, but 56k modems often operate at lower
speeds than the theoretical limit of 53k bps.
</P>
<P>
   And both 33k and 56k modems are too slow for enjoyable use of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most PCs offer 56k modems and buyers may be pleased with
the new iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
