<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHREPORT15-COX     07-14 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHREPORT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech Report: Laptop can accept new DVD disc
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you are selling widgets, you just want to sell a
bunch of them with a healthy profit margin. But if you are pushing
a format, then just selling 10 times more units than last year may
not be enough. You want it to be everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As the premiere issue of Business 2.0 puts it, in discussing the
emerging rules of the new economy, ``value rises exponentially with
market share'' _ at least for products that help establish a
platform or a standard. ``The more plentiful they become, the more
essential each individual unit is, a striking exception to the
economic rule that value comes from scarcity.''
</P>
<P>
   Or to think of it from the other side: If only one person owns a
fax machine, how much is it worth?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of DVD _ the digital versatile disc _ the format
doesn't completely have to replace the compact disc, which was the
first digital medium for pop culture, but it has to be in all the
places that people go for entertainment. For DVD to truly become a
roaring success, it must become the way people watch movies on
television and on computers, at home, in airports and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the challenge is like that faced by Apple Computer.
The Macintosh computer might be, as founder Steve Jobs once put it,
``insanely great,'' but it cannot survive unless a potential
purchaser knows there is plenty of Mac-friendly software and CD
games on the shelves. Apple has the advantage of already having a
large and largely loyal customer base, along with the disadvantage
of competing against the marketing machines of Microsoft, Intel and
IBM. Moreover, Mac competitors can argue that their format is as
good or better.
</P>
<P>
   DVD starts from nothing. Even worse, most consumers already own
CD players. But DVD has an inherent and critical advantage over
CDs: They can hold so much more than a CD. For instance, an entire
movie can fit on a single DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Another disadvantage Macintosh has faced is in pricing _ many
buyers will simply not pay a premium just to own an Apple. DVD too
has been more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But little by little, the manufacturers are trying to overcome
all these obstacles. More and more movie titles are available on
DVD. And DVD players will mostly be ``backward compatible'' _ that
is, capable of playing the millions of CDs that consumers have
already sunk money into. And the technology is increasingly moving
into the corners _ becoming as mobile as we increasingly expect
technology to be.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dell Computer Corp. has recently released notebook
personal computers with optional DVD drives. With that $299 option,
the Inspiron 3000 and 3200 notebooks can play full-motion video,
Dell says. Those notebooks also come with a device that lets users
play digital versatile discs and watch on their television. The
entry level version costs $2,300, including the DVD.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the Dell Inspiron, visit the company
Web site (http://www.dell.com/products/notebook/inspiron) or call
the company, 1-800-388-8542.
</P>
<P>
   True compressions
</P>
<P>
   With all the talk about cable modems, digital subscriber lines
and the like, if you are stuck at home downloading through your
28.8k bps modem, you may be forgiven for thinking that the
revolution has passed you by. No way, you sigh, that you can have
live video or piercing audio until you invest in one of those
high-priced, cutting-edge technologies for connecting to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but just perhaps you are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   RealPlayer 5.0 from RealNetworks uses data compression to let a
virtual flood of data pour through that skinny little pipeline that
runs to your PC. Reviewers writing in the summer edition of Windows
Magazine say the software gives you a pretty good shot at watching
live events, videos and hearing CD-quality music from sites like
C-SPAN, Sports Illustrated and Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a free download of the basic plug-in. For RealPlayer
Plus, it's $30. For more information, visit the Web site
(http://www.real.com).
</P>
<P>
   Better mail
</P>
<P>
   E-mail for most of us is just a tool. You want it to work, and
you probably don't care if it's super-durable, extraordinarily easy
to handle or stunningly reliable.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, you might want more from your tools if your work
_ or even your life _ depends on them. E-mail is essential to many
professionals. And even others who use e-mail for personal
messaging may be willing to pay a bit to have efficient and
reliable e-mail software. Perhaps Eudora Pro Email 4.0 from
Qualcomm is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   In its summer roundup, Windows Magazine recommends 4.0 as a
feature-rich way to organize and use e-mail. Eudora's lesser
offerings are available free, but 4.0 includes a variety of
displays and a task-bar that makes for swift and productive use.
</P>
<P>
   Eudora Pro Email 4.0 costs $59. For more information, call
Qualcomm at 1-800-238-3672 (1-800-2-EUDORA) or visit the Web site
at http://www.eudora.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
