<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SEWAGE15-COX     07-14 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SEWAGE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sewage woes seep into East Texas
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKELAND, Texas _ Missy and Bill Hanks built a path of bricks
and boards to their front door so they, their two children and a
foster child would not have to walk on dirt and grass dampened by a
leaking septic system.
</P>
<P>
   At $5,000, the septic system didn't come cheap. It leaks because
the lot is too small, the clay soil does not absorb well and it
rains a lot _ more than 50 inches a year in East Texas, a region of
small towns, big lakes and vast pine forests along the Louisiana
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who in the hell wants to live with sewage in your back yard?''
said Missy Hanks, 33, a full-time homemaker. ``We need something
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Water Development Board concluded three years ago that
sanitation was substandard in scattered parts of Sabine and Newton
counties. Many septic systems leak. Some households discharge raw
sewage through above-ground pipes to back yards or roadside
ditches. Water systems also need upgrading to meet federal and
state standards.
</P>
<P>
   The development board awarded Sabine County a $312,000 grant in
1995 to prepare engineering plans for $35 million in sewer and
water improvements to serve the Hanks family and more than 7,000
other people _ 70 percent of the county's population. Newton County
got $376,000 to plan a $30 million project to benefit 5,400
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The plans are almost complete. But now the development board's
sister agency, the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission,
has concluded that conditions in most of the two counties are only
bad enough to warrant grants covering half of the construction
cost. Without grants covering virtually all of the cost, county and
local officials say, the projects are unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the state has spent $688,000 in tax money to plan
water and sewer improvements that might never be constructed. The
Water Development Board is determined to avoid such an outcome but
concedes that some risk is inevitable in the $479 million program
to provide sewer and water services in the poorest areas of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabine and Newton projects are the largest among a
half-dozen in danger of never being built. The other stalled
projects are in Cameron, Hidalgo, Uvalde, Reeves and Bee counties.
</P>
<P>
   The delays, uncertainties and potential waste of money are
frustrating to state officials, local leaders and residents alike.
In all cases, the development board is working with local
officials, other agencies and residents in efforts to revive the
stalled projects, said Janice Cartwright, a spokeswoman for the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of sewage
</P>
<P>
   Sabine and Newton counties offer a case study in how poverty,
vague rules, bureaucratic infighting and lack of political will
have added to the challenge of providing adequate water and
sanitation systems. A daylong tour showed that it's not difficult
to find homes with leaking septic systems, or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Hanks household in Brookeland, a community with
about 170 residences wedged between the Sam Rayburn Reservoir on
the Angelina River and the Sabine National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The telltale odor of leaking sewage emanates from the ground
next to the family's blue-and-white mobile home. Black water stands
in the yard and in a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This all runs down to Sam Rayburn Reservoir. It's not even a
quarter-mile away,'' said Richard Tillery, a consultant who has
managed small water systems in the area for many years.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby neighborhood called Stumptown, Tom Donahoe, 61, a
retired Navy ordnance specialist, said his septic system routinely
overflows because the soil cannot absorb all of the wastewater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine starts flooding out here in the pasture,'' Donahoe said,
pointing out where wastewater was flowing under a public road and
down a foul-looking gully through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen miles north, in Bronson, white plastic pipes drain raw
sewage from several mobile homes to a ditch that meanders between
houses and pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that pipe right yonder? When it's hot, you catch the
odor,'' said Iverne Conner, 69, who has lived for 24 years in a
house with an exterior of rough boards on a lot bordering the
ditch.
</P>
<P>
   A question of nuisance
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, the Water Development Board runs the program to
provide aid for construction of sewer and water systems. But the
Natural Resource Conservation Commission decides whether water
supply and sanitation problems constitute ``a nuisance dangerous to
the public health and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   If the commission finds nuisance conditions, state law allows
the development board to award a grant covering up to 100 percent
of the construction cost. Nuisance findings have been issued for
scores of projects along the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   But if the conservation commission finds no nuisance, the board
may award a grant for no more than 50 percent of the cost and a
loan for the balance. Residents have to repay the loan through a
surcharge on water and sewer bills.
</P>
<P>
   For homeowners, the difference is significant. In a typical
project whose cost is substantially or completely covered by a
grant, monthly sewer and water bills total at least $15 or $20 per
household, sometimes more. But with no nuisance finding, the
monthly bill can double.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than many people in the Piney Woods of East Texas
can afford, county officials say. The average household income in
Brookeland, for example, is less than $10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In Sabine County, the conservation commission found nuisance
conditions only in two subdivisions near Pineland. Elsewhere in the
county, the commission's inspector reported seeing no failing
septic systems or raw discharges from pipes.
</P>
<P>
   After development board and county officials complained, the
commission conducted another inspection. This time, problems were
found: Of 170 homes and businesses in Brookeland, 10 were releasing
partially treated or raw sewage.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Pearson, then the executive director of the conservation
commission, concluded in a January letter to the development board
that this did not constitute a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Several other subdivisions in Sabine County did not warrant a
nuisance finding because they are resort communities on Toledo Bend
Reservoir, on the Sabine River, with residents who presumably could
afford more advanced septic systems, commission officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Newton County, the commission initially found no nuisance
conditions. After the county and the development board complained,
it conducted a second inspection and found nuisance conditions in
four subdivisions near Deweyville.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions were not identified during the first inspection
because the conservation commission had not been given maps and
other essential information on the project areas, according to
commission officials.
</P>
<P>
   Vague rules
</P>
<P>
   State law does not define what constitutes a nuisance, and the
conservation commission has no written guidelines. So the decision
boils down to a judgment call by the agency's regional offices,
officials said. Top officials in Austin typically follow regional
offices' recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of whether we find a nuisance or not is not tied to
whether we think these areas deserve help,'' said Vic Fair, manager
of the conservation commission's regional office in Beaumont.
``It's tied to whether we think there are enough failing systems to
say the community as a whole has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a prevalent, overwhelming problem'' in most of Sabine
and Newton counties, he said. ``It's something you could get a
handle on by fixing just a few systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the no-nuisance finding could be lack of
strong public and political support. Jack Leath, the Sabine County
judge, contrasted his county, with just 10,200 residents, to the
Rio Grande Valley, where a network of activists and Catholic Church
leaders has been instrumental in securing aid for water and sewer
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a nun in this county,'' Leath said.
``I can't send a nun out to plead for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duties and hopes
</P>
<P>
   The county and its residents bear some responsibility for the
sanitation problems. By law, the county is responsible for septic
system inspections, permits and enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   But the county has failed to administer the program for years,
leaving that task to the conservation commission, which cannot keep
up. As a result, violations are widespread.
</P>
<P>
   And the area's independent-minded residents haven't demonstrated
wide concern or a willingness to spend their own money on
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Leath conceded that the county has not carried out its
regulatory duties. He said county officials were reluctant to order
homeowners to spend thousands of dollars on advanced septic systems
that are prone to fail on small lots in poor soil and climate
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're telling someone to put in a $4,000 system, and they
don't have $4,'' Leath said. ``I'm not going to do something that's
going to damage the poor folks and the old folks in this county.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, projects in Pineland and Deweyville are poised to
proceed. The Water Development Board has not given up on the rest
of Sabine and Newton counties.
</P>
<P>
   The board is looking into whether other agencies, including the
Texas Department of Housing and Community Affairs and the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, might be able to offer grant money.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Norris Jr., an assistant division director for the
development board, offered a postscript on Sabine County that also
sums up the views of many government officials, activists and
residents on the broader efforts to provide safe drinking water and
proper sewage treatment to all of the state's impoverished areas:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see a quality system for people who need the
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
