<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ ATLANTA _ In Part 2 of Vanity Fair's 25,000-word
chronicle of the Reagans, correspondent Bob Colacello says, ``Mrs.
Reagan never tried to make policy. But she had a tremendous
influence.'' And other reviews of magazine features this week.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/13.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ ATLANTA _ As unlikely as it seems,
elevator-music kingpin Muzak, Footaction USA, Arista and Puff Daddy
are pooling resources to market ``Nothin' But the Hotness in '98,''
a compilation album. It's a consortium that is on the leading edge
of a trend uniting retailers, record labels and artists, and one
expected to be particularly effective in the hip-hop/rap arena.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/13.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GOODSTUFF _ Food shorts. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   NANTAHALA _ A family outing at North Carolina's Nantahala
Outdoor Center _ mountain biking, horseback riding, rafting and
shopping. (Brice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY SERIES
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-POOR _ Not everybody is riding the prosperity wave,
and even many of those managing to get by are skeptical about the
future. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Profile of somebody struggling to get by.
(DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-US _ How we have changed. Today's subject: Schools.
The 50s classrooms were far different from today's. It's not just
technology. Teaching methods have changed as well. But are we doing
any better at preparing our children for the workplace? According
to our poll, not many of us think so. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE/ENVIRONMENTAL (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SEWAGE _ BROOKELAND, Texas _ The Texas Water Development
Board concluded three years ago that sanitation was substandard in
scattered parts of Sabine and Newton counties. Many septic systems
leak. Some households discharge raw sewage through above-ground
pipes to back yards or roadside ditches. Water systems also need
upgrading to meet federal and state standards. ``Who in the hell
wants to live with sewage in your back yard?'' said Missy Hanks,
33, a full-time homemaker. ``We need something done.'' (Haurwitz,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY (also in f category)
</P>
<P>
   JUST-FOR-FUN _ This column no longer runs.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ Let's say you and your family are heading off on a
dream vacation next week. After years of excuses, you've decided to
spend what a good used Toyota would cost to go to Europe. That's
where the World Wide Web can come in handy. You'll find several
sites that can cushion the culture shock of an overseas vacation.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   MACREPORT _ Will the iMac's iridescent blue gumdrop body be the
candy that at last lures new users to the Mac platform? That's what
Apple Computer is hoping with the August release of its latest
consumer desktop computer. While it has some weaknesses, the iMac
looks like Apple Computer's best chance in years to expand its
market share. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS-TECHSUPPORT _ Why can't I get this scanner to work?
Where is that mouse cursor? What's wrong with this danged thing?
Those are just a few of the questions Windows 98 users are asking
that can be reproduced in a family newspaper. Two weeks after
launching the latest upgrade to the world's most popular operating
system, the customer support people are busy. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ ATLANTA _ In the case of DVD _ the digital
versatile disc _ the format doesn't completely have to replace the
compact disc, but it has to be in all the places that people go for
entertainment. For DVD to truly become a roaring success, it must
become the way people watch movies on television and on computers,
at home, in airports and hotels. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ I'm indebted to Bob Wildau for a set of
questions that are both interesting and within my ability to
answer, concerning telecommunications and graphics. ``I am about to
move to a home office,'' he reports, ``and question whether it's
worth going from a 33k bps modem to a 56k bps modem when the V.90
standard isn't yet standard and my phone line seems so poor?''
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ For the uninformed, Barbra Streisand,
wearing (what else?) a Donna Karan wedding dress, tied the knot
last week with longtime boyfriend Brolin. If, by chance, your
invitation got lost in the mail or your helicopter was in the shop
that day, you can find plenty of Barbra wedding news and info on
the Web. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ About a week ago, I set off on my great cable
adventure. What happened has very little to do with cable TV or the
companies that provide it. I could have just as easily been trying
to contact an insurance company or any other big business that uses
an automated voice mail system. Instead, what I found reminded me
of the price of technology, the price that doesn't appear on the
bill. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. (l, f)
</P>
