<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FLORIDA-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRES? WHAT FIRES? FOR FLORIDA TOURISM IT'S BUSINESS AS USUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Visitors to the Sunshine State this summer are being
greeted by a new slogan: ``Florida in Flames.'' Since Memorial Day,
thousands of wildfires have burned about a half million acres of
mostly forest land and threatened some communities. But even with
intermittent road closures and evacuations of residents, and
cancellation of Fourth of July events in some areas, it's been
business as usual at most attractions, parks and beaches, state
tourism officials said _ even under a blanket of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Everglades National Park in southern Florida, Miami-Dade County
beaches and Walt Disney World in Orlando reported no commercial
impact from the blazes as of early July, even when some had
operated under hazy skies from distant fires.
</P>
<P>
   Visit Florida, the agency that promotes tourism in the state,
said most hotels and attractions throughout Florida reported no
drop in attendance or cancellations although it was still too early
to tell how the continuing fires fed by the worst drought
conditions here in 50 years would undermine summer travel.
</P>
<P>
   The worst disruptions were in the northeast, where fires in
early July caused the evacuation of more than 100,000 residents in
Brevard, Volusia and Flagler counties and shut 140 miles of
Interstate 95, from Titusville east of Orlando to Jacksonville near
the Georgia border. The crisis lasted less than a week, but it came
during the peak tourist season for the northern portion of Florida.
Of 47 million visitors to Florida last year, Visit Florida figures
show, 12 million came between the months of April and June and
another 11 million visited between July and September.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke and the fire threat around the Fourth of July weekend shut
down attractions like the Fort Matanzas National Monument south of
St. Augustine and kept visitors away from those that remained open,
like the Canaveral National Seashore and the Kennedy Space Center.
It also interfered with fishing, hunting, camping and hiking at
piers and wilderness recreation areas and ruined the holiday
business for cities like Daytona Beach, which was forced to
postpone until Oct. 17 the Pepsi 400 Nascar Winston Cup race that
was expected to draw about 150,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   With a statewide ban on individual fireworks in effect and
firefighters so busy few were available to staff public displays,
Disney World canceled its Fourth of July fireworks show.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the fires have caused no deaths and less damage than
hurricanes or tornadoes. A persistent worry for both residents and
visitors, however, has been the haze that could be seen and smelled
from miles away throughout most of the state at times. It has
reduced visibility on roads, caused mild conditions such as
headaches, nausea and throat and eye irritation, and created more
serious problems for sensitive segments of the population such as
the elderly and children and those with heart disease and
respiratory ailments like asthma.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials have advised the most susceptible people,
and all residents in areas where smoke is heavy, to stay indoors as
much as possible, preferably in air-conditioned rooms. Those with
specific concerns have also been advised to check with their county
health departments.
</P>
<P>
   While people should heed shortness of breath and similar
warnings as signs to stay indoors, the officials said that exposure
to smoke does not pose a serious health risk to the general public.
``Unless somebody has severe lung compromise, I don't think that
should be an issue,'' said Dr. Eric Handler, the Florida Department
of Health's deputy secretary for children's medical services. ``I
wouldn't be fearful about coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the worst fires have raged across the central and
northern parts of Florida, most of the state has had to contend
with scattered fires sparked by lightning strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Many affected areas are operating normally again, but the fire
hazard has been so fluid, with the weather, winds, air quality and
other variables constantly changing, that state officials have
provided toll-free numbers for information about specific
destinations rather than issuing statewide advisories or
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists can call a 24-hour toll-free line, (888) 735-2872, for
reports and the telephone numbers of the visitor bureau or chamber
of commerce in the area they want to visit. For information about
road closings and detours, call the Florida Department of
Transportation at (800) 342-3557.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
