<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Beatles Tours &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you know of Beatles tours in London and Liverpool? _ Sarah
M. Loman, Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are enough Beatles sites and tours in both cities to
keep you busy for days.
</P>
<P>
   In London _ where Abbey Road Studios served as a recording base
for Paul McCartney, John Lennon, Ringo Starr and George Harrison _
the Original London Walks company offers several Beatles walking
tours. The 2-hour-and-45-minute Beatles Magical Mystery Tour, for
instance, is offered on Sunday and Thursday at 11 a.m. and
Wednesday at 2 p.m. It starts at the Tottenham Court Road subway
station and visits Abbey Road Studios, Savile Row where the Beatles
held a rooftop ``Let It Be'' concert in 1969, and Paul McCartney's
offices on Soho Square. The walk of about two miles costs $7.50.
Information: (44-171) 624 3978.
</P>
<P>
   A minibus tour called Beatles Sites and Rock n' Roll London
departs from outside London's Hard Rock Cafe on Old Park Lane at 2
p.m. on Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday and costs $25. In addition
to the Beatles' sites mentioned above, it takes in places connected
with other rock stars such as Elton John, Jimi Hendrix and Bob
Marley. Information: (44-181) 566 5312.
</P>
<P>
   For self-guided tours, you can pick up a free Rock and Pop Map
at Rock Circus, a branch of Madame Tussauds in Piccadilly Circus.
</P>
<P>
   In Liverpool, a two-hour Magical Mystery Tour is offered aboard
a copy of the vivid blue and yellow bus featured in the 1967 film
of the same name. Included on the itinerary are the Beatles'
childhood homes, their schools, Penny Lane, Strawberry Field and
the Cavern Club where they performed in the early '60s. The tour
runs daily at 2:20 p.m. from the Merseyside Welcome Center at the
Albert Dock. An additional tour runs in July and August on Saturday
at 11:50 a.m. The cost is $15. Information: (44-151) 709 3285.
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles Story, on Albert Dock in the basement of the
Britannia Pavilion, is an exhibition that uses music, film footage
of performances, photographs and a copy of the Cavern Club to
present a comprehensive history of the group. Open daily from 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is $11. Phone (44-151) 709 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Cavern City Tours organizes an annual International Beatles
Festival; this year it runs from Aug. 26 to Sept. 1. Events include
live music by Beatles lookalike bands, an auction and a garden
party in Straw-berry Field. Hotel packages for the festival start
at $125 for two nights. Information: (44-151) 236 9091, fax
(44-151) 236 8081. The company also publishes three maps: Discover
Lennon's Liverpool; Discover Beatles Liverpool and Discover Beatles
London. These can be ordered from the above number by mail; the
cost, including shipping, is $3.40.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Southern California Pass &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've heard there is a combination pass for Universal Studios
and other tourist attractions in southern California. Can you give
details? _ Maryanne Myers, East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A.This year, Universal Studios near Los Angeles joined with Sea
World in San Diego to offer a discounted admission package that
provides unlimited entry into the two parks for 14 consecutive
days. The package, known as the Southern California Value Pass,
entitles guests to all of the roller coaster rides and sea mammal
spectacles they want. The cost is $68.95 for adults, $50.95 for
children. Normally the general one-day admission cost for adults is
$38 for adults at Universal Studios, and $34.95 at Sea World, so
the saving is substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios is also offering the Celebrity Annual Pass,
which entitles guests to unlimited entry, free daytime parking,
invitations to special events, discounts on some merchandise and
reduced admission into such other California attractions as Knotts
Berry Farm, the Movieland Wax Museum, the Santa Cruz Boardwalk, and
Winchester Mystery House. The pass costs $69, $59 for senior
citizens and children. For information: (818) 622-3801.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Christmas in Capri &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A friend and I are planning to travel to Capri and the Amalfi
Coast between Christmas and New Year's. We would like information
on special events, and to know whether Pompeii, Herculaneum and
Paestum will be open. _ Beverly Elliott, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A. The 19-mile-long Amalfi coast and the island of Capri are
year-round tourist meccas. During the Christmas season, the mild
weather and holiday celebrations attract many Italian and foreign
tourists as well.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few annual events that have become part of the local
tradition, but specifics won't be released until late fall.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Eve in the town of Amalfi is marked by the ``descent
of the comet,'' in which a torch-lighted sculpture of metal and
wood is reeled down a steel wire from the top of Mount Cabar to St.
Andrew's Cathedral just before midnight Mass. The cathedral, which
dates back to medieval times, also plays host to choral concerts
during the week between Christmas and New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve celebrations begin on the morning of the 31st,
when a band parades through the streets playing typical Neapolitan
instruments: tambourines, rattles and drums of various kinds.
Midnight is marked by an open-air festival in the central piazza
where fireworks are set off against the backdrop of the Gulf of
Salerno. On New Year's Day, the ``banda del din din,'' strolls
through the town clanging on triangles. For more information call
the local tourist bureau at (39-089) 871107.
</P>
<P>
   Capri also plans a number of Christmas and New Year's
activities, including classical and Italian pop concerts, as well
as song and dance performances by folkloric groups. A large stage
is set up in the town of Capri's main piazza, which is decorated
with Christmas trees and serves as the focal point for the week's
events. Classical music concerts are held in the church of Santa
Stefano, and in the church of Santa Teresa, elaborate Nativity
scenes are set up as part of a creche-making competition. A jb band
playing Latino and disco rings in the New Year on the main piazza.
For information call the Capri Tourist Bureau at (39-081) 8370686.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the archeological sites at Pompeii, Herculaneum and
Paestum will all be open from 9 to 2 during that period, except for
Christmas and New Year's Day. Peastum is also closed the first and
third Mondays of the month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
