<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, July 14, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLLIDER-TOWN (Waxahachie, Texas) _ Common sense would suggest
the economy of this sleepy North Texas town would be as buried and
lifeless as the empty tunnels of the ill-fated superconducting
super collider that Congress killed five years ago. But today the
town is thriving. By ROY BRAGG.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-EXECUTE (San Francisco) _ Smiling broadly and professing
his innocence to the end, Thomas M. Thompson died in San Quentin's
death chamber early Tuesday for a 17-year-old rape and murder. He
was the fifth convict to be executed by California since the death
penalty was resumed there six years ago. By LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-AMBASSADOR (Mexico City) _ New U.S. Ambassador to Mexico
Jeffrey Davidow is scheduled to arrive here to begin working late
next week, officials in Washington confirmed. His arrival will end
an often-rocky interval of more than a year without a U.S.
ambassador to the country many consider the United States' most
important foreign policy concern. By PHILIP TRUE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-MACHINES (San Francisco) _ An industry in despair is the
theme at this year's Semicon West show, the largest annual
gathering of semiconductor-equipment makers. The companies that
make the machines that make the chips _ which become the brains of
computers, cell phones and a host of other electronic products _
are grappling with the worst industry slump in a decade. By WENDY
TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIKE-COP (Ballston Spa, N.Y.) _ Police Officer Michael J.
DeMartino loved riding his rust-colored Schwinn 10-speed while
growing up. He never dreamed he would have a career that enables
him to patrol the village on a black-and-gray 18-speed Smith &AMP;
Wesson mountain bike. By LINDA TRISCHITTA.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S-INN (Boerne, Texas) _ The Children's Inn located on
the grounds of the Benedictine monastery here was started by a
couple of women for kids with dysfunctional families, emotional
problems or serious medical conditions. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Now that Brit social climber Tina
Brown is no longer editor of the New Yorker, can the magazine
please return to American spellings and usages? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-FOUNDATION (San Francisco) _ I doubt people in Japan or its
suffering East Asian sisters complain today when the Asia
Foundation gives money away for good works _ about 1,000 small
grants each year to Asian nations and organizations, without
ostensible Cold War-style intentions. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD-SAFETY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Lead remains in some calcium
supplements, taken by more than 50 percent of American women during
pregnancy and by a third of American households, according to a
1997 report by the Natural Resources Defense Council in California.
There are no federal laws requiring calcium supplements to be
lead-free. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
</TEXT>
