<HEADER>
A3815 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SHARK-NAT     07-14 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SHARK-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  MAINE'S SHARKS IN GREAT DANGER
</P>
<P>
   By Kyra Leasure
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 13 -- Maine is one of eight states that is
failing to protect shark populations in its waters, according to a
report issued by an environmental coalition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shark populations in the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico are
decreasing at alarming rates, some as much as 85 percent over the
last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Within three miles of Maine's shoreline -- beyond which are
federal waters -- the state's fishers brought in 1.07 million
pounds of shark in 1996, mostly spiny dogfish, Ocean Wildlife
Campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   The group, a Washington-based coalition of environmentalists
such as the National Audubon Society, credited Maine with passing
groundfish regulations that reduced the number of dogfish caught,
but warned that the shark was still being vastly overfished.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS)
instituted a fishery management plan to prevent overfishing of
sharks in federal waters of the Atlantic and Gulf. However, as
sharks move in and out of these protected waters they are
increasingly falling prey to overfishing in state waters where
federal rules don't apply, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   They are also threatened by a growing market for shark fin soup,
which has led to an increase in finning -- a practice where the
fins are cut off of live sharks and then the wounded shark is
dumped back into the water and left to die, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most alarming is the absence of monitoring of estuaries
and bays which are critical for the bearing and nurturing of young
sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juvenile mortality must be reduced to speed the recovery of
large coastal sharks,'' said Mary Camhi, staff scientist at the
National Audubon Society's Living Oceans Program. ``The best way to
do this is to reduce fishing in nursery grounds, which primarily
occurs in state waters.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Sen. Jill Goldthwait, I-5th, defended Maine's stance
on shark fishing, saying the vast majority of sharks are far off
the coast and in federal waters, under the jurisdiction of the
NMFS.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature is much more concerned with the fate of lobster,
scallop, eel and groundfish fisheries, multi-million-dollar
industries for Maine's fishers, Goldthwait said.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say Maine, with the seventh largest commercial shark
fishery of any Atlantic or Gulf Coast state, isn't aware of the
damage its fishers are causing to the shark population. The dogfish
fishery does fall within state boundaries and accounted for 80
percent of all sharks hauled in by Maine fishers from 1990 through
1995.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, NMFS declared spiny dogfish overfished but there is
still no management of this fishery.
</P>
<P>
   ``States must now act to implement the policies that are vital
to the recovery of sharks,'' said David Wilmot, director of the
Ocean Wildlife Campaign. ``Strong Federal regulations are extremely
important, but they will not be effective unless the states also do
their part.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Audubon Society recommends that Maine adopt federal
regulations in state waters, require all state commercial shark
fishers to hold federal permits, ban finning of all sharks and
improve species-specific identification and reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under current management measures, it is highly probable that
the populations will continue to decline below their already
critically low levels of abundance. Some results suggest that even
if all fishing of large coastal sharks were to cease, recovery
could take decades,'' said Ellen Pikitch, director of the Wildlife
Conservation Society.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
