<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-14 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOLLY GOOD SHOW: KISS GOOD-BYE TO THE NEW YORKER'S `OLDE
ENGLISHE' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now that Brit social climber Tina Brown is no
longer editor of the New Yorker, can the magazine please return to
American spellings and usages?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't mind the celebrity photographs, the in-depth O.J.
coverage or the obscenities (in the cartoons too, egad) nearly as
much as having to labor through ``labour'' and ``honour'' and
references to dead mobsters being put in the ``boots'' of
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Anglicization of the New Yorker stopped short of rewriting
Roger Angell's baseball pieces and turning batters into
``batsmen.'' It wouldn't be cricket, and thank God didn't become
cricket.
</P>
<P>
   The one victory for the American language during the reign of
Queen Tina at the New Yorker came when she started running Monica
Lewinsky articles every week. The magazine had been spelling
``intern'' as ``interne,'' in the English fashion. But Monica
proved more powerful than Tina, and soon the magazine dropped the
E, and adopted the world-famous six-letter word ``intern.''
</P>
<P>
   As in English, not Olde Englishe. As in New York, not York.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Something has gone very wrong with the Republican Party. I miss
the good, reasonable old days of Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few months before congressional elections, something is
happening to distract Republicans from the concerns of average
Americans who think Congress should apply itself to education,
Social Security, health care, crime and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The following is the current platform of the Republican Party,
as near as I can figure from recent mouth-flapping in Washington:
The Republican Party is running against gays and lesbians. They're
also running against flag-burners, a group that doesn't exist
outside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The pinks, lavenders and red-white-and-blue-blackeners have
replaced the reds as America's boogeypersons.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party not only is against abortion, but now many
Republicans have come out against the birth control pill.
</P>
<P>
   This won't go over well with voters, who already need three jobs
to take care of the kids they have. Besides, if Republicans get rid
of the Pill, more women will get abortions and more gays will be
born.
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco, and I know what it's like to live without
a Republican Party. I want the Republican Party to survive as a
party that believes in individual liberty and responsibility, not
as the mullah of all parties.
</P>
<P>
   Next it'll be mandatory chains to keep women in the kitchen, and
I suppose if women, gays or population growth gets out of line,
that's where the NRA comes in. It's hard to find any other logic in
the GOP X-Files.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lately there has been plenty of idiocy among Democrats and
liberals, too. Let's review:
</P>
<P>
   In Washington last week, President Clinton inhaled deeply, and
launched a billion-dollar ad campaign to teach kids that drugs are
bad. The ads must be a gas to watch stoned, the way we watched
``Reefer Madness.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a stupid ad campaign. This is your brain on a stupid ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you know it? I came out for Mayor Willie Brown's
visionary plan to provide universal health care for all of San
Francisco's workers and poor people, and some of Brown's biggest
pals came out against it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a union, too, the supposedly progressive Service
Employees International Union. Yes, a union doesn't want to pool
its health money with federal and state dollars to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to solidarity? It'll be wall-to-wall solidarity in
the emergency room, as the uninsured keep crowding in to use the
only medical services they can get, the ones that cost taxpayers
the most.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco last week, gay leaders complained that the
police were discriminatory by busting only men for having sex in
bus station restrooms. Never mind that women don't do such things.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Why do gays have sex in public restrooms in San
Francisco? This is a city where anything goes except going to the
bathroom, because there aren't enough. Heck, if it's illicit sex
you want, you can move to South Carolina, and suffer real
oppression, instead of making it up.
</P>
<P>
   In Berkeley last week, huggy liberals spoke out against cops
busting the street kids who sit on Telegraph Avenue sidewalks all
day, making messes and bothering people. At the same time in
Berkeley, there is a controversy over whether public nudity should
be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise: All sidewalk sitters must be naked, and all
naked people must sit on the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   That'll fix all their bony butts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
