</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-FOUNDATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN FLU MAY EVENTUALLY SPREAD WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In 1976, a Communist member of the Japanese Diet
accused the San Francisco-based Asia Foundation of being a CIA
front. Executives at the foundation denied the charge, but anyone
who did the research would have found that the nonprofit
organization acknowledged using CIA funds in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Since then things have changed in every respect. In particular,
I doubt anyone in Japan or its suffering Asian sisters complain
today when the foundation gives money away for good works _ about
1,000 small grants each year to Asian nations and organizations,
without ostensible Cold War-style intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that ended 31 years ago, period,'' said William Fuller,
president of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say there aren't definite political designs,
direct and indirect. For example, Fuller said, the foundation
funded the first empirical look at corruption in Thailand, a
project at Chula Longkorn University in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now one of the professors has become an absolute advocate for
reform,'' Fuller said. ``He sees what has happened, as a result of
the financial crisis, as a wonderful opportunity to move on the
anti-corruption front. This will involve changes in the law, the
development of watchdog groups and the development of media
reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar foundation-funded program run by an aptly named group,
Transparency International Bangladesh, is studying corruption in
the judiciary, public works agencies and other governmental bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In Manila, the foundation is backing a group called Court Watch,
which monitors judges.
</P>
<P>
   Other foundation-funded efforts include programs intended to
empower women by helping them acquire income-generating skills and
teaching them how to finance and run political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   That project is important, Fuller said, because despite the
existence of a few women with political power _ such as former
Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto in Pakistan and Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga _ 99 percent of Asia's political
machinery is controlled by men.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Fuller said, the Asian men and women behind
reform efforts would have been thrown into jail. Today, the
necessity for change has made local initiatives politically
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if the foundation was stymied by fundamentalists.
Indonesia, a nation of 200 million, is chiefly Islamic. Fuller said
it was impossible to generalize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia is very diverse. There are moderate groups
attempting to build strong bridges between faiths,'' Fuller said.
``For example, Muslims working with Christians and other
non-Muslims on food shortages.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller believes the central issue facing Asia today _ the
economic crisis _ could take more than five years to play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things don't happen quickly,'' he said. ``You can say
you'll eliminate cronyism, but patterns of behavior take a long
time to change. Secondly, there's the problem of restoring consumer
confidence. There's not going to be heavy-duty money coming in to
match the outflows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese had something like $20 billion in business
activity in Indonesia, assets built up over 20 years. It just
evaporated.''
</P>
<P>
   California has fashioned itself as a big trading partner of
Pacific Rim nations. I asked Fuller if he thought the state would
feel any pain as a consequence of the Asian economic flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a sneeze in Indonesia, it's not entirely clear.
But a sneeze in Japan or China? I'd be very worried.''
</P>
<P>
   It's reasonable to assume everything we buy that's made in Asia
will cost less, he said. This could continue for some time, giving
us a false sense of security. Later on, however, we'll see Asian
markets for California products dry up. Our high tech goods,
timber, fruits, vegetables, movies and CDs may go begging.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Fuller said, this state is certain to catch the
same deadly strain of flu that began infecting Asia a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Winokur is a reporter for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
