<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3932 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAD-SAFETY-HNS &LR;      07-14 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAD-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SHOULD GET THE LEAD OUT OF CALCIUM SUPPLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I thought I was doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Like many women concerned about the potential for osteoporosis,
I try to make sure I get enough calcium. I drink fat-free milk, buy
orange juice fortified with calcium and take daily calcium
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I learned that my supplement, a brand made from oyster
shells, may also contain lead, a well-known health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Lead is a metal found naturally in the environment, in the food
we eat, the air we breathe and sometimes in the water we drink. At
high levels, it can cause high blood pressure, headaches, digestive
problems and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Small children and fetuses are especially vulnerable because
lead can damage the central nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   Federal laws passed in the 1970s prohibited the use of lead in
gasoline and paint, and have helped lessen our daily exposure to
this toxin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet lead remains in some calcium supplements, taken by more than
50 percent of American women during pregnancy and by a third of
American households, according to a 1997 report by the Natural
Resources Defense Council in California.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike food or medicine, there are no federal laws
requiring calcium supplements to be lead-free.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural Resources Defense Council is still waiting to hear
back from the Food and Drug Administration on a petition to
establish a national standard limiting the amount of lead in
supplements and antacids to no more than 0.5 micrograms per daily
dosage, a negligible amount.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts aren't advising people to stop taking supplements
but to choose those that have the lowest levels of lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For consumers who want to be cautious, there are a variety of
options out there,'' said Dr. Gina Solomon, the council's senior
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   In lab tests, the council cited several supplements that are
virtually lead-free.
</P>
<P>
   They include: TUMS 500 Calcium Supplement, Chewable; Posture D
High Potency Calcium Supplement with Vitamin D; Children's Mylanta
Chewable Antacid Fruit Punch and Bubble Gum flavors; and Children's
Mylanta Liquid Antacid in the same flavors.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about calcium, you can visit the Natural
Resrouces Defense Council's Web site at
http://www.nrdc.org/worldview/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find lead information on the label, but there are a
few guidelines to follow in selecting a brand. I've learned that
``natural sources'' of calcium aren't always better, though often
the cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is best to avoid calcium from bone meal, dolomite or
unrefined oyster shells, as these may contain lead or other toxic
metals,'' according to the National Osteoporosis Foundation in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fallon, a pharmacist in Clifton Park, N.Y., agrees. He
doesn't sell oyster shell because he knows most consumers aren't
``really aware of the differences in calcium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's the risk? It's not as high as lead paint, for example.
But since we're already exposed to lead in our environment, the
council argues that we should avoid any unnecessary exposure in our
supplements, no matter how minute, since the technology is
available to remove that lead.
</P>
<P>
   Progress is being made. As a result of a lawsuit filed by the
council, Leiner Health Products Group, the nation's largest
manufacturer of calcium supplements, such as ``Your Life'' brand,
agreed to remove almost all lead from its calcium, and other
manufacturers are following suit.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still trying to do the right thing. But I don't want to
invite one health risk while trying to offset another. If lead-free
is good enough for my car, it's good enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood is a health writer for the Albany Times Union, P.O.
Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABYRINTH-MYSTIQUE-AR     07-14 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABYRINTH-MYSTIQUE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JOURNEYS TO THE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Mass. _ ``When I put my labyrinth in a few years ago my
family thought I was absolutely mad,'' says Elizabeth Cherniack.
</P>
<P>
   But she managed to win them over. ``Last Christmas we all walked
it together and had a group hug in the center,'' says the mother of
three and grandmother of one. ``Labyrinths are trendy now.''
</P>
<P>
   Once almost forgotten in the Western world, the labyrinth has
been rediscovered in recent years and is now hailed as a powerful
spiritual and personal transformation tool by traditional
churchgoers and ardent new agers alike. Older than history,
labyrinths _ winding designs with a single and usually circling
path _ are found in cultures as diverse as Native American, ancient
Crete, and Medieval Europe. Also, in some form, in most major
religious traditions.
</P>
<P>
   While it may look rather odd to the uninitiated, enthusiasts say
going around in circles can straighten you out _ or at least make
you think a bit more clearly. The theory is that the act of
simultaneously meditating or praying while walking a circuitous
path in concentric circles engages both hemispheres of the brain to
produce a sense of calmness and a feeling of well-being that, among
other things, makes decisions easier.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows precisely how many labyrinths there are in
Massachusetts or anywhere else in the country. However,
knowledgeable local labyrinthians estimate that there are probably
about 30 accessible to the public in the eastern part of the state
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labyrinths are more than just a fad, this is a time when
people need energy and to center themselves and they give a sense
of direction,'' says Marty Cain of Newport, N.H., an artist who in
the past half-dozen years has designed more than 60 labyrinths in
this country and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Cherniack say she uses her labyrinth daily year-round,
regardless of weather. ``Walking a labyrinth is centering and gives
me a sense of proportion,'' she says; ``it's a sort of
mini-pilgrimage.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mazes, which are deliberately confusing and very easy to
get lost in, a labyrinth has no dead ends or tricky turns. There is
only one path, and it always leads to the center and back out again
but by a twisting route. Maze paths are lined with high walls or
hedges that obstruct the view, but a labyrinth is open and you can
always see where you're going, although it's not easy to tell
exactly how you'll get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``A labyrinth is a lot like life, you think you're getting to
the center of things and then you start to move away,'' says Susan
Burgess, a member of St. Andrew's Episcopal Church in Marblehead.
When Burgess and other members of the congregation laid out a
labyrinth in the memorial garden on the church lawn in 1993, they
thought they were creating a quiet place for solitary meditation.
That's not exactly what they got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to chase my 5-year-old grandson down it and then we sit
in the center and talk,'' says Sarah Lincoln Harrison, one of the
church volunteers who traced the labyrinth's path with stones
gathered from the nearby seashore. Many others at St. Andrew's have
also found their own satisfying, individual ways of going around in
circles.
</P>
<P>
   Some churchgoers make a point of walking the labyrinth before or
after services, for instance, while kids just let out of Sunday
school invariably run it as fast as they can. Participants in
12-step programs and yoga classes that meet at St. Andrew's usually
walk slowly and meditatively.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the church's blessing, all are welcome to go through
the labyrinth at whatever pace they want whenever the spirit moves
them. ``We haven't had any miracles,'' says church member Robert
Smythe, ``but a lot of people say they went into the labyrinth with
a problem and came out with a solution.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Two traditions  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although they can be any size, labyrinths are typically about 30
or 40 feet across and fit easily into parks and gardens, the naves
of churches, and the floors of public buildings. They can be
temporary or permanent, and are delineated in all sorts of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Cain, who specializes in public art, has traced temporary
labyrinths with beds of flowers, turkey feathers, and white paint
on grassy lawns but also uses permanent materials such as
fieldstones, brick, and chunks of quartz. A dowser, Cain says she
uses whatever appropriate materials are at hand and places her
labyrinths where _ by new age standards _ they belong. ``I just ask
the earth what she wants,''she says, seriously.
</P>
<P>
   For outdoor labyrinths, such as the one that she designed at St.
Andrew's, Cain favors the classic seven-circle form found in
ancient ruins at Cretan and Celtic sites, which is also the one
preferred by most new agers. Rivaling that design in popularity,
however, and more often used indoors, is an 11-circle labyrinth
based on the one in the nave of 13th-century Chartres cathedral in
France. Inlaid in the stone floor, the 42-square-foot Chartres
labyrinth _ which represents the meandering path of a pilgrim going
to Jerusalem _ has the same dimensions and proportions as the
cathedral's famous rose window.
</P>
<P>
   Although you can't get lost in a labyrinth, they can be hard to
find, even ones that welcome the public. For instance, there is an
11-circle Chartres-style labyrinth in St. Paul's Episcopal
Cathedral on Tremont Street in downtown Boston _ painted on the
floor of a lower-level meeting hall that is often covered with
chairs. The labyrinth is reserved exclusively for meditative
walking Mondays from 4 to 6 p.m. and Fridays noon to 2 p.m. but can
also be visited at other times _ provided the hall isn't in use.
</P>
<P>
   Susan McNeill of Leominster has marked out a 20-foot-wide Cretan
labyrinth in purple spray paint on the driveway of her home on West
Street and lets anyone who passes by use it if they want. ``I get
about 10 people a day,'' she says. ``Labyrinths can heal us and
they can heal the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, many people consider their labyrinths to be essentially
private places, an extension of home and the family circle. A
dowser and avid gardener, Cherniack picked an inconspicuous site at
the bottom of her garden, away from the street and out of sight of
nearby houses. ``It's also where two energy lines cross,'' she
says.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
A spiritual path
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual the labyrinth may be, but current interest in it has
also created a sort of mini-labyrinth industry. Cain, for instance,
charges $500 plus expenses to design a labyrinth.
</P>
<P>
   The founding mother of the labyrinth movement in America is the
Reverend Lauren Artress of Grace Episcopal Cathedral in San
Francisco, author of ``Walking a Sacred Path _ Rediscovering the
Labyrinth as a Sacred Tool.'' The nonprofit Veriditas Ministry that
Artress founded gives workshops on designing and using labyrinths
and trains facilitators to lead labyrinth meditation walks.
Veriditas also sells do-it-yourself design kits for $125 and
Chartres-size portable three-piece canvas labyrinths, priced at
$3,575.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Artress is organizing a ``global labyrinth
network,'' composed of people around the world who instead of
hoisting glasses of champagne at midnight on New Year's Eve 2000
will walk labyrinths as a gesture of unity with all life on the
planet. The Veriditas Web site (www.gracecathedral.org) lists more
than 100 labyrinths now in the network.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Keeler of Harwich, a Veriditas facilitator who is also a
registered and holistic nurse, has led labyrinth meditations for
hospice patients, senior citizens, community organizations,
schoolchildren, and even corporate executives. ``A labyrinth is
nonhierarchal and provides space for teamwork and community, and
the effect can be similar to that of ropes courses and other
confidence-building programs that executives often go through,''
she says, ``and it's about as metaphorical as you can get for the
way we go along life's path with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   As a seminar project, a group of students at the Cape Cod
Lighthouse Charter School in Orleans recently built an outdoor
labyrinth under Keeler's direction, its path lined with stones and
quahog shells picked up on the beaches of Pleasant Bay. ``It's in a
valley surrounded by woods,'' Keeler says, ``and the entrance faces
the spot where the sun will rise at the summer solstice.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeler says she frequently took the labyrinth-project kids to
the shore, drew a seven-circle design on the sand, and let them
play. It was fun, she says, but the children also seemed to
instinctively understand the labyrinth's ancient message. She
recalls the time when one 12-year-old, after running the labyrinth,
turned to her and remarked thoughtfully: ``We've been taught that a
straight line is the shortest distance between two points, but
maybe it isn't always the wisest choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
