<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW GRADES IN EDUCATION FOR BAY STATE POLITICIANS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The embarrassment of Massachusetts does not lie in
the fact that one crop of prospective schoolteachers did terribly
on some tests recently.
</P>
<P>
   The real embarrassment is that a state once known for its
maturity and vision is worth studying today for the way its
politicians play games with serious topics.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the test scores were made public, Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci has actually proposed legislation of which
two of the main components are already law.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the same acting governor who just three years ago
was joined with his predecessor, Bill Weld, in a high-profile
effort to get Massachusetts out of the teacher certification
business altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In the Legislature, meanwhile, the leadership from the House has
been virtually mute. And from the Senate has come a proposal so
tangential and fiscally questionable (signing bonuses of $20,000
for 250 new teachers a year) as to border on the humorous.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, any college kid watching this eruption of
cheap politics would be forgiven if he shipped his teaching
applications to states where teacher-bashing and education politics
are less a public sport. If the nonleadership at the highest levels
is too much even for the state's education commissioner _ and it
was _ how is someone with the commendable desire to teach school
supposed to feel?
</P>
<P>
   On first thought, perhaps House Speaker Tom Finneran should get
some credit for having the least to say or propose about this. The
harm done by doing nothing is less than that done by some of the
more headline-catching players.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, state Senate President Tom Birmingham at
least stayed on the fringes of activity by suggesting that with
$100 million in a trust fund, the interest could pay $20,000 to 250
top college students willing to become teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In a state of the Commonwealth's size, educators may have
difficulty imagining what the impact would be on hundreds of
thousands of kids from 250 supposedly ``elite'' new teachers each
year. And the rest of us may not understand how some undisclosed
selection criteria can justify treating those 250 better than
others in the top fourth of college seniors.
</P>
<P>
   But given the furious competition for the highest-achieving
graduates from the private sector, and given the likelihood that
some form of signing bonus can play a role in avoiding a massive
teacher shortage over the next decade or so, the idea at least has
merit.
</P>
<P>
   The position of Cellucci is much harder to justify.
</P>
<P>
   His current role of top teacher policeman was not his role in
1995, when the state's mission seemed to be to become chief
cheerleader for Newt Gingrich's attempted revolution. Perhaps
people have forgotten, but Weld-Cellucci were pushing open
enrollment in 1995, along with de facto privatization via vouchers
for elementary and secondary education.
</P>
<P>
   And along the way, if I may quote, ``In the new state
government, the Office of Education and Training would get out of
the business of teacher certification and recertification
altogether.'' Perhaps someday the acting governor might explain the
intellectual journey that got him from then to now.
</P>
<P>
   As for now, consider the plank in his latest proposal on college
loan forgiveness for new teachers. It claims that it ``expands''
the existing program to include young people who have graduated
with ``honors.'' Let's see now. The existing program includes all
those who graduate in the top fourth of their class. Has no one
stopped to wonder how many kids are in the top quarter of their
class and don't get honors?
</P>
<P>
   Or take Cellucci's tough-sounding proposal to require the
Education Department to produce by the end of this year a model
plan for local districts to develop new ways of certifying
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds nice, but the fact is, the law requiring this has been in
existence for the better part of five years. It is apparently the
acting governor's position that he needs a new law to tell his own
department what deadline it needs to meet. Gimme a break.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that serious education reform is being
implemented right now in Boston and several communities across the
state. It raises standards much higher for pupils and teachers
alike. A group may do badly on a given test, but that ought to
merely redouble the resolve of the people involved to make this
work. It definitely ought not lead to mindless teacher-bashing,
blame games, and minor-league politics.
</P>
<P>
   All this reform, don't forget, all this standards-raising, and
all this concern about shortage is occurring in the absence of any
real change in the horrid working conditions teachers endure and of
any serious attempt to make their pay and benefits commensurate
with less demanding tasks in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the state's leaders had a golden chance to
expand the base of support for reform, underline its urgency, and
increase their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And they blew it sky-high.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
