<HEADLINE>
LYNE'S `LOLITA' IS DEFENDED BY ITS STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It took ``Lolita,'' Vladimir Nabokov's 1954
novel, four years to find a US publisher. Almost half a century
later, director Adrian Lyne's adaptation of the now-classic book
has encountered a similarly rough road to the American public. Not
a single US theatrical distributor was willing to release the film,
which was completed two years ago and has already opened in
European theaters, and it looked as though the new ``Lolita'' would
never be available in the country in which it is set.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in May, cable TV's Showtime once again proved that it
could be nicknamed the Rescue Channel. Described by its president
of programming, Jerry Offsay, as a home for ``quality projects that
would not otherwise be seen,'' Showtime purchased the rights to
Lyne's movie and announced an Aug. 2 premiere. And then last week,
emboldened by Showtime's willingness to be controversial, Samuel
Goldwyn Films reached an agreement with Showtime to release the
movie to theaters sometime after Aug. 2. In recent years, Showtime
has provided similar emergency resuscitation on projects like
``Bastard Out of Carolina,'' which was deemed too disturbing for
TNT, and ``More Tales of the City,'' the sequel to ``Tales of the
City'' that was rejected by PBS.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is thanks to Showtime that we will now be deluged with
``Lolita,'' the second adaptation of the novel after director
Stanley Kubrick's 1962 version starring James Mason and Sue Lyons.
Lyne's ``Lolita,'' which cost $58 million, features a wonderfully
full-bodied performance by Jeremy Irons as Humbert Humbert, the
middle-aged man in an obsessive relationship with a 12-year-old
girl (played by newcomer Dominique Swain). Over the weekend,
Showtime brought Lyne, Irons (via satellite), Swain, and
screenwriter Stephen Schiff here to introduce and defend the movie
to TV critics gathered for the semiannual press tour.
</P>
<P>
   Irons, who said he was getting tired of talking about a movie he
made two years ago (``I'd like to move on,'' he joked), pointed out
that the perception of ``Lolita'' does not match the reality.
``When it was published in America, everybody went out to buy it,
and started thumbing through it, looking for the dirty bits,'' he
said. ``And of course there are not dirty bits in this novel. It's
extraordinary that it has the reputation it has, but it is not
salacious.'' He said the movie is a victim of ``very bad timing,''
as recent years have seen a growing awareness of pedophilia: ``We
were, in a way, used to our detriment by this _ what do you call it
_ lobby, airing a very important subject.''
</P>
<P>
   The sexuality portrayed in ``Lolita,'' while more explicit than
in Kubrick's adaptation, is relatively muted when compared with
most R-rated movies _ including other Lyne-directed hits like ``9
1/2 Weeks.'' Swain was 15 at the time ``Lolita'' was made, which
meant Lyne ended up spending six weeks in the editing room with a
lawyer: ``I did lose some shots that involved the body double,
because there was a law that came into being in 1996 ... that said,
essentially, you couldn't use an adult to imitate a minor.'' Lyne
said he tried to handle the filming of the sexual encounters with a
special sensitivity toward Swain: ``We always had her mother and
the teacher on the set, and we had something that became quite
famous called `the pad,' which was a cushion thing that we put
between Dominique and Jeremy during those particular scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, a New Yorker writer who was film critic at the Boston
Phoenix from 1978-83, said the movie's problems in America come
from our ``culture of fear.'' We are a ``very jumpy,
keep-it-in-the-dark-maybe-it-will-go-away kind of culture,'' he
said, adding that ``this movie would have had much less trouble,
maybe no trouble, had it come out in the late '70s or the early
'80s.'' He said people sometime forget that one of the virtues of
art is that it can re-create a difficult situation: ``This is not a
message movie, but it is a movie in which you are poured into
Humbert's skin, and if you don't feel uncomfortable there, then I
don't think we've done a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Showtime also introduced three other projects that might have
had trouble finding homes elsewhere in the TV universe. ``Rude
Awakening'' is an upbeat and offbeat comedy series that finds its
humor in the struggles of a newly sober woman in a 12-step program.
The show stars Sherilyn Fenn as the soap opera star who bottoms out
and Lynn Redgrave as her decadent mum. Comedian-actress Claudia
Lonow, the creator of the show, told critics she was tired of
humorless portrayals of sobriety. ``I've known a lot of people who
have gotten better, and the way they have gotten better is by not
taking themselves so seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Linc's'' is a 13-episode series that's being called ``Cheers''
from an African-American perspective. Set in a Washington, D.C.,
watering hole, the comedy revolves around the political, sexual,
and racial opinions of the ensemble, which includes Pam Grier,
Georg Stanford Brown, Tisha Campbell, and Steven Williams. It was
created by Tim Reid, who created ``Frank's Place.'' ``I think it's
too political for network TV,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime also previewed ``The Baby Dance,'' about a poor couple
who sell their forthcoming child _ their fifth _ to a couple
looking to adopt. The film, executive produced by Jodie Foster and
starring Laura Dern, brings a gritty reality and ambiguity to its
made-for-TV premise. ``There were a lot of people afraid of this
when we were going out with it in the beginning,'' said the movie's
producer, Meg LaFauve. ``But it was amazing to find Showtime
because they weren't afraid of it at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
