<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TAKE' TAKES THE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people have spoken on the question of bring vs. take, and
the people _ 73 percent of them, at any rate _ say they prefer to
take their Coppertone to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The question, posed in a column last month, was which verb to
choose in the sentence, ``For a pain-free vacation at the beach, be
sure to bring/take plenty of sunblock'' _ advice we assumed, for
the purpose of the poll, to be coming from a newspaper, not from a
friend at the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Responses came from 259 voters who claimed linguistic roots in
29 states (plus the District of Columbia) and seven other
countries, from Argentina to Australia. And the fiercest among them
were those with flags planted deep in take territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can there be any doubt?'' asked Cindy Day of Upton, Mass.
(educated in Auburn), and more than a dozen others like her
underlined their certainty with ``obviously'' ``unquestionably,''
and ``no doubt about it.'' Dana Guinn of Arlington, Mass. (via
Albuquerque and Cherry Hill, N.J.) worried that we'll be singing
``Bring Me Out to the Ballgame'' in our lifetimes _ or telling one
another, as the end draws near, ``You Can't Bring It With You.''
</P>
<P>
   Several writers had been schooled in the distinction with the
aid of a saying like the one offered by E. Cox of Peterborough,
N.H. (formerly of Long Island): ``Bring it with you when you come,
take it with you when you go.''
</P>
<P>
   But many, whether or not they chose take in the sample sentence,
were tolerant of deviance from the rule _ and ingenious in
explaining it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rich Ferrara of Amesbury, Mass., who comes from
Rhode Island, finds it natural (if ``incorrect'') to take a person
or animal, bring an inanimate object; ``I took my son to visit his
grandmother, and we brought her flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mary Stevenson, a Brooklynite transplanted to Brookline,
Mass., thinks the motion of the object toward or away from the
named location is the key: She would bring sunblock to the beach,
but take it from her home. ``The Visa ads seem to follow the same
rule,'' she notes: ```If you go to Ruby's, be sure to bring your
Visa card, because Ruby doesn't take American Express.'''
</P>
<P>
   But to readers brought up in the take camp, both examples sound
wrong, even headspinning, because they violate the bring-come,
take-go pairing enshrined in Cox's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Boyd of Haverhill, Mass., who grew up in Rhode Island,
votes for take in the sample sentence. But he argues that ``bring
Mary to the dance'' is the idiomatic expression, regardless of
direction. Not so in my corner of the Midwest, though: ``Who are
you taking to the dance?'' is the standard (and yes, I know it
should be whom, but it never is, is it?). A parent helping to
decorate the high school gym might ask a student, ``Who are you
bringing to the prom tonight?'' _ but from any other location the
verb would be take. Yes, you ``dance with the one that brung you,''
as the saying goes; once you get there, you have indeed brought (or
brung) him or her.
</P>
<P>
   We have far too little space to untangle this subject here, so
let's leapfrog to the conclusions of our unscientific survey _
noting firmly that this collection of opinions is the opposite of a
random sample. All it tells us is that among people who care quite
a lot about language _ enough to register an opinion via e-mail,
card, or letter _ the rulebook distinction between bring and take
is widely recognized.
</P>
<P>
   That's not surprising _ people interested in language, whatever
their background, are more likely to have learned along the way
what's considered ``proper'' usage. But actual conversation at your
neighborhood Starbucks or Dunkin' Donuts isn't likely to mirror
these results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the geographical groupings show some suggestive
differences. Among the 63 Massachusetts-educated respondents, take
took just 57 percent of the vote. For New England as a whole, the
take majority rose to 67 percent. The overall total, as noted
above, was 73 percent for take. And if Massachusetts was excluded
from the reckoning, the vote for take hit 78 percent. I'm no
statistician, but this does seem to hint that if bring for take is
a regionalism, Massachusetts is its home region.
</P>
<P>
   But why? A few correspondents touched on the question of foreign
language influences, but none offered any solid clues. Other
languages draw the bring/take distinction differently, or not at
all; maybe German or Yiddish or Italian has left its footprints on
the Freedom Trail.
</P>
<P>
   We still have some exploring to do on this one; teachers and
speakers of foreign languages, your help would be welcome.
Meanwhile, my thanks to everyone who wrote and voted, bringers and
takers alike.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
