<SLUG> BC-SHANGHAI-HOSPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SURGEON LENDS A HELPING HAND TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Children's Hospital chief surgeon Richard Jonas is
changing the way China provides health care.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a team for the US charity Project Hope, and working
hand-in-hand with Chinese government officials, Jonas helped build
the first world-class pediatric hospital in China at a cost of $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting specialists from the United States, Canada, and Europe
will teach Chinese doctors the latest in high-tech medicine at
Shanghai Children's Medical Center, then educate them to train
others, making the hospital the leading national teaching and
referral center. Hillary Rodham Clinton attended the ribbon-cutting
ceremony at the facility late last month.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pediatric cardiac surgeon faces an equally daunting
mission: helping the Chinese make sense out of the nation's
health-care funding. Long a Communist country known for its free
health care, China today is looking to the medical center to raise
enough money from patients to cover its costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's evolved into a market capitalist system without a good
insurance system,'' said Jonas, 46, who continues to serve as a
consultant on the hospital project.
</P>
<P>
   Under his direction, Shanghai has developed the only health
insurance system in China: it covers children under age 4, and only
for half the cost of care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospitals are asking for the rest of the money up front,''
Jonas said. And small employers in China still cannot afford to
provide any insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think health care was free in China,'' he said.
However, the unfortunate reality was ``it was completely free
because there wasn't any to get,'' he explained. Jonas wants to get
people to think of quality health care as a right, and to develop a
comprehensive insurance plan adapted to local conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Today, boomtown Shanghai is a wealthy, cultured, and fashionable
city, Jonas said, that historically has been a source of new ideas.
He hopes the rest of China will embrace Shanghai's new direction in
health care and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Boston after his 11th trip to China for the
ribbon-cutting ceremony last month, Jonas remembers his first call
in 1986 from Project Hope, a 40-year-old health-care charity for
children that spends $100 million a year in 30 countries. Officials
from Hope and the Chinese ministry of health asked him to lead a
group of cardiac surgeons and support staff to teach Chinese
doctors and health workers.
</P>
<P>
   He made the trip. And his group did so well that deaths from
simple surgeries in Shanghai plunged to 3 percent from 25 percent.
The number of surgeries soared to 1,000 from 200 a year. Since
heart problems are the most common life-threatening congenital
problem in children, Jonas said, pediatric hospitals need this
expertise as their cornerstone. The Chinese surgeons soon outgrew
their hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 1990s, Chinese officials made land available for a
new hospital, and money for construction and operating costs.
Project Hope pledged architectural and engineering support, and
training for the medical and administrative staff _ about one-third
of the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was literally nothing there,'' Jonas said. Steam and
water lines with steady pressure, power supplies free of erratic
surges _ everything had to be custom-designed and built.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a 410,000-square-foot hospital with 250 beds that
can care for 250,000 children a year. Surrounded by 13 landscaped
acres, it offers dental programs, laboratories, imaging centers,
and auxiliary functions.
</P>
<P>
   In China, about 140,000 children are born each year needing the
services the center provides. A waiting list in the thousands has
been shortened because of Jonas's success in training Chinese
surgeons who, he said, have learned quickly and are ready for more
complicated procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I already achieved in China will eclipse what I'll ever
achieve here (in Boston),'' Jonas said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonas has practiced or taught medicine in his native Australia,
the United Kingdom, Hungary, Singapore, South America, and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is particularly proud of elevating the status of
nurses in China through the first master's program there. He also
introduced a new focus on families with waiting rooms and
counseling for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, parents had been allowed only one hour a week for
visits with their child after a surgery. ``It was upsetting how
distressed they were,'' Jonas said. ``Now they can support a child
and help it to heal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
