<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHERN-FOREST-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED SALE OF NORTHERN FOREST LANDS BUILDS UP FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVER COVE, Maine _ Jim Glavine's rental cottages look across
the blue-black waters of Moosehead Lake to an unbroken line of
trees 12 miles long. At night, a single artificial light glows in
the vast darkness; only loons and the occasional bull moose in the
driveway break the silence.
</P>
<P>
   This is New England's wilderness, the biggest lake in one of the
largest forests in the eastern United States. But its fate may turn
on decisions made in far-off South Africa, where a paper company is
peddling 911,000 acres of Maine woods, including 60 miles of
Moosehead Lake shorefront.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa Pulp and Paper's proposed land sale is the most
dramatic among several plans that could sell off nearly 4 million
acres _ an area the size of Connecticut _ in the Northern Forest
this summer, raising fears that the best parts of the woods from
Maine to eastern New York could be turned from remote hideaways
open to all into real estate developers' bonanzas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to stand here 15 years from now and look
across and not see a marina and condos over there,'' said Glavine,
whose logging camp-style cabins look over timber company land,
including a small amount owned by South Africa Pulp and Paper,
known by its acronym SAPPI.
</P>
<P>
   Though new regulations could slow development _ and SAPPI
promises to sell its land for timber management only _ memories of
the 1980s real estate boom are too vivid to reassure people like
Glavine. Moosehead Lake still bears the scars of the last boom,
such as houses in the middle of nowhere put up by developers who
exploited legal loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Forest, the largest contiguous forest east of the
Mississippi, covers 26 million acres across northern Maine, New
Hampshire, Vermont, and New York. Last month, New York barely
averted a 15,000-acre development in the Adirondacks when the state
bought the land last month instead. But, with 70 million people
living within a seven-hour drive of the Northern Forest,
environmentalists fear that more second home and tourism projects
could soon follow.
</P>
<P>
   At root, forest residents, environmentalists, and state
officials alike are worried that the wave of land sales signals a
breakdown of the ``working forest'' system that has preserved the
woods since Henry David Thoreau canoed Moosehead in 1846. Under
this system, a handful of ``timber barons'' owned and logged the
land and cut trees, but kept the land public and left many
waterfronts alone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the globalization of the wood products industry,
timber barons have been replaced by distant corporations whose
decisions have little to do with preserving the forest. Analysts
say SAPPI, which bought Maine land just four years ago, is selling
partly to offset debt from buying a European paper firm.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the anxiety, Maine's largest land owner, South
Carolina-based Bowater Inc., confirmed on Friday that more than one
firm has expressed interest in buying its 2.1 million acres (3,281
square miles) of forest, as well as its Maine mills, as soon as it
finishes another purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation where one can depend on long-term ownership by
large paper companies is not the reality any more,'' said Catherine
B. Johnson of the Natural Resources Council of Maine, an
environmental group. ``Every time (properties) are bought and sold,
there is this tremendous risk that lands will be siphoned off and
liquidated.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, politicians in the four Northern Forest states as
well as the Clinton administration face a growing clamor for them
to protect the woods on a scale not seen since 1919 when Maine
Governor Percival Baxter personally bought 200,000 acres around
Mount Katahdin and gave it to the state of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public should buy this land while it's still in the hands
of a carpetbagger rather than an industrial owner who wants to turn
it into a plantation,'' said Michael Kellett of RESTORE: The North
Woods, which calls for a 3.2 million-acre national forest park
including much of SAPPI's land.
</P>
<P>
   More modestly, the Moosehead Messenger, a newspaper in
Greenville at Moosehead Lake's southern tip, is calling for
government purchase of key forest land ``to protect ourselves from
the whims of Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, calls for state and federal intervention come at
a time when only New York has a hefty fund to protect open space.
Maine has just $3 million to protect open space across the state,
while New Hampshire and Vermont have even less, and federal money
is tied up in congressional wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   So, Governor Angus King of Maine has asked his conservation
officials to give him a possible strategy for protecting important
parts of the SAPPI holdings, likely collaborating with private land
trusts to buy development rights on timber land while allowing
private owners to continue to log.
</P>
<P>
   However, King spokesman Dennis Bailey stressed that Maine's role
will have to be limited in a SAPPI land sale that could fetch $200
million to $320 million. ``The idea that we would scarf up 900,000
acres is a bit of a pipe dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt's designation of the
Northern Forest as one of his top three land acquisition priorities
may not translate into big money. Babbitt called for $5 million for
Northern Forest land in the Land and Water Conservation Fund in the
1999 budget, an amount congressional committees since have cut.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that environmentalists would object to SAPPI selling
its Maine land is ironic, considering how the company has treated
the woods. SAPPI uses herbicides to kill unwanted trees such as
maples, and strips virtually all of the trees from thousands of
acres in a practice known as clearcutting.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, SAPPI's harvesting methods, which leave large bare
patches on the roads along Moosehead Lake, were a prime reason for
the unsuccessful 1996 referendum effort to ban clearcutting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
