<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-TILBERIS-ART-     07-14 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-TILBERIS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER'S' LIZ TILBERIS SURVIVES IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Imagine accepting a coveted job as an assistant at the British
edition of Vogue magazine and then going home to a closet that's
virtually empty. What in the world would you wear every &UR;  &LR; day when
office culture dictates the most up-to-the-moment designer clothes
and most of your colleagues have trust funds?
</P>
<P>
   Liz Tilberis thought she could circumvent her problem by dyeing
her few pairs of shoes different colors every night to match the
next day's outfit. She was so broke in 1970 &UR;  &LR; when she started this
entry-level job, she shopped at Woolworth's and flea markets hoping
to emulate the look of the moment. And to supplement her meager
$1,500 annual salary, she even stooped to repairing the broken
zippers of her colleagues' pants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she was humiliated by her co-workers and reduced to tears
by her own self-doubt. One &UR;  &LR; woman, a Ferrari-driving heiress to a
piece of the Shell Oil fortune, told her that as a ``Voguette,''
she really had to dress better.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward almost 30 years and you'll see Tilberis is dressing
just fine. As the editor-in-chief of the fashion magazine Harper's
Bazaar in New York, Tilberis now wears Chanel suits and Gucci shoes
on a whim. Instead of shopping second-hand at flea markets, she has
personal shoppers shopping for her. While she never got that
Ferrari, she did manage to buy a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Now this former fashion flunky is telling her 700,000 readers
each month how (itals)they(unitals) can dress better. ``People do
read my editor's note,'' said Tilberis in her soft British accent
during a recent visit to Boston. ``If we say: wear pink, black, or
blue, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis is also telling readers _ not through her magazine but
through an autobiography ``No Time to Die'' _ of her tragic bout
with ovarian cancer. Diagnosed five years ago, she has endured
surgery, chemotherapy, a bone marrow transplant that ``smashed''
her to pieces, the loss of her hair, fingernails, eyelashes, and
eyebrows, and countless hours of excruciating pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live with a chronic disease,'' she said. ``If I hadn't come
to the States, I'd be dead by now,'' because, she said, American
health care is more aggressive in diagnosing cancer than England's.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis grew up in England. She was an ordinary brown-haired,
green-eyed young woman who was expelled from college for
entertaining her boyfriend in her room (she eventually graduated
from another college). She got her foot in the door at British
Vogue _ not through connections _ but by winning an essay contest.
She stood out because _ in an era focused on instant
self-gratification and entitlement _ she was willing to pay her
dues, even if it meant ironing a blouse for a photo shoot or
studying the latest in bra designs.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis transformed herself into an international style maven
because, as a true student of fashion, she eagerly studied fabrics
and design. She didn't care if she was a misfit among the wealthy
fashion crowd and she was never too proud to learn. ``I never had
good taste,'' said Tilberis, who moved to New York for Harper's
Bazaar in 1992 after 22 years at British Vogue in London (including
almost five years as editor-in-chief). ``Even today, I don't feel I
have great taste. I trained to become a designer, and I was a very
bad one. When I became a junior fashion editor, I was very
observant. I watched very carefully women with great taste,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her strategy paid off. &UR;  &LR; Today, the 50-year-old Tilberis is so
influential that on one occasion, a Harper's wannabe followed her
into a bathroom and slid a resume under the door of her stall. When
Tilberis hosted a Christmas party at her home a few years ago,
Calvin Klein was the first one there, followed by Ralph Lauren and
Donna Karan. And _ as a true sign of her importance _ the New York
tabloids hammered her when she arrived in the States over something
truly petty _ her weight.
</P>
<P>
   At the time she was 150 pounds. At 5-feet-7, that's certainly
normal for most people, but in the fashion industry, she was
considered (by one newspaper account) ``bovine.'' The editor has
since slimmed down to a skinny 120 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   With her cancer in remission, Tilberis has learned to be
grateful for every day. ``I try hard to take it easy,'' she says.
``I try to get out of a lot of things in the evening and I do fewer
lunches'' &UR;  &LR; socially.
</P>
<P>
   But a lighter schedule for Tilberis is still a heavy load for
most people. The editor has tackled the disease with the same drive
she used to take on the fashion industry, primarily because she's
convinced she developed ovarian cancer from the fertility treatment
she underwent years ago unsuccessfully (Tilberis and her husband,
Andrew, have two adopted sons, Robert, 17, and Christopher, 13).
</P>
<P>
   First, encouraged by her staff, Tilberis agreed to have the
story of her cancer and chemotherapy treatment profiled in
``Harper's Bazaar.'' ``Nobody knows about this kind of cancer,''
she said. Then, Tilberis and writer Aimee Lee Ball wrote a second
piece about her bone marrow transplant. The response amazed her.
``We got thousands of letters,'' she said. So Tilberis was inspired
to write a book.
</P>
<P>
   From January to August 1997, Tilberis, with Ball, wrote the
autobiography that chronicles her rise in the industry and her
struggle with the disease. ``We've sold 28,000 copies,'' said
Tilberis. ``It's a bestseller in England. But all I care about is
for a woman (with symptoms) to make an appointment'' with her
gynecologist, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the president of the nonprofit Ovarian Cancer Research Fund,
Tilberis travels the country speaking about her experiences and
encouraging other cancer survivers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she is still running the magazine as well. Rather
than let the disease hurt her career, she's just worked around it.
While recuperating from her bone marrow transplant in 1995, for
example, Tilberis still held staff meetings. They were just in her
hospital room where, for her own protection, her staff wore
surgical masks and gowns. To make light of her hair loss in an
industry obsessed with perfect looks (and for her children's sake),
Tilberis named the wig she wore ``Larry'' as a joke. Her hair has
since grown back into a chic, cropped style.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis's typical day starts around 9 a.m. when she makes
business calls to London in the car while her driver takes her from
her Manhattan home to her office. Once there, she often holds staff
meetings about upcoming issues and then spends an hour reading mail
before meeting with advertisers, designers, and retailers. ``I
spend most of my work life walking up and down corridors asking
people, `What happened there? Why this photo?''' she said. ``I
worry a lot about the magazine. I might feel the last issue wasn't
smiley enough or we didn't use the right celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Three or four nights a week, Tilberis has a dinner or gala to
attend. But when she's free, she'll leave work by 6 or 7 and return
home to cook dinner for Christopher and Andrew (who works out of
the house as an artist and exercise-device inventor). Robert is
away at boarding school. ``I have a housekeeper. She's bought
everything,'' she said. By 9 p.m., dinner is done and Tilberis is
watching television _ ``ER,'' ``The Practice,'' and ``Just Shoot
Me'' are her favorites. She'll help with homework when needed and
then read a novel.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekends, family members retreat to their Long Island
home, where they visit with friends, play tennis, go boating, and
cook traditional English fare: roast or lamb and apple tarts or
crumble. The family home is certainly noisy. The boys have two
canaries, a labrador, a cat who's flown the Concorde, and a
locust-eating lizard. ``I buy the locusts,'' Tilberis said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her vast Rolodex and a clothing allowance (she calls it
``nothing much''), Tilberis insists she has only two closets
containing ``a couple'' of trouser suits and skirts in colors like
gray and oatmeal. ``I changed my size when I dropped from 150
pounds to 120,'' she said. ``My wardrobe is very small.'' And
Tilberis isn't one to wear stilettos to a weekend movie. ``I live
in Old Navy pants,'' she said. ``On Fridays, I wear J. Crew shorts
or Old Navy cargo pants and a Gap T-shirt. This summer, I'm going
to buy brown Birkenstocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some fashion groupies in the business, Tilberis doesn't
keep track of what she wore last week and the week before. If she's
photographed wearing the same thing at various galas, she could
care less. ``Fashion is so relaxed now,'' she says with a wave of
her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, has she come a long way. Gone are the days when she worried
about making an impression. Nowadays the ultraconfident and
powerful editor _ who's been to the brink of death and has more
than paid her dues _ says without hesitation and with just a little
attitude, ``If they don't like it, I'm sorry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
