<HEADER>
A3970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MIRROR-BOS &LR;      07-14 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MIRROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATASHA THROUGH THE LOOKING GLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
GIRL IN THE MIRROR 
Three Generations of Black Women in Motion 
By Natasha Tarpley 
Beacon, 183 pp., $22 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The journey that Natasha Tarpley takes in ``Girl in the Mirror:
Three Generations of Black Women in Motion'' is not exactly new.
The book fits right into the stack of memoirs being published as
writers increasingly turn inward and readers continue to peek
inside the real lives of others.
</P>
<P>
   It is the path that Tarpley takes _ the meanderings, the stops
along the way, the observations she chooses to make on her journey
_ that moves ``Girl in the Mirror'' beyond the basic all-about-me
offering. Tarpley, a poet, looks for herself and sees the faces of
the women who came before her, her mother and her grandmother. She
sees that she is a reflection of them, that their spirits are so
intertwined with her own that separation is impossible. And in that
realization, there is strength.
</P>
<P>
   The author uses poetry, prose, letters, and even a funeral
notice to unfold the lives of these women as they make geographic
as well as psychological moves. In doing so, she brings freshness
to the memoir structure, making it read like a novel.
</P>
<P>
   The first section of the book is about grandmother Anna's move
from Alabama to Chicago in the 1940s; she follows her husband
north, where pots of golden opportunity were supposed to be waiting
for black folks fleeing the South. The second part deals with
Tarpley's mother, Marlene, and her own move to Cambridge, where she
pursues a master's at Harvard after her husband dies and she has to
figure out what she is beyond her previous role as a wife. Then
comes Tarpley's story, her struggle to fulfill herself, to ease the
ache for the elusive ``more'' that her mother and grandmother
experienced, and her move to Washington, D.C., seeking in law
school more security than writing could provide.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally, then, this is a book about ordinary folks moving
through life, dealing with deaths in the family, miscarriages, and
unsuccessful attempts to fill the empty places inside themselves
with the love of others.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley, who was born in 1971, takes on the voices of the women
whose lives she recalls. There is a push and pull in the way she
presents family members from one perspective, letting us know them
as they know themselves, and then shows them from outside, through
the eyes of others. This gives all her characters a delicious
richness.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens in 1942, with Anna confronting the loss of the
company of her husband, Jack, who is heading north from Alabama to
build a better life and find freedom in Chicago. She refuses to
wait patiently for the man to send for her, hops in a car with some
friends, and goes to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley's background in poetry is evident from the start, as
when she personifies emptiness _ making it not just a feeling but
an entity taking up space: ``So there it was. The emptiness he left
behind had beat me back to the house and was already in the
kitchen, leaning back in Jack's chair and grinning with its feet
propped up on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The language is lyrical without being flowery. Throughout,
Tarpley's way with description creates a breathtaking clarity, in
imagery so solid you can taste it. For example, with Anna's take on
love: ``When you're in love, you get so carried away over the fact
that somebody loves you, somebody wants to marry you. ... You hand
over your life like it was a piece of sweet potato pie, and you
watch him pull the plate close to him, then hold your breath until
he takes the first bite and smiles. But then he'll come back for
seconds and thirds, and you'll keep dishing it out. And what does
that leave you but the crumbs of a life somebody else has
devoured?''
</P>
<P>
   The book begins to flag only near the end of the journey, when
Tarpley deals with her own story. The imagery isn't as sharp, the
introspection not as telling, when she is closer to autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Girl in the Mirror'' remains a pleasant trip that anyone
can enjoy. We are all our mothers' daughters and our fathers' sons,
and Tarpley helps us recognize the importance of looking over our
shoulders to understand better what is ahead. As the author puts
it: ``You're constantly negotiating between where you come from and
where you're going. And, one is always tugging at the other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
