<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BEASTIE-BOS &LR;      07-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BEASTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO FLOW TO GO WITH IN `HELLO NASTY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SAUNDERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As examples of concept succeeding over content, few bands can
match the Beastie Boys' 15-year reign as one of pop music's most
glaringly overrated acts. Of course, none of that matters to the
legions of Beastie Boys fans who will file dutifully into shopping
malls across the country Tuesday (July 14) to buy the group's
latest disc, ``Hello Nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans love the idea of the Beastie Boys, the transcultural
novelty of wealthy upper-class New Yorkers copping B-Boy poses and
spouting frat-boy raps. Few other explanations exist for the nearly
universal deafness to the inescapable truth: Adam Horovitz (King
Adrock), Mike Diamond (Mike D), and Adam Yauch (MCA) have voices
like ice picks.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrical flow is a critical component of any effective hip-hop
track, or should be, in the Beastie Boys' case. Without that flow,
block-rocking beats fall apart, disjointed and unbound by vocal
mortar. This minimalist approach often works for the electronica
offshoot of breakbeat, but hip-hop thrives on The Word.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``Hello Nasty'' will re-kin-dle Middle America's
long-running love affair with the New York City trio, who first
injected hip-hop into the heartland with the 1986 disc ``Licensed
to Ill.'' That debut soared to No.1, the first rap disc to hit the
summit, and more significantly, got there without support from
blacks, then rap's biggest audience.. It was the first rap disc for
many white teens who discovered that the marriage of grinding
guitars and whiny vocals served the same purpose as heavy metal.
There has always been, and will always be, a demand for music that
both annoys parents and creates bonds between friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Licensed to Ill'' was also one of the first rap discs given
credence by rock critics, many of whom slept through Grandmaster
Flash, Run DMC, and Afrika Bambaataa, hoping the fad would pass. It
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways ``Hello Nasty'' is a familiar record, a collection
of sonic motifs that the Beastie Boys have toyed with since
``Licensed to Ill.'' Since it's more of a collage than a
thematically unified disc, ``Hello Nasty'' falls somewhere in the
middle of the Beastie Boys' previously explored territory. It
emerges as less bratty than ``Licensed to Ill,'' less trippy than
``Paul's Boutique,'' and far less funky than the best cuts from
``Check Your Head'' and ``Ill Communication.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Disco Breakin''' opens the disc, a track for the
old-school heads, the fans who waited four years to hear the
Beasties' hot-potato lyric trading. It's a rap style that faded
soon after Jordache jeans and Kangol caps vanished from wardrobes,
but it works within deliberately retro tracks such as this one, and
on ``Intergalactic,'' the first single released from the disc.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't work for very long.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every rap is delivered in that characteristic
high-pitched grating whine that sabotages great beats and cuts the
legs from dance tracks. For a fleeting, teasing, all-too-brief
moment during its introduction, ``Just A Test'' was nearly as
hip-loosening as any song the group has ever recorded, on a par
with the ultra-funky ``Get It Together'' from ``Ill
Communication.'' A promising foundation of ground-rumbling jeep
beats sprinkled with static and turntable scratches gets a brutal
funk-robbing beat-down from the vocal noise. ``The Negotiation
Limerick File,'' an amazing piece of rhythm manipulation, nearly
succumbs to the same fate.
</P>
<P>
   Restraint is rarely associated with the Beastie Boys in any
form, so any attempts to smooth the edges immediately stand out.
That's evident on the surprising cut `'Flowin Prose,'' which layers
a subdued Q-Tip style rap over a head-bobbing rhythm track. Subtle
seems to work best throughout ``Hello Nasty,'' especially the odd
semi-acoustic tracks that effectively keep the listener off
balance. ``I Don't Know'' is a low-fi gem that demands repeated
plays. ``And Me'' is a takeoff on a spare drum 'n' bass theme, a
strange, wonderfully spacey little song. ``Picture This'' mines the
same ground, helped greatly by an ethereal vocal by Brooke
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unite,'' one of the disc's best songs _ and one of the group's
best in a decade _ creeps up suddenly near the end of the party,
No. 19 of 22 tracks. Deftly placed piano and organ riffs trigger
involuntary head-bobbing; Beastie lover or not, it's impossible to
deny the funkiness of this cut, one of the rare Beastie Boys songs
with potential crossover appeal to serious hip-hop heads.
</P>
<P>
   The Boys get credit for eclecticism, as on ``Electrify,'' a
weighty track built atop a sample from Igor Stravinsky's ``The
Firebird Suite.'' By song's end, however, weighty becomes leaden
and the track seems much longer than 2 minutes and 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   This is the paradox of the Beastie Boys: contradictory elements
seemingly at war with each other. An excellent steel-drum sample is
the foundation of ``Body Movin','' another almost funky track that
loses all credibility with lyrics such as this:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``So kick off your shoes and put on your swim fins/When
it comes to quarries, I'm known to swim.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Let's try that again:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``If you try to knock me, you'll get mocked/I'll stir-fry
you in my wok.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, gentlemen. That's enough.
</P>
<P>
   Apologists will likely dress up this lameness in the
one-size-fits-all cloak of parody, either the popular self-parody
flavor (``By mocking their own failings, they elevate the entire
oeuvre''), or the more challenging genre/societal parody (``It's a
statement about the shallowness and impermanence of popular
American culture.'')
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you know there's trouble with the creative process
if novelty rapper Biz Markie is offering tips in the studio. It's
this weakness of words that hobbles the disc and saps the life from
the music. More than any previous Beastie Boys release, ``Hello
Nasty'' makes a case for the trio to focus on studio production and
leave the rapping to rappers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
