<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES FROM THE TITANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are thousands of tales relating to the doomed RMS Titanic.
Here are a few, courtesy of the people who have brought ``Titanic _
the Artifact Exhibition'' to Boston's World Trade Center:
</P>
<P>
   _Minutes after leaving on her maiden voyage on April 10, 1912,
the ocean liner nearly collided with the liner New York, whose
moorings had snapped because of the Titanic's massive wake.
</P>
<P>
   _The ``RMS'' stands for ``Royal Mail Steamer.'' The Titanic was
carrying hundreds of sacks of mail in addition to 2,228 people.
</P>
<P>
   _Among the last passengers to board a lifeboat were two
brothers, 3-year-old Michael and 2-year-old Edmond, who were handed
over by their father, who was traveling under the name ``M.
Hoffman.'' His real name was Michael Navrati, and he had taken the
boys from their mother during divorce proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   _The headline in the April 15, 1912, New York Sun read: ``All
Saved from Titanic After Collision.'' (In reality, only 705 people
survived the sinking 450 miles southeast of Newfoundland on April
15, 1912.)
</P>
<P>
   _Shortly after the ship struck an iceberg, a steward told
passengers, ``Oh, it'll be a few hours and we'll be on our way
again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of the Titanic: &LR;  There was a Jack Dawson aboard the
ship, but he was a hard-working fireman, not a Leonardo DiCaprio
lover boy who had that name in the movie. But that hasn't stopped
hundreds of adolescent and preadolescent girls from flocking to
Jack Dawson's grave in Halifax, Nova Scotia, for swooning purposes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  How many Titanic survivors are alive today? None,
one, five, 15, or 50? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Thirst for the sun! Thirst for the sand! Thirst for
the clocks that run slow!'' _ Jacques-Henri Lartigue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name:  &LR; A counter from which drinks are served has come to be
called a bar because of the wooden bars that enclosed colonial tap
rooms. (With thanks to Valerie A. Russo of Weymouth, who learned
the fact from Betty H. Wright, curator, during a tour of Fearing
Tavern in Wareham.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; No tipping turmoil: &LR;  The problem with tipping is not that people
don't want to reward good service but that they're not always sure
how much to tip whom. Boston's newest hotel, the Seaport, has a
policy that ends the confusion. You don't tip anyone, but a $2 per
room service charge is added to your bill and a 15 percent charge
is added at the hotel's fine restaurant, Aura. If you try to tip
anyone beyond that, the money will be refused. If you leave the
money and run, it will be donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  An East African newspaper
reported that ``A new swimming pool is rapidly taking shape since
the contractors have thrown in the bulk of their workers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel bookshelf: &LR;  Ah, nature! ``The National Audubon Society Field
Guide to New England'' by Peter Alden and Brian Cassie (Knopf,
$19.95) is filled with descriptions and photos of the region's
birds, animals, trees, wildflowers, insects, weather, nature
preserves, and then some. The 1,500 full-color images include more
than 1,300 photos, 150 drawings, 20 maps, and 16 night-sky charts.
Other books in the Audubon series include guides to Florida,
California, and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it?  &LR; Five Titanic survivors are alive today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
