FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: The words TILDE and AT in parentheses have been used
in Web addresses instead of the symbols, which cannot be
interpreted by many newspapers' computer systems. Also, this
article has been transmitted twice _ into the ``t'' travel news and
``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Since this summer's travel season is shaping up to be the
busiest in years, consumers need every bit of help they can to take
the sting out of their vacation's price tag.
 &HT;    Here are a few suggestions for those who've yet to make their
summer plans.
 FREQUENT-FLIER MILES  
 &HT;    For travelers who have a stash of frequent-flier miles, Randy
Petersen, editor of InsideFlyer (4715-C Town Center Drive, Colorado
Springs, Colo. 90816; 800-333-5937) has this advice: ``Don't even
think of using miles to go to New York, San Francisco, Los Angeles,
Orlando, Chicago or Las Vegas. The same is true for Boston, Denver,
Phoenix or Seattle. These are all top places for people to redeem
their awards, and those awards are pretty much already taken.''
 &HT;    But, on a more encouraging note, he advises looking for seats to
Tucson, Ariz.; Key West, Jacksonville and Sarasota, Fla.;
Indianapolis, Ind.; Portland, Ore.; Nashville, Tenn.; Austin and
San Antonio, Texas; and Milwaukee, Wis.
 &HT;    ``Since San Francisco is hard, consider flying to Oakland
instead,'' Petersen recommends. ``And Honolulu is tough, so think
about flying to Kona. As for Denver, look to Colorado Springs as an
alternative.''
 &HT;    Petersen also has some advice about international travel,
suggesting that travelers look to new airline routes. That means
Dublin and Edinburgh for Continental and the new seven-times-a-week
service to Hong Kong that United Airlines is offering.
 AIRLINE TICKETS  
 &HT;    A good source of bargains for last-minute travelers is the
Internet. American Airlines (www.americanair.com) has Net SAAver
Fares _ last-minute, round-trip deals that are posted every week to
subscribers via e-mail.
 &HT;    International deals are listed on Mondays, domestic deals on
Wednesdays. The e-mail subscription is offered for free.
 &HT;    Most flights originate at the airline's hub cities of Chicago,
Dallas and Miami. These deals are good for long weekend travel from
either Thursday to Monday or Friday to Monday or Tuesday.
 &HT;    American also offers discounted first-class fares every week.
And the Web site offers tickets for longer stays.
 &HT;    Look also to U.S. Airways (www.usairways.com) and Continental
(www.flycontinental.com) for weekly e-mail specials.
 &HT;    TWA (www.twa.com) has Trans World Specials, and Cathay Pacific
(www.cathaypacific(TILDE)air.com) sends deals out periodically.
Many of these airline sites also offer well-priced car-rental and
hotel deals too.
 &HT;    For price-sensitive travelers, Priceline.com (www.priceline.com)
is the newest source for airline tickets. A traveler logs onto this
site, decides what price he would like to pay for a round-trip
ticket, makes the request and guarantees it with a major credit
card.
 &HT;    Within one hour for domestic travel and 24 hours for
international trips, travelers can learn whether an airline has
agreed to release a seat and which flights and routing are
provided. Tickets are non-refundable, non-exchangeable and do not
earn frequent-flier miles.
 CONSOLIDATOR TICKETS  
 &HT;    This is the time of year when consolidator tickets to major
European cities can offer the best trans-Atlantic values around.
 &HT;    But the downside to these discounted tickets is that they are
usually not refundable, transferrable or good for frequent-flier
mileage credit.
 &HT;    These tickets are also typically non-endorsable, which means in
the event of a delay or cancellation, they cannot be used to travel
on another airline.
 &HT;    Many travel agents will procure these tickets. However, for
those who wish to do it themselves, one of the largest
consolidators around is Council Travel (205 East 42nd St., New
York, N.Y. 10017; 800-226-8624; www.ciee.org).
 ADVENTURE TRAVEL  
 &HT;    For anyone who needs a rafting, climbing, caving, biking or
sea-kayaking fix, the links provided by GORP, the Great Outdoors
Recreation Pages (www.gorp.com), could be useful, as could the
Outdoor Action Guide to Outdoor Resources
(www.princeton.edu/(TILDE)oa/outother.html). It's a quick way to
find out which companies still have space on a bike trip to the
Tetons or a hike in Maine.
 HOTELS  
 &HT;    Weekday and weekend hotel discounts exist, but consumers may
find they have to ask for them.
 &HT;    The same is true for discounts provided for members of
automobile clubs like the Automobile Association of America (AAA)
and organizations like the American Association of Retired Persons
(AARP).
 &HT;    Hotel brokers can offer larger discounts of 10 percent to 50
percent off the ``rack'' or published rate at select city and
resort properties throughout the country. Here's a short list.
 &HT;    Accommodations Express (801 Asbury Ave., Ocean City, N.J. 08226;
800-444-7666; www.accomodationsexp.com)
 &HT;    Branson Nights Reservations (P.O. Box 2321, Branson, Mo. 65616;
800-329-9999; www.branson-nights.com) works just with hotels in
Branson, Mo.
 &HT;    Capitol Reservations (1730 Rhode Island Ave. NW, Suite 1114,
Washington, D.C. 20036; 800-847-4832; www.hotelsdc.com) deals only
with properties in the Washington D.C. area.
 &HT;    Central Reservation Service (505 Maitland Ave., Suite 100,
Altamonte Springs, Fla. 32701;
800-548-3311;www.reservation(AT)america.com)
 &HT;    Express Reservations (3825 Iris Ave., Boulder, Colo. 80301;
800-356-1123; www.express-res.com) works only with hotels in New
York and Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Hotel Reservations Network (8140 Walnut Hill Lane, Suite 203,
Dallas, Texas 75231; 800-964-6835; www.180096hotel.com)
 &HT;    Quikbook (381 Park Avenue South, New York, N.Y. 10016;
800-789-9887; www.quikbook.com)
 &HT;    San Francisco Reservations (22 Second St., San Francisco, Calif.
94105; 800-677-1550; www.hotelres.com)
