<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BOS &LR;      07-14 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, THE HOSTS HAD THE MOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The success of France has its origins in the 1970s and
'80s, when Les Bleus established a reputation as one of the world's
most stylish international teams.
</P>
<P>
   Those players _ Jean Fernandez, Alain Giresse, Michel Platini,
Dominique Rocheteau, Didier Six, Jean Tigana _ became the coaches
and/or inspiration for the current generation of soccer players who
are the World Cup champions after crushing Brazil, 3-0, in the
final Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Platini, the most successful French footballer ever, is more
than the symbolic leader of this group _ he was the president of
the French Organizing Committee and, along with President Jacques
Chirac, the most enthusiastic of VIP presenters at the Stade de
France.
</P>
<P>
   And that was among the keys to France winning this championship
_ the home-country advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Aimee Jacquet developed a conservative, powerful group
that specialized in pressuring opponents into mistakes, then taking
advantage. France has many skilled players, resulting from a
traditional appreciation of the aesthetics of sport, and a
highly-competitive professional league.
</P>
<P>
   But the French have not always been as passionate for soccer as
their neighbors. That changed during this World Cup. The nation
galvanized behind the team as it continued to win, culminating in
what became a 24-hour party in the shadow of the Arc de Triomphe to
celebrate the win.
</P>
<P>
   The French were willing to compromise their aesthetic standards
for Jacquet's pragmatism, as long as the strategy succeeded. The
individual technical brilliance of Zinedine Zidane, the solid
defending of Laurent Blanc, Marcel Desailly, Bixente Lizarazu,
Lilian Thuram, and goalkeeper Fabian Barthez, and the opportunism
of the group, captured imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s and '80s, the French national team and clubs such as
Saint-Etienne also captured imaginations, but most of their forays
onto the international scene ended in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquet solved that problem by reducing the margin for error
with a conservative philosophy, stifling opponents with three
defensive midfielders, and attacking only through random long balls
to a lone striker. Les Bleus also capitalized on leniency from
referees, again a benefit of playing at home.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jacquet and Brazil coach Mario Zagallo were heavily
criticized for their team selections and strategies. Jacquet was
vindicated by success, Zagallo remained under intense pressure, and
concluded his post-match press conference by storming out after
arguing with Brazilian journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brazil's lackluster championship game performance
raised many questions. Ronaldo was excluded from the original
starting lineup, then reinstated less than an hour before the
start. His ankle had been X-rayed the morning of the match, and he
received a general check-up after complaining of aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo's ineffectiveness raised questions. If he was unfit, why
did he play? And, once it became obvious he could not perform, why
wasn't he substituted?
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo said Ronaldo's condition had a strong psychological
affect on Brazil, implying that the team's mentality was extremely
fragile. Brazilian critics noted that this could have been
countered with the presence of strong personalities such as
Romario, who was cut from the team in May, or that there were
outside pressures that forced Ronaldo to perform.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Brazil became one of the most disappointing teams
in the tournament, suffering the worst final-game defeat since
1970, when the Brazilians defeated Italy, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   There were other disappointments: Spain, eliminated in the first
round; Nigeria, the best African team, crushed by Denmark, 4-1, in
the second round; Italy, eliminated by France on penalty kicks as
coach Cesare Maldini made Jacquet seem like a risk-taker; the US,
which suffered its earliest elimination ever and trailed for 219 of
the 270 minutes it played against Germany, Iran, and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists field was expanded to 32 teams, and though the
lower-echelon nations experienced little success, they enlivened
the tournament. Croatia's third-place finish was the best by a
first-time entrant since Portugal in 1966. Japan's solid and
sometimes inspiring performance was encouraging, since it will
share the host role with South Korea in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, playing in its second World Cup finals, displayed tactical
discipline and technical excellence in defeating the United States,
2-1, in the politically-charged atmosphere of Stade Gerland in Lyon
June 21.
</P>
<P>
   England unveiled one of the game's brightest young stars,
18-year-old Michael Owen, but its fans caused enough problems to
probably vanquish the country's bid for the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   There were dozens of controversies. African nations protested
what they felt were the victimizations of Cameroon and Morocco,
both subjected to elimination by controversial refereeing
decisions. A group of former players actually attempted to sue in
French courts to have those teams remain in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Africans' only solace was the naming of Said Belqola of
Morocco as the first championship game referee from their
continent.
</P>
<P>
   So, who will be the France of the future, a team that brought
flair and imagination but ultimately failed in the final major
international sporting event of the century?
</P>
<P>
   There are many candidates _ Chile, Mexico, Morocco, Nigeria,
South Africa. Hopefully, Los Matadores Luis Hernandez and Marcelo
Salas, technicians Mustafa Hadji and Jay Jay Okocha, and Quinton
Fortune will teach their children well. Hopefully, they will remain
uninhibited, maintain their sense of La joie de jouer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
