<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIPPING UP SOME INTEREST IN THE BRITISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Welcome to the Lancashire coast, summer
resort central. The howling winds, plummeting temperatures,
occasional rain, and leaden skies were enough to drive everybody
indoors Monday at Royal Birkdale GC, where the 127th British Open
begins Thursday morning. If this is a prime summer resort, winter
must be a delight in these surroundings by the Irish Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Should this weather persist, it would set up a fun show outside
the more comfortable confines of the clubhouse that resembles a
ship washed ashore with its riggings and roof decks. The architect
who designed it in the 1930s envisioned it as a ship navigating its
way through the sand dunes to the nearby sea.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, who won the game's oldest championship two years ago
at nearby Royal Lythamm &AMP; St. Annes, grew up in the Minnesota
climate and compared the way it was Monday to an April day in the
Land of 10,000 Lakes. Which means March was a lot of fun. ``I'm not
sure this suits anybody's game,'' said Lehman. ``It's awfully
difficult. I played nine holes Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my driver, 5-iron and the putter with the six golf
balls. By the time I got to the eighth tee, I was out of golf
balls. It was blowing 45 miles an hour. I wouldn't say the course
was unplayable, but it was very difficult. On the second hole (410
yards), I hit two drivers and didn't get it there. That shows you
how hard it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's blowing between 25 to 30 miles per hour, and if you
play well today, you shoot around par or maybe 1 under. It's very
easy to shoot 77 or 78. I think the best players will come to the
top. When it's blowing hard, you just have to hit the ball solid.
If you don't hit it solid, you have no chance whatsoever of
winning. I don't care how good you play. The best ball strikers
definitely have an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you know when you come here this is what you should
expect. Obviously you don't get it all the time. We didn't get it
two years ago. You come and you need to expect to have some wind
and some rain. If you're not ready for that, you're probably not
going to do very well. I think (in these) sort of conditions you
have to take whatever it gives you and make the best of it. It's
very easy to lose your swing when the wind blows.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind was whipping though the press tents, and it seemed the
roof might blow away at any moment. And it raised havoc with the
putting. ``The wind blowing so strong, it can blow it off line,''
said Lehman. ``I remember a couple of years ago in the Scottish
Open when Howard Twitty had a 20-foot putt straight into the wind,
and it went 20 feet beyond the hole. The wind was blowing so hard
and he was leaning into it so much, he knocked it 20 feet by the
hole and right off the green. More than anything, it plays tricks
on your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, who won the 1994 US Open at Oakmont and repeated a
year ago at Congressional, termed the conditions ``almost
laughable.'' The wind was right to left on the 480-yard par-4
sixth, and then dead against the players after cutting the dogleg.
``I hit driver, 3-wood,'' said Els. He proceded to tip the cap in
favor of Englishman Lee Westwood, who Els said was on a roll that
has established him as one of the world's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see a little bit of breeze,'' said Els, ``but I
don't call that a breeze out there. I played the back nine 1 over,
and I thought I played quite nicely. I think when the wind is
blowing, it suits a stronger player because you aren't going to hit
all the fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   Added US Open champion Lee Janzen. `If it plays like this I
would be amazed if somebody played the whole tournament without a
double bogey. After all, he played his first practice round Sunday
and lost five balls. ``The wind just changes the course entirely.
You have to play all sorts of shots. The wind makes the ball go a
lot shorter for us. You're forced to hit more low, penetrating
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who played his first practice round at Royal
Birkdale in the blustery weather, tuned up en route with a round on
the Old Course at Ireland's Ballybunion GC. Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan,
his caddie, had played there in late April and had such an
enjoyable experience that he coaxed Woods to join Mark O'Meara and
Payne Stewart for a visit. Woods was 1 under for his round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
