</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-MISSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSION STATEMENTS ARE JOB1 -- FOR SOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a plaque in the lobby of Arrow Automotive
Industries' &UR;  &LR; headquarters is emblazoned the auto parts maker's
mission statement: ``We make good parts. We ship on time. We all
sleep good at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Developed by top managers a few years ago, the mission statement
appeared on company literature for about five months, remembers
Joel D. Holzwasser, Arrow's vice president of advertising and
public relations and a member of the writing committee at the
Framingham, Mass. company.
</P>
<P>
   But then employees lost interest, as did Holzwasser himself.
``I've never been an enthusiast of mission statements,'' he says.
``I think they're kind of hokey.''
</P>
<P>
   To some they're inspirational exhortations, to others they're
useless boilerplate.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, the corporate mission statement has become as
commonplace in the business world as company letterhead. Like the
project proposal and the Microsoft Powerpoint presentation, the
writing of mission statements has been elevated to a management
art.
</P>
<P>
   Every firm from the smallest widget maker to the largest Fortune
500 company seems to have one. In fact, 9 out of 10 firms now have
them, compared to 1 out of 3 in 1985, estimates Tom Brown,
president of Management General, a Louisville consulting firm.
Companies have embraced the statements, emblazoned on everything
from plaques to coffee mugs, as an important marketing tool. An
entire industry of consultants has sprung up to help companies
develop mission statements.
</P>
<P>
   But naysayers argue the statements are balderdash.
</P>
<P>
   Arrow's mission statement, which Holzwasser says is languishing
forgotten on a lobby wall, has gone the route of similar
declarations at other &UR;  &LR; companies, promulgated with great enthusiasm
before slipping into a haze of management buzzword-speak. While
mission statements became hot earlier this decade, today's
employees say they don't always need a formal code to understand
the inner meaning of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Today's mission statements read like a corporate wish list,
citing companies' commitment to lofty &UR;  &LR; ideals such as ethics,
customer satisfaction, employee development, diversity, and
devotion to the larger community. More cynical hopes for the bottom
line also often creep into mission statements.
</P>
<P>
   Michael L. Lovdal, a vice president with Mercer Management
Consulting in Lexington, Mass. who has worked on numerous mission
statements with clients, has identified what he calls the
``third-third-third rule.'' About one-third of businesses ``have a
mission statement, believe in it, use it as a reference,'' he says.
Another third ``have one but can't find it,'' while the remaining
third scoff at the whole idea, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The typical corporate candidate for a mission statement is a
troubled firm, which, ``as a result of increased competition or
market changes, has to do something different,'' says Dani Monroe,
president of Center Focus International, a Boston consulting firm
which helps businesses write mission statements and develop
employee diversity plans.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting a mission statement can be a drawn-out process, and
large firms often hire consultants like Monroe to help out.
Consultants can charge between $2,000 and $5,000 a &UR;  &LR; day to work on
mission &UR;  &LR; statement projects, Monroe says.
</P>
<P>
   Often, however, founders go it alone. At Staples Inc., chief
executive Thomas G. Stemberg came up with the mission statement
when he founded the company in 1986, according to Ronald L.
Sargent, president of North American operations for the
Westborough, Mass. office supply giant. Every employee at Staples
is issued &UR;  &LR; a laminated, wallet-sized card bearing the statement _
``Slashing the cost and hassle of running your office!''
</P>
<P>
   Collecto Inc., a Norwell, Mass. debt management firm, &UR;  &LR; pledges
in founder and president Paul E. Leary's words ``to provide
receivable services within the highest ethical and moral
standards.'' And employees at the bill collecting company say they
see it as an inspirational missive from the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to go out into the marketplace and sell our service,
you have to believe in what you're selling,'' says Thomas M. Walsh,
a Collecto marketing manager who keeps a copy of the mission
statement on the wall of his cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   But not all companies write mission statements as a gospel for
employees. Companies for which a mission statement is primarily a
publicity tool may farm the drafting process out to marketing
consultants or internal &UR;  &LR; advertising departments. At Converse Inc.,
the North Reading, Mass. shoe manufacturer, the romantic-sounding
mission statement _ ``Everything we do is a tribute to the athletes
who gave birth to their sport, to those who made it great and those
who re-invent it every day'' _ formed part of a new advertising
campaign &UR;  &LR; and was launched at a global sales meeting in December
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was drafted as part of an overall repositioning of the
company that we were working on from a strategic standpoint with
our marketing department and our ad agency,'' says Jennifer Murray,
vice president of marketing communications, who worked on the
statement. ``The writing was done by one of the head creative
directors.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But other firms try to turn mission statement writing &UR;  &LR; into a
consensus-building exercise. At Fairfield, Conn.-based General
Electric Co., tens of thousands of managers passing through the
company's retreat campus in Ossining, N.Y., between 1982 and 1992
contributed ideas to an emerging mission statement. Appearing for
the first time in a 1992 letter from chairman John F. Welch Jr.,
the ``GE Values'' declaration espouses a broad vision of happiness
for all.
</P>
<P>
   According to the statement, GE's managers, among other tenets,
``have a passion for excellence and hate bureaucracy,'' ``live
quality ... and drive cost and speed for competitive advantage,''
``have global brains ... and build diverse and global teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants say the statements require several key components.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you first try to do is figure out what you're better at
than anybody else in the universe, what they call `core
competencies,' '' says Robert H. Woosley, a managing member of
Lumen Consulting LLC in Atlanta, who has helped several corporate
clients write mission statements. ``Then you think about the trends
in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of this mix comes some pronouncement on the company's
strategy or future. Collecto's mission statement promises that the
firm will, among other things, ``accomplish unparalleled results
anchored by a philosophy of performance and client commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   But buzzwords tend to lace mission statements as well. Overused
lingo such as ``constituencies,'' ``clear customer focus,''
``effective use of technology,'' ``empower,'' and
``accountability'' crops up frequently.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Once the mission statement is written, executives face the
task of selling it to employees. Often, the chief execuitve calls
an employee meeting to formally present the statement, which can
also appear in the company newsletter, on its Web &UR;  &LR; site, or on a
lobby plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, however, make their mission statements public
with a flair. At Converse, each shoe bears a modified version of
the mission statement printed on the inside of the tongue. Lovdal,
the Mercer consultant, recalls that one client printed the firm's
mission statement on every coffee cup in the cafeteria. Woosley,
the Atlanta consultant, says he has seen mission statements on
pens &UR;  &LR; and t-shirts as well as the bottom of company letterhead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But gimmicks only go so far toward convincing doubters, who
think mission statements are pointless at best and laughable at
worst. Some workers say a mission statement simply states the
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows basically what they should be doing, but this
gives them a road map for what they can expect from us and what we
expect from them,'' says John A. Yezerski, general manager of a
Staples store in Boston, where the firm's mission statement is
posted in the employee break room and on the management suite's
doors.
</P>
<P>
   And others &UR;  &LR; question the necessity of having a mission statement
at all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At GE's aircraft engines and parts factory in Lynn, Mass.,
union leader Richard F. Casilli says the corporate mission
statement has little relevance for the factory's 3,000 workers who
are members of Local 201 of the International Union of Electronic,
Electrical, Salaried, Machine and Furniture Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think that's routine corporate talk, always
talking about productivity and efficiency and the global market,''
says the local's business agent. ``People are a little more
practical-minded at our plant. We're focused on making good
engines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
