u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-14 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OUT AGAINST SEXUAL HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the classes she holds at companies across the country,
consultant Natalie Camper tells a story about a female employee
who, after enduring six years of lewd behavior and suggestive
comments, finally confronted her harassers.
</P>
<P>
   But when the woman threatened to report her colleagues to the
firm's human resources department, the men turned to her and said:
``Fine. We know where your car is, and we know where you live.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they would have gone so far as to damage her car or
break into her home, the threat changed the woman's mind. She
decided not to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   The story shows why so many women are reluctant to report sexual
harassment when it happens, and may wait until they are no &UR;  &LR; longer
employed at a worksite to come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's groundbreaking U.S. Supreme Court ruling seems
especially suited to tackling this type of problem. It requires
that employers do all they can to prevent sexual harassment. That
means encouraging workers to come forward with their complaints .
</P>
<P>
   The justices ruled that employers could be held liable for
sexual harassment by a supervisor even if the abuse was never
reported to top management. The court also said that employers
could be held liable for threats a supervisor makes against a
worker for complaining about sexual harassment or for refusing
sexual attentions, even if no action is ever taken and the threats
are not carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Using a set of guidelines that supporters are hoping will
revolutionize the workplace, the justices' goal seemed to be
two-fold: To help employers do the right thing by developing and
instituting a policy with zero tolerance for harassment, and making
victims feel safe enough to put aside their qualms and come
forward.
</P>
<P>
   But will victims speak up?
</P>
<P>
   Camper, president of The Camper Group, a workplace consulting
firm, says the high court decision is hardly a panacea. She
believes most women will continue to balk at coming forward with a
complaint for fear their livelihoods _ even their lives _ will be
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the firings and demotions that may occur when women
complain, fear of physical harm still ranks as major &UR;  &LR;  deterrent.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a series of workplace studies on retaliation, Working Woman
magazine &UR;  &LR; found that 25 percent of working women who are sexually
harassed use their leave time to avoid uncomfortable situations; 15
percent quit their jobs because they fear retaliation; &UR;  &LR; and 50
percent try to ignore the offending behavior , with such serious
results as a 10 percent drop in productivity, increased stress; and
a loss in productivity among &UR;  &LR;  the women who work with them.
</P>
<P>
   Although retaliation is against most state and federal laws, it
can take extremely subtle forms, making it difficult to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, for example, the harasser is a `good old boy' who is
highly respected,'' says Camper, ``the woman learns that if she
reports to him she will be viewed as a troublemaker and the result
could very well be the loss of a career. The other problem is this:
The higher you go in a company or the more you've achieved, the
more you are expected to smile and go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Camper: ``For the woman at the top, the risk is even
greater because the losses are greater. The risk for them means
loss of reputation and loss of prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Take neurosurgeon Frances Conley. For 25 years, she put up with
demeaning remarks and harassment from male colleagues at Stanford
University's Medical School. Fearing her career would be damaged if
she spoke up, Conley said nothing. When she finally spoke up, she
was blacklisted by some prominent members of her profession who
felt she was making an unnecessary fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I put up with it as long as I did is I really
wanted to advance. You put up with a lot to try and be one of the
crowd,'' Conley says in ``Sexual Harassment on the Job: What It Is
&AMP; How To Stop It,'' (Nolo Press, January 1998, $18.95).
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where small employers were advised to adopt
sexual harassment guidelines two years ago, the June 26 US Supreme
Court ruling should reinforce what many ought to know: Companies
that take an aggressive stance against sexual harassment have less
to fear than employers who do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis is a Boston Globe staff member. She can be
reached at The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107, or by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
