<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-14 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORONADO ON QUEST TO JOIN 3-YEAR-OLD STUDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest, who easily won the $150,000 Dwyer Stakes at
Belmont Park Sunday, is ready to take on the big boys, and the big
boys, Real Quiet and Victory Gallop, may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Forty Niner, out of a Damascus mare, Coronado's Quest
ended 1997 by winning the Cowdin, Nashua, and Remsen, all at
Aqueduct, and went to Florida this winter stamped a prime Triple
Crown threat. As soon as Coronado's Quest saw the palm trees,
however, he flipped, literally. He would not behave in the paddock
or post parade, alternating between refusing to move and bucking
and rearing, in the Hutcheson, Fountain of Youth, or Florida Derby,
all at Gulfstream, and he lost each one.
</P>
<P>
   Shug McGaughey, who trains Coronado's Quest for owner Stuart
Janney, declared him out of the Kentucky Derby after the debacle in
the sun. McGaughey, a top horsemen, feared Coronado's Quest would
either kill himself or somebody else if he threw one of his
tantrums in the midst of the Kentucky Derby mob scene.
</P>
<P>
   But something else happened after Coronado's Quest finished a
disappointing fifth in the Kentucky Derby. It was discovered he had
an entrapped epiglottis. The handsome chestnut is undefeated since
an operation cured the problem, winning the Wood Memorial at
Aqueduct and the Riva Ridge at Belmont prior to the Dwyer. Perhaps
more important, he hasn't acted up since the surgery. McGaughey has
a theory that Coronado's Quest might have frozen up going to the
track to race because he knew when he ran, he wouldn't be able to
breathe properly. He thinks fear may have caused his bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Coronado's Quest has been unchallenged since
returning to New York. It wasn't so much that he won the Dwyer over
four hopelessly overmatched foes, it was how he won it. He broke
alertly under Mike Smith from post No. 3, settled nicely along the
rail, took over during the run down the backstretch and showed his
superiority turning for home, drawing away to tally by 5 lengths at
odds of 2-5 ($2.90 to win). The time for the mile and one-16th was
1:422/5.
</P>
<P>
   ``This colt is a bomb,'' said Smith. ``He ran great and gave a
real professional performance. He loaded well, broke well, and
behaved perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a bruised foot, suffered the morning before the race, kept
Coronado's Quest out of the Preakness, in which he had been made
the morning line favorite. The same bruise made it impossible for
McGaughey to train him hard enough to make the Belmont Stakes, at 1
1/2 miles, and he instead dominated the 7-furlong Riva Ridge on the
Belmont undercard. Having missed the entire Triple Crown, as Real
Quiet defeated Victory Gallop in the Derby and the Preakness before
Victory Gallop turned the tables in the Belmont, Coronado's Quest
will now get his chance to turn the Big 2 of the 3-year-old
division into the Big 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to consider the Dwyer one of his best races so far,''
said McGaughey, whose charge has a career record of 12-8-2-0 and
$860,790 in earnings. ``The Haskell (Aug. 9 against Real Quiet and,
perhaps, Victory Gallop) will be an interesting race for him and
we'll probably go to Monmouth a few days beforehand just to school
him in the paddock.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the knocks on Coronado's Quest is that he's only won in
New York. He's 2 for 3 at Saratoga, 4 for 4 at Aqueduct, and 2 for
2 at Belmont. This is the same criticism that was leveled at Easy
Goer, also trained by McGaughey, who captured only one race outside
of the Big Apple (the Swale at Gulfsteam) in his distinguished
career. However, what the critics fail to mention is that the
racing surfaces at Saratoga, Aqueduct, and Belmont are all
distinctly different, having nothing in common other than being
located in the same state.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet and Victory Gallop are both big-hearted horses, but
Coronado's Quest presents a challenge to their dominance because he
has two things they don't _ high early speed and a touch of
brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Weighty issue
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations between Sonny Hine, trainer of Skip Away, and
Monmouth officials, which led to the Aug. 30 Iselin Handicap being
lengthened from a mile and one-16th to a 1 1/8 miles, and enriched
from a purse of $250,000 to $500,000, revealed that trainers of top
handicap horses are often told how much weight their horse will be
assigned to carry far in advance of the official announcement. This
is a well-known but seldom discussed fact of life in the handicap
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away carried 130 pounds to victory in the Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk Downs, setting a track record of 1:471/5 for 9
furlongs in an outstanding performance. At the time, Hine thought
that would be Skip Away's final race in a handicap event. He was
planning on the Hollywood Gold Cup, Pacific Classic, Woodward
Stakes, Jockey Club Gold Cup, and Breeders's Cup Classic to round
out the 5-year-old Skip Away's career. Each of those races is
weight-for-age.
</P>
<P>
   However, after shipping from his Belmont base to Hollywood to
win the Gold Cup, Skip Away, who has been something of an iron
horse, came back tired and Hine decided not to ship him back to
California for the Aug. 15 Pacific Classic at Del Mar. That's when
negotiations over the Iselin began and an official told Hine that
Skip Away would be asked to carry 131 pounds, the minimum 1-pound
raise over the MassCap, in the New Jersey race. Frankly, Skip Away
was so brilliant in the MassCap he should have been given 135
pounds for the Iselin, but then Hine would not have run him. So,
hey, how about 132 pounds, at least?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of running a mile and one-16th,'' said
Hine. ``It's not fair to the horse. They want him to carry 131
pounds in the Iselin. It wouldn't be fair if he had to do that
sprinting. The horse has got to come first.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kulina, vice president and general manger at Monmouth,
acknowledged he had discussed the weight assignment with Hine.
``It's very unfair to talk about that until you know who you are
weighing, but, in this day and age, a 1-pound pick up is about what
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the purse, Hine wanted the increase because it will help
him in his quest to have Skip Away pass Cigar as the greatest North
American money-earner in history. He feels if Skip Away can
accomplish that feat, the Eclipse Award voters will be hard-pressed
to deny Skip Away the Horse of the Year crown he missed last year,
when 2-year-old Favorite Trick won in a controversial vote.
Two-time Horse of the Year Cigar earned $9,999,815, while Skip
Away, who was 3-year-old champion and then handicap champion, has
earned $8,906,360.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave my word that I would come if they changed the distance
of the race and if the purse put me in the position to win $10
million with Skip Away before the Breeders's Cup, and my word is my
bond,'' said Hine. ``If we just won the Woodward and the Jockey
Club Gold Cup, it would only give us $900,000, and we need just
over $1 million to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes made by Monmouth helped pursuade Hine to pass on the
$400,000 Whitney Handicap at Saratoga Aug. 8. Hine ran Skip Away,
who is currently on a seven-race winning streak, in both the
Whitney, in which he finished third, and the Iselin, in which he
finished second, last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know if I push for the Whitney, I'll be pushing too hard,''
said Hine. ``He's coming back to himself but he won't breeze for
awhile. With the Iselin being Aug. 30, I have a lot of time to work
on his feet and his legs and get everything perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Bearhart' is no bear
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chief Bearhart, who won the Eclipse Award as the best grass
horse in North America last year and was also Horse of the Year in
Canada, was upset in the $150,000 Bowling Green Handicap at Belmont
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a strong closing win in the Manhattan Handicap on the
Belmont Stakes undercard, Chief Bearhart was away at 3-10 under 124
pounds and Jose Santos, but was compromised by a slow pace and
could do no better than third, beaten a toal of 4 1/4 lengths.
Santos sat last off a pace that saw 6 furlongs run in 1:144/5 and a
mile run in 1:382/5, and Chief Bearhart could not make up enough
ground through the stretch. Cetewayo, a 9-1 shot ($21.20 to win)
who once ran for a $13,000 claiming tag, and John Velasquez
prevailed by 2 lengths over 16-1 chance Officious and Aaron Gryder
in the time of 2:13 2/5 for a 1 3/8 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those things,'' said Mark Frostad, who
trains Chief Bearhart. ``There was too slow of an early pace and he
just didn't get moving soon enough. The weight he carried may also
have been a factor. He gave somewhat of a mediocre performance. He
fired, it was just that he did it too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Chief Bearhart, who took the $2 million Breeders's Cup
Turf last year, will be the $300,000 Sword Dancer Handicap at
Saratoga Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Free House is back
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free House, who was an outstanding 3-year-old last year, made a
smashing 1998 debut Saturday, winning the $100,000 Bel Air Handicap
at Hollywood by 7 lengths. Bet down to 4-5 ($3.60 to win) in his
first race since bleeding in the Super Derby last September, Free
House and pilot Chris McCarron did not disappoint, laying second
through fast fractions before taking over turning for home to score
in 1:413/5 for the mile and one-16th.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Free House won the Santa Anita Derby and the Swaps, and
he ran 3-2-3, respectively, in the Kentucky Derby, Preakness, and
Belmont. If he has returned to full form, he will be a serious
player in the handicap ranks and he appears headed for the Pacific
Classic, where he would take on the dynamic duo of stablemates
Gentlemen and Puerto Madero, and, maybe, Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   I was worried about bleeding because he bled in the Super Derby,
but he looks pretty good,'' said trainer Paco Gonzalez. ``He looks
like he's not stressed. I think he is more mature now. He's
stronger, more relaxed. We hope he stays this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
