<P>
   Coupon savings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coupon books offer consumers ways to save on travel,
entertainment, dining, and shopping. Manhattan Today and Boston
Today are the newest offerings to the public. Both coupon books
have been around for about 10 years but only through corporations
and conventions. Each book is keyed to the city on the cover. Among
the savings offered are a US Airways Shuttle fare of $82 to Boston,
New York, or Washington (regularly $205 each way), discounts on
museums, tours, two-for-one entrees at a variety of restaurants,
and shopping discounts.The current Manhattan Today ($10) is valid
to Oct. 15 and Boston Today ($6) to Nov. 30; new issues will be
valid for six months. For more information or to buy a copy, call
800-685-6760 or 212-685-6700 (New York) or 617-720-2277 (Boston).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iron age walk
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A walk to explore the age of iron in Connecticut takes place
Aug. 15. The Blackberry River walk in the Litchfield Hills of East
Canaan celebrates 190 years of the area's iron history when as many
as 32 blast furnaces operated 24 hours a day along the river and
streams of the region. Historians will be along the walk, which
takes place 9 a.m. to noon, to explain the sites. For information
on the walk, other things to do, where to stay, and more, call the
Litchfield Hills Travel Council at 860-567-4506.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive lodging
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An inexpensive way to travel is to stay at a hostel. Among the
newest hostels associated with Hostelling International-American
Youth Hostels are two summer hostels in Madison, Wis, and
Searsport, Maine, and a year-round one in Middlebury, Vt. The
Madison hostel is located in Langdon Residence Hall near the
University of Wisconsin-Madison and offers beds at $13 and private
rooms at $25 (call 608-285-8536). The Searsport hostel has 10 beds
at $15 each. Call 207-548-2506. The Covered Bridge Home Hostel in
Middlebury has fees of $13 to $15 a night. Call 802-388-0401.
Hostels offer dorm-style accommodations for all ages and welcome
nonmembers, who pay an additional $3 a night. For information on
hostels, write to HI-AYA, 733 15th St. NW, Washington, DC 20005, or
call 202-783-6161. The association encompasses nearly 5,000 hostels
in 70 countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Authors to gather
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Times of London calls it ``the place where writers of the
world unite,'' and the Los Angeles Times says it's the ``Olympics
of Literature.'' The event is Toronto's International Festival of
Authors. The 19th annual edition of the largest festival of its
kind in the world will be held Oct. 21-31. More than 60 authors are
expected to participate in some 100 events ranging from readings to
interviews. Authors from around the world will be participating.
Most events will be held at or near the Harbourfront Centre, with
tickets priced from $8.50 to $25 Canadian. For tickets, call
416-973- 4000.
</P>
