<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR THINKS ELECTROMAGNETISM DOWNED FLIGHT 800 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is looking into the
possibility that the crash of TWA 800 on July 17, 1996, whose cause
has still not been pinpointed, might have been the result of
electromagnetic interference _ perhaps put out by high-powered
radar systems on nearby Navy ships.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility was first raised in an article and letters by
Harvard University professor of English Elaine Scarry that were
published in the New York Review of Books. James E. Hall, head of
the safety board, said in a letter responding to Scarry's article
that the board ``has considered the possibility'' that some form of
electromagnetic interference ``was a factor in the accident,'' and
that the possibility is still under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Scarry suggested that such interference, perhaps put out by one
of at least 10 military craft known to have been in the immediate
area, could have triggered the fatal spark believed to have ignited
fuel in the plane's central fuel tank. While investigators have
identified that tank as the likely point of origin of the
explosion, they have not yet been able to identify a source of
ignition.
</P>
<P>
   Scarry, though she has no personal expertise in technology or
electromagnetic systems, cites several specialists who have
endorsed her conclusion that this possibility should be taken
seriously, including physicists at Harvard, Yale, and the
California Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of those physicists, Yale University professor of biophysics
Robert Shulman, said in an interview Monday that ``there are many
ways'' that electromagnetic radiation ``could interfere with the
electronics'' of a commercial plane and that ``the investigation
should include that possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Such electromagnetic interference, while it had not been
publicly mentioned as a possible factor in the TWA 800 crash until
Scarry's article, is well known in military circles as a potential
hazard to airplane navigation systems. For example, a 1992 article
in the trade magazine Aviation Week and Space Technology said that
several US Army helicopter crashes since 1982 ``are thought to have
resulted from interference with flight control systems when flying
near radar or communications transmitters.''
</P>
<P>
   That article said the military was carrying out extensive
research to develop ways of protecting aircraft control systems
against such interference and to develop electronic weapons
designed to direct such interference deliberately toward target
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Rear Admiral (retired) Eugene Carroll,
now deputy director of the Center for Defense Information in
Washington, said he once encountered problems with a shipboard
navigation radar that would occasionally fail for no apparent
reason, leaving the Navy ship he commanded without needed
navigation information. It turned out that the failures were the
result of interference from a different transmitter aboard the same
ship, which was only used intermittently.
</P>
<P>
   That transmitter ``was just overwhelming the radar,'' Carroll
said, but it took a long time to pinpoint the equipment as the
problem's source because of its intermittent usage.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said that such interference, while long recognized as a
potential hazard in the Navy, ``was always ambiguous and
undefined.'' He said that precautions were routinely taken to guard
against it, especially during sensitive operations such as the
loading of munitions, but that there was no clear understanding of
exactly what situations or instruments might produce dangerous
results.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that Aegis-class radars on modern Navy ships have
``a very powerful array, they send out a very concentrated beam''
of electromagnetic radiation. There were four Navy ships close to
the scene at the time of the TWA 800 crash.
</P>
<P>
   A sufficiently powerful electromagnetic field can induce a
current in any piece of wire or metal that it crosses, and if that
current is sufficiently large it can sometimes produce a spark.
</P>
<P>
   Carrol said that in the case of that crash, ``it's not
impossible that the configuration was unique'' because of specific
arragements of wiring onboard, possible cracks or wear in
insulation, and the exact position and orientation relative to a
source of radio emissions, and that ``some fluke event occurred
which induced a spark and brought the plane down.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators ``at least ought to look at the potential emitters
out there, the potential sources,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the board said Monday that ``we are looking''
into the possibility of such sources. But he added that the NTSB's
director of aviation safety, Bernard Loeb, said that ``we have
looked at electromagnetic interference from the outset of this
investigation. We feel that the likelihood of an external source of
EMI causing the explosion of TWA flight 800 is extremely remote.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeb added that ``due to our interest in EMI and its effect on
aviation in general,'' the board has asked a military agency
responsible for keeping track of military equipment and
transmissions ``to further investigate possible external sources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
