<HEADLINE>
JUST WHAT EVERY 16-HANDICAPPER NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the upcoming PGA gonzo golf gig at Sahalee at
Redmond, Wash., next month, I thought I'd get one of those
limited-edition American Bison Leather golf bags that go for a mere
$1,850 per, plus tax, shipping and instructional video tape on how
to avoid interacting with whatever live bison that might appear in
the rough.
</P>
<P>
   This might not do a lot to dispel the notion that golf is a game
for the well-to-do, but American sports fans have always needed a
little pizazz in their respective pastimes, a little class. And you
sure ain't going to get it from Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I'm going to put it on the expense account because the
P-I has pulled out all the stops for coverage on this tournament.
The bag will be useful for carrying my lunch, thermos, sun
umbrella, cell phone and P-I subscription order blanks.
</P>
<P>
   The genuine bison bags _ advertised as a ``must for the
collector or serious golfer!'' _ number only 250, meaning a whole
lot of collectors and serious golfers will have to settle for
crocodile, kangaroo, ostrich or spotted owl skin bags because there
won't be enough to go around.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll stand out when I get out of the limo at Sahalee and walk
around to the trunk to personally unload my American Bison Leather
golf bag, made by the Denver Buffalo Co. The purists among you will
of course note that the American bison is not considered a true
buffalo, partly because of its large head and the fact that it has
14 pairs of ribs instead of the 13 pairs in so-called true buffalo.
But when you've been reduced to a golf bag, the distinction blurs
somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   To mollify those animal rights people, I'll not use the matching
leather club-head covers that look remarkably like bison hooves
sticking up out of the bag on the ends of skinny bison legs.
Instead, in a women's golf catalog, I've found an assortment of
``darling animal-head covers to protect your finest woods or
putters.''
</P>
<P>
   For a mere $24 each (only $9 per for putter size), I'm ordering
the whole darling collection so that my bison bag will be festooned
with the brightly colored fuzzy heads of little beavers, tigers,
Dalmatians, elephants, mallards, lobsters, gorillas, gophers, pigs
and walrus.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of graphite-shaft clubs, titanium club heads and bison
leather bags hits home before you even tee off. But there are
hidden costs to the after-golf life as well, as revealed in the
same women's golf-related-stuff catalog.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is the $65 polished chrome ``golf iron toilet
paper holder'' and the $20 bathroom plunger (``Lucite handle houses
multi-colored golf tees ... plunger topped with golf ball. Great
idea for tournament prizes.'').
</P>
<P>
   There's one more item that, in all honesty, seems a tad
extravagant. But when I saw it advertised in the same magazine as
the bison leather golf bag, I knew I just had to have: an Orbita
automatic Watchwinder. This nifty little gizmo keeps your
self-winding watch wound while you are busy playing golf, sleeping
or watching golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   It does electrically what your rotating wrist movement does, and
that keeps your ticker ticking. Your watch fits over a little
stubby shaft in a case that is heated ``to maintain your watch at
body temperature to prevent condensation.''
</P>
<P>
   And for $495 _ plus shipping and handling _ you can get an
Orbita single-watch case in fine hardwood with a choice of
lacquered emerald green, pecan, cherry, natural or cobalt blue
finish, or with a see-through glass top.
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to have three self-winding watches in need of
constant winding and temperature control in a black suede-lined
box, you can get the triple-head case for a mere $1,095, plus tax
and handling.
</P>
<P>
   I'll have to write for the bison leather golf bag accessories
catalog to see if they offer a compact electrical generator for my
watch-winding case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
