<HEADLINE>
ENVOY HEADING TO MEXICO TO FILL LONG-VACANT AMBASSADOR'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A career American diplomat will head to Mexico
City later this month to become the U.S. ambassador, filling a key
position that has been vacant for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Jeffrey Davidow will end an often-rocky interval
of without an ambassador to the country considered to be
Washington's most important foreign policy concern.
</P>
<P>
   The previous envoy, James Jones, resigned in June 1997 to accept
a job as president of the international division of the New
York-based Warnaco Group, which, among other things, manufactures
women's underwear at factories based in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's first choice, former Massachusetts Gov.
William Weld, was blocked by Senate Foreign Relations Committee
Jesse Helms. Helms, R-N.C., objected to his fellow Republican's
more liberal views on social issues and the use of marijuana for
medical purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Burned by the rejection of Weld, Clinton took his time looking
for a second choice before deciding on Davidow, a career diplomat
with experience in several Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow won easy Senate confirmation on June 26. A spokeswoman
said he would be sworn in on July 21 and head to his new posting
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   During the gap without an ambassador, U.S. relations with Mexico
hit bumps that an ambassador might have helped smooth, most
recently with the case of Operation Casablanca, a sweeping
money-laundering sting.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin stunned Mexican officials in late May when they announced
that 22 Mexican bankers had been arrested after the three-year
money-laundering investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities soon discovered that at least some
undercover work had been conducted in Mexico, without Mexican
permission, Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   An angered President Ernesto Zedillo ordered a full
investigation into possible illegal activities and Foreign Minister
Rosario Green told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that
extradition would be sought for U.S. agents suspected of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Congress passed a near-unanimous resolution supporting
the investigation and prohibiting the extradition of American
agents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
