<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE WHO LOVE LUCY STICK TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a granddaughter who is crazy about Lucille Ball. Is
there a fan club she can join?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.M., Stephenville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the most popular is the We Love Lucy Fan Club at Box
56234, Sherman Oaks, CA 91413.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old club costs $20 per year and offers a newsletter,
photographs and membership card, said Tom Watson, the club's
president. Send a self-addressed, stamped envelope for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   Another place for those who love Lucy is the Lucy-Desi Museum in
Jamestown, N.Y., Ball's hometown. The museum, which was started two
years ago, includes video clips of ``I Love Lucy,'' items from
Ball's wardrobe and audio remembrances from relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Lucy-Desi Museum, 116 E. Third
St., Jamestown, NY 14701.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm trying to find a singer whose biggest hit was
``Honeycomb.'' I thought it might be Johnny Horton. Do you know who
it is?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.B., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Honeycomb was a No. 1 hit for Jimmie F. Rodgers, a singer
with 18 hits on the charts in the '50s and '60s. All of them are
collected on the 1992 album ``The Best of Jimmie Rodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers is sometimes confused with his namesake, the country
music legend Jimmie Rodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the Biblical verse that Detective Andy Sipowicz read
at the end of an ``NYPD Blue'' episode this past season? _ E.F.,
Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: At the end of the two-part episode ``Lost Israel,'' Sipowicz
(Dennis Franz) read an excerpt about faith: Psalms 119:81-88.
</P>
<P>
   ABC answered this and other frequently asked questions about the
show on its ``NYPD Blue'' Web site at
www.abc.com/primetime/nypd_blue.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
