A4060 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-TEXAS-TEX     07-14 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY INVESTMENTS EXPANDS PLANS FOR SITE IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE, Texas _ Fidelity Investments has disclosed
dramatically ambitious plans for a Westlake office campus, filing
proposals to build a 3.4 million-square-foot complex that could
accommodate more than 10,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based company aims to double its North Texas work
force, Fidelity officials acknowledged Monday. But they declined to
detail plans for the Westlake campus, which would be one of the
largest corporate campuses in Texas, rivaling Plano's sprawling
Electronic Data Systems campus, which is 3.5 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have specific information to give out. Until we can
review those details with city officials, it's not appropriate for
us to discuss it publicly,'' said Lori Hanes, communications
manager for Fidelity operations in Irving. ``In terms of future
growth, we do anticipate possibly doubling our work force in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the negotiations for the Westlake site say the
company is considering relocating some units from Boston and other
out-of-state sites here.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move could offer the company tremendous savings, Dallas
economist Peter Malin suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, in an annual report, J.C. Penney stated they were
going to save $30 million a year by moving from New York to
Dallas,'' Malin said. ``If Fidelity is moving people from Boston or
other high-cost areas, you can see how this makes sense for them to
consolidate here near the airport or on a campus designed for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax incentives also might play a role in the company's decision.
Fidelity, the nation's No. 1 manager of mutual funds, has a track
record for sparking tax break competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity officials in Boston said they did not know of any plan
to relocate units to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ... (Fidelity) has been a highly visible corporate
citizen in Boston,'' said Ed O'Donald, a spokesman for Boston's
economic development department. ``I think they will continue to
make their home in Boston. But anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Fidelity, Massachusetts has begun offering tax
relief to mutual fund companies to persuade them to keep and create
jobs in the state. In April, for example, Fidelity's Investments
Institutional Services, which handles investments for institutional
clients, began moving workers to Smithfield, R.I., from locations
in Massachusetts. The company garnered tax breaks, credits against
lease payments and bonds floated by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The company has ``had discussions'' about seeking incentives
from Texas for its project, Hanes said, but she declined to
elaborate. The company has also sought aggressive tax breaks from
area taxing entities, most recently approaching Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Fidelity's plans in Westlake are contained in
documents that Fidelity filed with the town as part of its
application for rezoning approvals.
</P>
<P>
   According to the plans, the mutual fund giant initially wants to
build 600,000 square feet of offices, then expand it to 3.4 million
square feet by 2003 _ and to 6.8 million square feet by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Two Grapevine Mills malls would fit under the roofs of the
Fidelity project. Still, most of the Fidelity buildings would be no
higher than 5 stories, according to the plans.
</P>
<P>
   That facility is significantly larger than indicated by the
company last week, when it said that it wanted to build a campus in
Westlake to consolidate as many as 2,700 regional employees from
six offices in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   An aerial sketch included with the filing shows the proposed
campus fronting Texas 114 for almost a mile between Precinct Line
Road and Trophy Club Drive. The centerpiece tract would be Westlake
Mayor Scott Bradley's Paigebrooke Farm, with four major office
centers encircling a lake.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which boasts 24,000 employees worldwide, has divisions
in the Metroplex that include retail investor services, brokerage
services and an institutional retirement services company. This
spring, the firm began relocating about 60 employees from its
Kentucky regional division to Irving, where it has a regional
headquarters that employs 2,000. It also has a small office in
Westlake/Southlake at the Solana office park.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is seeking zoning approvals for a 311-acre Westlake
site that it has contracted to buy on Bradley's property and Ross
Perot Jr.'s Circle T Ranch. Westlake set a July 27 public hearing
to consider the proposal, which would allow Fidelity additional
leeway in developing within the town's master plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the massive deal, valued at $35 million in land purchases
alone, faces significant hurdles with Fort Worth and Roanoke, both
of which claim a stake in Perot's 2,500-acre Circle T Ranch after
its contested disannexation from Westlake last year. In recent
weeks, Fidelity, Perot and Westlake officials have lobbied Fort
Worth and Roanoke to drop their legal claims and cede the ranch
back to Westlake.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has said that Fort Worth makes or breaks the deal. In
return for giving up what is viewed as a billion-dollar economic
plum, Fort Worth officials say they need something ``substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Fort Worth officials downplayed the fact that
Fidelity's campus proposal is drastically larger than originally
thought. Assistant City Manager Mike Groomer said he did not expect
the city's position regarding the Circle T to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it materially changes the specifics and the
impact it will have on Fort Worth,'' he said. ``Fundamentally,
we're still talking about the same issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Westlake's appeal, Fidelity has said, is that the town
does not levy a property tax. Still, Fidelity also has received
informal assurances from Carrollton and The Colony to extend
10-year, 90 percent tax abatements on the Austin Ranch, another
site contender.
</P>
<P>
   James Spriggs, director of the Greater Irving/Las Colinas
Chamber of Commerce, said he and Irving Mayor Morris Parrish have
met with Fidelity officials to try to sway them to keep some
divisions in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great corporate citizen,'' Spriggs said. ``We told
them we would like to see what we can do to keep some of the
operation here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa McMillan, Tarrant County's economic development
coordinator, acknowledged that Fidelity had approached Tarrant
County about possible tax incentives during the last two weeks. But
county officials are also uneasy about the litigation and want it
resolved before extending any tax breaks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at what tax incentives are available for the
site,'' McMillan said. ``We're still concerned about the litigation
and want everything accelerated legally as far as the land. We
don't want to recognize one city over another.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
