<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     07-14 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY MEETING AUTHORS BEFORE THEIR DECLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having filled more than three decades on the books beat for
three newspapers in turn, I've been privileged to meet many notable
authors. (Privilege may not be the right word; not all authors _
notable or otherwise _ are lovable.)
</P>
<P>
   I name-drop authors for effect, and when someone exclaims of my
having met every author, I say, ``No, I've never met Saul Bellow,''
implying that my authorial dance card is otherwise filled.
</P>
<P>
   Counting perfunctory introductions and handshakes they've
forgotten and I haven't, I've met most American authors who count
with the literati, and a good many English and European types,
several South Americans, a few Asians, two eminent (white)
Africans, one Eskimo.
</P>
<P>
   Before I attained a professional foothold on the periphery of
the book-publishing world, I had lucky encounters with authors of
real consequence. I suspect divine intervention in two instances of
my childhood _ when Scott Fitzgerald bought me a movie magazine a
few days before he died, and when I played baseball catch with
William Faulkner, not knowing who he was.
</P>
<P>
   I've written about those encounters, and of having ogled Raymond
Chandler and James T. Cain dining together. Also noted were
memorable conversations in my days as a UCLA undergraduate _ with
Conrad Aiken, William Carlos Williams and T.S. Eliot in successive
weeks (along with some lesser poets on a prestige series). I also
met John Steinbeck on campus; interviewed Pearl Buck just before
her play ``A Desert Incident'' flopped on Broadway; and I saw
Sinclair Lewis riding in a car with his then-mistress Marcella
Powers, so I've done quite well with Nobel laureates.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two elbow-rubbings with authors that most impressed me
at those times were with men almost completely forgotten now,
although both were hot stuff in their coinciding heydays.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ames Williams came to my high school on a career-day-type
event to address students with light speculation on writing
careers. (That was University High in West Los Angeles, perhaps
most famous for having graduated, among others, Elizabeth Taylor
(after me), Ann Blyth and Roddy McDowall (before me), Anne Baxter
and Freddie Bartholomew (with my brother), Linda Darnell (with my
sister), Jane Powell (with me) and so many others; this
name-dropping is getting out of hand.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the wisdom imparted by Ben Ames Williams could be
summed up by the write-of-what-you-know cliche, I was awed by his
celebrity. After all, he had written ``All the Brothers Were
Valiant,'' which had regaled me during an adolescent preoccupation
with seafaring adventure. His ``Leave Her to Heaven'' had been a
whopping bestseller (later a hit movie), and high on the chart at
the time of our encounter was ``House Divided,'' Williams' Civil
War novel that was longer than ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, whose writing career spanned 35 years, was an
untarnished ``name'' author when he died in 1953 in his 65th year.
Robert Nathan, who left us only a few years ago, well into his 90s,
wrote nonstop for 60 years. (His debut novel, ``Peter Kindred,''
was published in 1919, the same year that introduced Williams with
``All the Brothers Were Valiant.''
</P>
<P>
   When I started college, Robert Nathan still was required reading
for English majors. I enjoyed his prose parables, so for me it was
a big deal when Nathan read from his own works in a convocation.
</P>
<P>
   He had been a vogue of the prewar years, turning out scores of
short novels in simple, direct language when most fiction was
long-winded. Fantasy was a frequent ingredient in Nathan's
parablelike tales, several of which were successfully filmed (''The
Bishop's Wife,'' ``One More Spring,'' ``Portrait of Jennie'' et
al.).
</P>
<P>
   Nathan's novelty value eroded as short novels in simple, direct
language became commonplace. Read his stuff today and wonder why
there ever was a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Sic transit gloria mundi.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
