<HEADLINE>
`SOMETHING ABOUT MARY' IS OFFENSIVE, BUT LOTS OF LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's crude, rude, lewd and totally politically incorrect but
yet still manages to make us laugh in spite of our better
instincts? It's the new Farrelly brothers movie, ``There's
Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   As in their past big screen irreverences, ``Dumb and Dumber''
and ``Kingpin,'' the brothers waste no time probing the depths of
bad taste and miraculously come up with something to offend just
about every walk of life while keeping everyone in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' suffers from the same
indecisions and irregularities in pace and rhythm of their previous
movies (could a critic dare say they're too ambitious in scope?).
</P>
<P>
   The Farrellys swear their film, at heart, is just a love story.
And, though it takes swipes at animals, the handicapped and just
about every other kind of socially conscious cause, it has a
goofily romantic heart, humor and canniness about the terrors of
love and vulnerability _ even though they're all presented in a
worst-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars Cameron Diaz, her real-life beau Matt Dillon, Ben
Stiller and a stable of the usual comedic supporting actors: Lee
Evans, Chris Elliott and the Farellys' ace-in-the-hole, the
game-for-anything actress Lin Shaye, who stole the show from Woody
Harrelson as his decadent landlady in ``Kingpin.'' And she nearly
steals the film again as Magda, Mary's overly tan and lascivious
roommate who dotes on her little dog just a bit too much.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Stroehmann (Stiller) has been in love with the beautiful,
perfect, Mother Teresa-ish _ and out of his league _ Mary Jenson
(Diaz) since high school. He once had a prom date with her but fate
prevailed _ he caught his privates in his tux zipper in a moment of
anxiety and it was then he discovered he was a bleeder.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years have passed and Ted is still in love with the
girl who got away. He hires a seedy, lying insurance private
investigator, Pat Healy (Dillon), to go to Miami and seek Mary out.
But a strange thing happens: Pat finds and falls for Mary, too.
Soon, it seems, everyone's in love with Mary and poor Ted may never
have a second chance with the only woman he's ever cared about.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the movie depends upon Mary being played by an actress
who has the right amount of allure and humanity. Diaz, who was
charming in ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' brings a buoyant, sweet
vulnerability to Mary. It's easy to see why these guys fall all
over themselves to be in her presence. Stiller and Dillon provide
ample backup as her erstwhile suitors and create a true, if odd,
chemistry as opposite sides of the same coin.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Farrellys clutter up the film with too much
peripheral business, the jokes are so unexpected and ingenious _
hair gel will never be looked at in the same way _ that they more
than compensate for the down time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, members of the audience at a preview screening were, for
the most part, way past 35 and were laughing themselves silly at
the inanities and anal humor that pervades the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's utterly offensive, ``There's Something About Mary''
manages to have a heart despite its disdain for convention.
Following ``The Truman Show'' and ``Bulworth,'' it may just be the
next movie to turn a tepid entertainment industry on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   There's Something About Mary. Directed by Peter and Bobby
Farrelly. Written by the Farrellys, Ed Dector, John J. Strauss.
Cast: Cameron Diaz, Matt Dillon, Ben Stiller. 20th Century Fox. 115
minutes. Rated R for language, nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
