<SLUG> BC-BIKE-COP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLICE FIND BIKES CAN BE A COP'S BEST FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITT  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALLSTON SPA, N.Y. _ When he was a child, Officer Michael J.
DeMartino loved riding his rust-colored Schwinn 10-speed. He never
dreamed then that he would have a career that enables him to patrol
on a black-and-gray 18-speed Smith &AMP; Wesson mountain bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the bike, I can stay in the shadows and observe drug use
or underage drinking,'' said DeMartino, a police officer in this
upstate New York village.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of police departments throughout the county are
using bikes to help fight crime.
</P>
<P>
   Officers like the bikes for several reasons, including low
maintenance costs and stealth. The police say they make arrests
that are not possible during a car or foot patrol because they can
sneak up on criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Officers say bikes are fun. Though they risk being taken less
seriously while furiously pedaling after someone, they say they are
more accessible to the public when out of the patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 police departments nationwide use bicycles, an
experiment that started when Seattle began using them in 1987,
according to John A. Fox, state instructor for the Law Enforcement
Bicycle Association. LEBA trainers annually conduct 2,000 40-hour
bicycle patrol safety courses for police departments in the United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some chiefs look at bikes as toys, or fun time,'' Fox said.
``It's not a fad anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Dominelli, executive director of the New York State
Association of Chiefs of Police, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody thinks the bike is a toy, they ought to put that
guy on the bike and let him see if it's a toy,'' Dominelli said.
``It's a hard job. And, you sit on that seat all day long, you know
you've been doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Albany bike Officer John L. Monte says that his arrest numbers
are higher since he began riding. ``Walking, I might do 15 arrests
per month; now on the bike, it's up to 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that bicycles bring officers closer to the people they
are supposed to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate 20 times more public contact for a bike cop versus
a car patrol; five times more than for a foot patrol officer,'' Fox
said. ``Officers add a heightened sense of hearing and smell to
their skill set, senses usually cut off in an air-conditioned
car.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albany police began their 12-bike program 10 months ago,
according to spokeswoman Lt. Lauren Signer. She said that bikes
fill a niche in fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a recent pursuit of a young male on a bike who had
cocaine packaged for sale in Arbor Hill,'' she said. ``Bicycles
give us the ability to deal with these criminals on their own
level. We're matching them in their mode of transport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bike is in between the beat and the car,'' Signer said,
adding that she enjoys the questions residents put to her officers.
``They ask, `How fast can the bike go?' They think it's got a
secret rocket on it or something.''
</P>
<P>
   But riding a bike can be dangerous, even for a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some minor knee swelling, and was back on the bike two
weeks later,'' said Monte, who collided with a sheriff's car last
April. He still prefers doing his tours on two wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can cover my whole zone six to 12 times per shift,'' said
Monte, who patrols Albany's South End.
</P>
<P>
   Police bikes with accessories, like helmets, uniforms, first-aid
kits and police lights for the handlebars, average $1,200 each;
unadorned police mountain bikes cost about $600.
</P>
<P>
   Officer John Kelly of the Saratoga Springs, N.Y., department
says the program is especially suited to his small community
outside Albany. ``The bikes have proven to be unbelievably flexible
in getting somewhere faster than a car, into the one-way streets
and narrow alleys that the city is full of.''
</P>
<P>
   Bike patrols give rise to unusual war stories: Kelly said he
once pulled over a Greyhound bus while on his two-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   ``He almost hit me. The riders were laughing and I was getting
thumbs up from the back of the bus as I wrote the ticket,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
