<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOMETHINGABOUTMARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SOMETHING DREADFUL ABOUT `MARY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you laughed at the little Benji dog in the full body cast in
the trailers for ``There's Something About Mary,'' you might find a
few more laughs in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you might get hit by a car and wind up in a full
body cast yourself _ a situation certainly preferable to shelling
out your hard-earned cash to sit through this dreck.
</P>
<P>
   Not that directors Peter and Bobby Farrelly have much of a track
record to recommend themselves. They found an unlikely cash cow in
the then relatively unknown Jim Carrey _ who managed to propel the
colossally stupid ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber'' (1994) to box-office success _
but faltered with their next effort, 1996's ``Kingpin,'' proving
that Woody Harrelson was more natural-born killer than comic.
</P>
<P>
   The brotherly boneheads have once again surrounded themselves
with an impressive variety of talent _ Ben Stiller, Matt Dillon,
Lee Evans, even the pretty-without-being-empty-headed Cameron Diaz
_ but that only succeeds in making audiences wonder what possessed
these people to appear in this garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller plays Ted, a high school dork whose gallant effort to
protect a mentally challenged youngster from a bully is rewarded
with a prom date with the boy's sister Mary (Diaz) _ who just
happens to be the school hottie.
</P>
<P>
   His dream date turns nightmarish when he manages to zip himself
up while using the facilities. The bit is actually funny for a
while, with Stiller subjected to a parade of wincing adults trying
to figure out how to undo the damage. But as there's no room for
subtlety in the Farrellys' world, you can count on a close-up shot
of the self-inflicted injury _ and that's actually one of the more
tasteful gags.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward more than a decade, and Ted's still pining for his
now long-lost love. Egged on by his ``happily married'' buddy Dom
(Chris Elliott), Ted hires a sleazy private eye to track her down.
Dillon does the honor, tracing her to Miami, but then tries to
sabotage things when he falls for her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Seems this is par for the course when it comes to Mary (there's
something about her, remember?). It turns out she's got an entire
platoon of obsessed suitors/stalkers who'll do or say anything to
have her.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems the Farrellys will do or say anything to make you
laugh at these idiots _ anything, that is, except stooping to, say,
wit. Even when they accidentally stumble onto something funny _
i.e. the attack on Stiller by the aforementioned Benji dog _ the
Farrellys' sledgehammer approach manages to bludgeon the bit long
after the laughs have expired.
</P>
<P>
   There are jokes at the expense of the disabled, mentally
retarded, women, gays and, of course, man's best friend. And for
anyone keeping tabs on the Farrelly scorecard of bodily function
jokes _ ``Mary'' should fill out the list nicely. There's enough
crass toilet humor here to make the entire run of Comedy Central's
``South Park'' seem like it was scripted by Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that will stop the maturity-challenged members of the
moviegoing public from flocking to the film and laughing themselves
hoarse at this nonsense. As always, there's no accounting for taste
_ or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``There's Something About Mary''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Peter and Bobby Farrelly
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ben Stiller, Cameron Diaz, Matt Dillon
</P>
<P>
   Length: 119 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ Crude humor, profanity, nudity and brain-damaging
subject matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7691. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
