<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; RED LOBSTER, WHITE TRASH AND THE BLUE LAGOON &QL; 
 &UR; Joe Queenan (Hyperion, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   Queenan managed for 14 years to avoid seeing the musical
``Cats''. Then he threw in the towel and attended a matinee. He
discovered that ``Cats'' was bad. Very, very bad. ``Cats'' was what
``Grease'' would look like if all the cast members dressed up like
KISS. He thought ``Cats'' would be the low point in his
experimental foray into popular culture, which he'd decided to make
after years of basking in urbane sophistication as a contributing
writer to ``GQ,'' ``George,'' ``Playboy'' and ``Movieline.'' Then
he bought a Michael Bolton record, and discovered that Bolton was
bad. Very, very bad. Bolton was ``Mandy Patinkin squared.'' Then
Queenan read ``The Horse Whisperer.'' Then he ate at Red Lobster.
This is his memoir of his time in America's cultural wasteland,
where he experienced, among other things, the Osmond Brothers,
Planet Hollywood, a Renaissance Faire, Taco Bell, ``Baywatch'' and
Yanni. It wasn't pretty, but it sure is funny. With his days in pop
culture over, would Queenan go back? ``I would rather spend 10
years in the Black Hole of Calcutta,'' he says. ``Twenty, even.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CAUGHT IN THE NET &QL; 
 &UR; Kimberly S. Young (Wiley, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   They don't know how old you are, they don't know how attractive
you are, and they can't tell whether you're shy or lonely. On the
Internet, you can be anything you want to be, for an audience of
people who are just as eager and invisible as you are. Proof of the
Internet's allure lies in the fact that there is a Center for
On-Line Addiction, which offers help to people who are compulsive
presences in chat rooms, have endless appetites for interactive
games and write e-mail by the hour. Here, Young, who founded the
center and is a psychology professor at the University of
Pittsburgh, offers advice on recognizing Internet addiction and
strategies for weaning yourself from your computer. If none of it
works, she invites you to write to her (ksy(at)pitt.edu) and tell
her all about it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FACES OF THE TWENTIETH CENTURY: MASTER PHOTOGRAPHERS AND THEIR
WORK &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Edward Harris (Abbeville, $45)
</P>
<P>
   This collection of work by 20 extraordinary photographers began
as a series of interviews done by Harris for ``Camera &AMP; Darkroom''
magazine. Each section opens with Harris' portrait of the
photographer (those of Annie Leibovitz and the late Alfred
Eisenstaedt are and were the artists' favorite pictures of
themselves). There are five signature works by each of the 20,
along with their thoughts on photography and anecdotes about how
the images were captured. Included are Andreas Feininger, Mary
Ellen Mark, Horace Bristol, Manuel Alvarez Bravo, Eve Arnold,
Helmut Newton, Peter Lindbergh, Marc Riboud, Carl Mydans, Joe
Rosenthal, Gordon Parks, Jean-Philippe Charbonnier, Edouard Boubat,
Eikoh Hosoe, Herb Ritts, Sebastiao Salgado, Jeanloup Sieff and
Elliott Erwitt. With an introduction by Vicki Goldberg, photography
critic for the New York Times. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; YELLOWSTONE AND THE BIOLOGY OF TIME &QL; 
 &UR; Mary Meagher and Douglas B. Houston (Oklahoma, $80)
</P>
<P>
   Meagher and Houston are retired research biologists who set out
more than 20 years ago to document landscape changes at Yellowstone
National Park by using repeat photography. They searched out
locations captured by early photographers (more than half of the
original images were taken before 1901) and rephotographed them in
the same place, and as near as possible to the same date and time
of day. In many cases, the authors made two sets of photographs of
each site, in the 1970s and again in the 1990s, to capture the
effects of the great fires of 1988. Their purpose was scientific:
to give some perspective on the vegetation changes that had
occurred historically in the park. But there's much more to
discover in these simple pictures, including a sense of how much
time is required to truly alter a landscape, and how ephemeral the
human presence has been in a place like Yellowstone. Roads and
ranches have disappeared, along with the men in cowboy hats who
roamed the grasslands on horseback. But not much else has changed.
On the cover is a 1971 photo of Minerva Terrace at Mammoth Hot
Springs, looking northwest to Sepulcher Mountain. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; IDIOM SAVANT: SLANG AS IT IS SLUNG &QL; 
 &UR; Jerry Dunn (Owl, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   According to Dunn, roller-coaster enthusiasts use the term
``fine decapo'' to describe the sensation that you are about to
have your head knocked off, ``usually by a beam or tunnel,'' and
``green alert'' as a warning that someone is getting sick on a
ride. Aren't you glad you asked? Prison inmates call a note
received from another inmate a ``kite,'' and meat served in the
prison mess hall ``Mr. Ed.'' Other ``subcultures'' in this book
include bird-watchers, pot smokers, sky divers, jugglers, ice
skaters, musicians, bowlers, gamblers, FBI agents, pickpockets,
skiers and fishermen, all of which, it seems, have been busy
developing their own little caches of slang. We, personally, don't
believe it _ we have a firsthand knowledge of volleyball, but
recognized few of the terms Dunn attributes to its players. Maybe
that's because he researched his book ``live on the Internet,''
which means submissions came from people with unproven expertise
and lots of time on their hands. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4097 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CHIMNEY-AZR &LR;      07-14 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHIMNEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY ALSO EXPLORES PUZZLE OF LOVING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Chimney Sweeper's Boy 
Barbara Vine (Harmony Books, $24) 
 
 By LELA STROMENGER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does a wife do when, within weeks of the death of her
husband of 34 years, she finds out she has never known his real
name? Real names are pivotal in ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy,'' a
book written under an assumed one.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Barbara Vine is not so much the pseudonym as the alter
ego of veteran British crime writer Ruth Rendell. The publisher of
the Vine books _ this is the ninth _ makes no attempt to conceal
the authorship of Rendell, whose long line of prize-winning
riddlers and thrillers last year won her the Grand Master Award of
the Mystery Writers of America. The ``more feminine, less bossy''
Vine was not created for concealment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than another name; it's another identity,'' Rendell
told the New York Times in 1995. ``Once I was Barbara Vine, I could
do something else.'' Compounded from Rendell's middle name and her
great-grandmother's maiden name, Barbara Vine is the second self of
a woman whose understanding of the magic of names is profound and
who knows what it is to live by the power of language.
</P>
<P>
   So does Gerald Candless, who, though he dies on page 14, is the
central figure of ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy.'' Gerald is that
lucky rarity, a serious writer whose books sell well. He lives in
Devon by the seaside (a beautifully realized and concretely
rendered seaside) with his deeply estranged wife, Ursula. The two
poles of his known life are his distinguished literary career and
his fierce love for their two daughters, ``my girls.''
</P>
<P>
   His girls, on whom he has lavished everything he can think of to
give, adore him in turn, the three forming a charmed circle outside
which the loving and unloved Ursula stands alone, her emotional
life co-opted and her confidence shattered by this brilliant,
ruthless man as by a force of nature.
</P>
<P>
   When Gerald has a fatal heart attack at 71, Ursula, at 57, is
left to pick up the strands of what life he has left her, and his
girls _ university lecturer Sarah and the poignantly named Hope, a
lawyer _ to mourn their wonderful ``Daddy.'' Then Sarah, in
researching a biography of him, discovers that Gerald Candless was
not his name and that there are no records of his life before 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery, in a sense the eternal one of a writer's identity
and relationships, is approached through writing: newspaper
clippings, Sarah's memoir, Gerald's 18 novels, the great works of
the past. The intensely bookish Vine/Rendell's devotion to
literature often surfaces in intensely bookish characters. In
Rendell's ``Make Death Love Me,'' a pair of lovers find each other
through a shared passion for Lytton Strachey's ``Eminent
Victorians.''
</P>
<P>
   Less innocuously, the very young Ursula is drawn to Gerald
partly because she sees him as Mr. Rochester to her Jane Eyre.
After their children are born, he puts them to bed with stories
spun from bits of Blake's ``Songs of Innocence.'' Ghostlike lines
from Shelley and Herbert haunt the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But the dominant writer in this book is ever the enigmatic and
fascinating Gerald: Ozymandias, fallen now but in his life a
colossus. His novels supply quotations for the chapter headings and
their plots offer clues to his own secret story. He has lived
through books, as many authors have done. But what are we to read
into that?
</P>
<P>
   Literature may be a mirror held up to life, an enrichment of
life, even a substitute for living, but it cannot be life itself.
It can't love us back. And loving, for Vine's characters, is what
life is about. At the core of ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy'' is a
complex of shifting views of love, ``being in love'' and sex.
</P>
<P>
   A girl falls for a romantic fantasy and has to live with a real
man. A father whose holiest grail is family affection turns a
daughter into a walking contradiction of the axiom that you can't
spoil a child with too much love. A highly sexual and highly
conventional wife lives with a husband who sleeps in a separate
room and locks his door at night. A grandfather confesses, ``I want
to be in love. I want to be possessed and obsessed by it. I want
the sky to change color and the sun to shine all the time. . . .''
A fiftyish Lothario strives compulsively for conquests he doesn't
really enjoy. A pair of casual acquaintances conduct a sizzling
affair by meeting in public to feign animosity, trading insults and
snubs, then leaving separately to consummate their psychodrama in
secret. In this book, people lose their souls through anonymous
sexual encounters, their hearts through mere proximity to anyone
halfway suitable.
</P>
<P>
   All these choices, insofar as they are choices, are made
consciously by intelligent adults, as such choices are made in the
real world every day. The reasons behind them, the moral conflicts
raised by them, the consequences to the chooser and the chosen,
reflect the great conundrum everyone faces sooner or later: the
puzzle of loving.
</P>
<P>
   Vine/Rendell has been this problem's novelist laureate, often
presenting characters so swept up in the maelstrom of some demented
love that it draws them into madness or death. In ``Gallowglass,''
Vine has one point out that ``passion'' doesn't mean what people
think it does. ``It means suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy,'' she lowers the stakes of the
conundrum game, making it more like the one most people play. But
perhaps most people don't think about it clearly enough. For that
reason, Vine deserves full credit for presenting it with clarity
and impact.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, aside from a gentle suggestion that love grows in the
light of knowledge, she doesn't present any solution to it. There
are some mysteries even Ruth Rendell couldn't unravel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
