<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR &LR;      07-14 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMORIST ROY BLOUNT JR. REVEALS SAD ROOTS OF HIS COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roy Blount Jr. likes to tell a little story about a conversation
that took place one night over dinner with friends, one of whom was
a fellow humorist. The humorist was bemoaning _ at great length
and, as Blount points out, ``to his own considerable morose
satisfaction'' _ some distressing thing that had happened to him.
One of the women at the table listened for awhile, then said, ``But
I read what you wrote about that! And it sounded like so much
fun!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said the humorist solemnly. ``But now I'm among
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Roy Blount. Among friends. He has written a memoir, ``Be
Sweet'' (Knopf, $24), and his fans have taken it home and read it
and somewhere past the early pages they've realized that it is not
entirely what they expected it to be. The book is funny, yes, but
as many reviewers have pointed out by now, it is also sad. And
there is Blount, nodding from the pages, confident of his audience
because where else but with his readers would he be so surely among
friends?
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Be Sweet'' is about Blount's difficult relationship
with his mother, Louise Blount, and how his consequent
self-loathing _ ``sefflo'' to him and other humorists who claim to
suffer the same affliction _ is at the heart of his efforts to make
people laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it's something nobody else has done exactly, to go
head-on and write about why you're funny,'' he says from his
Massachusetts home. ``It's sort of the last taboo, and I was
lookin' around for somethin' to violate. Maybe everybody's got a
childhood book they're always writing bits and pieces of. In my
case, it was as much my mother's book as mine. She was always
alluding, with delicious horror, to her childhood. It was the
backdrop to everything we did as children because there was always
something terrible that she'd lived through that was worse than
anything we could ever complain about.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dark side is her dark side. I've been bouncing off that all
my life and I figured it was time to dig down into it, the source
of my humor. Being funny is just a way of relieving fear and
distress and doubt. I don't know. I guess the more you talk about
it, the sillier it sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount, 56, speaks in a big, deep voice, with a drawl _ George
V. Higgins described it as an ``almost caloric Southern accent
coagulating like a big warm muddy river choked with catfish in the
sun'' _ that makes him sound friendly even when he's talking about
self-loathing and matricidal guilt. Still, explanations for this
book do not come easy to him. No sooner are the words out of his
mouth than he starts to squirm over them. He takes them back; he
tries again; he abandons a sentence before he is halfway through
it. Often _ mostly when he is talking directly about his mother _
he peters out altogether with a weary ``I don't know'' or ``Oh
God.'' You can't see him over the phone, but he sounds like he's
holding his head in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a failure of eloquence brought on by the memory of a
formidable and unhappy woman. More likely it's the sound of Blount
editing on his feet. As his fans know, the fine points of language
delight him (it galls him that Knopf removed a hyphen between the
words ``sweet'' and ``potato'' in one of his favorite sentences in
his book, a reference to the ``sweet potato-colored dirt'' of
Decatur, Ga.). It's why he is so driven, he says ``to rehabilitate
the spicy limerick'':
</P>
<P>
   (begin itals) ``Come up and see me,'' said Flower, &QL; 
And then, when I entered her bower, &QL; 
``The shower _ I'm in it _ &QL; 
Just give me a minute...'' &QL; 
I saw her and raised her an hour. (end itals)
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to write light verse,'' he says. ``You can play around
with it and hold it in your hand and fiddle with the commas. That's
the best part. The fiddling. The hard part is to get some kind of
macro-sense of what I'm doing. I mope around and put it off and
gather it in my head. It's regarding the project from afar that's
tough. Once you get into it, it's like killin' snakes _ there's
plenty to do, you start reacting and it's great in the middle of
all that chaos to feel that you've written a really nice sentence
that you can linger over and polish.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, Blount has written 13 books and contributed to many
more. He has freelanced for more than 100 publications, written a
screenplay (for ``Larger Than Life,'' starring his friend, Bill
Murray), played bit parts in movies and toured with a band of
writer-musicians that included Stephen King, Dave Barry and Amy Tan
(Blount's big vocal number was ``Wild Thing''). He has appeared on
talk shows _ Johnny Carson once leaned over to him during a
commercial break and confided, unnecessarily, that ``so often,
comedy is rooted in sadness.'' He has been married and divorced
twice, is a father and a grandfather and has survived at least a
decade of what he calls ``serial fizzled relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   With all of this has come a certain wisdom. If his way with
women has not improved much, he is at least beginning to understand
why it is such a struggle (he is incapable of being a sensitive
man, which he defines as one who ``gets a sense of what a woman
wants him to sense, and then pretends to sense it''). He calls
himself ``a jack of various trades and a fool by profession'' and
has learned to take career blips in stride, as when his ``Men's
Journal'' column was canceled by a new publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Parthenon proves,'' Blount wrote, ``columns come and
columns go.''
</P>
<P>
   He also is trying to make peace, long after their deaths, with
his mother and father. ``Be Sweet'' is really a statement to them,
and he knows that it's likely to set them spinning in their graves.
But he has come to believe that ``maybe people in their graves like
to turn over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was writing this I felt like I was having conversations
with the reader that I'd wanted to have with my parents,'' he says.
``Trying to find a way to tell them how I felt about them without
holding back anything. Without being too sweet. Seems the only way
to tell the truth is to mix some sourness in so that it tastes
real. It was a great relief to me, but also sad to be saying it
now, after they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing he will admit: If his mother's unhappiness was the
root of his humor, she was also the force behind his talent with
the written word.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a delight in language and figures of speech, even
though she didn't think of herself as a literary person,'' he says.
``She used memorable phrases and said memorable things, and
instilled an affection for language and provided a certain amount
of provocation so that I'd take a challenging attitude toward
language. I don't love it in any soft-hearted way.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did his literary heroes, S.J. Perelman, Mark Twain and
Robert Benchley, or do present-day friends like Garrison Keillor,
Calvin Trillin or Dave Barry. When they're together, Blount says,
``We talk about our children. We talk about the same things other
people do. But we also tell each other jokes. You do immediately
have something in common. And you like to make each other laugh. Or
at least smile. Humorists don't laugh a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That is left to the people who read their books. When Blount was
a boy, he had no less than three imaginary friends. They're long
gone now, but he doesn't miss them because, he says, he has his
readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' he says. ``Well, maybe it's not always so great,
because sometimes your wife wishes you were talking to her instead
of the reader. But you assume that there's some sort of ideal
person out there who is gonna understand what you say. You can get
up and talk in front of an audience and get immediate feedback and
a sense of what is funny. But writing is between you and the
reader. An inner thing. You're trying to lance a different kind of
boil. That's a pretty analogy, isn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1440EDT &QL; 
