<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-CRITICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN CAN'T GET OUT OF THE HOT SEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Cable News Network, its tail lodged firmly
between its legs, continues to be battered and bruised.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, CNN broadcast a story about the Pentagon's use of
nerve gas on U.S. defectors in Laos; a week ago, CNN News Group
Chairman Tom Johnson filed an on-air apology retracting the report
for lack of evidence to support its claims.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the walls have shaken at the Atlanta-based network,
considered one of the most-watched _ and most-credible _ news
operations in the world. But that shake-up doesn't compare with the
credibility whipping it has been taking here.
</P>
<P>
   With little other news trickling from this semiannual gathering
of the country's television critics, issues of TV news ethics and
anchor responsibilities have dominated the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The session conducted by Turner Broadcasting unquestionably
became the tour's hot ticket, even overshadowing Showtime's
``Lolita,'' the controversial reincarnation of Vladimir Nabokov's
tale of a 50ish pedophile and his tragic love affair with a
12-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   With journalists wanting to hear from Ted Turner, founder and
brainchild of CNN and now the vice chairman of CNN parent Time
Warner, a packed house waded through three hours of presentations
(CNN's mammoth 24-part documentary ``Cold War,'' movies and
specials on TBS and TNT, the latest animated heroes from the
Cartoon Network). Finally, Turner leaped from his seat to take the
podium, jokingly saying, ``I'll move over here ... make an easier
target standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's move got a huge laugh from the audience, nicely slicing
through an atmosphere tinged with tension and anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   At each press tour there's a whipping boy (or girl, in the case
of ABC's formerly beleaguered entertainment chief Jamie Tarses),
picked apart like carrion by hungry hyenas.
</P>
<P>
   This year, that means anyone with the slightest connection to
CNN has been drilled about their thoughts on the channel. And it's
not just about whether the news operation was at fault but rather
how damaging is this to this country's social fabric as we know it?
Pack journalism takes on the mood of McCarthyism. So, where were
you when CNN ran that story?
</P>
<P>
   During one early morning panel, news correspondent Jack Smith
wasn't in his seat two minutes before reminding us that he is not
the CNN producer Jack Smith fired along with two other producers
supervising the nerve gas story. (That Smith and colleague April
Oliver were canned after refusing to resign; executive producer
Pamela Hill handed in her resignation.)
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News correspondent and Vietnam veteran, Smith was
discussing The Learning Channel's ``Vietnam: The Soldiers' Story,''
a riveting documentary about Vietnam told from the soldiers' point
of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story when I heard about it didn't pass even the most
elementary journalistic smell tests,'' Smith said, explaining why
there were so many objections to the report.
</P>
<P>
   A cable chief, requesting anonymity because of his personal
relationship with the CNN brass, said, ``We always get burned when
we rush to put something on the air or publish something to meet an
artificial deadline.'' The artificial deadline in this case was the
June 7 debut of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' a joint venture between
electronic and print-news gathering machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is good but not at the sacrifice of accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The emerging subplot is whether a field reporter for a news
organization such as CNN bears enough knowledge of a story to
accept the ultimate responsibility should the story prove false.
Peter Arnett said he narrated the report and asked questions fed to
him by producers, but that was the extent of his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that putting a star reporter on to act like they were
the person that investigated the story, that's a bad practice,''
said Turner, who is now promising sweeping changes at CNN. ``That
whoever the person that did the story and did the research should
appear on camera rather than getting some blow-dried news anchor in
New York to try and persuade people that he or she was on the
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Former CNN correspondent Arthur Kent, who rose to fame for his
Gulf War coverage as the ``Scud Stud,'' found himself answering
more questions about CNN than the ``History Undercover'' series
he's fronting for The History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's helped explain to the viewing public something
very important,'' Kent said. ``That there is more than just the
on-air journalism in the task of news information and gathering,
writing and reportage.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
