<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RYE-BREAD (Berlin) _ The Germans have an unequalled passion for
traditional ryes, whether tan, brown or almost black. Most of them
have a malty, slightly sour taste. The best of them are moist when
fresh. When you bite into a dense, delectable slice, you have a
sense that you are eating something primeval, something undying,
something expressive of its origins, like honest wine. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BARBEQUE (New York) _ What do Kansas City, Chicago and
Oakland have that New York does not? Great barbecue, for one. When
it comes to real barbecue _ meat cooked ever-so-slowly over a low
wood fire until it is imbued with the tantalizing aroma and flavor
of smoke _ these cities thoroughly outdo New York.This is a
crushing fact for New York barbecue lovers. Barbecue may be the
most fetishized of all foods, inspiring countless books, odes and
arguments in which otherwise mild-mannered people rise into
passionate lathers over particular meats, methods, sauces and
sources. But on New York's deficiency they all agree. And so comes
the forlorn question: Why can't you get good barbecue in New York?
By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BOATHOUSE-RESTAURANT (New York) _ As the sun is setting the
final notes of music slide off the dock, skip across the water and
disappear into the trees. A swan glides into view, tracing a
graceful path through the last of the light. Birds swoop and call;
a gondola appears on the horizon.... ``Get a grip,'' says an inner
voice, ``Have you had too much wine? It's only Central Park.'' When
the band is playing on a warm summer evening it is easy to fall
under the spell of Park View, the new restaurant at the Loeb
Boathouse. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PIGS-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ ``Ka-BOSS, ka-BOSS, ka-BOSS.'' On a
sunny summer morning last week, Annie Farrell was using her
all-purpose animal call to round up Large Black piglets. The four
Large Blacks, three sows and a boar, came readily, thinking there
might be some food; the six piglets were having too much fun
foraging. ``They are wonderful pigs, good natured, great mothers,
very protective,'' she said, then stopped herself before adding:
``I don't want to get mushy about them because they are the best
eating.'' By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-COOKING (UNdated) _ How the Vietnamese use herbs _ by
the platterful. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   Wtih recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
