<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN'S-INN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CHILDREN'S INN, `MOMS' MAKE THE DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOERNE, Texas _ Caring for a sick child is enough to run many
parents ragged, physically and emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Children's Inn, dealing with serious medical problems
is just part of the daily routine. And the problems are no reason
to cancel a trip to South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a few clothes and a lot of toys,'' Kathleen Kean said
before setting off in a van last week with the six children who
live at the Children's Inn foster home.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary is flexible and the medicine chest well-stocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, will we have to bring pillows and that sort of stuff?''
asked Thomas, a rambunctious 4-year-old with spina bifida, a
congenital defect of the spine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we will,'' said Marilyn Haider.
</P>
<P>
   Haider and Kean are the licensed caregivers at the home located
on the grounds of the Benedictine monastery in this community
northwest of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we went to South Dakota, we got to New Braunfels
(Texas) and everybody was hungry and asking, `Are we there yet?'''
Haider recalled with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The women established the nonprofit organization in 1991, after
identifying a need for facilities for children with dysfunctional
families, emotional problems, or serious medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six children are considered permanent residents who
hope to make the cozy stone house their home until adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth spot, now filled by a seven-month-old San Antonio boy,
is reserved for youngsters placed by the state on a short-term
basis pending reunification with their families.
</P>
<P>
   Life is fast-paced at the Children's Inn, where the emphasis is
on education, fellowship and fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make them independent,'' Kean, 56, said over
the incessant squeaking of ``Chester'' the rocking horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``To infinity and beyond!'' yells John, 7, as he takes the
plastic pony to the limits of stability.
</P>
<P>
   Blind since his premature birth, John was a frail 8 pounds at
the age of five months when he arrived here on heart monitors and a
breathing apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely ill as a child, and he didn't talk until he
was 4,'' said Kean, a Sister of St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other children who live here, John now attends public
schools. He loves swimming, riding Chester and tour-bus trips,
providing commentary, from memory, of the sights he cannot see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loving care and attention they give those children is
phenomenal,'' said John's grandfather, John MacDonald of San
Antonio. ``They're just totally selfless.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a healthy respect for the women's willingness to
involve the children aged 12 and younger in activities like
scouting, sports leagues, church events and field trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do things that I would not even care to consider,'' said
MacDonald, 74. ``They mix it up and get down in crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Inn is one of thousands of foster homes across
Texas where an estimated 13,000 children live. But this facility
stands out because of the long-term commitment made to the five
youngsters, which extended to the adoption of two of them _ Thomas
and John _ by Haider four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love them. They've been with us since they were tiny
babies,'' said Haider, 50. ``I couldn't live every day thinking
that these kids have no stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider's decision to adopt the youngsters meant curtailing her
service as a Benedictine nun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, people in (the religious) community don't have
commitments to people outside of that community,'' explained
Haider. ``So when I took on the lifelong commitment to the kids by
adopting them, I made the decision not to belong to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   While Haider is the boys' ward on paper, the women are full
partners in parenting in every other respect.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, each ``mom'' serves as chauffeur, teacher, cook,
disciplinarian and role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time in doctors' offices,'' said Haider, who
is a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   At night, they take turns getting up to adjust feeding tubes,
administering medication or changing diapers for the youngsters who
require round-the-clock attention.
</P>
<P>
   They can keep up with the children now, but the women realize
their pledge of long-term care could tax their energy resources
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision because it's a big commitment, and
because of our age,'' Haider said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look a lot more towards the future and try to plan for
them,'' she said. ``We're not going to be here all the time, and
there's no doubt these kids will need assistance as they grow
older.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
