<HEADER>
A4148 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEIGHBORS-AZR &LR;      07-14 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIGHBORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS PITCH IN TO HELP TROUBLED FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CLANCY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - On the morning of May 15, Kim Jablonski of Phoenix
woke up unable to catch her breath.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, after an ordeal that included serious heart
surgery, she returned home to a scene that, well, left her
breathless.
</P>
<P>
   It all started that day in May. Reacting quickly to her
breathing difficulties, her husband, Marty, called his neighbors
Kelly and Jake Lang and asked them to watch the Jablonskis' sons,
Scott, 13, and Kory, 10.
</P>
<P>
   He called his next-door neighbors, Lloyd and Marlene Bauerman,
and asked them to keep an eye on his neatly kept house near 33rd
and Maryland avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left with perfect confidence that they would take care of
everything,'' Marty Jablonski said.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he know how much they would take care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a miracle,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jablonskis headed to the emergency room at Phoenix Baptist
Hospital, where Kim was diagnosed with congestive heart failure and
an ascending aortic aneurysm, indicated by their association with
her previously diagnosed Marfan's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jablonski was in serious jeopardy. A similar situation, in
which the aorta ultimately burst, took the life of former Olympic
volleyball great Flo Hyman, who also suffered from Marfan's but
never had been diagnosed. Marfan's syndrome is a congenital disease
of the connective tissue that leaves its victims tall and lanky and
causes weakness in the aorta, the main artery of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jablonski's case was so serious, the couple didn't come home
for almost six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of that first day, they were in Houston being seen by
Dr. Joseph Coselli. Coselli, widely recognized for his efforts in
treating Marfan's, has performed the surgery that Kim required more
than 1,000 times. He operated on her for 7{ hours that night. She
spent the rest of the six weeks recuperating with her husband at
her bedside in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Back at home, the neighbors in the area of tidy red brick homes
got to work. It wasn't unusual for them to pitch in. Most have
lived there for 20 or more years. They had gotten to know one
another because their kids were in school together, and, as one of
them explained, ``It helps when the men like to work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You really know when the chips are down who your friends
really are,'' said Jake Lang, who was in charge of the Jablonskis'
yard as well as helping watch their sons.
</P>
<P>
   As word spread, the neighbors started to gather. Knowing that
Kim Jablonski had begun working on redecorating a bathroom, Dave
Bell, who lives a couple of doors away, mentioned that he had some
extra tile at home. Lang said he had some spare paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to make ourselves at home,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell had come to know Jablonski 24 years earlier, when Bell and
his wife, Tia, first moved in. While they were reroofing the house,
Jablonski stopped over and asked if the Bells had ever done that
before. When they said no, Jablonski acknowledged that he had done
it only once, but that they could use his help.
</P>
<P>
   Such neighborliness gets repaid, over time.
</P>
<P>
   Bell and Lang decided Kim Jablonski would need her bathtub when
she got home. She had begun remodeling the tub when she fell ill,
and it was unusable.
</P>
<P>
   Tia Bell said that when her husband told her what he was going
to do, he said he would see her later that night. ``I said, `No,
I'll see you in three weeks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She had anticipated what the men figured out the next day when
they finished the floor in the bathroom and started laying tile in
the kitchen: If they were in for a penny, they might as well be in
for a pound.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Kim Jablonski's father, Jerry Adams, and her
brother, Chris, who each own fiberglass companies, they redecorated
the entire bathroom, adding new tub and tile, new floors, new
vanities and counter tops, new light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   How did they know what she wanted?
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Kim quite well, and we knew she liked my bathroom,''
said Lang's wife, Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   They kept it a secret from the Jablonskis. Marty, focused on his
wife's health, never caught on.
</P>
<P>
   As the men started moving down the hall _ where they had laid
new carpeting _ the rest of the neighborhood started to join in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody started bringing money, and groceries to feed the
boys,'' Tia Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors Fred Willey and Dave Andreini pitched in on dry wall,
painting and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The Jablonskis' home needed the work. Marty Jablonski said that
in the 24 years he has lived there, he never had upgraded the
property. ``I have a Ph.D. in procrastination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So everybody got to work. If they weren't directly involved in
the house, they helped in other ways, making donations of
construction materials or money or providing food for the Jablonski
boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our little neighborhood, this shocked me, the way the
neighbors pulled together,'' Tia Bell said. ``Neighbors were coming
from all over. It was amazing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Kory pitched in by holding a hot dog sale, attracting
people from miles around. They also kept the secret.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Lang said the work started quickly, moving out of the
bathroom, down the hall to the kitchen, then moving into the living
room, dining room and family room.
</P>
<P>
   They laid carpet, put down tile, painted walls, hung vertical
blinds and miniblinds, put up new light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked every night and weekends until midnight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They were finished in three weeks, then took their time with the
finishing touches.
</P>
<P>
   The final piece was removing a 50-foot-tall fan palm tree in the
front yard. Before the Jablonskis returned, it had been replaced
with a new, leafy tree. A red brick walk was added to the front
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the Jablonskis' surprise when they came home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was one of shock. It put me right back in
the hospital,'' Kim joked.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, her husband explained, she needed more time to recover
from her operation.
</P>
<P>
   Home again by the Fourth of July, she still is overcome by the
neighbors' generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed the palm tree was gone, replaced with a new tree.
There was a red brick walkway, and new plants,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I opened the front door. The first thing I saw was tile
in the kitchen, where there used to be bare cement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I noticed the new paint, the shades, the vertical blinds.
It was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband added, ``No words can adequately describe how
wonderful it is to have friends and neighbors like this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to do Kim's heart good. She is expected to recover
fully from the surgery, although she will need frequent checkups
for the Marfan's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the neighbors will be around to help out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
