<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SPOCK-TEX     07-14 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SPOCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDIATRICIAN TO A NATION: A PERSONAL LOOK AT THE MAN WHO CHANGED
PARENTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dr. Spock: An American Life'' is more than a well-researched
biography of America's favorite baby doctor; it is fascinating
social history that reads like a great adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin Spock, who remains controversial even after death
for pushing a vegetarian diet for young children in the latest
edition of his baby book, was an anti-war activist, civil rights
leader, health care reformer and one of the great liberals of the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   He introduced Freud to many unsuspecting parents, campaigned for
John F. Kennedy, marched with Dr. Martin Luther King, stood trial
for aiding and abetting draft dodgers during the Vietnam War,
preached in favor of Medicare and against nuclear weapons, ran for
president of the United States in 1972, and in 1993, at the age of
90, delivered $75,000 worth of donated supplies to the Cuban Red
Cross _ despite an American embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Maier's definitive biography keeps all the history in
mind while telling the very personal story of the pediatrician who
changed child rearing in this country forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new mothers of America were ready for a book that told
them love was as important as discipline, that cuddling was as
important as cleanliness,'' Maier points out.
</P>
<P>
   By the time America's baby boomers _ known as Spock babies _
began having babies of their own in the 1960s, there was only one
baby book, and everyone called the book ``Dr. Spock.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially named ``The Common Sense Book of Baby and Child
Care'' when first published in 1946, the book _ which has sold more
than 50 million copies _ is now in its seventh edition, published
two months after Spock's death in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any president, pope or populist, Spock brought about
a remarkable revolution since 1946, enacting a fundamental change
in how most parents bring up their children,'' writes Maier.
``Spock's book offered an alternative, a more loving way of
bringing up children than the moralistic, sometimes cruel methods
of old.''
</P>
<P>
   Maier's extensively researched book keeps in mind that the name
Spock evokes thoughts of children far more than memories of
political protests or debates about the merits of psychoanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   Spock's own family was dysfunctional, Maier points out through
interviews with the popular doctor's children and grandchildren:
Family members were constantly in psychotherapy, both individually
and in groups; Spock's first wife, Jane, suffered a nervous
breakdown and was an alcoholic; his grandson committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The biography is based on extensive interviews with Spock and
his family, friends and colleagues, numerous newspaper accounts,
magazine articles, speeches, personal letters, government
documents, pamphlets and unpublished transcripts, and tape
recordings made by Mary Morgan, Spock's second wife, when the two
of them were writing their 1989 book, ``Spock on Spock: A Memoir of
Growing Up With the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   That book, like earlier attempts at telling Spock's story,
failed in part because Spock suppressed many of the most personal
parts. Perhaps he sensed that time was running out; in any case, he
sent letters to friends and family inviting them to speak freely
with Maier and did not attempt to censor the work in any way.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Spock: An American Life''
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Maier
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt Brace, $30
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
