<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     07-14 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISM MARKETED FOR MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - I was all ready to make fun of people who care about
who runs ``The New Yorker,'' until I realized that I did.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, when Tina Brown stepped down as editor last
week, the story broke as big news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two columns and a picture on Tina Brown quitting?'' a
colleague asked, as he held up a copy of the ``New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I reckoned; sounds about right.
</P>
<P>
   But why?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer lies with Brown herself. When she moved from
``Vanity Fair'' to ``The New Yorker'' in 1992, the hew and cry
could be heard from all the usual buttoned-down guardians of
cultural literacy, some of whom had actually read ``The New
Yorker'' recently.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the old staff left. Others were asked to. (The most
lamentable loss was Ian Frazier, who now pops up less frequently in
``Outside'' and ``The Atlantic'').
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't waste any time giving defenders of Harold Ross and
William Shawn something to gripe about. Topicality ruled. Roseanne
served as guest editor of a special issue. Soon the hallowed pages
of the venerable magazine were rife with color ads, celebrity
profiles, even  &UR; pictures, for goodness' sake.
</P>
<P>
   The dumbing down of American culture was complete, the martini
set crowed. No wonder Jim Carrey was box-office king.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question: Did you ever read the old ``New
Yorker``? While acknowledging that the magazine produced some
classic journalism (think ``Hiroshima'' by John Hersey, or ``In
Cold Blood'' by Truman Capote), plowing through those articles week
in and week out was heavy sledding. Too much for me, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   My pal Kim, wise as the day is long, is one of the smartest
people I've ever known, and hands down the best reader. He's
read &UR; everything. He used to subscribe to the pre-Brown ``New
Yorker,'' but canceled his subscription and fired off a letter to
the editor explaining why: The articles were just too damn long.
</P>
<P>
   That's like Michael Jordan quitting basketball because it pays
too well. But it tells you all you need to know about the way the
magazine used to read.
</P>
<P>
   Once Brown settled in, a funny thing happened: The magazine
actually became fun, at least for lowbrows such as myself, people
who don't exactly move their lips when they read, but can't wade
through multipart series on grains.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there are weeks when I pick up the magazine, glance at
the table of contents and toss it atop the recycling pile. Other
weeks, I read everything in it. If Christopher Buckley writes
Shouts and Murmurs, I'll even save it and pass it along to friends.
</P>
<P>
   But the magazine's transformation came at a price. As much as
Brown improved ``The New Yorker'' (or desecrated it, depending upon
your point of view), her reign, with its stunts _ Roseanne's
``women's issue,'' inflammatory covers, celebrity puff pieces _
cast a bright light upon a shallow streak that colors journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is just another example of journalist as celebrity, of the
idea that the information isn't as important as who brings it to
us. If the editor has a high-enough profile _ if Brown and her
husband buying a luxury apartment makes news _ then her magazine
must be worth checking out, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, as anyone who has ever tried to read John F.
Kennedy Jr.'s ``George'' can tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the idea exists everywhere in media. Television
``journalism'' wouldn't exist without it. Check out any Sunday
morning news show. It wasn't long ago that a local station trotted
out Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio as a guest sportscaster. Why
do you think attractive news anchors live in a higher tax bracket?
Networks don't dish out all those millions to the likes of Katie
Couric and Dan Rather for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Credentials don't matter as much as smiles and salaries do.
More's the pity.
</P>
<P>
   But hope is on the horizon. Pulitzer Prize-winning author David
Remnick, whom Brown recruited to the magazine, will succeed her.
Maybe now the chattering classes will care as much about what's in
the magazine as who runs it. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
