<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAM-BOX14-COX     07-14 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAM-BOX14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPULAR E-MAIL SCAMS
 &HT;    With SPAM
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are some of the scams the Federal Trade
Commission has encountered most often:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Business Opportunities _ Usually promise a lot of income for a
small investment of time and money. Some are actually old-fashioned
pyramid schemes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bulk E-Mailings _ Offer lists of e-mail addresses or software
to allow you to make the mailings. What they don't mention is that
the lists are of poor quality, sending bulk e-mail violates the
terms of service of most Internet service providers, and several
states have laws regulating the sending of bulk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chain Letters _ Electronic versions of the old-fashioned chain
letters. They are as illegal as the old-fashioned paper versions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Work-at-Home Schemes _ Two popular versions are
envelope-stuffing and craft assembly. However, nobody will really
pay you for stuffing envelopes, and craft assembly promoters
usually refuse to buy crafts, claiming the work does not meet their
``quality standards.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Health And Diet Scams _ Offer ``scientific breakthroughs,''
``miraculous cures,'' ``exclusive products,'' ``secret formulas,''
and ``ancient ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get Something Free _ After paying a membership fee, consumers
learn that they don't quality for the ``free'' gift until they
recruit other ``members.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cable Descrambler Kits _ Offers for sale a kit that lets you
receive cable without paying subscription fees. Two problems: the
kits usually don't work and stealing cable service is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Credit Repair Scams _ For an up-front fee, they offer to clear
up a bad credit record for a charge or show you how to get an
Employer Identification Number. No one can erase a bad credit
record if it's accurate, and using an Employer Identification
Number to set up a new credit identity is against the law.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
