<HEADLINE>
MAMA'S GOT A COOL NEW RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot dog! I'm fit to be tied, whatever that means. I heard this
guy in one of those old Clint Eastwood spaghetti westerns use that
phrase once and I've been waiting years for an opportunity to
repeat it. Well, the moment has finally arrived and, like I said,
I'm just fit to be tied. Uh oh, my husband is looking over my
shoulder right now and he's grinning like an idiot so I suppose
some clarification is needed. Let's just say that I am very
excited.
</P>
<P>
   I'm excited because I got a new vehicle this week. Now, I'm not
one to brag. In fact, I take a dim view of people who spend a lot
of time talking about what they own, where they bought it, and what
it costs. However, for several years now, I have been riding around
in a foreign-made, two-cylinder, two-door matchbox car that was so
small it didn't have brakes. When I needed to slow down or stop,
I'd just open the door and drag my foot on the ground. For parking,
I used the kickstand on the rear bumper or a bicycle chain. I tell
you that car was teeny!
</P>
<P>
   I bought it during the fall clearance a while back, and when
winter came, the heater worked just fine. However, when those hot
days of summer steam rolled around, I could never get the AC cold
enough to cool off my head and my feet at the same time. When I
finally looked under the hood, I understood the problem. Instead of
a traditional air conditioning system, I had a gerbil in a box with
a little ice maker. Every five minutes, the gerbil would suck on a
piece of ice and then blow into this tube that leads to the vents
inside the car. Immediately, I took the car back to the dealer and
complained. They apologized and gave me a bigger gerbil.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the car was the gas mileage. I got 100
miles to the gallon. For $10, I could drive to New York _ if the
weather was cool enough. My children were toddlers when I bought
the car, so they didn't mind the absence of legroom. That was then.
Now they both have legs longer than my entire body. Before I sold
that car, Junior could sit behind the driver's seat and use his
toes to turn on the radio. I knew it was time for a bigger vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   My husband wanted a van. I went to the safe and got the
prenuptial agreement out. There in bold print it said, ``My wife
will never be forced to drive a van or a station wagon or cook a
German chocolate cake from scratch.'' Call me psychic, but I knew
the day would come when I would need that clause.
</P>
<P>
   Then, my love suggested a sport utility vehicle. ``You like
trucks,'' he said. ``These are just big trucks. They're safe,
they're sporty, there's room for the kids, and they have eight
cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean the AC works?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having an elephant with a glacier under the hood.''
</P>
<P>
   The test drive was unconvincing. I did like the power of the
vehicle, but it was so very big. I ran over curbs trying to make
simple turns. I had trouble parking. I was sitting up so high that
I could see things in other cars that I'm sure I wasn't supposed to
be seeing. And I thought nose picking at the red light was bad.
However, the boys loved it and my husband loved it. Knowing it was
American-made was comforting, but it was a different straw that
broke this camel's back. When the salesman turned the thermostat
all the way down and it got so cold that my lips froze together, I
said OK. Actually, I just nodded because I couldn't talk until my
lips thawed.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm sitting at the red light enjoying that new-car smell and
thinking about how cool I am when this nice-looking woman in a
minivan pulls up next to me. That's when I noticed that my
``truck'' was as long as her van. My ``truck'' was as wide as her
van. And my ``truck'' had three rows of seats just like her van.
The only difference was that I have four doors and she has three. I
realized then that I had been tricked into buying a fancy van.
</P>
<P>
   I rushed to the phone and called my husband to complain, but I
couldn't because my lips were frozen again. I heard him on the
other end just laughing heartily.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, that man is clever.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564. Write in care
of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington, TX
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
