<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 19,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORY  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOVIE-ACTORS (Los Angeles) _ A tide of movie and theater
actors, as well as established film writers, directors and
producers, are surging into a medium that they once scorned. And
just as important, the gates of movie studios have been flung open
to television actors and writers after decades of not-so benign
neglect. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OFFLEAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-RYAN-FILM (Undated) _ It's the morning of D-Day, June 6,
1944, just off Omaha Beach. Laden with rifles and unwieldy packs,
some of the men pray, others are sick into their helmets. A few are
visibly shaking. Then the doors to the landing craft fall open, and
Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which opens on July 24,
becomes an entirely different kind of movie than the audience
expects. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-THEATER-COPENHAGEN (London) _ Why did Werner Heisenberg,
the German who formulated the uncertainty principle, pay a visit to
Niels Bohr, the Dane who made key discoveries in quantum theory, in
the occupied Copenhagen of 1941? The meeting of the two Nobel
Prize-winning physicists could help explain why you and I are not
now living in a world controlled by Son of Hitler and his
cybernetic Gestapo. It certainly supplies Michael Frayn with the
material for one of the boldest, meatiest plays the Royal National
Theater has staged this decade: ``Copenhagen.'' By Benedict
Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   FORBIDDEN-BROADWAY (New York) _ Gerard Alessandrini, 44, has
been Broadway's premier parts collector for a long time. Since 1982
he has been presenting a series of rude, bitchy, yet ultimately
affectionate cabaret-style satires on the Broadway scene under the
moniker ``Forbidden Broadway,'' which he created, writes and
directs. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLE-THEATER-LONDON (LOndon) _ ``Whistle Down the Wind'' may
take as its source the Mary Hayley Bell novella that inspired the
1961 Bryan Forbes film starring Hayley Mills and Alan Bates. On
this hearing it is about a haunted man _ known, indeed, as The Man
and portrayed by Marcus Lovett, an American veteran of several
Andrew Lloyd Webber musicals _ in none too sublimated thrall to a
virginal girl-woman, the impressionable teen-age Swallow (Lottie
Mayor). But here, ``the music of the night,'' as the ``Phantom''
lyric puts it, has been supplanted by what a Jim Steinman lyric
terms ``the nature of the beast.'' By Matt Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HADID-CINCINNATI (Cincinnati) _ Herbert Muschamp reviews Zaha
Hadid's Museum of Contemporary Art in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PIMPERNEL-TV (Undated) _ Now A&AMP;E Television Networks, which
brought ``Pride and Prejudice,'' ``Emma'' and ``Tom Jones'' to
television, are producing ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' with the BBC.
The three 90-minute television films of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,''
replete with 1,200 costumes and visually rich locales in the Czech
Republic, promise to be not only lush in the style we've become so
accustomed to with literary adaptations. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEXY-OPERA-JACKETS (Undated) _ A jet-black man, facing front and
nearly naked but for a spiked leather G-string with matching spiked
sunglasses, and holding a dead white swan; a trio of skinny,
scantily clad, bewigged and beribboned drag queens who could be
drum majorettes in a Gay Day parade; a naked obese woman sitting on
a floor and cuddling a tiny dog between her fleshy arm and
humongous bosom, with heart-shaped trinkets masking her face and
nipples. These are the covers of three new RCA Victor recordings of
orchestral excerpts from Wagner operas. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEASTIE-BOYS (Undated) _ There is a term in hip-hop, flavor. It
is a good thing. Rappers want to have flavor: panache, style,
something extra that enables them to stand out from the pack. In
their 17 years together, however, the Beastie Boys have developed
something much better than flavor: taste. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   BRISTOL-POP-MUSIC (Undated) _ Bristol, England, has been the
capital of sonic murk and undertow for a decade, and it's not about
to give up the claim. Two new albums from Bristol's
standard-bearers _ Tricky's ``Angels With Dirty Faces'' (Island)
and Massive Attack's ``Mezzanine'' (Virgin) _ insist on the
continuing allure of ambiguity. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-TRENDS (New York) _ Two trends are in evidence at
auction houses: a surge in prices for Americana, and a growing
demand for anonymity by a new generation of wealthy collectors. By
Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WYETH-ART-MAINE (Rockland, Maine) _ On June 21, the Farnsworth
Center for the Wyeth Family in Maine opened, a place dedicated to
the work of the illustrator N.C. Wyeth, his son Andrew and Andrew's
son Jamie. The 130-year-old church contains the center's galleries;
there is also a private study area, in a separate building, with
storage for art and archives. A review by Deborah Weisgall.
</P>
<P>
   GYSIN-ART-EDMONTON (Edmonton, Alberta) _ He just thought it was
awful, nowheresville,'' William Burroughs said of Edmonton, the
boyhood home of his great friend and collaborator Brion Gysin.
Though Gysin shunned this ``wrong place'' that pummeled away at his
psyche, the city is embracing Gysin as a native son with the first
major North American retrospective of his works, at the Edmonton
Art Gallery through Aug. 31. By Kathryn Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Kool-Aid Week in Nebraska highlights
travel briefs.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Beatles tours in England and Christmas on
Capri are subjects of travel questions. By Suzanne MacNeille.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Clothing optional cruises. By
Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Traveling the net: Finding ATM's abroad
and student air fares. By L.R. Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FLORIDA (Miami) _ Despite the fires, Florida tourism
rolls on. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VANCOUVER-ISLAND (Vancouver Island) _ Rambles along a
remote shore. By Nancy R. Newhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
