<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSECTREPELLENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BUGS BUZZ OFF: WHEN IT COMES TO REPELLENTS, DEET CAN'T BE
BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by REPELLENTS-CHART) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the TV commercial back in the '60s in which the
fearless scientist thrust his arm into a cage of hungry,
blood-sucking mosquitoes to demonstrate the effectiveness of a
particular insect repellent?
</P>
<P>
   The arm-in-cage test is not just a television stunt, says Dr.
Jonathan Day, a medical entomologist with the University of
Florida, whose research focuses on the prevention of encephalitis,
a viral infection spread by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   The testing was developed by the U.S. Department of Agriculture
Entomological Laboratories in Florida to find repellents to protect
soldiers in malaria-ridden countries during World War II. The
chemical DEET (N, N-diethyl-m-toluamide) was patented by the Army
in 1946 and registered for use by the general public in 1957; it's
the active ingredient in such well-known bug sprays as Off!
</P>
<P>
   Day has endured a lot of mosquito bites in 20 years of testing
both chemical (synthetic) and natural (plant-derived) repellents,
as well as gadgets and gizmos like sonic repellers, ``magic''
wristbands and backyard zappers. About 1,000 potential new
repellents are tested each year, and so far none has been found
that compares with DEET in safety and effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   And though DEET periodically draws criticism that it is unsafe,
scientists and studies say otherwise. In April, after 40 years of
testing and usage, the Environmental Protection Agency concluded
that when used according to directions, DEET at any strength is
safe to use on people of any age, including children.
</P>
<P>
   ``DEET is the gold standard against which we test new
products,'' Day says. ``It may be that, purely by accident, we
found the best first.''
</P>
<P>
   Most insect repellents sold today rely on DEET or citronella, a
natural plant-based oil, as their active ingredient. They are the
only two insect repellents approved by the Environmental Protection
Agency for topical application to humans.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't stop people _ and marketers _ from searching for
other potions. Natural substances such as garlic, cayenne pepper,
bananas and vitamin B-1 are often touted as effective repellents,
but Day says there is no research to support their long-term
effectiveness, and in fact most have proved ineffective in
scientific studies.
</P>
<P>
   You still taste the same to a mosquito, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Carbon dioxide and lactic acid, given off by the human body
through the skin and breath, are the primary long-range mosquito
attractants. They can be detected by mosquitoes from about 120 feet
away.
</P>
<P>
   DEET works by jamming the sophisticated sensory receptors on the
antennae of mosquitoes and other biting insects. Once the sensory
system is jammed, movement toward the host ceases and there is no
further attempt to blood-feed until the DEET is cleared from the
receptors.
</P>
<P>
   A few plant oils, particularly citronella, eucalyptus, vanilla,
pennyroyal, geranium and cedar are natural repellents that evolved
along with the plants to keep harmful insects away from the plants
from which they are derived. In high concentrations, they can be
toxic to people, just like they are to bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people out there do get some benefit from the natural
oils, even in low concentrations. There are a variety of factors at
work and so much variation from person to person. You need to find
out what works for you in a particular situation and use it,'' Day
says. ``I get lots of calls from people telling me what works for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because something comes from a plant doesn't mean it is
safer than a synthetic chemical designed to do the same thing, Day
emphasizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a lot of science to any of the things available
to the public that are not DEET-based,'' said Dr. Mark Fradin, who
reviewed 30 years' worth of studies, medical literature, government
documents, case reports and articles for a recent article on
mosquito repellents published in the ``Annals of Internal
Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to mix garlic and peppermint and sell it for
insect repellent, you don't have to prove it works to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fradin says he found one new herbal product in his research,
that seems to be somewhat effective in repelling mosquitoes. Bite
Blocker contains soybean oil as its main active ingredient, along
with some geranium oil and coconut oil. It has been available in
Europe for several years and was released in the United States last
year. Scientists don't quite understand how it works, but somehow
it seems to jam the receptors on mosquitoes' antennae that allow
them to zero in on victims.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has not registered soybean oil as an insect repellent
because it is derived from food-grade soybeans and is considered
safe. They have registered citronella as a weak repellent that
protects up to two hours. The oil has a lemony scent and was
originally extracted from the grass plant Cymbopogon nardus _ never
used for food.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that citronella can be an effective repellent, but
it provides shorter complete protection than most DEET-based
products and must be reapplied frequently, Fradin notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing people need to know is the importance of
following the labels on different products,'' says Marilyn Blood,
marketing director for SC Johnson Wax, developers of the various
Off! insect repellents. ``DEET has been studied for years and has
an outstanding safety record, but toxic reactions can occur with
misuse. Don't use more than you need. Don't reapply unless
mosquitoes actually start bothering you.''
</P>
<P>
   Factors that determine the effectiveness of any repellent
include frequency and uniformity of application; the number and
species of organisms attempting to bite; the users inherent
attractiveness to blood-sucking arthropods; and the overall
activity level of the potential host.
</P>
<P>
   Abrasion from clothing rubbing against the body, evaporation and
absorption from the skin surface, wash-off from sweat or rain, high
temperatures and a windy environment all decrease effectiveness,
Fradin says.
</P>
<P>
   Fradin recommends following basic common sense guidelines,
printed on product labels. He also says parents should apply DEET
products to their own hands and rub them on young children. You
need to cover every square inch of exposed skin for full protection
and you should reapply only as needed when mosquitoes start biting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If efficacy is your No. 1 concern, I would say use a DEET
product no higher than 35 percent concentration. The American
Academy of Pediatrics recommends 10 percent or less for children,''
Fradin says.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
