<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-CHINA (Washington) _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., says Senate investigators have revealed a major security
breach in technology transfers to China. Based on the information,
Lott calls for the appointment of an independent counsel to probe
whether China tried to manipulate the American political system. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Washington) _ For Hillary Rodham Clinton, the
``Save America's Treasures'' tour that continues Wednesday in
upstate New York is emblematic of a lighter, less policy-driven
image that the first lady has projected in the president's second
term. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ The Justice Department says
it will appeal the federal court ruling that Secret Service agents
have to testify in the investigation of President Clinton's
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. By
JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GAYS (Washington) _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of
Texas is one of four House Republicans pushing to add a rider to an
appropriations bill to overturn a presidential order adding
homosexuals to anti-bias rules for federal workers. But the bill
they plan to try to attach it to is from a committee headed by a
gay congressman, Jim Kolbe of Arizona. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SUICIDE (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee
hears testimony about what doctors may do to comply with patients'
desires to hasten death. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SPAM (Washington) _ ``Spam,'' unsolicited commercial e-mail, is
often a ``tipoff to a ripoff,'' says a report issued by the Federal
Trade Commission. But the agency doesn't recommend banning it.
Instead it says companies sending such junk e-mail should be
prohibited from trying to disguise its content or origin, which
would allow people to better filter their incoming messages. By
NICOLE TSONG. Story also will move in the FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'')
category.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIOLOGICAL-THREAT (Laredo, Texas) _ A hearing is scheduled
Wednesday in federal court at Brownsville on the arrest of three
South Texas men on charges of conspiring to kill public figures,
including President Clinton and the FBI director, with biological
agents. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-ATTORNEYS (Jasper, Texas) _ Two criminal defense
attorneys in Beaumont have been appointed to represent Bill King
and Russell Brewer, who are accused in the dragging death of James
Byrd Jr. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APARTMENTS-HOUSTON (Houston) _ Houston is the hottest market in
the nation for apartment construction. Rising rents, higher
occupancy rates and strong job growth are luring developers to
build apartments at a pace not seen since the early 1980s. By RALPH
BIVINS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ President Clinton and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott are blaming each other for the
legislative stalemate in Congress. But neither one is pretending
that much of the nation's business is getting done. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BAKER-FINCH (Manchester, England) _ The last time the
British Open was played at Royal Birkdale, Ian Baker-Finch walked
off the 18th green on top of the world. The Australian golfer was
in his prime and had just won the British Open, the major
championship that he had always dreamed of winning. As it turned
out, that was the beginning of the end of Baker Finch's golf
career. By JAYNE CUSTRED.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Phoenix) _ Pitcher Shane Reynolds goes after his
12th victory of the season as the Houston Astros try to snap a
season-high four-game losing streak against the Arizona
Diamondbacks. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
