<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINO-URBAN-SCENE-NY     07-14 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-URBAN-SCENE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WOMAN, TWO CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SILVANA PATERNOSTRO  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   I live in New York City, the capital of English-speaking
culture. But I can go entire days without ever speaking English.
Today was one of those days. This morning, I didn't have exact
change for the bus ride so I went into a Korean deli and asked the
Ecuadorian behind the register for it.
</P>
<P>
   On the bus, coming down Seventh Avenue, I tried reading a few
pages of ``Three Trapped Tigers,'' by the Cuban writer Guillermo
Cabrera Infante. But I was distracted by the stories of a Dominican
mother, who, on a nearby seat, was telling her young son about his
grandmother's house in Santo Domingo.
</P>
<P>
   I closed my book and decided to notice New York's Latin face.
Behind me, two teen-age girlfriends chatted half in English, half
in Spanish. One of them carried a keychain with the Colombian flag
hooked to the pocket of her backpack; the other was wearing a
necklace of yellow, blue and red plastic beads that ended in the
three-color flag of five Latin countries.
</P>
<P>
   I recalled how at the Sunday rumba in Central Park, the bata
drums might as easily have been played by a Puerto Rican or a
Dominican as a Cuban. New York, I thought, has shown me so much of
my own culture. It is here, not in my native Colombia, after all,
where I have tried to dance a tango and a ``danzon.''
</P>
<P>
   New York has always been a city of immigrants. A 1998 report by
the Census Bureau shows that one out of five New Yorkers is
foreign-born. If at the turn of the century, they arrived from
Europe, today they are arriving from the Caribbean and from Central
and South America. Most of them come from the Dominican Republic.
They are followed, in the order of greatest numbers, by
Ecuadorians, Colombians, Peruvians, Hondurans, Salvadoreans,
Mexicans, Guatemalans and Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
   New York is living the dream of Latin American unity that Simon
Bolivar, the Great Liberator, held most dear _ the belief that a
single people has been divided only by the turmoil of historical
events. And now, curiously, there never has been the opportunity
for Latin Americans to know each other as there is today in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   I got off the bus at 14th Street, a wide, store-lined, two-way
path that reminds me of Panama's Avenida Calidonia or the
commercial thoroughfare of any Latin American downtown area. It is
a reflection of the Latino community which, according to the
Department of City Planning, will soon be the largest minority in
New York City _ surpassing even the African-American community,
which currently constitutes about 24 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteenth Street mirrors the needs, the growth and the
idiosyncrasy of the Latino community. Here a Latino finds whatever
he or she might need or yearn for _ from work offers, to law firms
offering green cards, to two Spanish-language bookstores where one
can find the novels that won this year's Alfaguara Prize, Spain's
new prestigious international literary award, as well as the
magazines covering the latest news of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Other stores sell guayaberas, CDs in Spanish, brand names at a
discount. On the sidewalk you are offered cellular phones, games of
Three-Card Monty, compliments, pushes, dirty looks, smiles _ all
Latino-style, in Spanish, and in the accents of many countries.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, I went to a restaurant where they offer the entire
Latin American region in their menu _ from chicken soup,
``empanadas chilenas,'' black and red beans to slivers of yellow
plantain, mango juice and flan.
</P>
<P>
   I ordered a ``batido de mamey,'' a milkshake made of a pink
tropical fruit, and asked the Mexican at the counter what was the
difference between a Cuban Sandwich, or a sanduche cubano, and a
Midnight Sandwich, or a media noche.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is in the bread,'' the young man from Puebla,
in central Mexico, told me. And I was sure he had never tasted a
Cuban sandwich before coming to New York. ``The Midnight is made
with `pan de huevo,' which is bread made with eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   I ordered it because that bread, sweet and yellowy, reminds me
of afternoons in Barranquilla, Colombia, where I was born. The
baker would pass by my house on his bicycle selling pan de huevo,
also made into rolls filled with a guava paste sprinkled with sugar
on top. I have not lived in Barranquilla for 20 years, but it only
takes a sip of the shake _ its smell, its taste _ or the sounds of
the chords of a Colombian vallenato song, to feel as if I am
sitting in the rocking chair on my grandmother's patio.
</P>
<P>
   My experience is not unique. It must be the same for that
Dominican woman who was talking to her son on the Seventh Avenue
bus, or for the hundreds of people who walk or work on 14th Street
every day. It is a surprise even to hear English here.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I turned around when I heard a masculine voice say,
in the tone that North Americans use when they go on vacation to
Latin America and their tourist package includes a native dance and
a cocktail of tropical fruit, ``This surely is colorful.''
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to tell him that this is the new face of New York. That
this wonderful convergence of cultures is more than a colorful
novelty. That this is his new country.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SILVANA PATERNOSTRO, a Colombian-born journalist, is the
author of ``In the Land of God and Man: Confronting Our Sexual
Culture,'' to be published by Dutton in November. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Her article on contemporary life in Cuba is forthcoming in The
New York Times Magazine.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paternostro has recently reported on Pope John Paul's historic
visit to Cuba, Gabriel Garcia Marquez's efforts to rejuvenate Latin
American journalism, New York City's Latino community and Mexico's
``narco-democracy.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (She is a proud winner of the Center for Documentary Studies'
Dorothea Lange-Paul Taylor Prize for her prior journalism on Cuba;
and has also written for The Paris Review, Spin, The Nation, The
Miami Herald and The New York Daily News. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paternostro holds a master's degree from Columbia University's
School of International and Public Affairs and is currently a
senior fellow at the World Policy Institute in Manhattan.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
