<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      07-14 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEERS OF THE NORTH FORK, FAREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cutchogue, N.Y. _ ``Twenty-five years is a long time for a
career in any sport,'' Alex Hargrave said. ``And winemaking is an
Olympic sport.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Hargrave's deceptively casual way of explaining why he
and his wife, Louisa, are ending their remarkable career as Long
Island's pioneer winemakers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, the couple _ he was 28, she 25 _ set out their first
vines in a former potato field on the North Fork. They were bravely
_ and in the opinion of just about everyone else, foolishly _
determined to produce wines to rival the best that California and
Europe could offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that we were so young,'' Mrs. Hargrave said, curled
up on a sofa in the family home here. ``When you're young, you
don't want to take advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Youthful enthusiasm paid off, as it often does. Starting from
scratch, the Hargraves created an industry that was ecologically
and culturally in tune with the times.
</P>
<P>
   And by demonstrating that vineyards and winemaking were
economically viable, they showed that it was possible for Eastern
Long Island to remain at least partly rural and agricultural.
</P>
<P>
   The Hargraves, who were wine drinkers when most Americans did
not know much about the stuff, particularly loved the grape
varieties found in the great wines of Bordeaux and Burgundy:
cabernet sauvignon, merlot, chardonnay, pinot noir.
</P>
<P>
   ``We resolved to go ahead only if we could make those kinds of
wine,'' Mrs. Hargrave said.
</P>
<P>
   They did, in the face of the conventional wisdom, much of it
from state agricultural officials, who warned: don't even think
about growing European grapes on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hargraves had visited other potential sites for their
business that were as close as the Finger Lakes and as distant as
British Columbia. Nothing they saw offered the climate and the soil
of the North Fork.
</P>
<P>
   They bought their first plot of land and in 1973 planted their
first grapes and installed their press and fermenters in an old
potato cellar. They produced their first wine, a cabernet
sauvignon, in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Within just a few years, those who had doubted them were giving
them respect instead, and many would-be winemakers followed in
their footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 20 wineries on Long Island, most of them within
10 miles of Hargrave Vineyards on Route 48. The wineries draw on
some 1,500 acres of wine grapes, none of which existed 25 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen more wineries are planned, and each week more and
more people, both farmers and wine hobbyists, inquire about getting
into the business, which now produces about 200,000 cases a year in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   That figure should double in the next few years, Hargrave said.
``Every bottle we make these days is spoken for,'' he said. ``Every
good bottle has a home.'' Hargrave Vineyard produces 6,000 to 7,000
cases a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, he continued, ``the North Fork has become a
wine destination.'' He added, ``All year long, people flock to the
wineries to taste, to learn and to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hargraves have had dozens of inquiries about their 84-acre
property, which includes the winery, the aging cellar, some 20
acres of vines, their home, a pool, tennis court and farm
buildings. They are asking about $3 million and said they may close
a deal sometime in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   So why are they selling? The end to their wine story has its
roots in its beginning. After graduating from Princeton University
in 1968, Hargrave, whose grandfather was chairman of Eastman Kodak
Co. in Rochester, did graduate work at Harvard University in Asian
studies. By 1969 he had married Louisa, a graduate of Smith
College, whose grandfather was Norman Thomas, the Socialist leader.
</P>
<P>
   While Hargrave was recuperating from back surgery, the couple
decided to leave academia and take on something they could do
together. They chose wine.
</P>
<P>
   In searching for a site, they visited John Wickham, a North Fork
farmer who had grown vinifera table grapes successfully for more
than a decade. Seeing his red Malagas convinced the Hargraves that
they could grow vinifera wine grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Island has always had the potential to be an important
wine region,'' Hargrave said, pointing out that wine grapes were
grown in what is now Queens in the 1830s. But most of the farmers
who were drawn to the region were teetotalers, he said. So
potatoes, not grapes, became the agricultural stars. Until the
Hargraves showed up, that is.
</P>
<P>
   But starting about seven years ago, Hargrave was drawn back to
Asian studies; particularly Chinese culture and specifically the
origins of Chinese languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called paleolinguistics,'' he said. Working at night and
during winter breaks from the vineyards, he has been reconstructing
what he calls a hypothetical language from which Chinese and other
languages must have come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find time to do the research, but not the writing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that eventually we'd have time to do other
things,'' he added. ``But a winery is like a sailboat _ someone's
always got to be at the helm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hargraves do not anticipate a complete break with the North
Fork and wine; they may serve as consultants. But they do foresee a
change in their life style, which may include his return to
academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``An apartment in Boston and a cottage here on Peconic Bay sound
pretty good to me,'' Hargrave said.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, the Hargraves, who have a son, 21, and a
daughter, 23, must get the 1998 harvest in, bottle the 1997 vintage
and prepare themselves for a new way of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it has something to do with choices, with making sense
of a life,'' Hargrave said. ``Do I want people saying he's a
vintner and his field is historical linguistics?''
</P>
<P>
   They hired a manager, to try and get more free time. ``But we
were still involved because it was the hands-on part that we loved
_ the aesthetics of making wine,'' he said. ``It's so beautiful.
That will be the hard part to give up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1623EDT &QL; 
