<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, July 15. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-Y2K (Washington) _ Addressing the potential year 2000
computer calamity for the first time, President Clinton today said
he would propose legislation that would make it easier for
companies to share data about year 2000 solutions without facing
legal liability if the information proves faulty. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LAWYER-IMPOSTER (New York) _ An ex-con accused of handling at
least 100 cases before courts on the East Coast by posing as a
lawyer, including handling the Columbia manuscripts case.
Prosecutors call him a ``dissembler of breathtaking audacity,'' and
acknowledge that some convictions may have to be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT (Poughkeepsie, N.Y.) _ Penalty phase begins in
the suit against Tawana Brawley's advisers. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATOINAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-U.S. (Washington) _ House votes on whether to
exempt agricultural exports from India-Pakistan sanctions. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-FUNERAL (Ballymoney, Northern Ireland) _ Funeral held
for the three young Catholic brothers killed in an arson house
fire. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 149 points at the close. By Sharon R.
King.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARK-TWAIN-BOOM (New York) _ The premiere of the newest Imax
film, ``Mark Twain's America in 3D,'' on Friday in Manhattan is a
testament to the continuing mass appeal of the cynosure of
Hannibal, Mo. Improbably, 88 years after his death and 122 years
after the publication of ``The Adventures of Tom Sawyer,'' America
is sustaining a Twain boom that betrays no sign of abating. By
Glenn Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ULTRA-MARATHONER (Bernardsville, N.J.) _ Lisa R. Smith leads
what she calls a ''very ordinary life.'' Here's a glimpse: In the
past four months, she ran 150 miles across the Sahara Desert in
temperatures of up to 130 degrees, got stung by a scorpion along
the way, but kept going and staggered across the finish line with a
fever of 103. She slogged 400 miles through the Montana wilderness
on a week-long ``adventure race'' that included white-water
kayaking, snowshoeing on glaciers and riding 100 miles on a
mountain bike. And she raced 50 miles along the spine of Long
Island in 6 hours and 43 minutes in a super-marathon where she won
and set a new course record. Now, she says, it's time for something
really difficult. Death Valley is calling. By Kirk Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
