A4332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APARTMENTS-HOUSTON-HN     07-14 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTMENTS-HOUSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APARTMENT MARKET IN HOUSTON BEST IN YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Las Vegas) 
 
By RALPH BIVINS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rising rents, higher occupancy rates and strong job
growth are luring developers to build new apartments at a pace
Houstonians haven't seen since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty apartment complexes with more than 15,000 units are under
construction in the Houston area and another 40 projects are
proposed, according to Apartment Data Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody went hog wild. There is a lot of stuff going on
right now,'' said Marty McAdams of the Marcus &AMP; Millichap real
estate firm.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent U.S. Housing Markets newsletter, Houston
was first in the nation in multifamily construction permits in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The city's 4,832 first-quarter apartment permits were more than
1,000 units above the second-place city, Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The new projects are everywhere, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any pocket that's not been covered,'' said
Timm Wooten, executive vice president of Martin J. Fein Interests,
a Houston apartment developer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find an empty apartment,'' said Sherry Moore of
Apartment Finders, which helps tenants find places to live. ``The
nice places lease up fast.``
</P>
<P>
   The citywide apartment occupancy rate was 91.5 percent in June,
up from 90.8 percent a year earlier, according to the June report
of Apartment Data Services. The uptick in occupancy comes even as
hundreds of new units are opened every month.
</P>
<P>
   Today's apartment occupancy rate represents a large increase
from a decade ago. In 1988, when the local economy was in the
doldrums, Houston had an 80.7 percent occupancy rate.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment locators say renters have to look harder and they may
not be able to live in the area they want, unless they are willing
to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is stuff available. But your choices are few and far
between,'' said Jim Kluter, vice president of Apartment Living
Locators.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Leatherwood, a 24-year-old first-year medical student at
the University of Texas Health Science Center, said he has been
struggling to find an apartment near the Texas Medical Center. He
wants to be able to ride his bicycle to classes there. Most of the
apartments he had been looking at rent for about $550 a month, but
he had been considering leasing a converted attic in an old house
for $405.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am kind of dealing with the fact that I'm going to spend a
lot more than I wanted to,'' Leatherwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Rents have been rising.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1998, the average Houston apartment rented for $514, up
6.3 percent from a year earlier, Apartment Data Services said.
However, O'Connor &AMP; Associates placed the city's rent increases at
only 4.3 percent over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rate hikes don't match up to the late 1980s and early 1990s.
Then, many Houston apartment dwellers were smacked with
double-digit annual increases in rent. In 1992, rents went into a
flat period where increases were about 2 or 3 percent annually,
until last year when they began rising faster again.
</P>
<P>
   Rent for a brand-new unit in Houston is typically over $800 per
month, depending on the location.
</P>
<P>
   Relief may be in store for Houston consumers. Some experts
expect to see the apartment market soften as huge amounts of new
units being built are finished later this year. The boom can't last
forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to soften up next winter. There's no doubt in my
mind,'' said Nancy Tropoli, president of the Apartment Connection,
an apartment locating firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next 12 months we expect to see occupancy rates fall
and rental rates stagnate,'' said Barton Smith, an economics
professor at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Developers aren't building any inexpensive apartments. The newly
built projects are aimed at the more affluent renters and a glut of
upper end apartments could develop, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we are in the process of becoming overbuilt in the
upscale market,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is seeing a large increase over the 4,000 new apartment
units that were opened in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the heavy construction, another bump in the road
for the apartment market in 1998 will be a slowdown in the economy,
Smith said. After adding about 90,000 jobs in 1997, Houston's job
growth could be half that amount in 1998, Smith said. Pressure from
a softer energy market, repercussions from the Asian economy and
recent layoffs at Compaq Computer Corp. all will damage the Houston
economy.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting a catastrophe. But the economy and the
apartment market may not continue to perform at outstanding levels.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ward, regional manager for Equity Residential Properties,
notes, however, that Houston landlords have been leasing the newly
built apartments with ease.
</P>
<P>
   With the apartment market humming at such a high speed, it's
difficult for some to utter many negative words about the Houston
apartment market today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The apartment market is better now than it's been since 1982.
It's nice to operate in good times again,'' said Eileen Subinsky,
president of the Houston Apartment Association.
</P>
<P>
   Subinsky said the apartment construction in Houston is not
nearly as wild as it was in the 1980s. The market will not go back
to the giveaway days when landlords were offering free TVs and VCRs
to tenants willing to sign a one-year lease, Subinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Others point out that Houston continues to add a lot of new
jobs, even if the economy may not burn as brightly in 1998 as it
did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And apartment rental rates and occupancy rates are definitely
high, said Steve Sweet of Gables Residential Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is very healthy right now,'' Sweet said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry McWherter, a realty broker with CB Richard Ellis, said he
has sold Houston-area land for four apartment construction sites so
far this year and he has another transaction in progress.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said in the last three weeks, he has seen the first
sign of fear among developers that they may be building too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple of these smaller developers getting
nervous,'' McWherter said.
</P>
<P>
   McWherter said he knows of two small apartment developers that
had options to buy land, but decided to sell the options contracts
to larger developers in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Developers from all over the nation have been flocking to
Houston and the city's native developers are holding their own in
the construction boom, McWherter said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
