<SLUG> BC-MONEY-HEZELL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Careful budgeting can keep couples ahead of money
squabbles
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This may be hard for newlyweds to accept, but it's true: Most
married couples fight about money.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the issue is straightforward, like keeping the
checkbook legible and up-to-date. Sometimes it's more complicated,
like establishing a budget or managing credit cards. Sometimes it's
both financial and emotional _ like finding out which spouse gets
to gratify which wishes.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone survey earlier this year, Minneapolis-based
Lutheran Brotherhood financial services company found that only 28
percent of married couples never disagree about handling their
money.
</P>
<P>
   But here's another truth: Most of these problems can be resolved
without the help of financial advisers, accountants or referees.
More often than not, the hardest part is just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with setting aside the time to talk about money,''
said Suzanne Boas, president of the Consumer Credit Counseling
Service of Greater Atlanta. ``Discussing the issues calmly can
prevent the situation from overheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's some other timely advice for newlyweds on melding their
financial lives:
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep no secrets. ``Honesty and trust are the hallmarks of a
strong relationship,'' Boas said. ``You need to commit to
discussing your financial positions openly.'' That includes both
assets and liability _ how much you own and how much you owe.
</P>
<P>
   -- Establish ground rules. If there is any chance of conflict,
agree in advance to remain calm, avoid character attacks and
postpone the discussion if things get too heated. The counseling
service also suggests picking a quiet and private place to talk.
</P>
<P>
   -- Share your experiences. ``Tell how money was handled in each
of your households growing up, and how you view money today as a
result,'' Boas said. ``You must realize that families have
different approaches to finances, and you must try to remain
non-judgmental about your partner's experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Agree on priorities. This is a two-step process. The first is
for each spouse, separately, to write down both short- and
long-term priorities. You might include getting out of debt, saving
for vacations and other major spending items, setting up an
emergency fund, starting a family and even saving for retirement.
Step two is to combine your lists, so you agree to work toward the
same goals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Count your pennies. For at least a month, each spouse needs
to keep a day-by-day spending diary. That includes everything, from
utility bills to lunch money. At the end of the month, you'll be
ready to sort out your spending into necessities, niceties and
downright frivolous spending.
</P>
<P>
   -- Develop a budget. Write down in one place all your income
sources and all the expenses you've been tracking in your diaries.
You can find a useful worksheet on the Internet at
http://www.cccsatl.org/money .htm. It is interactive, meaning that
you can type in your numbers and the machine will handle the adding
and subtracting for you.
</P>
<P>
   With these numbers gathered and organized, you're ready to move
from what you have been doing to what you want to do. For example,
you may find you're spending more than you earn. If that's so,
check out your entries and find places to cut back.
</P>
<P>
   You're also ready to start moving ahead. If your first priority
is saving for a rainy day, you can see how much extra income is
available. Or, you can go back into those relatively frivolous
spending categories and cut some more.
</P>
<P>
   -- Stay in touch. As you move along, your priorities will
change. So will your income. You'll need to check how well you're
sticking to your budget, and how you need to adjust it.
</P>
<P>
   Think of this as a joint endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a right or wrong way to manage expenses in a
marriage,'' said Cathy Egan, Lutheran Brotherhood's family
financial specialist. ``To avoid money quarrels, couples need to
mutually choose the method that works best for their situation and
then follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
