<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EXECUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA EXECUTES RAPIST WHO KILLED VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD and MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Smiling broadly and professing his innocence to
the end, Thomas M. Thompson was executed by lethal injection in San
Quentin's death chamber early Tuesday for a 17-year-old rape and
murder.
</P>
<P>
   He was the fifth convict to be executed in California since the
death penalty resumed six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 17 years, the attorney general has been pursuing the wrong
man,'' Thompson said in a statement to Warden Arthur Calderon 45
minutes before he died. ``In time, he will come to know this. I do
not want anyone to avenge my death. Instead, I want you to stop
killing people. God bless.''
</P>
<P>
   California Attorney General Dan Lungren, who was at the prison
but did not watch the execution, was unmoved by Thompson's last
words, saying it ended a process that went on far too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be no mistake about this, Mr. Thompson is a guilty
man,'' said Lungren, a Republican who is running for governor.
``There can be no question of guilt in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 43, was convicted of the 1981 rape and murder of
Ginger Fleischli, 20. He was the first of the state's five men
executed this decade who was not a multiple murderer, the first to
have no prior criminal record and the first to declare his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Fleischli, the brother of Thompson's victim, watched
Thompson die and said it was a fitting punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The execution came nearly 17 years after Thompson raped, then
murdered Ginger Fleischli by plunging a knife several times into
her head.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has always maintained his innocence, but his attorney's
main legal argument to prevent his execution has been that he and
Fleischli had consensual sex so there was no rape. Consequently,
they argued, the death penalty did not apply.
</P>
<P>
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Saturday did not
agree, nor did the U.S. Supreme Court on Monday, clearing the way
for the execution to take place.
</P>
<P>
   As the execution was carried out inside the heavily guarded,
maximum-security prison, about 250 anti-death penalty protesters
marched outside. There were a couple of pro-death penalty
demonstrators, but there were no major clashes.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson ordered the same last meal he asked for in August _
king crab legs with melted butter, Mandarin-style pork spare ribs,
spinach salad, pork fried rice, a chocolate sundae and a six-pack
of Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson came within six hours of being executed in August
before the Supreme Court stopped it to allow time for more appeals.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, about two dozen people, including relatives of both
Thompson and his victim, witnessed the execution. Curtains,
shielding the people who had strapped Thompson down and inserted
the IV tubes into his arms, were drawn back at about midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, arms outstretched, lay strapped to a table in what
used to be the gas chamber, now reconfigured for death by lethal
injection.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said Thompson seemed calm and mouthed messages to
friends and relatives on the other side of the heavy-duty glass
separating the death chamber from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a friend, Rita Barker, blew kisses to Thompson and
sobbingly mouthed the words, ``I love you'' and Thompson appeared
to reply, ``I know.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled broadly and one witness said he seemed to be trying to
put family and friends at ease. At one point, he mouthed, ``Bye,''
according to one witness.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 12:01 a.m., Thompson received an injection of sodium
pentothal to put him to sleep, pancuronium bromide to stop his
breathing and potassium chloride to stop his heart.
</P>
<P>
   He was pronounced dead at 12:06 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
