<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERB LESSONS ON A PLATTER IN VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent trip to Vietnam taught me a great lesson in how to use
herbs _ and lots of them. It was a lesson that was, quite
literally, handed to me on a platter.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after arriving in Ho Chi Minh City, which most locals
still seem to call Saigon, I was taken by a companion's relatives
for my first meal. Dishes began arriving almost immediately, along
with a plate piled high with leaf after leaf of fresh herbs, stems
and all. Some, especially basil, dill, chives and cilantro, were
intimate dinner-table friends. Others, like saw-tooth herb (a
long-leafed version of cilantro), two kinds of mint and varieties
of what seemed to be borage and lovage, were herbs I had long grown
in my garden but had little success in making use of, at least not
in the sort of quantities that nature routinely produces.
</P>
<P>
   That's the continuing problem, one that everyone whose herb
garden is larger than a window box must cope with: Lovage will grow
to 10 feet in its second year. Mint will grow up your leg if you
walk too slowly. Yet, with few exceptions _ pesto chief among them
_ the European tradition of using herbs calls for a few leaves or
sprigs in cooking, or a tablespoon or two as a garnish.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do with the rest of the bushel _ or for that matter
with the rest of the large clump you had to buy at the market to
obtain two or three pinches for a recipe?
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam, where there is enough rain, heat and sun to grow
almost anything in large quantity, herbs are treated much like what
most Americans consider ``eating'' greens. They sometimes form the
bulk of salads and soups and are often used as wrappers, seasonings
and condiments.
</P>
<P>
   At this dinner, spring rolls containing pork, squid or shrimp
were wrapped in whole herbs, or in lettuce with some herb leaves
thrown in. Each bite of grilled pork balls, fried fish cakes or
soft-shell crab was taken with a few herbs. Eventually, the servers
brought huge bowls of a brilliant soup combining pineapple,
tamarind and tomato, and we all tore up our choice of herbs,
sprinkling them on the soup and changing its texture and flavor. By
the end of the meal, the herb platter was empty.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was repeated at the noodle shop I visited the next
morning. Although the offerings were varied _ I had hard-boiled
eggs in caramel sauce, tiny spareribs, fish with lemon grass,
sauteed zucchini-like squash _ the specialty was pho bo, the
ubiquitous beef-and-noodle soup that is eaten at any time of the
day. The base of pho bo is a strong meat stock, and it almost
always contains thinly sliced beef, bean sprouts and rice noodles,
and often tofu, egg, vegetables, pate and other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Though the components are bland, it's the do-it-yourself nature
of pho that defines its character. The soup is always served with
minced chilies, lime wedges and a heaping plate of, yes, herbs,
usually basil, mint, cilantro and saw-tooth herb and often one or
two others. Again, I sat in front of my soup tearing handfuls of
herbs _ a half cup or more _ into it, tasting and retasting for the
right balance of flavors and textures. By the time I was done, I'd
used as many herbs in a bowl of soup as in a couple days of
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, when my herbs started appearing, I was ready. I
began using whole herb leaves rather than nicely minced bits; the
flavor is certainly more intense, and the change is positive (I
don't recommend this with overpowering herbs like rosemary). Then I
began bringing plates of herbs to the table at many meals, where I
encouraged everyone to tear them into salads, shower them onto
pasta, throw them in sandwiches _ always to taste. When that wasn't
enough, I taught myself how to make pho. Of course, I still can't
keep up with my garden's production, but at least I'm making a
dent.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAMESE BEEF-AND-NOODLE SOUP (PHO BO)
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { pound thin rice noodles (labeled ``vermicelli'' or ``rice
sticks'')
</P>
<P>
   8 cups rich beef or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 star anise
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 1-inch chunk peeled fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, quartered (don't bother to peel)
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless sirloin, tenderloin or round (chicken may be
substituted), cut into 16 thin slices
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fish sauce (nam pla or nuoc mam, available at
Asian markets) or soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   8 scallions, minced
</P>
<P>
   Several Thai or other chilies, stemmed, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   A heaping plate of mixed herbs, washed and dried: basil,
cilantro and mint are most important, but chervil, lovage, parsley,
shiso, dill, marjoram and other tender herbs are all appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   1. Soak rice noodles in hot water to cover.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, combine stock, star anise, cinnamon, ginger, onion
and cloves in saucepan; turn heat to high. When mixture boils, turn
heat to low, and cover. Let cook, undisturbed, for 20 minutes to 1
hour, depending on how much time you have (the longer the cooking,
the deeper the flavor). Strain, and return to saucepan; turn heat
to medium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Bring pot of water to boil. Drain noodles, add them to pot,
and boil for 30 seconds; drain well. Warm 4 large bowls by filling
them with hot water; discard water. Divide noodles among bowls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn heat under soup to medium, and add beef; stir once, and
then turn off heat. (The meat is traditionally left rare; if you
want to cook it more, go ahead, but these slices will cook through
in less than 2 minutes.) Add fish sauce or soy sauce and plenty of
pepper to the soup. Taste, and add salt or more seasoning, if
necessary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Top noodles with broth and meat, and then bring to the table.
Serve, passing lime wedges, scallions, chilies and herbs at the
table, so that everyone can add them to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
