<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BOATHOUSE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-14 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOATHOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOATHOUSE: IN HARMONY WITH THE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By RUTH REICHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the sun is setting, the final notes of music slide
off the dock, skip across the water and disappear into the trees. A
swan glides into view, tracing a graceful path through the last of
the light. Birds swoop and call; a gondola appears on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a grip,'' an inner voice says. ``Have you had too much
wine? It's only Central Park.''
</P>
<P>
   When the band is playing on a warm summer evening, it is easy to
fall under the spell of the new restaurant at the Loeb Boathouse.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan may have no more bucolic retreat, but the owners,
Frank and Jeanne Cretella, have finally understood that trees alone
do not make the spot special. It is the city surrounding Central
Park that makes the Boathouse seem so magical. And so they have, at
last, transformed the casually rustic Boathouse Cafe into Park
View, a restaurant with finesse. Sitting outside on the terraced
dock and gazing at the skyscrapers that peek over the trees, it is
easy to imagine that Fred Astaire will appear at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   Park View is just beginning to take root in Central Park. Open
only since April, it is still immature. On days when everything is
going smoothly, the food and service are good enough to show how
much promise the place has.
</P>
<P>
   But even when the food is disappointing and the service slow, it
is heartening to know that after 12 years the Cretellas have
finally seen the real potential of the place. This year they
invested $500,000 to create a serious restaurant that intends to
welcome diners all year long. For summer, they have covered the
dock with a canvas roof; in the winter, they are planning to serve
a game menu by the new indoor fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby Tavern on the Green may be a perfect place for
tourists, but Park View, hidden in the center of the park so that
it can be reached only by trolley or by foot, belongs to New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the Cretellas, who also own Lundy's in Sheepshead Bay
and the new American Park at the Battery, took over the Loeb
Boathouse and created a casual American cafe. They expanded the
following year and eventually turned the place into an Italian
restaurant. In 1993, it became a seafood restaurant. But during all
those incarnations it never seemed like more than a pretty place
turning out large quantities of food.
</P>
<P>
   Volume is still a problem _ the restaurant serves about 600
meals a day on weekends. But the new chef, John Villa, formerly of
Judson Grill, has done his best to create an interesting menu that
is an ode to the New York melting pot, offering everything from
Vietnamese rice-paper rolls to goat cheese ravioli and a foie gras
terrine.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, Peter Cassell, has given the restaurant a patina of
laid-back elegance that seems just right. He is savvy enough to
separate the starry-eyed couples holding hands at water's edge from
the children intent on feeding the birds. And he can discuss the
interesting wine list with admirable passion. What he can't seem to
do is speed up the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in his right mind would want to hurry through dinner at
Park View, but I have had nights when I longed for the food finally
to appear. Most evenings my guests and I ate our way through the
bread basket long before the appetizers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Indian spiced salmon tartar, which was ground
too finely and served on soggy papadums, this was not a terrible
thing. I was not in a big hurry for the baked fig salad, either;
the figs wrapped in prosciutto with Gorgonzola and an almond
vinaigrette were too ornate to tempt me.
</P>
<P>
   But when the refreshing rice-paper rolls filled with shrimp and
cellophane noodles finally showed up, I was sorry that my appetite
was not sharper. The terrine of foie gras and hazelnuts also made
me wish that I had not eaten quite so many rolls. But my real
regret came when I was served the marinated sashimi, which is
listed on the menu as ``chef's selection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the sashimi?'' I had asked the waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw fish,'' he replied. Pressed to describe what sort of raw
fish was being served, he allowed as to how it was tuna and striped
bass. So I was not prepared to find that the sliced raw fish was
hidden beneath a tangle of pea shoots and peppers; nor was I
prepared for it to be so completely delicious. Malpeque oysters
were good, too, served with an intriguing mignonette of sake and
pickled plums.
</P>
<P>
   As the night gets darker and the lights flicker on, Park View
becomes even more charming. This makes it easy to appreciate
Villa's grilled halibut with radicchio and grilled potatoes in a
caper and green peppercorn vinaigrette. The simply roasted rack of
lamb, covered with herbs and served with a fine potato gratin, is
also excellent. A big chunk of coriander-spiced tuna loin, served
rare with mango salsa, is truly delicious. And Villa's version of
surf and turf, lobster tail with an Asian-accented breast of squab,
is a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   These dishes are successful because they are simple, but some of
the more creative entrees don't work. The red snapper, for
instance, which is poached in milk and served with salmon roe, has
a distressingly soggy texture. Roasted monkfish is overwhelmed by
Moroccan spices (chermoula, preserved lemons and mint). And saddle
of rabbit is rolled around rosemary skewers so that each slice of
roasted meat looks strangely like a gray carrot.
</P>
<P>
   But even when you are eating one of the less fortunate entrees,
the staff at Park View is so pleasant and the setting so swell that
you feel lucky to be there. The live jazz at the adjacent cafe,
which is still called the Boathouse Cafe, is a real bonus. And if
you end your meal with the sweet, rich tres leches cake topped with
white chocolate mousse and a raspberry coulis, or caramelized mango
with coconut sorbet and macadamia crunch, you might just go dancing
off into the dark.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Park View At the Boathouse
</P>
<P>
   (Two stars)
</P>
<P>
   Loeb Boathouse, Central Park (trolley leaves from 72nd Street
and Fifth Avenue every 15 minutes); (212) 517-2233.
</P>
<P>
   ATMOSPHERE: The country in the city; one of Manhattan's
loveliest settings.
</P>
<P>
   SERVICE: Casual and professional, although often slow.
</P>
<P>
   SOUND LEVEL: Good.
</P>
<P>
   RECOMMENDED DISHES: Shrimp-and-rice-paper rolls, terrine of foie
gras, marinated sashimi, raw oysters, seared tuna carpaccio,
scallops with caviar and cauliflower mousse, lobster tail and
breast of squab, grilled halibut, roasted rack of lamb,
coriander-spiced tuna, tres leches cake, caramelized mango with
coconut sorbet, panna cotta.
</P>
<P>
   WINE LIST: Interesting and filled with unusual choices and
hard-to-find bottles.
</P>
<P>
   HOURS: Lunch, Monday to Friday, noon to 3:30 p.m.; brunch,
Saturday and Sunday, 1 to 3:30 p.m.; dinner nightly, 5:30 to 9:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE RANGE: Lunch appetizers, $10 to $11; main courses, $18 to
$26; brunch appetizers, $8 to $12; main courses, $14 to $23; dinner
appetizers, $8 to $13; main courses, $18 to $30; desserts, $7 to
$8.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT CARDS: All major cards.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELCHAIR ACCESSIBILITY: Indoor dining room at street level;
ramp down to dock.
</P>
</TEXT>
