<HEADER>
A4384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE16-COX     07-14 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Hail this great ale arriving in Atlanta
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first thing to get straight is the apostrophe.
</P>
<P>
   It's Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale, not Tupper's. God is in the
details, one of the philosophers said, and there's something of the
divine in this beer just now arriving in the Atlanta market.
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard about Tuppers' Hop Pocket _ or simply the Pocket, as
it's sometimes called _ from friends in northern Virginia and the
D.C. area and might have thought it was a cult beer. That's how
fervent its devotees were. But these were not cultists. They were
reasonably sane people, most of them, with a passion for beer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last fall, Tuppers' Hop Pocket won the gold medal for
American-style pale ales at the Great American Beer Festival in
Denver. No other category was so competitive. In blind tastings,
certified judges ranked Tuppers' Hop Pocket best among 109
entrants. It was no longer that beer from the Washington suburbs
with the curious name. (It comes from an old English term for a
sack in which hops were toted.)
</P>
<P>
   My first opportunity to sit down with this deep, harvest-gold
beer was over the Christmas holidays in Middleburg, Va., a few
miles away from Old Dominion Brewing Co., where it's brewed. What
strikes anyone on first tasting is the magnificent crown, the huge
aroma, the very long, slightly dry finish. Here is a beer that
didn't exist five years ago and only a handful of ales in the world
bear comparison with it.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer still have origins so unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   In their nearly 30 years of marriage, Bob and Ellie Tupper have
made it their avocation to taste beers around the world. Not just
taste them, but take careful notes and assiduously catalog them
all. Lagers common and classic, ales of every kind _ the Tuppers
have note cards on beers by the thousand. (They come by this
studiousness honestly _ he teaches history at a prep school in
Maryland, she is an editor at the American Society for
Microbiology.)
</P>
<P>
   But there was one that had eluded them. Neither in the historic
brewing lands _ Germany and Czechoslovakia, Britain and Belgium _
nor in the revivalist microbreweries of the United States had they
found quite what they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   What they had in mind, it turns out, didn't exist. At least not
as they conceived it.
</P>
<P>
   So, a few years ago, they approached their friend Jerry Bailey,
founder of Old Dominion in Ashburn, Va., which already was brewing
beers of distinction (while Hop Pocket was winning its gold medal
last year, Old Dominion Lager was winning in its own category).
</P>
<P>
   They described to Bailey a beer that would be emphatically an
ale _ Anchor Liberty was an inspiration _ but with certain lager
qualities. Although Bob Tupper had done some homebrewing, he knew
that only an artisan could put the idea into a glass.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to marry the piney, grapefruitlike character of the
Cascade hop _ pronounced in Anchor Liberty _ to the spicy, earthy
notes of Mount Hood hops. ``It seemed like every time we tasted an
ale we really liked, it had Mount Hoods,'' Bob Tupper says. ``We
thought, `Why aren't more people doing this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Galena and Willamette hops are also part of the recipe, but it's
the Cascades and Mount Hoods that come through.
</P>
<P>
   And there's one thing more: The beer undergoes a secondary
fermentation of up to six weeks _ far longer than most ales. The
result is a voluptuousness few ales achieve.
</P>
<P>
   The person who's never had a Tuppers' Hop Pocket can get a hint
of it by comparing the bouquet and taste of an Anchor Liberty with
those of a Samuel Adams lager. In the one, you have an ale's
fruitiness distinctly accented by Cascade hops; in the other, the
leanness of a lager subtly spiced by Hallertau Mittelfrueh hops
(also Tettnangs), a botanical cousin of Mount Hoods.
</P>
<P>
   But this would be a hint, nothing more. For one thing, Mount
Hoods are a little spicier, more earthy than Hallertaus. For
another, Hop Pocket is more assertive than even Anchor Liberty (60
International Bitterness Units, Bob Tupper estimates). The
hoppiness is balanced by a firm malt backbone, the two of them
together producing an ale of enormous complexity. For my money,
this is the most notable addition to Atlanta's beer scene in years.
</P>
<P>
   Its distributor, Thunder Head Distribution Services, has lined
up accounts at most major package stores as well as grocery stores
such as Harry's Farmers Market. Six-packs will cost about $7.
</P>
<P>
   Places where it will be available on draft include, so far,
Twain's in Decatur; Gravity Pub in East Atlanta; Yakatori, a
Japanese restaurant in Buckhead; Wild Wings Cafe in Marietta;
Monkey Barrel in Gainesville; and the Taco Mac pubs in Sandy
Springs and Snellville.
</P>
<P>
   But these are mere commercial details, necessary only to
experience the ones that are nothing less than heavenly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
