<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ITALIAN-COX     07-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ITALIAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For entertaining during summer, do as the Tuscans do: Relax and
be your own guest
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The guests for your small dinner party are due any moment. And
if you're like the most prepared of overprepared hosts, your ``to
do'' list already boasts enough columns of check marks to choke
Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Roast in the oven? Check. Silver polished? Check. Newly
purchased antique clothes collection organized on conspicuous
coatrack (as Stewart suggests in one of her books)? Check.
</P>
<P>
   But you did forget something very important. See, it's not on
your list. Right there, under ``guests'': You forgot to ``insert
your name here.''
</P>
<P>
   Be your own guest.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's a dinner party concept you ought to be able to sink
your teeth into. Forget all the formality (and especially the
waxing of floors). Entertain yourself while entertaining friends.
Sit calmly while enjoying everyone's company. Eat well-prepared
food served family style from massive plates without constantly
jumping out of your seat to run to the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   It can happen. And ``it's the way summer ought to be,'' says
Frances Mayes, author of The New York Times No. 1 best seller
``Under the Tuscan Sun,'' her homage to the wonders of living and
eating in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians take mealtime very seriously as a leisure activity
and a time to visit,'' Mayes says in a telephone interview from her
summer home near Cortona, in Tuscany in northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed my cooking radically. I grew up cooking out of
Julia Child. I thought you had to spend all day. In Italy ... I
have absorbed an easier way of cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that ease comes because the hot days of summer lend
themselves well to chilled or room-temperature food, ensuring that
nearly the entire meal can be made days in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner you serve for a small, casual gathering of friends
can still feel elaborate and substantial.
</P>
<P>
   But the simplicity and freshness of the ingredients in the
dishes you choose, and the know-how to spread cooking over several
days, can leave you the time to experience the luxury of being your
own dinner party guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer entertaining is an easy, fluid, carefree proposition,''
Molly O'Neill writes in her 1997 book ``The Pleasure of Your
Company.'' ``Guests are willing to be wooed in a more casual way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians of Tuscany have transformed it into an art.
</P>
<P>
   They often forgo strict courses. ``At my house in San Francisco,
one course is served, then it's cleared away, and then another is
brought out,'' Mayes says. In Tuscany, ``they make huge
arrangements on one platter. Antipasti become a regular part of the
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   And that meal, often consumed outdoors over an old table in a
rich garden setting of herbs, flowers and olive trees, takes on a
laid-back, communal nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in the day, after the last bone has been tossed to the
dogs, the last bit of sauce scraped from the plate with a crust of
bread, someone ... pushes back from the table and brings out a
fisarmonica or piano accordion. Then the old songs begin,'' writes
Nancy Harmon Jenkins in her cookbook ``Flavors of Tuscany.''
``Children fall asleep in their mothers' arms, and the moon rises
over the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayes refers to such moments as ``delicious stupor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are doing what everyone else in Italy is doing _ millions
of backsides being shined by chairs at millions of tables,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Especially for those times, ``cooking shouldn't be an ordeal,''
says Pino Luongo, creator of New York's Il Cantinori restaurant.
``It should be the pleasure of creating something you want to share
with the people you care most about.''
</P>
<P>
   And when that process of creating leaves time for the cook to
become a guest too, the rewards are as sweet as the world's best
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulders come down,'' Mayes says in describing the feeling
of being equal parts host and guest. ``I lose that kind of force
that I carry around with me that is there charging around in my
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I realize, `Oh, so this is the way life is supposed
to feel.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
