<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perfect planning can lead to a successful dinnner party
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's your small dinner party. You're the host. And food experts
such as Molly O'Neill say you ``must appear cool and unruffled,
offhand in attitude, disposed to easy and amiable chat.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty easy to say; pretty hard to live up to. But summer's the
time when being your own guest is easiest. Food can be made well
ahead, giving you the time to cool down and unruffle.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick tip list adapted from Jane Brody's ``Good Food
Gourmet'' that will help you on your way to amiability:
</P>
<P>
   -- Plan menu carefully. Start with dishes that can be made in
advance. The more you work ahead, the more time you'll have to
enjoy your own party.
</P>
<P>
   -- Consider refrigerator storage space. You'll have big platters
and bowls of food vying for cooling space, so plan to use up or
discard leftovers from other meals. Now is not the time to get the
urge to add a watermelon to the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   -- Plan on no more than one or two dishes that need last-minute
preparation. After company has arrived is no time to head for the
kitchen to preheat the oven and start a dish from scratch. Try to
have all the dishes done in advance, but tossing a salad, say, or
garnishing the meat dish is an easy chore that some of the guests
might even enjoy doing.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't attempt more than you can do comfortably. If you're
running behind, for instance, skip making the soup.
</P>
<P>
   -- Formulate your menu game plan to leave time for other chores.
Plot when you'll make dishes in conjunction with setting the table,
gathering flowers, performing basic cleanup and other aspects of
getting ready.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't go overboard. For a dinner party with Hawaiian dishes,
Martha Stewart suggests transforming your dining room into a
tropical garden (borrowing or renting large plants and buying a few
exotic succulents). Surely she has lost her mind. You'll have a
better time at your own party if you turn down the decor switch and
let your great-looking and great-tasting food carry the day. Simple
flowers, plates and tableware will help establish a homier feel.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Tomato-Bread Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour 45 minutes Cooling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   This dish, from Jenkins' ``Flavors of Tuscany,'' results in a
thick, comforting soup. While the instructions warn against
chilling the dish, you can refrigerate it if necessary and guests
will still rave.
</P>
<P>
   2pounds fresh red ripe tomatoes, cut in chunks
</P>
<P>
   1medium yellow onion, peeled and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1medium carrot, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1stalk celery, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4or 5 sprigs flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2cloves garlic, peeled, crushed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound country-style bread, crusts removed
</P>
<P>
   1stalk basil
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil and basil for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes, onion, carrot, celery and parsley in a soup
kettle with about 1/4 cup water. Bring to a boil and simmer,
uncovered, about 20 minutes or until vegetables are all very soft.
Midway through cooking, taste and add salt and pepper. Add a little
boiling water from time to time if necessary to keep the vegetables
from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   When vegetables are tender, remove kettle from heat and let cool
a little. Then put sauce through the fine disc of a food mill.
Strain the resulting puree if desired and set aside. You should
have about 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Heat olive oil in a soup pot over medium-low heat. Add the
garlic and cook, stirring, until it softens (do not let it color).
</P>
<P>
   While garlic is cooking, tear bread into big pieces and add to
pan, together with basil and 2 cups boiling water. Cook the bread
and basil in the water, stirring with a wooden spoon to break up
the bread and, from time to time, adding up to 1 cup more water.
</P>
<P>
   When bread has thoroughly broken down and absorbed the water,
add 2 1/2 cups of the tomato puree and stir it in. Taste again and
adjust seasoning if necessary, adding a little sugar if desired.
Cook over very low heat, stirring frequently, for 1 hour longer,
adding a little more boiling water or hot tomato sauce to keep soup
from sticking. It should be very dense but you should still be able
to eat it with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   When soup is done, set it aside to cool to room temperature (do
not refrigerate). Remove and discard basil.
</P>
<P>
   Taste soup and adjust seasoning if necessary. Serve each portion
with a bit of extra-virgin olive oil, garnished with a few basil
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 170 calories, 4 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 43), 22 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 158
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Etruscan Egg Crostini
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 15
minutes
</P>
<P>
   A yolk paste seasoned with fresh herbs, olh helps to loosen
skin. Use back of knife to scrape away charred skin.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 288 calories, 7 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 35 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Marinated Zucchini
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-20 minutes Chilling time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   From Julia Della Croce's ``Antipasti: The Little Dishes of
Italy'' (Chronicle Books; $18.95), this appetizer can be served at
the same time as the other dishes. Try wrapping the zucchini around
cooked shrimp, expensive buffalo-milk mozzarella and black olives.
Toss a few extra olives on the plate as garnish.
</P>
<P>
   2pounds zucchini, each no more than 6 ounces
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil as needed
</P>
<P>
   5large cloves garlic, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped fresh basil, mint or parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 500 degrees. Cut off stems and navels from
zucchini and cut lengthwise into 1/8-inch-thick slices. Generously
brush 2 baking sheets with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Place the zucchini slices on the sheets and brush tops with oil.
Bake on middle rack of preheated oven until tender and beginning to
brown, 15 to 20 minutes, turning slices once halfway through the
cooking and brushing the second side with more oil.
</P>
<P>
   Select serving dish in which you'll be able to put at least 3
layers of cooked zucchini slices. Arrange some of the zucchini in a
single layer. Drizzle generously with olive oil. Strew over some of
the garlic slices and the basil, mint or parsley and sprinkle with
some of the vinegar. Salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Continue to layer zucchini slices, garlic, herbs and vinegar
until all the zucchini and garlic have been used. Sprinkle top
layer with oil, salt, pepper and vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and chill overnight. The zucchini will keep well for
several days, but the flavors continue to sharpen.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Bring to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Per serving (one-sixth of recipe): 64 calories, 2 grams
protein, 5 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 67), 5 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 6 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Vitello Tonnato: Cold Sliced Veal With Tuna Sauce
</P>
<P>
   One of the joys of summer, this dish from Marcella Hazan's
``Essentials of Classic Italian Cooking'' (Knopf, $30) can be
served chilled or at room temperature. Instead of making your own
mayonnaise, you can substitute with store-bought and still achieve
remarkable results. Served in summer's heat, this is one dish you
have to keep an eye on to make sure it doesn't sit out too long.
</P>
<P>
   FOR POACHING MEAT:
</P>
<P>
   Lean veal roast (2-2 1/2 pounds), preferably the top round,
firmly trussed; or turkey breast or pork loin
</P>
<P>
   1medium carrot, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1stalk celery without the leaves
</P>
<P>
   1medium onion, peeled
</P>
<P>
   4sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1dried bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   TUNA SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   17-ounce can imported tuna packed in olive oil
</P>
<P>
   5flat anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   1cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons capers
</P>
<P>
   1to 1 1/2 cups mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   GARNISH:
</P>
<P>
   Thin slices of lemon
</P>
<P>
   Pitted black olives, cut
</P>
<P>
   into narrow wedges
</P>
<P>
   Whole capers
</P>
<P>
   Whole parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   In a pot just large enough to contain the veal (or turkey breast
or pork loin), put the meat, carrot, celery, onion, parsley, bay
leaf and just enough water to cover. Remove the meat and set it
aside. Cover the pot and bring the water to a boil, then return the
meat to the pot. When the water resumes boiling, cover the pot,
adjust heat to cook at a gentle, steady simmer and cook for 2
hours. (If it's turkey breast, cook it 1 hour.) Remove the pot from
heat and allow the meat to cool in its broth.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the canned tuna and put in a food processor together with
the anchovies, olive oil, lemon juice and capers. Process until it
becomes a creamy, uniformly blended sauce. Remove the sauce from
the processor bowl and fold it gently but thoroughly into the
mayonnaise. You may not need any salt because both the anchovies
and capers supply it, but taste to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   When the meat is quite cold, retrieve it from its broth, place
it on a cutting board or other work surface, snip off and remove
the trussing strings and cut it into uniformly thin slices.
</P>
<P>
   Smear the bottom of a serving platter with some of the tuna
sauce. Over it spread a single layer of veal (or turkey or pork)
slices, meeting edge to edge and without overlapping. Cover with
sauce, then make another layer of meat slices and cover again with
sauce. Repeat the procedure until you have used up all the meat,
reserving enough sauce to blanket the topmost layer.
</P>
<P>
   Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 24 hours.
Veal will keep a week, turkey for 3 days. Bring to room temperature
before serving. When removing the plastic wrap, use a spatula to
even off the top, and garnish with some or all of the suggested
garnish ingredients in an agreeable pattern.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Basil and Lemon Chicken
</P>
<P>
   In her memoir ``Under the Tuscan Sun'' (Broadway Books; $14),
author Frances Mayes includes recipes she's discovered in Tuscany.
This super-easy poultry dish works with the menu we created or can
be used, as Mayes suggests, accompanied by a platter of summer
squash and fresh tomatoes. It's good hot, warm or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped spring onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1chicken, cut into 6 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Basil leaves and lemon slices for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large bowl, mix onions and
basil leaves. Add the lemon juice, salt and pepper and mix. Rub
mixture onto 6 chicken pieces and place in a well-oiled baking pan.
Dribble with a little olive oil. Roast, uncovered, at 350 degrees
for about 30-40 minutes, depending on the size of the chicken
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with more basil leaves and lemon slices.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Almond Cake
</P>
<P>
   An intricate dinner calls for a simple dessert. This cake, from
Hazan's ``Essentials of Classic Italian Cooking,'' is a firm but
fairly airy dessert that is catapulted to the heavens when topped
with cold, fresh berries tossed with a little sugar and
refrigerated for several hours to bring out the juices.
</P>
<P>
   10ounces (about 2 cups) shelled, unpeeled almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   8egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Peel of 1 lemon, grated without digging into the white pith
beneath
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   8- or 9-inch springform pan
</P>
<P>
   Butter for greasing pan
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Put almonds and sugar in a blender
or food processor and grind to a fine consistency, turning the
motor on and off several times.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg whites with salt until they form stiff peaks. Add
the ground almonds and the grated lemon peel to the egg whites a
little bit at a time, folding them in gently but thoroughly. The
whites may deflate a bit, but if you mix carefully, there should be
no significant loss of volume. Add the flour, shaking a little of
it at a time through a strainer, and again, mixing gently.
</P>
<P>
   Smear the pan thickly with butter. Put the cake batter into the
pan, shaking the pan to level it off. Place the pan in the middle
of the oven and bake for 1 hour. Before removing it from the oven,
test the center of the cake by piercing it with a toothpick. If it
comes out dry, the cake is done. If it does not, cook a little
longer.
</P>
<P>
   When done, unlock the pan and remove the hoop. When the cake has
cooled to lukewarm, loosen it from the bottom of the pan. Serve
when it is completely cold. It will keep quite a while if stored in
a tin biscuit box.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Very Fresh Berries
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is easier or better than mixing berries with a little
sugar, refrigerating them, then witnessing guests beating the
summer heat with a knockout dessert. Be sure when you put these
berries on slices of Almond Cake that the sweetened fruit juices at
the bottom of the bowl are also spooned on. Guests love that juicy
juice seeping into their cake. If you're really decadent, add a
scoop of French vanilla ice cream or a dollop of whipped cream and
a sprig of mint to each serving.
</P>
<P>
   6ounces fresh raspberries
</P>
<P>
   1pint fresh blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1pint fresh blackberries
</P>
<P>
   1pound fresh strawberries
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2sprigs fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Wash and drain the raspberries, blueberries, blackberries and
strawberries. Select appropriate salad bowl and into it place
blueberries, raspberries and blackberries. Trim leaves and coarse
tops off strawberries and cut them into sizes similar to the other
fruit. Add to bowl. Sprinkle 1 tablespoon granulated sugar over the
berries and gently toss with a tablespoon. Repeat twice more.
Refrigerate for 2 to 4 hours. Garnish with mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
