<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snickers cake more decadent than the bars
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 16: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reason we love Snickers bars is the gooey combination of
chocolate, nuts and soft caramel. That's the same reason you'll
love a Snickers Cake, a decadent descendant of the beloved candy
bar. Reader Michele Tabor asked for it; several of you responded,
including one reader in Boulder, Colo., Barbara Ellwanger Kasc, who
saw the request in a Food section a friend in Atlanta had sent her.
We used the recipe sent to us from Elsie Reader of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The cake is delicious, but it can be lumpy and unattractive. If
that's a concern, consider sprinkling another cup of nuts on the
top. And because it's so moist, we recommend keeping it chilled
until serving.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Snickers Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   11 pound, 2.25-ounce German chocolate cake mix
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3eggs
</P>
<P>
   14ounces caramels, unwrapped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large bowl, mix cake mix
according to package directions, using water, oil and eggs as
called for. Pour half of batter into greased 9-by-13-inch baking
pan. Refrigerate remaining batter. Bake 20 minutes. Meanwhile,
place caramels, margarine and milk in a medium saucepan over
medium-low heat. Melt caramels, stirring occasionally. Remove cake
from oven and pour caramel mixture over top. Spread evenly, then
sprinkle on chocolate chips and nuts. Spoon remaining cake batter
over top. Reduce heat to 250 degrees and bake 20 minutes. Increase
temperature to 350 degrees and bake 10 minutes more. Cool
completely on wire rack, about 2 hours. Refrigerate leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 600 calories, 7 grams protein, 38 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 57), 65 grams carbohydrates, 56
milligrams cholesterol, 559 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Susan Bowers of McDonough wants to know if anyone has a
recipe for Lemon Butter, a breakfast syrup delicacy that her
grandmother served with biscuits or toast. She thinks it was made
of sugar, butter, lemon flavoring and cornstarch or another
thickener.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bonnie Lovins of Loganville is looking for recipes that will
help use all the pattypan squash growing in her garden.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
Include a daytime telephone number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
