<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NANTAHALA-COX     07-14 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NANTAHALA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heart-pumping rafting, tortuous mountain-biking all part of the
fun
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bryson City, N.C.--You've no doubt heard about the three most
important qualities in a piece of real estate: location, location,
location. The Nantahala Outdoor Center nails all three.
</P>
<P>
   Location: In the 500,000-acre Nantahala National Forest of
western North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Location: Along the banks of the cold and rushing Nantahala
River.
</P>
<P>
   Location: Less than 10 miles from the Cheoah Ranger District's
Tsali Trails, world-renowned as some of the best paths for mountain
biking, horseback riding and hiking in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big part of our success _ it is a near-ideal
location,'' said Nantahala Outdoor Center founder Payson Kennedy,
who has seen gross revenue jump from $45,000 when he opened in 1972
to a projected $16 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The NOC offers a wide array of activities for those who like to
suck in their outdoors in big gulps. Located on both banks of the
Nantahala River in the narrow and steep Nantahala Gorge, the NOC is
best known as a whitewater haven.
</P>
<P>
   With 90,000 river guests last year, the NOC is by far the
largest of the 18 companies that offered guided raft trips or
equipment rentals to more than 200,000 customers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That barely suggests, though, the NOC's near-fanatical
popularity among serious river rats, those people you see driving
up the interstate with two or three kayaks fastened to their car
roofs like water-seeking missiles. On just about any given morning
_ no matter the weather, no matter the season _ you can find a
handful of kayakers finessing their skills before dawn in the 45-
to 50-degree ``Nanty.'' On weekends, there's a veritable logjam.
Nearly all of them put in and take out at NOC land.
</P>
<P>
   But the wet set doesn't have a monopoly at the NOC, which in the
past decade has become an area leader in the burgeoning sport of
mountain biking. With more than 70 mountain bikes in its fleet, the
NOC had more than 2,000 rentals last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the NOC offers classes in mountain biking, canoeing
and kayaking and operates youth and corporate team-building
programs. Even though it's not part of the NOC, there's horseback
riding available at the nearby Nantahala Village Riding Stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning,'' Kennedy says, ``we wanted it to be an
outdoor center, not just a whitewater center.''
</P>
<P>
   The NOC also aims to become more of a hospitality center. Though
lodging is still regrettably scarce, the center is well on its way:
three restaurants (one offering fine dining, another has
stick-to-your ribs, carbo-and-protein-replenishing fare and the
third, fast food), five modern rental cabins, a hostel-like base
camp with semi-private bunk rooms and communal kitchen, dining room
and bathrooms, an outfitter's store and even a coin-operated
laundry.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the feet-numbing river and lung-busting mountains that
bring you here, so let's get started.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantahala River
</P>
<P>
   With rubber rafts tethered to its roof, a bus that has seen
younger days lumbers some eight miles up U.S. 19/74 to the put-in
point. This is a guided tour, meaning that one of the NOC's
seasoned staff members will accompany a small convoy of three or
four rafts down the river.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, you'll have the guide in your boat and you
won't have to do much work other than to follow instructions.
Paddle left. Paddle right. All paddle. Stop. The guide takes care
to maneuver the craft through the rocks and rapids that can make
for an exhilarating _ or humbling _ ride.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular day, the guide opts to pilot another boat,
and four of us _ two adults, two teens _ are the captains of our
own ship. After a quick course on the basics, we are set loose. We
soon will get to know quite a few of the rocks and rapids
chillingly up close.
</P>
<P>
   Water for the dam-controlled Nantahala is released from a power
station just upstream from the put-in spot. The river drops an
average of 38 feet per mile for its eight-mile run. The first half,
with a drop of 49 feet per mile, has more fast water and dynamic
eddies than the more sedate home leg.
</P>
<P>
   All the major rapids have names, and the two biggest ones, both
Class III, are at either end of the trip. The rest of the journey
consists of mild to medium Class I and II rapids.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 yards after putting in you'll have to navigate the
Class III Patton's Run, a hard-right turn named in memory of
Nantahala River pioneer Charlie Patton. You're supposed to stay far
right, on the inside of the curve. We smacked into the rocks in the
middle of the river and got hung up like a rubberized beached
whale. Our deep embarrassment was tempered only by our frenetic
efforts to rock our boat off the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had we extricated ourselves than we had to negotiate
the Isle of Dumping, Tumble Dry and Pop 'n Run. By this time, only
a mile into the trip, we were soaked.
</P>
<P>
   So it went for the rest of our voyage. We got hung up on a few
rocks, spun out on some rapids. We managed to avoid Jaws and the
aptly named Pyramid Rock and shot through Quarry Rapids with nary a
concern. Then somewhere, I believe it was Little SOB Rapid, with
rocks projecting from both sides of the river, we hit something and
the paddle flew out of my hands a good 10 feet into the air and _
kerplunk _ into the river.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two hours, we approached the end of our trip and
stopped to reconnoiter the other Class III rapid, Nantahala Falls.
You're supposed to run the falls by starting on the far left and
cutting diagonally right after the first drop. Ideally, you end up
in the middle of the falls and brace through the violent wave at
the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   We came close. Everything was fine, in fact, until we turned
sideways just before we shot over the drop. We went flying all over
the boat like four circus trampoline performers, clutching at the
sides and each other while getting the splash of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, but no one went overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Tsali Trails
</P>
<P>
   It's pronounced SAW-lee. But after two days of mountain biking
some of its 40 miles of single-track trails, I was pronouncing it
SAW-ree, as in sorry, as in how I felt. You want a leg-killing
mountain bike workout with scenic vistas, backwoods beauty and
lung-popping climbs, this is the place.
</P>
<P>
   Although as thousands of dirt riders agree, it's still possible
to avoid crowds. We hardly saw anyone on a couple of recent midweek
rides.
</P>
<P>
   Initially developed as horse-riding trails, the two-wheeled set
discovered Tsali a few years ago and now greatly outnumber their
four-legged counterparts. But unlike other places where hikers and
horse riders often battle with cyclists, a voluntary scheduling
system keeps the peace here.
</P>
<P>
   Tsali is divided into two segments of two trails each: the Right
and Left loops comprise one segment, while Mouse Branch and
Thompson loops make up the second part. You can bike Mouse Branch
and Thompson on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays. The Right and
Left loops are open to bikes on Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays and
Sundays. Horses use the trails closed to bikes. Hikers can walk any
day.
</P>
<P>
   Our riding group of five took the 7.4-mile Thompson Loop our
first day. We started furiously fast on a dirt road for a half mile
before turning into the woods _ and straight up a hill. I gasped
for air and thought about how I was in for a long afternoon. This
would also be the last time I saw the two teens in our group, who
blasted away as if on motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   The next six miles were a succession of laurel thickets,
rhododendron tunnels, creek crossings and the scarily narrow
mountainside trail through hardwood forests. At one point, we rode
high above Lake Fontana, which looked cool and shimmeringly
inviting. I stopped at a few clearings, ostensibly to take in the
view of the Smoky Mountains on the horizon, though I think my loud
wheezing gave me away.
</P>
<P>
   The last mile or so we spent on a bumpy thrill-ride descent that
brought us back to the dirt road and our van in the parking lot.
The two teens had been waiting for us for about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The second day, we took the trail up to the cliff overlook above
Lake Fontana. Any climbing we had done the day before seemed
inconsequential compared to the effort it took to reach the
overlook.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, I took a more scenic pace and the two teens left us
choking on their dust. We met up with them atop the overlook, where
we sat to grab a snack and some refreshments while we drank in the
view.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, across Lake Fontana, lay the Great Smoky Mountains
National Park and Clingman's Dome, at 6,642 feet the highest point
in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   We knew it was time to hop back on the bikes and leave when a
flock of turkey buzzards that had been circling lazily across the
lake drifted our way and started maneuvering above us. Even they
could tell we were cooked.
</P>
<P>
   We made it back to the van around sunset, tired, famished and
completely satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I wasn't feeling so Saw-ree after all.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Activity fees: Self-guided raft: $17-$22 per person. Ducky
(an inflatable kayak): $27-$30 per person. Guided raft: $28-$31 per
person. Mountain bike: $25-$40 per day, includes helmet and car
rack. Nantahala Village Riding Stable, $10 per hour; half-day, $45;
all-day, $80. 828-488-9649.
</P>
<P>
   -- NOC lodging: Cabins: $125-$335 per night. Base camp: $12 per
night.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lodging elsewhere: Nantahala Village, $45-$270 per night.
1-800-438-1507. Freeman's Motel and Cabins, $38-$150 per night,
828-488-2737.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: 1-800-232-7238 (lodging, boat rental);
1-888-662-1662 (bike rental).
</P>
