<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BYSTANDER AND THE DO-NOTHINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not much of the nation's business is getting done
in Congress these days _ and while voters and Washington insiders
seem temporarily to prefer it that way, ultimately the country is
likely to favor a sound legislative record over conspicuous
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton squarely blames the inaction on the
Republicans, faulting the majority party for a ``do-nothing
Congress'' callously neglecting urgent public needs. Clinton argues
that GOP incumbents are ignoring their responsibilities by going
along with polls showing voters like the political status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) recently returned
the favor by contending the current political gridlock is all the
president's fault for being out of town so much. Lott called
Clinton a political ``bystander'' too preoccupied with his personal
legal problems to become adequately engaged in national issues.
</P>
<P>
   This fingerpointing ironically acknowledges the mutual power of
the partisan opponents and concedes that in today's Washington
politics it takes two to tango.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 40 working days remain in this congressional session
while the countdown toward the fall campaigns for survival steadily
increases the pressure for more confrontation, not less. Bad
tempers and bad policies are an unfortunate consequence of the fact
that the combatant teams are reasonably well-matched.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of blame, as on practically everything else in
this highly politicized town, there are two sides. The Republicans
have done everything they could to block the president's
initiatives. They see him as a lame duck, discredited by scandal
and politically impotent.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats have countered by blocking the GOP
agenda, reinforced by the president's veto when necessary. In their
frustration, Clinton and his party have been increasingly united
against the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties' philosophical differences are so intense that
neither side has been interested in compromising on their rival,
incompatible agendas. And they would rather run on their favorite
issues for the fall campaign than a record of muddy legislation
that does not satisfy their key constituencies demanding all or
nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional GOP majority is checked by the presidential
veto, a sufficient Democratic margin in the Senate to sustain a
filibuster and the skimpy, uncertain 11 votes by which Republicans
control the House. The Democrats are checked by their congressional
minority role, which denies them committee chairmanships, the power
to issue subpoenas and control over the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The sole major legislative accomplishment this year is reform of
the Internal Revenue Service, which passed both houses with
bipartisan support and which the president has promised to sign.
Nobody defends the dreaded tax collector.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders have stalled antitobacco legislation, campaign
finance reform and new authority for patients in dealing with
managed health care plans. Although the president has threatened to
veto any bill containing abortion limitations, subsidies for
parochial schools or sanctions on companies selling missile
technology to Iran, the Republicans have added them to broader
measures anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, for their part, retaliated by attaching the
blocked managed-care bill to an essential administration spending
measure, which Lott then yanked from the Senate floor. Republicans
belatedly plan to propose their own watered-down version, which
Democrats are sure to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., also threatens to tie up
the Senate by pulling similar amendment-attaching stunts to force a
vote on other GOP-blocked measures. In addition the Democrats are
filibustering a product liability bill sought by Republicans and
attacking the GOP for failing to pass funding for education and the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is countering by holding up all administration judicial and
diplomatic nominees.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes on Capitol Hill. Round and round, getting
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The president, for his part, has been trying to do incrementally
by executive order what he can't get Congress to do by legislation.
Such actions ``may be good for media publicity,'' Lott sniffed,
``but they aren't good leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Lott conceded, the president's strategy creates at least
the illusion of action, however limited, in a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   After Congress refused to fully fund his proposal to add new
inspectors to ferret out tainted foods, Clinton unilaterally
ordered that warning labels be put on fruit and vegetable juices
that have not been pasteurized. After the Senate rejected
antismoking legislation, Clinton announced a survey of which brands
teen-agers smoke. After Congress balked at his health care reforms,
he instructed federal agencies to sign up millions more poor
children for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   None of these are blockbusters, but they are better than the
nothing we are getting from Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
