u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-BOX-071     07-14 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-BOX-0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ASSESSING JAPAN'S STRENGTHS, WEAKNESSES
 &HT;    With JAPAN-ECONOMY-0715.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese Economy: strengths and weaknesses
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Globally competitive manufacturing industries: automobiles;
consumer electronics; telecommunications; computers; industrial
machinery; semiconductor production equipment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Foreign Reserves: $220 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overseas holdings (net of foreign holdings in Japan): $800
billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  World's largest creditor nation: Took in $58 billion last year
in earnings, interest and dividends from loans and holdings
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Workforce: highly educated, proficient and motivated.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Social stability: Extremely low rates of violent crime, drug
abuse and births out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Banking system: Riddled with bad domestic debt, valued at some
$600 billion, that has crimped lending.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stagnation: The economy has grown little in seven out of the
past eight years and actually contracted during the last quarter of
1997 and the first quarter of 1998, meeting the formal definition
of recession. Many analysts believe there was additional
contraction in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Regional crisis: Japanese banks and exporters are heavily
exposed to regional economies such as Thailand, South Korea and
Indonesia, that are suffering daunting economic downturns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Government debt: $2.8 trillion, equal to 75 percent of gross
domestic product (GDP measures annual economic output) of $3.7
trillion for the year ended March. By comparison, the U.S. national
debt of $5.4 trillion is equal to 68 percent of GDP of $8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Political paralysis: Later this month, Japan will form its
seventh government since President Clinton took office 5 1/2 years
ago. Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto announced his resignation on
Monday, following a setback for his Liberal Democratic Party (LDP)
in Sunday parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Regulation: Japan's heavily regulated economy, critics allege,
isn't nimble enough to adapt effectively to the changing world
environment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unemployment: 3.9 percent, a generational high for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
