<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      07-14 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLE COOKING: A SLIMMER CARBONARA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The excitement once associated with the first
appearance of the true summer vegetables like tomatoes, cucumbers
and corn has been diminished by their year-round presence in the
markets. This, of course, is thanks to the fact that it's always
summer somewhere and that long-distance shipping has become
inexpensive and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nothing beats real seasonal produce, which is by
definition local and therefore more likely to be fresher and
tastier. And zucchini, among the first and most prolific of the
midsummer vegetables, is now at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best and most unusual uses for zucchini is as a
substitute for meat in a kind of vegetarian spaghetti alla
carbonara. Carbonara _ named for the charcoal producers who worked
for weeks on end in the woods and depended on long-keeping
ingredients for cooking _ was, for many Americans, one of the first
pasta dishes they ate that was not swimming in tomato sauce. Tossed
with egg, crisp bacon or pancetta and loads of Parmesan, it was a
revelation. Since then, spaghetti alla carbonara has become
something of a symbol for over-the-top pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Made with zucchini, the dish becomes a little less fat-laden.
But because the backbone of the sauce remains eggs and Parmesan, it
is still rich _ and quite delicious.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those pasta sauces that can be put together in
just about the time it takes to boil a gallon of water. And
although there is almost no technique involved, there are a few
points worth making:
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to cook the zucchini enough to brown it a bit, which
will enhance its flavor. The eggs will cook fully from the heat of
the pasta. But if this makes you at all nervous, do the final
tossing of eggs, cheese and pasta in the cooking pot, over the
lowest heat.
</P>
<P>
   Use top-quality hard cheese, since its flavor will dominate.
Genuine Parmigiano-Reggiano is probably best, but a good hard
pecorino is nice in this dish, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mint is the herb of choice; its fresh taste is the most unusual
aspect of this preparation. But you can substitute parsley or
basil.
</P>
<P>
   SPAGHETTI WITH ZUCCHINI AND MINT
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 small zucchini, about a pound, washed, trimmed and cut
into slices [ to \ inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti, linguine or other long pasta
</P>
<P>
   { cup roughly chopped mint, parsley or basil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Salt a large pot of water, and bring it to a boil over high
heat. Put the olive oil into a 10- or 12-inch skillet over
medium-high heat. A minute later, add the zucchini, and cook,
stirring only occasionally, until very tender and lightly browned,
10 to 15 minutes. Season with a little salt and a lot of pepper.
</P>
<P>
   2. Beat the eggs and { cup of the cheese together. Add the pasta
to the boiling water, and cook until it is tender but firm. When it
is done, drain it, and combine it immediately with the
egg-and-cheese mixture, tossing until the egg is cooked. Add the
zucchini, and toss again. Taste, and add more salt and pepper if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   3. Toss in the herb, and serve immediately, passing the
remaining cheese at the table. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
