<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLIDER-TOWN-HNS &LR;      07-14 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLIDER-TOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN COLLIDES WITH DESTINY, AND SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROY BRAGG  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAXAHACHIE, Texas _ Common sense would suggest the economy of
this historic town would be as buried and lifeless as the empty
tunnels of the ill-fated superconducting super collider.
</P>
<P>
   It has been five years since Congress killed the $11 billion
project that would have made this the global center for particle
physics.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal agencies spent $2 billion on the project.
Texas expected to see $30 billion in economic activity because of
it. And Waxahachie, about 30 minutes outside of Dallas, was gripped
by collider fever.
</P>
<P>
   When the project died _ only 20 percent completed _ locals
feared the town's economy would die with it.
</P>
<P>
   But Waxahachie, population 20,000, is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Super Wal-Mart. A Home Depot is being built and retail
stores and subdivisions are popping up on the northern and western
edges of town, said N.B. ``Buck'' Jordan, the Waxahachie Chamber of
Commerce executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Temple Re-Con, a fiber cement manufacturer, is building a $65
million plant here. Even old collider buildings are selling. Home
and commercial construction is up, unemployment is down, and sales
tax rebates are skyrocketing, all indicating healthy growth,
according to city and state data.
</P>
<P>
   The town officials are pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our economy is the best it has been in 16 years,''
Waxahachie City Manager Bob Sokoll said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fears about our demise were greatly exaggerated,'' Ellis
County Judge Al Cornelius said.
</P>
<P>
   The seat of Ellis County, Waxahachie is 30 miles south of Dallas
on Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scenic and easy-going place, where elm-shaded streets are
lined with gingerbread-laced Victorian houses. Folks still shop
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The town's name comes from an Indian word meaning cow or
buffalo, according to historical accounts. The city grew as a
cotton center in the late 1800s, taking advantage of the fertile
black prairie and its location as railroad hub.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton prices plummeted during the Depression and the city's
then-meteoric growth stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the town was best known for its backdrop of
historical homes. Several movies, including ``Trip to Bountiful''
and ``Tender Mercies,'' have taken advantage of its homey
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Things were quiet until 1988, when a high-stakes national search
by the Energy Department culminated in Waxahachie's selection as
the site for the superconducting super collider.
</P>
<P>
   The device would operate like this: Two proton rays, each about
as thin as a strand of human hair, would be whipped to near-light
speeds by 10,000 large, super-cooled magnets.
</P>
<P>
   The collisions would be studied in hopes they would shed light
on the origins of matter. The real-world impact would be in
scientific and economic innovations based on newly-gained knowledge
of sub-atomic particles.
</P>
<P>
   There were other colliders in Switzerland and Illinois, but this
was going to be the Texas-sized version _ bigger, better and
faster.
</P>
<P>
   The gold rush was on. Speculators bought land all over the
county. The Legislature approved $250 million in revenue bonds and
voters approved $250 million more in general obligation bonds to
fund the state's share of the tab. That included $75 million to buy
the land above the collider site, a move that forced nearly 200
landowners off their family farms.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as quickly, it was over. The project had been
approved with the help of Texans in Congress _ Democrats Jim Wright
was the House speaker and Lloyd Bentsen chaired the Senate Finance
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993, there were different leaders in Congress and the
push was on to control federal spending. Funding was cut, with many
opponents calling the superconducting super collider a boondoggle.
</P>
<P>
   The project was officially pronounced dead when President
Clinton signed the 1994 Energy and Water Development Appropriations
Bill on Oct. 28, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Sokoll, the city manager, blames the failure on politics and the
scientific community's inability to recognize the threat to the
project of angry legislators.
</P>
<P>
   A key factor in the superconducting super collider's demise was
the inability of Nobel Prize-winning physicists to explain exactly
what the project would do. Congressional debate over the origin of
matter in the universe didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be the smartest scientists in the world, but they
didn't do a good job of selling the project nationally,'' Sokoll
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sokoll believes the town survived the debacle, then thrived,
because officials were forced to hone their sales pitch while
seeking the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably learned a whole lot about economic development,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably recognized, more than anything else, that we
really do have a natural place for industry,'' added Jordan, the
chamber director. ``To have the cutting edge of science and
technology in your back yard would've been exciting. It was quite
an education.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The town's proximity to booming Dallas has helped in softening
the loss of the Energy Department project.
</P>
<P>
   Housing and commercial building starts have tripled since the
project was scrapped, according to city figures. Cornelius, the
county judge, says area unemployment is less than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales tax rebates to the city are up 60 percent from last year,
and the 1997 figure is up 53 percent from 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As for the collider, the bills are almost paid.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government paid Texas $210 million in cash and gave
the state $500 million in collider assets as part of a 1994
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Porras, general counsel of the Texas Public Finance
Authority, said the state has paid off the revenue bond debt and in
the last two years, retired about $144 million of the remaining
$250 million in general obligation bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings on the collider campus have been sold, said Ron
Calhoun, a General Land Office spokesman, and that money is being
used to pay off the bond debt.
</P>
<P>
   The hole remains. Nearly 15 miles of tunnel, most of it 16 feet
high and 200 feet below the surface, were excavated, Jordan said.
Today, entrances to the tunnel are plugged with rock and debris.
</P>
<P>
   Sokoll says townspeople have no regrets about seeking the prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, the ride was fun,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIGS-EATING-WELL-ART-     07-14 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGS-EATING-WELL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING RARE PIGS, THE TASTY SORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., England)   (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Ka-BOSS, ka-BOSS, ka-BOSS.''
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny morning last week, Annie Farrell was using her
all-purpose animal call to round up her Large Black pigs. The three
sows and a boar came readily, thinking there might be food; the six
piglets were having too much fun foraging.
</P>
<P>
   When they finally trotted over from a nearby field, Ms. Farrell
couldn't help gushing over the Large Blacks, one of the highly
endangered domesticated breeds she is trying to save on a farm less
than an hour from New York. ``They are wonderful pigs, good
natured, great mothers, very protective,'' she said, then stopped
herself before adding, ``I don't want to get mushy about them
because they are the best eating.''
</P>
<P>
   Good eating. That's Ms. Farrell's mantra.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing she has learned in her efforts to save
historic breeds of farm animals from extinction, it is the need to
get people excited about eating the food these animals produce.
It's all well and good to talk about preserving parts of the gene
pool, but the only thing that will make the idea economically
viable is meat tasty enough that people will want to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Just think of a Noah's Ark for epicures.
</P>
<P>
   The pig-calling might have been a scene out of ``Babe,'' but Ms.
Farrell and her patrons, Nancy and Jerome Kohlberg, are deadly
serious about their purpose at Cabbage Hill Farm, 200 bucolic acres
in the backwoods of Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   The broods at the farm include 29 Large Black pigs, a rare
Gloucestershire Old Spots sow, 32 Scottish Highland cattle, 72
Shetland sheep, 16 Shetland geese, 40 Shetland ducks and very rare
Bronze turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   These are the breeds that factory farming forgot, once popular
but now disappearing in favor of fast-growing animals that yield
the highest profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish cattle are accustomed to being outside in cold
weather, and they have adapted to it by growing a heavy hairy coat
rather than an extra layer of fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the meat tested at two different labs _ the first
report was so surprising we couldn't believe it,'' Ms. Farrell
said. ``The meat has the same cholesterol count as white-meat
chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish Highland cattle are not actually listed as
endangered by Britain's Rare Breeds Survival Trust, the pioneer
conservation organization, now a quarter-century old. But they are
classified as a ``minor'' breed, meaning they are definitely
outside mainstream agribusiness. ``We are watching them to make
sure they don't head toward our priority lists,'' said Richard
Lutwyche, the publicity officer of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Farrell is looking for butchers who are willing to hang
the Scottish Highland beef she and the Kohlbergs are raising (hint:
the farm's number is 914-241-2658). Fed exclusively on grass, the
beef is filled with the flavor anyone over 40 may remember. Without
grain, the beef is much leaner _ but it is also less tender until
it is hung.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know how good rare breed meat is because they are
used to fatty meat,'' she said. The Large Black pigs are far rarer:
``There are only 300 Large Black breeding sows on the planet,'' Ms.
Farrell explained as she continued rounding them up to meet a
visiting veterinarian. The three sows and the boar were imported
from Southwest England. Today they are doing well enough at the
farm that some of the offspring will be sold for meat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farrell looked perturbed for a moment: There was still one
pig missing, a sow that answers to the name of Abigail (when it
deigns to answer at all). She is a Gloucestershire Old Spots, also
``extremely flavorful,'' Ms. Farrell added. Like the Large Blacks,
which forage and are happy to root around for themselves, these
pigs are more flavorful than pigs from factory farms that are
fattened on corn.
</P>
<P>
   Abigail may be a good breeding sow, but her hearing is none too
sharp: she either had not heard the calls or chose to ignore them.
Then Ms. Farrell noticed a barely visible snout wiggling inside the
enclosure where the pigs go to farrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, sweetie _ come on Abby sweetie,'' she said, coaxing
her out. Abigail, who preferred snoozing, came out quite grumpily
and was even grumpier when she and the other pigs were vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   Lutwyche, in England, points to the Gloucestershire Old Spots
with cautious optimism. ``It was the most popular breed in England
in the 1920s,'' he said. ``There were four or five thousand, but in
the 1960s it had got down to 200 or so, almost all in one herd. Now
we're back up to five or six hundred.'' But it is still on the
trust's ``endangered'' list, its second most critical rating.
</P>
<P>
   What's so special about the Gloucestershire Old Spots? The fact
that they happily live outdoors makes them ideal ``free-range''
pigs. And their foraging skills are another thing in their favor,
saving on feed costs. Their high fat content gives them added
succulence and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All biological systems need to have genetic diversity to make
way for environmental change,'' said Dr. Donald E. Bixby, the
executive director of the American Livestock Breeds Conservancy in
Pittsboro, N.C. In other words, you can't respond to shifting
tastes and conditions if the gene pool is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Noah is only one of Ms. Farrell's goals at Cabbage Hill
Farm. She also produces salad greens, herbs and broccoli sprouts,
and farm-raised fish.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the snorts of indignation from just-vaccinated pigs, the
tour moved on to Ms. Farrell's aquaponics department, housed in a
greenhouse. It is a closed recirculating system: the water from the
fish tanks circulates through gravel beds, from which the plants
pick up nutrition. The water feeds the greens and is then cleaned
and returned to the fish tank. There are plenty of delicate, sweet
talapia for sale. (More good eating.)
</P>
<P>
   While the system at the farm is still too small to make a
profit, it is used as a model to teach people how aquaponics works.
The entire farm, in fact, is a teaching laboratory. Visitors have
come from as far away as Israel and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farrell, who sold baskets of mesclun at the Union Square
Greenmarket before most people knew what mesclun was, has been
involved in sustainable agriculture for all of her adult life,
though she has no formal training. She was known around New York as
the Veg Lady in the early '80s, when she grew speciality crops,
like white strawberries, for some of the city's best chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Building a showcase for rare breeds and sustainable agriculture
costs money, and Ms. Farrell is fortunate to have patrons like the
Kohlbergs, who share her passions and have the means to further
them through their Cabbage Hill Farm Foundation. (Kohlberg was a
founding partner of the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP;
Co.)
</P>
<P>
   She and the Kohlbergs met about five years ago through friends
and discovered their common interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kohlberg said to me, `What would you do if you could do
anything you wanted?' '' Ms. Farrell recalled. Four months later,
she was at Cabbage Hill Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone at the farm does chores, even the cattle. They gladly
do the initial ``mowing'' of the fields and are moved from one to
another as their task is completed. They are followed by the
Shetland sheep, who graze more intensively.
</P>
<P>
   Two imperious looking llamas, Felix and Eleanor, zealously guard
the sheep from coyotes, seen in the neighborhood. Coyotes tangle
with llamas at their own risk. ``The llamas either crush them to
death or they kick them,'' Ms. Farrell explained. So much for the
llamas' gentle looks.
</P>
<P>
   Just then there was a cry of ``Help, help!'' Or something like
it. ``That's either a peacock or a woman being attacked,'' Ms.
Farrell said. ``Peacocks are great watchdogs.'' In some places,
peacocks are also considered good eating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
