<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BARBECUE-ART-2TAKE     07-14 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BARBECUE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BARBECUE, NEW YORK IS JUST WHISTLING DIXIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What do Kansas City, Mo.; Chicago, and Oakland,
Calif., have that New York does not? Great barbecue, for one. When
it comes to real barbecue _ meat cooked ever so slowly over a low
wood fire until it is imbued with the tantalizing aroma of smoke _
these cities thoroughly outdo New York.
</P>
<P>
   This is a crushing fact for barbecue lovers in New York.
Barbecue may be the most fetishized of all foods, inspiring
countless books, odes and arguments in which otherwise
mild-mannered people rise into passionate lathers over particular
meats, methods, sauces and sources. But on New York's deficiency
they all agree. And so comes the forlorn question: Why CAN'T you
get great barbecue in New York?
</P>
<P>
   I've been asked this question many times, and I've asked it just
as many times myself. You would think that, given the wonderful
diversity of New York restaurants, you would not have to look far
for food as American as barbecue. But whether you are searching for
Alabama pork ribs or Texas beef brisket, the reality is mostly
grim.
</P>
<P>
   In the entire city, only one restaurant, Pearson's Texas
Barbecue, in Long Island City, Queens, serves up 'cue that keeps
pace with what's available in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Pearson's, New York has quite a few places that serve
food that approximates the taste of real barbecue but lacks its
depth of flavor, like keyboard synthesizers that can simulate
orchestras but can't duplicate them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these places can be very good, like Brothers Bar-B-Que
on Varick Street, Virgil's Real BBQ near Times Square and Brother
Jimmy's, with three locations in Manhattan. But as far as authentic
barbecue goes, they don't come close.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that many New Yorkers lack even a proper
definition of barbecue and mistake backyard grilling, or
``barbecuing,'' for barbecue. ``Barbecue has to be cooked on wood
or charcoal, and it has to be cooked slow enough so it's not
grilled, so you're using more smoke than flame,'' said Lolis Eric
Elie, whose ``Smokestack Lightning: Adventures in the Heart of
Barbecue Country'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 1996) is the best book
I've read on the subject. Cooking directly over wood, coals or gas
does not yield the subtle perfume of smoke nor the delicate
tenderness that are the hallmarks of genuine barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion, many restaurants trumpet their ribs or
chicken as ``barbecue,'' when in fact their food has been baked or
grilled. Emily's in Harlem serves terrific spareribs, but they
shouldn't be called barbecue; the ribs are baked.
</P>
<P>
   Without smoke, there is no barbecue, and therein lies the
problem for New York: the city environmental codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of fire codes and a lack of open spaces, they can't
have open pits,'' said Bruce Lane, the co-author with Scott Bryant
of ``New York's 50 Best Places to Eat Southern'' (City &AMP; Co.,
1998). ``Which, to my mind, is the key reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Classically, barbecue is cooked over an actual pit containing
smoldering wood. Today, the pit might be a brick oven above the
ground, or even a custom-made structure of steel and brick, with
all sorts of filtering devices. But the inescapable fact is that
pits produce smoke, which collides with another inescapable New
York fact: neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   This equation results in a morass of bureaucracy. A restaurant's
smoke emissions are regulated by the city Health Department's
environmental services division, but the ventilation systems are
regulated by the Buildings, Fire and Environmental Protection
departments, all of which have separate requirements and inspection
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``A problem could originate from a couple of different types of
sources, and the areas of expertise for fixing those problems can
lie in different agencies for reasons that can be quite logical,''
said John Gadd, an environmental services spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Logical, maybe, but not cheap, and certainly not easy. New York
is stricter about emissions than anywhere else, said Charles Morris
Mount, a noted restaurant designer in New York, who grew up in
Alabama and misses the barbecue of his youth. And he says, pits
pose problems that other equipment, like wood-burning pizza ovens,
do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbecue lets out a lot of `grease-laden vapors' _ that's how
they term it _ and the pizza oven has minimal grease-laden
vapors,'' he said. ``All smoke is not equal. The neighbors are the
ones that call.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan is simply too densely populated for authentic pits, so
restaurants must compromise. Brothers Bar-B-Que, for example, has a
kitchen smoker that uses hickory wood and, in fact, produces an
excellent North Carolina-style pulled pork, with a smoky flavor and
a properly vinegary sauce. It's the best pork shoulder barbecue
that I've had in New York, and yet there are subtle differences
from the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a flavor that just can't be approximated by a
smoker,'' Lane said. ``Some have chambers for hardwoods, and that
helps, but it's still not quite the same as being over the embers
in a pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's Texas Barbecue, formerly known as Stick to Your Ribs,
opened in Long Island City in 1992. Ellen Goldberg, the owner, and
her former partner, Robert Pearson, chose that site partly because
it was the only place they could find with no immediate neighbors
and a big open yard that could accommodate a pit. Even so, putting
in a pit was far more complicated than simply digging a hole. They
had to buy a wood-burning pit from a specialist, J.&AMP; R.
Manufacturing, which cost $13,000, and then have it customized for
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City has all kinds of special requirements, like a
whole electrical component, which we never use, that would work as
a convection oven, too,'' Ms. Goldman said. ``I don't know why _
it's New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Pearson's has not escaped the notice of New York's
myriad inspectors, who seem to have an inexhaustible supply of
rules. ``The environmental services division of the Health
Department gave us a clean bill of health,'' Ms. Goldman recalled.
``But anytime somebody complains, an inspector comes. Sometimes
they come and say everything is fine; half the time they cite us
for a violation, and the fines escalate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's might be able to pacify the inspectors for good if
they installed a charcoal-filtering system, but that costs tens of
thousands of dollars and hundreds in monthly maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant found out firsthand how costly a Manhattan
venture could be when it opened a branch on the Upper West Side a
few years back. Because of the expense and environmental
regulations, all the cooking was done in Long Island City, and the
meat was trucked to Manhattan. But that left the gloriously smoky
beef brisket dried out, a problem that was not solved before the
restaurant was damaged by a fire, ending the venture.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
