<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BARBECUE-ART-2NDTA     07-14 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BARBECUE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEW YORK: the venture.   &HT;    Given the expense and the complicated regulations, it's hard to
imagine the casual barbecue establishments that you find in Memphis
or Kansas City thriving here. In those places, barbecue joints are
simply a part of the fabric of neighborhoods, whether in the back
of a bar, in a shopping center or on a corner.
 &HT;    In Manhattan, at least, a place like Virgil's, near Times
Square, seems to be from another universe, a place that has more in
common with theme restaurants than with barbecue pits.
Notwithstanding Virgil's sincere veneration for authentic barbecue,
there's a slickness to it that sets it as far apart from a real
barbecue restaurant as the House of Blues is from a South Side
blues joint in Chicago.
 &HT;    Like Chicago blues, barbecue was imported to the North by
migrating Southerners, most of them black. You might think that you
would find barbecue restaurants in neighborhoods settled by former
Southerners, like Harlem; Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, and
Jamaica, Queens, but it's not the case. Many of these neighborhoods
have the same problems with population density and city
regulations.
 &HT;    Mississippi Barbecue, a takeout shack on a sparsely populated
stretch of Baisley Boulevard in Jamaica, is an exception, and
judging by the lines that often stretch out the door, a welcome
one. The cook there prepares the barbecue out behind the little
wood shack, and it's a small-enough operation to pose little bother
to neighbors or the city. The spareribs in particular are great for
New York; yet, truth be told, Mississippi Barbecue would be no
better than ordinary in barbecue centers.
 &HT;    ``You'd think that everybody would be copying them, but nobody
has,'' said Jim Leff, whose book, ``The Eclectic Gourmet Guide to
Greater New York City,'' is to be published this October by Menasha
Ridge Press. But Leff, who perpetually scours the city for offbeat
eating places, has noticed a wave of informal West Indian places,
like Seamorhen on Guy R. Brewer Boulevard in Jamaica.
 &HT;    On any given day, the enticing aroma of smoke that arises from
the half oil drum on the sidewalk outside Seamorhen comes from
jerk, the Jamaican variation of barbecue, in which the meat is
rubbed with a blend of chili and spices. The same is true in
Brooklyn, where you're not likely to find American barbecue, but
where you can find Badoo International on Church Avenue in East
Flatbush, where the smoky intensity of the jerk chicken rivals the
best barbecue.
 &HT;    Perhaps jerk will be New York's great contribution to the
nation's appetite for barbecue. It certainly reflects immigration
patterns. The City Planning Office says New York lags behind key
barbecue centers in the percentage of its population born in the
South. But New York far outdistances these cities in its
Caribbean-born population.
 &HT;    That offers little solace to New York's barbecue lovers, though.
Even so, few have gone to the lengths of Patricia Lee, the owner of
Carolina Country Kitchen and North Carolina Country Products in
Bedford-Stuyvesant. She makes her own sweet potato pies and braised
oxtails, but when it comes to barbecue, she has it shipped in from
North Carolina. ``To get the Southern taste here is kind of hard,''
she said.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    TRADITIONALIST'S MOTTO: SEEK, AND YOU SHALL EAT
 &HT;    By ERIC ASIMOV
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy to eat good barbecue in New York, but it can be
done. The best option may be by mail-order.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue doesn't always travel well _ chopped or sliced pork
shoulder and beef brisket, in particular, tend to dry out. But
ARMSTRONG'S of Helena, Ark., (870) 338-7746, ships only whole pork
shoulders, which arrive moist and tender. Heat them for about 20
minutes, covered, in a 350-degree oven, and then 15 minutes
uncovered: the result is a wonderfully soft-textured smoky shoulder
that you can pull apart with your fingers, far superior to anything
available in New York. The shoulders average seven to eight pounds
and cost $5.85 a pound, plus shipping. Each arrives with a pint of
Armstrong's hot sauce and a pint of its mild sauce, packed in old
sauerkraut jars. But this meat is so good that you won't want to
obscure the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, here are some of the better places for barbecue
_ American and jerk _ in the city:
</P>
<P>
   BADOO INTERNATIONAL, 5422 Church Ave. (55th Street), East
Flatbush, Brooklyn; (718) 345-7654. This takeout jerk parlor offers
clear evidence that jerk can be barbecue, too. The smoky flavor is
powerful yet not dominant, letting the flavors of the chicken and
the spicy sauce shine through as well.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER JIMMY'S, 1461 First Ave. (76th Street), (212) 288-0999;
1644 Third Ave. (92nd Street), (212) 426-2020, and 428 Amsterdam
Ave. (81st Street), (212) 501-7515. These rollicking bars are more
like never-ending fraternity parties than restaurants, but they do
serve passable though inconsistent pork ribs and chopped pork
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERS BAR-B-QUE, 225 Varick St. (Clarkson Street); (212)
727-2775. Brothers is a New York Southern restaurant, decorated
with old road signs and the like, but its barbecue is pretty good,
particularly the North Carolina pulled pork, soft-textured with a
subtly smoky flavor and a fine vinegary sauce with a hint of hot
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   MISSISSIPPI BARBECUE, 172-14 Baisley Boulevard, Jamaica, Queens;
(718) 978-8702. This takeout shack makes what may be the best
spareribs in New York, big and meaty with rosy red edges imbued
with smoke. The menu now includes jerk chicken, chopped pork and
other dishes, but the ribs are best.
</P>
<P>
   PEARSON'S TEXAS BARBECUE, 5-16 51st Ave., Long Island City,
Queens; (718) 937-3030. Pearson's has the only authentic barbecue
pit in New York, and the result is superb beef brisket, the cut of
choice in Texas. Slices are moist and tender, with a rosy-brown
crust that gives way to a pink center, evidence that smoke has
penetrated the meat. Pearson's offers other standard barbecue cuts,
like spareribs and chopped pork, but they are no match for the
brisket.
</P>
<P>
   SEAMORHEN, 118-29 Guy R. Brewer Boulevard, Jamaica, Queens;
(718) 723-9181. Another small takeout specialist with a wide menu,
including excellent fried fish. But the lightly smoky jerk chicken
is the best option.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIL'S REAL BBQ, 152 W. 44th Street; (212) 921-9494. This
barbecue emporium offers styles ranging from the familiar spareribs
to barbecued ham and barbecued lamb. It's all cooked over gas (with
some wood tossed in for flavoring), and so it is not genuine, but a
pretty good approximation. Pulled pork shoulder and pork ribs are
the best choices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
