<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-SWISSBANKS15-     07-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-SWISSBANKS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holocause victims' assets linked to Florida insurance
Commissioner
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Twice in the past three years, Insurance
Commissioner Bill Nelson approved multimillion-dollar contracts
with Swiss banks accused of stealing Holocaust victims' assets,
state records show.
</P>
<P>
   And when The Palm Beach Post pointed out the contracts recently,
Nelson said through an aide that he is considering breaking the
pacts.
</P>
<P>
   The politically-sensitive contracts come to light as Nelson
tries to assure South Florida's Jewish voters in an election year
that he is ``at the forefront'' of efforts to gain financial
justice for victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has pushed for new laws making it easier to file claims
and threatened to kick out European insurers that do not pay off
policies belonging to those who died in Nazi concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts are for loans to help pay insurance claims that
might arise after a major hurricane. Nelson signed orders approving
deals between the banks and the Joint Underwriting Association, the
state-created insurer of last resort.
</P>
<P>
   The lead bank and syndicating agent is Union Bank of
Switzerland, with Credit Suisse joining a group of other
international banks. Estimated fees for the Swiss banks: $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   The same banks are banned from state business in California and
facing possible sanctions in New York by Sept. 1 if they do not
improve on a $600 million settlement offer that negotiators for
Jewish groups rejected. The assets from Holocaust victims are worth
more like $1.5 billion in today's dollars, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Nelson renewed contracts with the Swiss banks in
February 1997 even after a $20 billion lawsuit was filed against
them in October 1996 by attorneys representing Holocaust victims.
The suit was front-page news in The Washington Post and Baltimore
Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time this was done to save Florida homeowners and make
sure their claims were paid,'' explained Karen Asher-Cohen, an
attorney in charge of Holocaust issues for Nelson. ``The filing of
a lawsuit is not the same thing as a judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust issue with respect to the Swiss banks was ``not on
his radar'' at the time, another Nelson aide said, though
Asher-Cohen said it was more a matter of home insurance matters
being more urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Asher-Cohen said Nelson is considering sanctions of his own by
Sept. 1 _ he will ask the JUA to drop the Swiss banks from their
agreement if there is no progress in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   That would break the second of two two-year contracts ending in
1999. A spokesman for the Swiss banks, Jeffrey Taufield in New
York, said of Florida's possible sanctions, ``We just think it's
the wrong thing to do in view of all the progress the Swiss banks
have made on rectifying a 50-year-old problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The news that Florida was doing business with the Swiss banks
was a surprise to many, including Melvyn Weiss, a New York attorney
and part-time resident of Boca Raton who is one of the negotiators
with the Swiss banks on behalf of Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me,'' Weiss said. ``Especially in a state like
Florida that has such an aged and very big Jewish population.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised and disappointed,'' said Ted Lapkin,
director of community relations for the Jewish Federation of Palm
Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Lapkin was quick not to assign any blame, but ``I certainly
would urge Commissioner Nelson to take all the facts into account
when this contract comes up for renewal. He should let the Swiss
know in no uncertain terms that Florida will not do business with
Swiss financial institutions until the issue of bank accounts is
satisfactorily resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men credited Nelson with his efforts to help settle
Holocaust insurance claims.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Peppard, counsel for the Anti-Defamation League in Miami,
declined to criticize Nelson's handling of the bank contracts: ``We
believe he has acted in good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 5,000 to 15,000 survivors of the
Holocaust in the state, mostly in South Florida. Thousands more
family members of Holocaust victims may be eligible for
compensation for bank accounts never claimed or insurance policies
never redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's political opponent in the fall election, Republican Tim
Ireland, blasted his Democratic foe on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Nelson put millions of dollars in profits into the same
banks that have stolen hundreds of millions of dollars from those
died in the Holocaust,'' said Ireland spokesman Joe Saviak. ``This
is morally indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland has not made Holocaust issues a prominent theme in his
campaign, aside from an April release calling for more
international cooperation to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the bank contracts may be awkward, but Nelson's
staff say they believe Jewish voters will look at his overall
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``At all times, Bill's been a national leader on Holocaust
issues,'' said Asher-Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-13-98 2023E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
