<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HMO15-COX     07-14 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HMO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HMO dispute less than expected
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Consumers apparently aren't as upset with the treatment
they get from health maintenance organizations as some thought they
were.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after Texas started a landmark independent review
program for consumers who want to dispute HMO treatment denials,
only 147 complaints have been filed with the Texas Department of
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Department officials had predicted they would see
4,400 complaints by the end of the year _ about 30 times the number
of complaints that have been filed to date.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, not one lawsuit has been filed alleging medical
malpractice by HMOs in the first year that Texans were permitted to
do so
</P>
<P>
   The Texas program, through which arbitrators give binding,
independent reviews of HMO and insurance company treatment denial
decisions when consumers complain, is one of the first in the
country. Reacting to consumer complaints, lawmakers approved the
program in 1997 and it went into effect in November.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Department officials said Monday they could not
provide a breakdown of complaints by company.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, said the numbers show that
problems about HMOs aren't as bad as some have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would have to say all the talk by the HMOs last
session about how the sky was going to fall was exaggerated,''
Sibley said. ``And I'm happy for them. The whole purpose of what we
did last session was to have physicians and patients make the
decisions, not HMO bookkeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the first 147 cases filed, the independent review by doctors
of the Texas Medical Foundation upheld the HMO in 67 cases and the
patient in 52 cases. The remainder are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   The slim number of complaints ``makes a lot of folks wonder
whether there were the serious problems that everybody alleged that
there were,'' said Jeff Kloster, general counsel for the Texas
Association of Health Plans, which represents HMOs and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason there may be so few medical malpractice suits is
because suits must involve allegations that occurred after
September 1, 1997, which limits the number of cases that can be
filed, Kloster said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, HMOs may be ``more conscientious'' in resolving
issues before they reach the independent review stage, said Lisa
McGiffert of Consumers Union in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that the numbers are rising, however: By May 15,
about 70 complaints had been filed; since then, the total number
has more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another reason why the number of complaints is relatively
low is simply that consumers don't know about the program, even
though HMOs are supposed to notify consumers about it.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer is preparing to send
bulletins to HMOs and health insurance companies reminding them
that patients should be informed of the independent review process
if a decision by the HMO goes against them on a treatment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Have a dispute with your HMO over treatment?
</P>
<P>
   If a patient or a patient's doctor disputes denial of treatment
by an HMO or health insurance company, he or she may appeal the
decision orally or in writing to a company representative.
</P>
<P>
   The company representative must include the reasons of the
outcome of the appeal. The consumer must also be notified of the
right to seek review of the denial with an independent review
organization under the Texas Department of Insurance program. A
decision by the review organization is binding on both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Further information on the process is available by calling the
Texas Department of Insurance at 322-4266 or (800) 578-4677.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
