<P>
   FLORIDA-SWISSBANK _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Twice in the past three
years, Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson approved
multimillion-dollar contracts with Swiss banks accused of stealing
Holocaust victims' assets, state records show. And when The Palm
Beach Post pointed out the contracts recently, Nelson said through
an aide that he is considering breaking the pacts. (Elmore, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HMO _ AUSTIN _ Consumers apparently aren't as upset with
the treatment they get from health maintenance organizations as
some thought they were. Eight months after Texas started a landmark
independent review program for consumers who want to dispute HMO
treatment denials, only 147 complaints have been filed with the
Texas Department of Insurance. (Golz, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WAY-2-CHEAP _ AUSTIN _ Four months after closing its doors,
Way2Cheap Inc. has gone to bankruptcy court to dispose of its
assets. In its bankruptcy filing, Way2Cheap listed debts of more
than $1 million owed to 359 creditors, including banks, parts
suppliers and former employees. Assets were $90,694, according to
the filing. Others with a claim against Way2Cheap can file it with
the bankruptcy court, said Harry Hobbs, a trustee for the Justice
Department. (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
