<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN15-COX     07-14 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big tree makes it a small world for some
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was like getting a message from a tree _ a historic and
greatly beloved tree.
</P>
<P>
   My son and I couldn't find the Caroline Avenue oak when we were
in Mobile, Ala.,driving blindly around streets no longer familiar.
When we saw a big stump, we decided disaster had come to Mobile's
most famous tree, also called the Duffee oak, and stopped looking.
</P>
<P>
   But I mentioned it here, and Walter G. Duffee Jr. of
Suwanee,Ga., came through with his own recollection of the oak, and
a letter from an Alabama cousin, who remembers the oak well and
assures us that it still lives.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to see the Duffee oak to believe it, a trunk more
than 10 feet in circumference and branches reaching out in all
directions to both sides of the street. I have no idea how old the
tree is, or who planted it there, but generations of Mobile
children have practically grown up in it. My son remembered that as
a little boy his father took him to see the oak and let him walk up
one of the low-lying branches to the heart of the great tree. His
father, grandfather and probably great-grandfather, all of whom
lived in the neighborhood, knew the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Duffee grew up in Birmingham, but visited the Mobile Duffees
and, of course, knew the big tree. He spread word to the family
when I wrote of the tree, and his cousin, Mary Louise Duffee
Philips, who now lives in Columbus, Ga., wrote reminding him that
the tree stood in front of the Duffee ``farm house'' at 1023
Caroline Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house was torn down years ago and an apartment complex
built that goes through the block,'' she wrote. ``My cousin Ruth
Duffee still lives next door, the last surviving Mobile Duffee.'' I
hated to hear that, hoping that my high school Latin teacher, Miss
Edith Duffee, was a member of the family with such a claim to the
oak.
</P>
<P>
   She continues: ``The oak is alive and well, with its seven
trunks merging into one. The limb that crossed the street and
touched the ground on the other side (we used to walk across it as
children) was destroyed years ago by a truck that violated a city
ordinance and came down that street. (Trucks were banned to protect
the tree.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The tree is listed in a book on Historic Trees in America,
published I think by the foresters society. I don't know whether if
is the biggest or the oldest, but it is one of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather, George Willespie Duffee, built the Caroline
Avenue house when he went into the dairy business out of town.''
``He also built two houses on Washington Square, one of the first
`flushing toilets' in Mobile. Running water was from a cistern he
built on the roof, running by gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was my misfortune not to know that my Miss Duffee had a
relationship to the oak, if she did. She was a wonderful Latin
teacher, and I might have tried harder and done better in her class
if I could have associated her with that big wonderful glamorous
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Philips did mention another connection. Her late brother,
Warren Duffee, was an Atlanta newspaperman (United Press, I
believe) when we moved to Atlanta, and he and I had many
interesting visits until he was transferred, I believe, to
Washington or New York. I remember him as an extremely handsome and
gifted reporter.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how a tree can bring people together.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
