<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-DARA-COX     07-14 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-DARA-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Dara, praised by colleagues, can still ease out a tune on the
spot
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Olu Dara never sweats it. Heeases . No rush.
</P>
<P>
   It's the defining trait of the performer's career, which has
stirringly touched on everything from avant-garde jazz to musical
theater. That, and his exceedingly dapper attire _ wide-brim hats
and slick, sharp suits. That, and the deliciously smeared
back-alley lyricism of his cornet playing. That, and his conjurer's
knack for weaving a tale from thin air.
</P>
<P>
   All of which may help to explain how the 57-year-old entertainer
managed to make it this far before recording his first album, the
sun-streaked and Mississippi-muddied ``In the World: From Natchez
to New York'' (Atlantic).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done everything I'd wanted to do,'' says Dara, a
National Black Arts Festival regular who pays a return visit to
Atlanta this week for collaborative dance theater programs with his
longtime artistic partner, choreographer Dianne McIntyre. Though
musical theater has been his bread and butter for more than a
decade _ composing for August Wilson's ``The Piano Lesson,''
co-authoring productions with McIntyre and poet Rita Dove _ Dara's
resume is a storied ramble. The Harlem resident, who grew up in
Natchez, has seen stints in U.S. Navy bands, Art Blakey's Jazz
Messengers and the Broadway musical ``Hair!'' as well as playing
scene-stealing cornet and trumpet on classic `80s jazz sessions led
by saxophonist David Murray and composer Henry Threadgill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olu can play in one note what most people can only play in a
whole solo,'' was how Butch Morris, a fellow cornetist who was also
part of the era's ``loft jazz'' scene, described Dara's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But making his own record, Dara says, ``was the one thing I
hadn't done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the World,'' which prompted a rave from Rolling Stone,
offers a charming mix of folklore and autobiography, sweet nothings
and heartfelt tributes to Zora Neale Hurston, the subject of
several theatrical projects involving Dara, and Duke Ellington
``jungle band'' cornetist Bubber Miley. Like Dara's live
performances, the recorded work is rich in country blues,
Afro-Caribbean cross-rhythms, early jazz swagger and the vocalist's
seductive, relaxed tenor phrasing. Fans of crossover jazz diva
Cassandra Wilson's recent albums will hear a kindred spirit (and
substantial influence).
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing his music is not: it's not self-conscious,''
says John Armwood, a jazz educator and former promoter who first
heard Dara perform in 1973, and later booked him for some memorable
shows at the 1991 Atlanta Jazz Festival. ``His focus has always
been on playing stuff that anyone could feel in their heart.
Whether it was an old person, a child or someone you could call
musically sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Dara's outfits _ the Orka Orchestra and the Natchezsippi
Dance Band _ were popular attractions around New York in the late
1970s and early '80s, the musician's indifference to recording kept
his name unduly obscured. Atlantic Records had long expressed
interest in a Dara project, but if not for the urging of Dara's
son, the platinum-selling rap artist Nas, the album might not
exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to do with his peer group, he wanted to show his peer
group that he's authentic,'' says Dara, whose son obviously
inherited those story-telling genes. They collaborated on the
innovative track ``Jungle Jay,'' that rare jazz-meets-hip-hop mind
meld that compromises neither party. ``You know, `just for
history's sake, Daddy, would you do it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dara's never been at a loss for material. ``If I had to make an
album now with 10 new songs, I could have it for you around 6
o'clock this evening, guaranteed,'' he says, without a trace of
braggadocio. Dara credits his workaday experiences in theater for
an almost casual sense of discipline. ``People expect me to do it.
They say, `We need a song right now.' It's not like I can go home
and bring it back tomorrow. I would force myself to write a song on
the spot, and found I had a talent for it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one quality that causes choreographer McIntyre to dub her
colleague ``a quiet genius.'' She joins Dara, along with dancers
and musicians, in an NBAF program of two recent pieces _ ``Blues
Rooms'' and the Obie Award-winning ``A New People on the Planet'' _
Thursday and Friday at the Rialto Center for the Performing Arts.
The artists also will take central roles in the festival-closer
``The Big Dance,'' a dance-party-as-history-lesson that has become
a crowd-pleasing staple of the NBAF. The finale should be the place
to catch Dara at his loose-and-limber best, making music on the
spot with a pick-up band. The more structured dance pieces,
however, speak to a unique and sustaining partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in working with Olu is you go back to doing what
is your first love,' says McIntyre, who has employed jazz musicians
in her dances since the 1970s. ``We've stripped down to really the
essence of what we believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of growing more complex, McIntyre's work with Dara glows
with a refined, soulful simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Dianne, it's on a higher plane than a marriage between a
man and a woman, because we do everything together, we create
together at all times,'' says Dara, who first hooked up with the
dancer more than 15 years ago, back when he was still numbered
among members of the ``gutbucket avant-garde,'' a group of
aesthetically frisky jazz musicians that had no qualms mixing the
blues tradition with freer forms. That improvisatory spirit
prevails. ``We create stories in the spur of the moment, create
dances and songs. It's unlike any other collaboration. We have like
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``In the World,'' though, means audiences will be
seeing more of Dara beyond the proscenium _ on tour with a band
that began 20 years ago as the Okra Orchestra. ``That created
another life for me,'' Dara says. ``I had no idea it would. New
fans, new people ...''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, old times are not forgotten. ``If I go to the jam
session, they always say, `Where's your horn?' They never say, `You
want to sing one?' I was always trying to get away from it. I
prefer telling stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues Rooms'' and ``A Brand New People on the Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration between choreographer/dancer Dianne McIntyre and
recording artist Olu Dara. 7:30 p.m. Thursday-Friday. Rialto Center
for the Performing Arts, Atlanta. $15.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Renaissance Atlanta Hotel, Georgia Ballroom. $10. Both
events sponsored by the National Black Arts Festival. Call for
tickets or information: 404-249-6400 or 404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
