<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIREMENT-AGE15-COX     07-14 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-AGE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RAISING RETIREMENT AGE NOT POPULAR WITH EVERYONE
 &HT;    650&AMP;add
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Labor leaders say Congress should consult some
roofers and nurses and other folks who sweat and strain on their
jobs before accepting the advice of demographers and economists to
raise the age for collecting Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political explosion waiting to happen,'' warned
Gerry Shea, an AFL-CIO national adviser for government affairs.
Millions of Americans ``who earn their livings through hard manual
labor'' will protest if their elected leaders push back the
retirement age, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of organized labor will be among the witnesses
Wednesday as the Senate Special Committee on Aging holds a hearing
on proposals to gradually raise the retirement age to 70 or higher
to keep the Social Security system solvent into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office is expected to report at the
hearing that the system could take a significant step toward
long-term solvency by raising the normal retirement age from 67 to
70 and the early retirement age _ where benefits are reduced by
about 20 percent _ from 62 to 65.
</P>
<P>
   Citing increases in life expectancy, most of the proposals for
reforming Social Security have recommended raising the eligibility
age for recipients. Under the plan introduced this year by Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., for instance, the age for
receiving full retirement benefits would rise to 70 by 2029. A
bipartisan commission, working with the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, even recommended increasing the retirement
age beyond 70 as the average life span increases in the middle of
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Once these proposed changes register on the public
consciousness, they are likely to spark an intense national debate,
because they would force most people to work longer than their
parents did.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly the opposite of what has been happening in
recent decades. The trend has been for Americans to retire younger,
not older, said John Trollinger, a spokesman for the Social
Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, 55 percent of workers waited until 65 to retire. Now,
more than 70 percent opt to start collecting reduced benefits at
62.
</P>
<P>
   But that trend must change to ensure the long-term health of the
Social Security system, several studies have warned.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is largely financed by current workers paying
the benefits of retirees. So the longer people stay on the job, the
more they pay into the system and the less they take out. Spending
more years in retirement, though, puts more strain on the system.
</P>
<P>
   When the eligibility age was set at 65 half a century ago, the
average life expectancy was 63.5 years. By 2030, it will have
increased to 79. In 1940, there were 9 million Americans aged 65 or
older, compared to 34 million in 1995. By 2050, there will be more
than 80 million.
</P>
<P>
   But focusing on a higher retirement age puts policy-making ahead
of people, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic case of business being conducted inside the
Beltway. I don't know how many policy discussions I've attended
where the participants said 'Life expectancy has increased so, of
course, we have to raise the retirement age,'' said Shea, the
AFL-CIO official. ``But this conversation has never included the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans aren't even aware that the age for receiving full
benefits is already gradually being raised from 65 to 67 under
changes adopted in 1983, said Shea. He predicted an angry outcry if
the retirement age is increased again to 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a construction worker, being asked to work to the age of
70 is a serious concern,'' said David Roscow, a spokesman for the
Laborers International Union of North America. People with
``physically tough'' jobs are often not capable of working past the
current retirement age, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But tradeoffs will have to be made if the national retirement
system is to survive, the reformers warn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they will have to find a job where they can do the work.
Does that seem unreasonable?'' asked Gary Burtless, a Brookings
Institution researcher who will testify at Wednesday's Senate
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has only three options in saving Social Security:
increase contributions, reduce benefits or increase the age of
eligibility, said Burtless.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three are unpopular,'' he conceded. ``But there isn't
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is popular is that people are living longer and healthier
lives,'' he added. ``So these tradeoffs were actually brought about
by good news.''
</P>
<P>
   One hope for the reformers is that surveys indicate a changing
attitude toward the so-called Golden Years. Unlike their parents'
generation, 80 percent of Baby Boomers expect to continue to work
during retirement, according to a national poll released last month
by the American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
