<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4548 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV21-     07-14 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 (For release Tuesday July 21)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good back road beckons in a way no freeway exit can. It does
not promise gas, food or lodging, only chance.
</P>
<P>
   You see a country road that catches your eye as you whip past, a
tempting ribbon that points straight up a hill or dives down into
the woods.
</P>
<P>
   You pass it on your way to work or going to a friend's house but
there is never time or reason to turn off and see where it leads.
</P>
<P>
   So one day you make the occasion, sneak an hour to detour
yourself, go the long way in between appointments. See how it feels
to drive without a destination.
</P>
<P>
   To give a back road total concentration you should probably see
it on foot or bicycle, but some of us are too driven not to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Choose a weekday morning in the summer when there are no school
buses and less chance of impatient drivers. You need to go slow in
order to look through fences, to back up and see if those are
llamas or donkeys. You don't want the air conditioning on for this
one. You want your windows open and your senses tuned. You want to
be able to smell a pond before you see it.
</P>
<P>
   Slow down by the rural cemetery. See a couple walking to the
headstones from a car with out-of-state plates.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a barn slumped to one side, as if it were leaning on its
elbows, probably walloped by the last winter storm.
</P>
<P>
   This is where they must go looking for chicken coops covered
with wisteria and other postcard and calendar scenes.
</P>
<P>
   On back roads the houses don't match. Funky and grand own the
same view.
</P>
<P>
   A rusted car up on bricks is what passes as garden art for some
people, for others, a satellite dish. There's a sign that someone
has a chest of drawers to sell. Another has starters for Swiss
chard and around the corner, someone offering meditation services.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino kept the Northern California hillside green through
midsummer but now there's the familiar patchwork of green and gold.
From a distance the yellowed grass on the hills looks as fuzzy as
Velcro with trees stuck to it.
</P>
<P>
   I meandered for an hour. I didn't come to any magical
intersection but I got to fall more in love with the neighborhood.
Maybe I noticed more because I was paying attention to where I was,
instead of where I was going.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered a couple great places for picnics, found a
Christmas tree farm full of dandelions and crept down a road so
narrow berry bushes brushed into the window. The rest were nice
homey details. A red barn with a weather vane in the shape of a
pig. A man walking to his mailbox in a sleeveless T-shirt like
1950s fathers used to wear and brown pants. A tractor driver with
two kids in the scoop. A white house trimmed in peppermint stripes
that would be shunned in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbing part was seeing how much of the land is giving up
its apples to make room for grapes. Much as you like your
zinfandel, it's a shock to come upon a newly prepared hillside,
stripped to the nub, nothing on it but a bulldozer. In some places
the earth looks so raw that if you didn't know that a farmer was
getting ready to plant the county's favorite cash crop you'd think
some alien space ship had landed and burned a whole into the
orchard.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of agriculture, I guess, when you switch crops but
some spots are so barren they look like a Kansas disaster scene
where the locusts ate everything but the house.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the empty spaces will be planted so that in future summers
they'll be rows of grape vines waving their leafy arms in the
breeze. But now the fields look like construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   Come over the top of one hill and you can see the uprooted
trunks of downed apple trees, waiting to be hauled away. It seems a
bit disrespectful, a mean way to treat old friends.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good local debate. How much to give up in exchange for a
wine industry that has brought the area jobs and attention and
tourists by the barrel-load.
</P>
<P>
   Some worry the vineyards are displacing not only trees but
wildlife. Some say that grapevines will be like the southern kudzu
whose vines climb so fast and thick they seem to swallow houses.
</P>
<P>
   But others say change happens and they'd rather see grapes than
houses or worse. Besides, the grape leaves in the fall give us some
of our best autumn color and we've got finer wine selections in our
minimarts than major restaurants in some cities.
</P>
<P>
   Some places along the road show that the apple is still queen.
The trees are leafed out right now, and the apples are about the
size of baby fists. The trees look solid, like survivors.
</P>
<P>
   One thing, since Sonoma County went to grapes it's been easier
to locate it for visitors. We used to say ``50 miles north of the
Golden Gate Bridge.'' Now we can say ``Wine Country.'' It sounds
pretentious but it's accurate, as long as you add, ``We have
apples, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartzpressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
