<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAM15-COX     07-14 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FTC WANTS TO STAMP OUT SPAM
 &HT;    With SPAM-BOX. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Want to make some money? Just send $20 for a list
of people you can e-mail and watch the money roll in. Or at least,
that's what spammers want you to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Spam is unsolicited commercial electronic mail, and it is sent
to almost anyone who has an e-mail account.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's annoying, it slows down the e-mail system, and a lot of
it is fraudulent,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the Bureau of
Consumer Protection for the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Spam _ sent in bulk to millions of e-mail recipients at a time _
usually takes the form of business opportunity offers, chain
letters and work-at-home schemes that offer infinite wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC released a list Tuesday of the twelve most common spams.
The commission compiled the list after an investigation that began
last fall. Using the FTC World Wide Web site and ``word of mouth''
advertisng on the Internet, the FTC encouraged people to send their
unwanted, unsolicited commercial e-mail to a special electronic
mailbox (uce(at)ftc.gov).
</P>
<P>
   The FTC built a searchable database so it could study the mail
and identify possible targets for law enforcement actions. Thus
far, the commission has brought five actions against spamming
companies, one of them resulting in a $2 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The database has also prevented other companies from getting
into trouble. FTC officials believed some of the spammers were
imitating others without realizing their actions might violate
state and federal laws prohibiting deceptive advertising claims in
all media, including e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC sent letters to more than 1,000 spammers identified
through the database informing them of the law and noting their
actions were being watched by law enforcement. Some companies
expressed appreciation to the FTC for sending the letters before
they got into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, consumers had forwarded more than 250,000
pieces of spam to the FTC Web site, and continue to do so at a rate
of between 1,000 and 1,500 spams per day.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC says they will continue to monitor the spam that they
receive for use in law enforcement and consumer education.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
