<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steamy conditions will cover a large portion of the central and
eastern states Wednesday as winds from the Gulf of Mexico circulate
very humid air toward the Canadian border. A cluster of showers and
thunderstorms will surround a high altitude low pressure area over
lower sections of the Mississippi and Ohio valleys. Some of the
storms will produce excessive rain that will lead to local
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered thunderstorms will also ignite from eastern
North Carolina to Florida as a jet stream disturbance off the
Atlantic Coast aids in lifting very humid air over the area. The
remainder of the Southeast will be partly sunny and warm with a
slight risk for afternoon thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-degree heat and hazy sunshine will embrace much of the
eastern Great Lakes and Northeast on Wednesday. An exception will
be along the southern New England and Great Lakes coasts where
cooling breezes off local waterways hold readings in the 80s.
Father west, spotty strong thunderstorms will erupt from Iowa to
northern Michigan as sultry air is lifted by an approaching cool
front.
</P>
<P>
   Ascending currents of unstable air induced by the uneven heating
of the varied terrain will fuel isolated potent afternoon storms
from New Mexico and northern Texas to the Front Range of the
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, intense heat will grip much of California and the
Southwest as a warm ridge of high pressure builds over the region.
The Northwest will be dry and seasonably warm with patchy low
clouds at the coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: LAZY SUMMER DAYS
</P>
<P>
   During the spring and early summer, the atmosphere shifts gears.
For most of the winter, storms move steadily at 30 mph to 40 mph.
The jet stream, a ribbon of winds between five and seven miles
above the earth that steers weather systems, is driven by
temperature contrasts between the Tropics and the Arctic, and
between continents and oceans. In summer, when these contrasts are
weak, the winds at 30,000 feet are much less. As a result, the
weather systems during the lazy days of summer typically move about
half as fast of those in the cold season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
