<SLUG> BC-BUTTER-TROUBLE_2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE SAY KC POLICE MAKE THEM AFRAID TO DO SPIRITUAL MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ John Kean and Jill Harmon of Kansas City,
known as John and Jill Butterflies, sat on Kansas City sidewalks
and distributed pamphlets to spread spiritual love, equality and
sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our creator does not value us for what we own,'' states one
pamphlet, ``but for the love we share.''
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts were not well received by Kansas City police.
</P>
<P>
   They charged Kean and Harmon three times under three different
laws. The couple sued the city twice and won. Despite their legal
successes, the couple's experiences with police _ who once sent a
helicopter to hover over them _ have left them afraid to return to
the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Police department attorney Dale Close said officers did nothing
wrong. ``Every time a ticket has been issued it's been issued for
some act prohibited by an ordinance,'' Close said.
</P>
<P>
   Kean and Harmon's struggle has raised questions about the city,
the police and free speech. U.S. District Judge Ortrie D. Smith
said so last month in a ruling on one of their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been browbeaten into forgoing conduct protected by
the First Amendment,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has declared unconstitutional city ordinances that
regulated sidewalk vendors and pamphlet distribution. He also
wondered why he had to intervene twice to protect the couple's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not Nazis, Klansmen or pornographers,'' he wrote.
``Their message heightens awareness about serious social issues and
offers positive and hopeful responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the court's view, these are messages the city should want
to be disseminated.''
</P>
<P>
   He ordered Kansas City to pay them $35,000. Last week their
lawyer submitted his bill for $65,000 more in city money. That's on
top of more than $31,000 in damages and lawyer fees in the earlier
case.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's lawyer, Robert Popper, said his clients weren't
after money. They had offered to settle if the city apologized,
trained police on the First Amendment and reviewed some possibly
unconstitutional laws, said the professor at the University of
Missouri School of Law in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Police now have orders not to enforce the laws declared
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   City attorneys declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kean and Harmon, they remain charged under a third law _
blocking a sidewalk. And Kean said he'll probably challenge the
city on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   Kean and Harmon spoke last week about their message and how they
became champions of the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to have their pictures taken, they said, because
they do not want to become celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to remain simple people,'' Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   At the interview, Kean, 34, had hair past his shoulders and wore
a T-shirt, blue-tinted glasses and a necklace of small beads. He
earned a degree in political science eight years ago from the
University of Missouri-Kansas City. He sought more meaning in life
after a personal tragedy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon, 21, wore a necklace shaped like a butterfly. She said
she grew up in Pleasant Hill, met Kean and the two agreed to start
their mission together two years ago. They adopted their spiritual
names, John and Jill Butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   On a cold March day in 1996, they started handing out pamphlets
with simple messages and pictures. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
