<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN STUDENTS FEEL EFFECTS OF ASIA'S FINANCIAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ ... being run by her brother, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Teh's story is typical, Stoltenberg said. Many students from
Asia come from families that own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To help students most in need, the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service decided in June to temporarily relax its
regulations for students holding visas from South Korea, Malaysia,
Thailand, Indonesia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The change makes its easier for needy students to work off
campus and allows them to study part-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unprecedented,'' said Thomas Burns, director of
international student affairs at UMKC. ``Even during the Chinese
Tiananmen Square period, students were not given that type of
economic relief.''
</P>
<P>
   UMKC is alerting employers in the area about the relaxed rules,
Burns said, and is hoping they are interested in hiring some of the
students in need.
</P>
<P>
   Worakamol Hemsmiti, a 24-year-old graduate student from Thailand
at UMKC, said he knows some Thai students who plan to work more
this fall. He considers himself lucky, he said, because his parents
have assured him they can support him until he graduates in
computer science in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have to work, but not much,'' Hemsmiti said. ``They have
collected money for a long time to send me here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoltenberg said he was not surprised that the Immigration and
Naturalization Service did not offer relief to students from China
and Japan, even though some could be suffering financially as well.
The United States typically reaches out to help only those in
developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Universities said that the students most in need seemed to be
the ones pegged for relief by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been seeing more Indonesian students coming in than any
other,'' said David Brandt, an international student adviser at the
University of California in Berkeley. ``In Indonesia, the situation
has gone from bad to worse, and it isn't getting any better. At
least in the other countries, the situation has somewhat
stabilized.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley has 66 students from Indonesia; its international
community numbers about 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   In Lawrence, KU's international advisers have talked with many
worried students since last fall, said Daphne Johnston, associate
director of international student services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said goodbye to many at Christmas,'' Johnston said, and
``we noticed a sharp decline in new arrivals in January, especially
Koreans.... We expect we'll see the biggest reduction in numbers
this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students who have had to drop out have been extremely
distraught, Johnston said: ``I just got a letter from one who had
to leave in December, and she desperately wants to come back and
has no way to fund herself.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is hurting undergraduates most because they generally
have to pay their way themselves. Graduate students, on the other
hand, almost always receive a teaching or research assistantship or
funding from some kind of grant.
</P>
<P>
   KU hooked up its students with a grant program offered by the
National Association of Foreign Student Advisers. Five of eight KU
students who applied received the grants, which required matching
funds from KU.
</P>
<P>
   In January, MU came up with $100,000 from private gifts and
grants, which it used to help 75 students. About half of them got
tuition grants ranging from $500 to $2,000, Heyl said; the rest
received short-term loans.
</P>
<P>
   He was not sure whether MU would do anything to help students
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Many universities across the country are helping in a variety of
ways, said Blumenthal, of the Institute of International Education.
The institute is offering zero-interest loans to students who
qualify, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Teh is working full-time this summer at KU's Watson Library. And
she expects to attend KU part-time this fall so she can continue to
work at least 20 hours a week. With no scholarship and no financial
aid, she doesn't have much choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard,'' Teh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
