<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-STUDENTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN STUDENTS FEEL EFFECTS OF ASIA'S FINANCIAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Chinleng Teh was one of Malaysia's lucky
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Her family was able to set aside enough money from its furniture
business to send her to college in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now in the middle of her studies at the University of Kansas,
Teh and her family find themselves hurt by the financial crisis
that hit Southeast Asia last fall. The value of Malaysia's
currency, the ringgit, has dropped by roughly half against the U.S.
dollar. That means the family will need almost twice as many
ringgits to cover Teh's tuition bill of $4,500 this fall.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   Teh, 22, has taken a job. But she worries she will have to drop
out of school before completing her degree in religious studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep praying that God will let me stay, but things like that
are really hard to say,'' said Teh. ``I'm not sure what the
situation will be next week.''
</P>
<P>
   A national e-mail survey last March of 128 colleges and
universities showed that some students from Southeast Asia already
had dropped out of school in January. Schools reported declines of
up to 10 percent for Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia, and up to 20
percent for South Korea, according to the Institute of
International Education, which conducted the survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (enrollment figures) will show in the fall is hard to
say,'' said Peggy Blumenthal, the institute's vice president for
educational services. ``The economic situation is certainly having
an impact on their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Many universities, including KU and the University of
Missouri-Columbia, expect fewer students will show this fall.
</P>
<P>
   MU could lose 50 to 100 Asian students, which would represent a
sizable number of its international community of 1,227, said John
Heyl, director of MU's international center.
</P>
<P>
   The university is trying to build up its international
community, Heyl said, so a loss of that magnitude would be
distressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that a global community that represents something
like 7 to 8 percent of the student community is a good critical
mass that can add to the cultural diversity of the campus,'' Heyl
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that shrinks too far, you can lose some of the effects
that come from a critical mass,'' such as cultural programming and
the promotion of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Growing numbers
</P>
<P>
   The number of foreign students attending colleges and
universities in the United States has increased many times over
since 1954. However, they still make up only 3.2 percent, or
486,000, of the total enrolled, according to the latest figures
compiled by the Institute of International Education.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest number, 4,657, attend Boston University. At least
25 other institutions have enrollments greater than 2,000. KU has
1,481, a few more than MU. Kansas State University, meanwhile, has
883 and the University of Missouri-Kansas City has about 750.
</P>
<P>
   About 17 percent of foreign students nationwide come from the
countries most seriously affected by the Asian crisis: South Korea,
Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia. Each of the countries has seen
the value of its currency fall by about 50 percent since last fall.
Indonesia's has fallen the most, by perhaps as much as 70 percent,
said Clyde Stoltenberg, a professor of business at KU with a
special interest in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Teh, the KU student, says her family's business in Malaysia is
suffering because the economy there is not good and people do not
want to spend money on furniture. That is forcing her family to
keep much of its money tied up in the business, which is being run
by her brother, she said. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
