<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN NEEDED TO SERVE ON STATE COMMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Women's Public Service Network of Greater
Kansas City is looking for a few good women, not to join the
military but to serve on state commissions and boards.
</P>
<P>
   The nonpartisan organization wants to ensure that qualified
women are considered for statewide appointments in Kansas and
Missouri. The 50-member network was established in 1988 to promote
effective public leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always tried to find ways we can become more involved
with the political process,'' said Rachael Steele, project
coordinator and the former assistant to U.S. Sen. Jack Danforth of
Missouri. ``Women are a large part of the population and they need
to be represented on these boards. They have different
viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials usually appoint people they already know to
these positions. As a result, men tend to select other men because
they are unaware of female candidates even though female officials
don't have difficulty finding other women, said former Jackson
County Executive Marsha Murphy, a chairwoman of the project
advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the complaint from public officials that they don't
have enough women in the pool, and we wanted to remedy the
problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that even though there are many highly
qualified women, they do not apply because they are unaware of the
positions since they are not politically involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who are not political activists, but
who are interested in being active citizens and can serve,'' Murphy
said. ``We're educating women so they know they don't need to run a
campaign to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest challenges in finding more candidates is
convincing the women that they have the credentials to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women worry about their qualifications much more than the
men do,'' said Murphy. ``Women frequently say, `Do I have enough
experience?' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   The network is working with other organizations to spread the
word. It also is providing application forms to potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The organization will forward those names to the existing talent
banks. In Missouri, the Institute for Women in Public Life housed
at the University of Missouri-St. Louis keeps a computerized
database.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office in Kansas maintains its own database of
persons interested in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Many officials recognize the value of diversity on these boards.
They want to appoint more women to state boards and commissions. So
it's up to us to put aside our insecurities and excuses and apply.
</P>
<P>
   Call Steele at 931-0105 for more information or for a public
service personal profile form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
