<HEADER>
A4630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIVER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-14 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONCE UPON THE RIVER LOVE': IN A LAND WHERE LOVE HAD NO PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrei Makine begins his new novel, ``Once Upon the River
Love,'' with an almost operatic act of love, and then he follows
quickly with the statement that love simply did not take root in
the ``austere country'' where he grew up. ``Love for love's sake,''
we are told by Makine's narrator, ``had, I think, simply been
forgotten _ had atrophied in the bloodbath of the war, been
garroted by the barbed-wire entanglements of the nearby camp,
frozen by the breath of the Arctic.''
</P>
<P>
   In that brief contrast of heated eroticism and a frigid past are
embedded the haunting images and the powerful themes of this
impressive coming-of-age tale set in the taiga, the virgin pine
forest of Eastern Siberia in the days of the Soviet Union. Makine's
new book overlaps somewhat with his highly acclaimed previous work,
``Dreams of My Russian Summers,'' in which a precociously aware boy
learns about France, and therefore about a more beautiful world
than that of the Soviet Union, while sitting at the feet of his
French-born grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Makine's new narrator is another precociously aware boy, a
hot-blooded, all-seeing, tender-minded adolescent named Mitya who
listens to the stories of a village woman named Olga and is thereby
propelled to a rebellious yearning for something more than the
place of prison camps and parched souls where he grows up.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Dreams of My Russian Summers'' marked Makine's arrival on
the literary scene, ``Once Upon the River Love'' indicates that he
will remain there. Written in French, rather than Makine's native
Russian, and marvelously translated by Geoffrey Strachan, it is an
accomplished, affecting work, psychologically complex, written in a
lyrical, sparely impassioned prose that serves as a kind of
magnifying glass on a fabulously exotic experience.
</P>
<P>
   Makine writes with just that touch of distance, that lightening
element of self-mockery that the adult brings to the most piercing
visions of boyhood. His new book is a portrait of the artist as a
young savage, a boy dressed in a fur hat and a sheepskin coat who
smells of cedar smoke. But he achieves a literary sensibility in a
region that, during the long years of the Soviet dictatorship, was
emblematic of human hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen, sixteen ... Here is what I was,'' Mitya says. ``A
strange alloy of the winds, silences, and sounds of the taiga, of
places visited or imagined. Someone who already knew, thanks to
Olga's library, that feudal chatelaines had long bodices, like the
bodice of the unhappy Emma Bovary. That the shoulders of a bathing
odalisque were tinged with amber.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitya passes the time with two friends, both of them marvelously
realized by Makine. One is a would-be poet named Utkin with a lame
leg, a shoulder that pointed to the sky and all of the complexes
that such physical deformities might encourage; the other is a
dashing would-be guerrilla fighter called Samurai. The three boys
live in ``a strange universe, without women,'' a place where the
word ``have'' is used to describe a man's sexual relationship with
a woman, as in: ``You know that Maria on the cash till? I've had
her.'' Mitya notes: ``Love seemed to us to be something carved from
the gray dusk of a dreary district center, where all the streets
led out into wastelands covered by wet sawdust.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitya compensates for the severity of the landscape by
fabricating a world of dreamy eroticism. He entertains fantasies of
a beautiful stranger whom he believes he sees in silhouette through
the window of the Trans-Siberian express. He notices a forlorn
figure of a woman who meets the local ferry every afternoon hoping
that her strayed husband will be on it. He remembers a wolf killed
in the forest and a frozen tear he saw in the corner of the
animal's eye. He sees the sun as an orb impaled on the watchtowers
of the prison camp, or entangled in barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   One day, just after Mitya has embarked on a disastrous inaugural
sexual experience, a French movie starring Jean-Paul Belmondo plays
in the cinema in the county town 22 miles away. The boys trek there
on snowshoes. Makine, reminiscent here of Milan Kundera, freights
every scene, including the most ostensibly nonpolitical, with the
weight of both political and esthetic rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnificent apolitical thighs,'' Mitya says of the beautiful
heroine whom Belmondo saves from disfigurement at the hands of the
enemy. ``Serenely amoral. Thighs outside History. Apart from all
ideology. Without any utilitarian ulterior motive. Thighs for
thighs' sake.'' It is the very pointlessness of Belmondo's
exploits, contrasted with the inevitable newsreels of medal-pinning
ceremonies in the Kremlin and the mandatory reports on the looming
radiant future, that gave them their irresistible iconoclastic
force. In the end, helped by Olga and Belmondo, all three of
Makine's youthful characters make their escape from Siberia, each
of them following a path ordained by their contrasting characters.
But these escapes are given a cast of melancholy, of rueful wisdom,
by Mitya's adult understanding of two things: one, that there is no
earthly paradise, despite the promise represented by Belmondo and
Olga's library; and the other, that the world left behind, the
``beauty and silence'' that prevailed along the River Amur, held
both the seeds of youthful revolt and the treasures of youthful
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Makine overdoes it in places. His opening scene, for example,
involves a degree of stylistic hyperventilation that is
inconsistent with the controlled force he normally displays. But
this is a minor fault. ``Once Upon the River Love'' marks a further
development in what is turning out to be an exciting literary
career. Makine leaves us with that rare sense of having been
drenched, entombed like a Siberian village under the heavy snow, in
an entirely unfamiliar, exotic world, captured and held there so
that it will long linger in the memory.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``ONCE UPON THE RIVER LOVE''
</P>
<P>
   By Andrei Makine
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Geoffrey Strachan. 209 pages. Arcade. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
