<HEADLINE>
LUTECE'S CHEF GROWS HIS SALAD, THEN SELLS IT  
 IMPROVEMENTS AT VINEGAR FACTORY  
 A GREENMARKET VOLUME  
 A CULINARY ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
(lb) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the salad greens grown by Eberhard Mueller, the
chef at Lutece, now available to the public, will his dressing be
next?
</P>
<P>
   The mesclun, the same mix of baby lettuces like lollo rosso, red
romaine and summer crisp that Mueller has at the restaurant and
also sells to the Four Seasons restaurant, is on the shelves on
Tuesdays and Thursdays at Gourmet Garage, 453 Broome St. (Mercer
Street), 2567 Broadway (96th Street) and 301 East 64th St.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Paulette Satur, grow the greens at Satur Farms,
their 18-acre property in Cutchogue, and they bring it in, rinsed
and dried. It is $6.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cheap right now because we don't feel we have it 100
percent the way we want,'' Mueller said. ``The price may go up.''
He said his mesclun is a French mixture. ``In New York you often
see mesclun with Oriental greens like tatsoi and mizuna, which they
don't do in France,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Though the mesclun is grown according to organic methods, it
can't be certified, Mueller said, because the farm was not organic
before they bought it two years ago, and three chemical-free years
are required for certification. Because the lettuce mixture is
delivered within 24 hours of picking, the leaves retain their
intense flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller and Ms. Satur will soon start harvesting tomatoes, too.
They have 650 plants of heirloom varieties. ``But I'm not ready to
quit my day job,'' he said. ``I like it too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvements at Vinegar Factory
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An urban farm has had its problems. Two weeks ago,
The New York Observer raised the issue of the materials that Eli
Zabar used to construct the plant bed in the rooftop greenhouses of
the Vinegar Factory, 431 East 91st St.
</P>
<P>
   Though the soil came from an upstate organic farm, the boxes
were made of pressure-treated wood, which is impregnated with
chemicals, including chromium and arsenic. (The Northeast Organic
Farming Association of New York prohibits the use of the wood for
garden beds on certified organic farms.)
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Eames-Sheavly, a horticultural educator at the Cornell
University School of Agriculture, said that she does not recommend
using such wood in vegetable gardens, because of concerns about the
danger from the materials in the wood.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of concerns voiced by shoppers, Zabar has now lined
the beds with plastic. Ms. Eames-Sheavly said that a plastic lining
should provide adequate protection from the chemicals. Zabar has
also had the soil, his lettuce and some tomatoes tested in a
laboratory, which stated, in its report, that it found ``no
leaching of arsenic from wood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vinegar Factory is now selling heirloom tomatoes harvested
on the roof. Last week there were big, rippled purple Russian Annas
for $4.99 a pound, and red and orange cherry tomatoes for $5.99 a
pound.
</P>
<P>
   A Greenmarket Volume
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joel Patraker, the manager of the Union Square
Greenmarket, is putting together a book of recipes and
recollections about New York Greenmarkets that is to be published
next year by Viking. Though he has plenty of his own material, he
says he is hoping that shoppers at Greenmarkets will contribute
photographs, shopping or cooking tips to the book. Contributions
can be sent to ``The Book,'' Box 320, Cooper Station, New York NY
10276, or faxed to (718) 398-6729.
</P>
<P>
   A Culinary Alliance
</P>
<P>
   The Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., has formed
an alliance with L'Ecole des Arts Culinaires et de L'Hotellerie de
Lyons, a culinary arts and management school in Ecully, France (a
suburb of Lyons). It was founded in 1985 as one of France's first
modern professional schools. The new alliance is expected to
include exchange programs for French and American students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
