<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4637 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONUMENT-REDO-TEX     07-14 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONUMENT-REDO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS! FABRIC! MONUMENTAL ACTION!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Washington Monument, the plain Jane of the
capital's tourist attractions for more than a century, is about to
get a glitzy new look.
</P>
<P>
   With help from 800 lights and some strategically placed fabric,
the towering obelisk will become an ever-changing piece of
environmental art late this year. It will shimmer on sunny days,
darken when storm clouds roll in, and glow at night.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-catching alterations are all for show. Behind the lights
and the decorative scaffolding, the monument is getting a $9.4
million facelift for the new millennium. Workers will seal cracks,
replenish crumbling mortar and repair damage inflicted by years of
exposure to wind, rain, snow and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Then, like Cinderella at the stroke of midnight, the monument
will shed its adornments shortly after the turn of the century and
resume its role as a model of simplicity in a city known for
self-aggrandizement.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service is going to extraordinary lengths to
make the two-year restoration as painless as possible for the
million-plus tourists who visit the 555-foot tower each year.
Rather than erect ``rusty old scaffolding,'' as park service
official Arnold Goldstein put it, the company in charge of the
project will disguise the workers' platforms with decorative
netting and fabric.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, the monument will appear to be sheathed in
oversized bricks. The blue fabric and transparent netting are also
designed to reflect the color of the sky and the glow of 800 lights
that will be attached to the scaffold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more of an artistic endeavor, to have the lines flow,
to have it look more pleasing,'' Goldstein said. ``It should look
quite nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cost of the restoration will be paid by Target
stores, Coca-Cola, Visa and other corporate sponsors. The
scaffolding will start going up in August, and the job is supposed
to be finished by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service already has upgraded the monument's elevators
as well as the heating and cooling systems. The final phase of the
renovation will include revamping the observation deck near the top
of the obelisk. The monument is expected to remain open to tourists
throughout the project, except for brief interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing structurally wrong,'' Goldstein said. ``Even
if we didn't do this, the monument is structurally sound. It
wouldn't move or fall or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the world's tallest unreinforced masonry structure is
beginning to show its age. Construction on the monument started in
1848, but the work stalled six years later when money and interest
in the project dwindled. The uncompleted tower remained stuck at
152 feet for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The monument was finally completed in 1884, but the
start-and-stop construction process left a distinct color change
about a third of the way up the obelisk.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who also oversees the Lincoln Memorial and the
Jefferson Memorial, said the most pressing problem at the monument
is water leakage. Tourists in the observation deck are pelted with
drips on rainy days.
</P>
<P>
   Workers will also repair damage to the monument's 36,000 stones.
Inside the monument, they will restore some of the 192
commemorative stones that were donated by each of the states and
various countries, organizations and individuals. The Texas stone,
which includes the state seal and the date 1845, commemorating
admission to the Union, appears to be in good shape, but others
have been damaged by souvenir-seekers and vandals.
</P>
<P>
   The wear and tear doesn't seem to bother the hordes of tourists
who line up for the 75-second elevator ride to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see everything!'' said 8-year-old Brittany Halterman
of Bellflower, Calif., after a recent visit with her aunt. ``We saw
the Capitol. We saw the Jefferson Memorial. It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said he is determined to keep the tourists happy
during the restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to please everybody,'' he said, ``just like we
always do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
