<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: NOMINEES FOR MTV AWARDS; EXHIBITS ON EARTH'S
HISTORY; READING OF `SOME LIKE IT HOT'; A BENEFIT FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With nine nominations for her videos ``Ray of Light'' and
``Frozen,'' Madonna topped the list of nominees for the 1998 MTV
Video Music Awards, which were announced Tuesday in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Madonna for ``Ray of Light,'' those nominated for best
video of the year included Brandy and Monica for ``The Boy Is
Mine''; Puff Daddy and the Family for ``It's All About the
Benjamins (Rock Remix)''; Will Smith for ``Gettin' Jiggy Wit It''
and the Verve for ``Bitter Sweet Symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV also announced that Madonna, Hole, Master P and the Dave
Matthews Band were among the artists who would perform at the 15th
annual awards show, to be televised live from Los Angeles on Sept.
10.
</P>
<P>
   Earthly Delights
</P>
<P>
   Built at a cost of some $11.5 million, four major galleries on
Earth's history open Thursday at the Natural History Museum in
London.
</P>
<P>
   They are ``From the Beginning,'' an exploration that looks back
15 billion years to the formation of the universe; ``Earth's
Treasury,'' a display of the planet's riches, including diamonds on
loan from De Beers; ``Earth Today and Tomorrow,'' focusing on
humans' impact on the environment, and ``Earth Lab,'' where
visitors can identify and compare fossils, minerals and rocks with
museum specimens.
</P>
<P>
   Summer Camp
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Some Like It Hot'' promises to turn into something
hotter when downtown performers like Everett Quinton, Dominique
Dibbell, Holly Hughes, Peggy Shaw, Lois Weaver, Carmelita Tropicana
and the playwright Craig Lucas, among many others, team up for a
one-night-only staged reading of the famed film comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1959 Billy Wilder film, starring Jack Lemmon, Tony
Curtis and Marilyn Monroe in the tale of two fugitive musicians who
join an all-girl band, featured only two male-to-female
cross-dressers and one diva, the reading at 7:30 Wednesday night at
the New York Theater Workshop (79 East Fourth St.) promises
gender-bending female-to-male-to-female cross-dressers and more
than 20 divas, including five Marilyns. Kevin Malony directs the
madness, and the Circus Amok Band plays on.
</P>
<P>
   Causal Relations
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vanessa Redgrave and her mother, Rachel Kempson, are
to perform with other show-business notables at the Cathedral of
St. John the Divine (1047 Amsterdam Ave., at 112th Street) at 8
p.m. Monday in a $50-a-ticket benefit for the people of Kosovo.
Scheduled to join Ms. Redgrave are Mandy Patinkin and Lee Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The event was organized by the Albanian-American women's
organization Motrat Qiriazi to raise money for food, clothing and
medicine for the Serbian province of Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians
account for 90 percent of the population and are fighting Serbian
forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACH-MARATHON-1STLD-A     07-14 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-MARATHON-1STLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GLORIES OF BACH, FROM GRAND TO PLAYFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add photo note; no other changes)   (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although it stands to reason that the most ambitious
projects will also be the most difficult, the Lincoln Center
Festival could hardly have imagined the misfortunes that were to
befall its two musical marathons this year. The sad fate of the
Chinese opera ``The Peony Pavilion,'' a recent victim of
bureaucratic wrangling in Shanghai, is by now familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the presentation of the organ works of Bach is also
sad, though the series started on schedule and most promisingly on
Monday evening, when Christopher Herrick gave the first of a daily
series of 14 hourlong recitals at Alice Tully Hall. The project was
conceived for Donald Joyce, a respected New York organist, who took
seriously ill last year and died in March. Herrick, an Englishman
who has recorded Bach extensively and excellently for Hyperion,
graciously stepped in, and he has dedicated the event to Joyce's
memory.
</P>
<P>
   The series is billed as the ``complete'' organ works of Bach,
but that term can only be a relative, because of uncertainties of
attribution, the existence of alternative versions and the like.
``Where distinctly different versions of the same work exist, I
have made a choice,'' Herrick writes in the program book.
``Arrangements of pieces by Vivaldi, Corelli, Telemann and Couperin
are included, while those of Ernst and Fasch are left out.
Incomplete works are excluded.'' All reasonable enough, to keep the
series within the confines of two weeks, though one has to wonder
what Herrick has against poor Ernst and Fasch.
</P>
<P>
   The first program, in any case, was a collection of gems,
beautifully calculated to draw listeners back. The imposing
grandeur of the Prelude and Fugue in A minor (BWV 543) and the
chorale partita ``Sei Gegruesset, Jesu Guetig'' (BWV 768) ideally
balanced the blithe piping of the Sonata in E flat (BWV 525) and
the brilliantly spirited gamesmanship of the Toccata, Adagio and
Fugue in C (BWV 564).
</P>
<P>
   The playful gaptoothed subject in that C major Fugue has always
struck one listener as stop-time in the best Joplin manner; the
words ``stamp, stamp,'' could be printed under the rests, as in
Joplin scores, although stamping a foot near organ pedals is risky
business. And in the end, Bach proceeds to fill those gaps even
more playfully with other voices.
</P>
<P>
   Herrick's performances were grand if not always great. The shape
and spirit of each work emerged superbly; the letter occasionally
left something to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   Herrick is a virtuoso, no question, and he took risks
accordingly. Nor is it fair to expect in live performance the
note-perfection of his recordings. Still, it is too bad that his
slips of finger and foot tended to happen at big moments and full
volume.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, his stamina seemed to flag a bit toward the end,
with a few melodies reshaped in the C major Toccata. Or he may
simply have been a bit nervous, in which case he will have plenty
of time to calm down over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Especially gratifying for a nonspecialist was Herrick's general
avoidance of registrations only an organist could love. In the
chorale partita, he presented a virtual parade of registrations,
venturing only once, in the third variation, into one of those
sonorities so steeped in overtones that the fundamental pitch could
only be intuited.
</P>
<P>
   A listener's main reservation had less to do with anything
Herrick did than with the shifting lights thrown on the pipes,
ranging from garish to gloomy in a seemingly arbitrary rotation.
Even if a sepulchral mood were arguable for the subdued D minor
Prelude (BWV 539), it was surely inappropriate for the little
``Fiddle'' Fugue that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Organ recitals can, to be sure, be uneventful affairs for the
eye, since the performer is often stashed unseen in a loft or
behind a console.
</P>
<P>
   But here, at the fine Kuhn organ in Tully Hall, Herrick is
eminently visible, even down to his footwork on the pedals. It
hardly seems necessary for these compact recitals to import the
tawdry trappings of a disco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
