<HEADLINE>
BEAUMONT ATTORNEYS TO REPRESENT MEN CHARGED IN JASPER DRAGGING
DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ Veteran Beaumont defense attorneys will
represent three white men charged with capital murder in the highly
publicized slaying of a black man who was dragged for almost three
miles behind a pickup outside Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Jr., 49, was killed early June 7 while he was on his
way home from a family gathering. The dragging of his body over a
rough country road tore off his right arm and head.
</P>
<P>
   Bill King and Shawn Berry, 23-year-old Jasper residents, and
Russell Brewer Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs were indicted by a
Jasper County grand jury last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, state District Judge Joe Bob Golden appointed
attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. to defend King and Douglas
Barlow to defend Brewer. Berry earlier hired Joseph C. ``Lum''
Hawthorn to be his defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Golden had earlier appointed Jasper attorneys for the three
defendants, but had to appoint new attorneys after they were
indicted on capital charges. State law requires attorneys
representing clients in death penalty cases to have special
certification. No Jasper lawyers have that certification.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs, 60, who holds his undergraduate and law degrees from
Baylor University in Waco, represented Joe Dugas, a Port Arthur
refinery worker sentenced to die by a Corpus Christi jury for the
1978 kidnapping and murder of five members of a Winnie
family. &UR;  &LR; Dugas died in 1983 when he was shot and killed after
trying to escape while being taken from Beaumont back to his death
row cell in Huntsville. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cribbs also defended David Lee Holland, who was executed in
1993 for the 1985 slaying of two clerks at a Port Arthur savings
and loan office during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Barlow, 44, holds an undergraduate degree from Texas A&AMP;M
University and a law degree from the University of Houston. He
represented Michael Lee Lockhart during the Ohio man's appeal for
his conviction for killing a Beaumont policeman in 1987. Lockhart
was executed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Barlow is serving as a special prosecutor in the appeal of James
Vanderbilt, a former rookie police officer twice convicted of
abducting and fatally shooting Katina Moyer, the 16-year-old
daughter of former state Rep. Hudson Moyer in Amarillo in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn, 56, is a former FBI special agent who also was an
assistant district attorney and assistant U.S. attorney. He holds
an undergraduate degree from Lamar University and a law degree from
the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 he defended Beaumont civic leader Rosine McFaddin
Wilson, who was accused of murder in the shooting death of a fired
ranch caretaker. A Houston jury convicted her of involuntary
manslaughter and sentenced her to five years probation and a $5,000
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn was also instrumental in getting a brace of pilfered
pistols back to the Lone Ranger. The pearl-handled pistols used by
actor Clayton Moore in his ``Lone Ranger'' television show in the
1940's and 50's were in a suitcase that disappeared from Houston's
Hobby Airport on Christmas Eve 1986. Hawthorn returned the pistols
after an unnamed client bought them and realized they were stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Barlow said Tuesday he hasn't studied Brewer's case enough to
comment on it. Cribbs could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said Berry wasn't a participant in Byrd's killing.
Although he owns the truck from which Byrd was chained and dragged,
Hawthorn said the young man contends he tried to stop his two
companions from harming Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been accused of guilt by association,'' Hawthorn said.
``He took no active part in this crime. In fact, he tried to stop
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
