<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORGES-POEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: UNPUBLISHED POEMS BY A YOUNG, OVERHEATED BORGES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ The essays, short stories and poetry
of Jorge Luis Borges are an elaborate maze of paradoxes and clues
as intriguing as they are ambiguous. If his literature defies easy
understanding, so too does his life. He lived as a hermit, toyed
with his interviewers and refused to embrace any literary or
political doctrine for any sustained period.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that the sudden appearance of two
unpublished poems he wrote as a teen-ager while living in
Switzerland and tinkered with over 10 years has inspired excitement
in the Argentine literary press even though the consensus is that
neither poem has much literary merit. Indeed, it seems that Borges,
who died in 1986, made a conscious decision never to publish them.
</P>
<P>
   But the poems remain enticing, in part because for some reason
Borges did not destroy them along with dozens of other early
writings. They also are the earliest poems by Borges known to have
survived and the only ones scholars know of that exist from his
brief enchantment with German Expressionism, from 1916 to 1918,
when all his published works were either translations of other
writers or critical essays.
</P>
<P>
   One, ``The Little Red Box,'' an erotic description of rough,
macho sex, may shed light on Borges' lifelong, problematic
relationships with women. The other, ``Landing,'' expresses the
anguish of an artist responding to the horrors of World War I. Both
are scribbled in different-color inks and were revised and signed
three times, in 1918, 1919 and 1928. And both include some
illustrations the writer apparently copied from a professional
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The poems are inflated by bombastic phrasing and breathless
adolescent emotions. ``My heart is a sponge inflamed by tears,''
young Borges wrote in the final stanza of ``Landing.'' In ``The
Little Red Box'' he begins, ``His sharp rapacious eye watches from
above the flesh of the distant prey.'' The prey is a woman, and in
love ``the impulse squeezes, the movement crushes.'' Many of the
stanzas make no grammatical sense, but are simply a rush of images,
many of which are sexual.
</P>
<P>
   The poems came to light after Alejandro Vaccaro, an Argentine
biographer of Borges and collector of the author's memorabilia,
bought the manuscripts for $50,000 from an Argentine rare book
collector at a Paris book fair six weeks ago. The collector, Victor
Aizenman, refused to tell Vaccaro where he obtained the poems.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Aizenman said, ``I have a source very close to
the Borges family.'' He added that his contact ``has been
stimulating me with the idea that more such early writings exist
that will eventually become available, but my source is very
discreet.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Borges' widow has sole publication rights over her
husband's writings, Vaccaro cannot publish the poems. He said he
would donate them to a museum or other literary institution
someday, while admitting that he hoped the publicity surrounding
the poems could polish his image and help him fulfill his dream of
becoming president of the Boca Juniors, the most popular soccer
club in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive and humorous twists behind the poems are
appropriately Borgesian, although the quality of these traumatic
soundings of an obviously excitable 19-year-old is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borges was a great writer not because he wrote these poems,
but because he rejected them,'' said Roberto Gonzalez Echeverria, a
professor of Hispanic and comparative literature at Yale
University. ``One can see why these tentative texts, redolent with
the metaphoric excesses of the avant-garde, would have repelled
him.'' Nevertheless, he added, ``Since it is Borges, we should
celebrate having them.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaccaro agreed that the poems merely represented ``small steps
Borges took on his march to becoming a great writer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every line Borges ever wrote is important,'' he added. ``We
need to know how Borges developed, and where he came from.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the time Borges wrote the first drafts of the two poems, he
was living with his family in Geneva and Lugano. It was a
particularly traumatic time for the young writer, since he had just
lost a beloved grandmother. He also wrote the poems a few months
after he had his first sexual experience, one set up by his father
with one of his own mistresses, which apparently ended with
embarrassing frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The poetry reflects Borges' deep if temporary link to the
Expressionist movement, many of whose artists and writers were
trying to deal with their anger toward those they held responsible
for the horrors of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   James Woodall, the English author of an acclaimed 1996 biography
of Borges, speculated that perhaps Borges did not immediately
publish the poems because he did not have ready outlets or because
he might have been reticent about embarrassing his family by
publishing work with a salacious content. Woodall noted that by the
time Borges had published three books of poetry in the 1920s, he
had already moved away from Expressionism and embraced Ultraism, a
Hispanic form of Futurism noted for its elaborate metaphors and
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Borges went back to the poems for a final revision in
1928, Woodall concluded, ``he might well have decided they were
just not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   After his final efforts on the two poems, Borges published no
poetry for 30 years. Toward the end of his life he wrote several
exquisite sonnets, but none were similar to either of the early
poems. Why, then, did he save those youthful verses? ``It may be
pure chance that these poems survived,'' said Gonzalez Echeverria.
``We just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   How Borgesian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
