<SLUG> BC-TV-BEST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST MAN': IN A GROUP HOME, AT 70 STILL THE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The important news for those who saw ``Best Boy,''
the fine documentary that won an Academy Award in 1979, is that
Philly is alive and kicking, or dancing when occasion invites.
Philip Wohl, known to everybody in his family and in his Queens
neighborhood as Philly, was 50 years old when his cousin Ira Wohl
first decided to tell his story; now, at 70, he is the endearing
hero of a sweet sequel, ``Best Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier work found Philly, mentally retarded since birth, at
a crucial moment. The parents who had cared for him all his life
were old and ailing, and he was about to be moved into a group home
for the retarded. When we meet him anew, his parents are dead, and
his sister, Frances, a widow who lives near the home, has taken on
the role of parent.
</P>
<P>
   Philly has not merely adapted to his new life but is
flourishing. His enthusiasms _ for coffee and danish, singing,
tidying up _ seem zestier than ever, and as this report reveals, he
is ready for new experiences.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to serving as producer, director and editor, Wohl
fills us in on the scattered Wohl family, but it is his cousin's
star power that carries his film.
</P>
<P>
   Philly is a natural. There is much that he cannot express, but
there is nothing foolish about what he says; he has a grasp of the
essentials, whether it is the memory of the parents who protected
him for so long or the warmth of the friends he has made in his new
home. His words are basic and blunt, but they suggest depths of
feeling. He is a man who inspires affection and repays it.
</P>
<P>
   We join Philly on ``family day'' at the home, where he has
become a considerable presence; at a disco party, where he shows
off and mugs for the camera; on a visit to Coney Island, where he
dances on the Boardwalk; on a trip to the cemetery, where he joins
in the prayer for his dead parents; at a talk on Judaism at the
92nd Street Y.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment that must move even viewers who have had enough of
``Fiddler on the Roof,'' he and Frances join in a duet of
``Sunrise, Sunset.'' Philly participates spiritedly in everything;
at 70, he is still the best boy.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of these cheering 90 minutes, Philly makes his
first flight on an airplane, to visit Los Angeles and his cousin
Ira, who notes that this is the first family visit he has ever
received.
</P>
<P>
   Wohl tells us that he is an only child with no son of his own,
and so he decides to give his cousin a bar mitzvah. Finally the
family and the residents of the home get together at the bar
mitzvah party, and ``Best Man'' ends on a tearful yet exhilarating
high with Philly, ever the star, presiding. ``Good song!'' he
announces.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BEST MAN'
</P>
<P>
   `Best Boy' and All of Us 20 Years Later
</P>
<P>
   6:30 p.m. ET Wednesday on Cinemax
</P>
<P>
   A Cinemax Reel Life documentary. Directed, written, produced and
edited by Ira Wohl; cinematography by Tom McDonough; production
design by Toby Corbett. A production of Only Child Motion Pictures
Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
