<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS &LR;      07-14 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US RIDER FINISHES THIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was so close, but not close enough for American rider George
Hincapie to take over the lead in the Tour de France Tuesday. The
US Postal Serivce team rider finished third in the race and moved
within two seconds of the overall lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a near miss for us, but it really put us in a position
to grab the (leader's) yellow jersey tomorrow,'' team spokesman Dan
Osipow said by telephone. ``There are three sprints with time
bonuses, and we intend to go after the jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the time of the race, time bonuses are given
during the first nine stages.
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie, 25, who became US champion in June and is on top of
the National Racing Calendar standings, was with a pack of nine
riders who made a dash for the finish line in the 105-mile stage
that ended in Lorient, France.
</P>
<P>
   But Jens Heppner of Germany and Xavier Jan of France pulled away
from the break with less than 2 miles to go, and Heppner bolted
over the line first, in 3 hours 33 minutes 36 seconds. Next was
Jan, and Hincapie sprinted to take third. That left him trailing
only the new Tour leader, Bo Hamburger of Denmark. Germany's Erik
Zabel, the Tour leader entering Tuesday's stage, fell back to 10th
place, 1:02 behind Hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie was upset over the way Heppner and Jan worked together
to set the pace of the small group and accused the two of failing
to push hard during the fast pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a sprint like that at the end, it is different because
everyone is so wasted except for those two other guys,'' Hincapie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Hincapie won the stage, he would have received 20 bonus
seconds and claimed the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cramped with about 10 kilometers to go,'' he said. ``I
floated in the back until my legs came back.''
</P>
<P>
   The only American ever to wear the yellow jersey is three-time
Tour winner Gred LeMond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to make George No. 2 (today),'' Osipow said.
</P>
<P>
   The stage on Bastille Day marked the Tour's arrival in host
country France after three days in Ireland. Hundreds of thousands
of people lined the course, celebrating Bastille Day and the party
hangover of France winning soccer's World Cup Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's stage is a 156-mile race as the Tour heads south
along the western coast of France.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the racing, talk on the Tour concerned news that a
masseur for the Festina team, charged last week with smuggling
doping products into France, had told police he had been acting on
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Willy Voet had confessed it was not the first time
he smuggled banned substances.
</P>
<P>
   Team boss Bruno Roussel said he was ``stunned'' by the
revelations and had asked to speak to police as soon as possible
``to set the record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
