<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIMPERNEL-TV-$ADV19-N     07-14 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIMPERNEL-TV-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIMPERNEL' AGAIN, BECAUSE EVERYBODY KNOWS HIS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19.)  
 (JT)  
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The gilt and crystal chandeliers
sparkle, the marble walls shimmer, and the elegant china on the
dining table is straight out of the 18th century. This is a set for
``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' the ever-popular story of love and
double lives, action and derring-do, in the aftermath of the French
Revolution. Apparently there can never be too many versions of the
story, which was immortalized by Leslie Howard and Merle Oberon on
film in 1935 and has been produced on stage and screen many times
since. There is even a musical version currently on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Now A&AMP;E, which brought ``Pride and Prejudice,'' ``Emma'' and
``Tom Jones'' to American cable television, is producing ``The
Scarlet Pimpernel'' with the BBC. The three-part, six-hour
mini-series, replete with 1,200 costumes and visually rich locales
in the Czech Republic, promises to be lush in the current
literary-adaptation style. One of the main attractions of filming
the Pimpernel's tale yet again, at a cost of $9.1 million, a
princely sum for television, is the opportunity for a high-class
adventure story.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all his disguises and rescues, the Pimpernel was really
like the first crusader, the first Superman,'' explained Delia
Fine, A&AMP;E's vice president for film, drama and the performing arts.
``When you put the combination of adventure and romance against the
horrors of the French Revolution, it stands the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while not everyone may remember the story line, the
recognition level of the name Scarlet Pimpernel in many parts of
the world is extraordinarily high.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the story, set in 1792, is Sir Percy Blakeney, a
foppish English aristocrat who is in reality the elusive Scarlet
Pimpernel, rescuer of innocent French aristocrats from the
guillotine. He is a master of disguise, whisking counts and
countesses from under the nose of Chauvelin, the French
government's most hard-headed zealot. Blakeney's wife is the
intelligent and beautiful Marguerite, a French actress who quotes
Rousseau and once had an affair with Chauvelin. The strained
marriage that we initially see between Percy and Marguerite is
transformed into one of love and trust as they work together under
life-threatening conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of this new version are Richard E. Grant, whose most
recent film role was as the Spice Girls' manager in ``Spice
World''; Elizabeth McGovern, the American actress who while still a
teen-ager rushed to fame in Robert Redford's ``Ordinary People''
and most recently appeared in the 1997 film ``The Wings of the
Dove,'' and the English actor Martin Shaw, who was on Broadway in
1996 in ``An Ideal Husband.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. McGovern, now married, a mother and living in London _
``Not many go from Hollywood to Hammersmith,'' she says with a
laugh _ the role of Marguerite is a chance to get inside the head
of a woman in a mature relationship. ``It's about people who have
passions and go for it; it's not about people who sit around and
think,'' she said during a break from the 90-day shooting schedule
in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always fighting,'' she said of Marguerite and Percy.
``But they love each other passionately. This is a portrait of a
marriage, not a love affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGovern, 35, said she was relieved to be able to be an
``actress and not the cutest, most idealized woman'' that most
Hollywood scripts demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a woman not in her 20s, the stories on television often
are more actor-friendly and often give the chance to play a real
part,'' Ms. McGovern said. ``This is a well-written relationship.
She's a grown-up. Not many parts are written for grown-up women.
And she's in the center of the action, which is something all
actresses are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   For Shaw, playing Chauvelin represents the challenge of turning
a character that has traditionally been played as an unremittingly
dark villain without any redemptive qualities into something more
nuanced. Shaw says he tries to make the character a bit more
believable and to highlight his motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the main baddie, the head of the secret police of
Robespierre, a cynical opportunist who was once a revolutionary,''
Shaw said. But even as such a malevolent zealot, Chauvelin retains
one ideal: his love for Marguerite, about whom he is obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   To give more currency to Chauvelin to contemporary audiences,
Shaw said, he plays the character as a 34-year-old, much younger
than in past productions. ``He's much more interesting viewed as a
1950s Maoist.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' promise plenty of
gorgeous scenery and staging. The Czech Republic was chosen for
most of the shooting because its castles and Prague itself are much
closer to the look of Paris in the 1790s than present-day France.
Paris, like Prague today, still had a medieval feel to it, said the
mini-series' BBC producer, Julian Murphy. Many of the castle
interiors are still in good condition _ like the Clam Gallas Palace
in Prague, where the crew spent a day shooting _ and many of the
palaces in the countryside are derelict enough to suggest
post-revolutionary France. The producers have avoided the
tourist-laden town squares that the Czech authorities have recently
redecorated in pastel pinks, blues and yellow and instead have
chosen more dilapidated areas or have filmed at night.
</P>
<P>
   The costume designers have had a whole new look to translate. By
the 1790s, all the corseting and restricted fashion of French dress
had given way to easier, almost punklike looks. Everybody's hair is
flowing or in loose ponytails. As for the dialogue, don't expect
anything too specific to the period or the book, which was written
in 1900 in London by Baroness Orczy, a Hungarian emigre. The story
always fascinated, but the writing was never considered great
literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Jane Austen wrote great dialogue, people felt obliged
to put that in and be faithful to it,'' said Ms. McGovern. ``With
this we can be freer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
