<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4668 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARY-REVIEW-LADN     07-14 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE IS `SOMETHING ABOUT MARY' 
OUR RATING: THREE STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Courage and comedy aren't two words that are
usually linked. But in politically correct times when most movies
assiduously avoid crossing the delicate line of vulgarity in fear
of losing mass appeal (and that all-important PG-13 rating), it is
positively heroic when a couple of guys manage to call to mind the
days of Mel Brooks and ``Springtime for Hitler'' and create a film
that manages both to joyfully entertain and creatively offend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' has all the spirit of Brooks
and Monty Python and ``Animal House'' in its manic zeal to milk
every sacred cow in the name of facetious fun. You'll laugh. You'll
groan. And often at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there would be no reason to celebrate ``Mary'' if it
were merely tasteless. (Karen Finley and other NEA gravy trainers
are learning that harsh reality now.) This is the most consistently
funny movie the Farrelly brothers have made, coming on the heels of
guilty pleasures ``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``Kingpin.'' ``Mary'' will
probably be tagged with the title ``Gross and Grosser,'' a
distinction it admittedly earns.
</P>
<P>
   But the Farrellys, who wrote and directed the film together,
populate their movie with surprisingly sympathetic characters,
which often makes the wicked humor kind of touching _ albeit in a
sick, twisted way.
</P>
<P>
   The movie puts a '90s spin on the age-old story of Boy Meets
Girl. Basically, it's ``Sleepless in Seattle'' with a court
restraining order thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' opens with an inspired, 20-minute time capsule
introducing the characters in their nerdy, mid-'80s high school
days. We meet Ted (Ben Stiller), a gangly geek with a bad haircut
and braces who has the hots for dream girl Mary (Cameron Diaz).
When Ted sticks up for Mary's mentally handicapped brother, she
rewards him by asking him to the prom. That sets up an unfortunate
incident involving Ted's zipper, and he never gets to see Mary
again.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward 13 years and Ted is still dreaming about Mary. His
loathsome pal, Dom (the perfectly cast Chris Elliott), suggests Ted
hire a private investigator to track her down. The goofball he
enlists, Pat Healy (Matt Dillon), ends up falling for Mary himself,
which puts into motion a love triangle that eventually expands to
include other idiotic suitors. You see, there is, indeed, something
about Mary, and it seems to attract every man on the Eastern
seaboard with an IQ of less than 50.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is too long and, like most good sketch comedies, its
humor misses as often as it connects. But there are several scenes
that will have you laugh so hard that you'll start to cry. Or maybe
it will work the other way around. Certainly, you will never look
at hair gel the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz brings great comic timing and a sweet vulnerability to
Mary, and Stiller and Dillon prove to be troopers in the face of
all sorts of indignities. Lin Shaye, Lee Evans, Markie Post (!),
Elliott and Jonathan Richman as a wandering troubadour (and
makeshift Greek chorus) straight out of ``Cat Ballou'' round out a
wonderfully funny supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the film's crude tastelessness won't play with
everyone. Sometimes you'll even hate yourself for laughing. But
laugh you will _ often and hard. ``There's Something About Mary''
is the funniest movie of the year, and it mixes in just enough
sweetness with its bodily fluids to make it good, deranged fun. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;        07-14 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
  
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There were more than a few days during the making
of the gleefully gross new comedy, ``There's Something About
Mary,'' that actor Ben Stiller did not exactly relish the idea of
coming into work. There was the day when a fish hook yanked his
mouth into cartoon proportions. And there was the day when he had
to pretend to get caught in the teeth of a zipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be cheerful,'' Stiller says, ``knowing your role
calls for your head to be bashed into a chair or for your thing to
be caught in a zipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing Stiller's words repeated to them, Bobby and Peter
Farrelly, who wrote and directed ``Mary'' surely sympathize. But
they hasten to add that Stiller got off easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cameron Diaz was the one who had the potential career-ender in
the movie,'' Peter says. ``She had to rub the ... how do I say this
... hair gel-like material in her hair. That could have stigmatized
her for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Bobby: ``Yeah, it's like Ned Beatty in `Deliverance.' The
only thing he did wrong was be too convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Farrelly brothers are nothing if not convincing, which to
their critics is part of the problem. The two Rhode Island natives
mined the depths of lowbrow humor with their first two films,
``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``Kingpin,'' wild, hit-and-miss movies
about sympathetic losers. The movies won fans with both audiences
and _ surprise _ critics, who found the brothers' in-your-face
humor to be a refreshing blast in an arid, politically correct
landscape. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
subhed: Beyond 13-year-old humor
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``There's Something About Mary,'' which could be
described as the first stalker romance, the Farrellys have expanded
their reach, possessing the clout to deliver their first R-rated
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was time,'' says Peter, at 41, a year older than
Bobby. ``The only guy who thinks along those lines seems to be
Woody Allen, and obviously he has a different thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one seems to set out to make adult comedies anymore,''
Bobby says. ``I think studios want to gear everything to
13-year-old boys. There's nothing wrong with that. We had that age
group in mind with `Dumb and Dumber,' since those guys were about
13 years old themselves mentally. But we've always had a lot of
stuff that we've wanted to do that the MPAA won't let us get away
with. And now we have our chance.''
</P>
<P>
   So ``Mary'' has outrageous scenes, gags that words can't begin
to fully describe and jokes that can't be repeated in a family
newspaper. There are no sacred cows. There are jabs at gay serial
killers, the handicapped and ``retards.'' A dog gets electroshock
treatment and later becomes an amphetamine-fueled whirling dervish.
And, of course, there's the scene with the zipper, a bit already
part of film lore even though the movie hasn't been released yet in
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask us, `How far will you go?''' Peter says.
``And the answer is: As far as the audience lets us. It's up to
them. We test a lot, mostly in colleges. And any time the laughter
stops, we cut the scene, sometimes by seconds or sometimes in its
entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``Mary'' also has _ something the two previous Farrelly
movies lacked _ is an actual story line, sort of a Boy Meets Girl,
Boy Meets Zipper, Boy Loses Girl, Boy Stalks Girl, Boy Gets Girl
Back Again kind of thing. It's a development that also stems from
the brothers' obsession with test screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both `Dumb and Dumber' and `Kingpin' tested in the 90s for
guys and the 40s for women, and with this movie we got the women,
too,'' Peter says. ``I don't know why, but women seem to need a
story. Guys can watch stuff like the Three Stooges and be fine.
Women need more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so needy,'' Bobby adds, mock contempt in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   subhed: Sibling revelry
</P>
<P>
   The Farrellys never appear to have been needy in their lives,
even though 15 years ago they were both floundering in sales jobs.
(``We were still enjoying life,'' Peter says. ``Life has always
been nice.'') Bobby, a geological engineering major (a misnomer, he
says, born from his days as a college stoner), was developing
Sunspot, the world's first round beach towel. Peter was selling
shipping space on cargo vessels. Then, after finishing his master's
degree in creative writing, Peter came up with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had written a book (`Outside Providence,' which will be
released as a film this year starring Alec Baldwin), but I kind of
figured out that I wasn't going to make much money writing fiction
and, besides, it takes too long to write,'' Peter says. ``So I
started writing screenplays with a friend and eventually dragged
Bobby out to L.A. to help because he knows what's funny and what
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Farrellys, along with writing partner Bennett Yellin, began
making a comfortable living cranking out unproduced screenplays.
Eddie Murphy purchased one, writer-director David Zucker another.
But it wasn't until they sold ``Dumb and Dumber'' that Peter and
Bobby finally got to see their work on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   With their debut, the brothers took no chances, demanding that
they direct the movie, even though neither had ever been to film
school or shot so much as a TV commercial. (``Hollywood isn't like
a regular industry where they do background checks,'' says Bobby,
who is married and has two children. ``We could have been escaped
convicts for all they could tell.'') The Farrellys figured they
knew the story and they knew how to tell a joke. (``What else is
there?'' Bobby asks.) The rest would somehow just work itself out. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
subhed: Flying blind &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have a panic attack the night before,'' says Peter, who
has been married for a year. ``We called David Zucker and he told
us to relax. He also told us to let everyone on the set know that
we didn't know what the hell we were doing and get their support.
We did, and we've been with the same crew ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not the only admirers. Jim Carrey credits the Farrellys
for putting his career on the map, and his ``Dumb and Dumber''
co-star Jeff Daniels appreciated the chance to drop his drawers and
dramatic chops and play stupid. (``He wasn't our first choice,''
Peter admits. ``We wanted Michael Richards, but he kept telling us
the story was a tragedy like `Of Mice and Men.' He called us after
the premiere and said, `You know, you guys were right.''')
</P>
<P>
   When ``Kingpin'' failed to ignite the box-office (``It wasn't
marketed very well,'' Bobby says), the Farrellys were courted by
20th Century Fox executive Tom Sherak, who gave the brothers a free
hand in bringing their vulgarity to full fruition. The studio is
pleased enough with the results to have signed the filmmaking team
to a three-year, writing-producing-directing deal. (Next up:
``Stuck on You,'' a comedy about Siamese twins.)
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest fans, though, might be Mom and Dad. Peter and
Bobby credit their parents for honing their humor, although no one
in the family could have guessed at where they would take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents were strict about stuff like TV, but what they
weren't strict about was humor,'' Peter says. ``We could tell any
joke. If it was funny, it was OK. We would sit around the dinner
table, my parents, Bobby and me and our three sisters and just have
a lot of laughs.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Bobby: ``Our father just has a brutal sense of humor, and
my mother can take any kind of joke. In fact, it used to piss our
sisters off. They'd be trying to stop us, screaming, `Mom! Don't
encourage them! They're sick.'''
</P>
<P>
   They still are. Only now, their audience is bigger than the
immediate family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
