<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MASTERPIECE-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MASTERPIECE THEATER' GOES AMERICAN
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ For the first time in its 27-year history,
``Masterpiece Theater'' will present American literary
masterpieces, starting next year, executives of the Public
Broadcasting Service announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the largest grant ever given by the Corporation for
Public Broadcasting, $15 million, as well as financing from Mobil
Corp., the regular sponsor of ``Masterpiece Theater,'' the program
will present dramatic adaptations of such works as Willa Cather's
``Song of the Lark,'' Langston Hughes' ``Cora Unashamed'' and Henry
James' ``American.'' Production of the shows is expected to take
place in both Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The works are to be presented under the title of ``Mobil
Masterpiece Theater's American Collection.'' PBS and Mobil
executives said they had long been urged by viewers to include
American literature in the long-running series, which has always
focused on adaptations of British literature.
</P>
<P>
   Robert O'Leary, the general manager for global public affairs
for Mobil, said: ``We all have a sense that this has been long
overdue. I know that we at Mobil always get letters from viewers
asking why we don't include works by American writers. It's great
to be addressing this at last.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said the decision to add the ``American Collection'' had
helped push Mobil to renew its commitment to ``Masterpiece
Theater'' one year early. He did not specify the amount that Mobil
donates but he said that over the history of the program Mobil had
contributed more than $250 million. The executive producer of
``Masterpiece Theater,'' Rebecca Eaton, announced Tuesday that
Mobil had extended its support for the show through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said that he hoped the new productions of American
literature would elicit the same response from American actors that
the British adaptations did from British actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best things to come out of this would be if
American actors saw these adaptations the way British actors do,
almost as an extension of their stage careers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Song of the Lark,'' a novel, is expected to be the first
of the American works presented on the air, Ms. Eaton said. No
specific date was announced for the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
