<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD SEES A KINDER, GENTLER HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the ups and downs of her husband's six
years in the White House, Hillary Rodham Clinton has enjoyed the
steady support of many American women who see her as a career model
or an inspiration for marital loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Even among Republican women _ hardly cheerleaders for the First
Lady _ Hillary Rodham Clinton received an approval rating of 45
percent in a Los Angeles Times poll taken in February. Overall,
respondents gave her thumbs up by a 2-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Feminists love her. A group of women's rights advocates meeting
in Boston in April took a straw poll of possible female
presidential candidates, according to Newsweek magazine. Hillary
Rodham Clinton's name was not on the list, but she won the most
votes as a write-in.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady's sometimes controversial role as
feminist-in-chief forms the backdrop Wednesday of her visit of
locales in the Albany area and Upstate New York that are associated
with the history of feminism.
</P>
<P>
   Her aggressive stance on women's issues has ruffled feelings
from time to time. For instance, in January 1992 on the CBS program
``60 Minutes,'' she reaffirmed her faith in her husband who had
been accused of adultery but then avowed that she was not ``some
little woman, standing by her man like Tammy Wynette.'' Wynette
fans were outraged.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the future First Lady defended her
high-powered career as a lawyer at Little Rock's Rose Law Firm: ``I
suppose I could have stayed home, baked cookies and had teas, but
what I decided was to fulfill my profession.'' Women who chose the
cookies-and-tea option _ and the men who loved them _ were angered.
</P>
<P>
   It looked for a while as if the governor of Arkansas was married
to a hard-driving, politically correct feminist out of touch with
mainstream American womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Clintons entered the White House in January
1994, Mrs. Clinton had gone a long way toward burying the Bess
Truman and Mamie Eisenhower model of first ladies, content to stand
in their husband's shadows.
</P>
<P>
   This incarnation reached its apex in 1994 when the First Lady
boldly stepped out from those shadows to spearhead the White
House's health care task force, which put forward a complex plan to
make health insurance universally available. Congress didn't buy it
_ and the legislative defeat was a prime factor in the Democrats
losing control of both the House and Senate that November.
</P>
<P>
   That marked a turning point. From then on, Mrs. Clinton sought
to adopt a lower profile, less focused on policy controversies. Her
efforts were only partially successful, mainly because of the
on-going investigation by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Starr's probe was centered on her work at the Rose Law
Firm back in Little Rock. The result was that she was asked to
testify in 1996 before a federal grand jury about the mysterious
reappearance at the White House of her long-missing Rose Law Firm
billing records.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, she became the butt of late-night comedian
jokes when author Bob Woodward revealed in his 1996 book, ``The
Choice,'' that Mrs. Clinton had brought in a psychic who got her to
hold an imaginary conversation with the late Eleanor Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Clinton won re-election handily with his wife
conspicuously inconspicuous.
</P>
<P>
   That was then.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Clinton well into his second term, Hillary Rodham
Clinton has long since downsized her image, reinventing herself as
the administration's advocate-in-chief for issues that everyone can
support _ in one manner or another.
</P>
<P>
   Her best-selling book, ``It Takes a Village,'' refocused the
spotlight on child care, an issue about which she has long held
strong views. Last October, as she turned 50, Mrs. Clinton chaired
a major White House conference on the subject, exploring ways to
make child care available particularly poor women leaving welfare
to enter the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   This effort has borne no resemblance to the health care task
force. It is way short on social engineering and long on personal
appearances by the First Lady at day care centers where she is
photographed amid smiling children.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mrs. Clinton insists there has been no retooling
of her public self. ``I continue to do what I want to do and what I
consider important,'' she told Time magazine last October. ``I
never thought I was living anybody else's role or anybody else's
expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, harsh political reality still intrudes. After the
brouhaha over the president's alleged sexual relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky exploded last January, a
spark of the old Hillary Rodham Clinton flashed on the screen. When
a federal court asked Starr to examine the matter, Mrs. Clinton
attacked him as ``politically motivated'' and ``allied with the
right-wing opponents of my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, just hours before she sat at the head table for the
annual White House Correspondents Association bash, Mrs. Clinton
underwent five hours of questioning at the White House by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as part of her ``Save America's Treasures'' tour,
the First Lady starts the day at the house of Kate Mullany, an
Irish immigrant who organized a union of women laundry workers in
the 1860s. She also is scheduled to visit the Auburn, N.Y., house
of Harriet Tubman, the legendary organizer of the ``Underground
Railroad'' that smuggled slaves to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is to end the day in Seneca Falls, N.Y., birthplace
of the effort to secure equality for women. She will speak at a
ceremony marking the 150th anniversary of ``The Declaration of
Sentiments,'' in which over 100 women in 1848 declared women and
men to be equals.
</P>
<P>
   So in a way, Hillary Rodham Clinton is coming full circle back
to her feminist beginnings in the public eye, circa 1992. The only
difference is this time, there is to be no confrontation, no
jarring quotes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
