<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-FUNERAL-BOS &LR;      07-14 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-FUNERAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE VICTIMS OF FIREBOMBING BURIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALLYMONEY, Northern Ireland _ Chrissie Quinn would not bury her
little boys here because she couldn't bear the thought of having to
return to the town where they were murdered, of walking on the same
ground as those who killed them.
</P>
<P>
   But the church in Rasharkin, next to the graveyard where the
boys will rest forever, is being renovated, and so Chrissie Quinn
bowed her head and came here to Ballymoney one last time Tuesday,
to the Church of Our Lady and St. Patrick, for their funeral Mass.
</P>
<P>
   She stood next to her 13-year-old son, Lee, who escaped the fate
of his three younger brothers because he spent the night at his
grandmother's. She kept her eyes down, seemingly unable to look at
the three small white caskets, so tiny they all fit in one hearse.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven-year-old Richard, 9-year-old Mark, and 8-year-old Jason
Quinn, who between them were as old as the Troubles, were
dispatched from this world after holding up a mirror to Northern
Ireland. Like Chrissie Quinn, many people had to avert their eyes,
because the images were too disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of the Quinn boys forced many people here to step
back and take stock. Was this an aberration, given the
determination of the overwhelming majority to use new political
institutions to seek accommodation and reconciliation? Or will a
small, intransigent and sometimes murderous minority be allowed to
subvert the democratic wishes of others?
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to contemplate such questions Tuesday, so heavy was
the grief on this, yet another overcast, almost chilly summer's
day.
</P>
<P>
   In a society where people categorize themselves and others by
religious and national allegiance, the Quinn brothers were an
anomaly. They were born to a Catholic mother but lived in a
Protestant neighborhood, a fact that police say led someone to
firebomb their home in the predawn hours of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The local Catholic school was closer to their home, but their
mother sent them to the Protestant state school, in part so that
they would fit in better locally. In their innocence, the boys
transcended tribal loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were being raised neutral, if there is such a thing in
this place,'' said Rev. Peter Forde, the priest who officiated at
their funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The boys gathered wood for one of the bonfires that loyalists
hold to celebrate the ``Glorious 12th,'' when Protestants celebrate
the 1690 victory of King William of Orange over the forces of
Catholic King James II.
</P>
<P>
   After the boys watched the bonfire and came home late Saturday,
Chrissie Quinn stayed up until 3:30 a.m., so fearful was she that
Protestant extremists might target her house as they had more than
120 others across Northern Ireland in the past week. An hour after
she went to bed, someone threw a firebomb into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her efforts and those of her Protestant boyfriend to
save them, the boys died screaming. Their deaths shocked Northern
Ireland, and the world. Two men, one with loyalist paramilitary
links, both of them from the Carnany housing project where the
Quinns lived, are being questioned by police.
</P>
<P>
   Although Catholic families are burned out of their homes every
July, when loyalist fervor peaks around the time of the July 12th
celebrations, many lay blame for the boys' deaths with the
hardliners who refuse to call off their protest in Portadown. Since
July 5, the Orange Order has engaged in a standoff with the
security forces who are blocking them from marching through a
Catholic neighborhood. Violence has flared every night of the
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The hardliners in Portadown accept no responsibility for
creating the climate that led to the murders of the Quinn boys, but
moderate Orangemen are melting away, leaving the hardliners
increasingly isolated. The murder of the boys has chastened many.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Patrick Walsh was in Lourdes when he got news of what
happened to the Quinn boys. He flew back to deliver the homily at
their funeral, making it clear he believed the Orangemen who
racheted up tension with apocalyptic rhetoric bore some
responsibility for the horrific deaths of three innocents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weapons of hate-filled words inevitably fuel weapons of
murderous destruction,'' Bishop Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Mass, Andrea Ramsey read a poem composed by local
schoolgirls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have so much evil at their fingertips?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard, Mark and Jason, in our memory you will stay. I can
still feel the cold, wet lips from when I kissed you and then you
ran away.''
</P>
<P>
   The 500 people packed into the church burst into applause when
the poem ended. Some of the several hundred people outside the
church burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Father Forde was joined in prayer by a Methodist minister and a
Presbyterian minister, a rare ecumenical moment in Northern Ireland
which demonstrated that Protestants and Catholics are united in
grief.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was time to make the eight-mile journey to
Rasharkin. John Dillon, the boys' father, and Frank Quinn, their
uncle, shouldered one of the tiny caskets, each of them stroking
the side of the coffin tenderly. Both men sobbed. Lee used the back
of his hands to wipe away tears.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie Quinn stepped from the church, supported by her mother,
Irene. This time, her head was up. She had work to do. She had to
bury her sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRISTOL-POP-MUSIC-$AD     07-14 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRISTOL-POP-MUSIC-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISTOL'S BROODING INNOVATORS DEFY EXPECTATIONS AND LABELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19.)  
 (JT)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bristol, England, has been the capital of sonic murk and
undertow for a decade, and it's not about to give up the claim. Two
new albums from Bristol's standard-bearers _ Tricky's ``Angels With
Dirty Faces'' (Island) and Massive Attack's ``Mezzanine'' (Virgin)
_ insist on the continuing allure of ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   Since the disk jockey and production collectives Soul II Soul
and Massive Attack emerged from Bristol, the city's aural signature
has been a slow, deep bass line _ reggae with English reticence _
below hazy sounds that drift through the mix like troubled
memories.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the music was labeled ``trip-hop,'' which
followers made into a fashionably self-conscious easy-listening
music. But the Bristol originators moved to outflank their
imitators. Their music, like their favorite sounds, refuses to
declare itself, lurking between genres with serene defiance. ``I
can't meet expectations of these radio stations 'cause I move in
different vibrations,'' Tricky proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky, who rapped with Massive Attack in 1991, has since
emerged as a producer, songwriter and brilliant self-made crank (he
is to perform in New York on July 21 at the Hammerstein Ballroom).
For most rappers, hip-hop is a display of extroversion, or at least
a way of flaunting a conspicuous cool. Not for Tricky: he raps like
someone muttering to himself, in a voice so low and scratchy it
could strip the floorboards. Every so often, a woman's voice
(Martina Topley-Bird or, as a guest, Polly Jean Harvey) arrives
with some melody, like a glimpse of a more elevated sphere.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Angels With Dirty Faces,'' Tricky spends most of the songs
grumbling about his career. He snarls at record companies, radio
stations and the press: ``Is this making music or making money? I
can't make my mind up.'' Since he's only a cult figure, not a
million-selling pop star, Tricky's complaints sound tendentious. He
even instructs his listeners. ``For all those who want to analyze
me,'' he intones, ``start it off in the hips/Move to my lips.'' But
he's right; the rhythm tracks are consistently arresting.
</P>
<P>
   Built from live musicians (including Marc Ribot on twangy,
clanky guitar and Perry Melius on unpredictably syncopated drums),
tape loops, drum machines and samples, Tricky's tracks swerve
between propulsion and disorientation. They evade current genres to
hook up with the bleakest blues and with the claustrophobic funk of
Sly and the Family Stone's ``There's a Riot Going On.'' Every song
has an ominous hollowness and, at the same time, an off-center
swing, lurch or throb.
</P>
<P>
   As Tricky charges, ``You trample on my soul,'' in ``Money
Greedy,'' the track scurries ahead in double time, as chattering
wah-wah guitars seethe with barely suppressed rage. ``Demise''
bounds along in 5/4 time on a ticking syncopated drum, a bass vamp,
a steel drumlike keyboard lick and guitar chords that stutter and
catch like a faulty car ignition. Blues licks are everywhere: in
``Mellow'' with stop-and-start drums in constant contention, and in
``Singing the Blues'' with the sound of a bass clarinet chortling
along behind the guitar. In ``Talk to Me,'' he whispers while Ms.
Topley-Bird sings above a track that undulates like the ocean below
a lifeboat, vast and indifferent. Through the album, Tricky's music
conjures solitudes, torments and struggles that are far broader
than his private gripes.
</P>
<P>
   Massive Attack is determined to expand trip-hop while
maintaining its atmosphere of steamy foreboding. Like Tricky,
Robert Del Naja and Grant Marshall of Massive Attack rap in deadpan
whispers, but where Tricky has let songs unravel into vamps with
vocals, Massive Attack has held on to song forms, enlisting singers
for melodies. Its third album, ``Mezzanine,'' is an aural revue,
with singers as diverse as the reggae crooner Horace Andy and Liz
Fraser of the Cocteau Twins. Massive Attack has also integrated
rock guitars into its songs. In ``Dissolved Girl,'' while the
singer Sara Jay ponders love in what could be a trip-hop song by
Portishead or Morcheeba, distorted guitars loom and then roar out
of the quiet bass line, turning a ballad into a hard-rock stomp
before melting away.
</P>
<P>
   Andy's tenor has a slowly building vibrato that can sound ardent
or troubled: yearning for love in ``Angel,'' as guitars build a
Pink Floyd-like drone and crescendo, or fretting about a neighbor
in ``Man Next Door,'' with the aching chorus, ``I've got to get
away from here.'' And Ms. Fraser is an unlikely but ideal
collaborator for Massive Attack. Her airy voice and leaping,
quasi-Celtic melodies are grounded by Massive Attack's stolid bass
lines and by sounds, low in the mix, that hover like thunderclouds.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Group Four,'' Massive Attack opens up the structure. Ms.
Fraser's tunes _ sometimes jazzy, sometimes Celtic _ and Massive
Attack's raps alternate over a measured bass line; they could be a
couple's stray thoughts or two strangers' internal monologues. The
song is a pure Bristol product: an enigma with a beat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
