<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: WITH PILLOW TALK, BOYZ II MEN HOLD THEIR PAJAMA PARTY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Fans waited an entire hour for the pajamas during
Boyz II Men's performance at Radio City Music Hall on Monday night.
The anticipated costumes weren't really pajamas anyway, just loose
white loungewear in diaphanous silk. And almost immediately, the
four Boyz pulled them off to reveal black tank tops and preripped
jeans, in keeping with their tentative new image as hip-hop-loving
roughnecks. It was as if they'd forgotten that the pajamas are what
it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   Boyz II Men are the great ambassadors of pajama pop, a subgenre
of rhythm-and-blues that has thrived since the swinging 1970s. As
one might expect of a style evoking sleepwear, pajama pop is
sexual; in the virtual stripteases performed by Next, the hot group
that preceded Boyz II Men onstage, it can come close to soft-core
porn.
</P>
<P>
   The night's headliners, however, have always stressed pajama
pop's gentler side. Its basic innovation was to temper classic soul
vocalizing and grooves with light jazz harmonies and
instrumentation, to tame the urgent desires expressed in soul and
turn it into genteel persuasion. Silk pajamas cover the bodies of
these singers, just as their elegant intimacies cover their raw
lusts.
</P>
<P>
   Boyz II Men have milked this suave eroticism, hitting platinum
sales with the tear-jerker ``End of the Road'' and the polite
come-on, ``I'll Make Love to You.'' When they revisited these hits
at Radio City, the reasons for their success became clear. Unlike
many other groups who begin as teeny-bop stars, the foursome _
Wanya Morris, Shawn Stockman, Nathan Morris and Michael McCarey _
possess genuine vocal talent and harmonized beautifully. They also
proved to be crowd-pleasing hams, by turns grandiose, vulnerable,
sassy and roguish.
</P>
<P>
   The love they expressed extended to everyone in the family. For
the many children present, there were athletic dance moves and
fireworks-style special effects. For matriarchs, there was
``Mama,'' a son's loyalty oath. For men, there was friendly advice.
``Don't be afraid to sway,'' Stockman advised. ``Girls like to see
fellas that are moving.'' Such words explained pajama pop's appeal
to men: like Hugh Hefner, another famous nightwear fan, Boyz II Men
exemplified a prowess achieved through good taste and careful
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   All of this would have made for a potent show, but Boyz II Men
strayed from their area of expertise. The group's faster songs
lacked focus, and the modified hip-hop-style costumes they wore for
half the show did not suit them. Boyz II Men have always had a
dance-oriented side, but their attempts to turn tough ring hollow.
During such moments they seemed more like yell kings than soul men.
The group needs to find another way to expand upon its pajama game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
