u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-STOCK-COX     07-14 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta to split stock, repurchase shares
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines plans a 2-for-1 stock split, as well
as a $750 million stock repurchase program in which the carrier
will buy back about 7 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, announced Tuesday, drove Atlanta-based Delta's stock
to a new high of $142.37 1/2. Shares closed at $142, up $6.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said the stock split -- its first since 1981 -- will be
paid Nov. 16 for shareholders of record on Nov. 2, assuming
shareholder approval. The move will make Delta stock more
affordable to smaller investors, and companies that split their
stock generally post better long-term returns.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, metro Atlanta's largest corporate employer with
about 26,000 locally based workers, could not provide the number of
Georgia shareholders. Most workers hold shares under an employee
ownership program, as well as stock options awarded under a
three-year incentive plan begun in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The split will double the number of those options and cut the
exercise price in half.
</P>
<P>
   The stock repurchase will occur over the next 18 months and will
be funded from Delta's cash reserves, which stood at $1.6 billion
on June 30, a spokesman said. The program will be in addition to an
existing buyback plan to acquire shares for reissue as employee
options.
</P>
<P>
   Repurchases are typically done by companies to decrease the
number of outstanding shares, boosting future per-share earnings
and the stock price. The company had 75.75 million shares
outstanding as of April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's stock is up about 19 percent this year, but returns have
lagged those at other carriers including American, Continental and
US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's reaffirmed its debt ratings for Delta
following the repurchase announcement and said the move ``signals a
more financially aggressive posture'' by Delta under Chief
Executive Leo F. Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   Delta reports fourth quarter and fiscal year earnings Thursday,
and analysts expect strong results buoyed by low fuel prices and
heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Delta shareholders will vote on the stock split at the Oct. 22
annual meeting, expected to be held for the first time in New York
City. Delta traditionally has had the meeting in its corporate
birthplace, Monroe, La., although it was in Atlanta in 1995 and
executives had indicated they would rotate it among larger cities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
