</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FEATURE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All golfers not big fans of England's climate
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Most of them love it despite the cold,
despite winds howling off the sea, despite the occasional lack of a
definite landing area. Some play the British Open because it's a
major dripping with tradition. Some simply play because they're
exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hoch, on the other hand, would rather be sweating in
Madison, Miss., at the Deposit Guaranty Classic. Or sweating
anywhere, for that matter. A man who ranks cold weather right there
with four-putts and tax audits, Hoch is at Royal Birkdale this week
only because the five-year contract he signed with Yonex this year
specifies that he play in the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch cares about neither tradition nor what other people think.
All he knows is that cold weather and his game are not compatible.
Playing the British Open last in 1995 at St. Andrews in cool, windy
weather, Hoch tied for 68th and trashed the sacred ground where
golf germinated, saying, ``I think they had some sheep and goats
there that died, and they just covered them over.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone get carried away and presume an attitude transplant,
Hoch said Tuesday, ``I've already let them (Yonex) know that
there's an upcoming British that I wasn't going to play in (St.
Andrews in 2000). ... I can't remember what year it is.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters laughed at that comment, Hoch didn't want anyone
to think he had anything against Scotland. Just the course and the
coarse weather bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot people don't know is that I'm (part) Scottish,''
Hoch said. ``My grandmother was from Scotland.''
</P>
<P>
   A British reporter suggested that his grandmother ``might turn
over in her grave'' if he bypasses St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she does,'' Hoch said, ``she's turned over for the third
time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly a matter of feeling for Hoch. When it gets cold, he
loses the feel for his short game. When wind-chills drop
drastically, Hoch feels like he's putting with a popsicle. A few
years ago he had the blood circulation to his hands checked, but
found no medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just not my type of weather,'' Hoch said. ``I'm not
sure it's anybody's type of weather, but I'm sure there are a lot
of other players that can play much better in this kind of stuff
than I can.''
</P>
<P>
   There's irony to the fact Hoch has an obligation to play this
year. The past two British Opens at Royal Troon and Royal Lytham
have brought atypically warm weather. This week the weather is so
cold and windy, even the Brits are complaining about it.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch's comments three years ago brought negative comments from
some PGA Tour colleagues. Brad Faxon, for one, suggested that
players who skip the British Open shouldn't get Ryder Cup points
for competing elsewhere that week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was wrong,'' Hoch said. ``... We're independent
contractors, so to speak, and we get to play where we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch actually likes Royal Birkdale, which is tighter than some
British Open venues and rewards finding the fairway. And what if he
were to somehow drive out his negative thoughts and win?
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought that could easily happen until I got over
here and saw the weather,'' he said. ``I thought that would show
that God has a sense of humor, wouldn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
