<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kuchar can't fathom millions
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar, 20, admittedly can not comprehend
the numbers that are being thrown at him by agents wishing that he
turn professional. ``I'm not too familiar with exactly what those
numbers mean,'' he said Tuesday. ``They're saying millions. I don't
really know what a million is going to do for me. I've always
played around with a couple of thousand to get by on tuition and
buying books and buying food for myself. I really don't know how
far a million could get me.'' He may find out soon enough. Some
expect him to turn pro before the U.S. Amateur next month. Ex-Tech
man Stewart Cink, whom Kuchar has counseled about the matter of
turning pro, said, ``It's going to be hard for him to turn down all
that's being thrown at him. For the long term, if he's going to
turn pro, probably the best time is very soon.'' Then again, Cink
said, ``I've told him if his game is good enough to turn pro out
here right now, it will be good enough in two years. It's not a
sprint; it's a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Open prep
</P>
<P>
   Comfort zones with links-style conditions might be present for
both Mark O'Meara and Tiger Woods this week. Granted, the weather
was different in Orlando, Fla., but last week before coming to
Ireland, they played The Old Course at Grand Cypress, a St.
Andrews-type layout. O'Meara shot 63 and lost money to Woods, who
shot a 62. On Monday, enjoying unreal downwind conditions, Woods
sailed a drive on Birkdale's eighth hole, which extends 457 yards,
to within eight yards of the green. It was all relative, though.
O'Meara had just carried a 338-yard 1-iron at No. 8. More often,
though, the British crowds will cheer for crafty shotmaking, rather
than brute force _ American or Brit. ``People in the UK are very
knowledgeable,'' O'Meara said. ``Over here you don't always have to
hit it to two feet to get a response from the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo's aching elbow survived a practice round Tuesday, but
not without some pain. He purposely hit tee shots into the rough to
avoid sharp contact with the ground from divots. ``I shall be
trying to hit all the fairways when Thursday comes _ not miss
them,'' said the three-time champion. ... Bill Glasson's elbow,
still recovering from surgery, hasn't held up as well and forced
his withdrawal. England's Barry Lane replaced him in the field. ...
David Duval, on the fury that Royal Birkdale has brought with wind
and cold this week: ``I read something in the paper that people
lost a lot of golf balls yesterday. I was one of them. I lost five.
The biggest is in the crosswinds. You hit it, it gets blown across
the fairway, bounces in the really high rough and you've lost your
golf ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
