<SLUG> BC-BIOLOGICAL-THREAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS ACCUSED OF THREATENING PRESIDENT WITH BIOLOGICAL WEAPONS
FACE HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Three self-proclaimed members of the Republic of
Texas separatist group are scheduled to appear in federal court
Wednesday for allegedly plotting to assassinate President Clinton
and other senior officials using cactus needles dipped in
biological agents.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys are expected to use the preliminary hearing to
try force the FBI to provide more evidence about why the men should
be charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Wise, 72, of Olmito; Jack Abbott Grebe Jr., 43, of Los
Fresnos; and Oliver Dean Emigh, 63, of Harlingen, have been held
without bail at the Cameron County Jail since they were arrested
July 1 on charges of conspiring to use of weapons of mass
destruction and using weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI contends that a ``Declaration of War'' was relayed by
e-mail in June in which the men threatened to attack Clinton, the
FBI director, the head of the Central Intelligence Agency, the U.S.
Attorney General and their families, according to documents
unsealed Monday in federal court at Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your FBI employees and their families have been targeted for
destruction by revenge,'' reads a sample message that FBI officials
allege was meant for the agency's director, Louis J. Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Non-traceable, personal delivery systems have been developed
to inject bacteria and/or viruses for the purpose of killing,
maiming, and causing great suffering,'' the message said, according
to the documents that were part of an affidavit for search
warrants.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks were to be carried out using cactus thorns dipped in
substances such as anthrax, rabies and HIV-tainted blood, according
to the documents, then shot at a target.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys declined to comment on the charges. U.S.
Magistrate John Black issued a gag order earlier this month that
forbids lawyers from discussing the case with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service declined to give statistics on how often
Clinton is threatened, but it said all threats against the
president are investigated.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet provides ``recipes'' for biological weapons
enabling a person without specialized training to make one from
botulism or anthrax, FBI Agent Frank Sharkey states in the federal
court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents, including hazardous materials specialists, made
arrests and searched the men's homes after an unnamed government
witness tipped authorities to the alleged plot, according to the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if investigators found anything to back up their
case, but they seized several books on chemistry and electronics, a
syringe and a jar of an unknown substance.
</P>
<P>
   The government witness contends the defendants introduced
themselves as members of the Republic of Texas and attempted to
recruit the witness into the organization to join the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
   Emigh allegedly wrote several versions of the Declaration of War
in May, and the government witness was asked to help find ways to
sent it without it being traced, according to the recently unsealed
documents.
</P>
<P>
   On June 12 and 26, Wise and Grebe supposedly met at the
government witness' house to send the threats using e-mail,
according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Wise and Grebe allegedly told the witness that the first target
would be Migadalia Lopez, a Cameron County Court-at-Law judge.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed tailing Lopez to find out where she shopped and
where she ate breakfast to ``more easily target her for
assassination,'' the document states.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez' staff declined to comment, but Eloy Cano, a chief deputy
at the Cameron County Sheriff's Department, said steps had been
taken to ensure her safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
