<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTWOOD MIGHT BREAK THROUGH AT BRITISH OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's young, polite, talented and witty. He relishes pressure
situations and still seeks the counsel of the mentor who has honed
his swing since his days as a junior golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he finds himself riding a hot streak as he heads
to this week's British Open in quest of the first major
championship of his professional career.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, those words could have been used to describe a
25-year-old named Justin Leonard. The Dallas resident went on to
hoist the claret jug at Royal Troon Golf Club in Troon, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the same description fits comfortably around
the shoulders of another 25-year-old. But with Lee Westwood, there
is the added pressure of trying to make history in his own back
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Westwood, a vital contributor in Europe's 1997 Ryder Cup
triumph, grew up in Worksop, England, a 90-minute drive from Royal
Birkdale Golf Club. The 124th winner of golf's oldest major
championship will be crowned Sunday at Royal Birkdale. And it is
Westwood, not Nick Faldo or Colin Montgomerie, who is viewed as the
Brit most likely to keep the coveted claret jug in the land of its
origin for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Most 25-year-olds would wilt under the weight of such lofty
expectations. Westwood welcomes the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He talks openly of winning this week and downplays any concern
about being the latest hero-in-waiting for a sports fandom reeling
from gut-wrenching near misses in the World Cup (England's
controversial loss to Argentina) and the Wimbledon men's semifinals
(Pete Sampras over England's Tim Henman).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind. If anything, it gives me a confidence boost,''
Westwood said of being considered atop the current list of Europe's
elite players. ``I'd rather be in that group than not in that
group. It's nice when people start talking about you like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his chances at Royal Birkdale, Westwood did not mince
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any point coming into a tournament
unless you think you can win it,'' he said. ``And I think the way I
am playing, if I play well this week, then I can win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder. Since November, Westwood has won seven
tournaments on four continents, including last week's Loch Lomond
event in Glasgow, Scotland. He's coming off his career-best effort
at a major championship, a tie for seventh at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Like Leonard, he radiates a quiet confidence and a taste for
pressure situations that is rare at any age. Like Leonard, he
should be considered a prime candidate for a major breakthrough at
25.
</P>
<P>
   In characterizing his prized pupil, Randy Smith once described
Leonard as the type of athlete who would insist on taking the
buzzer-beating shot at the end of a basketball game with the
outcome on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wilt under that kind of spotlight. He
absolutely craves it,'' Smith said. ``The more intense the
spotlight, the better he likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   John King, the man who has tutored Westwood throughout his
career, understands the sentiment. Hanging proudly in his office at
Worksop Golf Club, where King is the head golf professional, is a
photo of King lecturing a group of junior golfers. All are sitting
at rapt attention except Westwood, whose gaze is fixed on the
camera, with a wry smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   King said Westwood ``has always loved the limelight ... and
never seems affected by pressure'' while on the golf course. Those
traits were first displayed to U.S. audiences during the 1997 Ryder
Cup, when Westwood teamed with Faldo to defeat Tiger Woods and Mark
O'Meara, 3 and 1, in a pivotal four-ball match.
</P>
<P>
   Westwood, who finished 3-3 in Ryder Cup matches, also claimed
his first PGA Tour title at the Freeport-McDermott Classic on April
5. The victory in New Orleans came in just his seventh start on the
PGA Tour. In 10 career appearances at PGA Tour events, Westwood has
four top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Dating back to the 1997 British Open, Westwood has finished
10th, 29th, 44th and seventh in his last four major championships.
In Westwood's estimation, his Ryder Cup success has lifted his
level of play in every subsequent tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing every hole in the Ryder Cup is like playing the last
hole in a tournament needing a par to win,'' Westwood said. ``Any
time I am in contention now, I can go back on that experience of
playing in the Ryder Cup. I've got confidence now that I never had
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough confidence that Leonard, now 26, recognizes Westwood as a
legitimate threat to achieve the same type of career breakthrough
at Birkdale that he enjoyed last year at Troon. Age, in Leonard's
estimation, is an insignificant factor when judging potential
winners of major championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at anybody as a young guy or an old guy. Golf
isn't really a sport where age makes a huge difference,'' Leonard
said. ``Sure, the difference between a 15-year-old and a
30-year-old is big. But once you are a professional, ... I think it
depends on the individual. Age is not as big a factor as some
people make it out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a 26-year-old preparing to defend his first major
championship. With a talented, 25-year-old closing fast in his
rearview mirror.
CHIP SHOTS
Pak-ing them in
</P>
<P>
   How big a star is LPGA rookie Se Ri Pak, who is coming off a
record-setting victory at the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic?
</P>
<P>
   Big enough that Pak, 20, has had to give up eating at her
favorite restaurant to avoid autograph seekers. A native of South
Korea who won 30 amateur events and six professional tournaments in
her homeland before joining the LPGA tour this season, Pak has
established Orlando, Fla., as her U.S. residence.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, Pak's favorite Korean restaurant in the city also is
frequented by tour buses filled with Korean visitors to Walt Disney
World. K.R. Kim, Pak's manager, said his client has been besieged
for hours at a time while dining. And this was ``before'' Pak won
her second major championship of the season (the U.S. Women's Open)
and moved atop the LPGA season earnings list with her triumph at
the Kroger Classic ($645,170).
</P>
<P>
   ``If they see her, she won't have any food and the bus doesn't
leave,'' Kim said. ``She's happy with \Rfast food\S now.''
Tiger-like triumph
</P>
<P>
   Pak's 11-stroke victory Sunday has been likened to Tiger Woods'
12-stroke romp at the 1997 Masters, a valid comparison in that both
were eye-popping, record-setting achievements by tour rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are subtle, significant differences in the two
achievements and in the rookie seasons of the two golfers. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   Woods lapped the field in a major championship, where a wide
disparity between front-runners' scores is rare. Pak got hot in a
regular tour event, where scoring conditions are more favorable and
routs are more frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Pak's effort included the lowest single-round (61) and 72-hole
totals (261) in the history of the LPGA tour. Woods did not eclipse
either mark for PGA Tour competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Pak achieved her distinction as a 20-year-old rookie in a season
that has seen her win two (LPGA Championship, Women's Open) of
three major championships contested thus far. Woods won the 1997
Masters as a 21-year-old rookie but did not win another major that
season.
</P>
<P>
   Woods finished his rookie season with four victories, a second,
a third and three other top-10 efforts to set a PGA Tour season
earnings record ($2,066,833). In weeks when Pak has not won this
season, she has not cracked the top 10, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Comparisons between the two feats and players are
interesting but pointless. It's like the age-old comparison of
apples and oranges. There is not enough commonality to declare one
superior to another.
</P>
<P>
   But it is safe to say that these two triumphs stand as the most
dominant, 72-hole golfing displays of this decade. And, if they are
ever to be duplicated or eclipsed, Woods and Pak head the list of
players likely to do it.
SHORT PUTTS
</P>
<P>
   Of the five major championships awarded in 1998, four have gone
to residents of Orlando, Fla. The lone exception is Pat Hurst, who
hails from Incline Village, Nev., and won the LPGA's Nabisco Dinah
Shore event. Se Ri Pak took the other two LPGA titles, and the PGA
Tour winners have been Mark O'Meara (Masters) and Lee Janzen (U.S.
Open). That could bode well at this week's British Open for the
likes of fellow Orlando residents Tiger Woods, Ernie Els, Payne
Stewart, Scott Hoch, Corey Pavin and Ted Tryba. ... Hoch, by the
way, will be playing in only the third British Open of his 20-year
career. Why the sudden change of heart by a player who has never
finished better than 68th at the event? His equipment supplier,
Yonex, tempted Hoch with incentive clauses based on his performance
in the event. ... In his lone PGA Tour outing since switching back
to traditional blade irons, Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks shot
four rounds in the 60s while finishing 12th at the Canon Greater
Hartford Open. It marked the first time this season that Brooks
broke 70 in more than two consecutive rounds. Brooks will attempt
to extend the streak at the British Open, where he has finished
fifth (1996), third (1995) and 20th (1994) in three of his past
four appearances. ... Jim Furyk has 21 top-10 finishes in the past
18 months, tops among PGA Tour participants in that span.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
