<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY INVITATIONS TO PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All of a sudden, everyone in late-night television
is getting invited to appear in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost everyone. Late night's most popular star, Jay Leno,
is not included in this year's push to prime time. Conan O'Brien,
however, will get his first prime-time special for his show's fifth
anniversary on the air in September. And CBS will broadcast a
five-year anniversary show with David Letterman in November.
</P>
<P>
   Even ABC's ``Nightline'' is going prime time, with a special
series of reports that will be a reprise of that program's highly
praised investigations of life in American prisons.
</P>
<P>
   NBC announced Tuesday that O'Brien would star in his first
prime-time special Sept. 15 at 10 p.m. ``Late Night'' executive
producer Jeff Ross said the show would be mainly a collection of
the best moments in the O'Brien show's five years on the air, along
with some new material, with a sprinkling of guests.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's decision to ask O'Brien to take his act to prime time is
confirmation of the network's commitment to him as one of its
franchise stars.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment was a long time coming; for the first several
years O'Brien worked on short-term contracts with NBC. Ross said
that ``just being asked to do this by NBC was huge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien arrived at NBC in 1993 as a totally untried performer;
he had been a comedy writer, never a comedian. His skills were
widely criticized as rough, but he slowly gained acceptance, and
more lately praise, for his fresh approach to comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as has been the custom whenever a late-night star is
asked to step into prime time, O'Brien had some trepidation about
the request. ``I guess our feeling is, it's better for us than it
might be for the network,'' Ross said. ``Prime time has a different
scale; you have to be aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the opportunity and what it meant for the show's
relationship with the network, Ross said O'Brien had concluded that
whatever risk was involved was worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his days at NBC in the 1980s, Letterman had similar
reservations about doing specials in prime time, fearing that his
style was tailored for late-night audiences and might generate
disappointing ratings in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   But his NBC specials, and three he has done for CBS since then,
have all been critically praised and successful in the ratings. Rob
Burnett, Letterman's executive producer, said the comedian would
star in a 90-minute prime-time special in the November sweep rating
period to mark his fifth year on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, NBC announced that Leno would star in a prime-time
special on his fifth anniversary as host of the ``Tonight'' show,
but Leno soon killed the idea, saying he preferred to keep the show
in its regular time period.
</P>
<P>
   The shift of ``Nightline'' into prime time for the first time is
not related to any special anniversary, but has more to do with the
need for more news programming in prime time during the summer
months.
</P>
<P>
   ABC announced this week that ``Nightline'' would broadcast
special updated repeat editions of programs about crime in America
for five weeks on Thursday nights starting Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News spokesman Eileen Murphy said ``Nightline'' had been
looking for an outlet to rebroadcast some of its programs that are
not tied to daily breaking news events. ``For a while they were
considering going to one of our cable channels like A&AMP;E or the
History Channel,'' Ms. Murphy said. But then ABC itself stepped in
with the decision to find a prime-time home for the ``Nightline''
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Under the title ``Nightline in Prime Time: Crime in America,''
these are programs that focus on the prison system and will include
a series of shows in which the anchor, Ted Koppel, spent time on
Death Row, in solitary confinement and in other parts of jails.
</P>
<P>
   Koppel will add new introductions to each of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is clearly including the ``Nightline'' shows as part of a
strategy to use as much news programming as possible in the summer.
News magazines are in general becoming more and more a staple of
summer programming at the broadcast networks as the repeats of
entertainment shows _ especially hourlong drama shows _ attract
lower and lower ratings in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   On each of the five Thursdays when ``Nightline'' will fill the
10 p.m. time slot, ABC will fill the 9 p.m. hour with another
repackaged news program, a compilation of reports from its news
magazine shows on related topics.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on Aug. 6, the 9 p.m. show will include reports on
``The Art of the Con,'' revealing how telemarketing swindles target
consumers. The next two weeks, the shows will be reports on
consumer issues: how to be a better buyer and how to avoid being
taken. Another show, on the theme of ``Man and Nature,'' will
include previous reports on how to survive house fires, tornadoes
and other crises.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of repackaging news magazine reports into a themed hour
has worked particularly well this summer for CBS's ``48 Hours,''
which has taken some previous programs, labeled them ``48 Hours
Mysteries'' and put them on Monday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The shows have done well there, even on occasion attracting
higher ratings than original programs by the incumbent news
magazine in that time period, NBC's ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's edition of ``48 Hours Mysteries'' was the highest
rated so far this summer and again beat NBC's ``Dateline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
