<SLUG> BC-MA-TAX-CUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS PROPOSE $700 MILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS   AND TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Declaring that Democrats are not ``phobic'' over
cutting taxes, legislative leaders Tuesday proposed a nearly $700
million tax reduction package that won a strong endorsement from
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, but was ridiculed by fiscal
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   With the state's treasury overflowing, House Speaker Thomas
Finneran and Senate President Thomas Birmingham unveiled a plan
they said is ``progressive'' in its treatment of working families
and ``historic'' because of its size.
</P>
<P>
   But the two Democrats also said the plan provides for using some
of the state's huge revenue windfalls to build up the state's
stabilization _ or rainy-day _ fund and to invest in capital
projects, such as the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good day for the taxpayers of Massachusetts,''
Birmingham told a State House press conference. The plan would,
among other things, cut investment income tax from 12 percent to
5.95 pecent and double personal exemptions on earned income.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who has been seeking a $1.2 billion tax cut, said the
Democratic package is ``basically what I have been fighting for
over the past year.'' But he said he would continue to press for
his larger tax cut plan to reduce the state income tax from 5.95
percent to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Finneran and Birmingham said it was possible for such a cut
in the income tax, although neither would be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the last word on taxes,'' Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci Tuesday faced demands from fiscal conservatives asking
him to veto the Democratic tax plan, in part because it contains
Finneran's bid to increase the size of the rainy-day fund. The more
money that is squirreled away for future economic downturns, the
less money returned to taxpayers today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's outrageous,'' said Barbara Anderson, executive director
of Citizens for Limited Taxation &AMP; Government, adding that
Finneran's provision is, in effect, a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Under law, Cellucci can not selectively veto that provision when
the tax plan, but must accept or reject the whole plan even though
he objects to the rainy day fund increase.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson called on Cellucci to reject the entire $700 million
tax plan because of the stabilization fund change. She said he
should demand the Legislature enact his income tax cut plan. ``We
should hold out for what they should be doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's almost certain Cellucci will not heed Anderson's plea.
Aides said Cellucci did not like Finneran's rainy day fund idea,
but would accept it to get a major tax cut _ a cornerstone to his
bid for a full four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also received support from a fiscal watchdog group.
``Veto the largest tax cut in the history of the Commonwealth?''
said Michael Widmer, president of the Massachusetts Taxpayers'
Foundation, funded by major Massachusetts corporations. ``That
makes aboslutely no sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also rejected a demand from Republican gubernatorial
foe, State Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, to veto the plan because it
did not cut the income tax to 5 percent, the rate before it was
raised to pay for the fiscal crises of the late 1980's. ``I am not
going to put a much needed tax cut for families ... at risk,''
Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said Cellucci had ``rolled over'' for the Democratic
leadership. ``Instead of drawing the line in the sand, he raised
the white flag of surrender very early on in this process,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said Cellucci, by vetoing their plan, would raise public
pressure on the lawmakers to enact a bigger tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we fight for something we take the case to the public, we
do everything we possibly can do to make sure the people in this
building feel the heat,'' Malone said, describing what he said is
his style of battling the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic tax cut package _ phased in over two years _
would double the exemption for earned income, saving between $131
for a single filer to $262 for joint filers; and cut in half the 12
percent tax rate on interest and dividend income.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would increase the size of the rainy-day fund from 5
percent of current revenues to 7.5 percent, allowing reserves to
grow from $950 million to a maximum of $1.42 billion. The value of
that line item: $475 million.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the proposal would cut unemployment insurance rates by
$116 million. Of that, $18 million would be dedicated to a
workforce development program.
</P>
<P>
   And the state tax code also will be brought in line with the
federal tax code in several areas, including educational and Roth
Individual Retirement Accounts and capital gains on the principle
sale of a residence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
