<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BEACHES-BOS &LR;      07-14 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BEACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS SITES CLEANLINESS OF MASSACHUSETTS BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're planning a trip to the beach in one of Massachusetts'
70 oceanfront communities someday soon, you can feel confident the
water will be safe _ or the beach will be shut down if it is not.
</P>
<P>
   A new nationwide report from the Natural Resources Defense
Council concludes local governments, and in particular the
Metropolitan District Commission, which runs Boston Harbor beaches,
are doing a fairly good job testing the water regularly for
pollution compared to other states.
</P>
<P>
   But at least seven communities were faulted for having no
regular testing. Nearly half test water only once or twice a month.
And many use what is considered to be an outdated 1950s standard
for sewage contamination at beaches, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Harbor could be the model water quality monitoring
program for the whole country, but we're not there yet in terms of
coastwide monitoring across the state,'' said Joan LeBlanc of the
Boston Harbor Association, which participated in the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens have a fundamental right to know about the water
quality of our public beaches,'' said Joan Malik of the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group. ``We must do more to
ensure that every parent on the beach today can be certain that the
coast is clear and the water is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   As the $4 billion harbor cleanup project has made city beaches
once again safe for swimming most days, the MDC has instituted a
program of posting pennants to tell swimmers whether the water is
safe (blue) or contaminated (red), usually because rainstorms have
overwhelmed sewers.
</P>
<P>
   While the report's call for regularly testing every mile of
every beach may sound like a worthy goal, in some places it might
be a waste of time and money, some officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the report faults four Martha's Vineyard
communities _ Chilmark, Edgartown, Gay Head and West Tisbury _ for
having no monitoring programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Jo-Ann Taylor, coastal planner for the Martha's Vineyard
Commission, said there's a good explanation: ``There's no reason
for it, especially in those towns. There's nothing that would cause
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any industry. We don't have any sewage plants
that are discharging to the ocean,'' Taylor said. ``On the
south-facing side of the island, there's nothing between the beach
and Portugal.''
</P>
<P>
   The three other communities faulted for not having regular
monitoring programs were Newburyport and Rowley, which own parts of
Plum Island, and Provincetown.
</P>
<P>
   Newburyport harbormaster Ralph Steele said, ``This is the first
I've heard of any concern on anybody's part.'' He noted that the
city sewer department regularly tests discharges into the Merrimack
River, and last month asked him to shut down the beach after
torrential rains overwhelmed the sewage plant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Massachusetts public beaches _ chiefly in East Boston,
Dorchester and Quincy _ were closed at least 140 days because of
elevated bacteria levels from sewage overflows.
</P>
<P>
   That compared to 152 in 1996, 132 in 1995, and about 60 in each
of the four preceding years. Shifting weather patterns and spotty
reporting compliance make it difficult to declare any trend of
increasing or decreasing beach closures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-0715-CO     07-14 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-0715-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FACING TOUGH REFORMS, AILING JAPANESE ECONOMY CAN STILL CALL ON
RESERVE STRENGTH
 &HT;    With JAPAN-ECONOMY-BOX-0715.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less than a decade after being touted as an
economic superpower whose manufacturing prowess and virtuous saving
habits had destined it to lead the global marketplace into the 21st
Century, Japan has become the whipping boy of the world economy,
roundly and routinely scolded by central bankers from Washington to
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Japanese voters piled on, drubbing the long-ruling
Liberal Democratic Party in a parliamentary defeat that forced the
resignation of Ryutaro Hashimoto, Japan's sixth prime minister in
five years, in a harsh political reckoning for the sins of low
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Japan's economy is, indeed, a mess.
</P>
<P>
   It's generated little new wealth or jobs in seven out of the
past eight years, has actually been contracting since late last
year and will do well, analysts predict, to expand by a
half-percentage point in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't foresee any prospect of growth in any meaningful way
for at least the next 18 months,'' said Bradley Belt, director of
international finance and economic policy for the Center for
Strategic and International Studies, a Washington think tank.
''There are obviously some very significant structural problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, dire as Japan's short-term outlook appears, the
nation's economy, the world's second-largest, retains some bedrock
strengths that many analysts claim will pull the country out of its
torpor and power it back toward prosperity. Within two or three
years, some analysts believe, the 90s could be looked upon as the
period when Japan struggled to reshape its economy into a machine
capable of roaring back as an even stronger global competitor than
it was during the heady 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a hell of a lot of unrecognized value,'' in Japan at
the moment, said William Farrell, president of Dynamic Strategies
Asia, a consulting firm based in Leesburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Japanese did not just go brain dead,'' said Farrell, who
has worked closely with Japan for two decades. ''They're going to
come out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   That's far from the consensus view.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, U.S. officials from Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin on down have publicly excoriated the Japanese for failing to
reform their economy, stimulate domestic consumption and confront a
tsunami of bad debt that has swamped the country's banking system
and left it adrift in the horse latitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Peeved that Japan's ills have contributed to the broader
economic crisis in Asia and fearful that continuing troubles in
Tokyo could deepen the region's woes, even officials in Beijing --
who oversee the world's largest remaining communist nation -- have
taken aim at Japanese capitalism in recent weeks, warning darkly
that a devaluation in China's currency could result unless
''stability'' returns to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for the concern.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's banking system is riddled with bad loans -- valued at
some $600 billion -- not likely to be repaid, the sour legacy of
Japan's go-go 80's, when banks were flush with cash and eager to
lend it to anyone who could show projected sales increases or a
balance sheet pumped up with real estate or stocks. Sales
projections, like assets, turned out to be vastly overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks, moreover, are heavily exposed to regional
economies such as Thailand, South Korea and Indonesia, that are
suffering daunting economic downturns, meaning billions more in
international bad debt has yet to be swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Japan, for it's part, has piled up $2.8
trillion worth of debt, equal to 75 percent of gross domestic
product, or GDP (the measure annual economic output) of $3.7
trillion for the year ended March. That's higher, as a proportion
of the size of the economy, than even the U.S. debt, which, at $5.4
trillion, is roughly 67 percent of last year's GDP.
</P>
<P>
   The figures for Japan's public and bank debt are probably
conservative. Many analysts say that Japanese accounting procedures
are too opaque to fully assess.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of hidden numbers there that you just can't get
to the bottom of,'' said James Carlson, vice president for public
policy research with the New York investment firm, Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its difficulties and uncertainties, however, Japan
retains formidable economic resources.
</P>
<P>
   Japan remains globally competitive, if not dominant, in a host
of important manufacturing industries, including automobiles,
consumer electronics, telecommunications, computers, industrial
machinery and semiconductor production equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It has the richest coffers of foreign reserves -- $220 billion
at last count -- of any country in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It owns $800 billion more worth of overseas property, stocks and
bonds than foreigners own in Japan and it remains the world's
largest creditor nation, earning some $58 billion last year in
interest payments and dividends from its overseas investments and
loans.
</P>
<P>
   There is the vaunted Japanese workforce, among the
best-educated, highly motivated anywhere, performing in a closely
knitted country where social ills like violent crime and illicit
drug use are at levels among the world's lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fall of the Japanese yen, which has lost 20 percent of
its value against the U.S. dollar over the past year, helps Japan's
aggressive exporters, by making Japanese goods cheaper, in dollar
terms, and thus more attractive, in theory at least, to American
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have a basket case here at all,'' said Arthur
Alexander, president of the Japan Economic Institute of America, a
Washington-based information arm of the Foreign Ministry of Japan.
''It's individually wealthy; it's nationally wealthy; it has
skills, capabilities; there are a lot of strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   No one denies that difficult reform measures lie ahead for
Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Ridding the banks of bad loans -- much like the U.S.'s own
half-trillion dollar savings and loan crisis -- will be among the
most painful. The Japanese government hopes to begin a process for
doing that in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   And, analysts agree, the deeply indebted government needs to
mortgage its future even further to fund permanent tax cuts --
Hashimoto promised reductions before Sunday's elections and it's
not likely his successor, once picked sometime later this month,
would dare to renege -- at the same time it's committed to pumping
billions of additional dollars into public works aimed at
jump-starting the listless economy.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, much of the world may be suffering from a distorted
view of Japan's problems, said Hiro Ito, research associate with
the Economic Strategy Institute, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a perception that the whole economy's in trouble,''
said Ito, who is Japanese. In fact, he said, ''there's a huge gap
between the strong, competitive industries and the weak, regulated
industries. And the later is dragging down the former.''
</P>
<P>
   Ito, author of a recently published book, entitled ''A Cure for
Japan's Sick Banks,'' sees healing those institutions as the key to
setting the broader economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a little optimistic,'' Ito said. ''Japan might take about
two to two-and-a-half years to solve its bank loan problems. Once
Japan deals with that, the economy might start recovering.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
