<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES FALL AGAIN, HURT BY BY CURRENCY DEVELOPMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities fell for a second straight day
Tuesday, hurt by the dollar's decline against the yen in
foreign-exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Despite favorable economic news on consumer prices and retail
sales, the dollar's diminished value contributed to a bond sell-off
that pushed the 30-year Treasury yield to the highest level in
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the market remained focused on developments in
Japan, where the resignation of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on
Monday has contributed to some optimism that his yet-to-be-named
successor will take dramatic steps to stimulate the economy. The
dollar fell to 140.02 yen from 141.42 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's worst recession since World War II has been an
underlying force pushing Treasuries and the dollar's value higher
in recent weeks because United States assets are seen as safe-haven
investments from Asia's economic travails. If Japan starts to
strengthen, that could erode foreign investor demand for Treasuries
and the dollars needed to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The run-up in prices in the bond market over the past weeks
has come as a result of a flight to quality,'' said Robert
Pugliese, senior vice president and director of fixed income at
J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca Raton, Fla. ``So when that
begins to unwind you would expect the opposite to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   By close of the New York market the 30-year Treasury bond was
off 13/32 to a price of 105 26/32. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, was up to 5.71 percent from 5.69 percent
Monday. It was the highest since 5.73 percent June 16.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the decline, traders said, the underlying outlook for
bonds remains strong because there are few signs of rising
inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income investments.
</P>
<P>
   Economic reports released Tuesday reinforced that view. The June
consumer price index and retail sales data both rose by a
less-than-expected one-tenth of 1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
