<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAYS-BOS &LR;      07-14 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SLIDE CONTINUES AS THEY LOSE TO DEVIL RAYS, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ They've done it with baling wire and
mirrors, spare parts and extra heart.
</P>
<P>
   And it worked, for half a season.
</P>
<P>
   But five losses in their first six games since the All-Star
break, while no reason for anyone to be throwing a panic party, do
raise a few questions about the Red Sox as presently constituted,
none more urgent than this:
</P>
<P>
   Are opposition pitchers the only people around here aware that
the Red Sox badly need another proven righthanded hitter, and if
that knowledge has indeed reached the offices on Yawkey Way, how
quickly is Dan Duquette prepared to act?
</P>
<P>
   The general manager, who traded veteran Jim Leyritz and replaced
him with Billy Ashley, a player in whom manager Jimy Williams has
shown little confidence, has said he's looking for a
righthanded-hitting outfielder. But in the wake of Tuesday's 5-4
loss to the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays, Duquette may want to
accelerate that search.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try and do a better job on the offensive side,''
said Mo Vaughn, whose return to the lineup has dovetailed with the
team's dive since the All-Star break, even though he is hitting
.348 (8 for 23) with two home runs and four RBIs in that time. ``I
hope our pitchers don't get too frustrated with us. We have to hold
together and be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue may have taken on even greater urgency after Reggie
Jefferson, the lefthanded-hitting DH, pulled himself out of the
lineup in the seventh inning because his back problems flared up
again. Another righthanded hitter would allow the slumping John
Valentin (0 for 11, 1 for 16) to return to the No. 2 hole he
prefers, give needed protection to Vaughn, and even allow Williams
the option of restoring Nomar Garciaparra to the top of the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too good,'' said Jefferson, who on June 27 hurt his
back trying to twist out of the way of a fastball thrown behind him
by Florida pitcher Jesus Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   That pitch hit Jefferson in the base of the helmet but inflicted
more damage to his lower back than his head. He had a cortisone
injection in the affected area, but after just one hit and seven
strikeouts in 15 at-bats since the break, Jefferson yielded to
pinch hitter Midre Cummings with the potential go-ahead run on
second base. Cummings struck out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like it did a week ago,'' Jefferson said. ``It's
tightening up again.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bode well for the Red Sox, who return home after
collectively batting .226 while losing four straight to the Orioles
and splitting a pair with their expansion cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay ended an 11-game losing streak when Bret Saberhagen
failed to hold a 3-0 lead and relievers Ron Mahay and Carlos Reyes
gave up three straight hits in the bottom of the ninth, the last a
liner through the box by Miguel Cairo that nearly felled Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Cairo's game-winning single followed a double by Paul Sorrento
off Mahay that left a vapor trail through the legs of first baseman
Vaughn as it made its way into the right-field corner and sent
Bobby Smith to third. Sorrento, booed the night before, had four
hits during the matinee, including a fifth-inning home run off
Saberhagen, who until then had allowed only a single by Sorrento in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball could have killed me,'' Vaughn said of Sorrento's
double. ``I don't know where it was hit, but as soon as I looked,
it was by me. I couldn't tell you much about it. I'm glad I didn't
get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   It killed Saberhagen that he was unable to put away the Devil
Rays after being staked to a 3-0 lead. The Sox got on the board in
the first when Tampa Bay center fielder Randy Winn booted Vaughn's
single, allowing Garciaparra to score from first. They made it 2-0
in the second on Scott Hatteberg's opposite-field triple and Mike
Benjamin's sacrifice fly and went ahead by three in the fifth when
Damon Buford, starting in place of the injured Darren Bragg
(groin), doubled and scored on Darren Lewis's double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to lose when you know they've lost 11 in a
row and haven't gotten hits with runners in scoring position,''
Saberhagen said. ``We've lost two games to these guys, and I've
pitched in both of 'em. That doesn't sit well with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays bunched together a bloop single, a bunt hit, and
three straight line-drive singles off Saberhagen to take a 4-3 lead
in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we were on cruise control until that sixth
inning came along,'' Saberhagen said. ``They put the ball in play,
and I didn't bury them when I should have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
