<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND SENATORS CRITICIZE HOUSE SPENDING CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four moderate Republican senators from New England
Tuesday criticized the proposed spending cuts in the House budget
plan as ``unwise,'' in an opening skirmish among the GOP over the
size of the federal tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Senators John Chafee of Rhode Island, James Jeffords of Vermont,
Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, both of Maine, came out against
the House Budget Resolution, which proposes deep cuts in domestic
spending to pay for $101 billion in tax cuts over five years.
</P>
<P>
   They raised their objections in a letter to Senate Budget
Committee Chairman Pete V. Domenici, a Republican from New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here today to urge that fiscal responsibility rise
above fiscal temptation,'' Jeffords said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, being made public the day Domenici met with his
House counterpart, Representative John Kasich &UR;  &LR; of Ohio, to work out
differences in their budget bills, displayed the first significant
objection from Senate Republicans to the House tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If the four Republicans vote with Democrats on the final version
of a budget bill, the GOP majority in the Senate would be reduced
to one vote. The New England senators said at least two other
Republicans shared their concerns and would join them in voting
against the spending cuts needed to pay for the tax break proposed
by the House.
</P>
<P>
   The New Englanders said they were troubled by the additional
spending cuts called for in the House plan, because an estimated
$25 billion of the spending cuts would affect programs that help
low-income families and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spending reductions envisioned by the House would
effectively shred the safety net for low-income families and
children,'' said Chafee in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very very hard to carry this out without causing
considerable pain,'' he said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   While House Republican leaders have made large tax cuts a
priority, the House has not yet determined how to pay for them. The
Senate Budget Resolution calls for $30 billion in tax relief over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee said the initiative by the New England moderates is to
help Domenici find common ground with Kasich for a tax-and-spending
plan for the next five years, because the House version would not
pass in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee said he was concerned that momentum is building in the
Senate to support a budget plan closer to the House version than
the Senate on tax cuts. Senate Republican leader Trent Lott agreed
to a compromise with conservatives, including Senator John Ashcroft
of Missouri, on a $60 billion tax cut _ double the size Domenici
has said is affordable.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the letter from the New Englanders, Ashcroft,
Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire and three other conservatives
sent their own letter to Domeneci insisting that $101 billion in
tax relief was ``achievable.'' They vowed to oppose any budget
compromise that contained less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tax cuts will produce more revenues,'' Smith said in
an interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
