<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Wednesday, July 15. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
HAYWORTH (Undated) - Arizona's J.D. Hayworth, who had been trying
to tone down his image, returns to his old self with a fund-raising
letter calling Bill Clinton ``an unprincipled, philandering
president'' who has presided over ``the most corrupt administration
in U.S. history.'' The letter has outraged Democrats who are still
smarting over Indiana Republican Dan Burton calling Clinton a
``scumbag.'' ``This kind of bitter partisanship and mean-spirited
name-calling is shocking, even coming from Hayworth,'' said Mark
Fleisher, head of the state Democratic Party. The letter comes
after Hayworth was voted the second biggest ``windbag'' in Congress
by 1,200 Capitol Hill staffers in a survey published in the July
edition of ``Washingtonian'' magazine. By MIKE MURPHY. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BILINGUAL (Undated) - Concerned that only a small fraction of
bilingual students are becoming proficient in English, more than a
dozen Tucson parents and educators have begun pushing for a ballot
initiative to end bilingual education in Arizona. Their worries are
based partly on findings by the Arizona Department of Education
last month that just 2.8 percent of Limited English Proficient
students in the state learn enough English to enter the academic
mainstream. Mary Mendoza of Tucson, one of the leaders of the
group, said the figure is not surprising. ``There's no academic
component to bilingual programs,'' she said. ``There's no education
in them. Their goal is to keep Mexican students illiterate.'' By
RUBEN NAVARRETTE JR. Story will move int he ``A`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WYCLIFFE (SUPAI, Ariz.) - Scott and Lynanne Palmer brought their
love for God and master's degrees in linguistics to this dusty
village in the Grand Canyon's depths two decades ago. Today,
surrounded by the high red rock walls, they painstakingly continue
the work of their hearts: Translating the Bible into Havasupai.
They have lived with views of vivid blue sky by day and brilliant
stars by night, a short hike from the spectacular blue-green Havasu
Falls. They have raised two daughters in a home smaller than a
double garage with few modern conveniences. They have earned trust
and friendship and learned the Havasupai language, carefully
guarded by a tribe that does not want its words scattered outside
the canyon. And with the help of a few tribal members, they have
drafted about 6,500 Bible verses _ most of the New Testament and 17
chapters of Genesis _ into Havasupai, a language so different from
English that each verse is translated meaning to meaning rather
than word for word. By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH. With WYCLIFFE-SIDE and
photos. Story will move in the ``A`` and ``L'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEIGHBORS (Phoenix) _ When Kim Jablonski was hospitalized for
serious heart surgery, her neighbors decided to do what they could
to make her recovery easier. They remodeled her house. By MICHAEL
CLANCY. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
