<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT URGES SPECIAL COUNSEL TO PROBE CHINA'S ROLE IN 1996 U.S.
ELECTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Tuesday that
``new information,'' which he refused to detail, had emerged about
China's effort to influence the 1996 presidential election, and he
called for appointment of a special counsel to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's allegation was part of an intense attack the Mississippi
Republican launched against Clinton administration technological
dealings with China, including the claim that the Communist regime
in Beijing had benefited militarily from lax U.S. export controls.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said his charges, delivered in a Senate speech, were based
on Senate committee investigations that are continuing and which
the Democratic administration has sought to stymie by refusing to
provide requested documents and testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he would block Senate consideration of Clinton
nominees from ``non-cooperative agencies'' and that he and others
in the Republican leadership are ``actively examining our subpoena
options.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Democratic leaders on Capitol Hill said
Lott's contentions were ill-founded and politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Mike McCurry said Lott's remarks were ``not a
serious statement by a serious person'' but an attempt ``to connect
a lot of dots that, frankly, don't connect.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said, ``It's
partisanship at its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Lott's points were based on his interpretation of public
testimony before Senate committees over the past six weeks, but
that was not the case with his allegation that could be most
damaging to Clinton and his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``New information has come to light about China's efforts to
influence the American political process,'' Lott said. ``This new
information should remove all resistance to naming an independent
counsel to investigate the evidence and the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot comment in any detail about the nature of this
information,'' Lott said, but he said it had come to light since
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee finished its inquiry into
funding irregularities in the 1996 presidential campaign. ``And it
is significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for an outside, impartial investigation by an
independent counsel into serious and credible charges of direct
Chinese government financing of the 1996 elections. It is time to
end the stonewall and get to the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said such allegations are being investigated
properly by the Justice Department. During Clinton's recent trip to
China, President Jiang Zemin denied any attempt by the Chinese
government to influence U.S. elections.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said his Senate speech covered ``major interim judgments''
based on committee hearings since he formed a Senate task force in
late May to look into questions about possible transfers of
sensitive technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., co-chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, challenged Lott's presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication is that the committee has reached some kind of
conclusion. It most assuredly has not,'' Kerrey said.
</P>
<P>
   The multi-committee inquiry was sparked by allegations that a
U.S. satellite company, managed by the largest individual
contributor to the Democratic National Committee in the 1996
election cycle, had given China technical advice on improving the
accuracy of its troubled missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Since receiving the information, Lott said, Chinese missile
``launch reliability has been 100 percent. I agree with U.S.
government assessments that indicate this is not pure
coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the practice by which U.S. satellites are sent to
China to be launched on Chinese government rockets. Questions have
arisen about what technical details, with military as well a
commercial civilian applications, the Chinese may have learned
during such launches or post-launch reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration's export controls for satellites
are wholly inadequate,'' Lott said. ``They have not protected
sensitive U.S. technology. National security concerns are regularly
downplayed and even ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said China ``has received military benefit from U.S.
satellite exports'' and the Clinton administration has ``ignored
overwhelming information regarding Chinese (nuclear weapons)
proliferations, and has embarked on a de facto policy designed to
protect China and U.S. satellite companies from sanctions under
U.S. proliferation law.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that Clinton ``is confident that the licenses &UR;  &LR; that
he's granted have not contributed to China's ability to design,
develop, operate, maintain, modify or repair satellite launch
vehicles ....
</P>
<P>
   ``We've addressed these issues and made it quite clear that the
license waivers granted by the Clinton administration, pursuant to
a policy developed by President Reagan and first implemented by
President Bush, had been consistent with U.S. interest and had been
consistent with our desire to be competitive in the global
satellite and technology market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
