<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST ALL-NEW SCHOLARSHIP PAGEANT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   J &UR; eff Margolis &LR; , producer of the Miss America pageant, has
announced, ``This year, we are pushing the envelope further than we
have ever pushed it,'' which means pretty darned far.
</P>
<P>
   For the opening segment, for instance, contestants are free to
choose whatever clothes they like. And if that's not far enough,
contestants actually will dance in an ``MTV-type segment'' to the
music of ``recording artist &UR; Michael W. Smith &LR; ,'' whoever he is
(with apologies, Mike, if you live in the Bay Area). What's more,
outgoing Miss America Kate Shindle will present the 1998 Miss
America Woman of Achievement Award to
 &UR; Sharon Stone &LR; , whom Shindle selected for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are breaking the mold,'' said retiring pageant CEO
 &UR; Leonard Horn &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The panelists discussing Women &AMP; Business at the investment
banker Allen &AMP; Co.'s annual Sun Valley Conference last week
included  &UR; Katharine Graham &LR; , who owns the Washington Post,
 &UR; Diane Sawyer &LR; , who makes millions a year at ABC, and  &UR; Diane von &LR; 
 &UR; Furstenberg &LR; , noted dress designer and W gossip personality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the captains of industry who attended says the panelists
agreed that what women really want is ``to get control of their
lives'' (which must mean that Diane Sawyer is sick and tired of
scrubbing the kitchen floor).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A RUNNER-UP TELLS HIS STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Slate editor  &UR; Michael Kinsley &LR; , a candidate for the New Yorker
editorship that went to  &UR; David Remnick &LR; , described his experience
in a memo to his staff that was widely passed around the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley was summoned from Seattle to New York in a Friday
morning phone call from  &UR; Si Newhouse &LR; . He met Newhouse on Saturday
morning, talked, had lunch, &LR;  and then talked some more. ``And then
he says, `How would you react if I offered you X?' I say, `Are you
offering me the job?' He says yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley said he would answer in 48 hours; Newhouse said it was
too long; Kinsley agreed to tell him by Monday morning. On Sunday,
they talked, exchanged faxed proposals and counterproposals, and
Kinsley said he would probably take the job. The Kinsley and
Newhouse families dined together on Sunday night, talked
``virtually no business, &LR; '' and parted with Kinsley promising to
call Newhouse on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he got back to his hotel room, there was a message
asking him to call Newhouse. ``I call and he says, `You seem
reluctant.' I say, `It's a big decision, but if I do it I assure
you I'll be energetic and enthusiastic.' He says, `I'm starting to
feel reluctant, too. I think it would be better to call it off.' No
apology. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``He asks me to say that I had withdrawn my name. I say I'm not
going to lie about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Up, up and away: About halfway down the south side of San
