</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHT-WEAPONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., 20 OTHER NATIONS URGE CONTROLS ON SPREAD OF SMALL ARMS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ The United States joined 20 other countries
Tuesday in calling for measures to control the illicit and legal
sales of small arms and light weapons, pointing to their
uncontrolled spread and excessive accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was the first of its kind by governments acting in
concert. And although they failed to issue a statement of ``common
understanding,'' even after it had been watered down in two days of
closed meetings, the strongest advocates of controls on the
small-arms trade were pleased with the developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a step,'' the director of Belgium's foreign aid
agency, Marc Van Craen, said. Van Craen noted that it had taken 13
years to pass a United Nations convention on children's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-one countries reached a common understanding that we
have to do something about the plague of small weapons and a broad
agreement on what needs to be done,'' Van Craen said. ``But, of
course, once you get into the details the difficulty starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those difficulties were foreshadowed here during the
efforts to draft a statement of common understanding and
discussions on a treaty proposed by Canada that would restrict
small-arms sales. Reflecting the virtual absence of any
international legal controls, the treaty would bar only sales to
``nonstate actors'' like rebels, terrorist groups and criminal
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the United States and other countries had
misgivings about the proposed treaty, fearing that it would impinge
on foreign policy and commercial interests by barring covert sales
in support of liberation groups and sales to companies.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Col. Sirakoro Sangare, a military adviser to
the president of Mali, where a long civil war recently ended,
praised the Canadian proposal. Other countries said they felt that
the proposal did not go far enough because it did not deal with
sales to dictatorial governments or to regions with conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the floor, not the ceiling,'' said Steven Lee, a
member of the Canadian delegation and the director of the Canadian
Center for Foreign Policy Development. ``What we've tried to do is
put the puck on the ice and get the game started.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing virtually everyone here agreed on was that it was
going to be a long and difficult game.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles can be glimpsed in a comparison of the first and
final drafts of a document entitled ``An International Agenda on
Small Arms and Light Weapons: Elements of a Common Understanding.''
It was that document that failed to receive approval, after the
United States, Britain and some other countries said they would
have to send it back to their capitals for review.
</P>
<P>
   The final draft noticeably plays down the role of
nongovernmental organizations in controlling the small-arms trade.
It was nongovernmental organizations that forced governments to
enact a ban on land mines, and the United States does not want that
to be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   The first draft, which Norway circulated when the parley began,
notes ``the increasing number of governmental initiatives,'' and
refers to nongovernmental organizations as ``important partners.''
</P>
<P>
   The final draft says, ``governments bear the primary
responsibility for addressing these issues,'' and adds that
nongovernmental organizations ``contribute to our work.''
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of the United States, Britain and South
Africa, language was removed on asking governments to release
information on small-arms production and holdings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
