</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIAN GOVERNMENT TRIES TO BULLY VOTERS, U.N. IS TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ U.N. political and human rights officials
following preparations for elections in Cambodia on July 26 say the
country's electoral institutions have been heavily weighted in
favor of the Cambodian People's Party of Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen also controls all broadcasting and has barred coverage
of opposition campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing to the Security Council on Monday, Francesc
Vendrell, who oversees Asian political affairs, said that voter
intimidation by Hun Sen's party had been widespread and that his
supporters still operated in a climate of impunity that had led to
dozens of killings and disappearances, diplomats who heard his
briefing said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan is expected to send a cautionary
message to Cambodia in the next few days, a spokesman said Monday.
The United Nations organized and ran Cambodia's first democratic
election, in 1993, the largest such operation ever undertaken by
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen U.N. election monitors are based in Cambodia to watch
this year's process. About 300 international observers are expected
to monitor the voting, a number that political and human rights
officials said was probably insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   But statements by King Norodom Sihanouk and pledges by thousands
of volunteer Cambodian election observers to stay close to the
tallying of votes _ including sleeping overnight with ballot boxes
_ during a counting process that could take days have had some
effect in convincing people that they can vote as they choose,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement June 17 by the king, whose son Prince Norodom
Ranariddh leads the political opposition, told Cambodians not to
worry about threats and to feel confident that the secrecy of their
votes would be safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen has told voters that if they vote against him, all
development in their villages will cease, an official at the United
Nations in New York said. Some of his supporters have been more
violent in their threats, beating and in some cases torturing and
killing local opposition leaders who were trying to campaign for
election.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations and two leading U.S. institutes for promoting
democracy abroad agree that while the election process is seriously
flawed, the voters may still surprise the government.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday in Phnom Penh, the two U.S. groups, the National
Democratic Institute and the International Republican Institute,
said in a statement that ``systematic and widespread political
intimidation and violence'' had hampered opposition competition in
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the two institutes, affiliated with the Democratic and
Republican Parties, said that despite the significant coercion,
``the outcome of the election is not a foregone conclusion, and it
merits international attention.'' The two groups oppose a boycott
by monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has reduced its involvement in the
European-dominated Joint International Observer Group, which is
coordinated by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   American observers say the larger political environment, not
just the conduct of polling, must be judged when assessments are
made as to whether the elections are fair.
</P>
<P>
   The United States includes in that political environment the
violent coup of a year ago and the still unresolved killings or
disappearances of 100 opposition politicians, including supporters
of Ranariddh, who was ousted by Hun Sen, his junior partner in the
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Americans also say the control of all armed forces by Hun Sen's
party contributes to an uncertain climate for voting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
