<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-SUISSE-DEUTSCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT SUISSE HIRES DEUTSCHE BANK'S TECHNOLOGY GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Credit Suisse First Boston completed one of the
biggest talent raids in Wall Street history on Tuesday, luring more
than 100 technology bankers and analysts from Deutsche Bank AG.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Credit Suisse trumpeting its recruitment
coup came two weeks after it enticed the three leaders of the group
_ Frank Quattrone, George Boutros and Bill Brady _ into joining it.
The three had left Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. more than two years ago to
join Deutsche.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston and Deutsche reached a confidential
agreement late on Monday allowing for almost the wholesale transfer
of the German bank's technology group _ 132 employees including
secretaries. Now they are even negotiating the transfer of the
lease for the group's worldwide headquarters in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Quattrone and his two senior colleagues, who mailed letters to
clients in March assuring them that they would stay at Deutsche,
seemed pleased with their new bosses. ``We can really make a
difference with a firm that wants to be a leader,'' Quattrone said
in an interview Tuesday, maintaining that Deutsche has scaled back
its investment banking ambitions since he joined. ``Deutsche's
strategy of Europe first was not consistent with our strategy of
building a worldwide technology franchise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quattrone declined to comment on what financial incentives he
and his colleagues received to make the switch, but he described
reports of promised sums as high as $250 million as ``ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cautioned that international securities firms that have
tried to build their franchises quickly by assembling teams of
talented people have often stumbled, as the recent experience of
several big foreign banks _ including Union Bank of Switzerland,
Deutsche Bank, National Westminster Bank PLC and Barclays PLC, both
of Britain _ have shown. After expensive hiring binges, each of
these firms has pulled back from Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are zero examples of European banks that have been able
to build a franchise from within by buying people,'' said Evangelos
Kavouriadis, European banking analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP;
Co. But he quickly added that the Credit Suisse purchase of the
entire First Boston firm ``provides the only example of a
successful entry'' into Wall Street by a European firm.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche said little about the departures Tuesday. ``We are
pleased to have reached an amicable agreement with Credit Suisse
First Boston and Frank Quattrone,'' said Macy Egerton, a
spokeswoman for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf-Ernst Breuer, Deutsche's chief executive, said over the
weekend that his firm would seek to fill the gap created by recent
defections, perhaps by acquiring an international investment bank.
Analysts already have speculated that such Wall Street firms as
Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. and Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc.
would fit its needs.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of Quattrone's clients seem quite prepared to make
the switch with him to Credit Suisse. ``We are looking at the team,
Frank and his team, they are the people with the proven record,''
said Richard Kraber, chief financial officer of Wind Rivers
Systems, a California software company that Quattrone helped to
take public and one that has used many of Deutsche's banking
services. ``If you ask me whether the institution prevails over the
individuals, the answer is no. We will go with Frank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
