<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOTT CHARGES OF EXPORT ABUSES SPARK PARTISAN SPAT
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Tuesday that
the Clinton administration's ``wholly inadequate'' export policy
had resulted in the transfer of sensitive technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's statement on the Senate floor ignited a political tinder
box, with each party blaming the other for endangering national
security.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Republican's unexpected delivery of the findings
of what he termed an ``interim report'' of various Senate
investigations prompted leading Senate Democrats to assail him for
releasing classified information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is partisanship at its worst,'' said Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D. ``I am disappointed by the inaccuracies of the
statements and the recklessness of these statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats noted that Lott unveiled the findings just as
the wide-ranging investigation into campaign fund-raising abuses
_some involving China and other Asian nations _ appears to be
sputtering to an end without any high-ranking White House officials
implicated.
</P>
<P>
   Defense policy experts expressed concern that an opportunity to
examine whether the nation's security has been placed at risk may
be lost amid the partisan rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among those questions is: Did Loral Space and
Communications and Hughes Electronics, in helping figure out why a
satellite launch failed in February 1996 in southern China, convey
information that helped the Chinese improve the accuracy of their
nuclear missiles?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much willingness to accuse the other side of
partisanship. We need to discuss the facts,'' said Henry Sokolski,
who was the top Pentagon expert monitoring nuclear proliferation
during the Bush administration and who now runs the
Nonproliferation Policy Education Center in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the partisan outbreak on the Hill to two children
denying blame over a broken vase, Sokolski said, ``It's kind of
like two kids pointing at each other saying 'he did it,' when the
point is they are standing there in their bare feet with broken
glass everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger in all of this, Sokolski said, is that the focus will
be diverted away from closely examining the export policies of both
the Clinton and Bush administrations. ``It would be a shame if we
get stuck here in partisanship,'' he said. ``We need to address
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his floor statement, Lott said that the Senate had
conducted 13 hearings and heard testimony from 32 witnesses in four
Senate committees. From that testimony, he said, it clearly was
time for Attorney General Janet Reno to appoint an independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sharply criticizing the Clinton White House, Lott
said that China's military had benefited from the satellite exports
and that the administration had ``ignored overwhelming information
regarding Chinese proliferation'' and ``embarked on a de facto
policy designed to protect China and U.S. satellite companies from
sanctions under U.S. proliferation law.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of where the Clinton administration has looked the
other way, Lott said that testimony before the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee earlier this month revealed that Defense
Department monitors are not required to be present at satellite
launches in China. ``No one in the U.S. government knows what
transpired at these launches or if U.S. laws and polices on
technology transfer were followed,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's satellite export control system relies on the good
will of the Commerce Department, a department which has repeatedly
demonstrated its willingness to ignore national security concerns
on satellite exports,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   American satellite makers contend that transferring the
jurisdiction of approving satellite launches in China from the
State Department to the Commerce Department was crucial to their
business, with some comparing the State Department application
process to a ``roach motel,'' the type of place where you check in,
but never check out.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for the satellite industry. An economic
analysis by the Maryland-based Futron Corp. estimates that revenues
from the U.S. commercial satellite market, now valued $5.7 billion
could be worth more than six times that amount by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
