<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
news stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Wednesday, July 15, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Los Angeles at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-EDITOR-MAYOR _ (Los Angeles) Mayor Richard Riordan fulfilled
a longtime dream and got a lesson in the nitty-gritty of the news
business when he played editor-for-a-day at the Los Angeles Daily
News. Riordan discussed newspaper policy with the paper's editorial
board and ran the Daily News story meeting. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-TESTS (Los Angeles) _ A day after Stanford 9 test results
show LAUSD children did worse than the national average,
Superintendent Ruben Zacarias and the school board offer their
explanation. Also representatives of the teachers union and reform
groups analyze the scores and explain what needs to be done to fix
our schools. By Sherry Joe Crosby and Terri Hardy. (Will move in
the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BALDWIN-COURT (Los Angeles) _ Actor Alec Baldwin takes the stand
to explain why he punched a paparazzo outside his home. Tabloid
shooter Alan Zanger is suing Baldwin for assault, and Baldwin is
countersuing for invasion of privacy. The case raises questions
about a star's privacy rights versus the rights of the tabloid
press _ issues that have assumed special urgency since Princess
Diana's death. Zanger had been trying to get videotape of Baldwin
and wife Kim Basinger returning from the hospital with their
newborn baby. By Alex Roth. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-HOMES-SELLING (Los Angeles) _ When Harry and Elaine
Castellucci heard that the real estate market was rebounding, they
considered selling their home but waited. Then, when several
neighbors quickly sold their homes on Millionaires Row in the L.A.
suburb of Tarzana, they promptly put their $895,000 home on the
block. The empty nesters thought about moving into a smaller
residence when their children left home and feel now is a good time
to sell. All over L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, as potential equity
rises to levels not seen since the market rush of the late '80s,
homeowners are feeling more confident about selling their houses.
Demand has picked up for houses of all price ranges, including
upscale properties like the Castellucci residence. By Deborah
Adamson. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIG-20TH-CENTURY (Los Angeles) _ American International Group
bought more shares of 20th Century at the end of June, giving AIG
nearly 45 percent of 20th Century in common shares and covertable
shares. Officials with 20th Century haven't been able to stop the
slow takeover because as part of AIG's bailout of 20th Century
following the 1994 Northridge Earthquake, 20th Century agreed to
let AIG buy as many shares of 20th Century as it wanted. By Enrique
Rivero. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
