<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following financial
news stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Wednesday, July 15, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Los Angeles at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-HOMES-SELLING (Los Angeles) _ When Harry and Elaine
Castellucci heard that the real estate market was rebounding, they
considered selling their home but waited. Then, when several
neighbors quickly sold their homes on Millionaires Row in the L.A.
suburb of Tarzana, they promptly put their $895,000 home on the
block. The empty nesters thought about moving into a smaller
residence when their children left home and feel now is a good time
to sell. All over L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, as potential equity
rises to levels not seen since the market rush of the late '80s,
homeowners are feeling more confident about selling their houses.
Demand has picked up for houses of all price ranges, including
upscale properties like the Castellucci residence. By Deborah
Adamson. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIG-20TH-CENTURY (Los Angeles) _ American International Group
bought more shares of 20th Century at the end of June, giving AIG
nearly 45 percent of 20th Century in common shares and covertable
shares. Officials with 20th Century haven't been able to stop the
slow takeover because as part of AIG's bailout of 20th Century
following the 1994 Northridge Earthquake, 20th Century agreed to
let AIG buy as many shares of 20th Century as it wanted. By Enrique
Rivero. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
