grown to $1.5 billion, fast approaching the $1.9 billion for the
eight-month drought of 1996. The economic impact on the state over
the next 18 months will be $4.6 billion, according to one estimate,
and could eliminate about 40,000 jobs statewide. By NELSON ANTOSH.
