<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREMINS-COX     07-14 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREMINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech turnovers puts Cremins in hot seat
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seven underclassmen have left the Georgia Tech
basketball program in the past five years _ not an uncommon rate in
the ACC, but one that incites coach Bobby Cremins' critics and
concerns Tech athletics director Dave Braine.
</P>
<P>
   When starting point guard Travis Spivey announced two weeks ago
that he was transferring after one year at Tech, it fed the
perception that Cremins, under intense pressure to get the Yellow
Jackets back in the NCAA Tournament on a regular basis, is running
off players who don't live up to his high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I'm concerned with the perception,'' said Braine, who has
met with Cremins on several occasions. ``(But) the only ultimatum
I've delivered, if you want to call it that, was to get more
players and more depth. ... I'm not satisfied with the program, but
I'm never satisfied with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins takes the blame _ but only for recruiting players who
can't cut the tough academics at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm guilty of bringing in young men who are not comfortable
(in the classroom),'' Cremins said. ``I need to take a harder look
at their transcripts. I could kick myself for some of the mistakes
I've made. I hope I haven't hurt those players who have
transferred. I took risks that were unfair to everybody involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) people who know me, they know ... I would never run a
player off. If he wanted to stay here, I would honor his
scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven players who left Tech early, one turned pro, three
left for basketball reasons, and three left because of academic
problems _ although only one was on academic probation at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small forward Martice Moore (1992-94) transferred to Colorado
after his sophomore season, seeking more playing time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Point guard Stephon Marbury (1995-96) turned pro after his
freshman season and was the fourth pick in the NBA draft that year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forward Juan Gaston (1995-96) transferred to Clark Atlanta
after his freshman season because of academic problems. ``We knew
he was a risk (academically), but we decided to try it anyway,''
Cremins said. ``I take full responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Center Bucky Hodge (1994-96) transferred to Central Florida
after his sophomore season in search of increased playing time.
(Pablo Machado, the 1996 Mr. Georgia Basketball who lost his
starting job to freshman Alvin Jones last season, is considering a
transfer for a similar reason.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Shooting guard Gary Saunders (1995-97) missed the start of his
sophomore season while on academic probation and transferred to
Seton Hall after the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Point guard Kevin Morris (1996-97) struggled in his only
season against ACC competition and transferred to Georgia State of
the Trans America Athletic Conference last year.
</P>
<P>
   Spivey never was on academic probation, but has said he was
never comfortable in the classroom at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Would Cremins have encouraged Spivey, who averaged 5.6 points
per game last season, to transfer if he had averaged 21? ''If he
was struggling in the classroom, yes. If he was solid in school,
no,'' Cremins said.
</P>
<P>
   But the academic workload was not the only reason Spiver left.
He also was displeased that Cremins ``recruited over him'' this
season, signing Berkmar point guard Tony Akins. ``I felt it was in
my best interest if I transferred,'' Spivey said.
</P>
<P>
   Cremins defends the practice of transfers. ``You know,
transferring is very common and very healthy,'' he said. ``I don't
hesitate to encourage it when it's the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though players must sit out a year after transferring, it's
a fairly common practice around the ACC and nation _ and it works
both ways. Roshown McLeod transferred to Duke from St. John's and
had a great career, becoming the Hawks' first-round pick in this
year's NBA draft. Mike Chappell left Duke for Michigan State
because he wanted more playing time.
</P>
<P>
   And Jason Collier, a solid student and two-year starter at
Indiana, left the program and landed at Tech, where he'll be a
starter next season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look at out players who transferred (from Tech),'' Cremins
said. ''Almost all of them were starters. Basketball was not the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The players who have left the Tech program appear to harbor no
animosity toward Cremins. ''I don't have a problem with coach
Cremins,'' Spivey said. ''It was my decision to leave. He said he
wanted me to do whatever I felt was best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Saunders recommended our program highly to (high school
phenom) Al Harrington,'' Cremins said. ``Kevin Morris attended
several of our games last season and we talked a couple of times.
Juan Gaston is a great kid. I can't wait for college coaches to
call me about Travis Spivey. I hope Saunders does great at Seton
Hall. I hope Kevin Morris helps Lefty's program.''
</P>
<P>
   Braine has not put Cremins on any kind of warning, but said, ``I
do think this is a very important year. (But) it's not a demand.
I'm not telling him he has to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins is upbeat about next season, despite the loss of
four-year seniors Matt Harpring and Michael Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   ''This past year was really important to me,'' he said about
Tech's 19-14 finish _ a turnaround from the 9-18 disaster of the
season before. ''Two years ago, we were not a good basketball
program. I was upset by the lack of chemistry. I saw a lot coming
back this past year. We played four freshmen and were one win away
from the NCAAs and got to the third round of the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
