A4793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-SWIM-COX     07-14 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-SWIM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swimmer a big fish in an unusual pond
 &HT;    By Jon Gallo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Six years ago, Bobby Brewer heard his swimming career
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the word around the pool - that I was done, that I
was finished,'' he said. ``I was 18 years old and just out of high
school and people were laughing at me. I had college coaches
mailing me letters saying I had just made the worst decision of my
entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer hadn't done anything wrong while swimming at Morrow High
School, except for being the nation's top backstroker and a
four-time All-America selection. He was bombarded by phone calls
from the nation's top collegiate programs, followed by on-campus
trips. He was a swimmer every coach wanted, one who could make a
top program into a champion.
</P>
<P>
   Then Brewer did the unthinkable, something no state swimmer with
his acclaim had done before. He signed with the University of
Georgia, joining a Bulldog team that hadn't finished higher than
26th at NCAAs in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is without question the most important signee this program
has ever had,'' Georgia head coach Jack Bauerle said of Brewer, who
competes in the upcoming Goodwill Games. ``He showed everyone that
great swimmers come to our program. I can't imagine how much
confidence that must have took for him to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   After visiting some of the nation's premier programs, such as
Southern California, Texas, Arizona and Florida, Brewer decided
that his future looked brightest closest to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go to a place where I was going to be just
another superstar,'' said Brewer, who still holds 17 state high
school records. ``I wanted to go to a place where I could build a
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer promptly laid a new foundation at Georgia, as the
Bulldogs placed 15th and 16th at the '93 and '94 NCAA
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made an immediate impact,'' Bauerle said. ``He came in here
and gave us credibility when we didn't have it. He got us going in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, everything Brewer built crumbled. Heading into his junior
year, he ruptured a disk in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating more than anything else, like everything I
had worked for since I started swimming when I was 7 years old was
gone, `` Brewer said of his injury that led to a medical red-shirt
and 1995 and a relapse that forced him out of the pool for nearly a
month during 1996, which he had taken off to train for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer finished ninth at the Olympic Trials and watched the
Atlanta Games from his home. For a swimmer who in 1993 was ranked
eighth in the world, coping with failure was something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about quitting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't, and he helped lead Georgia to a school-record
third place at the 1997 NCAAs, followed by a seventh-place showing
this year. He then graduated with a degree in psychology, after
earning five All-American honors and 11 All-American honorable
mentions in the backstroke, distinctions he earned swimming
backstroke both individually and on Georgia's medley relay teams.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Brewer won the 100-meter backstroke at the college
Senior Nationals to clinch a spot on the Goodwill Games team, where
he will swim in the same event and a leg in the 400-medley relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years have definitely proven those who doubted me
when I came to Georgia wrong,'' he said, with a soft chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   No one is laughing at Brewer anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
