<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-REGISTRY-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS PROFESSIONAL REGISTRY GOES ON   LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Want to check out your electrician? Make sure your real
estate agent is properly licensed? Or perhaps find out whether your
hairdresser has been disciplined?
</P>
<P>
   State officials Tuesday unveiled a new $320,000 web site that
should provide an easy way for consumers to gain basic information
about the 590,000 professionals licensed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the future people will look back and see this as
one of the pivotal points in government opening up to the public,''
said Daniel A. Grabauskas, the state's director of consumer
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The site's address is www.state.ma.us/reg. State officials said
the site will allow licensees to interact with the boards that
regulate them and let consumers learn more about the people they
hire in a cost-effective manner.
</P>
<P>
   The information available to consumers is fairly basic. For
example, someone looking for an electrician can search by county or
town for a list of electricians in that area. The consumer can then
select a licensee and find out what type of license he or she
holds, whether that license is expired or active, and whether any
disciplinary actions have been taken against the licensee in the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 of the 45 professions regulated by the Division of
Registration _ including nurses, dentists, plumbers, pharmacists,
social workers, real estate agents, and marriage therapists _ the
web site also offers consumers tips on getting the most for their
money.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing a funeral director, for example, consumers are urged
to shop around because prices can vary widely. The tips also tell
consumers that state and federal law requires funeral directors to
provide an itemized price list and that Massachusetts now allows
consumers to rent rather than buy a casket.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Registration's web site also offers links to other
state web sites that provide information on doctors and home
improvement contractors, as well as consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   Those without access to computers can obtain the same
information, but they will have to call or visit the board offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
