<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
 
Mocha Express wins Lone Star's big award 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mocha Express seemed to be on a downhill slide when the season
at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie began two months ago. The
4-year-old racehorse had shown promise but started the year by
finishing no better than fifth in three races in Arkansas and
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Tim Harder had to lower his expectations. He simply
hoped the colt would fit in alongside the stakes horses at Grand
Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   But Mocha Express not only fit in, he dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Mocha Express was named Lone Star's horse of the
meeting for the thoroughbred season that concludes Sunday. He also
was named the meet's champion older horse and would have been
champion Texas-bred, too, if that category existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe he might have been in the running for it after
his last race,'' said Harder, who trains Mocha Express for his
father, Roger, and for Don Strate, both of Spokane, Wash. ``But I
never would have figured on it at the beginning of the meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Express clinched the awards by stepping out of the
Texas-bred ranks and whipping unrestricted company July 4 in the
Lone Star Park Handicap. Among his victims was Anet, last year's
horse of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Express also won the Assault Stakes for state-breds and a
grass allowance race and was second in the Premiere Stakes and
Crescent Stakes. He bankrolled $200,000 in purses at the meet, more
than he had accumulated in his 14 previous starts.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of six other divisional titles also were released
yesterday after voting by the media and the track's racing office
and publicity department.
</P>
<P>
   Yaqthan took honors in the turf horse category. Smolderin Heart
and Cinemine were voted the top 3-year-old and 3-year-old filly,
respectively, with Arctica an easy winner among older mares.
Spiritbound was the champion sprinter, and Vagabond Shoes was
champion claimer.
</P>
<P>
   Voting on the top 2-year-old and 2-year-old filly will be
conducted Sunday, enabling results of Saturday's Silver Spur Stakes
and Sunday's Middleground Stakes to be factored in.
</P>
<P>
   Yaqathan and Smolderin Heart each made one appearance at Lone
Star but made it count. Yaqthan came from Kentucky to win the May
25 Dallas Turf Cup, and Smolderin Heart arrived straight from
Arkansas to take the April 19 Lone Star Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Cinemine and Arctica were two-time stakes winners at the
meeting, Spiritbound won a grass sprint stakes and twice ran six
furlongs on dirt in 1:09 3-5, and Vagabond Shoes goes today for her
fourth victory of the meet.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, their seasons don't end with Lone Star's
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Express is scheduled to leave on a July 23 flight to
Seattle by way of Dayton, Ohio, to compete at Washington's Emerald
Downs in the Aug. 23 Longacres Mile. That traditional event was
once the signature race of the historic Longacres track, which was
torn down several years ago to make way for a Boeing plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race is a big deal up there,'' Harder said. ``Down here,
they don't really have a big race that's full of tradition, because
they've only been running a couple of years. Up there, Longacres
ran for a long time, and it was a really beautiful track. The race
is a remnant of Longacres, and it's got a long tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea what kind of horses they'll have up
there. I would think he'll fit in pretty good with the local
horses, but they usually send two or three from California. Usually
it's a pretty tough race.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it also kind of kills two birds with one stone. The owners
want to see him run close to home, and we needed to find some kind
of race anyway. This one just fits into the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, schedules have a way of changing at a moment's notice
when horses are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Mocha Express hardly looked like a candidate for
a cross-country trip, but look at him now.
Suspension begins
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Corey Lanerie will begin tomorrow serving a seven-day
suspension for careless riding.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension imposed by Lone Star stewards stems from the
spill in Saturday's Allen Bogan Memorial. Lanerie rode Desert Air,
who drifted into the path of odds-on favorite Smiling Time on the
backstretch and caused him to clip heels and stumble, unseating
jockey Eric Perner.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Air finished first, but was disqualified to third in the
four-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the suspension, Lanerie could still see action at Lone
Star this weekend under the state's ``designated stakes'' rule.
Because his careless-riding suspension is less than 10 days, he
qualifies under the rule to accept mounts at Lone Star on Saturday
and Sunday, but only if he is named at time of entry to ride horses
in stakes races on those days.
</P>
<P>
   Lanerie's suspension is scheduled to run through July 22. But if
he rides Saturday and Sunday, for example, his suspension will then
be extended to July 24.
A possibility
</P>
<P>
   Arlington International owner Dick Duchossois is floating a few
trial balloons to test the legislative waters for a possible
reopening of his suburban Chicago track in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Duchossois still insists the $200 million racing palace, which
was closed this summer, needs help from the state if it is to
reopen and compete with riverboat casinos legalized in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers ignored his pleas a year ago, but Duchossois might
have a new bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   An auto racing track is being built to coexist with the horse
track at Sportsman's Park in Cicero, which absorbed Arlington's
traditional summer dates along with next-door neighbor Hawthorne
Race Course in Stickney. Because of the construction, Sportsman's
might not be ready to hold a horse meeting next year. And that
makes the return of Arlington even more vital to the Illinois
thoroughbred industry.
</P>
<P>
   But that road must first go through Duchossois, who isn't an
easy man to please.
A yen for horses
</P>
<P>
   The economy of Japan might be in the tank, but plenty of yen are
still available for a good Sunday Silence colt.
</P>
<P>
   Former American champion Sunday Silence is now the champion sire
in Japan, and at an auction there yesterday, one of his colts sold
for $1.35 million, and a filly went for $1.28 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's big money, indeed, but it still sounds more impressive to
say 190 million yen.
Calling the shots
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar has boosted the purse of its July 25 San Diego Handicap
to assure the presence of Silver Charm. It had been a $150,000
race. Now the purse will be $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   That change came a week after Monmouth Park allowed Sonny Hine,
trainer of Skip Away, to name his purse and distance for the Aug.
30 Iselin Handicap. Hine chose to double the purse to $500,000 and
increase the distance from 1 1/16 miles to 1 1/8 miles. If Hine had
asked for a head start, it might have been granted, although Skip
Away doesn't need one.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Will horse owners hire agents to negotiate with
racetracks?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
