<SLUG> BC-NAACP-POWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL RAISES CAUTION FLAG ON AFFIRMATIVE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He was a conservative Republican in a stridently
liberal gathering, a black leader who Tuesday confessed to the
national convention of the NAACP -- the nation's most enduringly
important minority organization -- that he was missing in action
for the great civil rights battles of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Colin Powell conquered.
</P>
<P>
   The retired Army general was showered with adulation by 3,500
delegates, even as he raised a caution flag on affirmative action.
Powell, striking a moderate note at a gathering in which rhetoric
has trended to the militant, said he sees a continuing need for
race-based programs, but believes such policies will never bear
fruit unless steps are taken first to buttress home life and the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice is simple: Either getting back to the task of
building all children or just keep building more jails,'' Powell
said, in a speech that had moved some in the crowd to wish he would
rethink his reluctance to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no point in creating (affirmative action)
opportunities if we bring up children who can't use the English
language. If this generation of youth don't take advantage of those
opportunities, what's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's was an artful blend of support for social programs
backed by Democrats and family values ordinarily underscored by
Republicans. By turns personal and topical, it seemed to fall
somewhere between a testimonial and a campaign stump speech _ and
to judge by the three standing ovations he received, it proved
effective on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he thought America should take pride in its racial
progress, having done what ``no other country on the face of the
earth has done.'' On the other hand he made it clear he understands
the pain of racism and the need for continuing remedies to address
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need,'' he said, ``to keep affirmative action to compensate
for almost 300 years of preferences that were directed against
us.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, speaking of his upbringing in Harlem and the South
Bronx, Powell said of himself: ``He knew he was black and he had
everything in his life to remind him of it, and to remind him of
what being black meant in America. ... He knew there were places he
couldn't go, he thought there were dreams that he dare not dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, he said, ``I can't say that we have overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   He voiced regret at not having been on the front lines of the
civil rights struggle, in what he called the ``great battles of the
South.'' But he said he fully identifies with the struggle for
racial equality today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not just a struggle for the NAACP or for African
Americans alone, this is a struggle for all of America to rid
ourselves of the legacy of the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff now serves as
the head of America's Promise, a volunteer organization that offers
mentoring and other programs to youth. Powell linked the work it is
doing to uplift young people to the opportunities that could lie
ahead should affirmative action remain in place.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's speech, coming on the fourth-day of the NAACP
convention, which ends Thursday, gave some attendees the first real
chance to get a feel for a man who has in some measure remained a
mystery to them.
</P>
<P>
   Many black Americans have viewed Powell with a detached
skepticism since he declared himself a Republican in 1996 _ after
resisting the temptation to run for president _ because they
associate him with the party of House Speaker Newt Gingrich, North
Carolina Senator Jesse Helms and a Congress that has sought to
rollback affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I heard the man speak and saw him up close, I just
thought he was another black Republican,'' said Tempthia Battle,
president of the NAACP's South Middlesex, Mass. branch. I didn't
want any part of him.''
</P>
<P>
   But, after Powell ``related his life experiences, I could relate
to him so much better. It was a powerful experience for me,''
Battle said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Moore, a Miami airline ticket agent attending the
convention, said also had praise for Powell. ``He has not forgotten
what he stands for as an African American. He's not taken on the
total view of the Republican party; he has his own identity,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deloris Roach, an assistant coordinator of a minority program
for the Veteran's Administration in Cleveland, said she thought
Powell was ``courageous'' for admitting in front of the group that
he was AWOL during the civil rights struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But were he ever to run for president, her vote would be hard to
get. ``Even though he's black, he's still a Republican. I don't
think I'd go for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, for his part, made no suggestion at all that he was
seeking potential votes with his speech. He is, however, in the the
market for new voters _ saying that showing up on election day is
crucial to the future of minority America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vote Democrat, vote Republican, split your ticket but just
vote so your voice will be heard,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
