<P>
   WHEAT-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ Congress finalizes action to
exempt wheat sales from sanctions imposed against Pakistan for
testing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-MISSILE (Seattle) _ Even with more than $4 billion poured
into development, it is unlikely that the Pentagon will be able to
build a rudimentary defense against ballistic missiles targeted at
America in the next five years, according to a report by the
General Accounting Office. The missile defense system is being
managed by The Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle Mariners host Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-NICKLAUS (Undated) _ When the British Open tees off
Thursday, Jack Nicklaus will be nowhere in sight. For the first
time since 1957, Nicklaus will not be in a major. A perspective
piece on golf's greatest player and his amazing streak.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-THIEL-COLUMN (Southport, England) _ A spot of bother. A
bloody shame, too. Upon the eve of one of England's most revered
athletic tournaments, the Open (not the British Open, mind you;
it's the Open, and only ninnies from America call it anything
else), British athletes have had some lamentable times lately on
the playing fields, be it Eton or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS (Seattle) _ Under new owner Paul Allen, the
Seahawks are redefining the way they do business, and becoming
pacesetters in the NFL. This is intended to be a big-picture story
connecting a lot of dots made by staff additions over the past year
and the launching of the league's biggest marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
