<SLUG> BC-BABIES-R-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS `R' US PINS HOPES ON BABY STORE CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Charles Lazarus launched Toys ``R'' Us Inc. in 1948, most
toys were sold in mom-and-pop stores crammed with yo-yos and
Lincoln Logs. No one had ever heard of a ``supermarket for toys,''
Lazarus' concept for so-called big-box toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, the Toys ``R'' Us chain, based in Paramus, N.J.,
dominated the toy landscape. It bought toys by the boat load, and
unable to match Toys ``R'' Us on price, many small toy chains and
independently owned stores went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   But retail abhors a vacuum, and in the 1990s, giant discounters
and warehouse clubs began expanding their toy departments to fill
the void left by failed mom-and-pops.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a company that had become the country's largest toy
retailer by underselling its smaller competitors, now finds itself
up against some of the largest and shrewdest retailers in the
world, including Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Target, which have been
eating away at the dominant market share Toys ``R'' Us has long
enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to get back into Wall Street's good graces, Toys ``R''
Us is now attempting to reinvent itself by branching out beyond Ken
and Barbie dolls.
</P>
<P>
   As it struggles to become more profitable, the company is
seeking to do for baby products what it started out doing for toys.
In a new chain called Babies ``R'' Us, the company is gambling part
of its future on big-box stores that aim to provide one-stop
shopping for parents of infants and toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies ``R'' Us is an integral part of our long-term
strategy,'' said Robert C. Nakasone, who recently took over as
chief executive of Toys ``R'' Us Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical Toys ``R'' Us store, the shelves are piled high
with G.I. Joes, Monopoly games, and Sing &AMP; Snore Ernies.
</P>
<P>
   In a Babies ``R'' Us, shoppers find a similar variety of cribs,
high chairs, rocking-chairs, and breast pumps for new mothers. Need
diapers? Or pajamas for a preemie (an infant who weighs less than
six pounds)? Babies ``R'' Us has these items too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 80 kinds of strollers,'' said vice president David
Schoenbeck, who attended last week's opening of a Babies ``R'' Us
in Peabody, Mass., the 100th store in the chain and the second in
Massachusetts. The other store opened last year in Braintree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to buy a gift for a baby shower, this is the place
to go,'' Schoenbeck says.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that there's another baby boom that Toys ``R'' Us is
trying to exploit _ the US birth rate is roughly flat _ it's just
that competition isn't as intense in the baby products category as
it is in the toy business, Wall Street analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   While many retailers sell cribs, strollers, and clothing for
infants, no one seems to offer the breadth of selection that Babies
``R'' Us does in one superstore format, said retail analyst Walter
F. Loeb of Loeb Associates, who added, ``Babies ``R'' Us has a
``niche to themselves for the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chain has its roots in an acquisition that Toys ``R'' Us
made last year. After it bought a 77-store operation called Baby
Superstore for $376 million, the chain's name was changed to Babies
``R'' Us. Plans call for the chain to grow by about 20 new stores
annually for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, Toys ``R'' Us used the promise of free
diapers and baby formula to lure customers into its toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Babies ``R'' Us, the company has the opportunity to
hold onto parents as customers from the first trimester of mother's
pregnancy until her youngest child turns 13.
</P>
<P>
   Under this theory, parents will buy many of the things they need
for their infants and toddlers at Babies ``R'' Us. When a child
turns three, he or she is a ready-made customer for Kids ``R'' Us,
the company's chain of 218 clothing stores, and Toys ``R'' Us, its
worldwide chain of about 1,100 toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby ``R'' Us is our handshake with the customer, our
springboard to get them into Toys ``R'' Us and Kids ``R'' Us when
their children get older,'' Nakasone said.
</P>
<P>
   Although its balance sheet remains strong _ profits jumped from
$427 million to $490 million for its most recent fiscal year, a
company with just over $11 billion in annual sales could certainly
use a springboard.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the same month that a research firm called the NPD Group
reported that Toys ``R'' Us had lost some of its US toy marketshare
to Wal-Mart and Target, the company said that its first quarter
earnings had fallen 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And since the beginning of the year, Toys ``R'' Us has watched
the price of its stock shares fall from about 30 to 22.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday shares were up 3/8 on the New York Stock Exchange to
close at 23.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Toys ``R'' Us has taken a number of steps to preserve
its pre-eminence. Since becoming chief executive, Nakasone has
hired several new managers, and Toys ``R'' Us recently launched a
web site to sell toys over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, it revamped its inventory practices, a move
that resulted in its placing smaller orders with toy makers such as
Mattel Inc. and Hasbro Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mattel and Hasbro cited those smaller orders as a reason
for lower-than-expected quarterly earnings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, such changes will allow Toys ``R'' Us to compete more
effectively against the likes of Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us remains a formidable competitor _ too formidable
for some. According to the the Federal Trade Commission, Toys ``R''
Us has unfairly pressured toy makers to keep their most popular
toys out of the stores of rival retailers looking to grab a bigger
piece of the toy business.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC won an early round of that legal battle. Toys ``R'' Us,
which denies the FTC's charges, has appealed the decision. A ruling
on the appeal could come any day.
</P>
<P>
   As Toys ``R'' Us looks ahead, it has concluded that its old
formula for success needs to be fine-tuned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current vision of the company as the `pre-eminent
worldwide retailer of toys and juvenile products' is quite narrow
and no longer consistent with how our business is evolving,''
Nakasone wrote in the company's annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Nakasone sees Babies ``R'' Us as a part of this evolution.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for the new chain to give an immediate boost to
company earnings, said analyst Sally H. Wallick of Legg Mason Wood
Walker. Because Babies ``R'' Us represent only about 7 percent of
the company's total of nearly 1,500 stores, the company will
continue to depend on toy sales in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long haul, however, Nakasone believes that Babies ``R''
Us will be an important part of a strategy to reposition Toys ``R''
Us Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the worldwide authority on kids, family, and
fun,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
