<SLUG> BC-GM-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM SUES TO HALT UAW STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raising the stakes in the bitter six-week strike that has
crippled General Motors production nationwide, the company filed
suit Tuesday against the United Auto Workers union, asking a
federal judge to declare the walkout illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in US District Court in Detroit is a sign that
GM is desperate to end the strike, which has paralyzed 26 of 29
assembly plants and cost millions more than the company had
expected, analysts said. Second-quarter earnings released Tuesday
painted a dark picture for GM, whose profits and cash reserves
plummetted, largely because of losses sustained during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   But determined not to give in to the union, GM is escalating the
fight rather than backing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing hard ball. It's bare knuckles now,'' said John
Stamm, a labor relations expert at Babson College. ``What it really
shows is that the company wants this strike to end.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks an injunction ordering striking autoworkers at
two key parts plants in Flint, Mich., back to work. It also asks
for unspecified punitive damages against the UAW for violating
terms of a 1996 agreement with GM laying out conditions under which
the union could legally declare a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Since Flint workers walked out in early June, citing ``health
and safety'' issues, it has been an open secret that the strike is
really about larger issues, namely GM's drive to cut costs by
speeding up production, slashing jobs and replacing expensive
American plants with cheaper ones in countries like Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strike is not about health and safety, it's about where
GM puts its investment,'' Stamm said.
</P>
<P>
   But according to terms of the 1996 agreement, the union is
prohibited from striking over such matters as plant location.
Observers said that workers in Flint walked out under the guise of
health and safety problems, halting supplies to other assembly
plants and bringing GM's North American production to its knees. So
far, GM says it has canceled production on more than 227,000
vehicles and been forced to lay off 161,000 workers. The total cost
to GM now exceeds $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The bleeding was evident Tuesday in GM's quarterly earnings
report, which showed second-period profits fell to $433 million, or
59 cents a diluted share. By contrast, earning were $1.58 billion,
or $2.14 a share, for the same period in 1997. &UR;  &LR; Cash reserves fell
to $9.1 billion from $13.6 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   While earnings were slightly better than expected, prompting
GM's shares to rise 1 1/2 Tuesday to 70 3/8, analysts said the
strike's effect on GM's cash reserves is higher than anticipated,
possibly prompting the company's decision to file the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're now in a pretty weak cash position,'' said Nicholas,
Lobacarro, an analyst for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's filing comes after marathon talks over the weekend
failed to produce a resolution, something GM management said it
badly wanted. By Monday, GM vice president Donald Hackworth said
``it is very difficult to see how all this will be brought to an
end.''
</P>
<P>
   In a taped message on the status of talks, signs of conciliation
_ such as an earlier vow not cut medical benefits to striking
workers _ had disappeared. ``We will continue to pursue all options
to put an end to this strike and all other potential strikes,''
Hackworth said in the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our long-term viability is on the line. ... For that very
reason, we must take a firm stand today.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harder line, however, the lawsuit may not gain much
ground for the company, Babson College's Stamm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the court is going to kick it right back to them and
say fight it out yourselves,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
