u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITY-MARKET-2TAKES     07-14 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-MARKET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURMOIL IN ELECTRIC POWER TRADING SHOWS DEREGULATION'S
UNCERTAINTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Ky., Kan., Texas, Ohio)   (bl)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Paul McCoy watched a monitor displaying wholesale electricity
prices, he could not believe his eyes. Hour after hour, McCoy, a
senior vice president at Commonwealth Edison Co., the utility that
serves Chicago, saw prices surging to levels never seen before,
peaking at about 100 times normal.
</P>
<P>
   He faced a stark choice: Either black out areas of Chicago to
conserve power during a severe heat wave, just as storms had
knocked out some plants and key transmission lines in the Midwest,
or buy extra power at sky-high prices.
</P>
<P>
   He kept buying, in a single hour on June 25 spending about $4
million for power that would normally cost about $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not much of a choice,'' he said in an interview last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented price surge, which lasted two days, made it
clear that the volatile new market ushered in by utility
deregulation could bring some nasty surprises.
</P>
<P>
   For McCoy was far from alone, as many Midwest utilities were
caught in the same squeeze. Still other utilities, though, found
themselves with surplus power and sold it at huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   Enron, the nation's biggest trader of electricity, capitalized
on the shortages by selling large amounts of power to utilities at
high prices.
</P>
<P>
   Enron Capital &AMP; Trade Resources, the trading subsidiary,
reported a doubling of revenue in the second quarter, to $5.86
billion, and an 85 percent rise in income, to $241 million.
</P>
<P>
   Enron president Jeffrey Skilling said the company had strict
credit rules for the companies it trades with. ``We had no
transactions at risk with any of the marketers who have gone broke
or not performed on their contracts,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   This was all a marked contrast with the old days, when utilities
sold power to one another at reasonable prices during emergencies,
and it provides a vivid glimpse of the challenges facing this
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day price run-up also left a legacy of concerns about
the reliability of the wholesale markets. Since the events of last
month, the trading of power on Midwest markets has fallen
considerably, as utilities and others take more care in checking
the reliability and credit of power marketers.
</P>
<P>
   There have even been calls for investigations. And one utility
has called for price caps during emergencies, which existed in the
days of strict regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Some big industrial customers who had their power interrupted
have raised the issue of whether some utilities and marketers held
back power deliberately to make prices soar.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil has also added to the uncertainty of owning utility
stocks. A number of utilities, including First Energy of Akron,
Ohio, and Illinova of Decatur, Ill., said the added costs would
depress their earnings. In most cases, they cannot pass them on to
consumers, as they could under deregulation. Illinova even said
last week that it might have to cut its dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make it more risky for investors,'' said Barry
Abramson, a utility analyst for Paine Webber, ``especially for the
utilities that are short on capacity going into seasons of extreme
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Since electricity cannot be stored, peak demand must often be
met by getting surplus power from other regions. And the place
utilities must turn to to get extra power, the wholesale market,
has changed greatly since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which
oversees the industry, ordered utilities to open up their
transmission lines to competitors. Since then, hundreds of
companies that generate no electricity of their own have entered
the fray, and the trading in contracts has grown rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   During those two days in June, though, two companies did not
deliver the power they had contracted for. This failure, coming at
a critical time, added to the uncertainty and, some experts say,
was one of the main reasons prices surged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities were forced to scramble to cover those contracts,''
said Kenneth Gustafson, a vice president of Bankers Trust Corp. who
advises utilities on risk management and energy markets. ``That was
something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Most industry executives and experts stressed, however, that
even though prices surged, in the end the system worked. Enough
power became available on the wholesale market to enable all the
utilities to avoid blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   But they added that because new capacity has not been built to
keep up with demand in areas like the Midwest and the Northeast,
future peaks in demand could strain the wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives and analysts described the problems in
June as the growing pains of an industry adjusting to deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Strobel, vice president and general counsel of Unicom
Corp., the holding company for Commonwealth Edison, said the
utility's problems were ``a natural outgrowth of a developing
market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to expect that on a rough-and-tumble day like June
25, you're going to have some marketers that will fail,'' she said.
``They were not ready to play in that kind of market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of Las Vegas in this new world,'' she
added. ``When you sit down and make a bet, you don't get to change
your cards. You have to be more careful and sophisticated than
utilities have been in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hanson, a manager at Metzler &AMP; Associates, a consulting
firm based in Deerfield, Ill., who has watched how deregulation has
affected utilities, said: ``It was a brotherhood of monopolies;
your neighbor really wasn't a threat to you.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
