<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITY-MARKET-2NDTAK     07-14 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-MARKET-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to you.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month demonstrated how much the brotherhood has dissolved.
Some traders said that it appeared that utilities put power up for
sale only when prices peaked.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson, however, said the weaknesses of the system will correct
themselves in time and that marketers that cannot deliver will be
forced out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cracked in a few places,'' Hanson said. ``But the whole
system really did not fail.''
</P>
<P>
   And the price surge, he said, could help stimulate independent
power producers to build new plants. This would help to ease the
supply problems in the Midwest, where demand for electricity has
been robust.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Brown, director of public relations for the Electric Power
Supply Association, a trade group for independent producers, said
several were actively looking to build plants in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that they were being cautious since the rules
that govern the wholesale market were evolving and there was
concern whether they could get their investment back. A new
gas-fired turbine plant costs about $100 million to build.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities have been reluctant to build new capacity, since many
plan to spin off generating plants to enable them to survive better
when their states open up to full competition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some executives are uneasy, for no one is quite sure how
various market forces conspired to make prices surge.
</P>
<P>
   Four utilities _ Cinergy, based in Plainfield, Ind., Dynegy, in
Houston, NP Energy Inc., in Louisville, Ky., and Western Resources,
in Topeka, Kansas _ have filed a petition with the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission, which oversees the industry, asking that it
hold a hearing on what happened. The Public Utility Commission of
Ohio also plans an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit was filed by FirstEnergy, a utility holding company in
Ohio, against Federal Energy Sales Inc., a power marketer in Rocky
River, Ohio, that failed to deliver the power it had contracted
for. First Energy is claiming $25 million in damages since it was
forced to buy extra power.
</P>
<P>
   A vivid example of the utilities' new world was recalled by
McCoy, who is in charge of transmission and operations at
Commonwealth Edison.
</P>
<P>
   Like most utilities in the Midwest on June 25, he was preparing
for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   A heat wave was moving across the region, causing a surge in
demand for electricity. Violent storms had knocked out key
transmission lines and a nuclear plant in Ohio, causing further
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he felt he was well prepared, having contracted for power
months ahead in the wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the morning his backup plans began to unravel.
American Electric Power, a subsidiary of AEP Corp., one of the
largest utilities in the Midwest, notified Commonwealth Edison that
it would not deliver 1,300 megawatts it had promised, saying it
needed the capacity on its vast transmission network to cope with a
surge in demand in its own area.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth Edison, along with other utilities, began to cut
back power to some large industrial customers and asked its 3.2
million residential customers to turn off air-conditioners and
other appliances. It also warned that it might even have to black
out some areas for two hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that McCoy turned to the monitor on his desk on the
37th floor of an office tower in the Chicago Loop to see what was
available on the wholesale market, watching prices soar from an
average of $50 a megawatt hour to a peak of about $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not sure what happened that day,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
