<HEADLINE>
WOODS WARMS UP AT BALLYBUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Tiger Woods got a taste of Ireland on the
way to the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cowan, his celebrated caddie, had played there following
the Masters with a group of friends and steered his boss in that
direction. Woods played the Old Course at Ballybunion, Waterville,
and the K Club with his neighbor, Masters champion Mark O'Meara,
and Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was in contention at last month's US Open until the
final hole, had a hole-in-one on the third at Ballybunion, and
overall, it was a relaxing interlude before the start of the 127th
British Open tomorrow at Royal Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   Woods spent a lot of time in O'Meara's company. ``We went
fishing and just had a good time relaxing,'' said Woods Tuesday.
``I found Ballybunion very interesting. It's one of those courses
you have to play enough to know where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods played well through most of the British Open last year at
Royal Troon, but a quadruple bogey and a couple of triple bogeys
removed him from contention. ``I learned a few things,'' he said.
``I wasn't swinging very well going into the championship and
struggled, hit a lot of bad shots. This year I've changed my
preparation a little bit, worked more on my swing and tried to get
my plane better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think overall, my game is better. I am flighting the ball
better than I was at this time last year. I think overall, the ball
flight has improved and my bad shots aren't that bad. I'm not
hitting it two fairways over and stuff like that. I think overall,
my game is better, and it is really neat to see. Unfortunately, you
don't get the breaks sometimes and win. I've been right there. I've
had a lot of top fives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
