<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATCHMAKER-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MATCHMAKER': PARODY BECOMES A TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review) 
(JT) 
 By PETER MARKS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ It is all but impossible nowadays to watch
``The Matchmaker'' and not feel a song coming on. The instant
Cornelius Hackl announces to his young assistant, ``Get into your
Sunday clothes, Barnaby!'' your head fills with images of Gower
Champion's beaming chorus in fancy duds high-stepping its way past
the Yonkers train station and singing, ``Get out your feathers,
your patent leathers, your beads and buckles and bows.''
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Hello, Dolly!,'' of course, there was the play it was
based on, Thornton Wilder's winsome, all-American farce revolving
around the businesslike romantic schemes of Dolly Gallagher Levi, a
pragmatic yenta with designs on the gruff feed merchant, Horace
Vandergelder. And while the Williamstown Theater Festival tries
hard to cast aside memories of the juggernaut 1964 musical, one
senses in this somewhat enervating revival, directed by Nicholas
Martin and featuring Andrea Martin in the marquee role, the need
for a zesty number or two to perk things up.
</P>
<P>
   The production tries to recapture the dulcet innocence of
Wilder's vision of the 1880s with a new score of incidental, period
music by Mark Bennett, but the earnest effort does not camouflage
the problems the cast has in enlivening the comedy or in achieving
a coherent style of performance. The madcap events in the Harmonia
Gardens restaurant, for instance, are staged with no particular
flair for the coincidence and slapstick of farce; only Ms. Martin's
handling of the ladling of food for Horace (Lewis Stadlen) places
any dexterous physical comedy on display.
</P>
<P>
   Two supporting actors, though, do make beguiling impressions:
Kate Burton as a vivacious and hopeful Irene Molloy, the New York
hat shop owner desperate for security, and the reliably theatrical
Marian Seldes in an agreeably dizzy turn as a confused dowager so
out of it she hums to herself in crowded rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from them, however, most of the cast members appear only
to be in the preliminary stages of figuring out their characters.
As a result, there is a wanness about the production that tends to
render the plot mechanics as even more labored and transparent than
they seem on the page. Wilder himself seems to have had his tongue
firmly in his cheek when he wrote ``The Matchmaker'': ``This play
parodies the stock-company plays that I used to see at Ye Liberty
Theater, Oakland, Calif., when I was a boy,'' he once wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The director takes an opposing tack, declaring in the program
notes that his production is intended as ``a tribute to the summer
theaters and music halls of the past.'' But this sepia-toned
approach tends to bathe ``The Matchmaker'' in more nostalgia that
it can currently bear.
</P>
<P>
   As she has demonstrated in shows as diverse as the musical ``My
Favorite Year,'' for which she won a Tony Award, and the New York
Shakespeare Festival's ``Merry Wives of Windsor,'' Ms. Martin can
be a galvanic comic stage presence. Like Martin Short, one of her
former co-stars on SCTV, the brilliant television parody show,
she's at once utterly wacky and totally disciplined: there is the
sense about her of a wild wit tamed through the miracles of
pharmacology.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy period costumes, including bustles, seem to weigh her
down. Her Dolly is enjoyable but never endearing; she resorts in
desperate moments to familiar bits of shtick, as when she bellows a
reply, Ethel Merman-style. You never really believe that this is a
woman at a crossroads in her life, a woman who comes to an
understanding that she requires more from Horace than his bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   Stadlen delivers a Vandergelder who could be a cousin to his
Senex, the henpecked old goat of ``A Funny Thing Happened on the
Way to the Forum.'' He's the curmudgeonly butt of the joke again,
only this time, without the musical breaks in the action to add
some warmth. Yup, what this Horace needs is a song.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE MATCHMAKER'
</P>
<P>
   By Thornton Wilder; directed by Nicholas Martin; set by James
Noone; costumes by Michael Krass; lighting by Kenneth Posner;
composer, Mark Bennett; sound by Kurt Kellenberger; stage manager,
Kelley Kirkpatrick; production manager, James D'Asaro. Presented by
the Williamstown Theater Festival, Michael Ritchie, producer;
Deborah Fehr, general manager; Jenny Gersten, associate producer.
At Williamstown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Lewis Stadlen (Horance Vandergelder), Adam Trese
(Cornelius Hackl), Adrienne Gould (Ermengarde), MichaelJohn McGann
(Malachi Stack), Andrea Martin (Mrs. Levi), Christopher Fitzgerald
(Barnaby Tucker), Kate Burton (Mrs. Molloy), Katie MacNichol
(Minnie Fay) and Marian Seldes (Miss Flora Van Huysen).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
