<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TRUANCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUANCY RATE CONTINUES TO RISE IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ More than a quarter of Boston Public School students
were absent three weeks or more this past school year, a number
that continues to inch up despite efforts to crack down on the
city's massive truancy problem.
</P>
<P>
   Boston high schoolers already have one of the highest rates of
absenteeism in the country, and statistics provided to the Globe
Tuesday indicate the problem is growing worse: Chronic absenteeism
increased at almost every single high school in the city this year
compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston High School, almost 70 percent of students were absent
more than 14 days this past year; almost 50 percent were absent
more than 27 days.
</P>
<P>
   Students are supposed to fail a marking period if they miss more
than 15 percent of school days, and are supposed to fail for the
school year if they fail a majority of marking periods. Schools
have either three or five marking periods.
</P>
<P>
   But school statistics show students are routinely allowed to
advance to the next grade even when their absenteeism _ from 15
days to 27 days a year, depending on the number of marking periods
_ should block their promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in September, that should change as the city begins an
intensive effort to cut down on truancy, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a strict new promotion policy, students will only be
allowed 3 unexcused absenses a marking period _ or face failure.
The school department has also been meeting with police, state
Department of Youth Services and community officials to enforce the
new policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new student promotion policy takes a hard line on student
attendance because it is such a crucial issue,'' said
Superintendent Thomas Payzant. He said the issue of attendance is
of particular priority now as school officials wrap up two years of
putting reform into place in the city's 127 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students need to be in the classroom for these efforts to have
a full impact,'' Payzant said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, city officials are looking for ways to increase the
number of attendance officers in the school department, City
Councilor at Large Stephen Murphy said Tuesday. Now are there are
eight attendance officers for the city's 64,000 students. Police
cars will also be dedicated to curb truancy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Statewide, a bill is pending in the Senate to give teenagers a
driving license only if their school attendance is satisfactory;
another pending bill will give police officers the right to bring
truants back to school, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Boston high school students miss 28 days of school a
year, four days more than the average of the country's ten largest
cities, according to a report for the Boston schools by Bain &AMP;
Company, a Boston consulting firm. Yet Boston is the country's 22d
largest city.
</P>
<P>
   If Boston's new strict attendance policy is enforced, it will be
one of the country's strictest. Chicago, which just instituted a
strict new promotion policy three years ago, allows students to
have 20 unexcused absences a year. School officials there Tuesday
said the policy is strictly enforced, but were unable to provide
numbers of students specifically held back because of unexcused
absences.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's truancy problem has been exacerbated in recent years by
many high schools' policies of locking out tardy students for the
day if they are more than 15 or 20 minutes late, some parents and
students say.
</P>
<P>
   Most high schools have automatic phone machines that call a
student's home letting parents know their child is absent. But many
high schoolers simply take the call while their parents are at
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
