<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-SUSPECT-NYT &LR;      07-14 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI DOUBLES SEARCH TEAM AFTER BOMBING SUSPECT SPOTTED IN N.C.
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After five and a half months in hiding, the man wanted
for the fatal bombing of an Alabama abortion clinic emerged from
the woods of western North Carolina last week, took a large amount
of food and a pickup truck from a residence, then abandoned the
truck and vanished once more, federal authorities said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Andrews, N.C., Tuesday afternoon,
federal investigators said that the team of agents pursuing Eric
Robert Rudolph would be more than doubled from its previous size of
35. Bloodhounds also were tracking the fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have the resources that we will find him,'' said
Woody Enderson, the FBI agent who directs the multiagency Southeast
Bombing Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   The sighting last Thursday was clearly the most encouraging lead
in a frustrating search that has taken investigators across
hundreds of miles of mountainous terrain since Jan. 29, when a bomb
exploded outside the New Woman All Women Health Care Center, in
Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing killed an off-duty policeman who was working as a
security guard at the clinic and seriously injured a nurse.
Witnesses saw a man acting suspiciously shortly after the
explosion, and the North Carolina license plate on the man's truck
was traced to Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty significant step forward because we now know
for sure that he's in this area and that we are able to focus in on
a much smaller area than we have before,'' said Enderson.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, a 31-year-old carpenter with ties to extremist
religious groups, also is wanted for questioning in three bombings
in the Atlanta area in 1996 and 1997, including the July 27, 1996,
explosion at Centennial Olympic Park. That explosion killed one
woman and injured 111 people. Seven people were injured in a pair
of explosions on Jan. 27, 1997, outside a building housing an
abortion clinic in the Atlanta suburbs, and five were injured in a
Feb. 21, 1997, bombing at a gay nightclub in midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rudolph has only been formally charged in the
Birmingham bombing, forensic evidence suggests that he may have
been responsible for the Atlanta bombings as well, investigators
have said. In early May, the FBI placed Rudolph on its list of the
10 most wanted fugitives and offered a $1 million reward for
information leading to his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Enderson said that the man identified as Rudolph had appeared on
Thursday evening at a residence near Nantahala Lake, not far from
where Rudolph once lived. He said the fugitive took a blue 1977
Nissan pickup truck from the occupant of the residence, whom he did
not identify. He said Rudolph also took a large amount of food from
the resident, possibly enough to sustain him for five or six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the resident provided a description that
enabled them to produce a new sketch of the previously clean-shaven
Rudolph, showing him thinner, bearded and sporting a ponytail. He
was last seen wearing camouflage fatigues, a camouflage jacket and
gloves, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Enderson declined to say specifically whether the resident knew
Rudolph. ``Keep in mind that pretty much in this whole area, people
know each other,'' he said. ``The extent of the association I'm not
going to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that the resident, who was described as the owner
of a health food store, did not report the truck as stolen until
several days later. It was found, broken down and abandoned, at
about noon on Monday at the Bob Allison Campground, a picnic area
in the Nantahala National Forest, the official said. The official
also said that authorities found a note inside the truck explaining
who it belonged to, and they identified the handwriting as
Rudolph's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that we are dealing with Eric Robert
Rudolph,'' Enderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The law enforcement official said the truck apparently was not
at the picnic area 18 hours before it was found, meaning that
Rudolph has less than a day's head start on his pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   Enderson said that his troops had been energized by the sighting
of Rudolph. And he sounded reassured by the discovery that Rudolph
apparently spent the last five months in the hills of western North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials had long said they assumed that Rudolph, an
avid outdoorsman who has been described as a survivalist, was
hiding in the familiar woods near his home. ``We've said all along
that we had strong reason to believe that Eric Rudolph was in this
area, had not left this area, that he was alive, that he was acting
alone,'' Enderson said. ``We still believe that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WORLD-CHAMPIONSHI     07-14 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLD-CHAMPIONSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MONTE CARLO, Monaco _ In the National Lampoon film European
Vacation, Chevy Chase leads the Griswalds across the pond in
pursuit of fun, adventure and lots of quality bonding.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toss in the gold medal at the FIBA World Championship of
Basketball, and Rudy Tomjanovich has the same challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich and the U.S. team that will play in the World
Championship of Basketball arrived early today in the south of
France, then took the hourlong bus ride to ritzy Monte Carlo, where
they will spend the next week hoping to grow closer as a cohesive
unit _ a family.
</P>
<P>
   And Tomjanovich believes this team of replacement players for
NBA stars has the sort of personality to become a close-knit group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love the makeup of this team,'' Tomjanovich said.
``We've got guys from all different facets of basketball. We've got
two guys who are in college. We've got two guys who just got out of
college but didn't get drafted. We've got guys who have been in the
NBA. We've got journeymen. We've got guys who have been in the CBA,
and then we've got guys who come from an international situation,
Americans, who have played abroad. We've got old guys. We've got
young guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is a team that, when America sees it, it's going
to know this is an American team. It's a melting pot from all
different levels of basketball. When you think about it, it's a
heck of a story.''
</P>
<P>
   One Tomjanovich hopes will get better as the U.S team led by
players such as Jimmy King, Jason Sasser and David Wood begins
finding out where it stands in the international scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   While in Monte Carlo, the U.S. team will play exhibitions
against France on Saturday and Spain on Sunday. Those will be the
first tests for this learning-on-the-fly U.S. squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys that now that you've survived that first cut,
now our focus is that we're going to have to become a real team,''
Tomjanovich said. ``Not an all-star team. Not a group of guys from
a whole bunch of different parts of the country that just go out
and play. We have to become a family and develop a chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already talked about it, having a belief system. We have
to believe in the system we're using. We have to communicate. And
we have to like each other and depend on each other. Trust.
Expecting somebody to back you up. And then have our own
communication and terms on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this team has to do it on guts and heart. It has to be
where we're not playing for the Rockford Whoever-they-ares or the
Houston Rockets. We're playing for the United States. Once you get
that feeling _ and I think we'll have it _ then that gives you an
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of the country should help in that pursuit. It also
will expedite the process of the U.S. team developing a
personality. Nobody knows who is going to be the top scorers or
rebounders.
</P>
<P>
   But the players know what kind of style they want to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to be the butt-kicking, end-to-end,
in-your-face kind of defensive team,'' said Wood, 33, the elder
statesman among the players. ``I've been to Europe, and I just
can't see that not being effective. Going all out for 40 minutes,
that's going to wear some of those other teams down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich echoed that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to kick a lot of butt,'' Tomjanovich said when
asked what the strength of his team will be. ``No, I'm just
kidding, but we will have to use team defense and we do have some
guys who won't back down. And we have to make their big bodies move
because I've told our guys to be prepared to be undersized at every
position.''
</P>
<P>
   But height is not always what wins games. Wood said that message
was delivered early and often by Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy has told us that (camaraderie) is everything,'' Wood
said. ``He told us when the Rockets won the championship one of
those years, he felt like he had the seventh- or eighth-most
talented team. But they came together as a group and believed in
what they were doing, and they got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we've put the team first, played together and played
hard. And I think that's going to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Earl Boykins: ``I think this team has a very good chance
of winning it, but the only way to do it is to come together and
play as a unit. Last year when I played with the USA, we won the
gold medal because we played as a unit. Everybody had one main
goal, and that was to win the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Boykins, a 5-5 point guard, was the Most Valuable Player of the
USA World University Games team last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lon Kruger, coach at the University of Illinois and one of
Tomjanovich's assistants for this U.S. team, is a veteran of
numerous international competitions and believes jelling at the
right time will be important for this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially now,'' he said as the team arrived overseas.
``We're going to be playing against teams that have been together
for three, five, seven years in some cases. And they play with
great passion. We'll have to have good chemistry and have a real
team feeling, and Rudy, of course, does a great job of promoting
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But few challenges Tomjanovich has faced are as formidable as
this one _ getting this group of NBA-challenged players to be
competitive on a global stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from being the favorite with the NBA players to a
team that's right in the pack,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But we think
we have kids who have a tough mental attitude and believe we're
going to win the thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these kids come from backgrounds where they tried the
NBA and didn't make it, then went down to the CBA. Now, all of a
sudden, this is the highest-regarded international tournament in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've told them: This isn't national television; it's
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   What better circumstance to grow up as a family, right? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
