<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT COSTS TEXAS FARMERS, RANCHERS $1.5 BILLION, ECONOMISTS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In northwest Texas, cotton farmers have written off
most of this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lower Rio Grande Valley, citrus growers are beyond
worrying about their produce. It's whether they'll be able to
salvage their trees that's got them concerned.
</P>
<P>
   And in east Texas, cattle ranchers watch as ponds begin to dry
up, pastureland turns useless and hay prices rise.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than three months old, the drought of 1998 has
already cost Texas farmers and ranchers $1.5 billion, according to
economists at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   This is fast approaching the $1.9 billion in damages wreaked by
the drought of 1996, one of the worst natural disasters in the
state's history. That drought lasted about eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drought could easily wind up being worse than 1996 if we
don't get significant rain soon,'' Agricultural Extension Service
economist Roland Smith said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast isn't promising despite the brief downpour that
cooled parts of southeast Texas on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Weathermen were calling for a slight chance of thunderstorms
across west Texas through Wednesday, with scattered showers in
southeast Texas and more of the same dry skies in the South.
</P>
<P>
   But no one was predicting an end to the drought any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide damage estimates for both corn and grain sorghum
have been increased as the drought intensified, corn to an updated
$225 million and grain sorghum to $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   Damage to cotton, the No. 1 row crop in the state, is the same
as it was on June 30, about $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest hit area in the state is the South Plains and the
Rolling Plains, where crops of cotton and grain sorghum grown
without irrigation are ``almost a total loss,'' said Travis Miller,
Extension Service agronomist. Even the irrigated fields there will
be affected slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The overall damage estimate has soared since June 30, the last
update, as the result of adding $330 million for hay that won't be
baled and $55 million for fall-planted vegetables in the Lower Rio
Grande Valley that won't be planted because the supply of
irrigation water is running out.
</P>
<P>
   These vegetables range from carrots to onions. The current
estimate is that one-half the Valley's normal acreage of vegetables
will not get planted.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the irrigation districts in the Valley no longer have
water to put into the canals, and others are running low. The
combined water supply in the Falcon and Amistad reservoirs is about
23 percent of their capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus growers are worried about keeping their trees alive and
some have been unable to irrigate for nine weeks, said Gary
McBryde, an official of the Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville Citrus Center in
Weslaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, producers are not just worried about their
yields (of grapefruit and oranges this coming winter), they are
fighting to keep their trees alive,'' said McBryde. Up to half the
irrigation districts in South Texas will shut down in the near
future because of low water supplies in the reservoirs, he
predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The cattle business, the largest agricultural revenue-producer
in the state, is just starting to feel the brunt of the drought
with lost revenues of $44 million. This does not include the added
cost of feeding because of drought, which comes to $136 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers have begun to sell lightweight calves and culled cows
because of declining pastures, a process that economist Joe Outlaw
predicts will accelerate sharply during the next six weeks unless
it rains.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sunday, almost 70 percent of the pastures and rangeland in
the state were rated as in either poor or very poor condition. The
price of hay has risen by 15 to 20 percent. Many ponds used for
supplying drinking water have dried up in far west and southwest
Texas, a process that is beginning in east Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact on the state during the next 18 months will
be $4.6 billion, according to the economists. This compares with $5
billion for the 1996 drought.
</P>
<P>
   The drought will ultimately eliminate about 40,000 jobs
statewide, Outlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith remains optimistic that relatively few farmers will go out
of business because of crop insurance and emergency loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some _ that can't be avoided,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell County, which has its county seat in Sanderson, on
Tuesday became the first county in Texas to receive a drought
disaster declaration from the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Also named as contiguous disaster counties were Brewster,
Crockett, Pecos and Val Verde, according to the Texas Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   This means farmers and ranchers in those counties will be
considered for low-interest emergency loans. Currently, 110
counties in the state are at some stage of the disaster declaration
process, said Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
