<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SURGES TO REACH A RECORD LEVEL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market rallied sharply Tuesday as several
companies reported good or better-than-expected earnings for the
second quarter, easing concerns about the drag from Asia's economic
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The surge was enough to push the Dow Jones industrial average to
a new high, making it the last of the big three indexes to climb
back into record territory.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the rally will hold will depend a lot on how the the
rest of the second-quarter earnings season plays out. Only a small
proportion of the 500 companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's index have
reported so far and analysts are still predicting a lackluster
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed Tuesday, Intel Corp. reported that its
second-quarter earnings dropped 29 percent, to 66 cents a diluted
share, 2 cents below recent estimates. In after-hours trading,
Intel's stock dropped to $80.125 a share on the Instinet electronic
trading system after falling $1.6875, to $80.6875, in regular
trading.
</P>
<P>
   But it appeared Tuesday that the rush of money into the stock
market from Americans and foreigners is so strong that it may be
enough to overcome less than fabulous earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners are buying U.S. securities aggressively, stock
buybacks are big and mutual-fund flows are strong,'' said Byron
Wien, U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
``The market is being driven by liquidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wien marveled at the economy's ability to grow without a
resurgence in inflation and the refusal of investors to worry about
how far this market can go. ``It is sort of like having drink after
drink and not getting drunk and waking up the next morning without
a hangover and thinking that you can party all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also buoying investors is the fact that usually _ despite the
Intel disappointment _ there are a lot of positive earnings
surprises during the reporting season because companies work so
hard to manage expectations. Companies jawbone down earnings
forecasts until the beginning of the reporting season, making it
much easier for the actual reports to surpass those already-lowered
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened with the positive earnings reports Tuesday
from Weyerhaeuser, the manufacturer of wood and paper products. The
company announced earnings of 34 cents a diluted share, beating the
recent consensus estimate of analysts tallied by First Call Corp.
of 22 cents a share. But on June 16 the company said that its
earnings would be significantly below the then estimate of 38 cents
a share.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the health-care company, and Norwest and J.P.
Morgan, two major banks, also reported earnings Tuesday at or above
expectations. General Motors reported a sharp strike-induced loss
that was smaller than expected. And Allied Signal, the aerospace
company, reported positive results after the market's close on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow jumped 149.33 points, or 1.6 percent, to 9,245.54,
beating its previous high of 9,211.84 on May 13. The Dow's rally
back to new highs took just under two months, three times as fast
as the return to new highs in February after 1997's August peak and
the sharp one-day decline on Oct. 27 of 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index, which surpassed its April 22 high on July 8,
rose 2.88 points to a record of 1,968.41. The S&AMP;P 500-stock index,
which had surpassed its April 22 high on June 24, climbed 12.39
points, or 1.1 percent, to a record of 1,177.58.
</P>
<P>
   Big Board volume was 700.3 million shares, higher than average.
Advancing issues led decliners by 1,773 to 1,190.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The return to record highs, say some analysts, is not
surprising, because they believe that the underlying fundamentals
of the U.S. economy continue to be positive enough to support the
stock market, even if earnings growth has slowed well below the
double-digit pace that sent stocks higher during the last several
years.
</P>
<P>
   These positive fundamentals were reinforced Tuesday with the
report that the Consumer Price Index for June rose just 0.1
percent, leaving inflation up just 1.4 percent on an annual rate
this year. June retail sales rose 0.1 percent after a revised 1.2
percent gain in May.
</P>
<P>
   While bond prices fell and interest rates rose Tuesday, low
inflation and a slowing in economic growth _ signs of which are
beginning to pop up _ mean that interest rates could remain low,
which also helps the stock market by making equities look more
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower interest rates are more important than the difference
between 3 percent and 6 percent earnings growth,'' said Richard
Pucci, the director of research at IBES International, a firm that
follows earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``With inflation and long-term interest rates low and economic
activity healthy, I believe that investors are and will remain
unfazed by the slowdown in earnings growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And with this positive background there just seems to be an
urgency among investors to get their money into the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is so great to get the money in,'' said Marshall
Acuff, the equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney. Earnings
still count, he argued, but ``current earnings sometimes may not
make as much difference as people speculate that they will get
better in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Also aiding the market Tuesday was the improvement in the
outlook for Russia's economy following an agreement on Monday for
$17 billion in new international support. But the country's
legislature still must approve the domestic economic program that
goes along with the bailout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every problem out there that seems to scare us seems to get
solved,'' Wien said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
