<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIA-SECRETS-NYT &LR;      07-14 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIA-SECRETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA, GOING BACK ON PROMISES, SAYS IT WILL NOT RELEASE SECRET
RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Breaking repeated promises it made to the American
public, the CIA said on Tuesday that it will not release secret
records from most of its major Cold War covert operations in the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The director of central intelligence, George Tenet, said in a
written statement that the CIA had ``a responsibility to the
American people, and to history, to account for our actions and the
quality of our work.'' But, he said, the agency lacked the money
and the personnel to fulfill its promises anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The agency pledged five years ago to declassify thousands of
files on 11 major paramilitary and political operations launched
under Presidents Harry Truman, Dwight Eisenhower and John Kennedy.
It said then that records on these secret efforts at foiling
Communism and furthering American foreign policy in Europe, Asia,
Africa and the Caribbean would be released as early as 1994. Two
former CIA chiefs, Robert Gates and R. James Woolsey Jr.,
personally promised that the files would be released.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has published some documents from two of those
operations: the disastrous 1961 Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba and
the successful 1954 coup against the Guatemalan government. In the
case of Guatemala, the release so far represents less than 2
percent of the available files.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear on Tuesday that the agency never undertook a
serious effort to declassify the remaining nine operations. Tenet
said on Tuesday that he had decided ``to hold the reviews of these
covert actions in abeyance for the time being.'' A historian who
advises the CIA on the declassification program, Page Putnam
Miller, said on Tuesday that ``there are no resources now for this
project.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine operations constitute a secret history of American
power as used against foreign governments by three presidents. They
include efforts to shore up the noncommunist left in France and
Italy in the late 1940s and early 1950s, guerrilla operations in
North and South Korea during the Korean War, efforts ranging from
political propaganda to bombing missions in Indonesia in the 1950s,
paramilitary activities in Laos and Tibet during the first years of
the American involvement in Vietnam, and covert actions that
included assassination plots in the Congo and the Dominican
Republic in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also promised six years ago to release records of its
coup in Iran in 1954. It belatedly confessed last year that it had
destroyed most of those files in the early 1960s. Woolsey called
that destruction, which remained a secret within the agency, even
to him, ``a terrible breach of faith with the American people and
their ability to understand their own history.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the agency's directorate of operations have
steadfastly opposed releasing Cold War secrets, saying that even
40- and 50-year-old documents can reveal the agency's present-day
sources and methods. A senior intelligence official said that the
directorate accepts declassification in principle but often opposes
disclosures in practice. The tug of war between secrecy and
openness continues unresolved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet said on Tuesday that declassifying documents is a
painstaking process, requiring the purging of sensitive secrets,
which takes more time, money and people than the agency can commit.
</P>
<P>
   He said the CIA had released 227,000 pages to a government panel
on the assassination of President Kennedy and reams of information
for the State Department's official histories of American foreign
relations in the 1950s and 1960s. These releases, required by law,
took precedence over the voluntary effort to declassify covert
actions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A C.I.A. spokeswoman said that about 150 people, most retired
spies, work on declassification. They handle demands from the White
House, Congress and the State Department, as well as public
requests under the Freedom of Information Act. She declined to
reveal how much money was spent, saying the sum is secret.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
