<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SCOTLAND-$ADV19-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MISTY SCOTTISH ISLE OF SKYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19.)  
 (JT)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every right-thinking visitor to the Isle of Skye must master the
etiquette of the one-track road. The island, a large, many-fingered
blob between the western Highlands and the Outer Hebrides, does
have a basic network of two-lane roads, but the real driving begins
on the narrow trails, often unmarked, that wind from glen to glen,
skirting silvery lochs, crossing desolate moors and sheep pastures,
or running headlong into the forbidding, upthrust mountain chain
known as the Cuillins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, a car approaches. Or a fat caravan. Or, for
that special thrill, a tour bus barreling along at high speed.
Custom dictates that the vehicle closest to a passing place, a
bulge in the road indicated by a diamond-shaped sign, should pull
over and wait for the other vehicle to proceed. The driver who
forges ahead, must _ repeat, must _ acknowledge the courtesy with a
wave. If multiple cars are stopped, one wave for the group will not
do. Each waiting car gets its own payoff. It matters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the course of a week's stay on Skye, my wife, Nancy, and I
spent a fair amount of time analyzing the sociology of the single
track and criticizing our fellow drivers. We seethed at the louts
who zipped past a convenient passing place, forcing us to halt or
even back up, and then sped by without even a nod. As the sole
driver, I experimented with gradations of thanks, from a minimalist
one-finger wiggle to a Texas-caliber ``howdy'' wave. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I had lots of practice. Almost any road on Skye qualifies as a
scenic drive, so the temptation is strong to turn off the two-lane
roads and follow the corkscrew single-tracks wherever they may
lead, across squishy moorland covered in purple heather, over
alpine meadows and stretches of grassland that suggest high
chaparral country, along bold headlands thrusting out toward the
sea, past the mesalike formations known as MacLeod's tables, and
the scarred, ragged Red Cuillins and Black Cuillins, geological
lords of the island.
</P>
<P>
   The light on Skye is magic, the weather so unpredictable and
quick to change that listening to the forecast becomes something of
a joke, since everything is possible at any time, or so it seemed
in late August. Bright sunshine and a startlingly pure, pale blue
sky could vanish in an instant, as a flat gray lid of cloud slammed
down and emitted a fine, high-velocity spray of rain. After 10
minutes, a blue streak on the horizon would offer hope, and perhaps
a half hour later, cumulus clouds, soft and puffy enough for
cherubs, would pile up in a Marie Antoinette coiffe. Shafts of
sunlight would send diffused rays over glen and heather, creating
an effect we called ``the hand of God.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunsets provided a full evening's entertainment. Our base of
operations was a whitewashed cottage perched above Glendale, a
scooped-out valley in far northwestern Skye, on the Duirinish
Peninsula, with a view over Loch Pooltiel out to the low, rolling
hills of North Uist in the Outer Hebrides. As evening progressed, a
smear of lemon painted the horizon, setting it off from the
silver-gray surface of the loch, and scattered purplish clouds
floated by, occasionally flaring up with a golden light as they
captured the last rays of the setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   The sky eventually settled into bands of blue and bluish-gray.
The coastline softened, and the island appeared to levitate
slightly. As night fell, and sheep bleats were relayed from glen to
glen, Uist floated serenely, a silent dream at the end of the
earth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skye does not make enormous demands on the cultural tourist. Its
history is dominated by two clans, the MacDonalds and the MacLeods,
and two events, Bonnie Prince Charlie's secret journey across the
island after the Battle of Culloden in 1746, and the visit of
Samuel Johnson and James Boswell in 1773.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the mighty MacDonalds, who, as hereditary Lords
of the Islands, held sway over Skye, the Outer Hebrides and even
large chunks of the mainland in the 15th century, gets the full
treatment at the Clan Donald Visitor Center, in Armadale, on the
Sound of Sleat at the southern end of Skye. The center, a renovated
stable behind the ruins of Armadale Castle, includes a study center
and museum devoted to the 1,300-year history of the clan, as well
as 40 acres of nature trails and a restored Victorian garden. As
northerners, however, Nancy and I rallied to the cause of the
MacLeods, whose story can be read at Dunvegan Castle, an
uncompromising stone fortress facing Loch Dunvegan that has been
the clan's seat since 1200. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps ``cause'' is not the right word. The rivalry between
MacDonald and MacLeod, and of both clans with assorted lesser fry,
seems less like ``Braveheart'' than it does a kilted version of the
Hatfields and McCoys. MacLeod smote MacDonald, who smote Mackenzie,
who smote MacTavish, and so on down through the centuries. The
ceaseless struggle for land and power hit a low point one Sunday in
1578 when a marauding band of MacDonalds from Uist landed on
northern Skye, set fire to a church filled with MacLeods and
butchered anyone who escaped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alerted by the lone survivor from the church, an armed party of
MacLeods rushed from Dunvegan Castle and waved the magic Fairy
Flag, left hundreds of years earlier to a clan member by his fairy
lover with the instructions that it be used only in direst
emergency. Nature itself turned against the MacDonalds, who fled to
their boats in panic, only to find that the ebbing tide had left
them high, dry and firmly in the possession of the MacLeods, who
annihilated their enemy. A scrap of the Fairy Flag hangs in
Dunvegan Castle. Its origins are mysterious, but the eastern silk
from which it is made suggests that it may have flown during one of
the Crusades.  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The castle had taken on the interior comforts of a fine country
house, and added a landscaped garden, by the time Johnson and
Boswell dropped by for several days of feasting and good
conversation with Lord and Lady MacLeod, who distressed Boswell by
complaining that life was a bit of a bore in Dunvegan Castle.
``Keep to the rock,'' he admonished them. ``It is the very jewel of
the estate. It looks as if it had been let down from heaven by the
four corners, to be the residence of a chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Lady MacLeod would have none of it. ``It is very well for you,''
she said, ``who have a fine place and everything easy, to talk
thus, and think of chaining honest folks to a rock.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nerve center of Skye is Portree, an attractive port and
fishing town with a string of whitewashed hotels, restaurants and
shops lining the harbor. In summer the town teems with visitors,
many of them backpackers on hiking or climbing expeditions. The
tourist office, on Bayfield Lane, near the harbor, is large,
efficient, well stocked with maps, touring guides, hiking
itineraries, histories, Skye-related fiction, and even an
invaluable little treatise on the midge, a tiny, gnatlike
creature. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The midge is a fact of life in the Highlands and Islands. Nancy
and I arrived with fear in our hearts, especially after reading a
newspaper item about a sheep that caused a three-car pile-up after
bolting onto a road to escape a midge attack. Imagination painted
too lurid a picture, however. The breezes blow almost constantly on
Skye, dispersing the midges, which appear from late May to early
September. Sunlight also has a deterrent effect. Midge swarm-athons
tend to occur when the breeze dies down, and light begins to fade.
Know the ways of the midge, counsels the author of ``Midges in
Scotland,'' adjust your schedule, and the problem becomes
manageable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least that was true on Skye's northern peninsulas, where we
concentrated our touristic efforts. On our quiet country lane, amid
the Cheviots and Scottish black-face sheep, we came to look on
Portree and points south with a rustic's disdain. Yes, the south
could boast the charismatic Cuillins, an imposing horseshoe-shaped
chain that, under a threat-ening sky, suggests the stronghold of
the dark powers in ``The Lord of the Rings.'' True, the visitor
must go south to visit the island's lone distillery, Talisker, and
the drive from Carbost to Glenbrittle, skirting the Cuillins, is a
stunner.
</P>
<P>
   But the more thinly populated, wilder north caught our fancy.
Hardly a car was to be seen as we circled the Vaternish Peninsula,
an elevated headland pointing straight across the Minch to Harris.
At Trumpan, a steep coastal road passes the ruins of the church set
afire by the MacDonalds, and the MacLeod graveyard, before
descending to Stein, a tiny village overlooking Loch Bay whose
single street includes the 16th-century Stein Inn and the Loch Bay
Seafood Restaurant, an inviting, beamed room where the chalkboard
specials depend on the day's catch of hake, lemon sole, halibut,
haddock, Dover sole, monkfish, cod or plaice. As an appetizer,
order a pile of squat lobster tails, a local delicacy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greater drama lies just a step eastward, on the Trotternish
Peninsula, a thumblike protrusion whose coastal road offers views
of the Hebrides to the west and the Highlands to the east. Its
weirdly sculptured topography, carved by glaciers from the the
4,000 feet of lava that volcanoes deposited on what was once a
coastal lagoon, includes two of Skye's most famous rock formations,
the Old Man of Storr and the Quiraing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our own peninsula seemed to specialize in unusual museums,
although nothing quite matches the Haggis Museum in Portree, where
a series of dioramas present the natural history of the mythical
beast. Dunvegan itself, little more than a wide spot in the road,
is home to the Giant Angus Mac-Askill Museum, a one-room thatched
cottage devoted to a 19th-century man who, at 7 feet 9 inches and
425 pounds, found a career touring with P.T. Barnum in the United
States. Why the museum stands in Dunvegan is mysterious, since
MacAskill was born in the Western Isles and died in Nova Scotia.
The museum contains nothing that actually belonged to the man. For
a fee of 1 pound _ about $1.70 _ the visitor is treated to the
sight of an enormous coffin, suggestive of MacAskill's size, as
well as a giant chair and a giant bed. A life-size model of the
great man stands in one corner of the cottage, along with a model
of Tom Thumb, a colleague on his tours. It's worth the pound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more serious endeavor is the MacCrimmon Piping Heritage
Center, a small building in Boereraig, on land deeded to the
MacCrimmons, hereditary pipers to the MacLeods. For three
centuries, until the beginning of the 19th century, the MacCrimmons
ran a college of piping that attracted clan pipers from all over
Scotland. Do not enter if you are in an unenthusiastic mood. Geoff
Winter and his wife, Sarah Winter, have a missionary zeal for the
traditional bagpipe music known as piobaireachd (PEA-brokh), and
visitors are regarded as fresh recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The center offers courses of instruction, and at its shop, the
newly converted can buy CD's, tapes or, indeed, a full set of
bagpipes. Winter does not like to let visitors leave before they
have at least tried to get the pipes blowing, and for promising
beginners, he will do the fingering for ``Scotland the Brave.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also cheap at the price of 1 pound is the Colbost Croft Museum,
in Colbost, a traditional stone crofter's cottage with thatched
roof, a dirt floor, some rudimentary sticks of furniture, a few
dishes, and an iron pot suspended over a peat fire in the center of
the main room. The replica of an illegal whisky still sits out
back. That's it. There is no guide and no commentary, but the
cottage speaks eloquently of the harsh conditions endured by the
crofters who scratched out half a living from their tiny plots,
barely managing to put potatoes and herring on the table.
</P>
<P>
   In one of history's little ironies, the next-door neighbor
happens to be the Three Chimneys Restaurant, one of Skye's two
culinary temples, the other being the renowned Kinloch Lodge, run
by Lady Macdonald deep in the heart of Clan Donald territory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wretched crofter's cottage is the flip side of the proud
clan histories. In the late 18th century, when farmers from the
north of England learned that Cheviot sheep could survive the
Highland winters, they pushed northward, offering fat rents for
grazing land. In a miserable episode known as the clearances, the
clan chieftains forced their tenants off the land where they had
farmed and grazed sheep and cattle for generations. Thousands
emigrated, many of them to America. Skye became a hotbed of unrest,
and an uprising by crofters in Glendale led to land reforms that
still govern life on the island. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sheep play a major role in the tourist experience on Skye. The
fuzzy little darlings like to gather in the middle of the road for
a quick confab, and the background music on the island is the quiet
but unmistakable tearing and crunching sound made by a vast woolly
army, teeth moving triple-time over succulent grass.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a bitter disappointment to both of us that we missed the
sheep dog trials at Talisker, a chance to see ``Babe'' come to
life. But we did get the next-best thing. One fine evening, the
flock next door, a contented band supplemented by a pair of
arrogant roosters, a long-bearded goat, several rabbits and the
world's sweetest-tempered sheep dog, moved to the upper pasture.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic moment. Charlie, the dog, was now called upon
to do his best and round up the flock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Wendy,'' the owner shouted encouragingly. ``Don't forget
Janet, she's lagged behind.'' Charlie circled manically but, alas,
proved to be at best a C-plus sheep dog. Wendy tuned out the
nagging until she was good and ready to move along. Janet, wearing
a bland expression, continued to work on a promising patch of
grass. The flock moved across the road, one sheep short.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, something like a thought entered Janet's dim brain.
Sensing a sudden hush, she looked around, saw no one and emitted a
tentative bleat. There was no response. After puzzling over the
matter for several seconds, she flopped onto her side and fell
asleep. The last rays of light flashed off Loch Pooltiel, three
dark clouds scudded overhead and night fell over Skye. There would
be plenty of grass tomorrow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
