<HEADLINE>
TRANSFER OF SATELLITE TECHNOLOGY TO CHINA CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans said Tuesday their preliminary
investigation found the Clinton administration ``violated US
policy'' by providing China with sensitive satellite technology
that included military benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, in a surprise floor speech,
also said GOP investigators had obtained ``new information''
showing that China tried to influence US elections in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While Lott didn't provide much detail, he did say the next phase
of the investigation would look at why at least three US satellites
have been launched in China ``with no US monitors present.'' Lott
said the absence of US monitors, which previously has been
reported, is ``directly contrary to previous administration
claims.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Michael McCurry said Lott's announcement
``struck me a little bit like Alice in Wonderland time.'' McCurry
said the Mississippian's floor speech was ``not a serious statement
by a serious person.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as happened last year when Republicans claimed they had
evidence about foreign influence in Democratic campaigns, the GOP
Tuesday declined to make public any back-up evidence to support
both the allegations about satellite technology and foreign
campaign contributions. Republicans said they are partly bound by
security regulations to keep the information secret.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they had not been allowed to contribute to the
interim report and that no actual report was approved or written.
Instead, the report amounted to Lott's release of a seven-page
statment of what he said various Senate committees have learned so
far about the satellite and fund-raising matters.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, however, said the evidence regarding the satellites was
good enough to ``remove all resistance to naming an independent
counsel to investigate the evidence and the allegations.''
Republicans have previously requested that the attorney general ask
for an independent counsel to examine Democratic campaign
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also blasted the White House for failing to cooperate with
the investigations. Unless cooperation is forthcoming, Lott said,
he will be ``forced to consider other measures,'' including a
freeze on administration nominations and the use of new subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said Lott's
action was ``partisanship at its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Lott's statement focused on allegations that the Clinton
administration violated US policy by allowing an American company
to transfer satellite technology to China that could be used for
military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Lott opened his speech by noting that when Vice President Gore
was a senator in 1989, Gore criticized the Bush administration for
allowing three US satellites to be exported to China. ``Allowing
these launches is not in the best interests of our country or of
our relationship with China,'' Gore said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott said the Clinton administration has proceeded to do
just what Gore complained about a decade ago, allowing China to
launch satellites provided by Loral Space &AMP; Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Loral's chairman, Bernard Schwartz, is one of the biggest donors
to the Democratic Party. Republicans are investigating whether
there is a link between the campaign contributions and Clinton's
issuance of a waiver that allowed China to launch the Loral
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said an unnamed senior official of the Defense Trade and
Security Administration told a congressional committee last month
that the government has failed in its effort to control the
transfer of US technology with military implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The formal process ... has failed in its stated mission, to
safeguard the national security of the United States,'' the
official said, according to Lott. However, the testimony was not
released, making it impossible to know the context of the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also said the Senate Governmental Affairs subcommittee on
international security heard testimony last week that Defense
Department monitors are not required to be present at launches of
US satellites in China.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said this contradicts administration claims, although Lott
noted there is no statute requiring US monitors to be present.
Furthermore, Lott said China had derived significant benefits from
the launch of US satellites. He noted that China had five launch
failures between 1991 to 1996. But since China benefited from the
knowledge obtained during the launch of US satellites, China has
suffered no launch failures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the assertion that China received a military benefit from
US satellites, the Senate majority leader said, ``We have
established a great number of crossover benefits between a
commercial space launch program and the development of ballistic
missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's sweeping charges were reminiscent of the way Senator Fred
Thompson opened his Senate Governmental Affairs Committee hearings
last year by declaring he had proof China sought to influence
Democratic election campaigns. But Thompson failed to publicly
provide such evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Lott said investigators had obtained information about
the influence of China in US elections that is ``new since Senator
Thompson concluded his review.'' Lott declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Robert Kerrey of Nebraska, the ranking Democrat on the
Senate Intelligence Committee, said Lott was making misleading
statements about the panel's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication is that the committee has reached some kind of
conclusion,'' Kerrey said. ``It most assuredly has not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
