<SLUG> BC-NAACP-AFFIRM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powell tells convention-goers to set examples
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby and Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a young military commander, Colin Powell knew he
could face questions of whether his position was the result of
affirmative action. Powell, who later became a general and chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, set out to prove these skeptics wrong
by making sure his was the best unit around.
</P>
<P>
   Those who obtain opportunities through affirmative action need
to do the same, he told participants of the NAACP convention on
Tuesday _ they need to perform at the highest level to prove
affirmative action opponents wrong about the level of competency
among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potential recipients of affirmative action _ high
school students _ know the naysayers are out there.
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon session on affirmative action for about 500
members of the youth and college division of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, students worried
about how they would be perceived if they were the beneficiaries of
affirmative action in college admissions, jobs and federal
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Katrice Stinson, a second-year law student at Mercer University,
said affirmative action is owed to blacks and that the students
need not worry about what others think of them, as long as they
perform when given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing preferential about being African-American,''
said Stinson, adding while blacks lag behind whites in standardized
test scores, they do just as well, or better in most cases, once
they are admitted. ``This is something we deserve. If race isn't
used as a factor to help level the playing field, you can't get in.
Then what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who was forceful Tuesday in his support of affirmative
action, said it's important officials at educational institutions
be certain their campuses are diverse. ``This is the only way it
will reflect all of American and not just part of America,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A moderate Republican, Powell said his support of affirmative
action came ``not as an academic, but as a soldier who saw it work.
I saw what you could do in the Army when you have affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
