<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-IMAGE-COX     07-14 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-IMAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    African-Americans shouldn't let cultural standards shape their
views, panelists say
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The friction slave owners created between black people
of different hues has no place in the African-American community,
young NAACP delegates said Tuesday, and they are determined to stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   In a movement that works to advance all black people,
African-Americans must resist media and entertainment images that
supplant cohesiveness, the delegates said. From teen to teen to
teen, they proclaimed the only way to eradicate the centuries-old
problem, is to adopt and adhere to a standard of beauty they define
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There was standing room only during the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People's youth seminar titled ``What Are
You Looking At? Our Image: Lessons, Lies and Liabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The lessons started hundreds of years ago during slavery, said
panelist Selena Swan from Vibe magazine, which writes about the
black music industry. But the lies are perpetuated by the media and
entertainment industries in their selection of heroines and
negative portrayals of black people in the news, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some magazines now regularly feature models with prominent
African features, Swan said, but they should not set the tone for
how black people feel about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some change,'' she said. ``My thing is why do we have
to wait for them to think it's popular before we change?''
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Richardson, a youth delegate from New York, drew rousing
applause with his assessment of the effect on the black community.
``You have to think about the psychology of what's going on,'' he
said. ``We have our own people bleaching their hair until it falls
out. Respect yourself!''
</P>
<P>
   For some, that call is easier to heed than it is for others,
said Amanda Henley, an 18-year-old delegate from Pennsylvania. ``It
all depends on the confidence your parents instill in you,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Scott, a 27-year-old observer from Charlotte, N.C.,
implored the proud teenagers in the room to take on the
esteem-building role for other youth in their families and
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take leadership for ourselves,'' he said. ``We need
to go back home and plant the seed in younger brothers and sisters
as to what it means to be a beautiful black woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
