<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day 1 of job fair receives praise
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Laurel Green, 22, said she's glad the NAACP's annual
Diversity Job Fair lasts two days. Otherwise, she said she'd never
get through it in a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought 30 resumes with me. I have no idea how many I've
handed out today,'' she said on Monday, Day 1 of the job fair. A
recent Shaw University graduate, Green said the fair is much more
diverse than the others she's attended this year. She said she is
looking for a job in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Wakefield, a recruiter from the Georgia-based American
Family Life Assurance Co. of Columbus, said she was impressed with
the candidates she had seen on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very pleased,'' Wakefield said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120 companies attended the fair, sponsored by the
NAACP National Labor Department. The fair runs from noon to 6:30
p.m. today in the Georgia World Congress Center. The job fair is
free and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice King fought her own anger
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bernice King, daughter of the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr., addressed her own struggles in an address Monday to the youth
NAACP members.
</P>
<P>
   King said she had become increasingly angry and
``self-destructive'' over the years while trying to deal with the
deaths of her father and other relatives who were close to her. She
said the culmination came when she considered suicide when she
landed in academic trouble after her first year of law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I saw before me was failure. I said, `My God, if I don't
come out of this, then the whole world would know that Dr. King's
daughter is a failure,''' she said. ``God really, literally, came
into my home and told me to put that knife down, because I had a
reason and a purpose for living.''
</P>
<P>
   King encouraged the audience to recognize that they are destined
for greatness as well, and that their family or academic
circumstances do not have to dictate their fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, today, is the beginning of your new life regardless of
what happened yesterday,'' she said. ``Stop replaying the tape.
Live in the present.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
