<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-REMAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delegates urged to focus energies on what they do best
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's local need and then there's national agenda.
But even when the two are quite different, local NAACP chapters are
finding ways to champion both.
</P>
<P>
   This week, leaders within the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People have encouraged branches to
concentrate on what the country's oldest civil rights organization
does best and share the work of lifting the black community with
other African-American organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, NAACP chairman, emphasized the point Sunday evening
when he told delegates that they need to do old things better,
specifically organization, mobilization, litigation and coalition.
They must remember that the primary mission is fighting white
supremacy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume, revisited the
issue and warned branches not to stretch themselves thin by trying
to be all things to all people.
</P>
<P>
   He implored them to use the resources of the National Bar
Association, the Urban League and black sororities and fraternities
to help solve social problems plaguing the black community.
</P>
<P>
   For branches in metropolitan areas, those other organizations
are available. But what about rural towns? And what about the
problems that lie outside of the purview of litigation and
mobilization such as teen pregnancy, poor school performance and
drug-use prevention?
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said some branches in rural areas will likely need to be
all things to all people, and they can try to be. However, he said,
the national organization cannot stray from its expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Branch leaders say there's room for it all if necessary.
Furthermore, they said, Bond and Mfume's platforms are more
liberating than limiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have clear direction. A few years ago, I can't say the
leadership we had provided that for us,'' said Wes Mooney Jr.,
treasurer of the Waukesha, Wis., NAACP branch. ``But now we know
what we are about. ... Before, we were all going in different
directions and the populace would say, `What do you stand for?' and
`What are you about?' Now we can say we are about A, B and C with
clear-cut goals and objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to abandon social programs just because they
are not NAACP areas of expertise, said Madalynne Brooks of the
Lakeland, Fla., branch which operates a tutoring, teen-pregnancy
prevention and drug-use prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel we should put anything aside because it is
necessary,'' said Brooks, branch membership chairwoman. ``The need
is so great.''
</P>
<P>
   That branch shares its social service work with fraternities and
other civic organizations. And when the branch needs to support the
national protest, political and legal agenda, it enlists the help
of anyone _ even nonmembers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go in the highways and hedges and byways to find people,''
said Brooks, 78, who joined the organization 60 years ago. ``When
we are boycotting we go anywhere we can to get people. We'll go
into the juke joint and get people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Charles Town, W.V., the local branch takes Bond's advice on
being organizers to continue its social agenda, said branch
president George Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have to be about political action and fighting
racial discrimination,'' said Rutherford, whose town of 35,000 is
10 percent African-American. ``But anything that can help to
improve black people, we should play a role.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, his branch organized a teen youth program that
focuses on education and social and recreational activities. But
once it organized the program, the branch turned it over to the
local Masons to run and kept a supervisory role.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Mesiah, branch president in Buffalo, N.Y., said the local
NAACP volunteers must meet people's basic needs before promoting a
political and judicial agenda. ``It's not going to make sense to
talk to people about voter registration when their stomachs are
empty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
