<SLUG> BC-NAACP-SPOTLIGHT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Solving the puzzle of cancer's race gap
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Black Americans are more likely than whites to develop
cancer and to die of it. Doctors have known of this troubling
disparity _and have guessed some of the reasons behind it _ for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   What doctors don't have is enough solid information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some biological component to it, as there are
economical, cultural and environmental components. We need a
balanced approach,'' said Lovell Jones, co-chairman of the
Houston-based Intercultural Cancer Center, which addresses cancer
incidence and deaths among minorities. The NAACP, which is among
ICC's member organizations, will address the issue of cancer in the
African-American community at its convention today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't say that it's all poverty and then walk away,
because that gets into blaming the victim,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists haven't ignored the issue, but the puzzle of why
blacks suffer disproportionately from cancer won't be solved by
research alone _ it will take policy and social changes. Research
financing for minority health issues has only in the past few
decades become a health policy priority. And once scientists have
some answers, translating them to effective prevention and
treatment will be another hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 454 blacks out of 100,000 were likely to develop
cancer, compared to 394 whites out of 100,000, according to the
American Cancer Society. In addition, blacks are 30 percent more
likely to die of cancer than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Certain types of cancer are more common among blacks than other
racial or ethnic populations. Blacks have the highest prevalence of
lung cancer, the leading killer among cancers. Black men have much
higher incidence of prostate cancer than white men. Black women
develop breast cancer slightly less often than white women but are
more likely to die of it.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors may play a role.
</P>
<P>
   _ Black Americans are more likely than whites, although less
likely than Native Americans or Hispanics, to lack health
insurance. This leads to later diagnoses of medical problems,
reducing chances of successful treatment and survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's less early detection, less access to screening,'' said
Dr. Michael Thun, who heads epidemiological research for the cancer
society.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blacks also tend to have other risk factors such as obesity,
smoking and poor nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colon cancer is heavily related to diet,'' said Dr. Otis
Brawley, an oncologist at the National Cancer Institute in
Rockville, Md. ``People with high-fat, low-fiber diets are more
likely to get it. There are several different black cultures in the
United States, but the dietary habits are generally those favoring
colon cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Biological differences between blacks and people of other
racial or ethnic backgrounds may also be a factor in cancer
prevalence.
</P>
<P>
   Sickle cell anemia often is cited as an example of a genetically
inherited disease that is more common among, although not exclusive
to, blacks.
</P>
<P>
   A study released last week that showed that blacks absorb more
nicotine from cigarette smoking than whites or Mexican-Americans is
further evidence that biological differences are medically
significant.
</P>
<P>
   But research must be done to determine whether genetic or
metabolic differences contribute to blacks' high cancer rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know why the rate of prostate cancer in
African-American men is more than that of white Americans,'' said
Charles Jackson, the cancer society's director of advocacy for
special populations.
</P>
<P>
   To help answer that question, the cancer society and other
organizations, including the NAACP, have drawn up a plan to reduce
the disproportionate number of prostate cancer cases among black
men, primarily by pushing for more research and education for
doctors and patients. Other programs, such as a nationwide breast
cancer early detection program for uninsured women, are aimed at
high-risk populations with poor access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   The problem can be solved, oncologists say. Jones points to the
now decreasing rates of hypertension and cardiovascular disease
among blacks. He attributes this decline to concerted efforts by
scientific organizations as well as individual black doctors. The
same must be done for cancer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough black cardiologists to have an association of
black cardiologists,'' Jones said. ``But there aren't enough
oncologists to have an association of minority oncologists.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest changes must come from health care policy, doctors
and minority advocates agree. Health care must become more
flexible, to accommodate the needs of patients. Brawley recalls a
woman with breast cancer whose employer wouldn't let her come in
late a few times a week so she could receive radiation treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a job like that, I'd quit it and go on to another
one,'' Brawley said. ``Whereas she can't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to commitment,'' Jones said. ``I've heard a lot
of beautiful statements, and I'm still waiting for the
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
