<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SCOTLAND-$ADV19-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: grass tomorrow.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Getting There &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The fastest route from the mainland to the island is the A87 to
the new Skye Bridge, which connects Kyle of Lochalsh to Kyle-akin.
The toll is $9.65. The more romantic approach is the ferry from
Mallaig to Armadale, which operates daily from March to October,
Monday to Saturday the rest of the year and Sundays from May 17 to
Sept. 20. The trip takes 30 minutes. Passenger ferries run from
November through February only. The one-way fare is $4.30, plus $25
a car; (44-1471) 844-248.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where to Stay &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The tourist information center in Portree will help book
accommodations. It is open Monday to Saturday from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m.
and Sunday from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. in high season (until Aug. 17);
(44-1478) 612-137. Here are a few of the more attractive hotels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flodigarry Country House Hotel, &LR;  Staffin, (44-1470) 552-203,
fax 552-301. Including breakfast, the rate is $83 to $130 a person.
The hotel has 12 rooms in the main house, 7 in Flora MacDonald's
Cottage, the former home of the patriot who spirited Bonnie Prince
Charlie across Skye on his flight to France. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Viewfield House,  &LR; Portree, (44-1478) 612-217, fax (44-1478)
613-517. An atmospheric late-18th-century house with 11 rooms and
woodland gardens just outside town. Rates: $69 to $78 a person with
breakfast; $86 to $95, breakfast and dinner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Talisker House,  &LR; Talisker Bay, (44-1478) 640-245), fax
(44-1478) 640-214. Country house with four rooms built in 1723, on
spacious grounds, with dining room. Rate: $65.50 a person with
breakfast. A three-course dinner with cheese is $34. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kinloch Lodge,  &LR; Sleat, (44-1471) 833-214, fax (44-1471)
833-277; in the United States, (800) 322-2403. The lodge has 15
bedrooms of very different sizes, and the rates change according to
low, mid- and high season. In high season, it is $83 to $164 a
person, with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where to Eat &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kinloch Lodge: &LR;  A five-course fixed-price dinner is $60 in high
season, $55 other times. The menu changes nightly, but a typical
dinner might include cauliflower and Stilton soup or smoked salmon
terrine with cucumber dressing to start, then baked fillet of hake
with tomatoes and black olives served on a bed of spinach or roast
duck with an apple-Calvados puree served with a green peppercorn
sauce. Typical desserts are walnut tart with caramel ice cream or
baked raspberry creams. Not open for lunch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three Chimneys Restaurant,  &LR; Colbost (near Dunvegan), (44-1470)
511-258, has a three-course menu for $43 and a la carte seafood
specialties. When we were there, dinner appetizers included a
mussel tartlet with saffron cream ($7.75) and Skye langoustines
with warm garlic butter ($14.65). Main courses included grilled
loin of Highland lamb with a mushroom and kidney croustade ($30),
and halibut with a savory vanilla custard ($31). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Loch Bay Seafood Restaurant,  &LR; Stein, (44-1470) 592-235. Fresh
seafood (main courses $10 to $33) and traditional desserts, like
clootie dumpling ($5). Closed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What to See &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clan Donald Visitor Center,  &LR; Armadale, (44-1471) 844-305. Open
9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. It closes at the end of October until
around Easter. Admission: $6, $4 for the elderly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dunvegan Castle,  &LR; Dunvegan, (44-1470) 521-206. Open daily, 10
a.m. to 5:30 p.m., mid-March through October, then Monday through
Friday, 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission to castle and gardens, $8.60,
$7.75 students and the elderly, $4.30 children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MacCrimmon Piping Heritage Center,  &LR; Boreraig. Open year round,
Monday through Thursday, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Hourlong
introductory sessions are available Tuesday, Wednesday and Sunday
at noon and 3:30 p.m. Reservations advisable; (44-1470) 511-316,
fax (44-1470) 511-759. Admission $4.30, children $2.50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Talisker Distillery,  &LR; Carbost. Monday to Saturday 9 a.m. to
4:30 p.m. from July to September, shorter hours the rest of the
year. The $5 admission buys a dram of Talisker after the tour, and
a $5 discount on any bottle of whisky. (44-1478) 640-314.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
