<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-MEMORIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK DESCENDANT OF CONFEDERATE CAPTAIN CAN'T PRTICIPATE IN
CEREMONY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Emerson Emory of Dallas, a black psychiatrist and a
proud descendant of a Civil War veteran, was eager to participate
in this week's dedication ceremonies for a new African American
Civil War Memorial in the nation's capital. There's just one
problem: Emory's ancestor fought for the South.
</P>
<P>
   Emory, who had planned to lay a wreath honoring the Union's
178,000 black soldiers, was dropped from thursday's program at
Arlington National Cemetery because his great-grandfather fought
for the Confederacy in the 13th Texas Cavalry.
</P>
<P>
   A letter revoking Emory's invitation to the event said his
participation on behalf of the Sons of Confederate Veterans would
detract from the memorial's purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The belief and philosophy of this project and foundation
emphasize the struggle for attainment of freedom,'' Walter Hill,
the project's chief historian wrote Emory. ``We view the existence
of the Confederacy as a barrier to this cause and the freedom of
African American slaves and free people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill also told Emory that the memorial's backers do ``not share
and believe in the traditions and symbolism of the Confederate
States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1.6 million memorial will be built with private funding on
federal land in Washington's Shaw neighborhood. The area is named
for Col. Robert Gould Shaw, who led the black Massachusetts
regiment depicted in the movie, ``Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   The dedication ceremonies start on Wednesday with a symposium on
the role of black Union troops, followed by a tribute on Thursday
at Arlington National Cemetery. The memorial's centerpiece, a
bronze sculpture depicting a soldier leaving his family for war,
will be unveiled Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Emory, 73, said the memorial's backers misinterpreted history
and his motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had nothing to with me wishing to perpetuate slavery, but
only honoring people who died in battle,'' he said. ``I'm going to
put my wreath down anyway, even if it has to be in the middle of
the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Emory traces his Civil War ties to Capt. Henry Hancock, a white
slaveowner from Nacogdoches. Hancock died in battle, but not before
fathering a daughter by one his slaves. The daughter was Emory's
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Orlebeke of Dallas, who heads the Sons of Confederate
Veterans, said he asked Emory to represent the 25,000-member
organization at the dedication ceremonies in a symbolic display of
healing. Orlebeke said the South had at least 70,000 black troops,
including many who carried weapons. The Confederate descendants'
organization has about a dozen black members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a bunch of racists,'' Orlebeke said. ``We're trying
to extend the hand of friendship from our black troops to their
black troops, and it was refused.''
</P>
<P>
   Emory, a World War II veteran, said he is proud of his
Confederate ancestor, even if he was on the wrong side of history.
He summarized his view of the war in a poem, ``A Salute To The
Blue, From The Gray,'' that he had hoped to read at the dedication
ceremony:
</P>
<P>
   ``For while gray and blue are colors/
</P>
<P>
   For which men have fought and died./
</P>
<P>
   There was no color to the courage/
</P>
<P>
   That was shown by either side.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
