<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VANCOUVER-ISLA     07-14 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VANCOUVER-ISLAND-$ADV19-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VANCOUVER ISLAND: the island.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On another day, we drove up Radar Hill, a World War II radar
installation with sweeping views up and down the coast. Although we
didn't take the steep, long hike down to the beach, we did follow
the half-mile Schooner Trail through majestic, mossy forest, down
to Schooner Cove, yet another perfect beach (they're a dime a dozen
around here) with no more than a handful of people on it. Just next
door stretched Long Beach, all 6.8 miles of it, the centerpiece of
the Pacific Rim Park, and its most popular area.
</P>
<P>
   But we hardly needed to seek out beaches, since facing Frank
Island was a fine one. Unlike the majority of the beaches on this
stretch of coast, Chesterman is not part of the park, and is
developed. Although it is lined with private houses and a few
bed-and-breakfasts _ attractive homes, most large and expensive
looking _ they are almost invisible under a heavy fringe of
towering old-growth trees. Quite visible on a rocky point at the
end of the curving beach is the Wickaninnish Inn, a handsome
46-room hotel that opened in August 1996. We drove in to take a
look, and were impressed with the well-designed, three-story cedar
post-and-beam structure, the splendid views and the spacious,
high-ceilinged dining room looking over the water. (Seeing a few of
the luxurious rooms with fireplaces and ocean views, we wished we
could stay on.) The restaurant, the one elegant dining spot in the
area, was fully booked, so we reserved for a few days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   When the time came, we decided to hike down the beach to dinner,
which was delightful at sunset, and considerably more challenging
on the return, by flashlight, after a bottle of excellent Reserve
'95 Blue Mountain pinot gris, from a British Columbia vineyard. The
sophisticated menu, starring local fish as well as entries from
Hawaii and other seas, was impressive, and the service was
attentive _ all in all, a surprise on these remote shores.
</P>
<P>
   Our most adventurous trip was to Hot Springs Cove, one of the
popular excursions out of Tofino, which takes a good half day (the
sunset version sounded enticing too). We signed on to a comfortable
cabin cruiser for the hour-and-a-half trip up the coast, along with
about 10 other passengers and our First Nations captain (the
Indians in the region are called First Nations people) and his crew
of one. Along the way, we did a little whale-watching, adjusting
the route when the captain heard whales had been spotted in the
vicinity. Because he was generous sharing his radio information, a
couple of Zodiacs crammed with whale-watchers rushed to our
location more than once, but the most any of us saw were several
tantalizing spouts. (Mid-March to early April is the high season
for seeing migrating gray whales in these waters.)
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, we came into a deep cove that felt more like a
fjord, and debarked along with another boatload at the wharf for
the one-mile boardwalk trek through more lovely forest, carrying
our bathing suits and towels. The natural hot springs, long used by
the Indians, are now part of a provincial park. Up above the
shoreline are a cluster of small steaming, rocky pools, with
towering trees as backdrop. (There is a clean bathhouse for
changing, but no facilities.) After soaking in the water _ at the
upper limit of tolerable heat for me _ along with a handful of
other visitors, and edging along from one pool to the other, we
felt too Jell-O-like to clamber down the sharp, slippery rocks to
the water's edge. Some did, and they could actually sit in small
hot puddles trickling down the rocks while gentle cool waves broke
around them.
</P>
<P>
   It's the luck of the draw here whether you encounter just a few
other bathers or find yourself part of a loud and hilarious group _
something about the communal pools and the setting makes people
giggly. Not long after we arrived, a slightly boisterous ``Hi,
Dude'' group left to meet their boat, and the rest of us soaked in
relative serenity, looking out at the Pacific, where whispers of
fog were starting to drift in.
</P>
<P>
   After that day of exertion, we stayed put on our minuscule
island home, doing nothing more exciting than exploring the
colorful tidal pools. Our sole neighbor came bounding over the
rocks at midday, breaking the understood code of solitude to bring
us a wild salmon that he had caught and cleaned a half-hour before.
After grilling it on the barbecue that night, we resolved one
gastronomic issue: the mystique of wild salmon, its quality versus
that of the farm-raised version, is no myth. The dense, delicious
fish tasted unforgettably of the deep Pacific.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
