<HEADER>
A4865 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VANCOUVER-ISLA     07-14 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VANCOUVER-ISLAND-$ADV19-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VANCOUVER ISLAND: deep Pacific.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Park
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Rim National Park Reserve: For general information year
round, contact the Reserve, Post Office Box 280, Ucluelet, British
Columbia V0R 3A0; telephone, Monday to Friday, 8 a.m. to 12 p.m.
and 12:30 to 4 p.m.: (250) 726-7721; fax (250) 726-4720. For
information on summer park programs, call (250) 726-4212 from
mid-March to mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent paperback, Official Guide to Pacific Rim National
Park Reserve, with maps and color photos, gives complete
information, including descriptions of plant and animal life, for
the entire park; $10.50, plus tax, calculated at $1.42 Canadian to
the dollar; you can order the book from the following toll-free fax
order-form number: (888) 888-8187. It is also available at the Wild
Side Bookseller and at other bookstores and gift shops in Tofino.
</P>
<P>
   There is a campground, Green Point, in the Long Beach unit of
the park, in woods overlooking the Pacific. A walk-in site is $9.85
a night in peak season; a drive-in site, $14, in peak season. For
reservations (there is a $4.50 fee), call (800) 689-9025.
</P>
<P>
   Interpretive programs are given in the park from June 26 to
Sept. 13, for modest fees. They include evening slide presentations
at Green Point campground on such subjects as shipwrecks along the
coast, and guided walks built around tide pools, sand dunes or the
rain forest. Call (250) 726-4212.
</P>
<P>
   We found the park's boardwalk trails beautifully maintained and
clean. They are ideal for small children or those who might have
difficulty managing ordinary trails.
</P>
<P>
   Lodging and Dining
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Wickaninnish Inn &LR;  is three miles south of Tofino on Highway
4; Post Office Box 250, Tofino, British Columbia V0R 2Z0; (250)
725-3100, fax (250) 725-3110; Web site: www.wickinn.com. For
reservations, call (800) 333-4604.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms are luxurious and attractively furnished, emphasizing
local materials; all have fireplaces and balconies with ocean
views. Summer rates: double rooms from $183 to $240. There are also
winter packages for storm-watching weekends November through
February and whale-watching rates March through May.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome  &UR; Pointe Restaurant  &LR; at the Inn has water views and
careful service. Open daily for breakfast, lunch and dinner; dinner
for two with wine, around $70 to $85. Reservations for dinner
required year round; book well ahead in summer, as hotel guests get
priority. The bar, On-the-Rocks, is open daily from 11 a.m. to 11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   For information on hotel, motel and B&AMP;B accommodations in
Tofino, call the  &UR; Tofino Information Center,  &LR; (250) 725-3414, fax
(250) 725-3296. Open daily 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., June through
December. Faxes will be answered year round.
</P>
<P>
   We spent a night at the  &UR; Duffin Cove Resort,  &LR; in one of the six
``studio'' rooms in a unit overlooking the water; the rooms are
smallish and plain, with funky decor and balconies with lovely
views over a cove; $95 for a double. There are also two cabins,
$137 a double, and four one-bedroom suites with kitchenettes in
another building (not right on the water), $123, double occupancy.
Post Office Box 178, Tofino, British Columbia V0R 2Z0; (250)
725-3448 or (888) 629-2903, fax (250) 725-2390.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a number of resorts on Highway 4 between Tofino
and Ucluelet, most on the ocean side, and several attractive B&AMP;B's
on Lynn Road behind Chesterman Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Excursions
</P>
<P>
   The Tofino Information Center can also provide details on
whale-watching, kayaking and other excursions in the area. Downtown
Tofino is a hive of activity, with many small shops offering trips
and tours; by walking around, you can check out those that interest
you.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Wild Side Bookseller,  &LR; 320 Main St. (250) 725-2070, is open
daily year round and serves as an informal information center. It
is affiliated with Tofino Sea Kayaking, and carries a wide
selection of guidebooks, along with books on kayaking and
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Two kayaking companies in Tofino offer day trips:  &UR; Remote
Passages,  &LR;  (250) 725-3330, and  &UR; Tofino Sea Kayaking,  &LR; (250)
725-4222 (it also has overnight options).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tofino Air,  &LR; on the main dock in the harbor at the foot of
First Street, offers scenic flights; a 20-minute flight (the
minimum) for three people in a Cessna 180 is $92; (250) 725-4454.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Springs Cove: Several local operators make trips here. We
booked through  &UR; Seaside Adventures,  &LR; which is connected with Duffin
Cove Resort, for the half-day trip, which takes five and a half to
six hours; $53 per adult, $49 students and seniors, $35 ages 6 to
12. 300 Main St., Tofino; (888) 332-4252 or (250) 725-2292.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weather
</P>
<P>
   Although the west coast of Vancouver Island is famous for its
fog and winter storms, we had perfect weather, with the exception
of one foggy day, the August week we spent in the Tofino area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
