<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFGHANISTAN-U.N.-290&AMP;     07-14 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHANISTAN-U.N.-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N.'S IMPATIENCE GROWS OVER AFGHAN RESTRICTIONS ON AID WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The top U.N. official responsible for
Afghanistan said Tuesday that patience was running out with the
militant Islamic movement that controls most of the country and
that its disruptive stream of edicts has jeopardized all
international aid programs there.
</P>
<P>
   The movement, known as the the Taliban, Tuesday renewed an
ultimatum to all private aid organizations to move collectively
into an abandoned and broken down student hostel outside the Afghan
capital, Kabul, or leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an organization that hands out edicts to us that
prevent us from doing our job,'' said the official, Lakhdar
Brahimi, a former Algerian foreign minister who is U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Anna's special envoy for Afghanistan. He is in New
York to attend a meeting Tuesday of countries aiding Afghanistan
and one on Friday of U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Taliban, who have sought to gain tighter
control over relief agencies and make their workers abide by its
strict version of Islamic law, issued an edict forcing all foreign
Muslim women working for the United Nations to be accompanied by a
close male relative.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Taliban and the United Nations reached a broad
agreement to cooperate on working conditions in Afghanistan. That
pact was reached after tensions between Taliban representatives and
the United Nations led to a physical assault on one worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of that agreement, things are not what they should be
on the ground in Afghanistan,'' Brahimi said. He said he had told
the Security Council on Tuesday morning that the Taliban ``don't
seem to be taking any decision that is right concerning the work of
the humanitarian community in Afghanistan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are extremely concerned, worried,'' he said. ``We have
already informed the Taliban that this is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Brahimi defended the May agreement with the Taliban, which has
been criticized by some aid organizations and United Nations
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement that we have was indispensable, even if it has
weaknesses,'' he said. ``It was necessary to talk to the Taliban.
It was necessary to see if we can find a basis for us to work in
acceptable conditions. If these conditions are not acceptable my
opinion is that we will have to tell the Taliban: You have signed
an agreement. You will implement it, or let us go and work
somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Both donor nations and U.N. agencies as well as private relief
groups have faced calls for a withdrawal of foreign workers and a
curtailment of the aid on which the country depends for emergency
medical and food needs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Alfredo Witschi-Cestari, the U.N.
coordinator for Afghanistan, said that after the May agreement was
signed, there was ``tremendous enthusiasm'' in some ministries in
Kabul that deal with foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Witschi-Cestari, who is based in Pakistan, said that the accord
provided some positive results, especially in rural areas, where
cooperation increased and aid programs began to take off.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Taliban hard-liners in the ministry
for the prevention of vice and the promotion of virtue began to
issue contrary orders attacking many development programs,
Witschi-Cestari said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are Taliban who know that they have to come to terms
with the international community,'' he said. But how the divisions
and ambiguities in the movement resolve themselves remains to be
seen, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The calls for agencies to pull back are coming at a time when
peace in large areas Afghanistan controlled by the Taliban _
combined with good rain and international aid programs and projects
to remove land mines _ have allowed Afghanistan to produce its
largest harvest since the late 1970s, before the 1979 Soviet
invasion and the years of civil war that followed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Taliban, which controls about 85 percent of Afghanistan,
recently reopened fighting to take more land from opponents in the
country's north. Tuesday the Security Council called on all sides
to declare a cease-fire and resume talks that broke down May 3.
</P>
<P>
   In a presidential statement, just short of a resolution, the
Council also noted that the Taliban had signed the May agreement
pledging its cooperation with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   After briefing the Security Council on Tuesday, Brahimi told
reporters, ``The Taliban must know that not only is there a limit
to what you can stand, but that there are growing pressures on us _
in particular from the donor community _ to say that there's a
limit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
