<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SEEKS TESTIMONY FROM SECRET SERVICE AGENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Emboldened by a recent court victory, Whitewater
independent counsel Kenneth Starr has issued subpoenas for the
testimony of a dozen Secret Service agents for evidence of
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
administration officials and lawyers involved in the inquiry said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas ordered Larry Cockell, the agent in charge of the
presidential detail, along with other agents he supervises who
guard Clinton, to appear before the federal grand jury that is
investigating whether anyone committed obstruction of justice,
perjury or witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Two administration officials said the subpoenas required some of
the agents to appear before the grand jury on Thursday. In
response, the officials said, the administration was preparing to
file a sealed motion for a protective order that would block the
testimony of any agents while the Justice Department pursued a
further appeal of its contention that the agents should not be
compelled to testify. Attorney General Janet Reno filed a brief
Tuesday arguing that the full U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia should review the issue.
</P>
<P>
   As the legal battle was taking shape, a former Pentagon
colleague of Ms. Lewinsky, Linda Tripp, completed her fifth
appearance before the grand jury. Mrs. Tripp initiated the inquiry
when she called the independent counsel's office last January. She
is expected to return to the grand jury on Thursday, her spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas for the agents were issued following the decision
by a federal appeals panel last week upholding an order for the
testimony of three other Secret Service officials. The three-judge
panel of the court of appeals broadly rejected a claim by the
Treasury Department, which oversees the Secret Service, that agents
should be entitled to invoke a novel kind of privilege to maintain
the confidence of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department invoked the privilege to limit the
testimony of John Kelleher, the chief counsel to the Secret
Service, and two uniformed officers, Gary Byrne and Brian
Henderson. Investigators had sought to question the three men about
conversations they may have had about Ms. Lewinsky, who had worked
in the White House, lawyers involved in the inquiry said.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1996, Byrne had apparently informed Evelyn
Lieberman, then the deputy chief-of-staff at the White House, that
he had seen Ms. Lewinsky in the West Wing when he did not believe
she was authorized to be there. Ms. Lieberman has said that Ms.
Lewinsky was transferred to the Pentagon and removed from her White
House job because of ``immature and inappropriate behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   After a federal judge ordered the three Secret Service officials
to testify, the administration unsuccessfully appealed to the
three-judge panel. It gave the Justice Department seven days to
request that the full bench hear any further appeals. Such reviews
are rarely granted, but the move strongly suggests that the
administration will ultimately take the matter to the Supreme
Court, which would not decide whether to hear the case until after
its new term begins in October.
</P>
<P>
   The administration painted a dire picture of the consequences of
last week's decision compelling the testimony of the Secret
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case involves a national interest of the first magnitude:
the safety of the president of the United States,'' Ms. Reno
contended in the brief. ``The Secret Service has explained clearly
and unequivocally in uncontroverted declarations that the absence
of a privilege will gravely impair its ability to protect the
president and is likely to result in a national tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the independent counsel's office have
questioned more than 20 agents _ most outside the grand jury _ but
not about Clinton, lawyers involved in the inquiry said. The
questions have focused on the operations of the White House and on
Ms. Lewinsky's visits. Security records indicate that after she was
transferred to the Pentagon, Ms. Lewinsky made 37 visits to the
White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
