<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mystery surrounds land deal while Coke stonewallsBy Sallye
Salter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While Coca-Cola Co. stonewalls queries about plans for
its property adjacent to Centennial Olympic Park and whether it
will revive its early 1990s landmark tower proposal, land is
changing hands right in its back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Two land buys _ totaling $2.7 million _ across Simpson Street
from Coca-Cola's parkfront tract were completed over a 24-hour
period two weeks ago just as Coca-Cola was abandoning its plans to
buy and occupy Inforum, a parkside office building.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery buyer in both transactions was Atlantic Financial
Group, an Arlington, Texas-based firm. ``We are working with a
client on that parcel of land and are under a confidentiality
agreement not to discuss it,'' said Stephen Brookshire, a partner
in the firm, which buys properties and leases them to corporations.
He expects his client to disclose plans for the mostly vacant sites
in 30 to 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Is that client Coca-Cola?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in a position to talk about that,'' said Coca-Cola
spokesman Mark Preisinger. ``We are not in a position to talk about
any acquisition of property in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will Coca-Cola say whether a tower _ an on-again and
off-again proposal as high as 48 stories _ is on again in its real
estate planning since its efforts to buy the 710,000 square foot
Inforum collapsed. The company leases about a half million square
feet of office space at two Midtown towers and has several times
considered adding buildings at its North Avenue headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are exploring a number of options,'' Preisinger said,
refusing to confirm or rule out any and stressing that no decision
has been made.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Coca-Cola representatives have been
talking to owners of some other properties near its parkfront tract
about buying their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``They met with us about a month ago,'' said Jim Hochgertle,
whose wife is among heirs owning property at 235 Simpson St., which
lies between two of the parcels purchased by Atlantic Financial.
The property is currently occupied by Superior Printing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent an offer in the mail two weeks ago, and we've heard
nothing back except a phone call that they received it.'' The
family, which has owned the 19,500-square-foot property since 1962,
is asking $50 a square foot, and Coca-Cola is offering $28,
Hochgertle said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's record of buying properties in the area between the
park and its North Avenue headquarters has been established over
the past decade. On those purchases, Coca-Cola typically strived
for anonymity, buying through affiliates. For its Olympic City
festival area near the park, Coca-Cola spent $8 million buying two
blocks across Baker Street from Centennial Olympic Park. The area
is a key part of the area that has been designated for
redevelopment by the Centennial Olympic Park Authority. The company
leased other properties in that area before the Olympics. Since the
early 1990s, the soft drink giant has made a concerted effort to
beef up land holdings around its North Avenue base.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
