<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MORE QUERIES ON ACCOUNTING DRUB CENDANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news got worse Tuesday for investors in Cendant Corp.,
the marketing and franchising company whose accounting problems
have devastated its stock price over the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   On April 16, Cendant saw the stock price fall 46 percent after
it reported finding ``accounting irregularities'' in the 1997
ledgers of a unit of CUC International, which merged with HFS Inc.
late last year to form Cendant.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the stock, still battered, was bruised again as top
Cendant executives warned that the CUC division's questionable
accounting practices were deeper, wider and older than had
originally been reported _ and that less serious but previously
undetected accounting errors had compounded the financial damage.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant shares, which had fallen $3.125 on Monday after news of
the broader problems leaked into the marketplace, closed at
$15.6875 Tuesday, down $3.1875 more in heavy trading. Cendant had
almost touched $42 a share earlier this year, before the accounting
problems arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have certainly had a stock meltdown, but we have not had a
company meltdown,'' Henry Silverman, the Cendant chief executive,
said in an interview Tuesday. Silverman was previously chairman of
HFS Inc., whose franchises include Howard Johnson and Ramada Inn
hotels and Avis car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company warned Wall Street on Tuesday that its 1998
income might decline somewhat from current expectations, Silverman
said that profits were still expected to approach $1 billion in
1998 and that cash flow remained very strong.
</P>
<P>
   But that good news was dwarfed by the news that the accounting
irregularities under investigation were not limited to the
shopping-club membership program at CUC, as Cendant originally
reported, but affected ``all the major business units of CUC.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the irregularities were not confined to 1997 financial
statements, as Cendant said in April, but also affected CUC's
financial statements for 1995 and 1996. According to the company,
the irregularities included the improper use of merger reserves to
create ``fictitious revenues'' and the fabrication of accounts
receivable to inflate reported assets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company has found a number of serious
accounting errors, which it defines as practices that may not have
been deliberately deceptive but that did not conform to generally
accepted accounting principles. These included the use of
inappropriate depreciation schedules and delays in recognizing the
impact of insurance claims.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant also disclosed that it had doubled its estimate of the
effect the accounting problems would have on its 1997 profits,
which were originally reported as $900 million, or $1 a share,
before one-time charges that include merger expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Cendant warned that the accounting problems could
reduce its operating profit to somewhere between $783 million and
$801 million, or 87 to 89 cents a share. Now, it expects to report
income of $648 million to $702 million, or between 72 and 78 cents
a share, before the extraordinary expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Those extraordinary costs will also be reduced, however, because
current and past merger expenses were found to have been improperly
inflated. As a result, although operating profits will be sharply
lower, Cendant's official net income for 1997, after all
adjustments, should at worst decline by a ``relatively immaterial''
$54 million, or about 6 cents a share, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   How could such a broad array of accounting missteps go
undetected for so long?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the $64 question,'' Silverman said. ``If people want
to deceive you, then they will do so. That is what fraud is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cendant, based in Parsippany, N.J., did not blame anyone on
Tuesday for the disputed accounting policies. Silverman said he
expected the board's audit committee to report on its extensive
investigation by the end of August. The company is also continuing
to provide information about the matter to the Securities and
Exchange Commission and the U.S. attorney's office in Newark, N.J.,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, Cendant announced that it had dismissed Cosmo
Corigliano, an executive vice president of CUC and its former chief
financial officer. It gave no explanation for Corigliano's
dismissal. Corigliano's lawyer, Gary Naftalis, said Tuesday that
his client ``absolutely denies any knowledge of any accounting
irregularities or any other wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Revised financial statements for Cendant are expected by early
August, Silverman said. That will allow the company to move ahead
on its pending acquisition of American Bankers Insurance Group,
subject to regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   According to Silverman, the company had been at work on
Tuesday's report since at least Saturday and the news ``leaked
out'' sometime late Monday morning, contributing to the sharp
decline in Cendant shares that day.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange called the company three times
during the day to press for release of any pertinent news,
Silverman said, and the company promised to make an announcement
before trading resumed Tuesday. The company's lawyers have asked
the SEC to investigate Monday's trading in Cendant shares.
</P>
<P>
   Both Silverman and Walter Forbes, the former CUC chief executive
who is now chairman of Cendant, said they spent more than two hours
Tuesday morning fielding telephone questions from Wall Street
analysts and institutional investors, whose moods ranged from
patience to outrage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most outraged was Timothy Stevenson, a money manager
for the First Capital Group unit of First Union Corp., who said he
sold more than 250,000 Cendant shares Tuesday morning, despite the
day's downdraft. ``It's been one bad story after another,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts were more patient, and a few privately
commended Cendant for the wealth of detail it released Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
