<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SUICIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE DEFENDS PROPOSAL STRIPPING DOCTORS OF PRESCRIPTION LICENSES IN
ASSISTED-SUICIDE CASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., used an impassioned speech on the sanctity of life Tuesday
to defend his legislative proposal that would require the federal
government to strip doctors of their prescription licenses if they
intentionally help terminally ill patients commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all boils down to: `What do you think a human life is
worth?''' said Hyde, who was presiding over a subcommittee hearing
on his proposed Lethal Drug Abuse Prevention Act. ``Human life, no
matter how wretched, has an intrinsic value.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde introduced his legislation last month in response to
Attorney General Janet Reno's decision that the federal Controlled
Substances Act does not prohibit doctors from prescribing lethal
doses of medication to dying patients. In her decision, Reno said
the federal government would not stand in the way of doctors who
help terminally ill patients kill themselves in Oregon, the only
state where physician-assisted suicide is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Reno's decision could turn the ``slippery slope'' of
physician-assisted death, which he said began when the Supreme
Court legalized abortion, into a ``precipitous cliff.'' Oregon's
law permitting doctors to help with suicide could lead to the
untimely deaths of the ``unwanted, the despised, the helpless'' in
society, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Coleman, president of the disability rights group Not Dead
Yet, agreed with Hyde, saying his proposal would ``save the lives
of people with disabilities from a society which too often wishes
that we were dead.'' Coleman, who uses a wheelchair, urged Congress
to ``turn back the steamroller of the euthanasia movement before it
is too late.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oregon's Democratic Gov. John Kitzhaber defended his state's
unique and controversial law as a legitimate exercise of a state's
right to regulate physicians. He assailed Hyde's proposal as having
a ``chilling effect'' on doctors who treat terminally ill patients
in severe pain. If the bill is enacted, he said, doctors will
``think twice'' before prescribing needed pain medication out of
fear that they will lose their prescription licenses if their
patient dies from the medicine they ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't use the artifice of an amendment to the Controlled
Substances Act to establish a precedent-setting intervention by the
federal government into the practice of medicine,'' Kitzhaber told
the Constitution subcommittee. ``Don't intimidate and put at risk
physicians when your true objective is altering the choices
available to terminally ill patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association, despite its opposition to
physician-assisted suicide, also came out against Hyde's proposal
as striking fear in doctors who believe they must prescribe strong,
potentially lethal medicine to treat _ not kill _ their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physician-assisted suicide is ethically incompatible with the
physician's role as healer,'' Dr. Thomas Reardon, the association's
president-elect, told the subcommittee. ``However, we fear the
real-world consequences of the bill would be to discourage the kind
of appropriate aggressive palliative care that can dissuade
patients in pain from seeking just such an early death.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's 1994 Death with Dignity Act, both passed and later
upheld by a referendum, permits doctors to prescribe lethal doses
of medicine to patients expected to live only six more months. Two
doctors must share the dire prognosis and agree that the patient is
mentally competent to ask for medical assistance in committing
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, while allowed to prescribe lethal medications, are
prohibited under the law from giving deadly injections. At least
three terminally ill patients in Oregon have committed suicide with
the help of a doctor since the law went into effect Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   In her decision, Reno warned that doctors in states with no
assisted-suicide statute, or even those in Oregon who ignore the
law's safeguards, could face federal penalties. Reno, in refusing
to hinder the Oregon law, rejected the position of Thomas
Constantine, head of the Drug Enforcement Administration, who in
November said physicians prescribing lethal doses would be in
violation of the federal Controlled Substances Act and would run
the risk of losing their prescription licenses, which DEA issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
