A4877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCI-BRAZIL-COX     07-14 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-BRAZIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth enchanted by Brazil
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLAN TA _ It may not be quite a gold rush down in Latin
America, but for phone companies looking south from Atlanta, there
is glitter aplenty.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America is seen as a virtual chain of underdeveloped
markets, countries with troubled pasts but great potential, that
are now growing furiously. And for the companies that can service
and exploit that growth, there are fortunes to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Among those anxious to pan for the good stuff are BellSouth and
MCI.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, based in Atlanta and known for its local service to
the nine Southeastern states, has a ``back nine'' strategy in which
it has invested in nine Latin American countries, from Nicaragua to
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Most lucrative of all is Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   A country of about 163 million people, Brazil is woefully
underserved when it comes to phones. The nation has about 10 phones
for each 100 inhabitants _ compared with about 65 in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The stunningly long waiting list to get service from Telebras,
the national phone company, led BellSouth into a multibillion
dollar detour. Wireless, the company reasoned, would be a quicker,
easier and ultimately cheaper way to reach millions of potential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   So last year, when the Brazilian government sold the rights to
compete against Telebras, which has its own wireless offering,
BellSouth won two bids: one to provide service in Sao Paulo, the
other for the northeast of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   After months of frantic construction and marketing efforts,
service was turned up this spring.
</P>
<P>
   First results were mouth-watering. BellSouth has quickly signed
up about 230,000 customers in Sao Paulo, as well as 16,000 in the
poorer and more sparsely inhabited northeast. Plans are to have
nearly a half-million subscribers in Sao Paulo by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil privatization is barely getting started.
</P>
<P>
   The country is dividing Telebras into three wireline companies,
10 wireless units and one company offering long-distance, including
international. Later this year, Brazil plans to entertain bids for
those companies. BellSouth in the United States has been trying to
put together a package of local, wireless, Internet and
long-distance services _ as well as cable television in some
cities. ``Bundling'' is seen as the key to market dominance, and
the same kind of logic can apply in Latin America. And in fact,
BellSouth has registered for the auctions, although the company has
not decided which bids to make, said John Price, spokesman for
BellSouth International.
</P>
<P>
   But the enticement of privatization in a large and growing
economy has not gone unnoticed. As early as this month, Brazil
could start taking bids for Embratel, the company providing
long-distance and international long-distance in Brazil. Among the
other bidders is MCI, whose business unit is based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   MCI, which is planning a merger into WorldCom, has reserved the
right to bid for Embratel, said Manuel Wernicky, spokesman for
MCI's international operations.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has so far come into all bidding with the strategy of
overwhelming the opposition, plunking down bids so high they have
often been double those of the second-place bidder. But MCI _
especially as part of a very aggressive WorldCom _ is no financial
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   The result could be a multibillion dollar showdown: The
Brazilian government hopes to raise between $15 billion and $20
billion from the sale of the Telebras companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
