<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WYETH-ART-MAINE-$ADV1     07-14 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WYETH-ART-MAINE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYING TRIBUTE TO MAINE'S NO. 1 SUMMER FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19.)  
 (JT)  
 By DEBORAH WEISGALL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKLAND, Maine _ From the front window of a converted Methodist
church here, Penobscot Bay glimmered pale blue in the hazy June
afternoon. A huge roller was smoothing the street's new asphalt,
and down the block a landscaper's backhoes tied up traffic. Inside,
the church's old amber windowpanes lighted the stairwells like a
golden sunrise. Workers hung paintings in its newly finished
galleries. It felt as if the staff was rushing to finish a big
summer house for the family's arrival; in fact, that is what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, the Farnsworth Center for the Wyeth Family in Maine
opened, a place dedicated to the work of the illustrator N.C.
Wyeth, his son Andrew and Andrew's son Jamie. The 130-year-old
church contains the center's galleries; there is also a private
study area, in a separate building, with storage for art and
archives.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since N.C. Wyeth bought a place in Port Clyde, south of
Rockland, in the early 1930s, the family has summered here, and
Andrew Wyeth's painting ``Christina's World'' is, for many people,
synonymous with Maine. The Wyeth center is attached to the
Farnsworth Art Museum, a respected 50-year-old institution that
focuses on artists connected with Maine and that has built one of
the best small, specialized collections in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyeth center doubled the size of the Farnsworth and involved
rebuilding whole blocks of downtown Rockland. Designed by
Schwartz/Silver, a Boston firm, it is beautifully scaled and
elegantly complements the existing brick gallery and the
19th-century home of Lucy Farnsworth, the museum's founder.
</P>
<P>
   But there are dissonances. The low wooden shed containing the
study area echoes the long ell of the Farnsworth Mansion, but ends
with a fieldstone carriage house. Why fieldstone, when elsewhere
the architects were careful to use local materials like granite
(once a big industry in coastal Maine) and clapboard? The Wyeths
wanted fieldstone to remind them of their winter home in Chadds
Ford, Pa. And, besides, it's their center; the Farnsworth raised
$11 million in less than two years to build it for them. No other
artists working in Maine could generate this kind of money;
criticism of the Wyeths' work has never affected its great
popularity or high prices.
</P>
<P>
   This summer the Wyeth family enterprise has produced two lavish
catalogs (published by Abrams and Little, Brown) and mounted three
exhibitions. Andrew's landscapes are at the Whitney Museum of
American Art in New York; the whole family, including Andrew's
sisters, is represented at the Speed Art Museum in Louisville, Ky.
``Wondrous Strange: The Wyeth Tradition'' inaugurates the Wyeth
center in Rockland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wondrous Strange'' was conceived and hung by Betsy James
Wyeth, Andrew's wife and Jamie's mother. The huge show takes up the
entire museum. It was supposed to fit into the new church
galleries, but Mrs. Wyeth, who, according to the museum's director,
Christopher Crossman, was given free rein, chose so many works that
the Farnsworth's permanent collection was taken down to make room
for it.
</P>
<P>
   That is too bad. Maine's clear light, its bays and islands, its
rocky coast and steep hills have attracted artists for two
centuries, and the Farnsworth has acquired fine works by Fitz Hugh
Lane, Frederick Church, Albert Bierstadt, Winslow Homer, John
Marin, George Bellows, Edward Hopper, Rockwell Kent, Milton Avery
and Louise Nevelson, who grew up in Rockland. Alex Katz, Neil
Welliver and Robert Indiana are among the artists now working near
Rockland, and under its curator, Susan Larsen, the Farnsworth is
expanding the scope of its exhibitions and increasing its holdings
of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has collected Wyeths, too, but their context, their
place in the story of Maine art, is something that visitors to the
museum will glimpse in only one gallery this summer, where a show
called ``Bellows and Benson in Maine: The Dream and the Reality''
has been installed. Perhaps it was intentional that you can see
hardly anything but Wyeth this summer. Money buys space. The new
center is devoted exclusively to the Wyeths. So the Farnsworth
Center for the Wyeth Family in Maine will never return the favor
the Farnsworth Art Museum is doing it this summer by clearing out
for ``Wondrous Strange.''
</P>
<P>
   This could become awkward, especially since it is not exactly
clear what the center will have to show. The news release
announcing the center begins: ``With holdings of some 4,500 works
of arts and objects made available by the families of Andrew Wyeth
and Jamie Wyeth, the Farnsworth Art Museum in Rockland has
established a new Center for the Wyeth Family in Maine.'' When
asked what ``made available'' meant, Crossman said that there was a
nonspecific letter of intent from Andrew and Betsy Wyeth stating
that works of art and archival material relating to Maine would
eventually come to the museum. They have given nothing yet; they
can move things in and out of the center as they wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wondrous Strange'' is a loan exhibition. Many of the works
have nothing to do with Maine. The show aims to reveal Andrew and
Jamie Wyeth as storytellers in N.C. Wyeth's tradition and
illustrate the influence of N.C.'s teacher, Howard Pyle, on all
three Wyeth generations. Pyle and N.C. Wyeth, masters of
illustration, exemplified the heated-up romanticism of
turn-of-the-century America. While Andrew and Jamie work in cooler
times, there is no question that some of the images in ``Wondrous
Strange'' are really weird. Andrew paints a corpse emerging from a
block of melting ice and severed hands perched on ice floes; Jamie
portrays himself with a pumpkin head and as a clownish scarecrow.
He depicts lighthouses with the same fierce perspective that his
grandfather used for Peg Leg Pete.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to guess the stories behind these images. The
illustrations by N.C. and Pyle are given the titles of the texts
they refer to; the titles of Andrew's and Jamie's paintings are not
always illuminating. Andrew's works, in the merciless way they
render detail, could resonate with John Updike's bleak vision of
America. But Updike's prose sets up a paradox; if he sees godless,
loveless emptiness, his words reach for redemption. And Updike
looks relentlessly. Andrew Wyeth veers off into piety.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ``Night Shadow'' shows a sleeping woman, her head
dark, her breasts brightly and explicitly lighted. According to the
catalog, Andrew uses this work ``to memorialize the emotions he
felt upon viewing his father, N.C. Wyeth, in his casket.'' A
painting by Jamie titled ``Bowdoin Sophomore'' presents a boy,
possibly naked, draped in a blanket and holding a starfish.
Another, called ``Orca,'' shows an adolescent with electric hair
wearing a British uniform from the Revolutionary War (a red coat
that belonged to Pyle, according to Crossman). Jamie's casual
presentation of the macabre often reads like Stephen King, but he
is too detached to be scary.
</P>
<P>
   The real story the Wyeths are telling is the story of their own
celebrity. Orca is the name of a Maine island boy who often models
for Jamie Wyeth. The woman in ``Night Shadow'' turns out to be
Helga Testorf, who worked for the Wyeths. Although the artists
might disagree, these paintings could well be about class and
privilege, an enduring subject of art by summer people. Certainly
it informs the paintings in the small exhibition that runs
concurrently with ``Wondrous Strange.'' ``Bellows and Benson in
Maine'' centers on two recent gifts to the Farnsworth from the
bequest of Elizabeth B. Noyce: paintings by George Bellows and
Frank W. Benson, both of whom summered on the coast at the
beginning of this century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
