<HEADLINE>
MOVIE RATINGS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19.)  
 (JT)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADELINE
</P>
<P>
   Hatty Jones, Frances McDormand, Nigel Hawthorne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Daisy von Scherler Mayer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Madeline's appendix comes out. Genevieve the dog has a
role. Pepito, the sullen son of the Spanish Ambassador, moves in
next door and causes trouble. Miss Clavel (Ms. McDormand, fetching
in a wimple) points her finger in the air and says, ``Something is
not right!'' more than once. But on screen Ludwig Bemelmans'
Madeline stories have been expanded in a major way. The plot
includes a kidnapping as well as a looming threat that the school
will be sold out from under the 12 little girls in two straight
lines.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ The kidnapping is done without harm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ The closest thing is a joke involving smelly
cheese. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 _ Those who love the books will crow with recognition
but may find the movie a bit slow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-9 _ It's got all the right stuff for girls: plucky orphan
heroine who defies authority, cute boy, cute dog. Boys may be a
tougher sell, but Pepito does ride a motorcycle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10 AND UP _ Big kids and teen-agers won't want to go unless
they're baby-sitting, but fans of Bemelmans, Ms. McDormand and
Paris will find something to like. And parents will watch with
relief: finally, a ``children's'' movie with nothing objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   THE MASK OF ZORRO &QL; 
Anthony Hopkins, Antonio Banderas, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Stuart
Wilson, Matt Letscher &QL; 
Directed by Martin Campbell &QL; 
PG-13 _ 130 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That Z on the neck of Don Rafael Montero (Wilson) was carved 20
years ago by Zorro, a now aging Don Diego de la Vega (Hopkins).
When Zorro first opposed him, Montero was the Spanish governor of
California and brutally oppressed the peasants. Now Montero
enslaves them to mine gold. But behold the Z, slashed again on
walls and flaming on hillsides. Now there's a new Zorro (
Banderas), trained by Don Diego to champion the people and become
the latest movie incarnation of the pulp fiction hero originally
conjured by the police reporter Johnston McCulley. &QL; 
VIOLENCE _ Wordplay and shootings yield heinous injuries, but the
effect is softened by the spirit of dashing adventure. &QL; 
SEX _ None per se, but the Banderas Zorro and the beautiful Elena
(Ms. Zeta-Jones) do some serious smoldering on the dance floor, and
later she loses some articles of clothing to deft flicks of his
blade. &QL; 
PROFANITY _ None. &QL; 
For Which Children?  &QL; 
AGES 3-8 _ ``Children should never have to see the things we do,''
Montero says as he's about to execute three peasants. That is
certainly true of young children. &QL; 
AGES 9-12 _ By this age bracket, however, they are better able to
handle the violence, which is no worse than what they may encounter
in other films and on television, and they will love both Zorros. &QL; 
AGES 13 AND UP _ The more hip among them may turn up their noses,
but most teen-agers should have fun at this movie.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL SOLDIERS &QL; 
Kirsten Dunst, Gregory Smith, Jay Mohr, David Cross, Denis Leary,
Ann Magnuson, Phil Hartman; and the voices of Tommy Lee Jones,
Frank Langella, Ernest Borgnine, George Kennedy, Christina Ricci &QL; 
Directed by Joe Dante &QL; 
PG-13 _ 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Fighting, talking soldier action figures, the Commando Elite,
have been programmed to ``show no mercy'' to their sworn enemies,
the Gorgonites, and to believe that the rest of the world are the
toys, not them. But their inventors ( Mohr and Cross) have
installed flawed microchips, which leads to a recall, but not
before the Commandos have hunted down the Gorgonites, added humans
to their list of enemies and waged a full-scale assault on the
neighborhood. &QL; 
VIOLENCE _ Adversaries are mangled and pulverized, the Gorgonite
leader ( Langella) is tortured, creepy Barbie-type dolls swarm over
people like the little dinosaurs from ``The Lost World,'' a boy is
set afire, an action figure's legs are ground up in a garbage
disposer, an action-figure regiment is chopped into mulch by a lawn
mower ... &QL; 
SEX _ None. &QL; 
PROFANITY _ Some rough soldierly talk and some alarmed parental
expletives. &QL; 
For Which Children? &QL; 
AGES 3-8 _ Though the combatants are toys, make no mistake: this is
a war movie and inappropriate for small children. &QL; 
AGES 9-12 _ Probably the best audience: pre-teen-agers will be
amused when they get some of the comic pop references and will be
sophisticated enough to realize that real toys can't do the things
these computer-generated ones can. &QL; 
AGES 13 AND UP _ Fans of special-effects driven shoot-'em-ups may
be attracted to the film, but it's doubtful that many older teens
will be drawn to a story about toy soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   LETHAL WEAPON 4  &QL; 
Directed by Richard Donner &QL; 
Mel Gibson, Danny Glover, Chris Rock, Joe Pesci, Jet Li, Rene
Russo &QL; 
R _ 135 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Martin Riggs (Gibson) and Roger Murtaugh (Glover) are back,
promoted to captains of the Los Angeles Police Department in a move
that's supposed to keep them out of trouble and off the streets.
Ha! This time the pair confront Chinese slave labor barons, in
particular the brutal, Rasputin-like Wah Sing Ku (Li). But as tough
as they are, the two old dogs of the 11-year-old action-comedy
franchise can't beat Father Time. ``Getting too old for this,''
grumbles Murtaugh. But a spectacular car chase _ so 80's! _ makes
everyone feel young again, if only for a few minutes. &QL; 
VIOLENCE _ ``Gunfights, explosions, sharks _ the usual,'' Riggs
says. Not to mention strangulation, arson, eye gouging, near-death
by goring and unnecessary dental procedures. &QL; 
SEX _ There's no time for sex. Two women, however, are pregnant and
unmarried. &QL; 
PROFANITY _ Continual. &QL; 
For Which Children?  &QL; 
UNDER AGE 11 _ The movie has its comedic elements, but it's
inappropriate for young children, and unless you'd like to hear the
dialogue and see the karate kicks repeated at home, don't take
them. &QL; 
AGES 11 AND UP _ Don't even try to keep them away. Boys will even
forgive Gibson his skirt in ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
