<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEWINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeWine, Hall join call to raise awareness of Sudanese famine
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Ohio lawmakers have joined to bring attention
to the famine killing hundreds in the East African country of
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Dayton, and U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine,
R-Ohio, both signed a letter asking their colleagues to pay more
attention to starvation and suffering in the Bahr el Ghazal region
of Sudan. Hall, DeWine and U.S. Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., will brief
legislators and their staff on the Sudanese famine Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is starting to step out more on humanitarian issues, and
there aren't many people in Congress showing that kind of
compassion,'' Hall said. ``I really appreciate his partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who visited Sudan in June, has pushed for more
humanitarian aid to ease the famine. He has said he has not seen
such a severe famine since he visited Ethiopia in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A severe drought aggravated a food shortage caused by Sudan's
14-year civil war. The Islamic government stopped humanitarian
relief flights into the area several months ago, pushing about 1
million Sudanese closer to starvation. The flights resumed in June,
but humanitarian workers could not curb the food shortage in time.
</P>
<P>
   The famine struck areas held by the Sudanese People's Liberation
Army, which has been fighting a guerrilla war against the Islamic
government. The United Nations, with help from the United States
and other countries, has provided some famine relief, but feeding
centers must turn away all but the most severe cases.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and DeWine have been working on another front to curb food
shortages in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Both are co-sponsors of the Africa: Seeds of Hope Act, a bill to
provide assistance to African farmers and help promote agricultural
research.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is an original sponsor in the House; DeWine introduced the
bill with U.S. Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., in June.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Brown Brewer, DeWine's spokeswoman, said the bill followed
DeWine's interest in agriculture development and complemented
another bill to help increase trade to the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Shannon Joyce at (202) 887-8307.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
