<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLDOL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich's wallet $247,618 lighter
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich spent nearly a
quarter-million dollars in legal fees in the past three months,
according to his latest filing with the Federal Election
Commission. His campaign spokesman said the money was for work
performed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the spokesman, Mike Shields, could not say what the $247,618
paid to the Atlanta law firm Arnall, Golden &AMP; Gregory was for.
Gingrich's lawyer, J. Randolph Evans, is a partner in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the bill did not arrive until sometime this spring,
which is why it showed up on Gingrich's report of campaign finances
since April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, Gingrich's longtime friend and political associate, did
not return telephone calls. But Gingrich retained him in late 1996
as the speaker's ethics case neared its dramatic conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Evans helped negotiate Gingrich's reprimand by his colleagues
and $300,000 penalty for violating House rules by giving its ethics
committee false and misleading letters about the role the speaker's
onetime political action committee, GOPAC, played in developing his
college course.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics committee has yet to act on another complaint
alleging that Gingrich violated House rules by accepting travel,
fees and other reimbursements from GOPAC and receiving undisclosed
and excessive campaign aid from GOPAC during his closest
re-election campaign in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Van Der Mied, the ethics committee's chief counsel, said he
could not comment on pending cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service is separately investigating
potential violations of tax law from Gingrich's integration of
tax-exempt organizations into his partisan operations and GOPAC's
solicitations of money for a charity that then passed the money
back to GOPAC.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said he did not know if the legal fees covered ethics
matters or the IRS inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker has paid lawyers more than $1 million from his
campaign account to defend him against ethics charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's FEC filing, which showed that he has $1 million in
cash on hand for an expected easy re-election campaign this year,
also indicated that the speaker is continuing to dispute $196,000
in fees to Jan Baran, the lawyer Evans replaced and Gingrich blamed
for sending the misleading letters.
</P>
<P>
   Shields had no comment on the money owed Baran.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the Georgia Senate race, Democratic candidate
Michael Coles is keeping his campaign afloat with hefty loans from
his personal line of credit at Charter Bank &AMP; Trust in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Coles, founder of the Great American Cookie Co., has loaned or
contributed to his campaign nearly $1.1 million, including $617,000
worth of loans and contributions during the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, Coles raised slightly less than $200,000
from individuals and political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell, seeking to fend off a challenge
from Coles, reported raising $837,000 during the past three months
and now has $3.2 million in available cash, compared with $1
million for Coles.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Ken Foskett
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
