A4902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SATELLITES-COX     07-14 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lott causes stir by airing China trade details
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In taking to the Senate floor on Tuesday to
announce that the Clinton administration's ``wholly inadequate''
export policy had resulted in the transfer of sensitive technology
to China, Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) ignited a tinder
box, with each political party blaming the other for endangering
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's unexpected delivery of the findings of what he termed an
``interim report'' of various Senate investigations, prompted
leading Senate Democrats to assail him for releasing classified
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is partisanship at its worst,'' said Minority Leader Tom
Daschle (D-S.D.). ``I am disappointed by the inaccuracies of the
statements and the recklessness of these statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats noted that Lott unveiled the findings just as
the wide-ranging investigation into campaign fund-raising abuses
appears to be sputtering to an end without any high-ranking White
House officials implicated.
</P>
<P>
   Defense policy experts expressed concern that an opportunity to
examine whether the nation's security has been placed at risk would
be lost in all the partisan rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among those questions is this: Did Loral Space and
Communications and Hughes Electronics help the Chinese figure out
why a satellite launch failed in February 1996 in southern China?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much willingness to accuse the other side of
partisanship; we need to discuss the facts,'' said Henry Sokolski,
the top Pentagon expert monitoring nuclear proliferation during the
Bush administration and who now runs the Nonproliferation Policy
Education Center in Virginia. Comparing the partisan outbreak on
Capitol Hill to two children denying blame over a broken vase,
Sokolski said that both parties seemed to be preoccupied with
blaming the other. ``It's kind of like two kids pointing at each
other saying, `He did it,' when the point is they are standing
there in their bare feet with broken glass everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger in all of this, Sokolski said, is that the focus will
be diverted away from closely examining the export policies of both
the Clinton and Bush administrations. ``It would be a shame if we
get stuck here in partisanship,'' he said. ``We need to address
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his floor statement, Lott said the Senate had
conducted 13 hearings and heard testimony from 32 witnesses in four
Senate committees. From that testimony, he said it was time for
Attorney General Janet Reno to appoint an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sharply criticizing the Clinton White House, Lott
said China's military had benefited from the satellite exports and
that the administration had ``ignored overwhelming information
regarding Chinese proliferation'' and ``embarked on a de facto
policy designed to protect China and U.S. satellite companies from
sanctions under U.S. proliferation law.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of where the Clinton administration has looked the
other way, Lott said testimony before the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee earlier this month revealed Defense Department
monitors are not required to be present at satellite launches in
China. ``No one in the U.S. government knows what transpired at
these launches or if U.S. laws and polices on technology transfer
were followed,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's satellite export control system relies on the good
will of the Commerce Department, a department which has repeatedly
demonstrated its willingness to ignore national security concerns
on satellite exports,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   American satellite makers contend transferring the jurisdiction
of approving satellite launches in China from the State Department
to the Commerce Department was crucial to their business.
</P>
<P>
   Stakes are high for the satellite industry. An analysis by the
Maryland-based Futron Corp. estimates that revenues from the U.S.
commerical satellite market, now valued at $5.7 billion, could be
worth more than six times that amount by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
