<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK15-COX     07-14 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves have decision concerning Wohlers
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Wohlers is expected to be back in an Atlanta
uniform Thursday for the Milwaukee series. What happens after that
not only determines how the club stocks its bullpen for the final
two months, it also could dictate Wohlers' future as a Brave.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was looking forward to getting his closer back,
manager Bobby Cox replied, ``Yeah, if he's ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And if he's not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to answer that,'' general manager John
Schuerholz said. ``We hope that doesn't happen but if it does,
we'll have to keep working to try to get him through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox has not determined when and how to use him and that decision
is ticklish. Wohlers' inconsistency would rule against pitching him
late in a game, though with Atlanta starters typically working so
long per start, the late innings may be Cox's only choice. And he
must use Wohlers, for leaving him in the bullpen for more than
three days without an outing could set him back further. A primary
reason Wohlers accepted his minor-league assignment was he wasn't
getting any work.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the decision to return to Atlanta is Wohlers', as
dictated by a verbal agreement he made before leaving the team June
19. Though the All-Star break was his original target to return,
Wohlers subsequently agreed to remain with Class AAA Richmond
another week (players with five years experience must approve
optional minor-league assignments), though it cost him some pension
time.
</P>
<P>
   His level of performance has hardly answered any questions _
it's only added more. Wohlers was the losing pitcher in his last
outing, the first game of a doubleheader Monday (one inning, three
hits, two earned runs, two walks, no strikeouts and a home run
allowed). That gave him a 21.60 ERA in seven appearances, with 15
hits, 12 walks, six Ks and six wild pitches in 6 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made some progress, in the opinion of (Richmond
pitching coach) Bill Fischer,'' Schuerholz said, ``proabably not
the amount of progress that either Mark or Bill or any of us would
like to see ultimately. But he has made great strides. And Mark,
according to Bill Fischer, feels very good about what he's done, he
feels very good about the progress he's made, even though the
results statistically may reflect otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of Pride
</P>
<P>
   The club as expected activated outfielder Curtis Pride before
Tuesday's game and returned first baseman Randall Simon to
Richmond. Out since June 28 with a larcerated left index finger,
Pride went 3-for-6 with a pair of walks in a Monday re-hab
appearance in a doubleheader with the Richmond Braves.
</P>
<P>
   His injury occured when Pride took a bat to the cinderblock wall
after a pop-out. Asked if he'd been working on his bat-handling, he
replied, ``Yeah, I've been taking meditation classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
