<SLUG> BC-HUFFY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huffy breaks even in earnings
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Huffy Corp. on Tuesday reported break-even
earnings for the second quarter due to a $12.6 million charge
related to the closing of its Celina bike plant.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to shut down the world's largest bike plant is
expected to enhance Huffy's bike division long term, but the move
cost the company a 25 percent gain in second-quarter net earnings.
Without the $12.6 million charge, Huffy's earnings would have
increased to $7.8 million, or 63 cents per share, compared with
$6.2 million, or 49 cents per share, during the second quarter last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy's second-quarter sales rose 3.4 percent to $220 million
from $213 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Miamisburg-based Huffy shocked its 1,000 hourly workers in
Celina on May 28th when the bike manufacturer said it will close
the plant within a year. The company plans to transfer only a
handful of skilled trade workers from Celina to its bike plant in
Farmington, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy plans to increase bike production at the Farmington plant
and will import more bikes from Asia and Mexico to cover the lost
production in Celina.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the decision to reconfigure the bicycle operation
unfavorably impacted our second-quarter earnings, the elimination
of excess production capacity and reduction of operating expenses
will enhance performance in 1999 and beyond,'' said Don R. Graber,
Huffy's chairman, president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategies to generate consistent, acceptable levels of
earnings continue to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Huffy's bike division has fully recovered from a disastrous 1995
when it lost $10.5 million and was having trouble competing with
cheaper imported bikes from China. Layoffs at its Celina bike plant
are expected to begin in August.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of this year, Huffy's net earnings rose
26 percent to $11.6 million, or 93 cents per share, prior to the
$12.6 million charge for closing its bike plant. Sales for the
six-month period increased about 5 percent to $402 million compared
with $385 million during the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy also makes basketball backboards and lawn and garden
tools, and markets inventory and supplier services.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
