A4922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM15-COX     07-14 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM takes fight to court in attempt to end strikes
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ General Motors Corp. sought help in federal court
Tuesday to end a pair of crippling auto strikes that so far have
cost it $1.2 billion, arguing that the monthlong walkouts are
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed on the same day GM reported that its
second-quarter profits plummeted 81 percent because of the strikes
in Flint, Mich., that have shut down nearly all of the company's
North American production.
</P>
<P>
   In its lawsuit, GM asked the court to force the United Auto
Workers into arbitration to decide the legality of the strikes the
automaker considers a breach of its national UAW contract. It also
said it may ask the judge to order the 9,200 striking workers back
to work and award the company unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the arbitration motion was scheduled for today.
</P>
<P>
   The action was sure to intensify the rift between the two sides
as talks at the two parts plants in Flint dragged on Tuesday with
no signs a settlement. The strikes are into their sixth week and
have idled 175,000 workers nationwide, including nearly 8,000 GM
workers in the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   While the Flint talks are at a standstill, negotiators for GM
and the UAW in Dayton aren't doing much better in settling issues
that threaten the future of two local brake factories.
</P>
<P>
   UAW Local 696, which represents 3,400 workers at the brake
plants on Wisconsin Boulevard and Needmore Road, have been at odds
with GM for more than two years. The local talks center on
outsourcing issues, work rules and one company proposal that would
slash 1,800 jobs from the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The International UAW has threatened to call strikes in Dayton
and at a metal-stamping plant in Indianapolis. But GM has asked the
union for assurance that more strikes won't be called once the
Flint walkouts are settled.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, GM reported that it earned $389 million, or 52 cents
a diluted share, in the April-June period compared with $2.1
billion, or $2.67 a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue totaled $38.9 billion, down 14 percent from $45.1
billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   GM said the Flint strikes reduced after-tax profits by $1.2
billion, or $1.79 a share. The strikes have shuttered 25 assembly
plants and more than 100 parts plants across North America.
Analysts estimate the strikes are costing GM about $80 million a
day in lost production.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter results were in line with analysts'
expectations. The average estimate in a survey of 15 analysts by
First Call Corp. was 53 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, our financial performance in the second quarter of
1998 was severely impacted by the UAW strikes against our plants in
Flint, and was certainly not representative of the positive
momentum our financial performance had been building,'' said GM
chairman Jack Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The strike losses don't take into effect any production that may
be recouped after the walkouts are over.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said GM was re-evaluating its spending priorities to
``protect key product programs, such as our new generation of
full-size pickups.''
</P>
<P>
   GM said the strikes had forced it to temporarily suspend its $4
billion stock-repurchase program that began in March. The company
spent $1 billion in the second quarter to repurchase more than 14
million shares of common stock.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes also had a significant effect on GM's cash, which
totaled $9.1 billion at the end of the quarter. That was down from
$13.6 billion on March 31 and $14.9 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker said lower production volume and intense price
competition contributed to the drop in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   GM's Delphi Automotive Systems parts unit earned $374 million in
the quarter, down 28 percent from $522 million a year ago. And GM's
international operations earned $181 million, down 53 percent from
$385 million in the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   GM's earnings a year ago included the effects of less
devastating strikes at two assembly plants. Those strikes reduced
profits by $490 million, or 67 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
