<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-14 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SUBPOENAS HEAD OF CLINTON SECURITY DETAIL TO TESTIFY BEFORE
GRAND JURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Expanding efforts to wrestle evidence from the
Secret Service, independent counsel Kenneth Starr has subpoenaed
the head of President Clinton's security detail to testify before a
federal grand jury investigating an alleged presidential affair and
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Starr to question Special Agent Larry Cockrell, and
possibly other Secret Service agents, came Tuesday as the Justice
Department appealed a court decision compelling Secret Service
employees to appear before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Until Cockrell was summoned, Starr had limited his request for
Secret Service testimony to an agency attorney and two uniformed
officers, none of whom is a member of the president's personal
security detail.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cockrell, who often stands at the president's
shoulder and sits across from him in the presidential limousine,
six other Secret Service officers have been subpoenaed to tell what
they saw or heard while protecting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Also subpoenaed by Starr were records kept by the Secret Service
that would provide details of Clinton's activities and his
movements at night from 1995 through early 1997, dates that overlap
with the time Monica Lewinsky spent at the White House as an intern
and later on the president's legislative affairs staff. The latter
months include a period when Lewinsky reportedly made three dozen
visits to the White House and was cleared to enter the mansion by
someone in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena for Cockrell demanded him to appear before the
grand jury Thursday. Sources said administration lawyers were
preparing to ask the courts Wednesday for an emergency stay of the
subpoena. Cockrell is scheduled to accompany the president to
Arkansas and Louisiana later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Cockrell's subpoena raised the possibility that Starr also would
seek testimony from former heads of Clinton's personal security
detail, including David Carpenter, Lewis Merletti and Brian
Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   Merletti, currently the director of the Secret Service, has been
leading the effort to shield agents from having to testify before
Starr's grand jury. The tall, gray-haired Carpenter, who often is
mistaken for Clinton and has served as a decoy for the president,
left the agency to head the State Department's security team and
office of foreign missions.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, in a move that could further delay Starr's
investigation, the Justice Department asked all 11 members of the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia to review
decisions by a federal judge and three-judge appeals panel saying
that Secret Service agents must cooperate with the grand jury
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is being used by Starr to investigate whether
Clinton or his associates illegally tried to cover up alleged
sexual encounters between the president and Lewinsky and with White
House aide Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   In a 15-page motion, the Justice Department contends that the
three-judge panel erred when it ``substituted its judgment'' for
the opinions of experienced Secret Service agents who assert that
compelling them to testify would endanger a president's life.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service, a branch of the Treasury Department that is
represented in the appeal by Justice Department lawyers, has argued
that forcing agents to testify would jeopardize a president's trust
in his protectors' ability to keep confidential what they see and
hear. As a result, the agency asserts, a president would distance
himself from his security detail and increase the risk of
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no exaggeration to say that the difference of even a few
feet between a president and his protective detail could mean the
difference between life or death,'' Merletti said in a recent court
filing.
</P>
<P>
   After U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson and the three
appeals court judges declined to recognize a so-called ``protective
privilege'' to shield Secret Service agents from having to testify,
some Justice Department officials privately expressed doubts about
the agency's chance of winning before the full appeals court or,
eventually, the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, the federal court of appeals for D.C. has
handled more than 700 cases, and only two were heard by the full
court. Neither of those saw a reversal of a 3-0 decision as was
rendered in the Secret Service privilege case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the U.S. District Courthouse, Linda Tripp, whose
taped conversations with Lewinsky triggered the investigation of
possible perjury and obstruction of justice, appeared before the
grand jury for a fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's tapes reportedly include claims by Lewinsky that
contradict denials made under oath by her and Clinton that they
engaged in sex. The tapes also reportedly include claims by
Lewinsky that Clinton and close friend Vernon Jordan urged her to
lie about her relationship with the president. Clinton and Jordan
deny urging anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the tapes, according to accounts of those who have heard
portions of the secretly recorded telephone conversations, Lewinsky
discusses ways for Tripp to alter her recollection of a November
1993 encounter between Clinton and Willey outside the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Willey has testified under oath that during that meeting Clinton
kissed and fondled her against her will. Clinton acknowledged
meeting privately with Willey but denied any inappropriate
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's suggestions to Tripp reportedly were made after she
learned that she might be questioned under oath by attorneys for
Paula Jones, who at the time was suing Clinton for sexual
harassment over an incident when he was governor of Arkansas.
Jones' lawsuit has been dismissed by a federal judge in Little
Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
