<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      07-14 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: ALASKA-TO-JAPAN FLIGHTS; GREETING THE MILLENNIUM;
GIVING PRESENTS IN JAPAN; TRAVEL AGENTS' COMMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)  (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost a decade after Alaska lost its nonstop passenger service
to Japan, Northwest Airlines is currently making weekly nonstop
flights between Anchorage and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Gov. Tony Knowles of Alaska proposed $1 million in
incentives to any airline that provided direct service to Tokyo.
However, Northwest does not qualify for the incentive because it
plans to suspend service Sept. 24, at least until next summer.
</P>
<P>
   But its 15 summer round-trip flights are expected to bring in
more than 4,200 Japanese business and leisure travelers, and
Knowles said the flights would add more than $12 million to the
Alaskan economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to 1989, most international traffic stopped here to
refuel,'' said Morton Plumb, Jr., director of Anchorage
International Airport. But Anchorage was no longer needed after the
fall of communism opened the shorter polar routes to international
air traffic, and more fuel-efficient jet planes made refueling
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   While Anchorage does a big business in cargo flights, ranking
12th in the United States, its international traffic dwindled to
396,000 passengers in 1994, the fewest number in years, from 1.5
million in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   This year, including the expected 4,200 Northwest passengers and
those who connect from Hawaii and cities in the continental United
States, the foreign passenger tally in Anchorage will rise to about
720,000, Plumb said, while domestic passengers will total 4.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, annual gross sales at Anchorage's duty-free shops
have struggled back to about $16 million, double the amount of four
years ago but still only a fraction of the $118 million in gross
sales in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the drop in revenue is the result of the big
drop in international passengers. But Plumb observed that many of
the current Chinese and South Korean visitors spend less freely
than the Japanese passengers of a decade ago, and today's Japanese
visitors themselves spend less freely, no doubt because of their
nation's economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Cruises
</P>
<P>
   The jointly owned Royal Caribbean International and Celebrity
Cruises have announced millennium plans for their 17 ships. Royal
Caribbean's Legend of the Seas, for example, will be among the
first and last cruise ships to celebrate the first day, by
positioning itself west of the international date line on Dec. 31,
1999, and east of the dateline on Jan. 1, 2000. Its Vision of the
Seas will be the first to enter the Panama Canal from the Caribbean
in 2000, followed by Celebrity's Zenith.
</P>
<P>
   A Gift in Time
</P>
<P>
   By commissioning a line of gifts from some of Japan's leading
artists and craftsmen, the Park Hyatt Tokyo Hotel has made it easy
for its guests in that present-giving country to pick up a little
something for customers, business associates, family or friends _
remembrances ranging from paper coasters with artistic designs to
tea sets and sake bottles.
</P>
<P>
   These items, most of which are hand crafted, can be ordered from
hotel rooms and are wrapped by the hotel staff in traditional
Japanese paper and cord.
</P>
<P>
   Matter of Commissions
</P>
<P>
   Rumors abound in the travel-agent community that at least three
airlines plan to lower commission caps further or eliminate
commissions altogether.
</P>
<P>
   While the carriers have neither confirmed nor denied the rumors,
John Hawks, president of the Association of Retail Travel Agents,
appears guardedly optimistic that they are just that _ rumors. ``It
seems unlikely that the major carriers would take action now,'' he
said, ``given the very unfriendly atmosphere in Congress on issues
like airline alliances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
