<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIG-20TH-CENTURY-LADN     07-14 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIG-20TH-CENTURY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM BUYS NEW CHUNK OF 20TH CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- American International Group Inc., which rode in
like a white knight to save 20th Century Industries after the
Northridge quake, is poised to take a controlling stake in the auto
insurer.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City-based insurance and financial services firm
said late Tuesday it has purchased enough shares of 20th Century's
common stock to give it ownership of 15.4 percent of the
outstanding common shares.
</P>
<P>
   And if it converts the preferred stock and exercises the
warrants it acquired as part of its bailout deal with 20th Century,
it could own more than 50 percent of 20th Century's outstanding
common stock -- and a controlling interest.
</P>
<P>
   An AIG spokesman could not say how many additional shares AIG
bought most recently, when they were purchased or at what price.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 25 Securities and Exchange Commission filing, however,
the company said it owned about 3.21 million shares of 20th
Century's common stock. Conversion of the preferred stock and
exercise of the warrants at that time would have given AIG about
39.1 million, or 44.6 percent, of 20th Century's common stock.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 51.7 million common shares outstanding, said Rick
Hill, vice president of corporate relations for 20th Century.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had not seen the latest filings, but Tuesday's
announcement indicates that AIG is following through on its
intention revealed in April to own more than half of 20th Century's
voting stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I think (AIG) is going to want 100 percent of
it,'' Ira Zuckerman, an analyst at Nutmeg Securities Ltd. in
Westport, Conn., told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   AIG first invested in 20th Century in 1994 after nearly
two-thirds of 20th Century's capital was wiped out by claims
stemming from the Northridge earthquake. Part of AIG's bailout
included a provision allowing it to later buy as many shares of
20th Century as it wanted, preventing 20th Century officers from
enacting bylaws that most companies could use to stop an unwanted
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of 20th Century closed Tuesday at 27.9375, down 0.0625
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
