<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXY-OPERA-JACKETS-$A     07-14 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXY-OPERA-JACKETS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACKAGING WAGNER IN FLESH AND FLASH FOR FUN AND PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19.)  
 (JT)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A jet-black man, facing front and nearly naked but for a spiked
leather G-string with matching spiked sunglasses, and holding a
dead white swan; a trio of skinny, scantily clad, bewigged and
beribboned drag queens who could be drum majorettes in a Gay Day
parade; a naked obese woman sitting on a floor and cuddling a tiny
dog between her fleshy arm and humongous bosom, with heart-shaped
trinkets masking her face and nipples. Are we leafing through some
gay and lesbian soft-porn magazine? No, these are the covers of
three new RCA Victor recordings of orchestral excerpts and
arrangements from Wagner operas, performed by the Netherlands Radio
Philharmonic under the direction of the distinguished Dutch
conductor Edo de Waart.
</P>
<P>
   Slick, sensationalized cover art has often played a part in the
selling of classical recordings. But even David Kuehn, the vice
president for marketing and for artists and repertory at the New
York office of BMG Classics, which manufactures RCA recordings,
admits that the new Wagner covers are over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no middle of the road about them,'' Kuehn said
recently. ``Even within our own ranks, when we first presented the
covers and the marketing plans, it was pretty evenly divided
between fans and detractors. Some thought it was exactly what we
needed, but the core of the classical people thought it was really
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, certain stores are nervous as well. At the Tower
Records store near Lincoln Center in Manhattan, the new CD's have
not been given prominent display; they are in a bin labeled
``Wagner: with tasteful covers.'' The facetious tone of the
description is clearly intentional, and the hint of a disclaimer is
understandable. Whether you find these designs arousing and
imaginative or just plain grotesque, tasteful they are not.
</P>
<P>
   But taste, Kuehn suggests, is in the eye of the beholder. Or
perhaps in the hand of the beholder, for getting a CD into a
consumer's hands is the first step in selling it. ``I have
purchased recordings of music I did not know, based on intriguing
or provocative cover art,'' Kuehn said. And he disputes the idea
that classical-music consumers are immune to marketing techniques;
it's just that the marketing has to be creative and appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, in terms of eye-catching contemporary cover designs,
the classical record business has a lot of catching up to do. In
the heyday of long-playing records, during the 1950s and '60s,
cover designs were more often inept than tasteless. London Records
was famous for its maladroit covers of complete opera recordings
with great artists like Joan Sutherland and Renata Tebaldi. Ms.
Tebaldi's classic 1958 recording of ``Madama Butterfly'' featured a
photo of the diva costumed as Cio-Cio-San but looking like some
frump on her way to a Halloween party. Then there was the boringly
austere approach, typified by Westminster Records: against darkish
single-color backdrops the pertinent information was printed in
gold or silver italicized lettering.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Angel Records (now EMI Classics), knowing
that it had a glamorous star in Maria Callas, designed her covers
accordingly. Callas' 1964 recording of ``Carmen'' was first issued
in a deluxe blood-red, velvet-textured box with a picture of the
diva looking menacingly seductive, captioned, unabashedly, ``Callas
 &UR; is &LR;  Carmen.''
</P>
<P>
   There were all those adulatory Angel and Deutsche Grammophon
recordings conducted by Herbert von Karajan, with cover photos of
the silver-haired maestro in a leather coat standing next to his
white sports car or gazing regally at snowy vistas in the Austrian
Alps. Then came the teen-meat-in-jeans campaign for the winsome
violinist Joshua Bell, when he made his first recordings for London
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, BMG has been particularly bold _ some might say
crass _ in creating marketing concepts that executives deem
titillating. This is the company that produced ``Out Classics,'' a
collection of music by gay (or supposedly gay) composers, culled
from the BMG catalog. On the cover was a photograph showing the
upper body of a seemingly naked, impossibly hunky young man with an
intense, distracted look on his Byronic face.
</P>
<P>
   Does this kind of cover art sell records? And how do such
far-out design concepts relate to the music being marketed?
</P>
<P>
   De Waart offers performances of suites from several operas _
``orchestral summaries,'' they are called here _ arranged by Henk
de Vlieger, a Dutch composer. The disks are titled `` `Der Ring,'
an Orchestral Adventure,'' `` `Parsifal,' an Orchestral Quest'' and
`` `Tristan und Isolde,' an Orchestral Passion.'' Longer orchestral
passages, like the Prelude to ``Tristan,'' are performed intact
along with other excerpts in which de Vlieger has assigned the
vocal lines to instruments. The recordings were made between 1992
and 1995, so BMG has had plenty of time to decide how to market
them.
</P>
<P>
   De Vlieger's work is professional, and de Waart's performances,
though nothing special, are spacious and clear-headed. Yet de
Waart's magisterial approach to Wagner makes matters all the more
curious: What possessed BMG to produce such grotesquely silly cover
designs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, our company headquarters is in New York, but these disks
were produced locally in Holland,'' Kuehn said. ``We have not given
local territories enough opportunities to create their own
projects. So when these recordings came up, it was decided to find
a Dutch designer, someone with the same hip cachet of, say, Bruce
Weber in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The designer is an outfit called Edzeetera, but the crucial
aspect is the work of Erwin Olaf, a 38-year-old photographer who
first earned attention with his photos documenting the Dutch
homosexual-rights movement. A successful early exhibition in
Amsterdam, ``Among Men/Among Women,'' led Olaf to work with various
European homosexual magazines. He is considered a sort of Dutch
Robert Mapplethorpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The designs are obviously homoerotic,'' Kuehn said. But are
they?
</P>
<P>
   The muscular black man on the ``Parsifal'' disk could be some
Mad Max version of the opera's questing knight, holding over his
shoulder the limp swan he has just shot with his bow and arrow. The
three prancing drag-queens on the ``Ring'' album are clearly meant
to be the Rhinemaidens. And the obese woman on the ``Tristan''
recording (overweight naked women are a recurring theme in Olaf's
work) is certainly intended as a satirical depiction of an enormous
Wagnerian singer, complete with diva trappings, including her tiny
pooch. The heart that covers her face is no doubt metaphoric.
(Isolde blinded by love, get it?)
</P>
<P>
   The records are being heavily pitched to the gay male market.
BMG has been running frequent ads in The Advocate, the national
homosexual magazine, with sales copy as excessive as the cover
designs: ``No other composer is as sensual, dramatic, or intense as
Wagner ... For the first time a three-CD series that encompasses
the most enticing melodies of this composer's magical operas.''
</P>
<P>
   The covers seem more campy than magical. But what does a music
critic know about marketing design? The records have been selling
briskly, Kuehn says, especially in major urban markets, a fact that
at the very least should help combat the dismaying stereotype that
gay men have good taste. In Holland, the disks are available in a
boxed set with a booklet containing all 12 of Olaf's photographic
conceptions of various characters from the Wagner operas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
