<HEADLINE>
NEW TRANSLATIONS OF BIBLE CAN'T BE WORD FOR WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Translation is not replacing one English word with one Havasupai
word. In Havasupai, the structure of the sentence builds to the
point. English clauses may be difficult to convey.
</P>
<P>
   In the New International Version of the Bible, 1 Corinthians
1:18 reads: ``For the message of the cross is foolishness to those
who are perishing, but to us who are being saved it is the power of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Havasupai is roughly translated word for word, the same
verse reads ``Cross, Christ has died, people that God does not
know, when they hear it, it isn't worth anything, but people that
are saved, God they know, they God see great works his.''
</P>
<P>
   Some similes in Scripture are changed to reflect life in Supai,
such as the phrase from James 1:6: ``He who doubts is like a wave
of the sea, blown and tossed by the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   In Supai, the blue-green water flows in the same direction,
tumbling down the breathtaking falls. The erratic Canyon winds made
a better example.
</P>
<P>
   Other images aren't so easily conveyed the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In Luke 5, Jesus recruits his disciples, saying he will make
them fishers of men. The first translation came across as, ``A lot
of fish were on the shore and now a lot of people will come and
help pick the fish up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Havasupai text was revised again, and the new translation
was understood as, ``Your work has been getting fish, but from now
on you will get people to believe my word.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
