</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WYCLIFFE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY PROJECT IN GRAND CANYON: COUPLE WORK ON HAVASUPAI BIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUPAI, Ariz. _ Scott and Lynanne Palmer brought their love for
God and master's degrees in linguistics to this dusty village in
the Grand Canyon's depths two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, surrounded by the high red rock walls, they painstakingly
continue the work of their hearts: translating the Bible into
Havasupai.
</P>
<P>
   They have lived with views of vivid blue sky by day and
brilliant stars by night, a short hike from the spectacular
blue-green Havasu Falls. They have raised two daughters in a home
smaller than a double garage, with few modern conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   They have earned trust and friendship and learned the Havasupai
language, carefully guarded by a tribe that does not want its words
scattered outside the Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   And with the help of a few tribal members, they have drafted
about 6,500 Bible verses _ most of the New Testament and 17
chapters of Genesis _ into Havasupai, a language so different from
English that each verse is translated meaning-to-meaning, rather
than word for word.
</P>
<P>
   The turn of the millennium will creep by before the Havasupai
New Testament and Genesis are finished, likely in 2002,
representing 24 years and more than a million dollars invested.
</P>
<P>
   All for a tribe with 670 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``For everyone who has grown up here, Havasupai is their
language,'' said Lynanne Palmer, a Wycliffe Bible Translator along
with Scott. ``That's the language that is closest to your heart,
and everybody deserves the chance to hear God's word in their own
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, we don't know how much this
translation will be used. The church has always been in English.''
</P>
<P>
   Wycliffe Bible Translators sends missionaries around the world
to translate the Bible into obscure languages, based on the
conviction that Scripture is understood best in a person's native
tongue. The translators do not proselytize or build churches.
</P>
<P>
   Each country's languages are cataloged and its people surveyed
for interest in a New Testament project. That done, the Palmers
went to Supai to find Christians interested in a translation and to
get permission from the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Ida Iditicava was one of the first to help. Long before she met
the Palmers, she had heard the Navajos had the New Testament in
their own language. She believed in Jesus and thought maybe her
people should have a New Testament in their language, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read it in English, I kind of understand it,'' she
said. ``When I read it in my language, then I know it. It will be
good.'' &QL; 
__ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1976, when the Palmers married on their way to
becoming translators with Wycliffe. She planned to work with a
tribe in northern Quebec, following a call to missions she felt as
a fourth-grader in social studies class in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   He had planned to work on a project in Brazil, where his family
had lived when he was a boy. His father had worked on a ranch and
with a church mission there.
</P>
<P>
   Both projects fell through, and they weren't sure where in the
world they would be assigned, although they knew they would be
together. They finished their master's degrees, waited and prayed.
In the end, they went to the bottom of the Grand Canyon in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   They spent 1{ years learning the language before starting the
actual translation. The work is painfully slow, even with native
speakers' help. Each verse is translated into Havasupai. The verses
are typed into the computer; and the revisions, double checks and
triple checks begin.
</P>
<P>
   Havasupai speakers read the verses for comprehension. The
passages are translated back to English as another check for
understanding. The final step is a theological consultant who reads
that English translation for biblical accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bemus Uquallah became a staff member on the project and
now does the first draft translation. As a native speaker, he
completes the first rough draft more quickly than the Palmers, even
after their 20 years' experience with the language. Still, a day's
work may yield only 12 verses. &QL; 
Projects take years &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A typical translation project takes 15 to 30 years. The Palmers
optimistically figured their project would take five. They both
were working, and they had help from native speakers. The Havasupai
language was written. They had computers. A church had been in the
community for as long as most could remember.
</P>
<P>
   Two years into the project, they experienced what Scott calls
the death of their vision, and they became even more focused on
God's vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth it to ask `What does God want?' and to hang in
there, and it's worth it to leave to God how it fits in with
everything else,'' Scott said. ``Sometimes we see it and we're very
happy about that and sometimes we don't see it. But what's
important is not seeing or seeing. What's important is what God
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   So they stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's flood left a foot of water in their house and a
broken air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Their water heater is a large pot on the stove, and their
bathroom is an outhouse down the path. Their refrigerator is
smaller than those in college dorms. Ice and meat are a luxury.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have television, so they spend the evenings after the
supper dishes are washed visiting with neighbors and reading aloud.
They lead less modern lives than some of their neighbors who have
satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughters, 16-year-old Elena and 10-year-old Sarah, think
their lives are terrific, except for the packing and traveling back
and forth between their Canyon home and their home in Cottonwood,
where some of the translation work has been done. &QL; 
Hike out of Canyon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Palmers have lost track of how many times
they've been on the 8-mile trail in and out of the Canyon. A
helicopter taxis residents in and out of the village for $25 one
way, a little pricey for the family of four except in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Even while pregnant, Lynanne hiked. When she was too
uncomfortable to walk up and down the steep trail, Scott led her on
horseback, and their Supai friends made jokes about Mary and
Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   He carried their daughters for the next four years of their
lives, in a backpack carrier they rigged long before the baby
backpacks were marketed. Today, he carries a laptop computer _ only
4 pounds, he says with glee, and probably their most modern
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   For most translation projects, work is done in and out of the
village, because the chores of life can be time-consuming, said
Dick Mueller, associate director of the North American translation
work.
</P>
<P>
   The Palmers also spend time out of the Canyon, traveling in
their aged motorhome to talk to churches that financially support
the project.
</P>
<P>
   In the Grand Canyon's only church, more tourists than tribal
members attend most Sunday mornings. Scott often plays the keyboard
and Elena plays the flute to accompany the congregation, which
meets in a converted Quonset hut. &QL; 
New understanding &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Palmers' efforts have not caused a mass conversion to
Christianity in the village. But Uquallah, an elder in the church,
believes the translation is the only way his tribe will understand
that Jesus is not a White man's God.
</P>
<P>
   ``When different people come in to test the translation work, I
always hear something like, `Oh, is that what it says? I didn't
really understand that,' '' he said. ``I know that it's going to be
a big help to my people. The word of God, that's a powerful thing,
and they should be able to understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another project volunteer didn't quite understand the gospel
until she heard it in Havasupai, Lynanne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day, she prayed to trust Christ, and I got to be there
and listen,'' said Lynanne, who still meets with the woman.
</P>
<P>
   When the Palmers hike out of the Canyon for the last time, they
will take a copy of the Havasupai Bible only if the tribe gives
them one. They will not be credited as the translators, and years
from now, no one may even remember their names.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott has this picture in his head of heaven, an image from
a favorite verse in Revelation: ``There before me was a great
multitude that no one could count, from every nation, tribe, people
and language, standing before the throne . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those people, he says, will speak Havasupai. &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at 444-4877 or at
kelly.ettenborough(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
