<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WYCLIFFE-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRANSLATIONS OF BIBLE CAN'T BE WORD FOR WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Translation is not replacing one English word with one Havasupai
word. In Havasupai, the structure of the sentence builds to the
point. English clauses may be difficult to convey.
</P>
<P>
   In the New International Version of the Bible, 1 Corinthians
1:18 reads: ``For the message of the cross is foolishness to those
who are perishing, but to us who are being saved it is the power of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Havasupai is roughly translated word for word, the same
verse reads ``Cross, Christ has died, people that God does not
know, when they hear it, it isn't worth anything, but people that
are saved, God they know, they God see great works his.''
</P>
<P>
   Some similes in Scripture are changed to reflect life in Supai,
such as the phrase from James 1:6: ``He who doubts is like a wave
of the sea, blown and tossed by the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   In Supai, the blue-green water flows in the same direction,
tumbling down the breathtaking falls. The erratic Canyon winds made
a better example.
</P>
<P>
   Other images aren't so easily conveyed the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In Luke 5, Jesus recruits his disciples, saying he will make
them fishers of men. The first translation came across as, ``A lot
of fish were on the shore and now a lot of people will come and
help pick the fish up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Havasupai text was revised again, and the new translation
was understood as, ``Your work has been getting fish, but from now
on you will get people to believe my word.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARCRIMES-COURT-700&AMP;A     07-14 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARCRIMES-COURT-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRESSES ALLIES TO REIN IN PROPOSED WAR CRIMES COURT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The United States has been putting pressure on some of
its closest European allies to limit the scope of a future
permanent international war crimes court.
</P>
<P>
   Talking points said to have been prepared for Defense Secretary
William Cohen, for example, suggested that if Germany succeeded in
lobbying for ``universal jurisdiction'' for the court, the United
States might retaliate by removing its overseas troops, including
those in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Few Europeans took the threat seriously, believing that
Washington would not abandon its NATO commitments to protest the
formation of the international criminal court. And Germany was
dropping its support for the proposal anyway after being persuaded
by other European countries that it had too little support to end
up in the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But the talking points underscore how fiercely Washington
opposes the kind of court desired by some of its closest allies.
The United States is leading the opposition to the proposal for a
powerful court, with the support of France and some developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon denied on Tuesday that Cohen had threatened to
withdraw troops from Europe. But the Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth
Bacon, said Cohen had argued publicly and privately against
sweeping powers for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also said Cohen had never seen ``those talking points.''
Pentagon officials said they did not know where the document had
originated and did not believe that it had come from their
department.
</P>
<P>
   Delegations from more than 160 countries have been negotiating
the terms of a treaty at a U.N. conference in Rome. As the deadline
for a compromise looms this Friday, some of the most crucial and
contentious issues covering the court's power and jurisdiction have
yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the talking points spread through the conference
rooms on Tuesday, it created a stir at a gathering already marked
by tension and deep divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is one of more than 50 countries that have wanted a
powerful court that could prosecute individuals in any country, for
crimes ranging from genocide to crimes against humanity and war
crimes, whether or not their country signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The United States worries that its troops could someday be
hauled before foreign judges on politically motivated charges, and
has been lobbying relentlessly to limit the court's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should the universal jurisdiction proposal be adopted by the
Rome Conference, we would have to consider the implications for our
overseas presence, including our commitment of forces to Europe''
was how the American talking points prepared for conversations with
German defense officials expressed the U.S. position.
</P>
<P>
   The talking points, which were dated last Thursday, were
private, but a copy was made available to The New York Times.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   David Scheffer, who leads the U.S. delegation, made the American
position clear last week, when he told the conference that the
United States would countenance a permanent war crimes tribunal
only if its automatic jurisdiction was limited to genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer insisted that the United States would not allow the
court automatic jurisdiction crimes against humanity or war crimes.
To investigate those charges, the United States asserted, the court
would need the consent of accused country. Nations that have not
signed the treaty would have to agree before the court could act.
</P>
<P>
   Even on genocide charges, Washington says the court would have
jurisdiction only over countries that are party to the treaty. As
the talking points put it, the prospect of the new court
``pretending to have jurisdiction over our personnel, even though
we are not a party, is completely unacceptable to the United States
under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer declined to comment on the talking points, but a
spokesman for the American delegation said: ``We view these private
discussions as both a normal and essential part of our
negotiations. We enjoy close working relationships with our allies,
part of which includes speaking frankly on issues of importance.''
</P>
<P>
   The talking points angered many delegates who were upset by what
they viewed as American intransigence. Human rights groups, which
have been lobbying for the court to have the broadest possible
jurisdiction, were dismayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is what the United States is capable of doing in
order to get its way,'' said Jelena Pejic, head of the delegation
from the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights. ``If they can use
these kinds of bullying tactics on an ally like Germany, you can
imagine what they are doing to smaller countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The American hard line reflects Pentagon concerns, and also
strong opposition in the Senate, which must approve any treaty
signed in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, the North Carolina Republican who heads the
Foreign Relations Committee, has warned that any treaty creating an
international court that could sit in judgment of American citizens
would be ``dead on arrival.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration would be willing to sign a treaty,
but only if it was tightly tailored to protect American soldiers
from any risk of prosecution. Human rights groups and many
delegations argue that in seeking to protect its own citizens, the
United States would be giving people like President Saddam Hussein
of Iraq and the late Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
