u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT &LR;      07-14 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON THREATENS VETO AGAINST SPENDING BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday issued his strongest
veto threat yet against a spending bill for the next fiscal year,
but a powerful House committee did nothing to try to reshape the
bill to meet his demands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, lawmakers from both parties tacked on a series of
amendments concerning smoking, women's health care and the
impotency drug Viagra. Then the Appropriations Committee approved
the bill, which would drastically scale back the president's
initiatives on education and cut aid for home-heating fuel and
summer jobs for poor people.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which would provide $81.9 billion for labor, health
and education programs, is perceived by all sides as one of the
most contentious of the 13 spending bills that Congress must pass
to keep the federal government running in the next fiscal year,
which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority in Congress has defied the president's
wishes most directly in this bill. And the president said on
Tuesday that he ``would have no choice but to veto it'' in its
current form.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the bill ``denies essential educational
opportunities to young people across the country and important
training and job opportunities for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's actions allow both the Republicans and the
administration to stake out their positions _ the Republicans for
budget discipline, the president for education _ before more
intense negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Republicans in both houses have already said the cuts
are too drastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation will always be fluid until it lands on the
president's desk,'' Representative Robert Livingston of Louisiana,
the chairman of the Appropriations Committee, conceded on Tuesday
after the bill passed in a 32-to-23 vote along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained about the cuts at the four-hour meeting of
the Appropriations Committee. But they spent most of the time
discussing amendments that were unrelated to those cuts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rep. Carrie Meek, D-Fla., proposed a new label on
cigarette packs warning that smoking kills black people at a higher
rate than it kills others. It passed by voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., proposed a measure to allow women in
health maintenance organizations to designate their obstetricians
and gynecologists as their primary care doctors. It passed 29 to
25.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the highest ranking Democrat on
the Appropriations Committee, proposed a measure to prevent federal
money from being used to reimburse states whose Medicaid programs
pay for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Obey, citing estimates that his measure would save the federal
government $100 million a year, proposed using that savings to
treat children who are at risk for violent behavior. It passed by
voice vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
