<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT-620&AMP;A     07-14 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DEFAMATION DECIDED, BRAWLEY CASE MOVES TO QUESTION OF
DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-BRAWLEY-REACT) 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ A day after they were held liable for
defamation in the Tawana Brawley case, the Rev. Al Sharpton and two
other men began battling Tuesday to persuade the jury to award only
minimal damages, clearly hoping to claim a symbolic victory despite
Monday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   For both sides in the long-running case, the struggle over the
damages phase of the trial has at least as much symbolic
significance as practical importance, since all three defendants
say they have limited means.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most forceful defense arguments Tuesday, Michael
Hardy, Sharpton's lawyer, suggested to the jurors that their
decision might have been based on their dislike of Sharpton and
pleaded with them to put aside ``personal feelings as to Reverend
Sharpton'' when setting damages.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy's risky tactic of suggesting bias against his client
within the jury focused attention on just how much importance both
sides attach to the question of damages.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones has sought $395 million, an amount that he could say
confirmed the dimensions of the wrong that was committed when
Sharpton and the other two Brawley advisers, Alton Maddox and C.
Vernon Mason, said a decade ago that Pagones had raped and
kidnapped Miss Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   The jury could award anything from the full amount Pagones
requested to a nominal amount to zero, a sum that could give the
advisers the ability to assert that their defamations amounted to
harmless rhetoric in the pursuit of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones' lawyer, William Stanton, began the new phase of the
trial Tuesday morning with a terse opening statement urging the
jurors to assess the full compensatory and punitive damages ``to
punish the defendants and also to discourage others from similar
acts.''
</P>
<P>
   In their opening statements, the defendants took various tacks
to reach the same destination: Each made a case for the jury to
award minimal or no damages.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy said that some people see Sharpton as a ``caricature'' who
is loud and has political views with which they disagree. He urged
the jurors not to allow what he called such illicit feelings to
influence a decision on damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plead with you to make your decision based on the law and
the evidence, not on personal feelings as to Reverend Sharpton,''
Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's lawyer, Stephen Jackson, suggested to the jurors that an
award of minimal damages could begin to repair the wounds caused by
the case. ``There is an opportunity here to stop the bleeding,'' he
said. ``It's time for healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, who has argued the case on his own behalf, urged the
jurors not to be swayed by emotion. He asserted that Pagones had
suffered no financial losses and that any symptoms of anxiety
Pagones associated with the case had appeared before the advisers
had mentioned his name publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Among Pagones' friends and acquaintances, Maddox said, the fact
that the advisers had named Pagones as a participant in an assault
had not injured his reputation. And he said it would be a
miscarriage of justice ``to punish three men who have clearly given
their lives and their careers to help people who could not help
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton, who spoke first Tuesday, simply told the jurors in a
three-minute statement that Pagones had endured mental stress and
physical suffering as a result of false charges by the advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Implying that the case for extensive damages was obvious,
Stanton then entered Pagones' medical records into evidence,
reminded the jury that Pagones had testified for 25 days and rested
the plaintiff's case. The defense is to begin presentation of its
evidence on the damages issue on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hardy appeared the most shaken Tuesday as he addressed the
jurors after they found on Monday that Sharpton had slandered
Pagones seven times, while they found Mason liable for only one
defamatory statement and Maddox liable for only two statements.
Hardy said he had tried to understand what he considered
inconsistent decisions and had wondered whether attitudes about
Sharpton, rather than the evidence in the case, were behind the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope there's not an illicit motive behind that,'' Hardy
said as he stood before the jury box. Such things as the
unpopularity of political views ``or even dislikes, if you will, of
Reverend Sharpton'' should not play a part in any decision, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the six jurors had signed the verdict sheet on
Monday. Because Pagones' case is civil, only five votes were
required on any count. But Hardy suggested Tuesday that
inconsistent findings with respect to the advisers showed some
division on the jury.
</P>
<P>
   If there were deep tensions among the group, they were not
obvious Tuesday. In the courtroom for the brief proceedings, the
jurors appeared calm after the evident exhaustion of their four-day
deliberation. Although the jurors were sequestered over the
weekend, Judge S. Barrett Hickman had permitted them to return to
their homes on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the case said Tuesday that the juror who refused
to sign the verdict sheet is a black woman, one of two black
jurors. The other four jurors are white. It was unclear why the
juror had refused to sign the sheet or whether racial issues played
any part her decision. Just before they delivered their decision on
Monday, a white female juror told the judge that the panel was
divided 3-3 on some counts, which suggested that any division would
not have been along racial lines alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are no longer sequestered, the jurors are not
permitted to speak publicly until they have completed the damages
phase of the case. Lawyers said Tuesday that it was not clear how
long the damages phase would take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
