<SLUG> BC-GM-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM SAYS STRIKES LED TO EARNINGS DROP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Tenn., Okla.)  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ General Motors Corp. announced Tuesday that its
profits plunged 81 percent in the second quarter, mainly because of
strikes here. The automaker also filed a lawsuit demanding that the
United Auto Workers union allow immediate arbitration of the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In apparent retaliation, the UAW on Tuesday night scheduled a
strike vote this Sunday at GM's giant Saturn factory in Spring
Hill, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   GM made official its previous estimate that strikes at two parts
factories here had cost it $1.18 billion in lost after-tax profits
during the second quarter. Michael Losh, GM's chief financial
officer, said that while the automaker hoped to recoup some of that
loss through extra production later this year, the actual amount
that could be recovered would depend on how long the labor dispute
lasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the strike is over soon, we can make up a lot of that, but
the longer the strike goes on, the harder it is to make it up,''
Losh said in a telephone interview. GM executives are hoping that
customers will wait for its dealerships to be restocked with
popular models after production resumes, instead of shopping at
rival automakers' dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   GM reported that it earned $389 million in the second quarter,
or 52 cents a diluted share, down from $2.10 billion, or $2.67 a
share, in the period a year earlier. The earnings were a penny
short of Wall Street analysts' forecast of 53 cents, according to
First Call Corp., a Boston company that tracks earnings forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   GM's sales fell 15.8 percent, to $33.46 billion from $39.74
billion.
</P>
<P>
   GM's cash reserves dropped to $9.1 billion, from $13.6 billion
at the end of the first quarter, a slightly smaller decline than
Wall Street analysts had anticipated given the labor dispute. Losh
said that GM had made a $1.2 billion pension contribution during
the quarter, had repurchased $1 billion worth of stock and had paid
$2.2 billion in bills from suppliers of parts that mostly have not
yet been assembled into cars.
</P>
<P>
   GM has suspended its stock repurchases and does not need to make
another contribution to its pension plans soon, while the bills
from suppliers have mostly been paid, so the rate of decline in
GM's cash reserves should slow, Losh said. In addition to its cash
reserves, GM has $4 billion recently deposited in trust funds that
can be used to pay employee health costs during the strike if
necessary, Losh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong cash position and we have a strong balance
sheet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GM stock rose 75 cents Tuesday, to $69.625. Jack
Kirnan, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said GM's solid bank
account could allow it to withstand a fairly long strike, although
at the risk of market-share losses.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to put more pressure on the UAW to compromise, GM sued
the union Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   GM contended in its lawsuit that the strikes at two parts
factories here represented an illegal strike over GM's factory
investment decisions. GM's national agreement with the UAW, which
runs through September 1999, only allows strikes over three types
of local grievances: health and safety issues, subcontracting to
outside suppliers and production issues such as the speeding up of
assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   GM said in its complaint that the UAW had filed dozens of local
grievances only after GM notified the union on Feb. 6 of plans to
postpone some investments in a factory here that stamps auto-body
parts from sheets of steel. The number of pending production
grievances soared to 188 from six, the number of subcontracting
grievances doubled to four, and 54 health and safety grievances
were filed when previously there were none, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   GM asked the court to compel the union to participate in
expedited arbitration, and a hearing was scheduled for Wednesday
afternoon. Thomas Gottschalk, GM's general counsel, said that UAW
officials had refused to schedule a meeting with the arbitrator,
Thomas Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The GM lawsuit also asked the court for an injunction ordering
an end to the strike and for cash damages, but Gottschalk said that
expedited arbitration was the company's priority.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said
at a news conference that the strikes were legal and that the UAW's
national agreement with GM has a provision barring lawsuits. The
UAW is willing to engage in arbitration but has concluded that
expedited arbitration is not in the interest of its members, he
said. GM is losing $75 million a day because of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Of GM's 29 North American assembly plants, the Saturn factory is
one of only three still running. Even if a strike is approved,
workers would not be able to walk out without the national union
leadership's permission.
</P>
<P>
   GM's earnings in the second quarter of last year were also hurt
by strikes, as walkouts at a pickup-truck assembly plant in
Pontiac, Mich., and a midsized car-assembly plant in Oklahoma City
reduced the company's earnings then by $490 million.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the strikes this year and last year, and excluding a
partial spinoff of Hughes Electronics Corp. and various special
items, GM's earnings in the second quarter of this year totaled
$1.6 billion, or $2.40 a share, down from $2.1 billion, or $2.82 a
share, a year earlier, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings dropped after adjustments mainly because GM is
introducing new models, Losh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
