u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-AFFIRMKIDS-COX     07-14 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-AFFIRMKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youth workshop: Students want to protect affirmative action
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ LaRoddric Theodule assumed he was a sure bet to study
architecture at the University of California Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   A native of nearby San Jose, he had a 3.4 grade point average,
made a 1250 on the SAT, starred on the track team and worked 40
hours a week at an architectural firm. But because of California's
recently passed anti-affirmative action legislation, Proposition
209, Theodule was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I know about affirmative action? I've done more living it
than studying it,'' said the 18-year-old, who will attend
historically black Florida A&AMP;M University. ``I was more than
qualified to go to Berkeley. The year before, a large number of
blacks were admitted with equal or lower standards than I had.''
Proposition 209 was a 1996 ballot initiative that prohibited most
racial and gender preferences in public education and other
government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Theodule's story struck a chord among the 500 or so young people
gathered Tuesday afternoon for the NAACP's youth and college
division's workshop on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   While the theme of the workshop, ``A Handout or Handup,'' was
only mentioned in passing, the tone was quickly set that
affirmative action had to be protected.
</P>
<P>
   Erayne Gee, a junior at the University of Texas at Austin, noted
the impact when affirmative action is not present. Gee said only
about 1,000 of the 50,000 students at the University of Texas at
Austin are black. In Texas, the 5th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals
ruled that using race as a criterion for college admission was
illegal and that the need for college diversity is not a sufficient
reason for race-based admissions. The court decision ``not only
affected admissions, but our support services as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Katrice Stinson, who read the students a chilling e-mail she
received after her first semester at Mercer University School of
Law that denounced affirmative action and predicted that the whole
country would soon follow Texas and California's lead, said
students should use the convention as a springboard to learn as
much about affirmative action and its effects as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to know how to talk about it, how to discuss it and
what language we are going to allow others to use when talking
about us,'' said Stinson, who is entering her second year at
Mercer. ``Know what it is and how to defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Hutchinson, 19, who wants black organizations to work
with other minority groups to form a stronger collective body to
fight the backlash against affirmative action, fears that black
college and high school students still don't see the significance
of affirmative action, which was described by some as the ``civil
rights of our era.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to know that this will affect their futures,'' said
Hutchinson, a sophomore at the University of Oregon. ``Maybe not
now or in the next couple of years, but students need to start
thinking about this now before it is too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
