<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING SOUTH AFRICA, RUBIN SIDES WITH THE FREE-MARKETERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Stepping into a sharp South African
debate without acknowledging it, U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin repeatedly endorsed South African economic policies Tuesday
even as these policies faced attack by the government's closest
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, who is on a five-nation Africa trip, said in Soweto that
the country's economic policies were ``strong and stable'' and that
the government's controversial Growth, Employment and
Redistribution Policy ``sets forth a medium-term plan to keep them
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides South Africa, Rubin is visiting the Ivory Coast,
Namibia, Mozambique and Kenya to encourage policies that Washington
and international lending agencies endorse: austere budgets, open
markets, vigorous business competition and the sale of state-owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
   He also called here for expanding loans to small businesses,
more education for the poor and greater flexibility from labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   He deflected questions about the value of the South African
currency, the rand, which has fallen sharply, other than to repeat
that good economic and fiscal policies made for resilient
currencies. The rand rose 2.6 percent Tuesday to a rate of 5.985 to
the dollar. But it remains 19 percent below its value at the end of
1997, when it took 4.86 rand to buy a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rubin did not mention the political criticism faced by
the ruling African National Congress, he made it clear that the
United States supported the government's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   In an evening session with reporters, Rubin said he had ``no
ulterior motive'' in praising these policies and was not conveying
an American position on next year's South African national
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC's two closest political allies, the South African
Communist Party and the Congress of South African Trade Unions, an
umbrella organization of mostly black labor unions, strongly oppose
government economic policies, which favor cutting public payrolls,
keeping government debt low, accepting high interest rates to
control inflation and selling the airlines, railroads, ports, phone
and electric utilities, diamond mines and dozens of other companies
owned by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The government's opponents also oppose its request for ``labor
flexibility,'' considered a euphemism for union agreement to end
wildcat strikes and accept changes such as around-the-clock mining
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Such policies represent a sharp reversal for the ANC _ which,
until it came to power in 1994, took a socialist approach that
favored nationalization of the gold mines and full employment
through state projects.
</P>
<P>
   The unions and the Communists, who hold many seats in Parliament
in return for years of loyal support of the ANC, have criticized
these current policies because the economy grew less than 2 percent
last year, with a net loss by some estimates of 130,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, President Nelson Mandela and his heir apparent,
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, warned the unions and the Communists
that these policies would be ANC positions for the 1999 election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Rubin pressed here for stimulating the economy through
``micro-enterprise lending'' _ loans of as little as $50 given to
the poor to start businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To push the point, he visited a Soweto day care center run by
Francina Mbense, who has stocked it with books, toys and furniture
bought with a 15,000 rand loan _ about $2,500 _ which she received
under a program financed by the U.S. Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
   Although she pays 23.25 percent interest, Mrs. Mbense said she
was grateful because South African banks would not make loans of
less than 50,000 rand and Soweto loan sharks charged as much as 50
percent a month.
</P>
<P>
   At an hourlong discussion afterward with South African bankers
and small-business executives, Rubin heard bankers explain why they
did not make loans in impoverished areas. The cost of administering
the loans was too great, they said; they cannot offer the business
advice small borrowers need, and they are criticized when they
build cut-rate branch offices because they build fancy ones in
white suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin suggested that they look at American business models such
as pooling their money to be lent, and he noted that American
bankers had been pushed through legislation into making small loans
to customers in rundown areas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
