<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 2 DIE IN TENNESSEE FLOODS CAUSED BY RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ Nine inches of rain in four hours caused Shoal
Creek to pour out over its banks late Monday night, flooding
Lawrence County and killing at least two people.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were missing Tuesday, and at least 30 were treated
at hospitals for minor injuries. Bridges, cars and houses were
washed away in and around Lawrenceburg, the county seat, about 70
miles south of Nashville near the Alabama border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water came up extremely fast, within minutes, and it is
not common in that area, so there was not much warning,'' said
Randy Harris of the Tennessee Emergency Management Agency in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrenceburg's 10,500 residents were without drinking water
Tuesday because water and sewage treatment plants were disabled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Yurgel of the Lawrence County Emergency Management Agency
said the two flood victims were W.O. Watters, 74, and Martha
Maddox, 60. Watters' body was found Tuesday in his truck under a
bridge over U.S. 64. Ms. Maddox's car was also washed off U.S. 64
west of town. Yurgel said her body was recovered on Shoal Creek
about 100 yards from the entrance to David Crockett State Park.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 people were forced to evacuate late Monday, but the
creek quickly receded Tuesday and residents returned to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue crews continued searching for dead or injured Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a flash flood watch would remain in effect at
least until Wednesday morning for Lawrence and surrounding
counties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
