<SLUG> BC-MA-DEREG-BALLOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY DEREGULATION REPEAL VOTE CLEARS LEGAL HURDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A repeal of Massachusetts' new electric deregulation
law is one major step closer to appearing on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court has tossed out a legal challenge to
signatures that had been collected to launch the November ballot
question.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Tuesday clears all but one final hurdle for getting
the ballot question before voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-paragraph decision, the court upheld an April decision
by the state Ballot Law Commission, which gave the green light to
the repeal question after reviewing the signatures in a petition
drive required for a referendum question.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether there were sufficient signatures collected
from Barnstable and Berkshire counties.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Industries of Massachusetts, the trade group for
large businesses including Boston Edison and other utilities, had
challenged the validity of the signatures.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 66,000 signatures were collected.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, repeal advocates were celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great victory,'' said John T. O'Connor, chairman of
the Campaign for Fair Electric Rates, the group that is leading the
repeal fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the electric light companies will respect the
voters' wishes as well as the Massachusetts Supreme Court's
reaffirmation to allow a vote for lower electric rates and cleaner
air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's a loss and we knew a signature challenge is
difficult, but we'll move forward,'' said Robert R. Ruddock, AIM's
general counsel and executive vice president of energy and
environmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, AIM's remaining legal challenge is whether the proposed
ballot question is constitutional. The state's deregulation statute
includes a provision for state-run renewable energy programs that
would be funded by money collected in ratepayers' monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   Those funds _ a small percentage of the total electric bill _
are considered ``appropriations'' and under the Massachusetts
Constitution cannot be put before the voters in a ballot question,
AIM contends.
</P>
<P>
   This issue is still pending in the SJC, said Ruddock.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who is also running for Congress in the 8th
Congressional District, calls AIM's last challenge ``legal
harassment,'' adding it is a desperate measure to deny his group's
right to put the repeal before the voters.
</P>
<P>
   The state's utilities _ through AIM _ are expected to spend
millions of dollars to fight the repeal. AIM has retained a Los
Angeles firm that specializes in defeating voter referendums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never outspend them, so we must build a coalition of
small business and consumer groups to work with us,'' said
O'Connor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
