<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-MANAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEAM TAKING SHAPE AT SUNBEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DANA CANEDY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month after Sunbeam Corp. dismissed Al Dunlap as chairman and
chief executive and replaced him with another turnaround expert,
the new chief has appointed his own team to run the troubled
appliance maker, according to an internal memorandum to employees.
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, distributed Tuesday, Jerry Levin, the new chief
executive, announced a management team that replaces crucial
appointees of Dunlap with executives who helped turn around Coleman
Co., the outdoor equipment manufacturer that Sunbeam acquired in
March. Levin had been chief executive of Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Griffith has resigned as president of the household products
group, and Levin will take on his duties until a replacement is
found, the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Shapiro, a former vice president and general counsel at
Coleman, will become executive vice president and chief
administrative officer at Sunbeam, stepping into a post Dunlap had
been looking to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team brings together a few key Sunbeam veterans and
recent recruits with a number of proven executives, many of whom I
have previously worked with at Coleman,'' Levin said in the memo.
</P>
<P>
   Other important executive changes include the appointment of
Bobby Jenkins as executive vice president and chief financial
officer, a position he once held at Coleman. He replaces Russell
Kersh, who was Dunlap's most trusted lieutenant and who was
dismissed within days of the former chairman's ouster last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, while it is a new team, it's already a really
cohesive team,'' an executive close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also sought to reassure employees about Sunbeam's
future, saying that the new management was committed to helping the
maker of Sunbeam and Oster brand blenders and electric blankets
return to profitability. The memo also told employees that Sunbeam
had reached agreements with its bankers to give management time to
address the company's problems.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sunbeam declined to comment on the memo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
