<SLUG> BC-L.A.-TIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TIMES HAS NATIONAL PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times plans to introduce a national edition
later this year or early in 1999, according to top newsroom
executives.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype of the four-section paper has a main section of
national, international and regional news, with other sections
devoted to business, sports and features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take a couple of `let's see how this works'
steps,'' said Michael Parks, the editor of The Los Angeles Times,
which is a unit of Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   The edition's East Coast circulation will be concentrated in
Washington and New York, while its West Coast circulation will aim
at San Diego, the San Francisco Bay area and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper currently prints an edition that has circulation
of more than 3,500 copies in Washington and the East Coast, but
that paper is an abbreviated 12-page edition.
</P>
<P>
   James Helin, the president of the California edition who is the
executive in charge of the project, said that he envisioned an
eventual press run ``in the mid-five-figure'' range.
</P>
<P>
   The weekday circulation of The Los Angeles Times is slightly
less than 1.1 million; Sunday circulation is 1,362,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
