<SLUG> BC-LA-HOMES-SELLING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-END HOUSES JOIN IN REBOUND OF MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Crickets chirp along rustic Topeka Drive, hidden
among the luxury homes and manicured lawns that gave rise to the
area's nickname: Millionaires Row.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, it would have taken six months or longer for
these south-of-the-Boulevard homes to sell; the high-end market was
as soft as a flower bed. But recently, several homes in the
neighborhood above Ventura Boulevard have sold quickly, including
one in one day.
</P>
<P>
   It is under these circumstances that Harry and Elaine
Castellucci decided to put their 4,000-square-foot house on the
market for $895,000. Once the children left home, the empty-nesters
played with the idea of moving out. But it had to be the right time
and for the right price. The house holds many memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't such a great opportunity to sell, we wouldn't
leave,'' said Elaine Castellucci. ``It's very emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   All across L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, the tables are turning
for home buyers and home sellers. Once a buyer's market, the
housing rebound is tipping the scale toward sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the optimum time for sellers to put their homes on the
market,'' said Pat Zicarelli, president of Style Realty Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And while that's been the case for entry-level homes for at
least a few months, what makes this summer different than the
spring is the increased activity -- and prices -- in the high-end
market.
</P>
<P>
   In May, 98 Valley-area homes sold for $500,000 or higher, 44
percent higher than a year ago, according to the Southland Regional
Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   But high-price homes aren't the only news in this summer's hot
market. More homes are selling at or close to the asking price with
the average price reduction on a sale at 5.8 percent for June, the
trade group said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers have to realize that prices are going up,'' said Bud
Margolin of Fred Sands Northridge. ``The sooner they make an offer,
the better off they will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Margolin added, that doesn't mean sellers can price their
homes at 1989 levels. While market prices have risen 10 percent
from the low, they're still 25 percent below the levels of the late
'80s, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't shake Michael Shaman's optimism. He is selling
his Van Nuys house for $206,000. The house with three bedrooms, one
and three-quarter bath, and a spa has gotten interest from a dozen
people after an open house Sunday. The home has been listed for two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't sell it today, maybe I'll raise the price,'' he
joked, adding confidently, ``We'll sell it. ... I feel the market
has come up.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Zicarelli's clients, a home seller in Santa Monica, also
raised the asking price after hearing about the market upturn --
from $750,000 to $895,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the Castelluccis, selling their home of the last 15 years is
more than a financial decision. After all, they've made many
additions to the four-bedroom, five-bath house to make it cozy: a
fireplace, a jacuzzi and a lagoon pool with mini-waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Family mementos are scattered throughout the slanted ceiling
rooms with hardwood floors, giving the house a comfortable feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking to sell quickly,'' said Harry Castellucci,
looking around his home. ``We like it here.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
