<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-REACT-ART-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG BLACKS, RAGE OVER BRAWLEY CASE GIVES WAY TO ALIENATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once a merchant, now semiretired, Joey Coleman has
worked or lived around Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, for 35 years,
a witness to what has changed and what has not. So as he spent
Tuesday sitting with friends along Fulton Street, Coleman tried to
explain a frustration felt and endured more often than seen.
</P>
<P>
   No, Coleman said, he wasn't surprised that a jury in Dutchess
County _ a predominantly white jury, he pointed out _ had found the
Rev. Al Sharpton and two others liable for defamation in the
10-year-old case of Tawana Brawley. He expected little else from a
white jury, regardless of the particulars of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that people have begun to expect,'' said
Coleman, 53, who is black. ``They always expect the negative.''
</P>
<P>
   When the subject is Sharpton and Miss Brawley, it is almost a
reflex to return to Bedford-Stuyvesant to measure opinion like
ingredients in a recipe: How much anger, frustration or bitterness
remains? Ten years ago, Bedford-Stuyvesant, then Sharpton's
political base, became the center of protest after Miss Brawley,
then 15, accused a group of white men, including Steven Pagones, of
raping her.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a day after the defamation ruling against Sharpton and
two others in a civil lawsuit brought by Pagones, there were no
protests or marches in Bedford-Stuyvesant. The only fury along
commercial Fulton Street was the amplified voice of a preacher
leading a sparsely attended tent revival.
</P>
<P>
   But if time has doused the sense of rage, random interviews with
more than 20 black residents underscored the lingering sense of
alienation and frustration unleashed by the Brawley case. Ten years
later, there is not the same palpable anger, but neither is there
any sense of progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has just been so much injustice done that sometimes
blacks may overplay things,'' said Coleman. ``It's hard for a black
man now to believe all of a sudden that everything is on the
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Bedford-Stuyvesant, the defamation ruling was the talk of
many radio programs tailored to black audiences. Speaking on
WLIB-AM, Sharpton called the decision ``inconsistent and
political'' and warned that it would ``have a chilling effect on
activism and advocacy around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's host, Minister Conrad Muhammed, said, ``In our
community, it's shoot, lock you up, ask questions later.''
</P>
<P>
   The tortured storyline of the Brawley case is now familiar to
most New Yorkers: the sharp accusations against Pagones by Sharpton
and Miss Brawley's other advisers; the subsequent grand jury report
that exonerated Pagones and concluded that Miss Brawley had
fabricated her story; and, most recently, Monday's ruling against
Sharpton and the two other advisers, C. Vernon Mason and Alton
Maddox. The jury began hearing testimony in the damages phase of
the trial Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Bethany Baptist Church on Marcus Garvey Boulevard
that Miss Brawley's mother spent more than a month in
``sanctuary,'' avoiding arrest for refusing to testify before a
special grand jury investigating the case 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a few blocks away at the McCafe restaurant on
MacDonough Street, the Rev. F.D. Waddell predicted that the
decision _ and the news media attention from the trial _ would only
help Sharpton by providing him with more exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will enhance his political situation,'' Waddell said.
``What he does, and what I like about him, is he doesn't allow
something to be swept under the rug or forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the restaurant, Clara Walker, said she had known
Sharpton since he was a teen-ager. ``He tried to help but he might
have jumped the gun without getting all the facts. I know he
wouldn't put something together just to have something going. He
wouldn't do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grand jury report, Miss Walker, 63, like many other
black residents, said she believed ``something happened'' to Miss
Brawley, even if Pagones was not involved. ``Someone knows
something,'' she said. ``Something did happen to that child.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Joyce Turner, co-owner of Cross Boro Realty
on Fulton Street, said she had early doubts about Miss Brawley's
story but that she believed nonetheless that Sharpton had acted in
good faith. What she would like to see, she said, is some healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter who you are,'' she said of Pagones, ``I don't want
the wrong person to be accused of something.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than a few people criticized the news media as a biased
messenger in telling the Brawley story. Speaking on the radio
program, ``The Global Black Experience,'' Maddox accused the news
media of conspiring with the judicial system to win a decision
against the advisers. ``If this case was properly reported,'' he
said, ``everyone in this state would be in an uproar.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside her Albany Avenue apartment, Pamela Carter, 38,
agreed. ``I don't even care what happened,'' she said. ``The media
lies to us. They don't tell the real story. Sharpton, he's a black
man, he's for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sharpton did not enjoy universal support. ``Justice was
served yesterday,'' said a 47-year-old woman who asked not to be
identified as she carried groceries along Marcus Garvey Boulevard.
``And I hate to say it, but Al Sharpton can't tell me nothing. He
tried to raise a stink with it. Whenever something happens in the
black neighborhoods, here he comes. But to me, it's because he just
wants to be on the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   A 36-year-old woman who identified herself only as Renee
dismissed Miss Brawley's story. ``I believe she missed her curfew
and was scared her mother was going to tear her up and she
concocted that story,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Eberhart, 63, sat on a chair outside his apartment on
Albany Avenue, listening to the shouts from the nearby revival. ``I
think Sharpton should have checked before he went into it and
accused the man,'' Eberhart said. ``I'm not saying he's not right,
but I think he should have checked. Anything you hear out of
somebody's mouth doesn't have to be true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
