<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 More Mega-Mergers Ahead for Morgan Stanley Tech Expert   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Dealmaker Frank Quattrone may grab most of the ink, but Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter's Chuck Cory has honchoed some of the year's
biggest technology buyouts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quattrone, of course, is the investment banker credited with
building Morgan Stanley's tech practice in the Silicon Valley
earlier this decade before job- &QL; 
hopping to Deutche Bank Securities. He hung his money clip there
two years before bolting yet again to Credit Suisse First Boston a
couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cory, meantime, has toiled at Morgan Stanley for 17 years, the
first 15 of which he spent in New York. But two years ago, he was
dispatched to Menlo Park to fill the void left by Quattrone.
</P>
<P>
   Cory, 43, was no stranger to technology and telecom, having
represented AT&AMP;T in as many as 15 deals since the mid-80s. And as
Morgan Stanley's managing director of mergers and acquisitions for
technology worldwide, Cory is a rare breed: a Morgan Stanley banker
who runs an entire practice from outside Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-80s, I, like most investment bankers, was a
generalist,'' he says. Heading up a specialty ``just wasn't done
then.''
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed, and Morgan Stanley has changed with them
by requiring its bankers to specialize by industry, Cory says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment banking used to be about just being a deal
jockey,'' he notes. But not anymore. When it comes to advising
large corporations on acquisition decisions, ``you better be a
savvy industry observer who can provide intelligent advice,'' Cory
says.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's top chief executives must be listening.
Already this year, Cory has been the lead adviser on three
blockbuster technology deals totaling nearly $30 billion. He
represented Houston-based Compaq in its $9.6 billion buyout of
Digital Equipment, Santa Clara's Bay Networks in its $9.1 billion
merger with Northern Telecom and Ciena in its $7.1 billion merger
with Tellabs.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, while IPO underwriting keeps investment banks in
clover, M&AMP;A is where the action is. Eight of the 10 largest
transactions of all-time have been announced during the past three
months, according to Mergerstat, a deal tracking service in Los
Angeles. In fact, some 3,890 U.S. deals have been announced already
this year totaling more than $772 billion, which is more than
double the $285.1 billion in deals during the first half of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In what is amounting to the biggest consolidation of industry
since the turn of the century, ``more dominoes are certain to
fall,'' Cory says.
</P>
<P>
   And you can bet Cory and Morgan Stanley will be there to grab
their share.
</P>
<P>
   Access denied
</P>
<P>
   It's earnings season, and chief financial officers from Bangor,
Maine, to Burlingame are creatively putting their best spin on
their companies' latest financial results. But when unhappy news is
released, not everyone is granted the privilege of being spun.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case in San Francisco on Monday morning when the
Chronicle's semiconductor reporter, Dan Fost, wasn't allowed to
attend a special briefing held by Applied Materials for fund
analysts and managers at the posh Sheraton Plaza hotel.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Applied Materials warned Wall Street that it would
not meet analysts' consensus projections.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, shareholders wanted to hear a detailed explanation as
to why. So not to keep fund managers and analysts in the dark, the
Santa Clara semiconductor-equipment company arranged the briefing
to coincide with Semicon West, a semiconductor trade show being
held at the Moscone Center.
</P>
<P>
   With the preannouncement of a bad quarter and uncertainty
surrounding Japan's election (Applied does a lot of business in
Asia), rumors of layoffs were flying, Fost says.
</P>
<P>
   But once the reporter arrived at the registration table for the
briefing, he was told that he couldn't partake because it was ``for
analysts only.''
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials tried to make up for the inequity by holding a
separate news conference for reporters later in the day, and Fost
was given a 10-minute interview with chief executive Jim Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the institutional crowd was treated to three
hours of pointed explanation while the press and the public were
regaled with a few minutes of sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached at 901 Mission St., S.F. 94103, phone
at (415) 777-8444, or e-mail at mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com. He
also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak program on Tuesdays and
Thursdays.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
