<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTICE DELAYED AND DERAILED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno is going to report to the Senate
Judiciary Committee today, but nothing she says is likely to change
one big fact or clear up one lasting mystery. The fact is that even
with the Independent Counsel Act, if an attorney general is
determined to protect a sitting president from investigation there
is little that Congress or federal law enforcement agencies can do.
The mystery is why any attorney general would want his or her chief
legacy to be the preservation of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson said that was how history is likely to regard
the Justice Department's campaign finance inquiry if it stays on
its current track. As chairman of the Governmental Affairs
Committee, Thompson was not able to prove Chinese government
meddling in the 1996 election, but the information remains as
disturbing as it was back when the FBI first warned members of
Congress about the alleged Chinese plan. Johnny Chung, the accused
bagman who had such good entree to the Oval Office, may have been
the connection between the Chinese military and Democratic
fund-raisers, but Justice Department spin is that we may never
know.
</P>
<P>
   Such possibilities make most prosecutors curious. They make the
nation's top prosecutor militantly lethargic. Janet Reno has
rejected the obviously correct advice of Louis Freeh, the FBI
director, that she appoint an independent counsel, since her boss,
the president, was at the center of the most reckless fund-raising
effort since Watergate. The fact that even her tightly controlled
inquiry has already produced the indictment of 11 Democratic
figures argues for appointment of an independent prosecutor willing
to follow the trail into a White House where, according to a recent
indictment, a wealthy Asian businessman like Dhanin Chearvanont was
able to discuss economic issues with President Clinton and Don
Fowler, then the Democratic Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lashing her department to produce the truth, Reno has
steadily reinforced its balkiest instincts. For months in 1996, the
inquiry languished under inexperienced leadership. Charles Labella,
who arrived in October 1997 to fix things, is about to decamp to
California, abandoning his unfinished duty to David Vicinanzo, a
deputy U.S. attorney from New Hampshire. Maybe Ms. Reno learned
something during all those years she lived by the sea in Miami. If
you want to prevent a ship from reaching its destination, just keep
changing the navigators.
</P>
<P>
   We are pleased that Freeh has delayed a transfer for James
Desarno, the senior FBI investigator on the case. Freeh continues
to tell members of Congress that he thinks an independent counsel
is necessary. We would like to see him make more forceful and
persistent public statements. The worst that could happen would be
that Reno or the president would fire him. In this administration,
it would be refreshing to see someone dismissed for zealous
curiosity about how Clinton raised the money that got him
re-elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
