<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILOUT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 132 Follow Quattrone To Credit Suisse   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
After raiding the top three investment bankers from Deutsche Morgan
Grenfell's Technology Group two weeks ago, Credit Suisse First
Boston hired another 132 employees from its competitor yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mass defection represents about 95 percent of the employees
at DMG's tech group, a Menlo Park-based subsidiary of Germany's
Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The raid _ perhaps the biggest ever by a Wall Street firm _
included 75 investment bankers, more than 20 analysts and support
staff.
</P>
<P>
   They followed Frank Quattrone, who on July 1 announced that he
was quitting as DMG's managing director to head investment banking
and equity research for CSFB's technology clients around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined at the time by George Boutros, managing director
for mergers and acquisitions, and Bill Brady, managing director for
corporate finance.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, the trio jumped from Morgan Stanley with
nearly 20 of their colleagues to create a technology investment
``dream team'' for DMG.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, Quattrone had vehemently denied rumors that he was
about to leave DMG. ``I would have preferred not making this
move,'' he said yesterday. ``If Deutsche Bank's strategy didn't
change so dramatically in North America, we wouldn't have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing substantial loan losses in Asia as well as some other
problems, the giant German bank announced plans to restructure in
January. DMG's management staff was shuffled and then reshuffled.
Commitments to add research and sales force were withdrawn,
according to Quattrone.
</P>
<P>
   The company retrenched and shifted its focus back to Europe,
``making it increasingly difficult conducting business as usual,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers and prospective clients, especially those planning
initial public offerings, questioned whether Quattrone and crew
would stay put and whether they would continue to provide analyst
coverage and make markets in their stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, when Quattrone received the first inquiry from
CSFB, he says he didn't return the call. But by May, he began
talking to Charles Ward, managing director and global head of
corporate and investment banking at CSFB. Discussions became
serious in June. Quattrone and his two lieutenants jumped ship two
weeks ago. And on Monday, CSFB reached what the two sides are only
describing as an ``amicable'' agreement.
</P>
<P>
   No financial terms were discussed. Quattrone would say only that
the pay packages for himself and his colleagues ``had to be
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, DMG's high-tech practice generated about $120 million
on $200 million revenues, and profits reportedly were split about
evenly between the key producers and the company.
</P>
<P>
   Quattrone has denied rumors that he alone made $7 million to $10
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Like DMG, CSFB explored building its own technology investment
banking practice before opting to buy one. ``We concluded it would
take a very long time and the way to build critical mass would be
to hire a lot of people quickly,'' said CSFB's Ward.
</P>
<P>
   The investment banking unit of Switzerland's Credit Suisse is a
world power in several areas. In the first half of this year, it
ranked No. 3 in global mergers and acquisitions, with 123 deals
worth $249 billion. It represented AT&AMP;T in its merger with
Tele-Communications Inc., and Chrysler in the merger with
Daimler-Benz. In the past six months, it also ranked No. 5
worldwide in equity underwriting, managing 48 deals worth $11.8
billion. But in technology, it is a weakling, with just 17
investment bankers and 13 analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Those employees will report to Quattrone. The CSFB tech group
will be headquartered in Palo Alto, with about 90 employees. Other
offices will be in San Francisco, Boston, New York, London and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Some directors of competing firms suggested yesterday that
Quattrone has lost credibility after repeatedly pledging his
devotion to DMG.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1996, he left Morgan Stanley under the veneer of
building a world-class technology investment banking practice,''
said one. ``Doing it a second time, the veneer becomes thinner and
it looks like the motivation is personal gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some DMG investment banking clients _ including
Amazon.com, Atmel and PeopleSoft _ recently have taken deals to
Morgan Stanley and Merrill Lynch, others remain loyal to Quattrone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience has only been positive,'' said Peter Morris, a
partner with the venture capital firm New Enterprise Associates,
whose client Carrier Access is about to launch a public offering
with the help of Quattrone. ``We are staying with them.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the day before the mass exodus from DMG, Deutsche
Bank Chairman Rolf Breuer was quoted in the Financial Times as
saying that his firm is determined to expand investment banking in
the United States through acquisition or joint venture. But several
competitors are unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that they've lost their flagship franchise and are
pulling the tent down in the United States,'' said the managing
director of one company. He feels that CSFB poses a much graver
competitive threat than DMG ever did.
</P>
<P>
   ``They already have major-league distribution capability,'' he
said. ``They've got everything else, and now they have a new
industry group _ technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
