<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGGHEAD-SFCHRON &LR;      07-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGGHEAD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Egghead Cracks the Net   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Six months after scrapping its money-losing chain of stores,
Egghead.com Inc. could be the first big retailer to successfully
transform itself into a pure Internet company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its three Web sites comprise an online superstore with more than
40,000 computer products. The flagship site,  &LR; www.egghead.com &LR; ,
sells new hardware and software, while  &LR; www.surplusdirect.com &LR;  and
 &LR; www.surplusauction.com &LR;  offer older versions of products, along
with refurbished and surplus goods.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, sensing that Egghead could become a major shopping
presence on the Net, have driven the company's stock up from $8.44
at the start of July to $26.13 on Monday. The shares gave back some
yesterday, closing down $2.72 to $23.41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's finally setting in that Egghead is no longer the
chain of 170 little strip mall stores, and that they have a very
strong brand name that's recognized by anyone who's used a computer
over the past 10 years,'' said Paul Taylor, an analyst for Arcadia
Investment Corp. in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Egghead doesn't expect to return to profitability in the near
future, but it hopes that by slashing operating costs and focusing
on the Internet, it has set the stage for a rebound. The company
had an operating loss of $7.2 million in its fourth quarter that
ended in March _ its 11th loss in the past 12 quarters. However,
online sales _ the key to future success _ hit $30.5 million during
the quarter, exceeding forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Growth appears to be especially strong for
 &LR; www.surplusauction.com &UR; ,  &LR; a site that lets consumers bid online
for computer hardware and software. Egghead said that in the first
quarter that ended in June, revenues from the auction site nearly
doubled from the fourth quarter, reaching $13.7 million. (The
company will report first-quarter results on July 28.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; After what Egghead has endured during the past several years,
any positive news is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1984 as Egghead Software, it was the most prominent
chain selling computer software for a decade. At its zenith, it
boasted 250 stores and a thriving catalog business.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, however, computer superstores such as CompUSA were
starting to eat into Egghead's business. By the summer of 1996, the
company was on the rocks, buckling under the same pressures that
were afflicting other software chains such as Software Etc. and
Babbages, which also were finding it nearly impossible to turn a
profit with small stores based in shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   At that point the Egghead turned to its chairman, George Orban,
an early investor in the company who had also helped start several
other retail ventures, including Ross Stores, the chain of discount
clothing outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Orban became chief executive of Egghead in January of 1997,
replacing Terence Strom. Orban's first order of business was to
close about 80 stores (out of a total at that time of 160), and
concentrate on markets where he thought the company could compete.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Orban suggested that Egghead turn its
attention to the Internet. The company redesigned its Web site for
online shopping, and in August it acquired Surplus Direct, which
operated  &LR; www.surplusdirect.com &LR;  and the then-new
 &LR; www.surplusauction.com,  &LR; in a $31.5 million stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last year, Orban was confident Egghead could make
it exclusively on its growing Internet business. Last January 28,
the company said it would close its remaining 80 stores, lay off 80
percent of its 1,000 employees, take a $42 million restructuring
charge and change its name to Egghead.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point you could have made the case that Egghead would
not have long to live,'' conceded company spokesman John Hough.
</P>
<P>
   What brought Egghead back, said Orban, was its strong brand
name, a solid core of management, and the fact that it had more
than $60 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you have capital and intelligent people there are a
lot of things you can do even in as difficult a situation as
Egghead found itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Orban, 52, doesn't really see much difference between selling
out of a store or off the Web. ``I've often said this is no more a
technology business than a chain store is,'' he said. ``This is a
business of retailing in which you need to use technology to make
it successful.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to seen whether Orban's vision will translate into a
long-term rebound. The few analysts who follow the company are
taking a wait-and-see approach about the recent rise in its stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going crazy on all the Internet stocks, and this is
one that has just now been discovered,'' said Casey Stern of Starr
Securities in New York. ``What concerns me about these stocks is
that when they go up this quickly, if there's a hiccup they're
going to come down just as fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Egghead grow itself into an Internet shopping franchise? ``I
can't say at this point,'' Stern said. ``But I certainly like what
Egghead has done. It looks like they're on their way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
