<HEADER>
A4981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      07-14 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EARNINGS DECREASED 29 PERCENT AT INTEL IN SECOND QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel fell 2 percent Tuesday. After the market closed,
the chip maker reported a 29 percent drop in second-quarter
earnings, a greater-than-expected decline. Intel also said it does
not expect an improvement in the third quarter. Intel's earnings
have suffered recently from price cuts and a glut of personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   POWERFUL COMPUTING FROM SUN
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems plans to introduce the first consumer version
of a technology known as distributed computing. Such technology can
put the processing power of a supercomputer in the hands of average
users.
</P>
<P>
   STRIKES SHARPLY CUT GM'S PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Profits at General Motors fell 81 percent, mainly because of
strikes at two parts factories in Flint, Mich. The automaker also
filed a suit contending that the strikes were illegal and asking
the court to compel the United Auto Workers union to participate in
expedited arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS JUMP 13 PERCENT AT MERRILL LYNCH
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch reported a 13 percent jump in earnings for the
second quarter. Profits at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette increased
by 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McDONALD'S TO TAKE BIG CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's expects to take a pretax charge of $350 million
against its second-quarter earnings to carry out previously
announced staff layoffs and realignments and to pay for a new menu
ordering system.
</P>
<P>
   MORE DEPARTURES AT DEUTSCHE BANK
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 technology bankers and analysts are leaving
Deutsche Bank for Credit Suisse First Boston. Just two weeks ago
Credit Suisse hired the leaders of the global high-technology
banking group.
</P>
<P>
   NEW TEAM APPOINTED BY SUNBEAM
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Levin, who was named chief executive of Sunbeam a month
ago to replace the dismissed Albert Dunlap, has appointed a new
management team. Many of the appointees come from Coleman, the
outdoor-equipment manufacturer Sunbeam acquired in March. Coleman
was controlled by Ronald Perelman, whose MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes
Holdings is Sunbeam's second-largest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORT FOR SOUTH AFRICA'S POLICIES
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Treasury Robert Rubin repeatedly endorsed South
Africa's economic policies of fiscal austerity and privatization
during a visit there, even as these policies faced attack by the
government's closest allies. He deflected questions about the value
of the South African currency, the rand, which has been falling
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   NEW EDITION FOR LOS ANGELES TIMES
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times plans to introduce a national edition
later this year or early next year. A prototype of the four-section
paper has a main section of national, international and regional
news, with other sections devoted to business, sports and features.
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT ADDS TECHNOLOGY MARKETER
</P>
<P>
   Leo Burnett is acquiring TFA Communications, a
business-to-business technology marketer. TFA, which had billings
last year of $68 million, has more than 30 high-technology clients,
including Avid Technology, Motorola and News Edge.
</P>
<P>
   REPRIEVE FOR INDIA AND PAKISTAN
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives voted to exempt agriculture credits
from economic sanctions placed on Pakistan and India after they
exploded nuclear devices. The move was a response to concerns by
U.S. farmers facing heavy economic losses as a result of the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   30-YEAR BOND YIELD RISES TO 5.71 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 5.71 percent,
from 5.69 percent Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
