A4987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STATE-BORROWING-AR     07-14 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STATE-BORROWING-ART-430-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS OTHER STATES CUT DEBT, NEW YORK BORROWS MORE AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on New York state's national ranking in
outstanding debt is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There is an audacity to the way New York state
borrows money that can make even critics sound almost admiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it really is amazing,'' said Robert Kurtter, senior
vice president for state ratings at Moody's Investors Service. ``No
one else is even close.''
</P>
<P>
   While many states are taking advantage of the economic boom to
control or reduce their public debts, New York state is vigorously
bucking the trend, engaging in a borrowing spree that easily gives
it the largest debt of any state.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Mario Cuomo began his last term, on Jan. 1, 1991, New
York owed $20 billion in outstanding bonds that were being repaid
with state taxes. When Gov. George Pataki took office four years
later, the debt was $27 billion. Now it is almost $35 billion, and
the administration projects that it will reach $41 billion in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   California, with a population 75 percent larger than New York's,
is a distant second, with $21 billion in tax-supported debt.
</P>
<P>
   New York's public authorities, agencies like the Thruway
Authority and the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, which are
controlled by the governor, owed $60 billion at the start of 1991
and $71 billion when Pataki took office; they owe $85 billion
today. That figure, too, is expected to keep rising fast. Some of
that debt is supported by state taxes, but most of it is repaid
through the authorities' own revenues, like tolls and subway fares.
</P>
<P>
   This voracious borrowing has come even as the state has racked
up record surpluses in the last two years, and it has helped make
possible what Pataki, a Republican, holds up as his signal
achievement: cutting taxes deeply, even as state spending has
increased.
</P>
<P>
   Going billions of dollars deeper into debt has allowed the state
to expand its capital building programs, despite tax cuts, by
pushing the costs as much as 30 years into the future and leaving a
future generation of lawmakers to deal with the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they cut taxes, they had to either borrow a lot more
money, or let the capital program go to pieces,'' said Frank Mauro,
executive director of the Fiscal Policy Institute, a group financed
primarily by foundations and labor unions that studies state
finances.
</P>
<P>
   People who watch the state's finances from outside the Capitol,
including some who rate the state's bonds, warn of a debt crisis in
the making, one that in the next recession _ or even in a Wall
Street downturn _ could force severe program cuts and layoffs, or
increases in the taxes and fees that are used to pay off bonds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The state's debt has grown as the nation's economy has been
humming along _ though somewhat less tunefully in New York _ and
generating healthy tax revenues. Most states have used this period
to get their fiscal houses in order and their debts under control.
Louisiana, until recently the only state with a worse credit rating
than New York's (they are now tied for worst), has cut its debt in
half in five years.
</P>
<P>
   New York began the last recession as the biggest debtor state.
When some states borrowed to make ends meet during that downturn,
New York borrowed more. When sour times turned sweet, New York kept
borrowing and continues to borrow far more money, year in and year
out, than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   A new report by Moody's shows that New York state's
tax-supported debt is the fourth highest, per capita, of any state,
and fifth highest when measured against the income of state
residents.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, under Gov. Christie Whitman, has also bucked the
national trend, going much deeper into debt despite good times.
Before Whitman took office, New Jersey had a below-average debt
burden, but it has jumped to seventh worst in the Moody's rankings,
though still significantly less than New York's.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, long one of the most heavily indebted states, has
marginally increased its borrowing under Gov. John G. Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Pataki, who is running for re-election this year,
acknowledges that the state owes too much, and he has proposed some
modest steps to deal with the problem. But it is a measure of how
deeply ingrained borrowing is in the state's political culture that
while many other states have held debt steady or reduced it, the
governor's budget director, Robert King, boasts of having slowed
the rate at which New York's debt grows.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor and his aides have said the primary
blame for the growing debt lies with the Legislature, particularly
the Democrats who control the Assembly. Democratic Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver has repeatedly advocated more borrowing, despite the
state's huge cash surpluses of $2.1 billion this year and $1.4
billion last year. The administration also points to the burden of
keeping up the state's expansive infrastructure of roads, bridges,
colleges and mass transit, arguing that they were ill maintained in
Cuomo's last years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to tell you that the problem does not need to be
addressed,'' King, the budget director, said in an interview. ``We
are committed, the governor and the Budget Division, to trying to
reduce the size of the state debt.''
</P>
<P>
   But the growing debt has tarnished, somewhat, the governor's
carefully built and jealously guarded image as a fiscal
conservative, one that is central not just to his current campaign,
but to his potential aspirations for national office in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's record on debt is irresponsible, because New
York was already so deeply in debt when he took office,'' said Tom
Carroll, president of Change-NY, a group of fiscal conservatives
that has generally lauded Pataki's record. ``This is the one fiscal
problem he has made worse, rather than better. And it's
particularly inexcusable to keep borrowing more when the state is
running such big surpluses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats complain that while Pataki derided Cuomo as a
tax-and-spend Democrat, the governor has turned out to be a
borrow-and-spend Republican. New York City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone, a leading Democratic candidate for governor, has tried to
campaign to Pataki's right on fiscal matters, making himself out to
be the true conservative, and reminding audiences of his role in
creating New York City budgets that are, by most experts'
judgments, more sound than the state's.
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts say the problem has actually worsened under
Pataki, because the state borrows for more of its capital needs
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   For most of Cuomo's 12 years in office, the state paid well over
half of its capital budget with cash on hand, borrowing the rest.
In some years, the ``pay-as-you-go'' portion was over 70 percent,
and even in Cuomo's last two years in office, when the state's
economy was still stagnant, it was 51 percent and then 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pataki, it has fallen below 30 percent, despite the
state's record surpluses, and the administration's long-range plan
calls for it to drop to 10 percent soon.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``With these huge surpluses, we've not only blown a spectacular
opportunity to increase pay-as-you-go, cap borrowing and even pay
off some of the old debts, we've actually done the opposite, and
made it a lot worse,'' said Andrew Rein, senior researcher with the
Citizens Budget Commission, a nonprofit group that monitors the New
York city and state budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Most states spend less than 4 cents of every general fund dollar
repaying bonds. At the start of 1991, New York spent less than 6
cents. When Pataki took office in 1995, it spent 8 cents. This
fiscal year, it will spend $3.5 billion paying off loans, or 9{
cents of every dollar in the general fund.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is projected to keep rising fast, not only because
the state plans to keep borrowing, but because lawmakers have
approved a host of tax cuts that have not yet taken effect, and
that will cut into the available money in the general fund. The
increase is all the more striking because interest rates have been
very low in recent years, allowing the Pataki administration to
save money by refinancing bonds at lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   King, the budget director, spoke of the administration's
frustration at not being able to take more steps to control
borrowing. ``Patterns of behavior take a while to change,'' he
said. ``We're changing them as aggressively as our friends upstairs
will let us,'' he added, referring to the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pataki, the state has not engaged in some of the most
derided practices of the Cuomo years, like selling, in essence, the
Attica prison to itself to generate cash, or borrowing to meet
routine operating needs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pataki proposed early repayment of the $200 million
in Attica bonds, but the Legislature refused. This year, he
proposed paying cash for $425 million in already approved projects,
like a sports complex in Brooklyn and improvements to the Buffalo
Bills' stadium, rather than borrowing the money, but the
Legislature said no. He proposed the creation of a debt-reduction
fund that would use up to $800 million in surplus funds this year
to pay off debts; the Legislature created the fund, but would only
put $50 million in it.
</P>
<P>
   And in April, the governor, under some criticism for proposing
an 8 percent increase in state spending, vetoed more than $800
million in borrowing approved by the Legislature, saying the
projects were unnecessary, or could be paid for with cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   All of this lets Pataki claim, with some justification, that his
is the voice of restraint in Albany. But restraint is a relative
term.
</P>
<P>
   It was Pataki who this year started a six-year, $3-billion
borrowing campaign for improvements at State and City University
campuses. He agreed to the $425 million in borrowing for sports and
other facilities in last year's budget. He championed the $1.75
billion environmental bond act approved by voters in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, under Pataki's direction, the Long Island Power
Authority is issuing $7 billion in bonds, the largest state or
local bond issue in U.S. history, to buy the assets of the Long
Island Lighting Company. The MTA, which the governor controls, is
selling $3.5 billion in fare-backed bonds over three years, largely
because Pataki ended the state's practice of helping pay for new
trains and buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debt in New York is viewed as a free good,'' said Kurtter, of
Moody's. ``It's not viewed as a scarce resource. The concern is
first and foremost creating additional resources to afford current
spending, and deferring any costs that can be deferred as far as
possible into the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
