<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BAKER-FINCH-HNS &LR;      07-14 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAKER-FINCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SOUTHPORT, England _ The gloomy, cold weather settled around the
historic links of Royal Birkdale Golf Club on Tuesday much like the
bitter chill that has seeped into the heart of Ian Baker-Finch.
</P>
<P>
   This is not how Baker-Finch remembered it, with the rain and
gusting winds. But then nothing is like Baker-Finch remembers
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sunny, warm Sunday when Baker-Finch won here seven
years ago. Not just won, conquered. He shot 64, 66 for the final
two rounds, didn't miss a fairway or a green over the last 18 holes
and took his place among golf's elite as the British Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the end of his golf career.
</P>
<P>
   What would follow was the most horrific slump in golf history.
As Baker-Finch desperately fought to live up to his new status and
new title, the golf game that had gotten him there drifted away.
The perfect drives down the fairway became snap-hooks; the
taken-for-granted confidence turned into blinding fear.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, the essence of Baker-Finch the golfer was gone. In the
past three years, Baker-Finch has made just one cut worldwide and
is 0-for-32 in PGA Tour events. His total income on the golf course
for that span is less than the average teen-ager makes working for
minimum wage in a fast-food joint.
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch has been through more than 30 specialists _ coaches,
gurus, trainers, psychologists, hypnotists and well-meaning
advice-givers. He has taken his swing apart, piece by piece; spent
hours in front of a mirror trying to get back to basics; and
devoted thousands of hours to grueling practice sessions on the
driving range, always searching, always hoping.
</P>
<P>
   The result is always the same. No matter how good the swing
feels, no matter how much the mind is in sync, no matter how the
body feels, once Baker-Finch steps to the first tee in a
professional event, there's just nothing there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all been down to a lack of confidence,'' Baker-Finch
said. ``When you are young, you can pull up trees, move mountains,
rule the world. You haven't stumbled or suffered a fall. Then,
something happens and you start to realize that, yes, you are
fallible. And from that point on, it depends on how you handle
things. I just became drained of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing all my golf at the highest level and could only
stand by and watch as a new breed of young lions came through and
played better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if he had just stood by and watched, things might have
evened themselves out. But that wasn't Baker-Finch's way. So he
continued to grind, continued to pound away, beating his club
against the wall that was threatening to smother him.
</P>
<P>
   But it just got worse, and smack in the center of the spotlight
at that.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 British Open at St. Andrews, Baker-Finch, as a past
Open champion, was paired with Arnold Palmer, who was playing in
his last Open Championship. The crowds gathered around the first
tee were enormous. It should have been a simple task to land a tee
shot on what is possibly one of the widest fairways in golf.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Baker-Finch snap-hooked his drive so far, it cleared
two fairways and went out of bounds on No. 18, more than 170 yards
left.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 at Royal Lytham, Baker-Finch started with a 78 and
finished with an 84, coming in last. And then came the worst blow.
Baker-Finch had such high hopes coming into the 1997 British Open
at Royal Troon. He had played in a pro-am the week before and
carded a solid 67. But by the time he stepped to the first tee
Thursday, the demons were back in full force.
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch double-bogeyed the second, sixth and eighth holes;
made bogey on the first three holes on the back side; doubled the
13th with a hooked drive; tripled the 16th by driving out of
bounds; and then doubled the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was absolutely the worst feeling I've ever known,''
Baker-Finch said, ``walking up the 18th at the British Open about
to shoot 92.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until months later that Baker-Finch described in an
article for Sports Illustrated how he and his wife, Jennie, walked
into the champions' locker room following the round, curled up on
the floor together in a fetal position and sobbed. Then after 45
minutes of misery, Baker-Finch pulled himself together and went to
the media center to answer every last painful question from
reporters. That evening, he packed his bags and left, withdrawing
from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Baker-Finch has taken a retirement of sorts from
golf. He continues to practice and play with his friends, maybe a
club event here or there, but nothing in any official competitive
capacity. And surprisingly, his game has been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so relaxed, I am playing really well,'' Baker-Finch said.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, he has come full circle. Back to the place where
it all started and then ended. But this year, Baker-Finch arrived
at Royal Birkdale without his clubs. He is working this week as a
color commentator for ESPN and ABC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am qualified to play at Birkdale by virtue of being a
previous winner of the Open,'' Baker-Finch said. ``But I decided
some time ago to give it a miss this year. I am covering the
tournament for ABC. I can offer them a good insight into what is
going on, and what might be going through a player's mind, or how a
tournament is unfolding in terms of who might win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch returned to Royal Birkdale last month for the first
time since his victory, doing work for Japanese television. The
Birkdale staff had rigged loudspeakers at No. 18, and when
Baker-Finch walked up the 18th fairway, they played the tape of the
cheers and yells that accompanied his walk up that last fairway in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Baker-Finch said. ``The staff had all
gathered at the windows of the clubhouse, and they were all
applauding. It was a marvelous moment, one I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the one seven years ago, when Baker-Finch was hugging
his wife in the bright sunshine on the 18th green at Royal Birkdale
and kissing the coveted Claret Jug. In his heart, he believes one
day that he and the sunshine will return to the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only 37,'' Baker-Finch said. ``I'll be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
