<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-MISSILE-SPI &LR;      07-14 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MISSILE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS BOEING'S MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM MAY NOT BE READY IN
TIME  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The national missile defense system, for which The
Boeing Co. recently won an initial $1.6 billion contract to develop
and manage, faces significant risks and technical challenges and is
unlikely to be ready in time to protect the country from attack by
2003 as planned, the General Accounting Office said in a
just-released report.
</P>
<P>
   The findings likely will provide more ammunition to the
project's critics in Congress, who have belittled it as the ``son
of Star Wars,'' the much-maligned 15-year-old proposal by former
President Ronald Reagan for a space-based missile-defense shield
against attack by the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars was considered technically and financially
impractical.
</P>
<P>
   The system under development by Boeing is less ambitious and is
designed to protect the United States from an attack by a rogue
nation, or an accidental missile launch by Russia or China.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Jeff Bingaman, a Democrat from New Mexico and a program
critic, called the report ``disturbing.'' He said it's still not
clear, despite much research, that the system will even work.
</P>
<P>
   For Boeing, it's a $5 billion question. That's what it would be
worth to the Seattle-based aerospace giant if the administration
decides in 2000 to build the system and extend Boeing's contract to
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing must first demonstrate by 2000 that even a
rudimentary missile shield will work and can be deployed by 2003 in
either Grand Forks, N.D., or in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The project has the strong support of many congressional
Republicans, who would like to see such a system deployed sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Even meeting the current deployment schedule is doubtful,
according to the General Accounting Office, the independent
investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accomplishing all the required contracting, development,
integration and testing planned before the initial decision point
in fiscal year 2000 is, and will continue to be, high risk,'' said
the GAO report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any decision in fiscal year 2000 to deploy an NMD (national
missile defense) system by 2003 would involve high technical risk
because the associated compressed schedule will permit only limited
testing of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO prepared a less detailed report on the project last
December. The latest report was requested by Democrats on the
Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon on June 30 awarded the initial development contract
to Boeing, which beat out United Missile Defense Co., a joint
venture among Lockheed Martin, Raytheon and TRW. The team from
United Missile Defense was considered the front runner because it
had more experience than Boeing in missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.6 billion contract was the largest yet awarded for a
national missile defense program.
</P>
<P>
   The initial development phase of the project is being run by
Boeing's Space Systems Division in Downey, Calif., and will involve
about 250 workers in the region. Half those workers will be new
hires, Boeing has said.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with reporters when Boeing was
selected, John Peller, Boeing's vice president overseeing the
project, said the company would be able to overcome the
technological difficulties. He said much has been learned during
the years of research that the Pentagon had conducted at a cost of
about $50 billion on previous efforts to build a missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confident that the technology is in place,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing spokesman said Tuesday that Peller has seen the GAO
report but has not yet had time to read it and could not comment on
its conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Boeing's risk is significant because the
program's schedule only permits limited flight testing before 2000,
when the Defense Department will decide whether to deploy the
system in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of flight testing is limited compared to other
programs,'' the GAO report warned.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department, in a letter attached to the GAO report,
said it agreed with the risk assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department concurs that the National Missile Defense (NMD)
program faces significant challenges because of high schedule and
technical risks. The report is generally accurate ....''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year a panel appointed by the Pentagon, headed by
Gen. Larry Welch, a former Air Force chief of staff, warned against
``a rush to failure'' because of the project's ambitious schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had requested $2 billion for fiscal
years 1996 to 1998, but Congress more than doubled the amount to
$4.6 billion for increased testing.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the missile system is much smaller than the Star
Wars shield envisioned by Reagan in the 1980s, the technical
challenges are still daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing must develop space and ground-based radar to provide
early warning of attacking missiles, a ground-based radar system to
identify and track the missiles, and an anti-missile interceptor to
hit and destroy the incoming missile.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report did note that since its last look at the project
in December 1997, some technical progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Sensors successfully tracked and obtained data needed to
identify simulated targets and decoys, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   More flight tests have been added, the report said, but they may
not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   If a decision is made in 2000 to deploy the system by 2003,
three flight tests would be conducted in fiscal year 2000, and four
a year in fiscal years 2001 through 2003. But the GAO quoted
Boeing's program manager as saying even the expanded flight test
program is ``anemic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
