<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. HAYWORTH'S LETTER ASSAILS CLINTON, INFURIATES DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona Rep. J.D. Hayworth, who had been trying to soften his
caustic style, has enraged Democrats with a fund-raising letter
calling Clinton an ``unprincipled, philandering president.''
</P>
<P>
   In the July 1 appeal for money, the Arizona Republican also said
that Clinton has presided over ``the most corrupt administration in
U.S. history.''
</P>
<P>
   And it warned that Hayworth's Democratic opponent, Steve Owens,
is being bankrolled by ``trial lawyers, radical homosexual rights
groups, environmental extremists . . . along with almost every
other left-wing wacko group you can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-page letter has embittered Democrats who are still
smarting over Indiana Republican Dan Burton's reference to Clinton
as a ``scum bag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of bitter partisanship and meanspirited name-calling
is shocking, even coming from Hayworth,'' Mark Fleisher, head of
the state Democratic Party, said Tuesday in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayworth's chief of staff, Joe Eule, said Fleisher ``takes
hypocrisy to new heights'' by accusing the congressman of
name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a June 29 Democratic Party news release saying
Hayworth had been named the ``dumbest member of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The release relied on a July ``Washingtonian'' magazine survey
of 1,200 Capitol Hill staffers that rated Hayworth No. 1 in the
``No Rocket Scientist'' category among House members.
</P>
<P>
   Owens also has been less than flattering to Hayworth in his
fund-raising appeals.
</P>
<P>
   One Owens letter branded Hayworth a ``partisan yes man'' for
House Speaker Newt Gingrich and another said the congressman is
``beholden to the liquor lobby that opposes tougher drunk driving
limits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I take issue with the idea that this is any more vitriolic
than any other fund-raising letter,'' Eule said of Hayworth's
missive. ``It's no more vitriolic than the ones our opponent sends
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth's fund-raising appeal is designed to fire up
conservative voters in his sprawling 6th Congressional District,
but a copy was inadvertently mailed to a Democrat who turned the
letter over to state party officials.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seized upon it as a sign that Hayworth was reverting
to the cutting style that gained him so much publicity during his
first term in Congress. After narrowly escaping defeat in 1996,
Hayworth had taken a much lower profile while gaining more
prominence in Congress with a seat on the prestigious House Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretended to be a kinder, gentler J.D., but it doesn't
seem to be that way after this letter,'' Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Hayworth also calls California Democrat Rep. Henry
Waxman, head of the House committee that has been investigating
Democratic fund-raising, an ``oleaginous left-winger.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman press aide Phil Schiliro said Hayworth's letter
symbolizes ``what people find so repugnant about politics today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about ideas or who's better, it's about trading
insults,'' he said. ``It's just unfortunate that's what his
politics has sunk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth is facing a sharp challenge from Owens, a former
Democratic Party chairman and an old friend of Vice President Al
Gore. Owens came within a whisker of defeating the former TV
sportscaster in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth's letter suggests that Clinton's fate could be decided
in part by the the outcome of his own re-election because Democrats
have made him a top target in their effort to regain control of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to survive, they must beat me,'' Hayworth's letter
states. He also suggests that Clinton likely would be impeached by
a re-elected GOP Congress: ``Make no mistake,'' he wrote ``the
Clinton gang will approach this election as if their very survival
is at stake. They should. It is.'' &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
