<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYER-IMPOSTOR-1STLD     07-14 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-IMPOSTOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER HANDLING MANY CASES, MAN HELD FOR POSING AS LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 6th graf to give location and correct date of hearing; subs
9th graf to give location where brief was filed; subs 10th graf to
give location of home; adds 15 grafs at end) 
(ATTN: N.Y., Md., Va., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He calls himself Paul C. Kurtz Esq., and those who
know him say that he has done a commendable job of representing
defendants in federal courts in New York and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to how Kurtz has represented himself, that is
a different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a still-unraveling case that prosecutors suggest
may be one of the more audacious legal hoaxes of recent years,
Kurtz was arrested in Maryland by the FBI and charged with two
counts of lying to judges about being a lawyer, and investigators
say he may have similarly misrepresented himself to as many as 100
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, prosecutors say Kurtz is not a lawyer. They say he is a
56-year-old con man from Bethesda, Md., who has fooled judges in
courthouses in Manhattan, Brooklyn and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has not said whether it has evidence
that Kurtz has actually tried cases, his role in plea bargains and
sentencing proceedings has led to concern that some of those
convictions and sentences may be in jeopardy in cases where
defendants believed that Kurtz was a genuine lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been trying to get a handle on exactly how extensive
this catastrophe is,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney James Benjamin told
U.S. District Court Judge Sidney Stein at a hearing on July 8 in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   His performance was good enough to convince others of his legal
savvy. One lawyer, H. Elliot Wales, said Tuesday by telephone that
Kurtz had performed admirably in presenting a legal brief and
arguments at a sentencing hearing at which they both represented a
defendant, and seemed to be extremely dedicated to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should say, I thought his brief was superb,'' Wales said.
``I thought he made a good oral argument. I thought he was
professional in every way. If all lawyers acted as well and as
competently in proceedings as he did, we would have a great bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz filed that sentencing brief in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan sitrict on behalf of one of Wales' clients, Daniel
Spiegelman, who had been convicted of stealing valuable documents
from Columbia University's rare book and manuscript collection.
Investigators say that widely publicized case was among the scores
in which Kurtz may have misrepresented himself.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, investigators executed a search warrant and seized 36
file boxes from Kurtz's home in Bethesda. By the end of last week,
they were still sifting through the contents of the boxes, the
investigators told Stein, and they believe there are 80 to 100
cases ``where Kurtz has stood up in front of a judge,'' the
prosecutor, Benjamin, said, ``and has blatantly misrepresented who
he is and what his qualifications are.''
</P>
<P>
   For prosecutors, the revelations about Kurtz are a potential
headache. Benjamin added: ``It is going to have extremely serious
consequences requiring the reopening of what appears to be numerous
settled criminal cases with serious cost to the administration of
justice, prejudice to the government, and to the courts as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey C. Hazard, professor of legal ethics at the University
of Pennsylvania School of Law, said that the real cost in such
cases is borne by the defendant. ``He's entitled to a lawyer,''
Hazard said. ``He didn't have a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz is being held with a bond of $200,000 in Maryland pending
further proceedings, and could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
The government is seeking to have him transferred to Manhattan to
face the charges.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Brian Shaughnessy, would not comment on the case
except to say that Kurtz is an expert in the complex rules that
govern federal sentencing and was often consulted by lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was highly knowledgeable in those areas,'' Shaughnessy
said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials say they were first tipped off to questions about
Kurtz's background on July 2 from a source they will not identify.
They conducted a computerized nationwide check and found no record
that Kurtz was licensed to practice law anywhere in the United
States, Agent Jeffrey Drubner wrote in the federal complaint filed
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also found that Kurtz had a record of convictions
dating back to the early 1970s in Virginia, Pennsylvania and
Washington for crimes including passing bad checks, larceny, bank
fraud and theft, Drubner wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be learned Tuesday whether Kurtz had attended some
law school or where he might have picked up his legal knowledge.
His business card, which is included in court records, describes
him as ``attorney at law'' at the ``National Correctional
Counseling Center'' in Bethesda.
</P>
<P>
   In March, while Kurtz was representing a defendant who was
pleading guilty to money laundering in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, Kurtz was asked by Judge Leonard Sand about his
affiliation. Sand said that he was not familiar with the National
Correctional Counseling Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an adjunct part of my practice, Your Honor,'' Kurtz
replied, according to the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz told the judge that the primary focus of his practice ``is
to deal with sentencing matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sand, addressing the defendant, Tohmes Peter, asked, ``Are you
satisfied with the representation you have received from your
attorney?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Peter responded.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Kurtz lied again, prosecutors said, when he wrote
to another judge who was assigned to handle Peter's sentencing.
Kurtz asked Judge Kevin Duffy for a postponement of the hearing,
explaining, ``I have recently lost my elderly mother and, as a
result of attending to personal family business, have fallen behind
in attending to client affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   But last Thursday it was revealed in court that Kurtz's
87-year-old mother is alive and lives in Silver Spring, Md. Kurtz's
lawyer, Shaughnessy, agreed with that assertion, the transcript
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is alive,'' Shaughnessy conceded. ``It is a fact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
