<HEADLINE>
JURY PICKED IN CADET CAPITAL MURDER TRIAL, TESTIMONY TO BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Whittled down from an initial pool of 181
Comal County residents, a dozen jurors were selected Tuesday in
former Air Force Academy Cadet David Graham's highly publicized
capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of seven men and five women cleared the way for
opening arguments to begin Wednesday morning. District Judge Don
Leonard allotted 20 minutes for prosecutors and defense attorneys
to make their opening remarks. After that, prosecutors were to
begin presenting witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Mike Parrish said he expects to take
at least one week to build his case against Graham, who is accused
of killing Adrianne Jones, 16, of Mansfield, Texas, in December
1995. He would not disclose who his first witnesses will be.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 20, faces life in prison if convicted of capital murder.
His former fiance, Diane Zamora, was convicted of capital murder in
February and is serving a life sentence at a women's prison in
Gatesville. Prosecutors say the pair plotted Jones' death after
Graham said he had a relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors hearing Graham's case include a race-horse trainer, an
industrial psychology consultant, a civilian Air Force aviation
mechanic and a pool hall operator. The jury also includes two
Hispanics and the only African-American in the initial pool.
</P>
<P>
   Some on the panel initially said they were biased against Graham
based on extensive publicity about the case, but all agreed that
they would be impartial jurors. One juror said judging someone is
against her religious beliefs but later agreed that she could
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Lead defense attorney Dan Cogdell spent most of Tuesday's court
session questioning the pool. The Houston lawyer stressed that
prosecutors are required by law to prove that Graham is guilty of
Jones' slaying and that the defense team is not required to prove
that Graham is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell also suggested reasons why a ``hypothetical'' defendant
might make a written confession that was not true. ``What if they
loved another person very much and agreed to take responsibility
with them?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The understanding of laws regarding written confessions and
reasons people make them will be a key part of the defense because
Graham submitted a hand-written statement detailing Jones' slaying,
Cogdell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that the statement is going to be an issue in
this case. ... It's a critical inquiry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the questioning, Cogdell asked the potential
jurors whether any of them thought that Graham is innocent based on
his portrayal in the news media and the Zamora's trial in February.
No hands raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a bigger burden than I ought to have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he is ``elated'' with the jury panel. ``I wanted
smart, free-thinking jurors and I think I got them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish, the lead prosecutor, declined to comment about the
jury. He questioned the prospective jury pool Monday, at one point
asking for assurances from the panel that they would not let their
first impressions of a defendant influence their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Cogdell asked Graham to stand up and walk into the
center of the jury pool. As the 6-foot, 2-inch former cadet turned
to face all the panelists, Cogdell asked if anything about Graham's
appearance made them believe that Graham might be guilty. No hands
were raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good-looking kid, and I wanted the jury to see that his
looks are inconsistent with that of a killer,'' Cogdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's trial was moved to New Braunfels out of concern that
extensive publicity about Zamora's trial would hamper jury
selection in Tarrant County, where the slaying occurred.
</P>
<P>
   According to police records and Zamora's trial testimony, Zamora
and Graham carried out a plan to kill Jones after Graham claimed he
had sex with her. Jones was found beaten and shot to death along a
rural southwest Grand Prairie road. The case went unsolved for nine
months until Zamora confided to her roommates at the Naval Academy
about her role in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said he plans to call Zamora to testify in order to show
inconsistencies between a written statement she made to police and
her testimony during her trial.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
