<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-SANCTIONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS EXEMPTS WHEAT SALES FROM PAKISTAN SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress gave final approval Tuesday to a measure
that allows Northwest farmers to sell wheat to Pakistan, removing a
major obstacle for an industry reeling from the effects of the
Asian financial crisis and overabundant harvests worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said President Clinton would sign into law the
measure, which exempts wheat sales from sanctions imposed on
Pakistan for its testing of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was crucial because Pakistan Wednesday plans to buy
about $35 million of wheat. Northwest growers now are free to bid
against farmers from Canada and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The mandatory sanctions Clinton imposed against India and
Pakistan after they tested nuclear weapons in May prohibited the
United States from issuing credit guarantees, which Pakistan needs
to borrow money from private banks to buy U.S. wheat. The measure
approved by the House and Senate Tuesday exempts those credits.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was not controversial _ the final version passed
both houses on a voice vote when few members were present _ but it
was only the announcement of the impending purchase by Pakistan
that finally propelled Congress to action.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest lawmakers, who have been trying to get the sanctions
lifted since the day they were imposed, were jubilant. Pakistan,
which prefers the white wheat grown in the Northwest to the red
wheat grown in other parts of the United States, bought more than a
third of Washington state's wheat crop last year at a price of more
than $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news for eastern Washington,'' said Sen. Patty
Murray, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat is now Washington state's second most valuable export,
after Boeing airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is critically important that we not cut off people who will
buy our product,'' said Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash., whose
district includes the southeastern Washington region where the
wheat industry is concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt personally delivered the bill to the White House for
Clinton to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly stated his willingness to change the
sanctions law to exempt agricultural export credits.
</P>
<P>
   The president ``does not believe food should be used as a weapon
in the imposition of sanctions,'' said White House spokesman P.J.
Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat farmers, who by some estimates are facing the lowest price
for their crop in 70 years, are relieved to have access to the
Pakistani market. Some wheat industry officials hope that a
Northwest sale to Pakistan will help raise prices on the overall
wheat market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful news,'' said Thomas Mick, chief executive
officer of the Washington Wheat Commission. ``This is something we
really need at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   During about 30 minutes of debate on the House floor Tuesday, no
one spoke against the bill. But the plight of the wheat farmers has
fueled anti-sanctions sentiment in Congress, and some members
suggested that many more sanctions should be lifted to help other
industries sell products abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation does not go far enough,'' said Rep. Calvin
Dooley, D-Calif. ``Why does it not make sense for us to limit
sanctions on any other product? It is in the interest of U.S.
workers to eliminate sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   That thinking drew concern from some, including House
International Relations Committee Chairman Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that we can help our farmers ... but we are
approving U.S. loans, funded by taxpayer dollars, to replace the
money the Pakistanis could have used to take care of their own
needs, and instead they used that money to develop nuclear
weapons,'' he said. ``There is definitely a role for unilateral and
multilateral sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., the ranking Democrat on the
International Relations Committee, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill should not be construed as a lessening of our
commitment to nonproliferation,'' he said. ``To the contrary, by
crafting a more focused sanctions policy, it helps secure the
domestic base for continuing sanctions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
