<HEADLINE>
AT BOLLETTIERI, TENNIS PRODIGIES RUB ELBOWS, MASSAGE EGOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add 1st name for Nick Bollettieri, 17th graf)  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(gm) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite age restrictions on the women's tour and the need for a
power game on the men's tour, tennis prodigies continue to spring
up like mushrooms, many of them traveling to the United States with
eager parents who still believe that the sport can deliver their
children to the pot of gold at the end of a global rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   Like divas sharing the same stage, two of these players
brandished their racquets and pounded away last spring on adjacent
practice courts at the Bollettieri Sports Academy in Bradenton,
Fla., without ever acknowledging the other's existence.
</P>
<P>
   They plowed through intense practices like workhorses in
blinders: 15-year-old Yelena Bovina, working out with a coach and a
male sparring partner under the watchful eye of her mother,
Marguerite, and 11-year-old Maria Sharipova, whose effervescent and
opinionated father, Uri, has received strict orders to stay mum
while his daughter learns her trade.
</P>
<P>
   All that was at stake, according to both young emigrants, was a
happy future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to come to Bollettieri's: back home I played
on a piece of street, but here you've got good coaching, good
weather, good everything,'' said the freckle-faced Bovina, a
6-foot-2-inch power hitter who likens her style to Monica Seles and
Venus Williams, and who won her professional debut recently in a
satellite event in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Bovina once took 90-minute subway rides to practice in Moscow
but now lives in a brand-new apartment a stone's throw from the
Bollettieri complex. ``You have everything here. When I saw this
place, I wanted to stay,'' said Bovina, who arrived with a single
suitcase, intending only to play the Eddie Herr junior event in
December. She never went home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one way for my daughter to become the best, to
realize all of her potential,'' added Marguerite Bovina, who left
her husband and another daughter behind in Moscow to chaperon
Yelena's quest.
</P>
<P>
   Bovina and Sharipova are two of the latest influx of Russian
prodigies plucked up by talent scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Each is poised for a direct launch into professionalism, a place
where, in Sharipova's carefully enunciated vision, she said: ``If
you're good enough, you're going to make a lot of money. I won't
make a million dollars by staying back in Russia and being the No.
1 junior in the world. Because I came here to Florida, I gave
myself the ability to make it in the pros.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharipova signed with the International Management Group when
she was 9 and already commands a ballerina's poise. She said she
planned to use her tennis earnings to ``buy a house in the
mountains and help all my grandparents, because life is hard for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bovina, who was discovered in Moscow three years ago by scouts
for IMG, which owns the Bollettieri complex in Bradenton, got to
the pro circuit sooner than Sharipova. ``In Russia I was always the
best for my age; now I get to prove I can be the best in the
world,'' said Bovina, who insists she has selected her own destiny
and expresses gratitude to her parents for helping her pursue it.
</P>
<P>
   Bovina first gripped a racquet at 4 in Morocco, where her father
had a stint with the consulate; back in Moscow, she played and won
her first tournament at 8. She and her family were hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Though the sneaker companies are in a retrenchment mode and the
popularity meter does not shine as brightly on tennis as it once
did, business is booming at the tennis academies that dot south
Florida. While the mission of the camps is to turn out graduates
with college scholarships, what makes them famous is the superstars
they spawn.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bovina and Sharipova, nearly everybody is in a hurry _ with
a clear conscience. All the parents say they have nothing but the
maximization of the child's talent in mind, an assertion echoed by
the academies, with a caveat: ``The role of the parent in a
player's career is huge, and there's often a fine line between
coach and parent, but we're getting better at dealing with it,''
said Ted Meekma, the head of I.M.G.'s academies division. ``We're
trying to educate them that the best role of the parent is usually
just that, to be a parent, not the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ross of Advantage International, who represents Australia's
17-year-old Lleyton Hewitt, said: ``As managers, it's our job to
exploit and extract the very best opportunities for our clients,
but for the players themselves, and their families, it can't be all
about the money. At least, it shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, parents like Hewitt's, who waited for a nod from John
Newcombe and Tony Roche, the sages of Australian tennis, before
letting their son turn professional at 16, appear more restrained
than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the carrot and the stick, and it's created a
monster,'' said Mike DePalmer Sr., a former coach at the University
of Tennessee and a longtime associate of Nick Bollettieri, the
mentor who developed Andre Agassi, Monica Seles and Anna
Kournikova. ``The downside to the equation is the pressures on some
kids; the upside is that kids who graduated from this place
received $2.2 million in college scholarships last year alone.''
</P>
<P>
   But those were ``normal'' teen-agers with no chance of making a
splash in the pros. The prodigies, according to IMG's Gavin Forbes,
are not normal. ``They're like your little Mozarts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The precedents set by 17-year-old Martina Hingis' No. 1 ranking
and megamillions, 16-year-old Anna Kournikova's multimillion-dollar
clothing contracts even before she has won a tournament and the
dual celebrity of the teen-aged Williams sisters despite bypassing
the traditional junior development route have had a galvanizing
impact. If you're extraordinary, you're marketable. Now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Bovina already has a Nike contract and a clear-cut goal. ``I
want to be No. 1,'' she said in succinct English as her mother
beamed. ``Then I want to buy a house and 10 horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bollettieri's blueprint for Bovina includes a slew of $10,000
Challenger events and a summer of World Team Tennis. ``She's got a
lot working for her if she can come through on the playing end:
she's tall, blonde, pretty, friendly, a natural for television,''
he said. ``But I don't know what will happen if we don't have quick
results. I need two more years, but I'm not sure they think that
way. I think she overworks, but when we talk about cutting back her
court time, the mother, who happens to be a lovely person, starts
to cry. So there's pressure coming from somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of teen professionals is more common, but not
limited to the women's side: Belgium's 17-year-old Xavier Malisse
and Australia's Hewitt made their mark on the men's circuit in a
matter of weeks. Malisse came within 2 points of upsetting a fellow
high school dropout, top-ranked Pete Sampras, last February in his
professional debut in Philadelphia, and Hewitt made history at 16
by defeating Agassi en route to his first career title at Auckland,
New Zealand, in January. Now the 17-year-old generating the most
fuss, along with a feeding frenzy of agents eager to represent him,
is southern California's Taylor Dent, the son of Phil Dent, a
former Australian touring pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early for a guy these days,'' said Jose Lambert, who
coaches Malisse at Bollettieri's, ``and I would never tell a
17-year-old boy he better be ready to hang with the consummate
pros. But Xavier's got the God-gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got me a winner and a character,'' Bollettieri said
proudly about Malisse. ``He's a magician, moves like lightning, and
oh boy, the mark he can make if he stays halfway sane when the
money starts rolling in. He's my breakthrough player for late
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes Maria Sharipova Bollettieri's player for 2002,
barring a revision of a rule that keeps her off the women's pro
tour until she's 15. ``I keep telling the dad, what's the rush,
we've got an age rule here,'' Bollettieri said. ``The girl knows
how to win, and all the fundamentals are there, but I can't send
her out when she's 13, even if she's ready. And I can't switch her
to a lefty just because he says it's in the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   But Uri Sharipova, who worked the mines in Siberia to pay for
his daughter's passage to the United States four years ago, a
passage that separated Maria from her mother in Sochi for two
years, remains impatiently optimistic. As he observed from
courtside during one of Maria's morning practice sessions at the
Bollettieri academy: ``This place is Mecca for the dreams, isn't
it? So maybe the rule will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Macci, whose academy is based in Fort Lauderdale, says the
new tennis parents are well-informed, hypercritical and demanding.
``With the parents,'' he said, ``no matter what you do, it's never
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Macci estimates the total yearly costs of top-caliber full-time
private training can hit $100,000. No wonder the parents, whether
they are paying now or paying back later (an arrangement Macci
often employs), can get overwrought about their investment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bollettieri and Macci sent home an 8-year-old candidate
from England. Though Macci now coaches 13-year-old Todd Reid, the
Australian prodigy who arrived at Bollettieri's last fall with his
own agent and sponsorship portfolio, he admits that ``they put the
cart before the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can know how a 13-year-old boy will turn out,'' Macci
said. ``I even had some parents bring in a 5-year-old for me to
look at, and what I said was, `This is insane.'''
</P>
<P>
   But signing 11-year-old girls like Katia Afinogenov, a Russian
prospect whose mother was a world-class runner at 800 meters and
whose brother has been drafted by the National Hockey League's
Buffalo Sabres, to a 10-year contract is, according to Macci, a
sane maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer Capriati was 10 when she came here, and Venus and
Serena Williams were 10 and 11,'' Macci said. ``When you know
you've got a can't-miss on your hands, especially with the girls,
this is when to get serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
