<HEADLINE>
A PARADE OF THREE SMALL COFFINS, A FAREWELL TO 3 BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new 8th graf to clarify wording about the father. No
other changes.)  (ART ADV: photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RASHARKIN, Northern Ireland _ A day after Orangemen in their
bowler hats staged their jaunty annual parades throughout Northern
Ireland, a procession with an anguished pace followed three small
coffins up a hillside road Tuesday to a country churchyard here.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the white coffins, with polished brass nameplates on top,
were the bodies of Richard Quinn, 11, and his brothers Mark, 10,
and Jason, 9. They were burned to death in their beds in the early
hours of Sunday morning by a firebomb thrown in the ground-floor
window of their two-story row house in nearby Ballymoney.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few Catholics in a predominantly Protestant housing
project, the boys were the latest victims of this province's
sectarian violence, which has claimed the lives of more than 3,200
people. Two men have been arrested, and one of them is suspected of
links to a fringe Protestant paramilitary group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news of the deaths of these three boys has touched the
hearts of people across the continents,'' the Rev. Peter Forde told
the mourners, who thronged every aisle and standing area of the
Church of Our Lady and St. Patrick. A loudspeaker brought the
Requiem Mass to people outside who could not fit in. The church,
itself a target of arsonists in past years, has stained-glass rose
windows that are fortified with metal grills.
</P>
<P>
   The sorrowful silence was broken only by sobs from friends and
family members who stared at the boys' coffins in pain and
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie Quinn, 29, the boys' mother, sat expressionless in the
first pew, comforted by her remaining son, Lee, 12. He survived
because he was staying that night at the house of his grandmother,
Irene Quinn, in Rasharkin.
</P>
<P>
   The coffins were carried into the nave as the steeple bell
tolled dirgeful single notes. People throughout the church pressed
handkerchiefs to their faces, and children clutched their parents.
The coffin bearers, teen-agers and young men, shook with grief, and
substitutes rushed to shoulder their burden.
</P>
<P>
   The most distraught of them, a man with tattoos and facial
jewelry named John Dillon, 28, who lives in England, is the father
of at least one of the boys, all of whom had taken their mother's
name. He was left to mourn alone, at times taking up the front line
of pallbearers and tearfully caressing the coffins. References to
remembrances for special prayers during the services avoided
mentioning the name of any father, talking instead of ``Chrissie,
Lee and the extended family.''
</P>
<P>
   The scripture readings spoke of resurrection. An achingly sweet
poem composed by two teen-agers from the housing project where the
dead boys lived asked: ``Why would someone do this? is the question
on our lips. Who would have so much evil at their fingertips?''
</P>
<P>
   Forde invited Presbyterian and Methodist ministers to help him
lead the service. ``One could even say that we are all united by
this horrible event,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Patrick Walsh, of the diocese of Down and Connor, said he
had spent the past week visiting parishes ``where people have been
living under a constant cloud of fear, anxiety and tension _ so
many intimidated, so many homes attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to disputes over Protestant marches, disputes
that have provoked arson attacks on Catholic churches and homes,
and letters with bullets and threatening notes sent to Catholics
living in Protestant areas. The mob violence culminated in the
killings of the boys on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airwaves, the printed page, have been saturated with
noises _ strident, harsh, discordant noises _ carrying words of
hatred, of incitement or recrimination, words not found in the
vocabulary of Christianity,'' Walsh said. Leaving no doubt that he
saw linkage between defiant protests and violent acts, he said,
``The weapons of hate-filled words inevitably fuel weapons of
murderous destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The standoff between the Protestant Orange Order and government
security forces at Drumcree, outside Portadown, is in its 10th day.
The number of protesters and rioters has been greatly reduced, but
the Orange leaders say they are determined to carry on despite
calls from Protestant clerics and politicians to withdraw out of
respect for the boys.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At issue is the right of the Portadown Orange Lodge members to
return from Drumcree parish to their downtown headquarters along a
road that goes through a neighborhood of Catholic housing projects.
The government's Parades Commission ordered them to return by
another route but they refused. The Orangemen have been camped at
the site since July 5, when they encountered the barricades and
troops placed in their way.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night the Rev. Ian Paisley, hard-line leader of the
Protestant cause, turned aside suggestions from Ronnie Flanagan,
commissioner of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, from David Trimble,
the new first minister of the Northern Ireland Assembly, and from
others that the protest contributed to mob violence that had ended
in the killing of the Quinn boys.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally at Drumcree lighted by bonfires, Paisley urged the
demonstrators to maintain their stand and said politicians seeking
an end to the protest were ``dancing on these young fellows'
graves.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Irish Republican Army had committed ``much
worse crimes'' against Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Orange Order's own religious leaders stepped up the
pressure on the protesters to end their standoff at Drumcree, which
has been a flash point of violence for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Backing the calls to leave the scene, the clerics said, ``We
place on record our utter revulsion at the murder of the three
little boys in Ballymoney and extend our sincere sympathy to the
parents and to all the bereaved family.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement, from the Representative Group of Orange Order
Chaplains, continued: ``We also express to the Roman Catholic
community in Northern Ireland our deep sorrow that so many of them
have been intimidated out of their homes and that several of their
churches have been burned. Our bitter shame at all this, allegedly
carried out in the name of Protestantism, is not in any way
lessened by the fact that many of our own people are the victims of
terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's service at the Church of Our Lady ended with a moving
antiphon. From the altar Forde said, ``Now in peace let us take our
little boys to their final rest in Rasharkin,'' and as the coffins
filed back down the center aisle, a soprano in the choir loft sang,
``Suffer Little Children to Come Unto Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The coffins were lifted into a single hearse and taken seven
miles to a street corner 100 yards down the hill from the cemetery,
and the pallbearers took up their doleful duty for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   With a final prayer, the white coffins were lowered into a
single large fresh grave, and hundreds of bouquets were placed on
top. Three floral tributes spelled out the boys' nicknames, Tavish,
Marky and Ace.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said Miss Quinn had asked that the boys be buried
here so that she would never have to return to Ballymoney.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Carnany Estate, where the Quinns lived in
Ballymoney, Samuel Montgomery, 8, pedaled his bicycle up to a
visitor at the soot-blackened facade of the grey stucco home where
the boys died. They had been his friends, he said, and the bike
still leaning against the fence belonged to ``the wee one.''
</P>
<P>
   He peered through the boarded-up window and asked if they were
still inside. Told no, he paused. Then he brightened. ``They're
going to heaven today, right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
