<HEADLINE>
FANS TO BE SITTING PRETTY AT ROSE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ They remodeled his scoreboard and they built
his new video board. Now, Granddaddy has a new face.
</P>
<P>
   Individual, flip-up seats have replaced bleachers from goal line
to goal line at the 75-year-old Rose Bowl, the latest phase of the
venerable stadium's $22.5 million renovation. The end zones remain
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The year-long project _ scheduled for completion before UCLA's
home opener on Sept. 12 _ has reduced capacity from 100,089 to
approximately 93,500 and forced the Bruins to revamp their seating
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great old stadium, but it's never been very
comfortable,'' Pacific-10 Conference assistant commissioner Jim
Muldoon said.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation project began in 1993, when the Rose Bowl
Operating Committee formed a wish list of 33 changes to carry the
stadium into the next millennium. A video board, advertising
panels, seats, dressing rooms and remodeled scoreboard topped the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping the changes would attract a Super Bowl and perhaps an NFL
team, the Pasadena City Council approved the remodeling and issued
a municipal bond. The seating phase alone cost $6 million,
according to Rose Bowl general manager Dave Jacobs. Several rows
for handicapped seating have also been added.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for reduced capacity, tickets to the Jan. 1 Rose
Bowl game have increased to $110 from $75. But the greatest impact
is on UCLA's 30,000 season-ticket holders, who this week will
receive a letter detailing the process and explaining why their
seats have been moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people have been moved up or down two, three or
four rows,'' associate athletic director Rick Purdy said. ``We
thought two things were important: to move people up or down
instead of left or right, and also to move everyone. We thought it
was more fair to move everyone a little than move some people
significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA initially notified season-ticket holders in February. But
when the new seats arrived this spring, they were too small. A new,
wider batch was ordered, further reducing capacity and forcing UCLA
to revise its seating plan a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Purdy is bracing for complaints once tickets are mailed next
month _ ``I'm sure it'll be frustrating for some people'' _ but he
hopes the arm rests, improved back support, expanded leg room and
flip-up bottoms make the changes worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best news for everybody (is the flip-up bottoms),'' he
said. ``Now you don't have to go through contortions to let
somebody by.''
</P>
<P>
   With the City Council's blessing, the Rose Bowl Operating
Committee sent photos and information packets to the NFL office and
team owners. Although the Super Bowl is booked through 2003 _
Miami, Atlanta, Tampa, San Diego/New Orleans, and San Francisco are
the upcoming hosts _ the changes match league preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, we like stadiums with seats as opposed to
bleachers. That's more attractive,'' said Greg Aiello, NFL vice
president for public relations. ``Traditionally, we like to play
Super Bowls in league cities, but that's not etched in concrete. We
won't rule it out, but there isn't a Super Bowl available for a few
years down the road. Hopefully, by then there will be an NFL team
in L.A.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
