<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/14/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- July 14, 1998 --
GLF-WOMEN-GOLFERS, 7-14 -- Nancy Lopez, left, and Se Ri Pak, golf's
newest star, at Wykagyl in New Rochelle, on Tuesday during
practice. Golf fans who missed them Tuesday will get another chance
later this week, under more competitive circumstances. Lopez and
Pak will be paired together, along with Hiromi Kobayashi, in the
first two rounds of the JAL Big Apple Classic tournament Thursday
and Friday. (Bernie Nunez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 14, 1998 -- COMPUTING-TECHNOLOGY,
7-14 -- William Joy, a co-founder of Sun Microsystems, is the chief
designer of Jini, which would endow common appliances with borrowed
intelligence available from powerful computer networks. ``The trend
is very clear,'' says Joy. ``We are moving toward a world in which
it will be possible to move software codes that act as our personal
agents between many different computers in a global network.''
(Thor Swift/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 14, 1998 -- BUSH-POLITICS, 7-14 --
Though Gov. George W. Bush of Texas says he thinks he has ``a
pretty clear view of where a better tomorrow is for everybody,'' he
also insists that he has not made up his mind on whether to run for
president. But throughout an interview on Monday, Bush, 51, offered
signals of encouragement for those who want him to run. (Ted
Albracht/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- AVIATION-EDUC, 7-14 -- At a
Kennedy hangar, Oscar Mendez, right, and Immanuel Thangavelu help
maintain a 747 through an Aviation High intern program. For three
years, Tower Air and the high school have worked together. About 40
seniors are interns there during a fifth year at the school,
spending 20 hours a week at Kennedy instead of in shop classes.
Tower Air has hired all its student interns after graduation either
full time or part time. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- NY-BRAWLEY-REACT-2, 7-14 --
The manager of the McCafe restaurant, Clara Walker, says she has
known the Rev. Al Sharpton since he was a teen-ager. ``He tried to
help but he might have jumped the gun without getting all the
facts,'' she says of the recent verdict, which found Sharpton and
two others liable for defamation in connection with the Tawana
Brawley trial. ``I know he wouldn't put something together just to
have something going. He wouldn't do that.'' (Chester Higgins
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- NY-BRAWLEY-REACT-1, 7-14 --
At the McCafe restaurant, the Rev. F.D. Waddell predicts that all
the attention from the Tawana Brawley trial will only help the Rev.
Al Sharpton by providing him with more exposure. ``This will
enhance his political situation,'' says Waddell of the verdict,
which found Sharpton and two others liable for defamation in
connection with the 10-year-old Brawley saga. ``What he does, and
what I like about him, is he doesn't allow something to be swept
under the rug or forgotten.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TALLULAH, La. -- July 14, 1998 -- JUVENILE-PRISON-2,
7-14 -- Warden David Bonnette looks over books with some inmates at
the Tallulah Correctional Center for Youth. Placed on a wall in the
bathroom, the books are for leisure reading. This juvenile prison
is so rife with brutality, cronyism and neglect that many legal
experts say it is the worst in the nation. The prison, which opened
just four years ago, houses 620 boys and young men, age 11 to 20,
in stifling corrugated-iron barracks jammed with bunks. (Greg
Campbell/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) TALLULAH, La. -- July 14, 1998 -- JUVENILE-PRISON-1,
7-14 -- Hands clasped behind their backs, inmates are counted
before marching off to their barracks at the Tallulah Correctional
Center for Youth. This juvenile prison in the middle of the
impoverished Mississippi Delta is so rife with brutality and
neglect that many legal experts say it is the worst in the nation.
The prison, which opened just four years ago, houses 620 boys and
young men, age 11 to 20, in stifling corrugated-iron barracks
jammed with bunks. (Greg Campbell/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RICHVALE, Calif. -- July 14, 1998 -- BABBIT-WEST, 7-14
-- Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt takes a sledge hammer to
the half-century-old McPherrin Dam during a visit and press
conference here Tuesday. ``That's one small blow for salmon,'' he
says. The destructive display heralds the start of what Babbitt
says will be an era in which many of the nation's 75,000 dams will
be judged by whether they did more harm than good. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BERNARDSVILLE, N.J. -- July 13, 1998 --
ULTRA-MARATHONER, 7-13 -- Lisa Smith, 37, relaxes at home with her
running partner of four years, Beau, a Yellow Labrador Retriever.
Smith is part of a tiny band of super endurance runners who stake
their claims on the frontiers of human physical possibility. For
the third time, she has set her sites on the Death Valley
ultra-marathon called ``Badwater.'' ``It's the hardest race in the
world,'' says Smith, a massage therapist and sports trainer.
(Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- BACH-MARATHON, 7-14 --
Christopher Herrick opens a series of Bach's organ works. The
series is billed as the ``complete'' organ works of Bach, but that
term can only be a relative, because of uncertainties of
attribution, the existence of alternative versions and the like.
``Where distinctly different versions of the same work exist, I
have made a choice,'' Herrick writes in the program book. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WESTCHESTER COUNTY, N.Y. -- July 14, 1998 --
PIGS-EATING-WELL-2, 7-14 -- llamas protect the Shetland sheep at
Cabbage Hill Farm in Westchester County. If there is one thing
Annie Farrell has learned in her efforts to save historic breeds of
farm animals from extinction, it is the need to get people excited
about eating the food these animals produce. She knows that the
only thing that will make the idea economically viable is meat
tasty enough that people will want to buy it. (Susan Farley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WESTCHESTER COUNTY, N.Y. -- July 14, 1998 --
PIGS-EATING-WELL-1, 7-14 -- A rare Gloucestershire Old Spots sow, a
free-range pig, at Cabbage Hill Farm in Westchester County. This is
just one of the highly endangered domesticated breeds Annie Farrell
is trying to save on a farm less than an hour from New York. The
Gloucestershire Old Spots' foraging skills save on feed costs, and
its high fat content gives it added succulence and flavor. (Susan
Farley/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- NY-BARBECUE-2, 7-14 --
Throughout New York, only one restaurant, Pearson's Texas Barbecue,
in Long Island City, Queens, serves up barbecue that keeps pace
with what's available in other parts of the country. Robert Pearson
stokes the wood-burning pit, which produces char-broiled steaks
like the one in the foreground. (Barbara Alper/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- NY-BARBECUE-1, 7-14 -- In
New York, barbecue often means jerk, like this chicken being cooked
in a half oil drum at Seamorhen in Jamaica, Queens. Perhaps jerk
will be New York's great contribution to the nation's appetite for
barbecue. The City Planning Office says New York lags behind key
barbecue centers in the percentage of its population born in the
South. But New York far outdistances these cities in its
Caribbean-born population. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CUTCHOGUE, N.Y. -- July 14, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 7-14 --
Alex and Louisa Hargrave at their Long Island vineyard.
``Twenty-five years is a long time for a career in any sport, and
winemaking is an Olympic sport,'' says Mr. Hargrave. This is his
deceptively casual way of explaining why he and his wife, Louisa,
are ending their remarkable career as Long Island's pioneer
winemakers. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- NY-BOATHOUSE-RESTAURANT,
7-14 -- From the terrace, Park View at the Boathouse in Central
Park lives up to its name. When the band is playing on a warm
summer evening it is easy to fall under the spell this new
restaurant at the Loeb Boathouse. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 14, 1998 -- RYE-BREAD-BAKERY, 7-14 --
``For me, bread is rye bread,'' says Abram Orwasher, at his oven on
the Upper East Side. Look out, focaccia: rye is back. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BALLYMONEY, Northern Ireland -- July 14, 1998 --
NIRELAND-FUNERAL-2, 7-14 -- An emotional John Dillon, estranged
husband of Christine Quinn and father of the three murdered boys Q
Richard, Mark and Jason Quinn Q helps carry one of their coffins en
route to a rural Roman Catholic church Tuesday. The people of
Northern Ireland said a tear-filled farewell to three young
brothers burned to death in a sectarian attack that came as they
slept. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BALLYMONEY, Northern Ireland -- July 14, 1998 --
NIRELAND-FUNERAL-1, 7-14 -- As a bell tolls mournfully, the small
coffins of Richard, Mark and Jason Quinn Q three boys born to a
Catholic mother who were being raised as Protestants Q are carried
into a rural Roman Catholic church Tuesday by friends and family,
their faces contorted with grief. The people of Northern Ireland
said a tear-filled farewell to three young brothers burned to death
in a sectarian attack that came as they slept. (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- July 14, 1998 -- FASHION-TILBERIS-BOS, 7-14 --
Liz Tilberis, the editor-in-chief of Harper's Bazaar, takes time
out from a recent interview. Ms. Tilberis's recently released
autobiography ``No Time to Die'' tells of her tragic bout with
ovarian cancer. ``I live with a chronic disease,'' she says. ``If I
hadn't come to the States, I'd be dead by now because American
health care is more aggressive in diagnosing cancer than
England's.'' (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DARTMOUTH, Mass. -- July 14, 1998 --
LABYRINTH-MYSTIQUE-BOS, 7-14 -- Students walk a labyrinth during a
workshop conducted at the University of Massachusetts's Dartmouth
campus. Unlike mazes, which are deliberately confusing and very
easy to get lost in, a labyrinth has no dead ends or tricky turns.
There is only one path, and it always leads to the center and back
out again but by a twisting route. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BRADENTON, Fla. -- July 14, 1998 -- FLA-TENNIS-ACADEMY-2,
7-14 -- Maria Sharipova, 11, stretches out for a forehand during a
recent practice at Bollettieri Sports Academy. Maria's father, Uri,
worked the mines in Siberia to pay for his daughter's passage to
the United States four years ago. Now he is under strict orders
from the Academy not to interfere with his daughter's training.
(Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BRADENTON, Fla. -- July 14, 1998 -- FLA-TENNIS-ACADEMY-1,
7-14 -- Russian-born Yelena Bovina, 15, practices her serve at
Bollettieri Sports Academy. ``This is the one way for my daughter
to become the best, to realize all of her potential,'' says
Marguerite Bovina, who left her husband and another daughter behind
in Moscow to chaperon Yelena's quest. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
