<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-N     07-14 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE TRY TO LINK MISSING WOMAN TO SUSPECTS' CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Still no closer to finding Irene Silverman, the
wealthy widow who vanished under suspicious circumstances 10 days
ago, city detectives Tuesday focused on clues that might place her
in the car of the two suspects in her disappearance, examining
minute samples of hair and saliva recovered from the back seat to
determine whether they match hers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Silverman, 82, vanished on July 5, and detectives have been
investigating a former tenant, Kenneth Kimes, 23, and his mother,
Sante Kimes, 63, who rented a $6,000-a-month suite in her East 65th
Street town house. The Kimeses were arrested the same day on an
unrelated charge of passing a bad check in Utah in April, and were
carrying Mrs. Silverman's passport and other identification when
federal agents took them into custody, authorities have said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives are also reviewing eight microcassette tapes of
telephone conversations made by the Kimeses at Mrs. Silverman's
home earlier this month, said an investigator who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. In one of the conversations, a woman
claiming to be the manager of a Las Vegas casino told Mrs.
Silverman that she had won a free vacation. The caller, who
investigators believe was Mrs. Kimes, then tried unsuccessfully to
get Mrs. Silverman to give out her Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes were found in the back seat of the Kimeses' car, along
with a 9-millimeter automatic pistol, 10 wigs, business documents
and a box of ammunition for a .22-caliber pistol. Detectives said
the Kimeses had apparently emptied their trunk sometime before they
were captured, moving even the spare tire and jack into the back
seat with the duffel bag and other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a search warrant prepared by the Manhattan district
attorney's office, investigators seized physical evidence from the
Kimeses' car, including blood from a small stain on the seat belt,
hair found inside a large black duffel bag and a pillow with a
saliva stain.
</P>
<P>
   The bloodstain is of no value as evidence against the Kimeses,
said a second detective who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
because a test by the Medical Examiner's office determined that the
blood came from a man. Another spot of blood found outside Mrs.
Silverman's home is also being tested, but investigators said it
may be too small and tainted by exposure to the elements to yield
any conclusive results.
</P>
<P>
   But police last week removed a hairbrush and a toothbrush from
Mrs. Silverman's home and are waiting for results from the crime
lab to learn whether hair and saliva from her home matched the
evidence taken from the Kimeses' car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have a body yet, but if there is evidence to put
Mrs. Silverman in that car, at least we have a starting point to a
criminal case,'' said the first investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Las Vegas, California, and the Bahamas also want to
question the Kimeses about questionable business deals, the murder
of their former business partner in Los Angeles, and the
disappearance of an auditor examining their bank accounts in the
Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police say the Kimeses are suspects in the murder of
the businessman, David Kazdin. Los Angeles detectives returned to
California on Monday with palm prints from both suspects and are
awaiting results of tests to determine whether they match a partial
print found on the garbage bin where Kazdin's body was discovered
March 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses, who are being held on Rikers Island, have refused
to be interviewed by police, but their lawyers deny that the
Kimeses were involved in Mrs. Silverman's disappearance, and on
Monday suggested that members of her housekeeping staff might have
harmed her because of her abrasive manner.
</P>
<P>
   A former employee of the Kimeses who later became an FBI
informer told detectives that Mrs. Kimes asked him to fly to New
York because she wanted him to manage a new mansion she had
obtained from an unnamed former ballerina, the first investigator
said. Mrs. Silverman once danced with the corps de ballet at Radio
City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Police also recovered two medical syringes and a vial of a
sedative from the back seat. Investigators said it was unlikely
that they were used recently because the syringes were still in
their sealed wrappers and the medicine was so old that it contained
mold and had probably lost its potency.
</P>
</TEXT>
