<SLUG> BC-NY-SEX-ZONING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ACTION MOVES NYC SEX ZONING LAW CLOSER TO IMPLEMENTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's sex shops and their customers have lost
yet another round in their court fight to block tough zoning laws
intended to restrict the adult-entertainment industry, and their
legal remedies have essentially been reduced to one: an appeal to
the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything goes right in getting the Supreme Court to look
at the case, then the city won't be able to enforce the law at
least until next year,'' said Beth Haroules, a lawyer for the New
York Civil Liberties Union. ``It's also possible that it's the end
of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Their plight elicited little sympathy from City Hall. When city
officials learned Tuesday that a federal appeals court had decided
to end its involvement in the case, they immediately began dusting
off their plans to begin enforcing the new laws, as early as
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready,'' said Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the recent decision by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals provided only punctuation to a previous ruling by the
court. Last month a three-judge panel for the court upheld the
zoning law, which would ban strip clubs and X-rated book and video
shops from operating within 500 feet of residential areas, schools,
day care centers, houses of worship or one another. It also
declined to examine the free speech implications of the law, saying
that New York's highest court had already done so.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the owners and customers of the sex shops quickly
asked for a special hearing before the full court, even though such
requests are rarely granted. Last Thursday, the court denied the
request filed on behalf of customers by the New York Civil
Liberties Union. Then on Monday, the court denied a similar plea
from the sex shop's owners.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haroules said that the federal appeals court's decision was
disheartening, yet also expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've already looked at the zoning ordinance a couple of
times,'' she said. ``So it's not unexpected. But it is another
procedural step that has to be taken before you can go to the
Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the ruling allowed Giuliani to continue his public
count of judges _ now up to 23 _ who have upheld the city's right
to enforce the zoning laws. He added that city inspectors ``are
ready to begin enforcement on this important `quality of life'
initiative as soon as the last legal impediments are removed from
the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent budget fight that has occupied city government,
the court ruling also provided a rare moment in which the City
Council and the mayor's office find themselves in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is a great boost for the neighborhoods throughout
our city that have suffered from the harmful proliferation of adult
entertainment uses,'' said Councilman Walter McCaffrey, a Democrat
from Queens who played an early role in drafting legislation that
targeted sex shops.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the industry said they had not abandoned hope
that the Supreme Court would recognize the city's zoning law as
overly aggressive and an infringement on the rights of those who
prefer to have X-rated stores in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Price Fahringer, a lawyer representing 107 adult-entertainment
businesses, did not respond to several messages left at his office
Tuesday. But those close to the case say that Fahringer may ask the
Court of Appeals to continue preventing the city from enforcing the
law while he pursues an appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lawyers for the sex-shop industry may also ask Ruth
Bader Ginsburg, the Supreme Court justice responsible for the New
York region, for a similar stay as part of their appeal to the
country's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would affect 146 of the city's 164
adult-entertainment businesses. City officials say that they hope
rigorous enforcement will persuade most owners to go out of
business. But some business owners vow to adapt: one strip club
owner has said his dancers will wear bikinis, while an adult-video
store owner has begun to diversify his stock with old comedies and
children's movies. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
