<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-BROOM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA DROPS BROOM BECAUSE OF GRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Dion Broom's basketball scholarship at Arizona will
not be renewed for 1998-99 by Coach Lute Olson, leaving the former
Mesa Westwood High star in limbo for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Broom, a power forward, lost his scholarship because he did not
meet team academic requirements, a UA spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Olson could not be reached for comment. Broom hung up the
telephone when contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Olson already has begun stocking up for 1999. On
Tuesday, UA received an oral commitment from point guard Jason
Gardner, one of the most sought-after high school players in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner (5 feet 11, 170 pounds), who will be a senior at
Indianapolis North Central High School, was a teammate of UA
freshman Michael Wright on the USA's gold-medal winner in the
Junior World Championships last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family and I decided it would be best to commit now so I
can concentrate on school and basketball,'' Gardner said. ``I just
did not want to be bothered by all the recruiting stuff over the
next couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's basketball instincts and the manner in which he runs a
team have been compared with former UA All-America point guard Mike
Bibby, who led the Wildcats to their first NCAA title as a freshman
and was the second player chosen in last month's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to be in the same sentence with Mike Bibby,''
Gardner said. ``It will be a challenge to uphold the level of
excellence he established at UA.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner likely will succeed Jason Terry as the Wildcats point
guard in 1999-2000. Terry will be a senior this season. There are
no other true point guards currently in the program. Oral
commitments are non-binding. High school seniors may sign binding
letters of intent from Nov. 11-17.
</P>
<P>
   The Broom decision helps UA clear up a scholarship logjam
created by the signing of six freshman recruits and the transfer of
7-foot-1 Loren Woods of Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   To get down to the NCAA limit of 13 scholarships, UA also did
not renew the scholarship of guard Josh Pastner, a former walk-on
who has served as the Wildcats' unofficial shooting coach the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Pastner agreed last year to give up his scholarship if Olson
needed it. He is scheduled to graduate in December and will have to
pay tuition only for one semester.
</P>
<P>
   Pastner is expected to remain on the team. He is listed on the
UA preseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   Broom's future is less certain. His name is not on the roster.
He has not been dismissed from the university, and he is eligible
to remain in classes at UA if he pays his own way.
</P>
<P>
   Broom would have to sit out a year if he transfers to another
NCAA four-year institution. He would be eligible to play this year
at a junior college.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest in a series of fateful twists the past two
years for Broom.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the state's bright prospects during his junior
year at Westwood. Then, one week after signing his letter of intent
to UA in November 1996, the 6-foot-8, 265-pound Broom suffered a
torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee. The remainder of
his senior season was lost.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled to catch up in the classroom after undergoing
surgery and finished his high school career with a 2.44 grade-point
average _ just missing the 2.5 he needed to qualify for freshman
athletic eligibility at UA.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Broom attended Chandler-Gilbert Community College last
fall, where he earned the necessary grades and made a qualifying
score on the Scholastic Aptitude Test to become eligible at UA for
the second semester.
</P>
<P>
   He transferred to the Tucson campus in December, but Olson was
not satisfied with Broom's overall conditioning nor the
rehabilitation on Broom's repaired knee. He practiced with the
Wildcats but did not appear in games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
