u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-MISCONDUCT-     07-14 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-MISCONDUCT-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE UNION AGREES TO DROP 48-HOUR RULE ON INFRACTIONS BY
OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The union that represents police sergeants in New
York City reached a tentative agreement with the Giuliani
administration Tuesday on a contract that eliminates the right of
police officers to wait two full business days before having to
answer questions about possible misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeants Benevolent Association president Joe Toal said the
union's board voted Tuesday to send the contract to its delegates,
who in turn will decide whether to send it to the 4,500 members for
ratification. ``We're going to recommend that the contract be
ratified by our membership,'' Toal said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials hope to eliminate what is known as the 48-hour
rule in subsequent contracts with other police unions, including
the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, which represents the bulk
of the 40,000-member force.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has said that the rule, which has been a
part of police contracts since 1971, hampers its ability to
investigate infractions that would not be the subject of criminal
investigations, which could range from procedural errors to
brutality. And critics outside the department have said that the
rule contributes to a perception that police officers accused of
crimes are treated differently than civilians, largely because of
the clout their powerful police unions wield.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rule is rarely relevant in cases where police
officers face both criminal proceedings, which can result in jail
terms, and departmental proceedings, which can result in
suspensions or dismissals. In such cases, prosecutors usually ask
departmental investigators to delay questioning officers in order
to avoid compromising their testimony in a possible criminal trial,
and officers retain the same right as civilians not to incriminate
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Reppetto, the president of the Citizens Crime
Commission of New York City, a private watchdog group and a member
of the Mayor's Task Force on Police-Community Relations, which has
voted to abolish the rule, said it was important to eliminate the
rule because it gives an impression that ``somehow police officers
can have more rights than anyone else in a criminal
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, said
Tuesday night, ``The mayor has long held the belief that the rule
should not be in existence.'' The Police Department said it would
not comment on the rule or the tentative accord until the sergeants
had voted on the contract.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The PBA has staunchly resisted the city's efforts to eliminate
the rule. Tuesday, PBA spokesman Joe Mancini reiterated his union's
opposition. ``Eliminating the 48-hour rule would just be denying
cops who are the subject of internal investigations _ for violating
things in the patrol guide, for instance _ of their rights,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sergeants Benevolent Association did not let the rule go
willingly. When the city announced six or seven months ago that it
did not consider the rule a mandatory subject for collective
bargaining, and thus was not going to negotiate on it, the
association filed an complaint with the city's Board of Collective
Bargaining, said James Hanley, the commissioner of the city's
Office of Labor Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Toal said the association had argued that the rule should be a
subject for negotiation because it had been in its contracts for
more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 30, the board sided with the city, saying the rule
concerned a disciplinary issue and thus was not a mandatory subject
of negotiation. The ruling also covers the Lieutenants Benevolent
Association, which is now negotiating a contract with the city.
Hanley said the collective bargaining board is also considering
whether the rule should be considered a mandatory subject in
current negotiations with the detectives' and captains' unions.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley said he believed that the board would act similarly when
the patrolmen's contract expires in the year 2000. ``The PBA will
continue to enjoy this provision in their contracts,'' Hanley said,
``but when the contract expires, I'm sure we'll be focusing on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mancini predicted that the board's decision involving the
sergeants' and lieutenants' contracts would be challenged in court,
rendering it moot by the time his members negotiate their next
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But Toal said he did not think the sergeants' union would mount
a legal challenge to the board's decision. ``There's no place to
challenge it,'' he said. ``Take something like that to court and
you're never successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
