r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-SHOCK-LIEBERMAN-A     07-14 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SHOCK-LIEBERMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEIBERMAN-CLINE HAPPY ON THE BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was just for one season, and a short one at that.
More of a fling than a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The feelings can hardly be the same as those sure to come should
Kevin Johnson show up post-lockout at America West Arena in, say, a
Lakers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something poignant about the return of Nancy
Lieberman-Cline to the court where her Hall of Fame playing career
ended 10{ months ago _ with one minute and no points in a 59-41
WNBA semifinal playoff loss to the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew for sure that was the end for the oldest player in
the first-year league, but reality eventually bites everyone. She
would not have returned to the Mercury as a 40-year-old player,
Cheryl Miller said. But Lieberman-Cline clung to the playing dream
right up to her decision in January to become coach-general manager
of the expansion Detroit Shock.
</P>
<P>
   Like Miller, the Mercury coach-GM and fellow Naismith Memorial
Basketball Hall of Famer, Lieberman-Cline is happy on the sideline,
which is where she'll be tonight at 7 for the rematch against the
Mercury. The teams played in Detroit a week ago, with Phoenix
winning on a buzzer beater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how I'd feel until I got out there, but I don't
miss playing,'' said Lieberman-Cline, whose job includes
front-office business duties that the Mercury delegates to its vice
president/operations Seth Sulka. ``I had to do one thing well and
use 100 percent of my time and energy to build this organization.
It's an awesome task.''
</P>
<P>
   One that, judging by the standings, she is doing well. At the
halfway point of the season, the Shock is just one game out of the
fourth and final playoff berth and 4{ games ahead of its expansion
counterpart Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit rebounds better than any team in the league and uses the
boards to trigger the kind of running game Lieberman-Cline
cherished as a player. The kind she thought she could still play
last season had she been given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was obviously a little disappointed with how Cheryl dealt
with me as an athlete and a person,'' said Lieberman-Cline, who
averaged 11.2 minutes in 25 regular-season games. ``It surprised
me, her lack of sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the lines of communication would have been better.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller essentially had no choice but to select Lieberman-Cline
with the next-to-last pick of the elite draft in February 1997. The
other candidate was plodding 6-foot-8 center Haixia Zheng, who
would have had no chance in the Mercury's transition offense.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity between what Lieberman-Cline thought she could
contribute and Miller's opinion grew with the achiness in the
backup's right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there as a player,'' said Miller, forced into early
retirement in 1987 because of bad knees. ``What you're physically
able to do is always invariably different than what your mind says
you can do. If you can accept that and can accept the role, it
makes things easier. But that's a hard place to get to in a short
amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said dealing with Lieberman-Cline became a distraction:
``It was hard on Nancy, it was hard on the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline insists she tried not to let her frustration
become a team cancer. ``There is no tougher role than being on the
bench,'' she said. ``It requires a multitude of personalities. If I
wasn't going to play more minutes, my job was to make Michele
Timms, Bridget Pettis and Umeki Webb better (in practice).''
</P>
<P>
   There was at least one shining moment. In her first game back
after spending three on the injured list, she helped rescue the
team from a tailspin that threatened the playoff berth. Her five
spectacular minutes in relief of a struggling Timms turned a
stretch game against Cleveland. ``Nancy was all-world,'' Timms
said. ``We owe her a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to June 17, 1998, and the hauntingly familiar
comments by this season's oldest player in the WNBA: ``I feel I can
help this team if I get the opportunity. I have a lot of pride as a
player. I can play any position in the game, and that includes the
bench. If they want me to play the bench, that's a position, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynette Woodard, an eventual Hall of Famer who turns 39 on Aug.
12, was speaking to the ``Detroit News'' about her lack of
early-season playing time with the Shock, which started 0-4.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline, who selected Woodard from Cleveland in the
expansion draft, sees appreciable differences between her
relationship with Woodard and hers with Miller. Or maybe it's just
being on the other side of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have honor and respect for her contribution to the game,''
said Lieberman-Cline. ``When you honor and trust and respect
someone, you can deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline said she was brutally honest with Woodard, who
started all but one game for the Rockers in 1997. To survive
training camp, Woodard had to improve on a laundry list of items,
the new coach said. And if she did, would being last on an 11-woman
roster prove acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave her the worst possible scenario, hoping she would make
it better,'' Lieberman-Cline said. ``She said, `Tell me what I need
to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard then did what was asked well enough to be promoted to
starting small forward four games ago. ``I'm so proud of her
because she's handled it the right way,'' Lieberman-Cline said.
``Last year gave me a better understanding. If I hadn't had that,
who knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline became a great player and competent broadcaster
by learning from others and knows enough to do the same as a rookie
coach. ``If I have all the answers, we're in trouble,'' she said,
laughing about a critical moment at New York nine days ago. ``I had
never diagrammed a last-second play in the huddle. Ever. Not even
on an Etch-a-Sketch.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to help from a veteran staff that includes her first
pro coach, Greg Williams, and former NBA assistant Sonny Allen,
Lieberman-Cline took a Coaching 101 crash course from her 1976
Olympic coach, Billie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 hours over three days, Moore answered all the questions
that Lieberman-Cline could muster. ``I told her, `Treat me like a
moron and tell me what you know about the game.' Afterwards I said,
`Billie, why didn't you teach me this when you were a coach?' I
thought I knew so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline knows for certain what she wants to accomplish
tonight, beyond beating the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to say thanks to a city that quickly embraced her and
made the last of her more than 20 years as a player meaningful
beyond its historical intersection with the renewal of U.S. pro
women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to come out there and I want to wave to our fans and I
want to shake the hand of the Colangelos,'' she said. ``It's a very
special place for me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
