<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAMP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' CONSTANT: CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Cowboys trek into a city portrayed as
a sleepy outpost today bearing the black-hat reputation of their
recent past.
</P>
<P>
   But when practices begin tomorrow, citizens of Wichita Falls
will wake up to a team that bears few resemblances _ on and off the
field _ to the one of dopin', gun-totin' and dorm-trashin' repute
that won six NFC East and three Super Bowl titles since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Camp Change.
</P>
<P>
   While the biggest stars, like quarterback Troy Aikman, running
back Emmitt Smith, receiver Michael Irvin and cornerback Deion
Sanders remain, the prevailing theme for the Cowboys as training
camp opens at Midwestern State University is change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of this franchise is about change,'' Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones said. ``But we have undergone more change this year
than any year since I've been here. Change is good. I believe it
can be positive and make for more excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Cowboys' shift of their training camp from
the enticements of Austin to laid-back Wichita Falls, the Cowboys'
off-season was highlighted by major alterations in image, personnel
and offensive philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   There were no controversial off-field incidents. Team gatherings
for Bible study, rather than at strip bars, garnered headlines in
national publications. The team hired a new coach, Chan Gailey, and
signed former Pro Bowl running back Chris Warren.
</P>
<P>
   A new offense that includes the shotgun formation has been
installed. And several longtime and popular veterans like Herschel
Walker, Bill Bates and Tony Tolbert aren't on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys vice president Stephen Jones said the training-camp move
was inevitable because the team had outgrown its location at St.
Edward's University in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that most of the organizational moves with
players and coaches were born out of the frustration from a 6-10
1997 season, when the Cowboys missed the playoffs for the first
time since 1990 and ended the season on a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Other lowlights from last season include:
</P>
<P>
   Futility inside the opponent's 20-yard line by an offense that
scored only 19 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   A once-dominant offensive line allowing 39 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Not one Cowboys defender recording more than six sacks, the
fewest by a team leader since Bob Lilly led the 1963 Cowboys with
five.
</P>
<P>
   A defense that had only seven interceptions, the fewest this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   A defense that allowed 1,994 yards rushing, the most since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Jones said the players have taken to the changes because
they were frustrated at the dismal ending of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change will be positive,'' he said. ``I don't factor the
training camp move into it. But as far as Chan is concerned, him
coming in will be fresh for everybody. It's a wakeup call that
there needed to be change. No matter who was here, there needed to
be change for us to get back where we were over the past few years.
Change is tough, but it definitely can be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Change in the 1998 Cowboys will also feature six new offensive
and defensive starters. Free safety Brock Marion was lost to free
agency. Tackle Mark Tuinei, wide receiver Anthony Miller and
defensive end Tolbert were released. David LaFleur replaces Eric
Bjornson at tight end. And defensive end Shante Carver was not
re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, the former Pittsburgh Steelers offensive coordinator,
rejects any comparisons to his predecessor, Barry Switzer, or talk
of what went wrong last season. However, his presence and his
get-tough style represents much of the concrete change that Jerry
Jones was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't compare last year's team,'' Gailey said. ``I'm trying
to do what we think is right for this team, this year. I would hope
that everything we do is toward getting this team back to the NFL's
elite.''
</P>
<P>
   Several position battles will be Gailey's focal point over the
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Stoutmire and George Teague are battling to fill Marion's
free safety spot. Macey Brooks, Ernie Mills, Jimmy Oliver and
Stepfret Williams will battle Billy Davis for the second receiver
position.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Fred Strickland's starting job is up for
grabs, with the team giving strongside linebacker Randall Godfrey a
shot in the middle. That means that veteran linebacker Broderick
Thomas and rookie Darren Hambrick have a chance to win Godfrey's
spot on the strong side.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are also looking for a kick returner to replace
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones acknowledges that the modifications in the Cowboys
from last season have resulted in more questions about the team
going into 1998 than in recent years. And, while he understands
that line of thinking, because ``we are not as talented as we used
to be,'' Jones said his goals going into training camp are no
different than they have been the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not viewed as the most talented team in football
anymore,'' Jones said. ``And rightly so; we have a lot of
questions. But we have questions with talent, which gives us a good
shot of going \Rto the Super Bowl\S if we can get those questions
answered. It would be fun to go to the Super Bowl without everybody
expecting you to go. That will be fun to watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
