r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-RATTLERS-OLIVER-A     07-14 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-RATTLERS-OLIVER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY KNEE GIVES HOPE TO RATTLERS DEFEN SIVE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Muhammad Oliver doesn't claim to be a basketball
player. Never has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played organized ball before,'' he said. ``I just love
to jump and dunk. Don't ask me to dribble and shoot from outside.
Just feed me alley-oops.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the day he dunked a basketball, however, that he knew he
was ready to return to professional football, something that seemed
far-fetched two years ago after undergoing reconstructive surgery
on his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back on the court, dunking the ball any way I want, doing
the things I did before at the same level,'' said Oliver, a former
North High star.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent two weeks ago, in his first game with the
Rattlers. First he came up to stuff the run from his defensive back
position, then, a play later, he intercepted a pass and returned it
for a touchdown in Arizona's most lopsided win of the season, 69-27
over the Grand Rapids Rampage.
</P>
<P>
   It was Oliver's first pro football game since 1996, when he tore
up his knee in a scrimmage with the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   He said doctors cleared him to return to play in '97, but he
didn't trust his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I use to judge my progress is everyday activities, like
playing basketball,'' he said. ``I wasn't able to dunk a basketball
that well, so I knew I wasn't at 100 percent. I talked to my wife
and I decided to sit out the entire year.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Oliver, 29, who graduated from North in '87, is making a
push to get back on an NFL field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being advised by his agent to avoid playing Arena
football, Oliver figured this was the ultimate place, where he has
to make quick cuts and stops on the 50-yard field, to test his
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers had approached Oliver before, only to get ``no''
for an answer. But after watching a couple of games and enjoying
what he saw, Oliver approached the Rattlers about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent really doesn't belive it's a steppingstone back to
the NFL and there is a risk factor, but I need to know where I
stand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, 5-foot-11, 185 pounds, has been working in a finance
business and shooting commercials in Phoenix. He got tired of
waiting for an NFL team to call. With the Rattlers, at least, he
can stay home, play before friends and family and hope to catch the
attention of some neighbors _ the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream, in all honesty,'' he says, ``is to play for the
Cardinals. I see a need for a corner like myself to play for them.
They've got Anaeas (Williams). I could add depth at that other
corner position. I would love to play for them.''
</P>
<P>
   With defensive specialist Cedric Walker gone for the season
after reconstructive knee surgery, the Rattlers are happy to help
him pursue his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought him in as a two-way player when Randy (Gatewood)
got hurt,'' Coach Danny White said. ``It appears now he has much
more impact as a defensive specialist. He's a good enough athlete
to play receiver also. ''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver still toys with the idea of returning to track and field,
where he once was a top decathlete.
</P>
<P>
   He says he plans to resume training next year for the decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not I compete at the world-class level, I'm not
pushing for that,'' he said. ``It's something else I miss doing. I
enjoy the training and stuff. I know that's weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (2000) Olympics still crosses my mind. It's a goal to
compete there.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver qualified for the 1996 Olympic Trials but was unable to
perform because of his knee, which has been scoped twice since the
days he was teaming with Phillippi Sparks in the secondary for a
national championship team at Glendale Community College.
</P>
<P>
   From Glendale, he continued his college career at Oregon, then
spent parts of four seasons in the NFL with the Denver Broncos,
Miami Dolphins and Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   He coached track at North High last spring while rehabilitating
his knee. His inspiration, he says, comes from his golf partner,
NFL defensive back Anthony Parker, a former Tempe McClintock and
Arizona State star.
</P>
<P>
   Parker made it big in the NFL only after recovering from
reconstructive knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just seeing him achieve things is motivation itself,'' Oliver
said. ``I know what he's gone through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident I can achieve that level. I pray I will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
