<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5069 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-ARBITRATI     07-14 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ARBITRATION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 COYOTES TURN TO ARBITRATOR  
 CANUCKS SIGN BARON TO 3-YEAR CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Coyotes forwards Dallas Drake and Bob Corkum, two of
eight unsigned restricted Group II free agents on the team, will
file for arbitration today in an effort to bolster their salaries
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Murray Baron, meanwhile, agreed to a three-year
contract Tuesday as an unrestricted free agent with the Vancouver
Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms were not disclosed, but Baron, who spent the
past 1{ seasons in Phoenix, is believed to have signed a deal worth
more than $2 million a year, including a signing bonus of at least
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith tendered qualifying offers
for the minimum 10-percent increase to both Drake and Corkum, but
neither player is prepared to accept his one-year offer for
$650,000 and $550,000, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, a physical right wing who plays predominately on the
team's top two lines, is seeking a two-year deal worth about $1.3
million per year. Corkum, the team's third-line center, best
faceoff man and a top penalty killer, wants at least $1 million for
one season.
</P>
<P>
   By going to arbitration, which most players and teams usually
hope to avoid, Drake and Corkum can present their case for higher
salaries, the Coyotes can argue it, and an independent judge will
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the verdict, it also guarantees that both players
will be back in Phoenix uniforms for the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitration hearings begin Aug. 1 and can last through Aug. 15.
Eligible players must file no later than today.
</P>
<P>
   Teams can continue negotiating through the arbitration process,
and in most cases, deals are usually struck before the arbitrator
makes a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that likely will happen with Drake, 29, and Corkum,
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to try and get a deal done, yes,'' Smith said
Tuesday from San Diego, where he is vacationing with his family.
``A lot of times, these deals get done that way. A lot of times,
they get done at the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake notified the league and Smith on Monday of his plans to
file for arbitration, according to his agent, Tom Laidlaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll continue to talk and, hopefully, get something
resolved,'' Laidlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum, meanwhile, is scheduled to become an unrestricted free
agent after next season and will settle for a one-year deal,
although he'd prefer a multiyear pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along I like it in Phoenix, and if they're
willing to give me a long-term deal to buy me out of the free
agency I get next year, I'd be more than happy to do that,'' Corkum
said Tuesday from his home near Boston. ``But I don't know if they
have the budget in place to give me the three- or four-year deal I
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly their choice, so most definitely, I'm
prepared to go to arbitration. I think (Smith) pretty much expected
this is what would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbitration hearings, by nature, can become bitter and extremely
personal. Nevertheless, Corkum said he's ready to enter the fray if
that's what it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business, and I wouldn't take anything personal,'' he
said. ``But I'm worth more than the $500,000 I was playing for for
the last two years. I'm not looking to break the bank. I just want
what's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Keith Carney, acquired last season from Chicago in
the Chad Kilger trade, is also eligible for arbitration. Neither he
nor his agent, Brian Lawton, could be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other restricted free agents who remain unsigned but have been
tendered qualifying offers by the Coyotes, include forwards Shane
Doan and Louie DeBrusk, defensemen Deron Quint and Sean Gagnon, and
goalie Scott Langkow.
</P>
<P>
   As for Baron, the Canucks signed him in part to replace
free-agent defenseman Jyrki Lumme, who agreed to a five-year, $17
million deal with the Coyotes on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good fit for Murray,'' said Baron's agent, Steve
Mountain, who also represents Corkum. ``(Vancouver Coach Mike)
Keenan will give him plenty of ice time, at least 20 to 22 minutes
a night, and that's what Murray needs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
