<HEADLINE>
CLOSE CALL ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bare majority of the House on Tuesday night
narrowly fended off another effort to amend a bipartisan
campaign-finance bill, keeping the measure intact through another
night of debate.
</P>
<P>
   The 219-201 vote to defeat an amendment by Rep. John Doolittle,
R-Calif., granted a slim victory to the bipartisan coalition
arrayed behind the bill. But the vote was far closer than those on
previous amendments, suggesting that groups like the National Right
to Life Committee and the Christian Coalition could be making
headway in their efforts to defeat the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign-finance measure, sponsored by Reps. Chris Shays,
R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., would effectively ban the
large unregulated contributions to political parties that were at
the heart of the 1996 campaign-finance abuses. The legislation
would also curb independent advertising by interest groups just
before a general or primary election.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has been fiercely opposed by the Republican
leadership, whose party traditionally holds a fund-raising
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Tuesday night's debate focused on the restrictions on
independent advertising in the Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle and his supporters said his amendment would ensure
that voter guides put out by groups like the Christian Coalition
and the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
would not be jeopardized by ambiguities in the wording of the
campaign-finance bill.
</P>
<P>
   Shays and Meehan argued that their bill would protect voter
guides and that the amendment would undercut the restrictions they
were seeking to impose on commercials run by independent groups,
which have proliferated in recent campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
