r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RIPKEN-STREAK-TEX     07-14 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RIPKEN-STREAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPKEN'S STATS OFF, BUT THE STREAK GOES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The All-Star break was a bleak time for the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The team with the highest payroll in baseball was 261/2 games
out of first place. There were rumors and stories of dissension in
the clubhouse and in the front office, and owner Peter Angelos was
said to be ready to start trading potential free agents, including
Rafael Palmeiro and Roberto Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   But most notable, from a historical perspective, the debate was
raging once again: Should All-Star third baseman Cal Ripken, having
a substandard offensive season, take a day off and end his
magnificent streak of consecutive games played?
</P>
<P>
   Everybody seemed to have an opinion, especially in the news
media. Some were calling it the most selfless streak in history.
Others called it the most selfish. However, the two whose opinions
matter most continue to defend the streak, and Ripken is in the
Orioles' lineup indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Cal has on any given day is good enough for me,''
Orioles manager Ray Miller told Baltimore reporters before the
break. ``I have a tough enough time getting guys to play two weeks
in a row, let alone every game.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that if Ripken asked for a day off, he
would get one. But he has no intention of doing so, and the streak
will reach 2,572 games when the Orioles play the Rangers tonight at
The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep perspective and the simple approach,'' Ripken
said at the All-Star Game. ``I'm considered the everyday third
baseman for the Orioles, and my job is to come out and help us win.
If the manager is making his lineup, thinking I can be one of those
guys that can help us win, I'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's mediocre offensive numbers invite debate.
</P>
<P>
   He is hitting .257 with seven home runs and 37 runs batted in.
His .371 slugging percentage on the day the American League
All-Stars were announced was lowest on the team, lower than even
defensive-minded shortstop Omar Vizquel. The Orioles' .359 slugging
percentage from their third basemen, usually considered a power
position, is third-lowest in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes if your performance is down, I'd rather have people
talk about your performance, rather than the streak,'' Ripken said.
``Taking a day off is not going to help your performance. Actually
working hard and correcting your hitting will correct your
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Every major-league player is prone to slumps. But when Ripken
goes through them, there is an immediate tendency to blame the
streak.
</P>
<P>
   That happened in 1990, when Ripken's batting average dropped to
a career-low .250 with 21 home runs, 78 runs and 84 RBI, relatively
low numbers for him. The streak was blamed, but Ripken responded
the next year by hitting .323 with 34 home runs and 114 RBI, good
enough to be named the AL Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   However, he isn't getting younger. Ripken will be 38 next month,
an age when many players contemplate retirement, being a designated
hitter or a platoon situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak itself can be analyzed, dissected, opinions can be
formed in all different directions,'' Ripken said. ``But I don't
worry about that kind of stuff. I worry about the thing that
matters most, my approach to the game. It's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   He has staunch defenders, including Rangers first baseman Will
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people who say he needs to take a day off don't realize
how hard it is to go out there and play every day,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Florida manager Jim Leyland: ``Cal Ripken is a great player
and still a very productive player. If Cal Ripken is healthy, he's
like any other great player _ you want him in the lineup. I'll
never believe that Cal Ripken is hurting his team by playing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Twins' Paul Molitor had to go on the disabled list for
the 14th time in his career after getting hit in the ribs by a
pitch, he wondered aloud why such things don't happen to Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, he'd probably be playing tomorrow,'' Molitor said.
``He'd probably hit left-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans seemed to weigh in with an opinion at the All-Star
break. A sellout crowd at Coors Field gave Ripken a standing
ovation in pregame introductions equal to that given Mark McGwire
and Rockies hometown favorite Larry Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the streak ends, it will take care of itself,'' Ripken
said. ``The situation will present itself, which will make sense,
and it will happen. I can't tell you how it would happen, but it's
not going to go on forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
