<HEADLINE>
HIKIND DECIDES TO SKIP RACE FOR CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after he was acquitted of accepting illegal
payoffs, Assemblyman Dov Hikind said he would not run for the
congressional seat being vacated by Rep. Charles Schumer, saying it
was too late to enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little late to pursue that goal,'' Hikind said. ``We're
looking at several other things, but not in 1998. But it will be
for a major position.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikind said that he would not yet endorse any of the Democratic
candidates for the congressional seat in Brooklyn; Schumer is
running for the Democratic Senate nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Hikind said he might run for re-election to the state Assembly,
and that he had already received 5,000 signatures to put him on the
ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
