<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-THEATER-NYT &LR;      07-14 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HARD TIMES FOR ART IN REALM OF THE COIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Martin Russell took over a tiny Times Square movie
house last year, spending 18 months and $100,000 to convert it into
a performance space for poets, actors and musicians. Since he
didn't learn carpentry or painting when he studied at the Royal
Academy of Dramatic Art, he improvised his way through fixing up
raw space with sweat equity.
</P>
<P>
   As unfamiliar as Russell was with those skills, the space itself
was no stranger to sweaty rawness. He took over a theater with a
black-walled basement dungeon and another room lined with cramped
booths that were once used for anonymous sex. Until 1995, it was
the New King Cinema, a gay X-rated theater that city officials
closed after investigators found that it was the setting for risky
and unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   Combining artistic vision and let's-put-on-a-show impulsiveness,
Russell and his wife, Jill, struggled to give the decrepit theater
a second act. They turned it into the Eden Arcade and plan to offer
a nonstop cultural smorgasbord. Above the theater's entrance on
West 44th Street, they wryly wrote, ``Important Intangible Cultural
Property.'' Now it could become the ultimate in intangible:
defunct.
</P>
<P>
   The cost and time needed for renovations exceeded the Russells'
expectations. Unable to open the theater, they are still waiting
for various licenses and certificates that would allow them to
serve food and liquor to generate income. They are behind on their
rent and worry that they will be cast from their private paradise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware we're asking for an extraordinary privilege to be in
New York, in Times Square, at the turn of the century,'' said
Russell, who is British. ``To have a showcase where people can say
what they want. To have movies, music and poetry. That's Eden,
ain't it? We're really within touching distance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russells' kooky gutsiness has been tested in the
now-sanitized Times Square, where they have lived since the 1970s.
They came from Europe, where they had studied theater, intent on
performing. Russell grew dismayed when people said he needed a
nonprofit group to gain legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you don't understand,'' Russell said he told them. ``Art.
`No,' they told me, `you don't understand. If you want
respectability, you have to become producers in spite of
yourselves.'''
</P>
<P>
   They did, migrating from space to space until they found a good
one on West 43rd Street. By early 1996, they were set to sign a
10-year lease when the neighborhood started buzzing with the
arrival of Disney and its big plans for the seedy strip. The
landlord wanted more money. With no luck and no home, they
discovered that even storefronts in the Hell's Kitchen section were
going for ridiculous rents in anticipation of a golden age.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became victims of this upscale thing,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like canaries in the English mines. They brought them
down to see if they would live. They now send in the artists, and
when the neighborhood goes up, they throw us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, he and his wife came across the closed X-rated theater
and struck a deal with the landlord, who they said was eager to
return it to legitimate use. But it took a lot more than the three
months they had planned on to strip the chairs and floors of
accumulated years of Lord knows what. They also found themselves
having to spend time and money fixing walls and exits to meet
building and fire codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid I used to see all these guys working in the theater
and ask, `How did they get so cynical?''' Russell said. ``The
theater is such a joy. A bouquet. The hardest thing is trying to
remain sane in the middle of all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they have worked out a payment schedule to catch up on
the back rent, the Russells continue to look for angels in the
neighborhood. They have sent out about 1,300 ``begging letters,''
as Russell calls his fund-raising pitch packages, which boast not
only of his performance plans but also of his training programs for
young people.
</P>
<P>
   Sex sold; that's what he learned when someone told him that the
old theater raked in $7,000 in cash each day. Now he has to worry
about selling people on the arts as an alternative to the
mass-market stuff that dominates the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kid, 10 years ago on the way to school in the Village, she
saw these hookers standing on the street in bathing suits and high
heels, waiting for the guys driving in from Jersey,'' he said.
``She looked at me and said, `There's nobody looking for YOU at
8:30 in the morning with a 20 spot.' You'd think that music, drama
and poetry would sell. That's the rich bouquet you want in life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
