<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BOBWHITES-NYT &LR;      07-14 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOBWHITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BOBWHITES IN THE BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2000, man and nature permitting, flora and fauna
that have not been seen in these parts for years will be thriving
in New York City's parks _ screech owls and lunar moths in
Manhattan, bobwhite quail in the Bronx, water shrews in Queens,
butterfly weed in Brooklyn, tree frogs in Staten Island. These
species are part of Parks Commissioner Henry Stern's experiment to
enhance the biodiversity and the educational value of the urban
landscape. Whether it works or not, his plan is powerful evidence
of how far New York City's parks have come. Not so long ago the
parks were dumping grounds for abandoned cars. Today they are
healthy enough to allow their supervisors to think more
ambitiously.
</P>
<P>
   Re-introducing species is a complex business. For one thing, the
species must fit logically into a food chain capable of sustaining
it. Screech owls, for example, need small rodents to survive.
Central Park has mice galore. Wanderlust is an obvious danger,
especially in birds, but park officials say that neither screech
owls nor bobwhites are migratory. Finally, park officials must make
their own adjustments. The lunar moth builds its cocoons in messy
piles of leaves underneath trees. The maintenance staff must
therefore resist the impulse to keep the premises manicured.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shot in the dark'' is the way one wildlife biologist
describes Stern's vision. But what is there to lose? Besides, the
species themselves might welcome a change of venue. The bobwhite
quail, for example, is under siege in its native habitat, partly
because the hedgerows where quails congregate are being mowed down
as farms consolidate. The Bronx's Pelham Bay Park might provide
just the cover they need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980714.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLYHARDWARE-COX     07-14 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYHARDWARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toys to T-shirts, Christian market is big business
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Hey, everybody, what time is it?
</P>
<P>
   It's Jesus time.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the answer from the owner of a Christian-message
watch company and the rest of the 1,552 exhibitors in six acres of
convention space here.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Convention Center is jammed with more than 13,000
members of the Christian Booksellers Association who are meeting
here through Thursday. Publishers and wholesalers are hawking wares
from books to birdhouses, and store owners are looking for products
in a retail industry that is generating more than $2 billion a year
in sales. The booksellers association's goal is to double that
figure by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Call it what you will _ evangelism or a cash cow _ today's
Christian marketplace is becoming a sophisticated industry that
employs secular marketing techniques and business savvy. Strong
economic times coupled with more demand has created higher profit
margins, with some products selling for almost three times
wholesale cost.
</P>
<P>
   You can ``Soar with Jesus'' on a toy airplane or keep your
breath fresh with Testamints. You can host a party with Jesus
napkins, plates and cups or send your kids to school with Nativity
erasers in their God First backpack.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to work with your Virtues brand commuter coffee mug
that proclaims ``Integrity, The just man walketh in his integrity''
from Proverbs and dash into the office with a leather briefcase
embroidered with a Latin cross. Later, you can put on your Jesus
socks, T-shirt and shorts, slip into your tennis shoes that
announce you are a ``Jesus Freak'' on a plate attached by the
shoestrings and take a jog. If that's not your sport, try a
skateboard with an inspirational message, or a round of golf with
golfballs inscribed with ``Jesus. The new hole-in-one.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling a little blue? J-Mar Associates in Waco has the cure for
what ails you: pill containers that instruct the patient to ``Take
as needed for spiritual renewal.'' Inside, the container has 50
tear-off Bible verses. They are a big hit with hospital chaplains,
said Bob Gager, J-Mar's operations manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things just fly out of our place,'' he added. The
company sells more than 25,000 pill containers a year.
</P>
<P>
   Never be late for an important appointment with a Citizen watch
offered by Harry Ko of Garden Grove, Calif. Among the more than 300
watches bearing Christian messages, face designs include ``Pray
Hard,'' ``His Pain Your Gain'' and ``Jesus is Watching Every Second
of Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The watches, which retail for $39.95, come with a lifetime
guarantee, Ko said. ``I hate to see them throw in it in the trash
with the message on it,'' he explained. ``I'd rather they send it
in and I fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a caveat: No guarantee on salvation, Ko said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolates, gravy dishes, pens, pencils, videos, games, clothes
_ you name it and wholesalers have God, Jesus and the Scriptures on
it.
</P>
<P>
   From junk to big business
</P>
<P>
   The industry has come a long way from three years ago when it
was awash in cheap, tacky gift items, such as Jesus toenail
clippers. ``We were here one year, and they had Bible toilet
paper,'' recalls Vernon Wilson, a custom-jewelry maker.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders call it holy hardware and Jesus junk. The Rev. Franklin
Graham, son of the Rev. Billy Graham, calls it garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lot of trash that comes out in the name of
Jesus Christ,'' he said Monday. ``There's big money, big
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Anderson, president of the Colorado-based booksellers
organization, said retail sales, which are showing a 13 percent
gain in 1998 over the same period last year, are about reaching
more people for Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales is merely the measurement by which we can gauge
increased outreach, increased impact in the lives of people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Christian manufacturers are quickly responding to secular
trends, producing alternative merchandise, including a burgeoning
music industry, to counter what many see as commercial enterprises
designed to neutralize God or demean Christian values in society.
</P>
<P>
   Besides answering secular trends, the Christian market has
started its own.
</P>
<P>
   Market sets trends
</P>
<P>
   Products bearing the W.W.J.D. (What Would Jesus Do) motto, for
example, are spreading faster than a Texas wildfire. The movement
began by targeting adolescents. They used W.W.J.D. to guide them
through the tough decisions teens face during puberty. Now, these
products' popularity is exploding among adults, with goods ranging
from bracelets to ties.
</P>
<P>
   The newest initiative launched by the booksellers association at
the convention is a ``Think Kids First'' campaign that has brought
together 23 children's-product suppliers to encourage Christian
bookstores to devote more space to children's materials. If the
campaign is successful, it could eventually lead to a new breed of
stores dealing exclusively in children's merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, according to Anderson, is to have such a good,
high-profile selection of quality children's products that parents
and kids will think of shopping at Kids First stores before other
toy stores.
</P>
<P>
   Britt Beemer, president of American's Research Group, a
market-research firm, said a study he did for the booksellers
association concluded that the Christian retail industry ``is
currently doing about one-sixth of their potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence in the market is seen in the humor of some products.
For years, the industry felt the seriousness of the mission _ to
spread the gospel of Jesus _ left little room to poke fun. Now,
numerous vendors are showing a lighter side and are marketing to
mainline Protestant Christians as well as their faithful
evangelical-Christian customers.
</P>
<P>
   There's the toddler-size hooded sweatshirts with ``Precious Lil'
Protestant'' embroidered on the front, and infant bibs with such
catchy sayings as ``Perky Lil' Presbyterian,'' ``Mighty Lil'
Episcopalian'' and ``Itty, Bitty Baptist.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumper stickers proclaim, ``Lord, Bless that Tailgater,''
``Caution: Christian in Training, Danger of Derailment'' and ``My
Boss is a Jewish Carpenter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians can look at themselves tongue-and-cheek,'' said Dan
Zimmerman of Spirit Marketing Inc. in Minneapolis, Minn. His line
of doormats include such lighthearted sayings as ``Dear God, help
me to be even half the person my dog thinks I am,'' and ``Jesus is
coming. Quit standing around on this mat.''
</P>
<P>
   In smaller print on the bottom of each mat is ``Knock and the
door will be opened Matt. 7:7.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
