<SLUG> BC-NBAF-THAMYRIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concert review: Thamyris with Tania Leon, Pheeroan akLaff and
Dianne Monroe
 &HT;    Georgia State University Recital Hall
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the too well-kept secrets of the National Black Arts
Festival is its focus on contemporary chamber works by
African-American composers. One of the too well-kept secrets of the
Atlanta music scene is the dedicated and adventurous ensemble
Thamyris, which has, for years, been steadily, keenly going about
its business: creating imaginative programs that push the envelope
in thoroughly inviting ways.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case Tuesday night as Thamyris was joined by
several special guests -- and a host of composers in the audience
(yes, they're alive) -- to perform recent works and revisit some
prior commissions as part of the NBAF's ongoing mission. These
concerts are remarkable for their consistency and synergistic flow;
there's something almost tart and crisp in the way the musicians
connect with these pieces, which ranged from the oscillating
percussive overlay of Anthony Davis's 1981gamelan-influenced
``Wayang II -- Shadow Dance'' to Wendell Logan's 1992 ``Moments,''
an apt title for a work rich in dramatic interludes, discrete
embellishments and sustained rhythmic tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The program built up from works that featured spare
instrumentation (Tania Leon's ``A la Par,'' T.J. Anderson's
``Inermezzi'') into denser constructions for the full-scale
ensemble (plus such guests as violinist Diane Monroe and drummer
Pheeroan akLaff, known for work in the jazz world, and
conductor/composer Leon). The critical mass was complex without
being confounding. For sheer impact, though, it was the solemnly
piercing soprano of Cheryl Boyd-Waddell (on Alvin Singleton's
``Between Sisters,'' a setting of Rita Dove's poem ``The House
Slave'') that struck home with chilling simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
