<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXING-LADN     07-14 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING CRITICS CITE MINDS THAT HAVE TURNED TO MUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Chacon, 46, has the mentality of a small child. A look
into the eyes of once-charismatic Jerry Quarry, 53, his sister says
sadly, and ``no one is home.''
</P>
<P>
   And who can forget the startling image of Muhammad Ali, 56,
shaking uncontrollably as he tried to light the Olympic flame in
Atlanta in 1996?
</P>
<P>
   This, as much as rich lore and rich purses, is the legacy of
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment the possibility of death in the ring.
Statistically, boxing is well down the list of sports when it comes
to fatalities. However, this cannot be denied: Boxing leads the way
in chronic brain damage, an all-too-overlooked reality that turns
too many robust men into living, breathing zombies. Chacon, Quarry
and Ali are only high-profile examples of a larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises an important question: Is it time to ban the sport?
</P>
<P>
   Those who say ``no'' argue that aspiring fighters know the risks
and have the God-given right to take them, pointing out that boxing
officials go to considerable lengths to make the sport as safe as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Those who say ``yes'' point to the victims, the fighters whose
brains have been destroyed, and ask, ``Does this belong in a
civilized society?''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's an emotional issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do anything to get boxing stopped,'' said Dianna Quarry,
who watched helplessly as two of her brothers, Jerry and Mike,
deteriorated after successful boxing careers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bad for the brain
</P>
<P>
   The Journal of the American Medical Association is one entity
that advocates a ban.
</P>
<P>
   Its editor, Dr. George Lundberg, was once a fan of the sport. He
marveled at the ability of fighters like Ali and Floyd Patterson
and rarely missed the Friday night fights on television.
</P>
<P>
   And then the data came in. Studies done in the early 1980s in
the U.S., Italy and Finland concluded roughly the same thing: 75-80
percent of boxers with a substantial number of fights _ he
suggested 20 but pointed out that many blows are taken in sparring
_ show evidence of chronic brain damage that can only worsen.
</P>
<P>
   That's when both the journal and Lundberg took their ban-boxing
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I thought the risk was sporadic,'' Lundberg said.
``Sure, once in a while someone died and once in a while someone
became punch drunk. It was the nature of the sport, an exciting
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the numbers came out (in the studies), though, as a
physician, I had to change my mind completely....
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing is medically wrong and morally wrong. Medically wrong
because of the frequency of chronic brain damage and morally wrong
because a boxer wins by harming his opponent. While this might
occur in other sports, in theory it's an undesired side effect and
not the purpose of the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Jerry Quarry is tragic but not unique.
</P>
<P>
   Quarry was once one of the top heavyweights in the world, a
contemporary of Ali and Joe Frazier who never realized his dream of
winning the championship. He was a brawler, a fighter who was
willing to take punches to give them. Ultimately, the repeated
blows to his head _ and their effect on his brain _ began to take a
toll.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, he gradually lost his short-term memory and,
as a result, his ability to function normally. For example, he
might ask a question but cannot retain the answer.
</P>
<P>
   He must be cared for by his family. He lived with Dianna in
Atascadero for six years but recently moved in with another sister,
Brenda, in Paso Robles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted him for a while,'' Dianna said. ``He's degressing,
of course. She wanted to spend time with him while he's still able
to recognize her....
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this what the world wants? A man who, beginning at around
40, has the mind of an 80-year-old? A man who can't always
recognize members of his own family? For what? A few dollars? For
what people call `fame?' They're willing to sacrifice a mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to act as if nothing is wrong, to avoid eye contact
(with Jerry). Otherwise, I'd break down, I'd just break down.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A matter of choice
</P>
<P>
   Those who defend boxing have compassion for their brethren.
Boxing is an extremely tight fraternity. At the same time, they
demand the right to determine their own destiny _ even if they
endanger themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What about mountain climbing? Or sky diving? Or motorcycle
racing? Or, a popular sport boxing people mention often, football?
Are we also to ban these activities because they're dangerous?
</P>
<P>
   And, they say, boxing provides so many boys _ particularly those
from poor neighborhoods _ a direction. Even if they don't become
professional boxers, it teaches them discipline and respect,
provides a sense of belonging and gives them an outlet for
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, some make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone was meant to carry a briefcase,'' said former
champion Sugar Ray Leonard. ``Not everyone was meant to get a
college degree. There are certain opportunities that exist for us,
for people who are unfortunate. Boxing is one of those
opportunities. We're not hurting anyone but ourselves. And there
are risks in everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a capitalist society and this is the vocation I
decided upon. How can someone want to abolish the sport that made
me the man I am today?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boxing and legislation
</P>
<P>
   The British Medical Association also advocates an end to boxing.
And it actively pursues a ban.
</P>
<P>
   BMA doctors engage in public debates with boxing authorities and
they produce anti-boxing advertisements. And, apparently, people
are listening: A proposed bill to ban boxing failed to pass by a
single vote in parliament's upper house in 1994, according to Dr.
Bill O'Neill, a research adviser to the BMA.
</P>
<P>
   He believes a tragedy in connection with boxing's latest
phenomenon _ women fighters _ might be all it takes to kill the
sport in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Here, an end to boxing is nowhere in sight. The Journal of the
AMA stands vociferously against it, but no meaningful action has
been taken to bring about its demise.
</P>
<P>
   Under these circumstances, doctors, boxing officials and now
politicians _ U.S. senators John McCain and Richard Bryan, whose
bill to improve safety standards is now law _ do what they can to
protect the fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Among a litany of regulations in California, which has the most
stringent standards: To be licensed, boxers must take physical, eye
and neurological exams and be tested for HIV and hepatitis B. They
cannot fight for at least 45 days if they're knocked out. Two
doctors must be present at all bouts. And the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Ringside physicians, who regularly meet to discuss safety
issues, also are constantly seeking ways to make the sport even
safer and to address issues facing the women fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the AMA to have a negative opinion (of boxing),''
said Dr. Paul Wallace, a ringside physician. ``But it's not their
choice. The job of physicians is to make the participant as safe as
possible given the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dentist doesn't say you can't eat candy. He says if you're
going to eat it, brush your teeth afterward. In boxing, we adhere
to certain standards. They have physicals, neurological exams and
so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``These participants aren't my private patients. I'm just here
to see that the environment is made as safe as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, those opposed to the sport don't buy such an
argument. The risk, they say, is simply too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like saying, `If you want to be heroin addict, go ahead.
If you want to drive your car at 150 miles per hour on a mountain
road, I guess you can do that.' I mean, you could sell out Soldiers
Field (in Chicago) for a shootout with six-guns if the parties
signed a consent,'' Lundberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't make it all right. At times people have to be
protected from themselves. That's what public health is all
about....
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more sad than anything else. It's the nature of humanity
that causes some people to get their excitement and joy out of
other people's pain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2330EDT &QL; 
