<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE REV. AL SHARPTON THINKS THE VERDICT OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may be wondering whether the Rev. Al Sharpton feels sorry
for Steven Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones, a former assistant district attorney in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., has spent the last decade under the cloud of Sharpton's
charges that he was part of a gang of white men who supposedly
raped and abducted Tawana Brawley. This week a jury found Sharpton
liable on seven counts of defamation, apparently agreeing with a
grand jury's earlier conclusion that Miss Brawley had made the rape
story up.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones, who gave up his legal career to pursue the case against
Sharpton and two of his associates, expressed pleasure at the
long-awaited verdict. His wife, at his side, had the look of a
woman who might have preferred to spend the last 10 years living
quietly in another state.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sharpton, he speaks of a remorse that seems to stop short
of agonizing repentance. ``I don't regret getting involved,'' he
said. ``I don't regret repeating what a victim said, what I
believed she said. Do I regret the personal attacks? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago Al Sharpton was very much in the shadow of the
attorneys C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox, both of whom have since
fallen off the edge of the world of political influence. Sharpton
has become a far more influential and inclusive figure, having
undergone what he refers to as ``my metamorphosis.'' But his core
constituency includes many people who passionately believe that
Tawana Brawley told the truth _ or that to question her story is to
betray all the black women who were raped and disbelieved
throughout American history.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, Sharpton said he still did not believe the
incident was a hoax, and he is not going to disavow Miss Brawley's
story at this late date. But at times, he comes pretty close.
Speculating about legal strategy for the inevitable appeal, he
says: ``If the grand jury's theory was that Tawana and her mother
did it'' _ made up the rape story _ ``to fool the stepfather, why
wouldn't somebody say she could fool me and Maddox and Mason? How
would we know her better? You can't have it both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   When the defamation verdict came in, Sharpton's first reaction
was to position himself up against the long-suffering Pagones as a
victim. ``After all I've been through, this seems very civil,'' he
said, recounting his resume of fasts and jailings and having been
stabbing by a white man. His next response, which also seemed to be
partly aimed at Pagones, was to go back to that metamorphosis. A
key moment comes when Sharpton forgives the man who stabbed him and
asks the court for leniency. ``I admit to having grown, to having
the need to grow. I'm wondering have others grown with me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a performance that will appeal only to a specific
audience. Many people find Sharpton far too slippery for comfort.
But it comes as a certain relief after the rhetoric of Mason and
Maddox, now both disbarred lawyers still rearguing the Brawley
case, promising proof that does not arrive, branding dissenters as
racist. Sharpton never gives the impression he is operating in a
separate reality. He is working very much in this one, and trying
to make his way out of a difficult corner with all the verbal skill
at his command without doing the obvious, which is to say he's
sorry for a terrible mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton noted that his co-defendants were found guilty of
defaming Pagones after the grand jury exonerated him. ``But I
wasn't sued for anything beyond the grand jury,'' he said. There
was, of course, an interview with a magazine writer in which
Sharpton cited unnamed witnesses and unproduced sperm samples that
he claimed could prove Ms. Brawley had been raped by a gang that
included Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but I wasn't sued for it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
