</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-STANDARDBEARER-ART-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGENTS' QUIET VOICE FOR TEACHER STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was with ``a great burst of naivete'' that Diane
O'Neill McGivern submitted her name in 1991 to join the New York
State Board of Regents, the state's highest educational authority.
A nurse and a teacher, she headed the nursing division at New York
University, but had no political experience and had never tangled
with behemoths like the United Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   She laughs now, as if recalling youthful innocence. An article
in The Staten Island Advance, her local paper, had mentioned a
vacancy on what was then a sleepy group of overseers, and she
applied with the passionate but vague hope of improving education
and the process for licensing medical and other professionals,
another of the regents' duties. There wasn't much competition.
</P>
<P>
   But within a few years, education had swiftly moved to the top
of the political agenda, elected officials began to campaign on
school issues, and the regents awoke from their slumber to become a
significant force in statewide education policy. They imposed tough
graduation requirements on high school students, took control of
poorly performing schools and issued the first school-by-school
performance reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGivern, along with the board's chancellor, Carl Hayden,
and the education commissioner, Richard Mills, has quietly but
forcefully been in the forefront of those efforts. As the board's
vice chancellor, she was named co-chairwoman of what may be the
board's most contentious initiative yet, the task force to improve
teaching in the state.
</P>
<P>
   If the committee's report, two years in the making, is approved
by the full Board of Regents on Thursday, it will begin one of the
most sweeping changes ever made to teaching standards in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a real sense of frustration,'' she said Tuesday
in her office at NYU. ``Every year we revisit school failure, we
revisit large numbers of children not reaching the literacy or the
math levels we'd like. It seemed that all these incremental things
that we were doing were not having much impact. And I suppose that
once you have a lot of that frustration for a while, collectively,
you feel the need to act.''
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent proposal in the report, and the one that has
drawn the most concern from the highly organized groups of teachers
around the state, is the one that effectively ends the permanent
licenses now held by the state's 202,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposal does not explicitly end tenure, it
requires new teachers to take 175 hours of continuing education
every five years to retain their licenses. (Existing teachers are
exempt from the requirement.) It is unclear how school districts
will pay for such education.
</P>
<P>
   The task force would also strengthen requirements for teacher
education at state colleges, and require administrators to impose
tougher standards in evaluating a district's teachers. At the same
time, it proposes a package of financial incentives to attract and
retain the best teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGivern is aware that many teachers, already feeling
underpaid and underappreciated, may see the report as yet another
attempt to blame them for the failings of the education system, at
a time buildings are falling apart and classrooms are overflowing
with children. She insists that is not the case, but believes that
if students are held to higher standards, teachers should be as
well.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For reform to work, the other side of the equation is the
teacher, and that is the last piece to fit into the reform
effort,'' she said. ``People say that once you start down this
road, you're criticizing teachers, you're not holding them in
enough regard. But if you look across the state, the quality of
teacher preparation and performance is very variable.''
</P>
<P>
   Her restraint in this description, much appreciated by her 15
colleagues on the board, reflects a diplomatic awareness that she
must balance reform with recognition of the power of teachers'
unions, who can often block change. But the final report, the
subject of considerable compromise and horse trading, has won
something like praise from both the State School Boards
Association, representing administrators, and the teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, the president of the United Federation of
Teachers, the New York City teachers union, said she respects Ms.
McGivern's quiet tenacity. Steven Sanders, chairman of the state
Assembly's education committee, said that quality is one reason she
was reappointed earlier this year when the Assembly was replacing
regents right and left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no accident her term of office was extended,'' he said.
``She was one of the few who actually went out and spent time in
schools, and we were very impressed with her demeanor and her
assertiveness in supporting more rigorous standards. She is a real
consensus builder.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of her school visits take place in Brooklyn and Staten
Island, the two boroughs she represents. Ms. McGivern, 59, lives in
Dongan Hills, on Staten Island, with her husband, Bernard, an oral
surgeon, and about a dozen Hungarian pointers, which she and her
husband breed. She grew up in a suburb of Cleveland, and never left
New York after coming to study nursing in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how much things have changed that when she
calls ahead for a school visit, one of six or seven a month,
teachers and principals scramble. ``You have to call ahead, or they
would really faint,'' she said, laughing. Something must have
shaken them up.
</P>
</TEXT>
