u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      07-14 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES 4, METS 2
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is the scenario the Mets have craved. An
important series at Shea Stadium against the awesome Atlanta Braves
_ even if it is for only two games _ and another chance for the
Mets to prove that they are serious contenders to play in October.
With Todd Hundley back in the lineup, the Mets had momentum and,
most of all, they had hope.
</P>
<P>
   But hope changed to hopelessness for one more dreary night as
John Smoltz asserted himself on the mound and the Braves asserted
themselves on the field by marching to a 4-2 victory. The Mets?
They did not assert themselves. Instead, they aggravated
themselves. Again.
</P>
<P>
   While the final score sounds reasonably close, the outcome was
not in much doubt once the Braves took a two-run lead in the fifth.
Smoltz limited the Mets to one hit over the last five innings he
pitched to help Atlanta end a three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can play with them,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
had said before the team's deficit behind the first-place Braves
increased to 12 1/2 games. ``To win games, we've got to play well
and make a break or two. We're due for a break or two.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine failed to get a break in a key situation that
helped doom the Mets in the seventh inning. He instructed Edgardo
Alfonzo to try a sacrifice bunt with runners on first and second
and none out, a sound enough choice for advancing the potential
tying runs. But the problem came after Alfonzo fouled off two
attempts and had a 2-2 count.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine removed the bunt sign, but Alfonzo, a good contact
hitter, tried one anyway. The ball rolled foul along the third base
line.
</P>
<P>
   The strikeout sucked the enthusiasm out of Shea and, apparently,
out of the Mets. John Olerud followed by flying out to left field,
and Mike Piazza had a weak at-bat against Smoltz as he reached out
and tapped a pitch back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 38,000 fans groaned about the lost opportunity,
which also proved to be New York's last opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz (7-2), who permitted two runs and six hits in eight
innings, retired the last six batters he faced. The Mets' Bobby
Jones (7-6) pitched decently while allowing four runs and eight
hits in seven innings, but the right-hander now has one victory in
his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley singled in both runs for the Mets, who are 2-1 since his
return.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz hurt New York's chances in the fourth, but in an
unexpected manner. With the score tied, 2-2, the Braves had runners
on second and third and one out because Javier Lopez had singled
and Andruw Jones had doubled. Jones needed to retire Smoltz, an
easy enough task, but he hung a 2-2 curveball, and Smoltz waited
and then slapped it softly to right for a run-scoring single. It
was Smoltz's fourth hit and fourth run batted in of the season, and
it gave Atlanta a 3-2 lead. One inning later, Chipper Jones homered
to right field to make it 4-2. It was Jones' 24th homer of the
season, his first in 90 at-bats as a left-handed batter.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were deflated by Smoltz's hit, especially since they
had tied the score in the third on Hundley's two-run single. With
two outs, Olerud singled and Piazza doubled to put two runners in
scoring position and put Hundley in an inviting position. The
catcher-turned-outfielder smoked a line drive to center, which
briefly belonged to Andruw Jones. He dived as if center field was a
10-foot pool, trying to make a nifty two-handed catch, but the ball
bounced free when his glove slammed against the ground. Olerud and
Piazza scored, enlivening Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta had grabbed a 2-0 lead in the third inning, also by
scoring after there were two outs. Chipper Jones doubled off the
left field fence to knock in the first run, and Andres Galarraga
scorched a single to right to drive in the second. Butch Huskey
charged in too far on Galarraga's hit and then awkwardly tried to
block it with his glove. That failed, and Galarraga took second on
the miscue, but Bobby Jones stranded him.
</P>
</TEXT>
