<SLUG> BC-NY-SQUEEGEE-SHOOTING-295&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS IN SQUEEGEE SHOOTING FOCUS ON REQUEST TO OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators are exploring the possibility that a
New York City police officer charged with trying to kill a squeegee
man in the Bronx last month may have asked another officer to cover
up for him in the minutes after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may need your help on this,'' Officer Michael Meyer told
Officer Sheila Hennessy about 20 minutes after the June 14
shooting, according to court papers unsealed Tuesday. Investigators
said they were looking into the possibility that the remark was a
request for a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer pleaded not guilty at his arraignment Tuesday to a charge
of attempted murder in the shooting of Antoine Reid, a squeegee man
who had put soap on his windshield while he was stopped in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer's lawyer, Bruce Smirti, said he did not believe that Meyer
had asked anyone to cover up the crime or commit perjury to protect
a fellow officer.
</P>
<P>
   Smirti called that interpretation a ``sinister spin,'' and
added, ``People normally don't like to get involved as witnesses,
and he was saying, `Look, you're going to have to testify.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department's Internal Affairs Bureau has been
investigating whether the first detectives on the scene tried to
prepare their reports to make it appear that Reid was trying to rob
Meyer. Witnesses, and Reid, have said that Meyer shot Reid after
becoming enraged, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the shooting, according to the court papers, Meyer
told the first police officers who arrived: ``He tried to rob me.
He hit me in the face. He hit me with the squeegee.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was arrested the night of the shooting and arraigned
Tuesday on charges of attempted murder, two counts of assault,
criminal use of a firearm and reckless endangerment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meyer has been in trouble with the department before. After he
accumulated an unusually high number of civilian complaints
accusing him of using excessive force on duty, he was removed from
patrol and placed in the department's building maintenance section,
where he would have little contact with the public. But he was
allowed to keep his 9-millimeter service pistol, the handgun that
prosecutors say he used to shoot Reid.
</P>
<P>
   In the days immediately after the shooting, the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association, the officers' union, appeared to distance
itself from Meyer by saying that because the shooting occurred
while he was off duty, it had not decided whether to pay his legal
fees. Tuesday, Smirti and union officials said the union would pay
the fees.
</P>
<P>
   Several union leaders and dozens of officers were in the Bronx
courtroom Tuesday for Meyer's arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are backing him, and as the facts unfold, I believe you'll
see why,'' said Dan Tirelli, a union financial secretary in Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
