<HEADER>
A5247 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBING-PLOT-TRIAL-29     07-14 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-PLOT-TRIAL-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT SPOKE OF WANTING TO BOMB SUBWAY, AGENT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal agent testified Tuesday that a man charged
with plotting to explode a powerful pipe bomb in a New York City
subway told him that he had wanted to bomb a rush-hour train on the
B line in Brooklyn ``because there are a lot of Jews that ride that
train.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Ghazi Ibrahim Abu Maizar, is one of two
Palestinian immigrants on trial on charges of conspiring to bomb
the subway. Prosecutors say they were motivated by a hatred of
Israel and Jews generally, and by opposition to the peace process
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first trial testimony to cite a specific subway line
as a target. The B line runs through Brooklyn's Borough Park
section, home to one of the city's most concentrated populations of
Orthodox Jews, on its route between Coney Island, Brooklyn, and
Manhattan and the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent Michael Anticev said in the second week of the federal
trial that Abu Maizar also told him during questioning that he had
been only hours away from placing the bomb on July 31 during that
morning's rush when the police raided his apartment in Park Slope,
Brooklyn, shortly after 4:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Maizar, 24, and the second defendant, Lafi Khalil, 23, were
shot and wounded in the raid, in which the police said they seized
a ``fully rigged'' pipe bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Abu Maizar have not disputed that their client had
the bomb, but they have maintained that he did not intend to
explode it. Rather, they have suggested that he planned to use it
as a prop in a plot to defraud a government anti-terrorism program
of reward money. Khalil's lawyer has not yet addressed the jury,
but Khalil told investigators after his arrest that he had not
known that the bomb existed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The defendants were shot, officers testified earlier in the
trial, because they feared that one was trying to set off the bomb
and that the other was trying to grab an officer's gun. Anticev
questioned Abu Maizar in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Maizar's lawyer, Jan Rostal, sought Tuesday to cast doubt on
the reliability of her client's purported statements. Although
Anticev said that Abu Maizar had been ``alert and responsive''
during questioning, Ms. Rostal suggested during her
cross-examination that Abu Maizar could not have been able to speak
rationally, because he had been in surgery for several hours
earlier and was under medication.
</P>
<P>
   She got the agent to acknowledge that Abu Maizar ``was in
obvious pain'' and that he had not recorded the session.
</P>
<P>
   Anticev also testified that before they talked, he had told Abu
Maizar that he had a right to remain silent. Ms. Rostal implied in
her questions that Abu Maizar's medical condition meant that his
waiver of his rights was not truly voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Reena Raggi interrupted the testimony to tell the jury
that the issues it would decide would include whether Abu Maizar
had made the statements Anticev attributed to him, and whether they
were voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the raid, the police said the defendants had
been planning to blow up the busy Atlantic Avenue subway station in
downtown Brooklyn, but more recently investigators have not spoken
of that station. The B line does not stop at that station, but it
does stop at the Pacific Street station, which is connected to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-14-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
