<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-FUND-RAISIN     07-14 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-FUND-RAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S FUND-RAISING EFFORT SURPASSES '94 CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki has collected $15.5 million for
his re-election effort, surpassing his total for the entire 1994
campaign and apparently far outpacing his Democratic rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki took in $4.3 million in the first half of this year
alone, according to figures released by his campaign Tuesday night.
If he continues harvesting money at this rate, he is likely to rank
as one of the most successful fund-raisers in the history of state
politics. Four years ago, when he was an Republican state senator,
Pataki collected more than $14.5 million in defeating the
Democratic incumbent, Mario Cuomo, who raised more than $11
million.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has $12.2 million on hand, after spending $3.3 million in
the first half of the year, mostly for television and radio
advertising and fund-raising events, according to a summary of his
disclosure report.
</P>
<P>
   Details on contributors to the governor's campaign will not be
available until Wednesday, when the full report is to be filed with
state election authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The four Democratic contenders did not release figures Tuesday
but are expected to on Wednesday. In their last disclosure in
January, the Democrats reported having far less money than Pataki,
who has hewed to a strategy of raising money aggressively
throughout his term in order to avoid having to do so in the final
weeks of his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats with the biggest bank accounts as of January
were Lieut. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross and City Council Speaker
Peter Vallone, both of whom had raised more than $2 million. The
vast majority of Ms. McCaughey Ross' money came in a single
contribution from her husband, the financier Wilbur L. Ross Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's spokeswoman, Zenia Mucha, did not respond to phone
messages Tuesday night. But she has said in the past that he has
excelled at fund-raising because people are pleased with his
policies on issues like crime, welfare and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have contended that the governor's fund-raising is
unseemly, pointing out that much of the money is from donors with
interests before the state government.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his own campaign money, the governor can also rely on
the financial support of the New York Republican State Committee,
which has been collecting record sums since Pataki took office in
1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
