<HEADLINE>
A MODEL OFFICIAL  
 `ABBIE!' IS A MOVIE!  
 FRETFUL FOR FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Would District Attorney JEANINE PIRRO of Westchester
County really rather be a fashion model? There she is, one of 30
women in ANNIE LEIBOVITZ photographs in a 32-page magazine
advertisement for Anne Klein, the struggling sportswear
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   But no, she is not trading politics for photo shoots and day-in,
day-out dieting. She found that posing with LISA LESLIE, the
women's basketball star _ and being attended to by makeup and hair
stylists _ was ``awkward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This, I thought, was an opportunity to say women could be and
do anything they could do and still have a soft side,'' she said.
``I think there are women who still don't feel they have the same
opportunities as men, but the women in this campaign are successful
women. They're women out there doing it without being anorexic.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, times have changed. ``When I was a little girl
growing up in Elmira and said I wanted to be a lawyer, people would
say, `Don't you want to be a mother?''' she said. ``I grew up
thinking they're mutually exclusive. Now my son says, `Mom, can
boys be DAs?'''
</P>
<P>
   `Abbie!' Is a Movie!
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbie!,'' a film about Abbie Hoffman, the 1960s radical who
helped organize the protests at the 1968 Democratic convention in
Chicago, will go into production, exclamation point and all.
VINCENT D'ONOFRIO will play Hoffman, JANEANE GARAFOLO his ex-wife
ANITA, and KEVIN CORRIGAN his fellow Yippie JERRY RUBIN.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's 37-year-old son ANDREW, who runs a soup kitchen in
Cambridge, Mass., is complaining that he has not been consulted.
``I would like them to have the input of his children,'' Andrew
Hoffman said. ``Abbie's entire life was about the youth of America,
and I think that I would have a lot to offer. I was at the Chicago
Seven trial when I was 8 years old. I was witness to a lot of
important political moments in the '60s, '70s, '80s and '90s, and
I'm just saying, hey, what about me, don't forget the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT GREENWALD, the producer of ``Abbie!,'' said that he did
not want to forget anyone, and added that Anita Hoffman would
appear in a courtroom scene.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Hoffman said he was worried that ``Abbie!'' would be
``Abbie meets `Starsky and Hutch.''' But at least Greenwald met
Abbie Hoffman before his death in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point when he was underground, he was in Los Angeles
and he wanted to meet a few people, which I assumed would be three
people hiding in a car someplace,'' Greenwald said. ``Instead, it
was this incredibly elaborate dinner in a restaurant, 25 people
sitting on the floor. He'd taken over the entire restaurant. He was
fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   Fretful for Flowers
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the 74-foot-tall Christmas tree was finally
turned into mulch a few weeks ago, DAVID MURBACH turned his
attention to Rockefeller Center's $3.5 million flower and garden
show, which opens Wednesday night. It is, he declared as he
scurried beneath the 25-foot-high faux mountain that has appeared
between 48th and 51st streets, the only true outdoor flower show in
the country (no tents).
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest fear I have is always torrential downpours,'' said
Murbach, the manager of Rockefeller Center's gardens division. ``A
hailstorm would be horrendous. Hail destroys flowers and destroys
leaves, which in a garden is bad. Flowers bloom out a week or two
later. In a garden show, you don't have that leeway. We're on the
stage, the performance is now.''
</P>
<P>
   But enough of summer. Christmas is just around the corner, as
far as he is concerned. So when will he pick this year's tree?
``I'll be making my decision shortly,'' he said. ``There's a
miniature-train garden from the New York Botanical Garden in the
show that's called Christmas in July. It's a way of reminding me
that I don't have much time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
