<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS OPT FOR YOUTH, SPEED IN TRADING VETERAN BASSEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars yesterday made a move toward youth and speed,
but they continue to lose toughness.
</P>
<P>
   In shipping veteran left winger Bob Bassen to the Calgary
Flames, the Stars were not so intent on getting versatile center
Aaron Gavey in exchange as they were in opening a spot on the left
side for promising prospect Jamie Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the emergence of Jamie Wright and with some of our other
left wingers, we decided we needed to give them a chance to play,''
said Doug Armstrong, assistant to Stars general manager Bob Gainey.
``We're sad to see Bob Bassen go, but this is a move that helps us
get younger and faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bassen, 33, was injured for much of his three seasons with the
Stars. But during the playoffs the past two seasons, he was an
important contributor, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wright, 22, gave the Stars a new dimension in the
playoffs _ speed. That speed could become even more important as
the NHL continues to try to reduce obstruction and open the game by
moving the goal line two feet forward next season, making it
tougher for goalies to play the puck and increasing the need for
speedy forecheckers to run the dump-and-chase style of offense.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Wright, the Stars likely will also give burly
prospect Jason Botterill the chance to get some playing time on the
left side.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey, 24, is by no means a ``throw-in'' on the deal. At
6-foot-1, 195 pounds, he is a durable checking line center who
likely will be pegged as a reserve this season and a possible
replacement for Guy Carbonneau, who at 38, is playing year to year.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey, who is scheduled to make $525,000 this season, played in
26 games for the Flames last season, scoring two goals and adding
three assists to 24 penalty minutes. In 156 career NHL games, he
has 18 goals and 18 assists with 126 penalty minutes. He might be
best known for the 1996 on-ice accident in which he was struck in
the face by a skate and required 120 stitches to close the gash.
</P>
<P>
   Bassen, who was the Stars' first big free-agent signing with a
four-year, $4 million contract in 1995, played 117 regular-season
games for the Stars, scoring eight goals and adding 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   He returns to the town of his birth with the trade _ a place his
family still calls home. Bassen's dad, Hank, was an NHL goalie for
nine seasons and still is one of the better-known figures in
Calgary.  &LR; tagtop:Mike Heika (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
